<HEADER>
A7927 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-GIANTS-HN     12-14 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-GIANTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In a perfect world, John Elway would have
thrown the winning touchdown pass to Shannon Sharpe with 48 seconds
remaining, sending Denver on its way to Miami with a 14-0 record.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But this is an imperfect world, and it was Giants quarterback
Kent Graham and receiver Amani Toomer who wrote NFL history and
proved once again that nobody's perfect _ except for the 1972 Miami
Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Denver's quest for perfection ended Sunday when Toomer outfought
cornerback Tito Paul for the ball on a 37-yard touchdown pass at
the back of the end zone as New York defeated the Broncos 20-16,
handing Denver its first loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since we lost, and it brings back some
bad memories, but the only way we're going to top winning the last
Super Bowl is to win this one,'' Elway said after the Broncos fell
for the first time in 12 months. ``Finishing undefeated would have
made it even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win that many games in a row, you start to think you
can't lose. That (going unbeaten) was a goal of ours, but it wasn't
our main goal. We're disappointed, obviously, but it's not like our
season's down the drain.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Broncos tried to put on a happy face, it was
obvious in their actions and expressions how important it was to
them to become the first team to finish 19-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't give the Vince Lombardi Trophy for numbers,''
Sharpe said. ``They give it for winning the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather this happen now than four weeks from now. Our
objective has been and is to play in Miami (Super Bowl XXXIII) in
late January, and anything less is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're judged by the end result. If we win another Super Bowl,
this game won't mean a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway and Sharpe were right, of course, but six other teams have
won back-to-back Super Bowls. The 1972 Dolphins, who finished 17-0,
remain the NFL's only unbeaten and untied champion.
</P>
<P>
   By allowing the Giants to go 86 yards in six plays to win on
Graham's pass to Toomer, the Broncos also blew their chance to set
an NFL record with 19 consecutive victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking for myself, I'm happy as hell that's off our backs,''
Denver defensive tackle Keith Traylor said. ``We had a killer run,
but our goal is to win the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams started ganging up on us and passing their game plan
down the line. We're champions, and champions don't like to lose,
but the wear and tear of it (the winning streak) was wearing me
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why the Broncos' defense collapsed on the last
series.
</P>
<P>
   It never should have come down to the last series, but the
Giants' defense was outstanding, limiting Denver to three Jason
Elam field goals until the last five minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Davis, who finished with 147 yards on 28 carries, scored
Denver's only touchdown on a 27-yard run, giving the Broncos a
16-13 lead with 4:08 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' Gary Brown, who ran for 112 yards, had touched the
ball 807 times since he lost a fumble in 1994 with the Oilers. With
3:36 left in the game, he had the ball stripped by safety Tyrone
Braxton. Linebacker Bill Romanowski recovered at Denver's 29.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos faced second-and-one, but the Giants threw Davis and
fullback Howard Griffith for losses, forcing a Tom Rouen punt that
gave New York the ball at its 14. Graham had 1:49 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Graham completed two passes for 26 yards, then ran for 23. Then,
on first down from the 37 with 57 seconds left, Graham found Toomer
in the end zone for one of the most dramatic touchdowns in Giants
history.
</P>
<P>
   One official signaled that Toomer was out of the end zone. But
after a brief discussion, he was overruled.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't panic, but neither did we,'' Giants offensive
tackle Scott Gragg said. ``We knew we had to play a perfect game.
It wasn't perfect, but it was close enough. We were lucky to have
two turnovers and still beat a team like the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the nature of the game _ every team's beatable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos had shown they weren't invincible in their last two
victories, over San Diego and Kansas City. Although they entered
play Sunday third in the league in points allowed, they don't have
a great defense.
</P>
<P>
   And the Broncos proved it again Sunday when they allowed the
Giants to drive 86 yards at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lot like last year when we lost two of our last
three,'' said Elway, who completed 19 of 36 passes for 180 yards
with one interception. ``But we turned that around, and we can do
it again. At this point, everything is designed to be playing our
best football going into the playoffs, and we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Braxton said, ``It's very disappointing any time you get a
chance to separate yourself from the league for years and years and
years, and you don't achieve that goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing and depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver's next game is at Miami a week from tonight. The Broncos
close at home against Seattle. They need more consistency on
offense, and they have to get tougher on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't look past the Giants,'' Elway said. ``It didn't
matter who we were playing in the next game. We just got beat by a
team that played a great game. Their defense was outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the Broncos have the same 13-1 record as
Minnesota, and the Vikings are playing better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been getting tougher every week because we were getting
everybody's best shot,'' Elway said. ``We definitely weren't going
to be sneaking up on anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got bothersome to keep talking about going unbeaten. We
didn't bring it up until the media asked us about it, which was
almost every day. It gives me a new appreciation for the 1972
Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't lose, and that's hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The streak was special, something we were shooting for,''
coach Mike Shanahan said. ``It's tough to lose this one, and
everybody's real disappointed. It's going to take awhile to get
over, but we're still looking forward to the challenge that's ahead
of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
