<P>
   IMPEACH-REPUBS _ In a surprising shift of political
calculations, many prominent Republicans now say that the party's
march toward impeachment would cause no lasting and political
damage. Republican Governors, state party leaders and strategists
around the country _ many of whom had complained that their party
had badly mishandled the scandal all year long _ said in interviews
that the stakes are far lower than they were in the fall because
there is no looming election. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REACT (Canton, Ohio) _ Residents talk about impeachment
at the local newsstand. By Michael Winerip.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT5) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-DOCTRINE _ A look at some comparisons between Watergate
and the Lewinsky scandal, as cited by Judiciary Committee members.
Also assessing the role of the committee: Is it like a grand jury?
Is impeachment a deterrent, or the first step toward removing a
president from office? By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LEGACY _ What the impeachment investigation may mean to
the presidency. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-JACKSON _ In opposing a censure of President Clinton,
many Republicans argued that the Constitution contains no words
allowing Congress to take that step. Perhaps not, but that has not
stopped lawmakers of yesteryear. By David Stout.
</P>
