<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON-SCENE (Jerusalem) _ President Clinton may have
left the United States on the heels of what one Israeli daily
termed a Congressional intifada, using the Arab term for uprising.
But there is no question that Clinton is engaged in a critical
salvage mission for the faltering peace effort. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   NAZI-SLAVELABOR (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Spurred on by Germany's
new Social Democratic government and a huge trans-Atlantic merger,
Germany's banks and industrial conglomerates are urgently trying to
devise a broad new plan to compensate Holocaust survivors and
millions of Poles, Russians, and other Europeans enslaved by the
Nazis. The corporations, from Deutsche Bank AG to Siemens and
DaimlerChrysler AG, want to free themselves from a slew of new
American class-action lawsuits alleging that they profited by
collaborating with the Nazis during World War II. The controversy
also threatens to pull in U.S. government officials who, for now,
are taking a cautious approach to direct involvement. By Barry
Meier and Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-COPING (Mozhaivsk) _ How wards of the Russian state
manage to survive in a calamity-prone economy. The answer is, as
usual, a mish-mash involving the kindness of strangers and a dash
of native ingenuity. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-CHRISTIANS (Harare, Zimbabwe) _ The Church in Africa
refuses to accept an African denomination that allows polygamy
among its clergy. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DIABETES-CHILDREN (New York) _ A look at an alarming new health
trend: the sharp increase in the number of youngsters with Type 2
diabetes, also known as adult-onset diabetes, an incurable and
progressively damaging disease that can cause kidney failure,
blindness and poor circulation, which, in turn, can lead to
amputation. Doctors long believed the disease occurred only during
middle age or later. Although there have not been any national
surveys documenting the rise of this form of diabetes in children,
several small-scale studies have found that such cases have more
than tripled in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT3) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-UDALL (Undated) _ Morris Udall, a former U.S. congressman
and Democratic Party presidential candidate, has died at age 76. By
Richard Severo.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT8) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   ABUSE-KILLINGS (Seattle) _ Examination of the case of an abused
wife who was slain, along with her son, by her estranged husband.
She had gotten a restraining order against him, and had sought the
safety of a shelter. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PENTAGON-BUDGET _ The Pentagon has asked President Clinton for
the largest increase in military spending since the first four
years of Ronald Reagan's Cold War buildup, but the administration
has balked at the size of the request, having already pledged to
preserve budget surpluses for the Social Security system. By Steven
Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOFT-TRIAL-ASSESS (Undated) In the Microsoft trial, the Justice
Department has depicted Microsoft as unfairly using the technical
leverage and market power that stems from its 90 percent share of
the operating system market to stifle competition. Yet while the
case raises the issue of access to technology, it also shows that
doing anything to force Microsoft to provide access to its
technology will be tricky, both on legal and practical grounds. A
news analysis by Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   READERS-PUBLISHERS-MEDIA (New Orleans) _ Fast Company may be the
only magazine to host a conference at which the former secretary of
labor, Robert Reich, led an audience of hundreds in an impromptu
kazoo concert, but it is not alone in its mission. In an attempt to
solidify the relationship with readers _ and their checkbooks _
publishers have begun to organize events for subscribers and
readers outside the pages of their magazine. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT1,2) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   AETNA-HEALTH-GIANT (Undated) _ Aetna Inc. has transformed itself
in less than three years from an insurance giant known as a
relatively easygoing nice guy into a hard-driving managed-care
company that many doctors say they hate. Now, by swallowing two
sizable competitors, Aetna is making a risky bet that it can
dominate the nation's health-care system. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SOFT-WITNESS-PROFILE (Undated) _ Among all the computer
scientists in the world, the Department of Justice chose David
Farber as an expert witness for a trial in which a central issue is
Microsoft's supposed attempt to monopolize the market for so-called
Internet browser software. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT9) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SPAM-BLACKLIST (Redwood City, Calif.) _ If David Farber
is noteworthy for the number of people who want to be included on
his influential E-mail list, Paul Vixie is famous _ some would say
notorious _ for publishing an online list that companies
desperately want to avoid being on. By Matt Ritchel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT12) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   COPIER-WARS (Undated) _ The copier wars are full upon us. But
despite hugely expensive advertising campaigns that promote each
product's features, the war will not be won on the product
battlefield alone. Instead, whoever locks in the best distribution
network may well push up to the head of the line. By Claudia H.
Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ Internet companies, many with no
product, no profits and, often, no proven or sustainable business
model _ are taking their companies public and hitting the jackpot
with shares that are valued far beyond reason. By Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Why is BellSouth Corp. talking
up its stock? While the speculation is nowhere near a boil, it is
clear that BellSouth has become more aggressive in promoting its
stock than it has been at any time at least since passage of the
Telecommunications Act of 1996. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SPANISH-RADIO-MEDIA (New York) _ It might have seemed
unimaginable five years ago that a Spanish-language radio station
would dominate the metropolitan New York market. But since last
summer, WSKQ-FM, which promotes itself as Mega 97.9, has been No.
1, surpassing the market's longtime leader, the light-rock station
WLTW-FM. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CARNEGIEHALL-EXPAND (New York) _ In a major expansion of one of
the nation's premier cultural landmarks, Carnegie Hall is going
underground, turning a subterranean recital hall from 1891 into a
high-tech performance space for small operas and other productions.
By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   PRINCE-EGYPT-CREATOR (Hollywood) _ What makes executives
responsible for ``The Prince of Egypt'' nervous is that this
animated film is a somber musical saga designed for adults and
children who are not toddlers. One of its creators says he he has
sought to make a film that borrows far less from the cartoon
tradition and far more from David Lean's ``Lawrence of Arabia,''
and even from the French impressionist Claude Monet and from the
biblical etchings of the 19th-century illustrator Gustave Dore. By
Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
