<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGERS EASY PICKINGS FOR SEAHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After a season of disappointment, a week of answering
questions about whether the Seahawks would come out flat after
being robbed by an official's call and too many days of hearing
raves for the San Diego Chargers' defense, Darryl Williams had
endured enough.
</P>
<P>
   When the Seahawk defensive players gathered Saturday night for
their weekly meeting, Williams, the Pro Bowl free safety and
defensive co-captain, stood up and guaranteed there would be no
lack of effort from his unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to let that happen and I know 22 guys on defense
who aren't going to let that happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' message came across oh-so-loud and ever-so-clear at
the Kingdome Sunday, as the defense scored twice and set up three
other scores in the Seahawks' stunning 38-17 romp over the
Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks forced eight turnovers and set an NFL record for
touchdown returns with their 11th and 12th of the season. Defensive
tackle Cortez Kennedy scooped up a fumble and ran it back 39 yards
for the first score of his career, and nickel back Terry McDaniel
returned an interception 43 yards for another TD.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle also set a club record by intercepting the Chargers'
befuddled tandem of Craig Whelihan and Ryan Leaf seven times _
including two each by cornerback Shawn Springs, strong safety Jay
Bellamy and Williams.
</P>
<P>
   It was an effort that left defensive coordinator Greg McMackin
in tears as he tried to explain just what it meant to him, his
players and embattled coach Dennis Erickson, especially after the
one-point loss to the Jets last week where New York quarterback
Vinny Testaverde was awarded a game-winning TD despite not getting
into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of pride on this team,'' McMackin said. ``They
care about coach Erickson, and that's obvious the way they play for
him. They won't quit. Everybody thought they'd be flat after last
week, but I had no doubt in my mind that they would come out and
play because they're a class act and there's no quit in them.''
</P>
<P>
   It also was an effort that left the Seahawks 7-7 and still in
the AFC playoff chase _ mathematically, if not realistically. The
Seahawks can get to nine wins by defeating the Indianapolis Colts
at the Kingdome this week and the now once-beaten Broncos in Denver
next week. Even that won't get them into the playoffs for the first
time since 1988 without help, a lot of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playoffs?'' defensive end Michael Sinclair asked with a
puzzled look. ``At this point, I don't even care. We've got Indy
coming in here, so all our focus is on getting (win) No. 8. I'm not
thinking about anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Number 7 was just one more dominating defensive performance in a
game where the still-struggling offense needed all the help it
could get. Quarterback Jon Kitna, making his third start, had the
worst outing of his young NFL career, completing 16 of 31 passes
for 140 yards and three interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won a lot of games this year because of our defense,''
said running back Ricky Watters, who ran for 69 yards and became
the first player in NFL history to have 1,000-yard seasons with
three different teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawk triumph was bitter for Chargers interim coach June
Jones, who announced last week he was leaving after the season to
become head coach at the University of Hawaii, his alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed,'' Jones said. ``Our defense showed the
spirit that has made them No. 1 all year, but you can't give the
ball away that many times on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried about everything to get it going, and we just
couldn't throw it to the right guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Whelihan, the Chargers' starter, threw five interceptions. Leaf,
the rookie from Washington State and No. 2 pick in last spring's
draft, had two passes picked off and also fumbled twice. Jones
shuffled the two in the second half, but neither could get the job
done.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks didn't do anything fancy defensively. They just did
it well. They blitzed more than they have in recent weeks, using
the front seven to pressure the quarterback. That left the
secondary to make plays. And make plays. And make plays.
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel was up first. He intercepted a Whelihan pass that was
intended for Ryan Thelwell and dove into the end zone to give the
Seahawks a 14-7 lead at the end of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Williams then picked Whelihan again to set up a 1-yard TD run by
Watters in the second quarter. It was Williams' first interception
this season after tying for the AFC lead last year with eight.
</P>
<P>
   Williams struck again midway through the third quarter. This
time, he picked off Leaf to set up Kitna's 9-yard TD pass to Joey
Galloway, giving the Seahawks a 28-14 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The clincher was Kennedy's rumbling return of a Leaf fumble
early in the fourth quarter. It was enough that the 306-pound
tackle recovered the fumble caused when defensive end Matt LaBounty
sacked Leaf. But Kennedy then spun to elude a would-be tackler and
was gone. No one caught him. No one even got close, as Kennedy
crossed the goal line and disappeared up the tunnel that leads to
the visiting locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had high-stepped,'' Springs offered with a grin, ``I
probably would have passed out.''
</P>
<P>
   What made the Seahawk defensive effort even more impressive was
that they did it without several key performers. Middle linebacker
Dean Wells, situational safety Mark Collins and No. 3 defensive
tackle Dan Saleaumua remained out with injuries. Cornerback Willie
Williams was named inactive before the game with the strained heel
he received in last week's loss to the Jets. And Sinclair, the AFC
sack leader and Pro Bowl defensive end, sat out the second half
after pinching a nerve in his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie linebacker DeShone Myles, backup safety Kerry Joseph, No.
4 defensive tackle Riddick Parker, cornerbacks Fred Thomas and
McDaniel and LaBounty not only stepped in, they stepped up.
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair had a front-row seat after his injury, and he was
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a Picasso,'' Sinclair said. ``Those guys were all
over the place. I was entertained myself. I don't think you could
have drawn it up any better today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
