<HEADLINE>
ASTROS SAY CLEMENS DEAL TOO COSTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Johnny Oates sat at a table on a ballroom
dais hoping to talk baseball but was instead looking for an escape.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers manager was taking all sorts of questions
about small markets and large markets, private jets and hotel
suites, players set to earn $100,000 every 25 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like talking baseball,'' Oates said Sunday at baseball's
winter meetings. ``I don't know bottom line, red line, whatever. I
like to talk hit-and-run, breaking ball ...''
</P>
<P>
   No such luck. Four hours later, from the same platform, Houston
Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker called a news conference and
threw a high, hard one under the chin of Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are Clemens' hometown team and seemed to be the
pitcher's likely destination after he demanded a trade from the
Toronto Blue Jays. But that changed when Clemens' agents, Randy and
Alan Hendricks, told Houston owner Drayton McLane just how much it
would take to restructure Clemens' contract.
</P>
<P>
   For Houston, it's Roger, over and out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, we are absolutely stunned and really outraged
at the demands,'' Hunsicker said. ``I was with this franchise when
we made Nolan Ryan the first $1 million player, and I remember how
aghast the industry was at paying one player $1 million. So I guess
I've become hardened to the fact that anything can and eventually
does happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just extremely concerned about the health of the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, pitcher Kevin Brown became baseball's first $100
million player, signing a seven-year, $105 million contract with
the Los Angeles Dodgers that guarantees him a suite on the road and
12 flights per year for his family on the Fox jet.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who has five Cy Young awards _ five more than Brown _
reportedly asked for one year and $27.4 million to be added to his
contract, which pays him $16.1 million for the next two years.
Clemens' deal was the richest ever for a pitcher when he signed it
in 1996, but he has leverage now because he can veto any trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers and Colorado Rockies remain interested in Clemens,
and the New York Yankees are always a possibility. The Blue Jays
and Clemens had an understanding that Clemens could be traded to a
contender if he was unhappy with the direction of the franchise,
but Toronto general manager Gord Ash said Clemens could remain with
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' Ash said. ``He has a contract.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole situation is ``mind-boggling'' to Hunsicker. If
Houston were to pay Clemens what he wanted and trade Toronto what
it wanted, he said, the club could not contend anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, I don't blame the player, because this is a
free-market society and everyone wants to get what people are
willing to pay,'' Hunsicker said. ``I'm concerned for the industry,
because more and more people seem to be trying to extract every
last nickel from the system. And it's not a matter of trying to pay
the bills every month. It's going way past that. It's
one-upsmanship, is what it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the rate we're going, it won't be long until clubs will
have to close up shop. ... Everybody recognizes the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The winter meetings were brought back to capitalize on
baseball's renaissance, but talk has centered on the industry's
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's lunacy, it really is,'' said San Diego Padres general
manager Kevin Towers, whose team lost Brown on Saturday. ``It's
crazy, and I think we're headed for disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest thing is we're all so competitive, but I think we
need to police ourselves _ not just owners but the players union
and everyone in the industry. ... The thing we need to keep in mind
is the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Towers said he hoped negotiations on the next Basic Agreement
would be less contentious because of two additions to the
commissioner's office _ former Toronto president Paul Beeston and
former Oakland president Sandy Alderson, who was critical of the
Brown signing Saturday. But even with two to three years remaining
on the labor agreement that came out of the 1994-95 strike, people
are wondering what that mess was all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, it will end. The question is, who's going to end
it, who's in charge to end it,'' said Montreal Expos manager Felipe
Alou, who turned down an offer from the cash-rich Dodgers this
winter to stay with the cash-poor Expos. ``I can't complain,
because I'm getting paid real well myself, but four years after the
strike, it's amazing to see what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what to say about it. I'm surprised every
day when I wake up and read the papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Another small-market manager, Jack McKeon of the Cincinnati
Reds, had similar concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you sit back and wonder where we're going and how
many jobs are going to be left if we continue to go at this pace
and don't put people in the ballpark,'' he said. ``Sometimes it's
scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds, like the Padres, Mariners and others, will soon open a
new ballpark that should give hope to the franchise. But what has
happened this winter _ especially this week _ signifies to many
that a new facility is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker, whose team opens a retractable-roof park in 2000,
believes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it means,'' he said, ``is most of us are in trouble if
we're not going to be able to compete for the top talent in this
industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
