<SLUG> BC-GEN-CSUNPAD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASS'AD WANTS TO COACH WOMEN'S TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Marwan Ass'ad spent a coaching lifetime building
Cal State Northridge's men's soccer team but is willing to give it
up to become the women's soccer coach at the school.
</P>
<P>
   That position will be vacant Dec. 31, when coach Brian Wiesner's
resignation takes effect.
</P>
<P>
   But why would the 44-year-old Ass'ad make the switch? Simple.
Stability and potential.
</P>
<P>
   Much more emphasis is placed on the women's program at CSUN than
the men's program. Just look at the scholarship allotments for each
program.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining part of his reasoning for making the jump, if the
job were offered to him, Ass'ad said the commitment from the
administration was in place to build the women's team into a
winning program. He said he liked the fact the women's program is
given 12 scholarships; the men's program must operate on only two.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential for the program is incredible,'' Ass'ad said.
``There are so many people who support women's soccer in the
Valley. I think we can have 2,000 people there per game. I don't
think it's a dream to get 2,000 people to a game.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also more stability in the women's program. Less than
two years ago CSUN created a public relations gaffe by dropping
four sports, one of which was men's soccer. The long-reaching
ramifications are still being felt.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN president Blenda Wilson said the sports were reinstated for
the long term, but fairly or not, speculation and mumblings exist
about the program's future.
</P>
<P>
   Finances are also an issue. Ass'ad said he made $18,000 annually
and supplements his income through camps and offseason coaching.
That supplementing would be possible with the women's job, but with
a higher base salary. Wiesner earned $37,956 per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I would be doing it for the money because I
would have left by now if that was the case,'' said Ass'ad, who has
been at CSUN since 1983. ``I love the Valley. I don't want to
leave.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Another gridiron transfer? CSUN football coaches continue to
recruit the area high schools, but more news is being made in the
way of Division I transfers.
</P>
<P>
   The latest ``bounce back'' expected to transfer to CSUN is
Gardena product DeJuan Gilmore, sources in Pullman, Wash., said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore, a running back, was on CSUN's campus a few weeks ago
and was impressed with the Matadors' coaching staff. He was
Washington State's second-leading rusher this past season. He
carried 65 times for 305 yards and three touchdowns. Gilmore also
caught six passes for 57 yards.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Harris chronicles: It's hard to get any kind of measure
on men's basketball player Rico Harris, who's long-awaited
indoctrination into Division I basketball has been filled with
pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, bothered by a hip-pointer, missed his third straight
game Saturday when the Matadors had their winning streak snapped at
five games at Brigham Young.
</P>
<P>
   However, he is hoping to be ready for Saturday's game with UCLA
at Pauley Pavilion, and for good reason. Plenty should be at stake
for the 6-foot-9 power forward.
</P>
<P>
   Barring the NCAA tournament, this is the final time NBA scouts
will have an opportunity to gauge Harris against the best
competition in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Harris, who's averaging 11.8 points and 6.4
rebounds per game, had such a chance was when the Matadors (6-3)
played at Tennessee last month. But he was suspended for violating
team rules, leaving a few handfuls of NBA scouts with little to
watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 0046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
