<SLUG> BC-NY-VACCO-CONCEDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACCO EXPECTED TO CONCEDE RACE FOR ATTORNEY GENERAL
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Attorney General Dennis Vacco, the Republican who
has spent the last six weeks alleging voter fraud and fighting in
court to prevent the certification of his Democratic challenger,
Eliot Spitzer, as his successor, is expected to concede to Spitzer
on Monday, Republican officials said on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of an appearance in State Supreme Court, where Vacco
has been asked to show evidence of his many claims of voting
irregularities in New York City, the attorney general is preparing
for what is likely to be the end to one of the most unusual and
controversial episodes in New York political history _ one in which
his re-election effort touched quarters including the state courts
and the New York City Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Vacco said on Sunday night that the campaign
believed it had amassed evidence of voter fraud, but not enough to
make a difference in the outcome of the election.
</P>
<P>
   Since Election Day, when unofficial results showed him trailing
in one of the closest contests in this century, Vacco has lodged
several complaints of voting irregularities in New York City. He
raised allegations of votes being cast in the names of dead people
and claimed that thousands of people voted twice. But in the end,
his lawyers said, the attorney general did not accumulate enough
data to persuade the court to do what Vacco had sought: call a new
election or declare him the winner.
</P>
<P>
   If Justice Thomas Keegan of state Supreme Court dismisses
Vacco's case _ something both campaigns now consider likely _ it
will remove the final roadblock to certification of the unofficial
results: Spitzer won the election by 26,011 votes.
</P>
<P>
   While not confirming what position Vacco will take, Thomas
Spargo, a lawyer for the attorney general's campaign, said on
Sunday night that he would present evidence of thousands of votes
cast under some sort of cloud. He said he would detail votes that
were cast by people for whom death benefits were being paid as well
as votes case by New York City residents who had moved outside of
the state and registered to vote elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent the day reviewing our proof,'' Spargo said on Sunday
night, following a meeting with Vacco and William Powers, the state
Republican Party chairman. ``And while we think it's very
significant, it has not yet come up to the numbers that are needed
to impact the outcome of the election at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   While his fight to win a second term had seemed to many _
particularly in the Spitzer campaign _ to have been relentless,
several Republican elected officials said that the attorney
general's intermediaries had been hinting in recent days that
Vacco's effort was likely to be unsuccessful and that he would
concede on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general has indicated that he felt it was time to
end the legal maneuvers,'' said a Republican member of the
legislature, who asked not to be named. ``He has been preparing for
this eventuality. He knows it's time to end this.''
</P>
<P>
   In unofficial results from the State Board of Elections, Spitzer
led with a margin of 26,011 votes out of 4.2 million cast. While
the Democratic challenger has declared victory, Vacco has not
conceded. The matter is becoming more urgent as Tuesday's deadline
for the Board of Elections to certify the election approaches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
