<HEADER>
A7966 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES_TKACHUK-A     12-14 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_TKACHUK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK PICKS HIS BATTLES THIS SEASON  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ In an eye-for-an-eye, tooth-for-a-tooth league, Keith
Tkachuk can turn the other cheek only so many times before he has
to pull a Norman Bates and go psycho.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case last week in Phoenix, when after repeatedly
getting cross-checked in the back by Montreal's Alain Nasreddine,
the Coyotes captain threw down his gloves and began using
Nasreddine's face as a punching bag.
</P>
<P>
   It was Tkachuk's first major penalty of the season. And as well
as he has behaved lately, it probably won't be his last.
</P>
<P>
   Take tonight, for instance, when Tkachuk and the streaking
Coyotes (17-3-3) visit Nasreddine and the Canadiens (8-16-4) in a
rematch of Wednesday's grudge match, won by Phoenix, 4-2.
Nasreddine is back after serving a two-game suspension for his part
in the Tkachuk fight, and if he wants to duke it out again, that's
fine by Tkachuk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing my best to try and stay out of the box,'' said
Tkachuk, who two seasons ago became the first player in NHL history
to lead the league in goals scored (52) and collect more than 200
penalty minutes (228).
</P>
<P>
   ``But sometimes during the year, when guys are taking extra
liberties, you have to show people around the league that you're
not going to always take it, that you're going to do something
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Tkachuk's 35 penalty minutes through 23 games, almost half
came at the 3:56 mark of the third period during the Nasreddine
incident. He picked up an instigator penalty in addition to his
fighting major, and then got the obligatory 10-minute misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Nasreddine, meanwhile, got it where it hurts the most _ not just
in the head, but in the wallet. While trying to go toe to toe with
Tkachuk, he inexplicably dragged linesman Wayne Bonney to the ice.
The league suspended Nasreddine for ``physically demeaning'' the
official and fined him $1,000, the maximum allowed. He also
forfeited $3,900 in lost salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't mean to push the linesman,'' Nasreddine said. ``I was
falling down and I grabbed onto him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk has seen several replays of the incident, but said, ``I
don't know what he was thinking. That was just stupidity by him.''
</P>
<P>
   As for tonight's game at the Molson Centre, Tkachuk isn't
expecting any retaliatory swipes from Nasreddine or the rest of the
Canadiens. With 15 goals and 28 points, and the Coyotes off to
their best start in franchise history, there are far more important
things to consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just part of hockey, what happened between me and
him,'' Tkachuk said. ``You move on. You don't hold any grudges. At
least I don't. He cheap-shotted me. But I took care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld has been pleased with Tkachuk's
restraint. At the same time, though, he said he was glad to see
Tkachuk take care of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great,'' Schoenfeld said. ``He's got to pick the
right time, but I think he absolutely has to take a stand
sometimes. Keith's been extremely disciplined all season long, but
there's a fine line there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want him to be disciplined. You want him to play through
all that nonsense. But there comes a point in time where opponents
cross the line and take advantage of the situation. They think,
`Well, geez, here's this big, tough guy that's going to let me off
the hook.' But you can't keep letting them off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is, Keith knows when to make a stand and
when to play through it.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't just been Tkachuk. With proven heavyweight Jim
Cummins, the team's lone enforcer, being a healthy scratch for the
past 12 games, the Coyotes have collectively kept their cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most teams around the league see us as a pretty
disciplined team,'' Tkachuk said. ``I mean, we've got guys who can
back it up, but we play real well in between the whistles. We've
done a real good job of that this year. But as good as we've been,
as many games as we've won, we haven't played our best yet this
year. And that's kind of scary.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
