<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7968 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GOMEZ-COLUMN-CLEM     12-14 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GOMEZ-COLUMN-CLEMENS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ Roger Clemens made an impassioned plea to the
Toronto Blue Jays two weeks ago, expressing a strong desire to be
traded to a contender.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, the only pitcher ever to win five Cy Young Awards, had
a handshake deal with the Blue Jays to trade him if he believed
Toronto was not going to have a chance to seriously contend.
</P>
<P>
   It all sounded so sweet and sincere, especially because Clemens
wanted to play closer to his home in suburban Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Hah!
</P>
<P>
   Now we know what Clemens really wants, and it's not necessarily
to play for a contender. Clemens, watching fellow pitchers Kevin
Brown and Randy Johnson sign contracts that will pay each in excess
of $13 million per season, wants money. Lots of it.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants the special perks that have become the rage among
the elite free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' demands came into full view Sunday afternoon after
Houston General Manager Gerry Hunsicker called a news conference to
announce the Astros, Clemens' hometown club, were dropping out of
the trade talks with Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime followers of baseball couldn't recall a time when a
club called a press conference to state they would NOT be making a
trade. Then again, baseball in 1998 is looking more bizarre by the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, whose current contract calls for him to be paid a
combined $16.1 million over the next two seasons, wants a third
year tacked on to his current deal that will pay him $27.4 million,
bringing the total package to $43.5 million and putting him the
same economic stratosphere as Brown.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters easier for whatever club trades for Clemens, the
American League's Cy Young winner the past two seasons, the
right-hander is willing to spread that additional money over the
three years. What a guy.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens also wanted not one but two luxury suites and the use of
a corporate jet from the Astros. Why he wanted the jet is unknown,
considering his home is about a 40-minute drive to the Astrodome or
the Astros' new ballpark, which is scheduled to open in 2000. He
also wanted a luxury suite when the club is on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were absolutely stunned and outraged at the demands made by
his agents (Alan and Randy Hendricks),'' Hunsicker said.
``Philosophically, we were opposed to restructuring his contract.
But when they gave us their terms, it became a moot point.''
</P>
<P>
   It's become a childish game in which each of these elite players
is simply looking over his shoulder and saying, ``Hey, if Jimmy has
a candy bar and a Coke, then I want one. And I want a new bike,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   When will it all end?
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are to be commended for making their stand and
saying, ``No. We will not be blackmailed, no matter what we may be
giving up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were flabbergasted at the claims being made by
Clemens, who you'd think could afford any and all of the
above-mentioned requests with the millions of dollars he is being
paid.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker quickly said he could not, in good conscience, allow
Clemens to have a suite while fellow All-Stars Jeff Bagwell and
Craig Biggio did not.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, baseball is played by individuals, but its the team concept
that remains the integral component of the game.
</P>
<P>
   It would be too naive to believe all the players will be treated
equally. Rightfully so, Babe Ruth had special concessions from the
Yankees, but those perks basically centered around money.
</P>
<P>
   Give the stars all the money, that's fine. But some of the
absurd requests clubs are giving in to can lead to divisions in
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, some other club will turn around and probably
give in on Clemens' ``requirements,'' and that truly is too bad.
</P>
<P>
   All we can hope for is that the people who play this game for
the simple love of it never become outnumbered. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 0130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
