<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAKE SUSPENDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Los Angeles Kings captain Rob Blake, who
returned to the lineup Saturday after missing six weeks with a
broken foot, once again found himself out of action Sunday, though
this time not because of an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Blake learned Sunday morning that he'd been suspended for what
would be a 3-0 loss to the Anaheim Mighty Ducks at the Pond for
slashing Vancouver's Harry York in the third period of Saturday's
3-0 victory over the Canucks. Blake, general manager Dave Taylor
and coach Larry Robinson will participate today in a telephone
hearing with NHL vice president Colin Campbell, at which point it
will be determined whether Blake will receive an extended sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very dirty game all around,'' Robinson said of
Saturday's game following Sunday's 3-0 loss to the Mighty Ducks at
the Pond. ``They had guys out there trying to hurt us, and one of
our guys ends up getting suspended. It doesn't seem fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake received a major slashing penalty and a game misconduct
from referee Don Koharski in the third period Saturday when he
slashed York on the arm. York left the game with a bruise and did
not return. Koharski could have assessed a match penalty to Blake
on the play _ which would have carried with it an automatic
suspension _ but chose not to. But Campbell saw the play and
believed at least a one-game suspension was warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to whack his stick and at the last second, he reached
out for the puck,'' Blake said. ``I don't think it was that bad,
but (York) went down like he was shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake is the second King suspended by the NHL this season.
Enforcer Matt Johnson is serving a 12-game suspension for
blindsiding defenseman Jeff Beukeboom of the New York Rangers on
Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had repeat-offender status, which contributed to the
severity of his suspension. Blake's last suspension - two games for
a high-sticking incident early in 1997 - was more than 18 months
ago, so he does not qualify under league rules as a repeat
offender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob Blake has been a pretty honest player in this league for a
long time,'' Taylor said. ``He plays hard, but he's certainly not
considered a dirty player.''
</P>
<P>
   One argument the Kings probably will make in Blake's defense is
that they were shorthanded at the time of his infraction and it's
doubtful he wanted to pick up another penalty that would leave his
team two men short.
</P>
<P>
   __ Bad ice: Not for the first time, complaints were issued about
the quality of the playing surface at the Pond, this time after the
Ducks defeated the Kings on Sunday. This time, it was Ducks right
wing Teemu Selanne who was grousing about the effect of poor ice on
the quality of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking with (Ducks chairman Tony Tavares),'' said
Selanne, who scored two goals. ``I said, `We need to do something.'
They had a concert here (Saturday) night. It's always bad when they
put down new ice. Maybe we should practice here. The ice seems to
get better the more we use it. It would be so good for all the
skill players.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Pleasant problem: Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg insists he
wants to get backup goalie Dominic Roussel into some games. But the
excellent play of No. 1 goalie Guy Hebert is making that difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert stopped 35 shots by the Kings on Sunday in recording his
second consecutive shutout and his fourth this season, matching a
career high. He has a 2.16 goals-against average and a .930 save
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get (Roussel) in there,'' Hartsburg said, ``but
I'm not going to take out a guy who's playing unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Loose pucks: The shutout was the first by either team in the
all-time series. The teams have met 29 times, and the series is
tied, 12-12-5. The Ducks have won the first two of six meetings
this season by a combined margin of 6-1. . . . Kings winger Eric
Lacroix suffered a broken clavicle in the Vancouver game and is
expected to be sidelined for at least a month. Lacroix's injury,
coupled with Blake's suspension, left the Kings with just enough
players to dress for Sunday's game. Rookie forward Olli Jokinen and
defenseman Garry Galley returned to the lineup after being healthy
scratches Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
