<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS LIMP TOWARD THEIR DESTINY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In the quiet of the Cowboys' locker room,
Leon Lett stood at his locker.
</P>
<P>
   Well, he sort of stood.
</P>
<P>
   Bruised and beaten, slowed by apparent pain, Lett's upper body
draped at an odd angle as he attempted to slip into his black
shirt. He looked like the Leaning Tower of Leon.
</P>
<P>
   Less than five feet away, Michael Irvin likewise dressed
oh-so-slowly. His torso at half-mast, Irvin had to steady himself
against the locker, just to get up from a stool.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams strut into the playoffs. History tells us that the
Cowboys prefer a diamond-studded swagger.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no strut. The Cowboys yesterday, losers of three
straight, had all the looks of a team with a limp, a limp toward
their destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in excuses,'' coach Chan Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Really? OK, we won't, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that whoever steps in there, we expect them to be
able to play,'' Gailey continued, the 20-17 loss to the Kansas City
Chiefs still fresh in his craw.
</P>
<P>
   If life deals a coach lemons, Gailey's style is to try to turn
it into Team Lemonade. That's what he says, at least. That's what
they all said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we've been without a lot of people,'' quarterback Troy
Aikman echoed. ``But that's part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't dwell on those guys who are not playing. You've just
got to go out and do your job.''
</P>
<P>
   No excuses, they said. And said.
</P>
<P>
   And so we won't offer any for them, either.
</P>
<P>
   We will ignore the missing Deion Sanders, cornerback, out with a
bad toe. We will forget the impact of receiver Ernie Mills, gone
for the season. We also won't mention tight end David LaFleur,
whose absence continues to stymie the running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're on this team for a reason,'' center Mike Kiselak said.
``When you get the opportunity, you've got to play. Someone has to
rise to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way, indeed, that it is supposed to work on teams
with championship ambitions. Behind every Elway is supposed to be a
Bubby Brister. The stars limp off. The beat goes on.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens when all of your salary-cap chips are riding on
the same star numbers? Who picks up the slack against the Chiefs,
against the Saints?
</P>
<P>
   Country Day's own Patrick Jeffers, for one. With first Mills
out, and then yesterday Irvin, the third-year receiver found
himself targeted by Aikman time and again. Some he caught; some he
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike is known as `The Playmaker,' and there's a reason for
that,'' Jeffers said. ``When he went out, Billy \RDavis\S and I
looked at each other and said it was time to make some plays, time
to get some points.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Jeffers did help get the Cowboys into the end zone.
But he had one notable, drive-killing drop. And as for Davis, he
plainly disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, who once thought they enjoyed the luxury of team
depth, have found that depth is a relative term in the NFL of the
'90s. Because of injuries, they've had to go three- and four-deep
at the receiver and cornerback positions.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones' decision to invest in a select, long-term
nucleus of star players means that there is little, if any, to
spend on stand-ins. It is a decision that Owner Jones has always
defended.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but both the head coach and the quarterback say,
``Injuries are part of the game.'' And the owner spends like the
team is Clark Kent.
</P>
<P>
   The offense struggled yesterday when the Chiefs decided that
they weren't about to let Emmitt Smith beat them. When Mills was
healthy and playing, receivers were getting open. Aikman seemed to
have a smorgasbord of choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably the most surprised,'' Gailey said. ``I thought we
were playing good, doing well. All of a sudden, we've hit a stretch
here where we're not moving the football. We've got to get that
straightened out.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams with ambitions find a way, Gailey knows. For three weeks,
though, his team has only found ways to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries. The bruises. The soreness and spasms. Those are
all part of the game, the Cowboys themselves reminded us yesterday.
Lett isn't even one of the ones listed as officially hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. With two weeks to go until the playoffs, the Cowboys
are not themselves, in some cases literally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not `our team'? '' Irvin repeated. ``Every guy out there
wearing those helmets with the stars on them is our team.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a team with a limp, we saw clearly yesterday. And one with
still a long road to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
