<HEADER>
A7974 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-COLUMN     12-14 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS COME WITH NO GUAR ANTEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ They haven't beaten one team with a winning
record.
</P>
<P>
   Many look at them the way a bright, suspicious child looks at a
department store Santa, checking out the red suit that smells of
mothballs and studying the fit of the old man's remarkably white
beard.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a legitimate playoff team?
</P>
<P>
   Are the Cards for ``real''?
</P>
<P>
   When we tell them what we want for Christmas _ two more wins and
a January rematch with the Cowboys _ what assurances are there they
will come through?
</P>
<P>
   None, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ````Nothing's'' easy for us,'' Vince Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a guarantee, buy a toaster.
</P>
<P>
   There was no guarantee Sunday that the Cardinals could build on
a 10-0 lead. Or that they could make a first down on a questionable
fourth-and-one gamble. Or that their new kicker would step up and
nail a medium-range field goal from the middle of the field in the
final seconds of the fourth quarter to beat the Eagles, one of the
NFL's worst teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Cards blew the lead. Botched the gamble. The kick _ good
grief _ was wide.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the difference between the 3-11 Eagles and the 7-7
Cardinals may be not much more than a lucky guess uttered by an
offensive lineman who his teammates will tell you is older than a
Perry Como Christmas album.
</P>
<P>
   Lomas Brown called ``heads.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Heads, heads, heads, baby,'' Lomas said later, reliving the
moment, the most important call of the day. His whole face smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Heads it was.
</P>
<P>
   The score tied, the visitors won the toss and took the ball to
start overtime. Then, Jake Plummer and Rob Moore played catch and
Adrian Murrell ran, which he did all day, and when the time came to
redeem himself Chris Jacke used his mulligan to kick the ball 32
yards between the uprights.
</P>
<P>
   Cards, 20-17.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bidwill, wearing a winter topcoat, strolled through the
happy locker room reciting his favorite line after a close call _
``another laugher'' _ and smiling to himself. His son, Michael, lit
a victory cigar.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Wadsworth spoke for Jacke and Plummer and Moore and
Murrell and the injury-depleted defense. He spoke for everyone who
holds to the old-fashioned belief that if you work hard and keep
trying, good things come to those who wait. Goodness knows the
Cardinals have waited for something good to happen for a long, long
time.
</P>
<P>
   What Wadsworth said was this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Whew.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals held their position in the wild-card chase. If the
playoffs began next week, Arizona would be in.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Arizona Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Is this for real? Is it an illusion? One coach sighed with
relief and confessed, ``We're pulling rabbits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have many critics. Even when the team wins, some
dismiss the achievement with a snort and dash off e-mails like one
that arrived in my office mailbox last week. It said, and I'm
paraphrasing, ``The Cardinals STINK!!! If you're not going to tell
it like it is, they should FIRE you.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Vince Tobin, I very much want to remain gainfully employed,
seeing as how my wife and I have three kids and a dog to feed and a
stack of bills, some overdue. It's not always easy writing about
the Cards for a living. I cannot begin to imagine coaching them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard on your nerves,'' Tobin said after this
cliff-hanger, or cliff-dweller, as one pressbox humorist called it.
``You get ``so'' wound up . . . then when it's over you feel
limp.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tobin wore a smile, and it looked good on him. After the
last two games, both losses, Vince paled, his face hardening like
ready-mix cement.
</P>
<P>
   The coach had every reason to feel pleased. His team found a way
to win a game it ``had'' to win on the road in a stadium _
Veterinarian Stadium, locals now call it _ that has not been kind
to the Cardinals in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Do our lads deserve to make the playoffs? If they get in, they
do.
</P>
<P>
   And on a cold dreary day they took another step toward that
goal, surviving a close hard-fought affair, although it's possible
that White House lawyers may argue that what transpired between
these two teams comprised of consenting adults technically does not
fall within the strict, legal definition of the word ``affair'' as
set forth by the judge in the grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
