r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-EAGLES-     12-14 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-EAGLES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN IN OT RAISES HOPE FOR PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Second-year quarterback Jake Plummer went hunting
for Cardinals kicker Chris Jacke on the sideline Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He passed several depressed offensive linemen, who had just
watched Jacke's 34-yard field goal attempt go wide right with 11
seconds left in regulation and the game tied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `Get up, this isn't over,' '' Plummer said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he found Jacke, who was in only his second game with
the team. ``I said, `Get ready. We're going to give you another
chance,' '' Plummer said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacke's second chance came with 4:30 gone in overtime, and he
connected from 32 yards to give the Cardinals a 20-17 victory over
3-11 Philadelphia before a much-smaller-than-announced crowd of
62,176 at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big confidence boost for us,'' Plummer said. ``Had
we lost, the season was pretty much over.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory evened the Cardinals' record at 7-7 and left them
tied with Tampa Bay, a 16-3 winner over Pittsburgh, for the NFC's
third and last wild-card spot. But the Cardinals hold the edge over
the Buccaneers in the playoff tiebreaker because of a better NFC
record (7-4 to Tampa's 6-5).
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals win their remaining two games, both at home,
they will make the playoffs for the first time since 1982. They
play New Orleans (6-8) next Sunday and San Diego (5-9) on Dec. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right where we need to be,'' offensive tackle Lomas
Brown said. `` You couldn't ask for a better scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin already is looking for a big home-field
advantage at Sun Devil Stadium and made a public plea for fan
support next week against the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope the fans get behind this football team and realize
that this is a playoff atmosphere,'' Tobin said. ``We're going to
need all the help we can get.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, who blew a 10-0 first-quarter lead, appeared to
be in trouble with 2:29 left in regulation when the Eagles' Chris
Boniol lined up for a 33-yard field goal. Boniol, the NFL's most
accurate kicker ever, had made 67 field goals in a row from inside
the 36-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   But Boniol missed wide right, giving the Cardinals a chance to
break the 17-17 tie. ``I hit it low, and it spun off my toe and
went straight to the right,'' Boniol said. ``It never had a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   A 23-yard run by Adrian Murrell, who finished with a game-high
174 yards, gave the Cardinals a first down at the Eagles' 39 with
1:55 left. Then Plummer's 19-yard pass to wide receiver Rob Moore
gave Jacke a try for the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   Jacke had made both of his field-goal tries since being signed
on Dec. 1 to replace the injured Joe Nedney. But, he, too, missed
wide right, sending the game into overtime, the Cardinals' first
extra session this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a bad kick,'' Jacke said.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals safety Tommy Bennett, who scored on a 70-yard
interception return in the first quarter, said his ``heart
dropped'' when Jacke missed.
</P>
<P>
   Brown acknowledged that many of the players were devastated.
But, unlike Plummer, he didn't say a word to Jacke, who had helped
Green Bay win a Super Bowl two years ago. ``It's better I didn't
say anything, with what I was thinking,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Brown's job to call the coin toss in overtime. He
correctly called heads, giving the Cardinals the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great call by Lomas,'' rookie cornerback Corey
Chavous said. ``Fortunately, the referee heard the call correctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, when I play the ``Playstation'' game, that's what I
call in overtime _ heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer came out throwing in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   His 30-yard pass to Moore gave the Cardinals a first down at the
Eagles' 41.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on third and 8, Plummer read the blitz and threw a pass to
Moore on the right sideline. Moore beat cornerback Troy Vincent for
a 16-yard gain to the Eagles' 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a classic fade route,'' said Moore, who finished
with seven catches for 109 yards and one score. ``Jake gave me the
signal. It just was step and go, and he threw the perfect pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Murrell's three runs left the Cardinals with a fourth and 1 at
the Eagles' 14.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Coach Ray Rhodes tried to ice Jacke by calling
timeout, but it didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timeouts don't do anything,'' Jacke said. ``I was disappointed
I missed the first one. But then we got down there for a relatively
short one again. I'm the lucky one. I got another opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer hit eight of his final 10 passes in the fourth quarter
and overtime, including a nine-yard scoring toss to Moore, who made
a diving catch in the end zone to tie the game at 17 with 8:14 left
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The touchdown ended nearly 3{ quarters of frustration for the
Cardinals offense, which had scored only a field goal in three
trips inside the Eagles' 20-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only people who stopped us today is ourselves,'' said
center Aaron Graham of the team's 434 yards, including a
season-high 204 on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals banged-up defense, minus four starters, stiffened
in the second half after letting the Eagles Duce Staley run at will
earlier. Staley had career-high 118 yards in the first half but
only 23 in the second half and overtime. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
