r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-LADN     12-14 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING FOR CHARITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Fred Vinson hitting from downtown. . . . it's
FAN-tastic!
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly, but in the near-apocalyptic climate of a
locked-out NBA season, a charity game combining All-Stars and
All-Nobodies was enough to sate some fan appetites at UCLA's Pauley
Pavilion on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   No-names such as Vinson played alongside stars like Eddie Jones
in the Chris Mills Charity Game, and it would be charitable indeed
to call this pro basketball.
</P>
<P>
   A team dubbed Mid-Valley _ led by Mills, Tracy Murray and Bryon
Russell _ beat a team dubbed NBA All-Stars _ led by Jones, Kenny
Anderson and Maurice Taylor _ 128-119 in a game that featured a lot
of 3-pointers, minimal officiating and occasional defense.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the estimated crowd of 1,800 seemed to care much.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the game was held to benefit the Mills Youth
Foundation, United Way and the Hollenbeck Youth Center.
Unofficially,, the game benefited locked-out NBA players who need a
public relations boost, and fans who were desperate for pro hoops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little basketball fix,'' said Armando Olivas, a
27-year-old student, attending with his brother Raymond, 15. ``It
seems like forever since I've seen a basketball game.''
</P>
<P>
   And they will be waiting a while longer, perhaps until next
fall. Negotiations in the NBA's 5{-month-long labor battle fell
apart again Saturday after only 30 minutes, and the two sides did
not speak Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   If an agreement is not reached within the next few weeks, the
1998-99 season is probably dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go ahead and kill it,'' said Russell, the Utah Jazz forward
and San Bernardino native.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, personally, I hope it ain't a season. What's the use of
starting halfway?'' Russell said. ``If they're going to do
something, they need to do it now. But it doesn't look like it.
What's the use of it.? (Players) can go and make money overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, they'll play for free. The 20 players volunteered their
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Christmas holiday, it's a way of giving back,'' said
Mills, the New York Knicks guard and Los Angeles native who
organized the event. ``Everybody wants to do something . . . give
back to the kids and just put a smile on someone's face.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans who paid $10 to $25 for seats at Pauley got a decent
show and tried to sustain the usual Forum traditions _ roaring at
Jones' every move, booing the Jazz's Russell and heading for the
exits with three minutes left. There was even a celebrity sighting,
though former NFL great Eric Dickerson is no Jack Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   The sparse crowd, about 10,000 short of a sellout, was
comparable to a handful of other exhibitions NBA players have
staged around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Mills brushed off any notion that public backlash over the
lockout hurt attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what kind of (backlash) you're talking about,''
he said. ``Whatever turnout (we get), if I can give back to anybody
I'll be happy with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The game, which started 30 minutes late, produced some laughable
moments _ from Laker Tony Battie begging a referee for an
illegal-defense call to the public-address announcer bellowing,
``3-pointer, Shea Seals!'' after a shot by Vinson. Seals, a Laker
last season, was not in the building. Vinson, who gets an
occasional 10-day contract and needs the publicity, rushed to the
scorer's table to demand a correction.
</P>
<P>
   The rosters for the game even misspelled four names _ including
that of the event's namesake, listed as ``Cris'' Mills.
</P>
<P>
   But it was as close to NBA basketball as anyone could hope for
at this point. And hope is getting hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discouraged,'' Jones said of the failed negotiations. ``If
you're not talking, there's no way in the world you can come up
with any type of compromise . . . so it makes the season look very
dim.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jones is trying to be optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, in my heart, I believe there will be a
season. It may be a short season, but there will be a season,'' he
said. ``The owners, players, we want to play real bad. . . . I love
to play, that's all I have. To sit out a season, I don't think
that'll help anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
