<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FRAUENHEIM-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOORE AHEAD OF HIS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Archie Moore's nickname was ap propriate. The Mongoose was
always quicker to do something before anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   He was winning titles at a seemingly impossible age long before
George Foreman, or Nolan Ryan, or Warren Moon played into the
middle ages.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, the light-heavyweight champ at 49, always made anything
seem possible. The reason? A willingness to fight on. That was
evident three years ago when Steve Eisner, longtime Valley promoter
and manager, spent a day with Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner was there to visit an old ally in a crazy business.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing is full of wannabes and entourages. They're here today
without a dime and gone tomorrow with somebody else's money. The
parade has come and gone as often as the tide.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner and Moore were always there as either fighters, corner
men, cut men, promoters or managers. They are survivors in the
toughest game of all, and that makes them part of the only family
boxing has ever had.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of San Diego with the octogenarian Moore, Eisner
was reminded of that bond as they rode around town in Moore's old
Cadillac.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some punks pull alongside,'' said Eisner, who promoted Phoenix
cards over the past 30 years with Moore, including one of Foreman's
initial comeback bouts against Bert Cooper. ``They were giving us
the eye, and Archie rolled down the window and looked right back at
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the stoplight, they're starting to talk at us. `Hey you,
old man, yeah you. Who you lookin' at? I'm talking to you, old
man.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the next stoplight, Archie tells them: `If you pull that
car over, I'll help you find out what I used to do for a living.'
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the kids suddenly stops talking as though Archie is
somehow familiar. The kid yells: `Better go, cause that guy used to
fight.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They took off. As they did, Archie says: `You know, I wish
they had pulled over.' He was that kind of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a fighter from an era when the best fought each other,
and fought often. There were dues to be paid in those days, unlike
this era, when only guaranteed money is paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar De La Hoya and Roy Jones Jr. would have been preliminary
fighters in Archie's day,'' Eisner said. ``Today, kids retire as
millionaires after 40 fights.''
</P>
<P>
   With Moore's death, a link to a different era died. There are
fewer fighters, but more money for the best. Boxing also has been
pushed to the fringes of media attention. It's an oddity that often
embarrasses as much as it entertains. It's hard to take seriously,
perhaps because there just aren't many serious fighters left.
</P>
<P>
   One of the last of a handful died Wednesday. The Mongoose was
84, but, as usual, he went too quickly. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Briefly. . .
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson is back at Phoenix's Madison Square Garden after the
announcement last week of his bout against Frans Botha. Contracts
have yet to be filed with the Nevada Athletic Commission.
Speculative reports have Tyson's purse at $30 million, or $15
million per bite on Evander Holyfield's ears.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carbajal might make a long-awaited comeback in Miami a
week before the Super Bowl. America Presents might put together a
card before next month's game. Carbajal was supposed to fight on a
Super Bowl card in Phoenix a couple of years ago. He withdrew
because of an illness.
</P>
<P>
   Best young prospect has to be Fernando Vargas, who stopped Yory
Boy Campas for the International Boxing Federation's
junior-middleweight title Saturday night. Vargas, 21, is the second
1996 Olympian with a major title. Vargas is also the anti-Oscar.
He's not shy about expressing his dislike for De La Hoya. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Norm Frauenheim can
be reached at norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
