<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     12-14 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAVE OF INJURIES WASHES PATRIOTS UNDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette may not agree
with this, but after what happened in the Trans World Dome Sunday
it seems appropriate to say one thing about the New England
Patriots' season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sky is falling! The sky is falling!''
</P>
<P>
   You don't like to be a Chicken Little about these things, but
Sunday's 32-18 loss to the lowly St. Louis Rams had an alarming
sense of foreboding to it and not simply because it dropped the
Patriots back into fourth place in the AFC East. Math being what it
is, they are still alive in the hunt for a wild-card playoff spot,
and in some scenarios even could still win the division title, so
all technically was not lost Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But that is a mathematician's point of view, about which I know
nothing. The math says the Patriots still can finish 10-6, get into
the playoffs, sweep through them, and end up in Miami playing for a
Super Bowl title. That's what the math says.
</P>
<P>
   Like most people who can't balance their checkbook two months in
a row, I ignore math as much as possible. I believe in reality, not
mathematical probabilities, and reality tells me something
different about the Patriots' hopes for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Reality tells me they're dead.
</P>
<P>
   It's over for the Patriots, regardless of what happens against
the San Francisco 49ers next Sunday in Foxborough because a team,
any team, only can take so much, and this one has been asked to
take too much.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries may be part of this violent game and must be ignored
and played through, but there is a limit and the Patriots have
exceeded it. They have shouldered the burden of endless injury and
inflated expectations and fought them both. For a time it appeared
all was lost during their midseason swoon, but they came back, as
they have done often the past few years, and won three in a row to
get back into the race.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a team of men, not machines, and men can only take
so much pressure, and Sunday it became too much to overcome. It was
not simply the loss to the Rams, although that was disheartening
enough. It was the loss of wide receiver Terry Glenn to a broken
ankle and starting fullback Tony Carter to a recurring knee and
ankle sprain and the loss of his backup, rookie Chris Floyd, and
the likely loss of quarterback Drew Bledsoe to a fractured index
finger on his throwing hand that finally has had it after the pins
that were inserted to stabilize it began to do the hula by the end
of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the Patriots will fight the Niners and the hated Jets the
following weekend, but some things are not meant to be. No matter
how broad your shoulders are there are burdens no one can carry,
and the loss of Glenn, and, effectively if not literally, Bledsoe
coupled with other losses they already were struggling with will
overwhelm their dreams and all their efforts between now and the
end of this long, sad season.
</P>
<P>
   What team could lose its two best offensive players and its two
best defensive players _ as New England now has with linebacker Ted
Johnson and defensive end Willie McGinest already sidelined along
with Glenn and Bledsoe _ and muddle through to the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   Could the Vikings win without Randy Moss and Randall Cunningham
and John Randle and Dwayne Rudd? Could the Broncos win without John
Elway and Terrell Davis and Bill Romanowski and Neil Smith? How
well would the Jets do without Vinny Testaverde and Keyshawn
Johnson and Aaron Glenn and Mo Lewis? We know what happens to
Atlanta when just quarterback Chris Chandler goes out, so in their
case we don't have to add any other suspects, although throw in a
limping Jamal Anderson and see how you like their chances.
</P>
<P>
   If New England had amassed a big lead in its division maybe it
could survive what has happened, but it has no lead in its
division. What the Patriots have is a hold on fourth place,
trailing the Jets, Dolphins, and Bills. They have a team that fell
again to two games off the lead with two to play, which means they
have no margin for error anymore, no matter what their competitors
do.
</P>
<P>
   They must do only one thing to survive. They must find ways to
win with a team broken at its strongest places and even then they
have to hope there are enough wild-card options to keep them alive.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the way it was supposed to be this season, but then
again Bledsoe wasn't supposed to break his finger, and Glenn wasn't
supposed to break his ankle, and Johnson wasn't supposed to tear
his biceps, and McGinest wasn't supposed to pop his groin, and all
the other players who are important in their own way even if less
noticed weren't supposed to be limping and sore either.
</P>
<P>
   But they did and they are, and so whether you like it or not,
Duke, the sky is falling in Foxborough even if everything's bright
and shiny on Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The momentum we worked so hard to build the last month has
taken a big hit,'' coach Pete Carroll said. ``We made it so hard on
ourselves. The opportunity we let slip away ... the opportunity to
get back on top of our division. We had a chance to do that by
winning today and winning out. I don't know if we'll have that
opportunity again. It's out of our hands now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a major hit right here. But we don't have the freedom
to give in to it. That's not available to us. What is important to
us at this point is that we have to come back and fight these last
two weeks and get everything we can get out of this season and see
what happens at the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   What will happen is that it will end with a whimper, not a bang.
It will end in sad defeat, not glorious victory, and it will end
soon because there really is no other option left.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are out of players and out of time. In their
hearts, even they know that now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all sounds good to say other guys have to step up but face
it,'' said linebacker Chris Slade, who has been playing hurt much
of this season himself. ``You gotta go with your best guys to win
for long, and where are our best guys?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to say we're going to play with the other guys, but
injuries are a big part of this game and who wins in it. It's gonna
be tough now. We'll see what this team is made of now.''
</P>
<P>
   What they are made of at the moment are guys on crutches, and
guys in slings, and guys in casts, and guys in splints, and guys in
the tub. They are a broken army of game warriors under siege who
simply have sustained too many casualties to hold out much longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
