<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL_FINANCES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL HEADED FOR BREAK DOWN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ No one is coming out and openly saying it, but many
baseball executives quietly believe the game is headed toward an
Armageddon of sorts that will make the last work stoppage, one that
included the cancellation of the World Series, seem like nothing.
</P>
<P>
   `` Baseball America'' magazine assembled a discussion group
during the winter meetings Sunday afternoon to address some of
those problems, highlighted by the growing disparity between clubs
with money and those without.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks managing general partner Jerry Colangelo, one of
the six panelists, said he fully understands the economic problems
that exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that disparity is a problem,'' Colangelo said.
``But I can't solve that problem. I shouldn't be looked at alone as
the problem. It should be the ten or eleven teams that are spending
that should be looked at. I don't think anyone really has an answer
as to how to rectify what's happening. I'm willing to listen,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, recently hired as an executive vice president in
the commissioner's office, is a strong and vocal opponent to the
growing size of contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The annual summer draft was discussed as a microcosm of the
game's dilemmas. It's no secret that small-market clubs, those that
are supposed to benefit most from the draft, must think before
taking the best players.
</P>
<P>
   With the way signing bonuses for the top picks have skyrocketed
in recent years, there is no way some small-market clubs can afford
to pay the going rate.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, those clubs wind up taking a less-talented player who
won't command the $10 million or so bonuses that J.D. Drew and
Travis Lee have received in recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The draft is supposed to allocate talent evenly,'' Alderson
said. ``That's not happening now.''
</P>
<P>
   One topic that seems to have growing interest within the game's
inner circle is the advent of the world-wide draft, similar to the
NBA and NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Players not residing in the United States, Canada or Puerto Rico
are the only ones currently eligible to the draft. All others are
free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The belief among baseball officials is that such a draft will
help even the playing field between the richest clubs and one at
the other end. Suddenly, players such as ``El Duque'' Hernandez,
who was signed by the Yankees as a free agent because he defected
from Cuba, would be subject to the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The way it stands now, the Yankees have received their own first
round draft picks the last two years, plus pitchers Hernandez and
Hideki Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   `What works about sports is not knowing the outcome of the
game,'' Detroit General Man ager Randy Smith said. ``As soon as
that happens, there is no game. We're quietly approach ing that
level.''
</P>
<P>
   And that has a lot of people in the game worried. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 0148EST &QL; 
