<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-RAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS SPIRITLESS IN ST. LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ There hadn't been so much excitement in St. Louis
since Mark McGwire hit No. 70. There hadn't been so much despair in
New England since ... well ... the last time the Patriots lost a
big game they should have won.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got our asses whipped,'' summed up Todd Collins quite
efficiently following Sunday's 32-18 thumping of the Patriots by
the 4-10 St. Louis Rams. ``We got beat at every phase of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Chris Slade called his teammates ``flat,''
quarterback Drew Bledsoe said that maybe he needs to sit one out,
and coach Pete Carroll confirmed that the team may have to reassess
Bledsoe's playing status next week vs. the 49ers after the pins
that were implanted at Massachusetts General Hospital Tuesday did
not stabilize the finger, as had been the hope.
</P>
<P>
   WBZ Television's Steve Burton stated on ``Fifth Quarter'' that
team doctors and Bledsoe have decided that he will ``shut it down
next week'' against San Francisco, but team spokesman Stacey James
would not confirm that Sunday night, adding doctors rarely say a
week ahead of time whether a player will suit up.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who fell to 8-6, still control their own destiny.
If they beat San Francisco next week and the Jets in the
regular-season finale, they will be in the playoffs at 10-6. The
Patriots hold the head-to-head tie-breaker with Tennessee, which
also could finish 10-6.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe missed about five minutes of the game spanning the end
of the first quarter and the start of the second while in the
locker room having doctors fiddle with the pins and resplint the
finger.
</P>
<P>
   But the quarterback, whose first-quarter interception led to a
Rams touchdown and a quick 10-0 deficit, never really got his
rhythm back. Nor did the rest of the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Lovett Purnell, who replaced Ben Coates at tight end, said
Bledsoe's throws were ``tailing off to the left.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe completed only 11 of 35 passes for 176 yards, with one
touchdown and one interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the game, the pins started pushing through to the
other side of my fingers,'' Bledsoe said. ``They were poking
through my skin from the other side. We numbed it up, pushed it
back, and I came back in. It was really painful.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, wide receiver Terry Glenn fractured his right ankle in the
second quarter and is out for the season, joining Ted Johnson, who
was lost for the year last week against the Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's ankle was crunched by Todd Lyght when he tried to come
down with a pass on a third-and-15 situation.
</P>
<P>
   With Bledsoe's throws going wild, Glenn out, and Coates
attending his mother's funeral in South Carolina, the Patriots
needed to establish a running game.
</P>
<P>
   They did in a way, with rookie Robert Edwards gaining 196 yards
on 24 carries. He busted loose for runs of 53, 47, 36, and 21 yards
on quick hits off tackle, but he was stuffed when short yardage was
needed.
</P>
<P>
   The first time came early in the second quarter, when Edwards
was stopped for no gain on a third-and-1 from the St. Louis 4-yard
line. After Bledsoe returned, he handed off to Edwards, who was
knocked back for a 1-yard loss, and the Patriots turned the ball
over.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, Edwards, who had run up the middle for a
21-yard gain to the Rams' 2, failed on three attempts to get the
ball in, and the Patriots had to settle for an Adam Vinatieri field
goal that put them up for the first time, 18-17, with 7:49
remaining in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't execute well enough to win the game,'' said Carroll.
``It looks like we ran the ball well because we got some big hunks
of yardage, but when we needed the yards at the goal line, we
couldn't get them. Having to settle for a field goal ... we should
have knocked it in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win, you have to play well. Why didn't we play well? These
guys were jacked up all week. They knew what was at stake. They
were ready to play, but it just didn't happen on the field. The
Rams really mixed it up with their offense and kept us off-balance.
Drew had problems throwing it and I think it's clear what Ben
Coates means to our offense.''
</P>
<P>
   On backup quarterback Scott Zolak's first play, with the
Patriots trailing, 10-3, Zolak dropped back and got drilled by Ray
Agnew, forcing a fumble that was recovered at the Patriots' 11 by
the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   That play didn't lead to points, as a bad hold caused a botched
field goal attempt and gave the Patriots the ball at their 11.
</P>
<P>
   A 41-yard field goal by Vinatieri made it 10-6, but the Rams,
now guided by backup quarterback Steve Bono after Tony Banks
suffered a season-ending knee injury in the first quarter, took
over at their 38 and scored on a June Henley 1-yard run with 4:02
remaining in the second quarter to go up, 17-6. The big play was a
20-yard interference penalty on Steve Israel in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   After the Patriots went three and out, as Glenn got hurt, Henry
Thomas sacked Bono, knocking the ball out of his hands; it was
picked up by Chad Eaton at the Rams' 26.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards accounted for 10 yards on the ground before Bledsoe,
rolling to his right, spotted Purnell in the right corner of the
end zone for 6 points. The Patriots, trailing, 17-12, elected to go
for 2, but Bledsoe's pass intended for Mike Bartrum was knocked
down.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots tried a field goal attempt of 55 yards with 25
seconds remaining in the half. Vinatieri made it with room to
spare, tying Matt Bahr for the longest field goal in team history.
</P>
<P>
   After the Patriots went ahead, 18-17, in the third quarter, Bono
struck on two long passes, then rookie receiver Az-Zahir Hakim
executed a reverse to perfection, taking it around right end to the
end zone from 34 yards out. That was followed by Bono's sneak for a
2-point conversion, making it 25-18.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, punting from his goal line, Tom Tupa, arguably one
of the best in the league, shanked one 18 yards to the New England
33. Henley eventually got in from the 1 to give the Rams the 32-18
lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
