<HEADLINE>
TOBIN'S 4TH DOWN CALL SURPRISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Coach Vince Tobin knows he went against
conventional wisdom when he bypassed a chip-shot field goal early
in the third quarter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had a fourth and 1 at the Eagles' 11 yard line
with the game tied at 10.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of sending Chris Jacke out to break the tie with a field
goal, Tobin went for it on fourth down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had a good chance to pick up the first down,''
Tobin said. ``The way the first half had gone, I felt we were going
to to need points.''
</P>
<P>
   But running back Mario Bates was stuffed for a 6-yard loss, and
Tobin's decision could have come back to haunt the Cardinals had
they not rallied to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you're a head coach and make those type of decisions,
that might happen,'' Tobin said. ``That's the nature of the
business. You have to live with those decisions and do what's best
for your team.''
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't it have been best for the team to try to take a
13-10 lead?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be able to get 1 yard,'' quarterback Jake Plummer
said. ``We have to respond. I know I want that play back. Their
defense was so overloaded on one side, I should have called
timeout. If I kept it, I might have walked in.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Gift touchdown &QL; 
 &QL; 
It took until the 14th game to finally get a defensive touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals entered the game with an NFL-high 32 takeaways,
but they had no scores until safety Tommy Bennett ended the first
quarter by scoring on a 70-yard interception return.
</P>
<P>
   The play came on a zone blitz, and Eagles quarterback Koy Detmer
threw it right to Bennett, who could have walked in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought they were going to throw a quick pass to the
end (Karl Hankton),'' Bennett said. ``I didn't want to make that
much of a move and stay home. I recognized the formation they were
in and dropped back. I made the read, waited for him to throw the
ball and baited him. He (Detmer) threw it right into my arms.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good timing &QL; 
 &QL; 
At halftime, defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis made a significant
adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   He went to a five-man defensive front after the Eagles' Duce
Staley had rushed for 118 yards and a score in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give the coaches credit,'' defensive end Simeon
Rice said of the halftime switch. ``It was a good change of pace.
We showed something different, and it took them time to get
adjusted. Actually, they never really did get adjusted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, who had 122 yards in the first half, gained only 26
yards on the ground after intermission. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Short shot &QL; 
 &QL; 
Plummer was in position to throw the final block on what could have
been an 83-yard touchdown by running back Adrian Murrell in the
first quarter. Murrell gained 32 yards on the play when Plummer
missed the block on safety Brian Dawkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had a good angle on him,'' Plummer said. ``But he
just sped up. I was trying to cut him. Maybe I should have tried to
just get into him and hold him up. But I've never done much
blocking, maybe only 10 or 12 times in my career.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Staff writer Lee Shappell contributed to this article. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
