<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-PLUMMER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAKE PICKS SPOTS  
 MAKES BIG PLAYS IN CRUCIAL SITUATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ This wasn't shaping up as the dominating day that
many believed the Cardinals would need from quarterback Jake
Plummer to beat Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive fronts of both teams were badly nicked by
injuries. It appeared the Cardinals, playing for a playoff spot,
would have to outscore the Eagles, who were playing for nothing
except to avoid being hit by decaying fruit hurled by irate fans.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the way, Plummer did not dominate an Eagles defense that
appeared determined not to let him. Then, Plummer made two big pass
plays to Rob Moore in the drive for the game-winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer had been equally erratic in a 23-19 loss the previous
week to the New York Giants, suffering two interceptions and a
fumble as the offense got only three points on three trips inside
the Giants 10-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't much more effective here, the difference being that
Plummer saved his few big plays for the most opportune times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done it all year,'' said Plummer. ``When our backs are
against the wall, we gather around each other and tend to make
things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, a 30-yard pass play to Moore on the second play in
overtime, followed three plays later by a perfectly executed fade
pattern to Moore against a blitz that covered 16 yards to the
Eagles 23. That set up Chris Jacke for the game-winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer acknowledged he was delighted to be in that position
during an afternoon in which he:
</P>
<P>
   Overthrew Frank Sanders, who was open in the end zone, and the
Cardinals had to settle for a field goal on their opening drive
after reaching the Eagles 10.
</P>
<P>
   Took a sack that moved the Cardinals out of field-goal range on
a third-down on the second series, forcing a punt.
</P>
<P>
   Underthrew Moore, streaking down the right sideline, leading to
an interception in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Took a third-down sack from the Eagles 27 in the third when he
had time to dump the ball, again taking the team out of field goal
range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was up and down,'' Plummer said of his 18 of 26 passing for
234 yards and a touchdown. ``I could have made some better throws.
But they weren't giving us much in the passing game. We didn't do
what we wanted to offensively. We only had 17 points in regulation,
and seven of those were by our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer said the Eagles dropped a safety deep in zone coverage
and took big-play opportunities from receivers. But, it helped open
the running game for Adrian Murrell (season-high 174 rushing yards)
as the Cardinals rolled to 424 total yards, topped this season only
by 480 in a home loss to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still had too many missed opportunities in the red zone,
just like last week,'' Plummer said. ``Any time you're within range
of scoring points, you've got to capitalize.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer came up big when he had to, though, including
three-for-three passing and a touchdown to Moore that tied the game
at 17 with 8:14 left, and then the passes to Moore in overtime that
positioned the team to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of our offensive line, and their great job of
protection,'' Plummer said. ``Everybody stepped it up at crunch
time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
