<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-WINTER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS PULL OUT OF BIDDING FOR CLEMENS 
</HEADLINE>
 MEETINGS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ There will be no homecoming for Roger Clemens in
Houston. And for the first time since Clemens demanded a trade from
Toronto, Blue Jays general manager Gord Ash conceded that Clemens
still could be with the Blue Jays at the start of next season.
</P>
<P>
   Astros GM Gerry Hunsicker took the highly unusual step of
calling a press conference Sunday to announce that his club,
``absolutely stunned and frankly outraged'' by the contract demands
imposed by Clemens's agents, has withdrawn from the bidding for the
five-time Cy Young Award winner.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros bowed out after hearing this ``mind-boggling''
proposal from Clemens's agents, Alan and Randy Hendricks: Clemens,
due to be paid $16.1 million in the two remaining years of his
contract with the Blue Jays, reportedly asked for a one-year
extension of $27.4 million, which would push his earnings the next
three years to $43.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   That averages to $14.5 million a year, which would make him
second to Kevin Brown, who will average $15 million a year under
the terms of his seven-year, $105 million deal signed Saturday with
the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money for us is prohibitive,'' Hunsicker said. ``There's
absolutely no way we can accommodate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This industry has some serious problems, especially with the
lunacy we've seen in regard to the escalation of salaries. It will
put some clubs out of business. Already, many clubs can't
compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker said Clemens's demands came unsolicited by Houston
from the Hendrickses in a phone call Saturday to Astros owner
Drayton McLane. ``If we had known this going in, we wouldn't have
had one conversation'' with the Blue Jays about a trade, Hunsicker
said. ``It was implied to us (by the Blue Jays) that it was not an
issue with us. This caught us off-guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker said the Astros refuse to restructure a contract as a
condition to making a deal, but claimed that the Hendrickses
informed the team there would be no deal without a restructuring,
and that Clemens had veto power over any deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to have it both ways,'' Hunsicker said. ``They
want to treat him as if Roger was a free agent and pay him
accordingly, and also give up a package of talent commensurate with
acquiring a player of his caliber.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has told Toronto that he wanted to be traded to a team
closer to his home, and a contender. Asked if Clemens's demands
suggested that what he really wants is more money, Hunsicker said:
``You can draw your own conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays have been soliciting two or three players that are
big-league ready from the teams interested in Clemens, who won 20
or more games in both of his seasons with Toronto. Originally, Ash
said, there were 12-14 teams that made inquiries, including the Red
Sox, according to GM Dan Duquette, who said he made an offer last
week.
</P>
<P>
   That list is down to a handful of clubs, believed to include the
Rangers, Angels, Rockies, and Indians, with the Yankees, as ever,
lurking on the periphery. The Astros, with Clemens living in the
Houston suburb of Katy, looked like an ideal match. They were
defending NL Central Division winners, and had quality players to
offer Toronto in return.
</P>
<P>
   But that scenario blew up Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned for an industry in which more and more people
try to extract the last nickel out of the system,'' Hunsicker said.
``One-upmanship is what it is. We're not in position to compete
with some of this madness.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as Dodgers GM Kevin Malone justified Brown's signing
Saturday by saying that if the Dodgers didn't give him $105
million, someone else would have, Clemens still had his suitors.
Sunday night, Rangers officials met with the Brothers Hendricks.
</P>
<P>
   Ash had said initially that he wanted a trade before the winter
meetings. Then he said he wanted to make a deal before the meetings
end Tuesday. Now? ``This is a no-lose situation for us,'' he said.
``If we trade Roger Clemens, or we don't trade Roger Clemens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 0151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7988 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-MURRELL     12-14 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-MURRELL-AZR </SLUG>
  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Christmas gift-buying season is upon us, and
what better for that special person on the list than something that
slices and dices, and makes small work of the biggest jobs?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Bill Bidwill and the Cardinals, they don't have
to sit and hope they find it under the tree. They traded for it
last off-season, and all it cost them was a third-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   There won't be any better deal on the cable TV infomercials than
Adrian Murrell has been for the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, when the Cardinals needed not only to win to stay in
the race for an NFC playoff spot but also to control the ball in
hopes of keeping its battered defense off the field, Murrell rushed
for 174 yards in a 20-17 overtime win over the Eagles. That was his
most since moving west from the New York Jets and the eighth most
ever by a Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   The three-minute edge in time of possession was critical for the
Cardinals (7-7), who with two more wins will be in the playoffs for
the first time since they moved to Arizona. With one more win, they
will equal the most since they've been in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Murrell's performances since missing the Detroit game Nov. 1
because of a calf injury have resembled those of the two-time
1,000-yard rusher that he is.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the season, his gains were more measurable by the inch
when the Cardinals' line was learning how to play with Murrell and
as a unit, and when early deficits caused the Cardinals to throw
instead of run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thought when Mario (Bates, signed as a free agent)
and I joined the team that things were going to change overnight
and we'd suddenly be an effective rushing team,'' Murrell said.
``But the thing you have to remember is that those guys up front
are young. They hadn't played much together, and they certainly
hadn't played with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarely have the Cardinals been in position to hand the ball to a
back 32 times as they did to Murrell at Veterans Stadium, four
carries short of the club record. The magic number for most
featured backs to get into the rhythm of a game is 20 carries, a
plateau Murrell has reached only seven times with his new team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a growth situation like this, that's big,'' he said.
``There have not always been a lot of opportunities for me to get a
feel for them, or vice versa. When the run-pass ratio is lopsided
toward the pass, it is difficult for the guys up front. There's no
doubt the line has gotten better every week. The last four or five
games, we have been able to run the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Murrell is 48 yards from his third straight 1,000-yard season,
537 of those coming in the past six games. With the maturation of
the line, the Cardinals became a serious playoff contender. The
biggest difference is on first down. With Murrell slicing and
dicing, they have faced far fewer third-and-longs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adrian and our line are now in sync,'' center Aaron Graham
said. ``We have found some plays, a group of plays, that give
Adrian the opportunity to cut back and run to daylight . . . When
you give him the whole field, that's when he is at his best.''
</P>
<P>
   Murrell no longer is to be confused with Leeland McElroy, who
contributed to the Cardinals leading the league in rushing plays
for negative yardage last season. Murrell is averaging 4.6 yards a
carry over this six-game break-out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
