<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7994 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      12-14 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' EFFORT HASN'T BEEN CONSISTENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They entered Saturday night's key matchup against
Buffalo riding an eight-game unbeaten streak (6-0-2). As impressive
as that was, what was masked was how often the Bruins were getting
away with a lousy period here, two lousy periods there, and still
coming up with wins and ties.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Sabres, as the saying goes, the emperor wore no
clothes, and the Bruins were dispatched, 4-1, with Buffalo scoring
three times in the first period to go ahead, 3-0. End of game.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps what is most telling is that coach Pat Burns felt it
necessary to warn his goaltender, Byron Dafoe, that he was in for
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat's come to me in a lot of these games right before and
said, `Be ready the first 10 minutes, guys aren't into it,''' said
Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he should be doing that. We're a talented,
fast-skating team and especially at home, we should be jumping the
gun. We should have teams wondering what's going to come out and we
should buzz them. But Pat's usually right. I can't put a finger on
it. We're all trying to figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe was talking about the last three games. Against Vancouver,
the Bruins were fortunate to emerge with a 1-1 tie. Against
Pittsburgh, they were far luckier to beat the Penguins, 2-1.
Against Carolina last Thursday, they escaped with a 3-2 win.They
could have lost any one of those games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat's not happy with us,'' said Dafoe, who skated with his
teammates for 25 minutes early Sunday morning and then was forced
to watch video of the pivotal first period. ``It was a huge game
and we just didn't come out prepared and that has been a bit of a
trend the last few games and I think it finally caught up with us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good time to sit back and figure out why that's
happening because our schedule doesn't get any easier. We've found
ways to win so we kind of take it lightly. After this, we have to
take a look at why it's happening. It's a sellout, it's a big
division game and we're down, 3-0, after the first period. That's
just not our type of hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got Detroit, Ottawa, and Detroit, so it doesn't get any
easier by any means and we'd better be prepared to start every game
coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns's pet peeve during the stretch was how complicated his
skill players were making the game by looking for the perfect pass.
They'd move the puck well during the power play but either nobody
would shoot or the one extra pass would be picked off by the other
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to think we're always going to get away with a
bang-bang offensive flashy play,'' he said. ``You watch (Buffalo's)
goals and there's no bang-bang designed plays. They put the puck to
the net. It's simple. The game of hockey is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's teams are so better prepared defensively that you're
not going to get away with things. We have to get more from our
better players of playing basic hockey. Right now they're not and
that's why we're not getting power-play goals. All of a sudden, it
has to be a bang-bang picture play. You're going to have to pay the
price. That's one of the reasons we're not scoring five-on-five
goals that much.''
</P>
<P>
   What's frustrating for the coach is how well his club played in
the second period, when the outcome had been all but determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all over them, we were behind them, we were hitting
them, but that's the way you're supposed to play,'' said Burns.
``Ken Belanger put the puck in the corner, he chased it, all of a
sudden he was coming out with the puck because they didn't want to
have part of it. That's the way a Boston Bruin team is supposed to
play and that's the way the Boston Bruins team will play.''
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Rob DiMaio, who has been hindered by an ankle injury
he's been playing on since Nov. 3, said it's been the most
frustrating period for him. He said the only thing that has made it
bearable is that the club has been winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few of these games we've gotten lucky,'' he said. ``We
haven't played great. We had good goaltending. We started slow
against Buffalo and we knew if we got behind on that guy (Dominik
Hasek) and that team, that it's tough to come back against. We dug
our own grave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
