<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-GATTI-ROBINSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON, GATTI STAND TOE TO TOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY _ For 19 rounds they had beaten each other up. Now
it was nearly over for Arturo Gatti and Ivan Robinson, but before
they engaged in three last minutes of hell, something had to be
said.
</P>
<P>
   As the bell rang Saturday night to open the 10th and final round
of their terrifyingly terrific rematch at the Mark Etess Arena, the
two neighborhood gladiators walked warily to the center of the ring
and faced each other for several long seconds. Tradition demanded
the two touch gloves, but what had gone on between them over those
19 rounds _ stretched over the course of two fights _ demanded
something more and both bravehearts knew it.
</P>
<P>
   So as their gloves touched Gatti and Robinson spontaneously
leaned toward each other and also touched foreheads. It was a
silent acknowledgement that something had passed between them that
no witness soon would forget, a bond that comes only with the loss
of blood without a loss of heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arturo may have that desperate way about him but he earns your
respect and he gives it when it's due,'' Robinson said after he had
been awarded a unanimous decision that came within a deducted point
from Gatti for a low blow in the eighth round from being declared a
draw. ``That was about respect. We were in a clinch in the sixth
round and he said to me, `You're a champion, man. I love you.' I
was thinking, `I'm beating you up. Why you saying that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night everyone in the crowd of 4,396 except for a judge
named Jean Williams respected what Gatti and Robinson had done. Joe
Pasquale and George Colon gave the nod to Robinson, 95-94, that one
deducted point after two previous warnings from referee Benji
Estevez (and two dozen belt-line blows by Gatti) preventing the
fight from being declared a technical draw. While those cards
accurately reflected what happened, Williams had Robinson a
lopsided 97-92 victor. How that could be in a fight so close many
ringside observers had Gatti winning by a point was difficult to
fathom but easy to overlook because of the nobility of what had
gone on between the two boxers both Saturday night and in their
Aug. 22 fight, which Robinson won by split decision in a war so
fierce the bout has been nominated for fight of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Few men could have taken the punishment Gatti absorbed over
those 10 rounds Saturday night. Fewer still would have stood up to
the pounding to the ribs Robinson faced once Gatti's plight grew
desperate.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Gatti's face would suffer the more obvious damage,
with his left eye bleeding badly and swollen nearly shut, but he
would lose not from the blood on his face but from the ferocity of
that body attack, one so wild and savage that Estevez had little
choice but to deduct a point after Gatti had blasted Robinson so
low it was more likely to cause a thigh bruise than any other
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Arturo was better than in the first fight and he was
dirtier too,'' Robinson (27-2) said. ``I learned the first fight
that when you hurt Arturo it just makes him mad. It makes him dig
deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   That has been Gatti's modus operandi since his career began and
it not only helped make him the International Boxing Federation
junior lightweight champion for a time but also turned him into a
crowd pleaser.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti (29-4) is now on a three-fight losing streak, having been
cut by Angel Manfredy in the first round of their fight in January
so severely the bout was stopped seven rounds later, and twice
losing to Robinson. Each time it seemed it took less to swell
Gatti's face, which began to puff within 90 seconds of Robinson
hitting it with a solid jab and some stinging combinations Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's battle plan had been to stay so busy that Gatti's
face would be forced to surrender. That it would not do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did my best,'' Gatti said. ``I trained really hard. But I
started too late. Ivan is a great defensive fighter. I had a hard
time connecting my punches on him.''
</P>
<P>
   When the last punches had landed _ fittingly a body shot by
Gatti and a straight right hand to the face by Robinson _ it
mattered little who won. The two victories enhanced Robinson's
career to the point where HBO is trying to schedule a lightweight
title fight for him with either IBF champion Shane Mosley or World
Boxing Council titleholder Caesar Bazan, but Gatti lost no luster
from his defeat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
