<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8013 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     12-14 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CLASS ACT' KENNEDY RIGHTFUL RECIPIENT OF GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Subs to fix Seahawk record in ninth graph   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For a split second, Cortez Kennedy thought he'd better
just fall on the football.
</P>
<P>
   It was bouncing on the turf below him, punched loose from the
hands of San Diego rookie/punk quarterback Ryan Leaf, who was
making a desperation appearance at the Kingdome thanks to a Seahawk
defense hell-bent on making the Chargers pay for every rotten thing
the Seahawks have experienced this season.
</P>
<P>
   That is why when Kennedy saw the ball skittering under his giant
feet, his eyes grew huge.
</P>
<P>
   The ball looked as big and juicy as a porterhouse. And Lord
knows how good a steak looks to a 306-pound defensive tackle _
impossible to resist.
</P>
<P>
   So at that very moment, with the Hawks already leading the
Chargers at the start of the fourth quarter and the game gone awry
with interceptions and turnovers, Kennedy thought about falling on
the ball. But then the man called Tez got a better idea.
</P>
<P>
   He decided he was gonna run. Just run, baby, all the way to the
promised land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first touchdown ever, ever in life,'' Kennedy said
after the 38-17 Seahawk win _ a game nearly as hysterical as it was
historical, because quarterbacks Jon Kitna, Craig Whelihan and Leaf
appeared to have read the wrong rule book.
</P>
<P>
   The point of the game is to put the ball into the hands of your
own teammates, not the other guys'.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna was picked off three times, but the Hawks victimized Leaf
and Whelihan seven times _ twice for touchdowns. Then there was the
exclamation point.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's 39-yard touchdown gambol was the 12th Seahawk
touchdown off turnover or kick returns this season, setting an NFL
record.
</P>
<P>
   Tez, his teammates and the chipper Kingdome crowd ate up the
sight of the big man rumbling to glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the greatest feelings in the world,'' Kennedy
said. ``At first I thought (Seahawk corner) Fred Thomas was one of
the Chargers. I thought I'd better put my hand on the ball and fall
down. But then I saw it was Fred, so I turned on a little more
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Speed? Well, not exactly Joey Galloway afterburner stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he ran like he did when he was a senior at the
University of Miami, when he was 26 years old,'' coach Dennis
Erickson joked.
</P>
<P>
   Tez denied a youthful burst of energy: ``I felt like I was about
40 years old. I wasn't meant to run that fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Moon was so concerned he greeted Kennedy at the sideline
with an oxygen tank and mask in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a joke,'' Moon said. ``He needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was determined, though. He has watched all season as his
defensive partners have racked up nearly as many points as the
Seahawk offense. He figured it was his turn to make the highlights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense has been doing it all year,'' Kennedy said. ``I
was just jumping in there with Chad Brown, Sam Adams and the rest
of those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Except there is a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of 11-year veteran Brian Blades, no current Seahawk has
been with the team longer than Kennedy, a six-time Pro Bowler.
</P>
<P>
   No players outside of Blades and Michael Sinclair knows what
it's like to live through a 2-14 season and play though an
ownership shake-up, then to have payroll increased to $65 million
and still come up short, as the Hawks have this season.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Seahawks lost a game to the Jets. Lost, too, was
any realistic shot at the playoffs _ thanks in large part to a
terrible call on Vinny Testaverde's quarterback draw.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was on the line that Sunday. He tripped up Testaverde.
It was Kennedy's tackle and safety Jay Bellamy's crushing hit on
Testaverde that should have sealed the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that bitter taste stayed with us strong and hard all
week,'' Bellamy said. ``We talked about it this week. We talked
about it during our meeting (Saturday night).
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show everyone the way this defense could respond
to a game like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence, all the pass rushes Sunday. All the pressure, all the
picks, and then the exclamation point touchdown run by the
nine-year veteran.
</P>
<P>
   It won't make up for a season gone bust. It won't make it easier
for Erickson to keep his job, though surely the Hawk defense is
showing there is no quit this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could not have been scripted any more perfectly than to
have a class act like Cortez make such a great play worthy of
recognition for the entire team, for the entire defense,''
defensive coordinator Greg McMackin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are going to be remembered for something, it's just
really fitting for it to be Cortez to make the big play. He's been
a class act. When we came here, he was the cornerstone we built our
defense on.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the cornerstone decided to run. What a funny, wonderful,
excellent call.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 0201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
