<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8015 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-DOLPHINS-BOS     12-14 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-DOLPHINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETTING INTO THE PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For a second, but only a second, he allowed himself to
enjoy the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``From 1-15 to the tournament in two years isn't bad,'' said
Jets coach Bill Parcells Sunday night. ``It's great to be in the
playoffs ... but now we've got a real big game in Buffalo
(Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before, Parcells and his Jets had stunned the Miami
Dolphins, 21-16, to gain a playoff spot with two games remaining in
the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   First place in the AFC East will be up for grabs Saturday when
the Jets travel to Buffalo. With a win in either of its two final
games (the Jets finish by hosting the Patriots), New York will win
its division for the first time since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   If they win both, with Jacksonville losing Sunday, the Jets
could wind up with the second-best record in the AFC and get a
first-round bye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vinny Testaverde played a big game for us,'' said Jets wide
receiver Keyshawn Johnson. ``This game was very important to him.
He wanted it bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory really belonged to the Jets' defense, which
pressured Dan Marino like he seldom has been on his home field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knocked him down a lot tonight,'' said Parcells. ``We got
after him all night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets scored on a 12-yard touchdown pass from Testaverde to
Wayne Chrebet, a 9-yard run by Curtis Martin, and a crucial 23-yard
fumble return for a touchdown by linebacker Chad Cascadden.
</P>
<P>
   Miami had just 3 points through the first three periods, a
24-yard field goal by Olindo Mare in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet's grab later in that quarter made it 7-3, Jets, and
Martin's run in the third, on a nifty cutback, made it 14-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran well against them to the outside when we beat them in
New York,'' said Johnson, ``and we had some big plays on the
outside against them tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins scored two fourth-quarter touchdowns, but the last
came with three seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial sequence in the game came in the fourth, with two
minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   New York led, 14-10, but Miami had the ball with a good chance
to go downfield and win. That would have been consistent with the
Jets' history in big games, but they did not cough it up this time.
</P>
<P>
   Marino went back to throw from his 33, and linebacker Cascadden
came up the middle on a blitz. Marino was forced to step up in the
pocket, and when he did, nose tackle Ernie Logan slapped the ball
out of his hands. Cascadden picked the ball up and ran untouched
into the end zone to make the score 21-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset and frustrated,'' said Marino. ``We were playing at
home and we should have won. No doubt we should have won this game.
Offensively, we were horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offensive line was banged up,'' said Miami coach Jimmy
Johnson. ``We had trouble protecting Marino and they did a nice job
with their pass coverages. They are a fine football team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to stop their running game,'' said Jets safety
Corwin Brown, ``and we did. And when they threw the ball we had
good pressure. We wanted to make sure we had coverage on McDuffie
in key situations, because Marino likes to go with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino threw 57 times. He completed 30 passes for 321 yards. But
he turned the ball over twice in the fourth period with an
interception and the fumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in the playoffs,'' said backup quarterback
Glenn Foley. ``Five years in the league, and this will be my first
time in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How come?'' asked punter John Kidd, a newcomer to the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I've been with the Jets my whole career,'' said Foley
with a smile. ``That's why.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
