<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8016 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-OFFENSE-     12-14 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-OFFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH PIECES MISSING, OFFENSE PUZZLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ It was clear after only five minutes of Sunday's
game with the Rams that the Patriots were not prepared _ or had not
been prepared _ to take what should have been theirs, a convincing
win over a doormat team.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll's team would not be able to close what should have
been a most-easy deal, a win over arguably the worst team in the
NFL. That was clear from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about this game,'' said Carroll, ``we knew what the
issues were, you know (the Rams) are a team that is struggling and
you know that we're a team on the rise. We faced all that up, but
we didn't come out to play. This is a hard, hard lesson for us to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was even clearer five minutes after this loss that tossed
away so much of the hard work and confidence-building of the last
three straight wins, that New England's Season of The Injury now
has crossed a threshold that makes any prospects for success in the
playoffs dim. Terry Glenn's broken ankle was in a cast, Drew
Bledsoe's broken finger was so grisly that he admitted, ``Maybe
it's time to sit down now.''
</P>
<P>
   With Bledsoe no longer defying medical science, not knowing
whether his passes were going to a receiver in St. Louis or to a
fan in Kansas City, and with Glenn gone, and opposing defenses no
longer forced to focus on the speedy wide receiver, Carroll's words
after Sunday's debacle were apt, ``We took a major hit right
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Glenn's season-ending injury, Carroll said, ``That's part of
the disappointment. I was talking last week about how we were
getting stronger and we were coming back and then it turns out that
we took a major hit. We took a major hit and we're just going to
have to overcome it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Coates's absence Sunday _ his mother died last week and he
was attending to family matters _ obviously played into the
offensive futility. The absence of New England's defense, with no
apparent excuse, added to this whole surreal day.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Lovett Purnell, who replaced Coates, said Bledsoe's
passes were particularly wayward ``any time he tried to throw to
his left. You could see he was having trouble trying to throw out
to his left. But all of us also could see he showed a lot of
courage.''
</P>
<P>
   As many Patriots have done the last month, but now New England
seems out of healthy bodies for its most important players. When
Glenn went down with his broken ankle late in the first half, said
wide receiver Troy Brown, ``I was praying that it was just a sprain
for Terry. He's been through so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Patriots fans know all too well by now that Glenn is near
irreplaceable ``and I think it's pretty obvious what not having Ben
does to us,'' said Carroll. It's just a fact, the coach went on,
``and we're not making excuses, but Ben is a big-time player that
we count on.''
</P>
<P>
   Coates will be back next week, but Glenn will not. ``It's real
obvious Terry is a great football player when he's out there and he
gives us a dynamic that we don't seem to come up with without him.
I think it's pretty clear that guy does that for us,'' Carroll
said.
</P>
<P>
   He was so unsure of his team that even with the tip of the ball
virtually touching the St. Louis end zone, on a fourth down in the
third quarter, he chose to go for a field goal that gave New
England an 18-17 lead, rather than a fourth try at a touchdown.
Even those 3 points did little to soothe Carroll's soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I didn't feel we were in control with that lead,'' he
said. ``We went ahead, but we went ahead with a field goal. We
should have scored a touchdown there. We didn't take control of the
football game there and they came right back and put it right down
the field on us (for a 25-18 lead).''
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, the Patriots apparently had their best running game
of the season with Robert Edwards gaining 107 yards in the first
quarter alone, 166 by halftime, and 196 (on 24 carries) for the
game. Twice, though, the Patriots could not run the ball in at the
most opportune moment. Edwards foiled on a fourth-and-1 at the Rams
4-yard line on the second play of the second quarter and he was
again stopped an inch or so from the goal line on that
third-quarter drive before Adam Vinatieri's field goal gave the
Patriots the 18-17 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we were running it, we weren't scoring well,''
said Carroll, of his decision to go for 3 points. ``We weren't
running it effectively down there near the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, after the Rams romped 79 yards down the field and
scored on a 34-yard reverse by Az-Zahir Hakim and regained the
lead, the Patriots' offense gave up on the run. A sack of Bledsoe
and two wayward passes preceded a horrible 18-yard shank by the
usually reliable Tom Tupa, and the Rams soon had a another TD.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to use all of our guns,'' said Carroll of the move
away from Edwards (the rookie would carry the ball only once the
rest of the game). ``We just wanted to make sure we used all of our
offense to see if we could get moving faster.''
</P>
<P>
   With Coates absent, with Bledsoe unsure of any pass he threw,
with Glenn gone, the feeling of the last month that New England
could come back from a fourth-quarter deficit just was not there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
