<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE COULDN'T DIG OUT OF EARLY HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ It was a team they should have stopped, especially
after starter Tony Banks was injured in the first quarter and
carted off the field.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots' defense gave up too many big plays in Sunday's
32-18 loss to the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   The defense seemed confused at times by an unorthodox St. Louis
offense that had nothing to lose but a little more self-respect.
Instead, the Patriots allowed the offense to jell from the opening
drive of the game, when the Rams went on a nine-play, 51-yard march
that ended with a 48-yard field goal by Jeff Wilkins. After Drew
Bledsoe threw an interception from the Patriot 15, Banks passed to
Az-Zahir Hakim for 9 yards and the touchdown that made it 10-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough when you go out there and you're down, 10-0,'' said
New England safety Willie Clay. ``Things happen and it's been
tough, but it's over now. You can't really cry about it. We gave
(backup Steve) Bono too much time to throw and guys got open.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks, a restricted free agent after the season who may not be a
part of the Rams' plans next year, injured his left knee on the
second play of the Rams' fourth series when Henry Thomas
bull-rushed left guard Fred Miller into the back of Banks's knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to see a young quarterback who is beginning to do
some things in his career suffer an injury like that,'' said
Thomas, who said a few words to Banks before he was carted off the
field. ``But then Bono came in and just made plays for them. They
did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas called the loss ``definitely disappointing and
heart-wrenching. I'm really out of words right now. What more can I
say?''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas made nine tackles and was credited with all three Patriot
sacks, doing a good job in the middle of the defense. But it's
obvious the Patriots missed Willie McGinest's pass rush and
presence.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas has been playing all season with a sprained right ankle.
Though he got back on the field for the first time in three weeks,
Thomas admitted it hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had (the ankle) shot up and I've played that way for
seven weeks now,'' said Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   With linebacker Ted Johnson gone for the season, Marty Moore,
Todd Collins, and Tedy Bruschi all took turns playing some in the
middle. Moore made only one tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Israel had one interception, but Patriots coach Pete
Carroll said what killed the team were a couple of third-down
conversions. One was a third-and-12 throw from Bono to J.T. Thomas
that went for 21 yards to the Patriots' 34, from where Hakim pulled
off a scoring run on a reverse, and the other came earlier in that
go-ahead drive when Bono hit Hakim on a third-and-9 for a 13-yard
gain to the 47.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we stop them on those it could be a different game,'' said
Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Rams converted 36 percent of their third-down
chances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
