<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8018 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HOLLEYCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-14 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS RAN INTO TROUBLE AT TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Robert Edwards had a conversation with himself
Sunday. It was a pleasant exchange. It took place at the Trans
World Dome, during halftime of the Patriots-Rams game. After having
part of the dialogue revealed to me, I am convinced of a couple of
things:
</P>
<P>
   1. The football gods clearly socialize with the gods who are
known for irony and role reversal.
</P>
<P>
   2. It is obvious that a statement can be simultaneously true and
false.
</P>
<P>
   After running for 166 yards in one half against the Rams,
Edwards jogged toward the Patriots locker room and told himself,
``They can't stop us.'' He was telling the truth. He was talking
about the way St. Louis defenders often stood as if they were
blue-and-gold safety cones, letting Edwards weave through them with
no resistance. He touched the ball 14 times and averaged 11 yards
each time he touched it. He was the man. He was the bomb. He was
literally old school, running on the Rams like no one had since Jim
Brown in 1957 (237 yards) and Steve Van Buren in '49 (196). He was
in his own sphere, a man juking and cutting on his own planet. As
they like to yelp on TV, ``He could go all the way ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Well, hold it right there. That was one of the problems. Edwards
ran all over the dome's tough carpet. But he could not go all the
way. He had a 53-yard run and a 47-yard run in one half. He had 117
yards in the first quarter. The last time he ran like that in such
a short time was ``probably against Tennessee. I only played two
quarters that game.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be the Tennessee Volunteers of the Southeastern
Conference, not the Tennessee Oilers of the NFL. So this was a
professional breakout for Edwards. But this is why his true
statement was also false: He ran for 196 yards and averaged 8.2
yards a touch, but he often found hell when he tried to gain only 1
yard. Indeed, the Rams could stop him because he could not score.
</P>
<P>
   On the same drive that Edwards ran for 53 yards, the Patriots
kicked a field goal. On the drive that he ran for 47 yards, the
Patriots had to punt. In the third quarter, Edwards ran up the
middle of the field for 21 yards. He got all the way to the 1. The
ball was nearly kissing the goal line. All Edwards had to do was
slip, seemingly, and he would fall in the end zone. It didn't
happen. He ran toward the Ram defenders who had seemed so passive
before and found out that they were suddenly inspired and excited.
The Patriots kicked another field goal. The Patriots eventually
lost, 32-18.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, the football gods live in a neighborhood that has a
warped sense of humor. Patriot fans have been praying all season
for a running game. They have pointed to a weak rushing attack that
came into Sunday ranked last in the league. They have recited
football cliche, saying something about playoff teams only being
successful when they are able to run the ball. Last week, the
Patriots scarcely had a running game, but still had enough for
Edwards to score and the team to win by 14. Sunday, the gods gave
them a running game. And a 14-point loss.
</P>
<P>
   Across the field from Edwards, a young back named June Henley
was running for the Rams. Edwards had more than twice as many yards
as Henley. He also had twice the yards-per-carry average. But
Henley had two more touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you told me that I'd have that many yards before the game,
I would think that we would be in a pretty good situation,''
Edwards said. He knows they are not in a good situation now. They
lost to a team playing without its starting quarterback, usual
starting running back, and star receiver. They lost to a team that
had won only three of its 13 previous games.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are 8-6 and could easily win their final two games
of the season, against the 49ers and Jets. They also could lose
them and watch the playoffs just like the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're not done yet,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   No, they aren't done. They are simply men who now know how
strange life can look when oddities crash into expectations:
</P>
<P>
   You begin to expect Edwards not to run well, but one day he does
run well and the team loses;
</P>
<P>
   You begin to expect (and hope) that Terry Glenn will not have
hamstring problems, so one day he is not bothered by a hamstring
but is hobbled by a broken right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   You begin to expect the Patriots to shuffle the cornerback
opposite Ty Law, but Steve Israel begins to play very well, like
the man Pete Carroll saw in San Francisco ... and, instead, the
Patriots shuffle middle linebackers when they lose Ted Johnson for
the season.
</P>
<P>
   People like Woody Allen have made movies about bizarre
situations like this. And people like the Patriots _ moviegoers _
have laughed about life's absurdities as they appear on the screen.
But this is no film. It is the Patriots' season. It may be the
story of a team that lost its playoff chances during a Sunday in
St. Louis. That's certainly odd. But it's not funny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
