<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE PUT FINGER ON PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Drew Bledsoe didn't have to see a hand specialist to
know his fractured finger had deserted him Sunday. He just had to
see his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was warming up behind the Patriots' bench with just over
five minutes to play in the first quarter of a game the St. Louis
Rams already were leading when familiar discomfort suddenly turned
into alarming discouragement.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden things were moving inside his index finger.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, things that weren't supposed to be moving were
moving.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, things that were supposed to be anchors had
begun to float and because of it his team had begun to sink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to take some throws and I felt the pins (that had been
surgically inserted Tuesday to shore up the double fracture) poking
at the skin from the other side,'' Bledsoe said, not long after the
Rams had poked a hole in the Patriots' playoff chances with a
surprising 32-18 victory at the Trans World Dome that dropped them
to 8-6 and back into fourth place in the AFC East.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't where they had been. They weren't where they were
supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon neither was Bledsoe. With his team ready to go onto the
field, he rushed to the locker room from behind the bench to have
the pins pushed back into place. Once done, a needle was inserted
and more pain killer was pumped into a finger that was already so
high it should have belonged to a junkie, not a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   That done, Bledsoe headed back to the field, but before he could
get there he saw a golf cart in a hallway under the stands and Rams
quarterback Tony Banks laid out on the back of it.
</P>
<P>
   As one game continued on the field without them, another was
unfolding under the stands as Bledsoe ran down to console Banks,
who had torn the medial collateral ligament in his knee only
minutes after Bledsoe had left the field.
</P>
<P>
   There they stood, the starting quarterbacks of the Patriots and
Rams in full battle gear, both infirm, both in pain, both watching
while their teams played without them. This was the side of
football few people ever see, the broken warriors standing in the
echoes as their teams fight on without them.
</P>
<P>
   After exchanging brief words with Banks and patting him on the
wrist, Bledsoe ran back down the hallway and out onto the field,
but by the time he came back the omens were mounting against his
team. Scott Zolak had replaced him and been knocked flat on his
back on his first play and the ball went flying. When it was
finally scooped up by Grant Wistrom, it belonged to the Rams at the
Patriots 11 and all seemed to be slipping away from a team that has
been running uphill for two months now.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams would not score in part because it was two plays later
that Banks went out, but nothing was the same for New England after
that because the underpinnings of Bledsoe's fractured finger had
come loose and so had the underpinnings of his team's playoff
hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe quickly was reinserted in the lineup not long after
Banks's replacement, Steve Bono, also fumbled at the Rams 13. New
England would take four cracks at the St. Louis defense from there,
each time handing off to running back Robert Edwards. On the fourth
one, Bledsoe came back in the game but he was not asked to throw
and Edwards was stopped a yard short of a first down. Four plays,
no passes, no points. And so it went.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew had some problems with his finger again,'' Patriots coach
Pete Carroll said at the conclusion of one of the worst statistical
days of Bledsoe's career, a day when he went 11 for 35, was sacked
four times, threw one interception, and might have thrown several
more if the Rams could catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell by the way the ball was flying that it wasn't
flying as good as normal. Your play falls off because the guys you
need aren't there. There's no mystery to it. Our playmakers weren't
all there and all the pressure went on Drew and he was in a bad
way. When his ball wobbles play after play, you know he doesn't
have the control he usually does.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed he did not and it showed when his team needed him most.
Down the stretch, as the Patriots were trying to come back from a
two-touchdown deficit, Bledsoe went 5 for 17. By then the pins in
his finger were sliding around like toddlers on ice skates and he
simply could not control them or the ball, especially when he would
try to throw to his left.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell he was gutting it out,'' receiver Troy Brown
said. ``A lot of plays he used to make with ease were difficult for
him. He told me he couldn't throw to his left and for me to stay on
the right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see where he had the pins pushing out. His velocity
and accuracy both suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   So did his team. Although Bledsoe played on, he was a sprinter
with a bad foot. A color-blind painter. A mason without a trowel.
Damaged goods.
</P>
<P>
   There was no way he could do his work properly by the end and
when it was over even he seemed to accept that for the first time
after the doctors had worked on the finger again in the trainer's
room and told him the situation had worsened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very good,'' Bledsoe admitted. ``Maybe it's time to
sit down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be time to reassess things after today,'' Carroll said.
``The doctors indicated there may be further problems.'' In fact,
Channel 4's Steve Burton stated on ``Fifth Quarter'' that Bledsoe
and team doctors have decided he will sit out Sunday against San
Francisco, although team spokesman Stacey James would not confirm
it Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   That a change in Bledsoe's situation may be needed was obvious
after Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
