</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GLENN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, GLENN IS DONE FOR GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Instead of happiness and joy and a family reunion
and a Patriots victory, Terry Glenn was absolutely where he most
dreaded to be a few minutes after New England lost so miserably to
St. Louis Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn was sitting on a pile of boxes in a hallway of the Trans
World Dome, his ankle in a cast, crutches leaning against a wall,
his heart in his feet, his soul searching for the whys of this most
unlucky of seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to be out there on the field to help the
chances of our team to win,'' said Glenn, head down more. ``It just
seems that things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   This time it was the injury _ a broken ankle _ that breaks the
spirit as well as the bone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let myself down,'' said the wide receiver. ``But more than
that, I let the whole organization down, including the players,
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   By suffering a broken ankle?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're counting on me to make plays,'' said Glenn, who broke
the ankle with 3:09 left in the first half, on a third-and-15 pass
from Drew Bledsoe. ``But I'm not out ... I mean, we got guys who
can make plays, but when I'm out there, I'm just an extra guy that
can make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   At about this same moment, June Henley was in the locker room of
the Rams, unaware of any of this. And his parents, Charles and Mary
Henley, also the ``parents'' of Glenn, also were unaware of Glenn's
plight, but even more poignantly so.
</P>
<P>
   Henley and Glenn had grown up together in Columbus, Ohio, and
when life's cruel fortune had sent Glenn to the streets after his
mother was murdered, June Henley and his parents took the
13-year-old Glenn into their home and raised him. Sunday was
supposed to be the grandest of reunions, Glenn starring for the
Patriots on the same field as Henley, making his first start at
running back for the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   The two had met on the field before the game ``and I hadn't seen
Terry in months,'' said Henley. ``We talked before the game but it
wasn't about the game. We were just so glad to see each other. It
was a joy.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Glenn was down on the field for long minutes, Henley
hoped for the best. Then, ``I saw him walking off the field,''
Henley said of his ``brother,'' and ``I just thought it was an
ankle sprain.''
</P>
<P>
   But Glenn's ankle was broken, Henley was told. ``Wow ... that's
a bad thing any time you get hurt,'' Henley said. ``I feel bad
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the St. Louis locker room, the feelings were worse. Mary
Henley said, ``When I saw Terry go down, it took everything out of
me. I haven't recovered yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Henleys were notified by the Rams to go to Section 118 ``and
we went there as they said,'' said Charles Henley, wearing a New
England jersey with the number ``88'' on it and the name ``Glenn''
stitched across the back. ``But no one was there. The people down
there told us someone was looking for us,'' but the Henleys never
could make connections so they could see Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they called me, we didn't know where to go,'' said Mary
Henley. ``We never did get to see Terry.'' And both parents went
on, saying they ``were happy June was doing good,'' as Mary Henley
put it, ``but when I saw Terry get hurt, I knew he was in
trouble,'' as Charles Henley put it.
</P>
<P>
   And there, in that hallway across the way, Terry Glenn sat on
those boxes, his crutches and his cast as companions instead of his
parents and brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things were seeming to go in our favor there for a while,''
said Glenn, who had played well the last four weeks since returning
from a hamstring injury. ``But this is hard ... I don't know what
to say anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing he can do, said Glenn, ``is to go home and think
of this situation that occurred and hopefully I can come back
stronger and try it all over again. I mean, that's the only thing
that I really can do.''
</P>
<P>
   In this Season Of The Injury for the Patriots, the injury to
Glenn Sunday was so painfully deja vu, occurring almost exactly the
same as the ankle injury wide receiver Troy Brown suffered six
weeks ago. Even more, said Brown, the pattern Glenn ran Sunday
``was very similar'' to the pattern Brown was running when he got
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember I was going for the ball and somebody was on
my back,'' said Glenn. ``And that guy started bringing me down even
before I really had the ball. And I guess his knee or something
went down on my ankle ... sort of the same thing that happened to
Troy Brown. The exact same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Glenn was finally on his feet, and finally had limped to
the sideline, a tableau ensued that described so much of what these
injures had done to Glenn's heart. Glenn insisted on standing near
the team bench, even as team doctors were insisting that he head to
the locker room for X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn would not go. Then, as Patriot officials called for the
medical cart to transport Glenn to the locker room, he still would
not move.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept telling me I had to go into the locker room to get
X-rays,'' said Glenn, ``but I really didn't want to. I wanted to be
out there on the field to help the chances of our team to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, said Glenn, ``I was in denial ... greatly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 0211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8023 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-TUPA-BOS     12-14 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-TUPA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY THINGS WENT ASTRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ It was the worst series of the day and Tom Tupa just
happened to put the exclamation point on it. It's OK. You could say
that to the Patriot punter's face and he wouldn't disagree with
you. Just don't ask him to explain the science of an 18-yard
blunder.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa will tell you that nothing profound happened at the Trans
World Dome. He tried to kick the football from his 15-yard line
with four minutes remaining in the third quarter. The Patriots
trailed the Rams at the time, 25-18. A typical Tupa punt would have
traveled more than 40 yards. This was atypical. It wobbled badly
toward the right sideline. Distance: 18 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``It went off the side of my foot,'' Tupa explained. ``You can
put that on the list of things that went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Tupa's punt, the Patriots were having a miserable series.
Drew Bledsoe was sacked for a 9-yard loss and had incompletions
intended for Robert Edwards and Tony Simmons. Next was Tupa's
18-yarder. The Rams needed only five plays (and 60 seconds) to make
things worse. They got a touchdown from running back June Henley,
his second of the day, and led by 14 over the dazed New Englanders.
They would win the game, 32-18.
</P>
<P>
   Some people will wonder if Tupa, a very good punter, had some
type of miscommunication with his teammates. Was the snap high? Was
the crowd noise a distraction? Were his shoes slippery? Was there a
defender in his face who caused confusion?
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Nothing like that. Just a bad punt. Very bad, in fact.
Probably his worst of the year. ``Oh, by far,'' Tupa said of the
worst-punt-of-the-season suggestion. On most days, he receives the
ball cleanly, kicks it cleanly, and walks off the field content. He
couldn't even do that Sunday. A few minutes after his 18-yarder,
Tupa had to come back and kick again. He stood at his 29 and got
off a punt that traveled 60 yards in the air. Unfortunately for
Tupa, the ball came down in the hands of return man Eddie Kennison,
who caught the ball at his 11.
</P>
<P>
   So there was Kennison, dodging Patriots and heading upfield. He
passed the 20. And the 30. And the 40. By that time, there were not
many defenders in his path. The people here, nearly 50,000 of them,
began to get loud with their cheers of anticipation. Only a few men
were in position to tackle Kennison. One of them was Tom Tupa.
Return men like to see that because punters are perceived by many
as associate football players. But Tupa is not that type of punter.
He made the tackle. Had he not, the score would have been 39-18.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa, who is also a talented golfer and basketball player,
likened his punt to a bad golf shot. Sometimes things go astray
without warning. ``I've only had one of these this year,'' Tupa
said. Shortly after saying that, he shrugged and walked out of the
locker room. Some things cannot be explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
