<HEADER>
A8024 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     12-14 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The only sight of Deion Sanders on the Arrowhead
Stadium field was during pre-game warm-ups when he ran some sprints
and tried a few backpedaling drills. Then, it was over to the
sidelines with a sore toe to watch the latest chapter of a season
growing increasingly painful.
</P>
<P>
   The ranks of visiting spectators from Dallas grew by another one
late in the second quarter when Michael Irvin took a shot in the
back from Dale Carter and wound up hobbling off the field like
either a wounded crab or a very old man, both of which would also
describe the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Another season is coming undone like an oversexed presidency,
and for the second straight year for the Cowboys, December
performance has a great deal in common with the celebration of
Christmas in Cuba _ it's nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it was a lifeless 20-17 loss to the Chiefs, and the
big question with the Cowboys is no longer whether they can make it
to the playoffs _ though they have not yet clinched a spot _ but if
they can even make it to the end of the regular season without
falling apart in the street like so much twisted metal and used
bolts.
</P>
<P>
   To find one's way from the happy days when the Cowboys were 8-3
and talking about trying to catch up to Atlanta and Minnesota in
the bid for a first-round playoff bye to the current three-game
losing streak, you simply follow the trail of broken pieces and
loose parts.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Ernie Mills is out for the season following
abdominal surgery, guard Everett McIver was lost to knee surgery,
tight end David LaFleur has a sprained knee, running back Chris
Warren has a groin pull, and now Irvin joins the list. That's just
on offense.
</P>
<P>
   The defense, missing Sanders for the third straight game, was
also without cornerback Kevin Smith, who has a bruised back, and in
his spot had Kevin Mathis, who is wearing a cast on a fractured
forearm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Injuries are a part of the game, and I don't believe in using
them as an excuse,'' said Cowboys coach Chan Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   However, injuries are a reality, and it is also a fact of life
that these Cowboys no longer have the depth that used to set them
apart from the rest of the pack back in the Super Bowl days.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, if one piece of the puzzle was missing, there
was always somebody else to plug into the space. But now, the
Cowboys, even in the best of times, are walking the tightrope
between being a better-than-average team with playoff potential if
all goes right to falling over the edge into non-contending
oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the 8-6 Cowboys are not really sure how good they are
or how far they can go. What's more, they are now only one game up
on 7-7 Arizona in the suddenly re-engaged NFC East race.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the Cowboys have still not beaten a team all year that
has a winning record, and the Chiefs were an underachieving bunch
themselves that did not have to play particularly inspired ball to
win this one.
</P>
<P>
   All it took was for Kansas City coach Marty Schottenheimer to
stop getting fancy and pound the ball down the Cowboys' throat. In
the first half, Chiefs quarterback Rich Gannon threw an ungodly 34
passes and completed only 13, and all that was good for was a 3-3
tie.
</P>
<P>
   After the break, Schottenheimer finally decided to stop trying
to reinvent the wheel and simply handed the ball to Bam Morris. In
the second half, the Chiefs rushed the ball 27 times and threw only
seven passes. Morris looked like a tank rolling through a flower
bed against the Cowboys' defense.
</P>
<P>
   George Teague frequently tried to tackle Morris by grabbing onto
his waist and riding him like a rodeo bull. The result was Teague's
getting constantly thrown. Mathis was bowled over by Morris.
Charlie Williams bounced off Morris like a tenpin being hit by a
bowling ball. These Cowboys were lifeless, maybe heartless, but
mostly helpless.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the time, we were in the right position,'' said
Gailey. ``But we couldn't tackle. You know, you have to be able to
tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   We know. Morris finished the game with 137 yards and a touchdown
on 27 carries, and that meant the Cowboys' offense was going to
have to produce.
</P>
<P>
   After extending its streak without a touchdown to seven straight
quarters, Dallas finally was able to slip into gear in the fourth
period, getting two touchdown passes by Troy Aikman to Patrick
Jeffers and Emmitt Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too little, too late,'' said Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention too little of the front-line talent that can
still win games and make a difference for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   This is looking more and more like one of those ``replacement''
teams left over from the labor strike of 1987. Remember those
unknowns who came from nowhere and only looked like the Cowboys
because they wore the same uniforms and same stars on their
helmets?
</P>
<P>
   For several years now, the Cowboys' offense has searched
desperately for a complementary receiver to Irvin. On Sunday, the
Cowboys needed somebody to be Irvin himself. They had to look to a
couple of guys named Jeffers and Billy Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Michael went out, Billy and I looked at each other and
said, `Well, somebody has to make some plays,''' Jeffers said.
``But you know, it's tough. Michael is such a playmaker. I mean,
that's his name, Playmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Cowboys have too few of them, and the wins are getting
as scarce as Santas in downtown Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget about how far we can go in the playoffs,'' said Gailey.
``We still have to make them.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, that's not such a sure thing anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
