<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UMASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHIPPLE PROVES TRUE TO HIS WORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATCHITOCHES, La. _ Words were just words, but a common goal had
to be established and affixed to the words. So, when Mark Whipple
first mentioned the words ``national championship'' to his
University of Massachusetts football team at his introductory press
conference last Dec. 16 at Mullins Center, the coach's comments
were met, quite naturally, with some skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   No one doubted Whipple's coaching ability. He had succeeded at
New Haven, taking the Chargers to the Division 2 playoffs in 1992
and '93. And Whipple succeeded during a four-year stint at his alma
mater, Brown, where he compiled a 24-16 record.
</P>
<P>
   It was just that the Minutemen had come off a 2-9 season. And
here was the new guy, newly arrived from the boola-boola Ivy
League, talking about a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talks those words at the beginning of every year,
you know?'' said junior left guard Mike Wynne. ``It's like, `We're
going to win the A-10. We're going to win the national
championship,' but coming off 2-9 you had to be like ...''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptical?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, pretty much,'' Wynne said. ``We didn't think it was
going to happen right away, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at all, truth be told.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, my reaction was like, `Well, that'd be nice, but
we've got to face reality,''' said sophomore tailback Marcel Shipp.
``We didn't believe we could make it this far in the beginning, but
he kept putting it in our heads that we could do it and the
confidence level on the team just rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we know we can do it. We can do whatever we want to do
and all we have to do is play with confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11th-seeded Minutemen (11-3) were brimming with confidence
after scoring a 41-31 semifinal victory over host Northwestern
State in the NCAA Division 1-AA semifinals to earn a ticket to ride
to Chattanooga, Tenn., where UMass will face top-seeded Georgia
Southern (14-0) Saturday at 2 p.m. (EST) in the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may ask, `How are you playing for the national
championship?''' said Whipple, who in his first year has guided
UMass to its second title appearance in 20 years. ``Well, I had all
the (UMass football) schedules changed in the spring and I had them
put all the playoff dates on it, and that's the schedule we give
out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys we had a 15-game schedule,'' he added. ``I
told the kids in doubles (during preseason camp), `You have to
practice better than what you've been practicing because I can't
keep going over and over things, because you won't have any legs
and you'll be dead and won't last for a 15-game schedule.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way we're going to run this program. Those are the
things we've talked about with our kids, and the more you talk
about it, the more they believe in it and that's what we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   But did he detect any skepticism among his players when he first
uttered the words ``national championship''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know,'' Whipple said, shrugging. ``It's just kind
of what I've done. It's what I did at New Haven and it's what I've
done here. We just weren't able to do that at Brown, because we've
got a 10-game season, so this allows people to be the best and lay
it on the line on the field and that's the way it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   In Division 1-AA football, there are no quixotic quartiles or
confounding polls or perplexing permutations on strength of
schedule and such nonsense. The best 16 teams are seeded in a
playoff format and decide the national championship on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we're in, we don't care what we're seeded as long
as we've got a chance to play,'' Whipple said. ``Our goal as
coaches is to make our student-athletes the best people they can
be. Our philosophy is that if we say we're going to make you the
best and we don't shoot for the national championship, then you're
sending a poor message.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 0214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8026 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-14 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Let's go to the replay.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, we are going there by choice, not necessity. We are
going there for another look at what should be the NFL's play of
the year for 1998, an unbelievable, nerve-splitting moment given to
us by a forgotten quarterback and a gangly, frustrated receiver.
</P>
<P>
   And we are going there to take another long, hard look at the
fellas in the middle of all the turbulence and pressure of the
moment _ the officials _ and give them something they haven't
gotten in a long, long time. Credit.
</P>
<P>
   It was a play that finally broke the Broncos, stopped numerous
potential records and had champagne corks popping all across Miami.
Christmas didn't come early for the 1972 Dolphins with the New York
Giants' stunning 20-16 win Sunday over previously undefeated
Denver. New Year's Eve did.
</P>
<P>
   It started with Kent Graham, the rangy, seven-year Giants
veteran you might never have heard of before and, well, shouldn't
have. Before Sunday, Graham had bounced from here to there and back
again, riding his up-and-down NFL career like just another Danny
Kanell. Before Sunday, Graham resembled the great John Elway in
outward appearance only, with his big, toothy smile, a big, burly
body and enough aw-shucks in his demeanor to be a Jethro Bodine
stand-in.
</P>
<P>
   As a scrambler, he was slow and mostly top-heavy, as teammate
Michael Strahan so aptly described him in the giddy Giants locker
room afterward. Explaining the critical 23-yard dash that set up
the game-winner, Strahan said of Graham: ``It looked like his head
was too heavy. Have you seen the size of that thing? This time, he
had to be happy with that big head. He was leaning forward so much,
his head actually caused him to fall about four more yards.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day, Graham was not just Elway-like for four quarters
(21-of-33, 265 yards, two TDs) but was a little of everything. He
was part Kent, as in Clark Kent, and part Graham, as in Otto
Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was unbelievable,'' Giants coach Jim Fassel said. ``He made
all the plays we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Included was the one you saw over and over again on Sunday's
highlight shows. Graham took the snap out of the shotgun with 57
seconds remaining and the entire NFL world keeping an eye on
Denver's 13-0 record. Like it had all day, the Giants' offensive
line picked up the Broncos' blitz and gave Graham enough time to
float to his right and find Amani Toomer dashing into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   All season, Toomer, frustrated with the scarcity of balls thrown
his way, had been asking for a chance like this. Before the play,
he told Graham, ``Throw it to me, and I'll make you famous.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham lofted the ball high, and Toomer fell through the end
line, cradling the ball as he crashed to the ground and causing
players, coaches and 72,366 fans to gasp and wonder who among the
striped shirts might become infamous.
</P>
<P>
   But none did, and that might have been as important and heroic
as the game, the pass and the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Their names are David Warden and Kirk Dornan, the field judge
and back judge on referee Mike Carey's crew. Considering how NFL
officials have been charged with and indicted for not being able to
make heads or tails of such game-deciding situations this year,
they were under the kind of pressure to which only the Broncos
might have related.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner was planning a conference call this week to
broach the issue of instituting instant replay for the upcoming
playoffs. NFL director of officiating Jerry Seeman was issuing
scathing weekly reports to his crews. In numerous games, officials
were acting like panicked short-timers afraid of their own shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Three times on Sunday, in fact, Carey even felt compelled to
click on his microphone and explain to the crowd why certain calls
were not made. It was a sort of, ``FYI, you shouldn't be booing us
because '' statement rarely seen in NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   But on the decisive play, the zebras earned honors, not horns.
Warden's view was obstructed as Toomer fell to the ground. Warden
did not make a call but immediately jogged toward Dornan, the back
judge, and conferred. Moments later, both signaled touchdown, and
replays indicated the call was, like the play, unbelievably close.
But it was right.
</P>
<P>
   Had the officials blinked, or choked, as they have been wont to
do this season, the repercussions would have been dire and
far-reaching.
</P>
<P>
   Had Denver gone on to win its remaining games, an enormous taint
would have been cast on the greatest winning streak in NFL history.
An enormous uproar would have occurred across the league. An
enormous mountain of pressure would have been heaped atop the one
already there for the guys in the striped shirts.
</P>
<P>
   But as it turned out, there was the marvelous game-winning play
and the right call. Fassel bounced off the field and told the world
that those perfect 1972 Dolphins should ``send some of that
champagne to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget to save a couple of swigs for the officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 0214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8028 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-CLEMENS-HN     12-14 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CLEMENS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Rocket science turned into weird science Sunday,
depending on who was giving the lecture.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A day of twists and turns began with Astros general manager
Gerry Hunsicker calling a news conference to announce the club was
halting its pursuit of five-time Cy Young Award winner Roger
Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday night, Randy Hendricks, one of Clemens' agents, said
the announcement had been made without the knowledge of Astros
owner Drayton McLane Jr., who indicated the issue may have been put
to rest a bit prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   It still appears the Astros are out of the running for Clemens,
but McLane said he would make a decision today whether to keep
pursuing a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem like we're going to be able to do a deal, but
we're certainly going to try,'' McLane said.
</P>
<P>
   That was a much softer assessment of the team's position than
the one Hunsicker had given earlier in the day when he said the
Astros were out of the Clemens sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This came from an official qualification from Roger's agent
that any trade involving Roger would necessitate a restructuring of
his current contract,'' said Hunsicker, adding the Astros and Blue
Jays never agreed on which players would be involved in a potential
trade. ``Philosophically, we're opposed to that, but more
importantly, the agents did give us the terms they would be looking
for and we were shocked; we were just stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a situation where it's hard enough agonizing over the
talent that you may have to give up to trade for a player like
this. But in addition, you have to restructure his contract as if
he were a free agent on the open market and pay him what the elite
pitchers who have just signed over the last month are commanding.
Economically, there's just no way that we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks was caught off-guard by Hunsicker's comments, and the
situation became more clouded after a conversation between the
Houston-based agent and McLane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drayton called me personally to apologize and to say that this
was not anything he had authorized,'' Hendricks said. ``In my
opinion, this was done by petulant children who resent the fact
that I've been dealing with Drayton and not them. There are some
people over there who have never wanted to see this happen. Why
else would they do this?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I called (McLane) up, he knew nothing about this. I don't
understand why his people feel the need to dress us down in public.
They may resent the fact that I've been dealing with Drayton. I
have not talked to Gerry Hunsicker since July.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Clemens, who already is under contract for $16.1
million over the next two seasons, asked the Astros for a new
three-year deal worth $43.5 million with a fourth-year vesting
option worth an additional $15 million. The deal called for a $12
million signing bonus to be spread over the life of the contract,
not to mention the usual list of perks such as hotel suites when
the team is on the road, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The merits of making such a deal were discussed by McLane,
Hunsicker, Astros president Tal Smith and senior vice president Bob
McLaren. A sense of concern arose from that meeting, some of which
was conveyed in Hunsicker's address to a gathering of national
media members.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are believed to have been willing to part with
outfielder Derek Bell and righthanded pitcher Scott Elarton in a
package to acquire Clemens, but had they met Clemens' salary
demands, the club would have been forced to dump other
high-salaried players to stay within its budget.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hunsicker: ``Quite frankly, I think Roger would agree _ if
he understood what we'd have to do to make room for him _ even
after trading away the talent to secure his services, he wouldn't
be happy with the team we would be left with. Unfortunately, this
looks like the end of the Houston Astros' involvement in attempting
to trade for Roger Clemens.''
</P>
<P>
   Or is it? That all depends on how successful McLane is at
convincing Hendricks to lower the asking price.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really looks doubtful with everything they wanted,'' McLane
said. ``Truthfully, things would have to change a great deal. It's
probably a long shot to get it done, but we're going to look at it
again, and I told Randy I'd get back in touch with him (today).''
</P>
<P>
   The fact the Astros called a news conference to announce they
were discontinuing their efforts to trade for Clemens was unusual.
Then again, it was an unusual day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's inappropriate and unprofessional,'' Hendricks said.
``For them to respond to me through a news conference is third-rate
and unprofessional. Quite frankly, I'm stunned and shocked that we
would be attacked this way in our own town. We've always had a
respectful relationship with the Astros.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who has won back-to-back Cy Youngs and American League
pitching triple crowns, asked the Blue Jays to trade him earlier
this month based on a handshake agreement with former team
president Paul Beeston, who told Clemens he would deal him if the
pitcher no longer viewed the club as a contender.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 12 teams originally expressed interest in Clemens,
but the number had dwindled to five as recently as Friday. Some
clubs were turned off by the fact they not only had to reach an
agreement with the Blue Jays on players but also strike a new deal
with Clemens' agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unusual,'' Hunsicker said. ``Philosophically, we're
opposed to this, because this is a player who is already under
contract, and we're attempting to trade for that player. In
addition to that, the player is suggesting that he also must have
his contract restructured. That's the first time I've ever been
involved in something like that, and quite frankly I can't think of
another circumstance that I can remember where this has happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you compete for someone's services in the free-agent
market, you understand the parameters; it's an open market, and you
can choose to compete or not to compete. When you're trying to
trade for a player, it normally comes down to whether you can
satisfy the club that currently has his services. But this has
become a combination of both; it's kind of like having your cake
and eating it, too. You're not a free agent, but you want to be
treated like a free agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Most likely having found it too costly to acquire a proven No. 1
pitcher _ the Astros also pulled out of the running for Randy
Johnson (four years, $52.4 million from the Diamondbacks) last
month _ the Astros probably will enter next season with their
current cast of players. Hunsicker added All-Star third baseman Ken
Caminiti earlier this offseason, and he hopes to shore up the
bullpen with a righthanded reliever and bolster the bench with
another righthanded hitter.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clemens, the deep-pocketed Rangers and Yankees would
appear to have the best chance of satisfying his demands, along
with the Orioles and Rockies _ two teams that missed out on their
chance to sign a No. 1 starter when Kevin Brown brokered a
seven-year, $105 million contract with the Dodgers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
