<HEADLINE>
UNBEATEN UCONN LEAVES AN IMPRESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ Another day, another blowout for the University
of Connecticut women's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday it was the Svet and Swin Show as sophomore Svetlana
Abrosimova and freshman Swin Cash led the way with 20 and 15
points, respectively, as the Huskies rolled over St. John's, 91-51.
Shooting guard Shea Ralph added 14 points in the Big East matchup
before a sold-out crowd of 10,027 at Gampel Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Abrosimova, a 6-foot-2-inch forward, has led the Huskies in
scoring in four of the team's games, including a career-high 39
against UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   UConn, undefeated at 8-0, is ranked No. 1 nationally, while St.
John's fell to 4-7. The Huskies' narrowest margin of victory this
season is 11 points and their largest is 51 against Holy Cross.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's might have been invigorated by its win over Manhattan
Friday night. Instead, the Red Storm seemed exhausted and couldn't
put up much of a fight against such a powerhouse. They tied the
score four times in the first five minutes but never grabbed the
lead. In fact, after forward Natasha Johnson made a jumper with 13
minutes to go in the first half, the Red Storm didn't hit a field
goal for the next eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-moving defense of UConn _ along with the feistiness of
freshman point guard Keirsten Walters, who scored only 2 points but
came away with four steals _ caused St. John's to miss shot after
shot. The Red Storm shot 30.2 percent from the floor, compared to
57.6 percent for UConn (64 percent in the first half).
</P>
<P>
   St. John's couldn't get off many uncontested shots as the
Huskies pressed them under the baskets and pulled down 45 rebounds
to score 22 points off the fast break. UConn, sparked by a
last-minute 9-0 run, took a 50-28 lead at halftime. From then on,
the Huskies had control.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's senior Ebony Dickinson scored a team-high 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never moved the ball well because they pressured us,'' said
St. John's coach Charlene Thomas-Swinson. ``And any time you turn
the ball over 28 times, you know it's going to be a bad day.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, St. John's committed 24 personal fouls, repeatedly sending
UConn to the line to pad its lead.
</P>
<P>
   UConn coach Geno Auriemma, who said he thought the game ``was a
little uneven,'' refused to either gloat over his team's perfect
record or get nervous about an upcoming schedule that includes
meetings against Tennessee, Old Dominion, and Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we'll worry about them when it's time to play them,'' he
said. ``And whatever happens, happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 0216EST &QL; 
