 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2507 - December 14, 1998   NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2507 -- Dec. 14, 1998 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. SOLDIERS OF FASHION A decade ago, Ralph Lauren made fitted
military-style jackets trimmed with gold buttons and braid. In the
current spring collection, he - and other international fashion
designers - prove again that the military is always in style. As
long as combat persists, whether it is in Croatia, the Crimea, the
two world wars or post-Cold War scenarios, the demands of the
battlefield affect design on the home front (e.g. Land Rovers,
Cartier tank watches, cardigans, Wellington boots, khaki trench
coats etc .... ) By Julia Reed. From The New York Times Magazine.
1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
HAS GUS VAN SANT GONE PSYCHO? When the director of ``Drugstore
Cowboy'' and ``My Own Private Idaho'' announced his shot-by-shot
remake of the Hitchcock classic thriller ``Psycho,'' cinephiles
screamed sellout. But it may be Gus Van Sant's most experimental
film yet. By R.J. Smith. From The New York Times Magazine.
Full-length (3,000 words) + edited article available.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
FROM PROSPECT MAGAZINE (N/A U.K.)
</P>
<P>
   A. THE NEW NUCLEAR THREAT : Most people assume that the end of
the Cold War has erased the risk of nuclear confrontation. But the
break-up of the Soviet Union has actually increased the risk of
accidental or ``unauthorized'' nuclear strikes. By Christoph Bluth.
2,000 words. B. GUT WRENCHING : The 1970s student generation now in
power in Great Britain assumed that Pinochet was a synonym for
infamy. They had to think again. By Michael Ignatieff. 1,500 words.
C. A LITTLE BLACK BLIP : Just a few miles from the Italian coast is
a lawless country - Albania - struggling to grow out of its bloody
adolescence. By Helena Smith. 800 words. D. NATIONAL SUCCESS :
Successful nation states have been built not on race, but on
liberal political institutions and a dominant language or culture.
But the EU is not a nation or a state, and is neither democratic
nor culturally coherent. We should think twice about abandoning the
liberal national state - the best institution we have, writes Ian
Buruma. 3,000 words. E. LATE NIGHT IN LVIV : What happens to
superannuated critics? They become judges at international drama
festivals. Few are as bizarre as the one just held in the historic
heart of the Ukraine. By Irving Wardle. 1,500 words. F.
MANUFACTURING A MASTERPIECE : Valentine Cunningham tries to
understand why a derivative debut novel (Arundhati Roy's ``The God
Of Small Things'') has become a global bestseller. 2,000 words. 4.
FROM MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   A. HOLIDAY ALLERGY : Instead of visions of sugar plums, do you
sneeze and have itchy eyes on Christmas Eve? Here are tips on how
to reduce seasonal allergy symptoms this holiday season. 300 words.
B. CRANBERRY TEETH : Don't be surprised if one day your dentist
recommends that you start brushing with cranberry toothpaste.
Israeli researchers have discovered that a substance in the tart
berry helps prevent plaque. C. DECORATION SAFETY : Since holiday
decorations often put fire and foliage under one roof, each season
increases the risk for in-home injuries. Here is some good advice
for a festive and injury-free holiday. 350 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
BIOLOGICAL INSURANCE Should parents pay a blood bank to store the
blood from their newborn baby's umbilical cord and placenta, in
case that child or another family member ever needs it to treat
cancer or leukemia? Expectant parents are being urged to do so by
companies that have sprung up during the past few years to sell
cord-blood banking as a form of ``biological insurance'' against
such dreaded diseases. By Denise Grady. New York Times Science
Times. 1,150 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
FROM NEW SCIENTIST magazine (N/A Brazil, Australia, New Zealand)
</P>
<P>
   A. BEYOND THE FRINGE : Ancient locks of hair can show what their
owners ate, perhaps thousands of years ago, just as reliably as
your hair says what you ate last week. By Stephanie Pain. 2,000
words. B. NATURAL BORN FATHERS : Who says females have a monopoly
on good parenting? The males of some species dote on their
offspring and, like their mates, undergo hormonal changes in
preparation for the birth. By Alison Motluk. 2,000 words. C. THE
WILD BUNCH : How has a bunch of idealistic hackers managed to
completely wrong foot the world's biggest software companies? By
Glyn Moody. 2,000 words.
