<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 08:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8161 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-HOUSE-KAN &LR;      12-14 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-HOUSE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIX THE WHITE HOUSE? SURE, BUT NOT THIS WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My fellow patriots, we must act quickly to prevent $300 million
from being misspent on a huge but misguided renovation of the White
House. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By quickly, I mean that we have only until March 11 to make our
public comments against this knuckle-headed idea. If we are silent,
we will deserve what we get in the way of unsatisfactory changes in
this grand national icon (and petting zoo). Oh, it has too been a
petty zoo. Ask Monica Lewinsky. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service recently released the draft of a
20-year plan to change lots of stuff at the White House. Naturally,
the draft plan has a name almost as long as completing the changes
is estimated to take: ``Comprehensive Design Plan for the White
House and President's Park.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert G. Stanton, National Park Service director, said _ rather
stuffily, I thought _ that the White House ``must be able to meet
the demands of the 21st century presidency.'' So right there we
learned that having a president in the next century is practically
inevitable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the plan Stanton tossed out for public comment is woefully
off key. Oh, some of it is all right, I suppose. It proposes, for
instance, ``modernizing its infrastructure,'' and surely that's an
admirable goal, although the contrived wording of it almost
certainly would not have been understood by any president from
Washington through Nixon. (Wasn't it, after all, about 1975 that we
first started having infrastructure?) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But so much of the rest of this White House fix-up plan flies in
the face of what we now know _ and at considerable cost _ about
presidents. So I say let's spend some money on the place, but let's
not ignore the lessons of recent history. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new plan, for instance, proposes expanding indoor recreation
space for the first family. Oh, come on. How do you think Bill
Clinton got in so much trouble in the first place? Too much indoor
recreation space. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, it might be all right to add some of this kind of space as
long as all the walls and doors are made out of glass so that
whoever is in there recreating can always be seen. But the last
thing this country needs is to make it easier for future presidents
to recreate even more on the job. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The plan also calls for more meeting and storage space. Those
are two more bozo ideas. What happens at White House meetings?
People dream up ways to spend more of our money. What resides in
White House storage space? Piles of reports suggesting more ways to
spend our money. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The White House needs less meeting and storage space, not more.
If you hold a meeting where everyone has to stand up because the
room is so tiny, it won't last very long. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, if you tell people that each employee gets storage
space equal to the size of a shoe box, nobody is going to hang on
to a 40-pound report called ``Proposals for Optimizing the Use of
Tax-Supported Day Schools for Feline-Americans and Other Pets.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you think those renovation ideas are stupid, wait until you
hear about this golden nugget: more space for the press. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, really. Do you want it to be easier for the Washington
press corps to interview itself and breathlessly report its
findings about alleged scandals that nobody cares about? Puh-leeze.
Cut down on press space in the White House and maybe these
reporters will go outdoors and talk to real people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So send e-mail to white_house_liaison(at)nps.gov or write Draft
Plan/EIS, Office of White House Liaison, 1100 Ohio Drive, S.W.,
Washington, D.C. 20242. And while you're at it, suggest another
paint color, too. Hasn't the place been white long enough? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
