 (Repeating for all needing)  
(The Week in Review) 
(bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arms Inspections Yield Mixed Results in Iraq
</P>
<P>
   After a week of surprise inspections in Iraq, United Nations
arms inspectors will most likely give the Iraqis a mixed report
card this week when no-notice searches end and the Security Council
begins to decide whether Saddam Hussein has cooperated sufficiently
to qualify for a broad review of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has said it will wait for the report from Richard
Butler, the head of the inspection commission, before making any
decisions about military action if the Iraqis are found to be in
serious breach of agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has not complied fully. It barred inspectors from the
ruling party offices and refused to disclose the location of some
biological material that was moved during a break in inspections
last month and was suspected of being part of an illegal arms
program.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   Charges in Army Sex Case
</P>
<P>
   A former two-star general who served briefly as the Army's
deputy inspector general was charged with 17 counts of wrongdoing
stemming from ``improper relationships'' he had with the wives of
four subordinate officers.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which also included charges that he lied to cover up
his adulterous affairs, has been an embarrassment for the Army. The
officer, Maj. Gen. David Hale, was allowed to retire last February
even though one of the women had already filed a complaint against
him.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN LEE MYERS &QR;
</P>
<P>
   It's the Heat and the Humidity
</P>
<P>
   If you think heat waves are worst when there's no relief at
night, you don't know how right you are. A study in the journal
Nature shows not only that uncomfortable nighttime heat is more
hazardous to health than its blazing midday cousin, but that the
heat stress of the wee hours has risen markedly in the past half
century.
</P>
<P>
   If this warming continues, the study says, more heat-related
deaths will follow _ especially with a rising elderly population.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING &QR;
</P>
<P>
   New NATO Role Urged
</P>
<P>
   At a NATO meeting in Brussels, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright pressed allies to combat the threat of biological and
chemical weapons deliverable by missile. She cited the weapons as
an example of the new threats a post-Soviet NATO must face in the
next century.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans proposed a new clearinghouse for intelligence
sharing aimed at assessing threats by terrorist groups and by
states like Iran and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Allies worry that Washington wants a globalized NATO, acting in
the Middle East and beyond, and want to keep the alliance focused
on collective security in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN ERLANGER &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Tackling Social Security
</P>
<P>
   After spending a year encouraging proposals on how to shore up
Social Security for the baby-boomers' retirement, President Clinton
began seeking a politically viable compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met with 48 members of Congress from both parties to
review the options, which include establishing individual
investment accounts, raising the retirement age and increasing
taxes on middle- and upper-income workers. But given the
politically sensitive nature of the plans, all sides said a
bipartisan deal would be difficult at best.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   New Clues to Human Roots
</P>
<P>
   A new member of the early human family has come to light in
South Africa. Paleontologists reported finding a nearly complete
skull and skeleton of an adult hominid who lived more than 3.2
million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The apelike being, sex undetermined, was about 4 feet tall and
apparently swung in the trees but also walked upright. Scientists
at the University of Witwatersrand in Johannesburg said it would be
another year before they extract all the bones from the cave site.
The specimen is older and much more complete than the ``Lucy''
skeleton found in Ethiopia in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD
</P>
<P>
   NBA Cancels All-Star Game
</P>
<P>
   An All-Star Game is a midseason breather, an extravaganza that
points the way to the playoffs. But on Day 162 of the National
Basketball Association lockout, the league canceled its Feb. 14
All-Star Game in Philadelphia and stirred expectations that the
entire season is close to being wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just isn't enough time left to have a season and an
All-Star Game,'' said NBA commissioner David Stern. Billy Hunter,
the union's executive director, called the cancellation an ``effort
to further intimidate the players,'' who have made ``unprecedented
concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD SANDOMIR
</P>
<P>
   Eight Clones From One Cow
</P>
<P>
   Japanese scientists say they have cloned a cow with a success
rate at least as good as obtained with test-tube fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers began by gathering cow cells from a
slaughterhouse, picking up tissue from a cow that had just been
killed. Using cells that clung to the cow's eggs and cells that
lined its fallopian tubes, they created embryos that they put in
surrogate mothers.
</P>
<P>
   The mothers gave birth to eight calves that were genetic
replicas of the dead cow. Four calves died at or shortly after
