</P>
<P>
   _ By GINA KOLATA
</P>
<P>
   Canadian's Execution Halted
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Stanley Faulder was 30 minutes from a lethal injection in
the Texas death chamber when the U.S. Supreme Court delayed his
execution. Faulder is a Canadian and his government had appealed
for his life because he was not allowed to seek assistance from the
Canadian counsel after his arrest in 1977 on charges of murdering
an elderly woman.
</P>
<P>
   International convention requires that people arrested in a
foreign country be given that right; Texas officials said they did
not realize that Faulder, who had a Texas driver's license, was
from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups expressed concern that failure to observe
the treaty might lead to abuse against Americans arrested abroad.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Police Searches Curbed
</P>
<P>
   When the Supreme Court weighs the competing interests of the
police and ordinary citizens these days, the police usually come
out ahead. So a decision that a speeding ticket does not
automatically allow the police to search a car was notable.
</P>
<P>
   The justices overturned a ruling by the Supreme Court in Iowa,
where a law authorized police to conduct a full-blown search
whenever they issue a traffic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The 1983 law was the only one of its kind in the country, but
had the court upheld it, the idea would undoubtedly have spread.
Chief Justice William Rehnquist said there was no justification for
the search; once a driver is stopped for speeding, he said, all the
necessary evidence of the offense has been obtained.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Space Station Opens
</P>
<P>
   The international space station, or at least the first part of
it, opened for business. Robert Cabana, the U.S. commander of the
shuttle Endeavour, and a Russian astronaut, Sergei Krikalev,
entered simultaneously to share the honor of being the first humans
aboard, emphasizing the international nature of the 16-nation, $60
billion venture to build the station over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   _ By WARREN E. LEARY &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Harmonizing by Cell Phone
</P>
<P>
   There's a subtle change in the air at pop and rock concerts
these days. Since the 1960s, matches and lighters have been a
concert staple, held aloft by thousands of audience members during
sentimental ballads or while waiting for encores. But with smoking
no longer allowed at many arenas and concert halls, some of which
even confiscate lighters and cigarettes at the door, pop concerts
have been growing dark.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, a new kind of luminosity has been emerging: the green
glows and flashing red lights of cellular phones. At concerts
around the world, especially in cell phone-friendly cities from Los
Angeles to Hong Kong, audience members can be spotted holding the
gadgets in the air like surrogate lighters.
</P>
<P>
   But they are not trying to make a connection with other members
of the audience, as their brethren were doing with their flames in
the late '60s and '70s. Instead, they are making a connection with
someone else _ sometimes a friend stuck at home who wants to hear
the music, sometimes even with their own answering machine at home.
And sometimes they're just bored and trying to catch up on work or
kill time.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, some in the concert business are wondering whether
the cell phone will become as intrinsic to pop concerts as spilled
beer, loud volumes and souvenir T-shirts in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NEIL STRAUSS
</P>
<P>
   Put 'Em Up, You Man of Letters
</P>
<P>
   What is art?
</P>
<P>
   No, no, that's far too grand a question. Try this one: If
literature is caught entertaining, should it be tossed
unceremoniously out of the clubhouse?
</P>
<P>
   Or this: Can a man who wears cream-colored suits write real
literature?
</P>
<P>
   The topic, of course: Tom Wolfe's new best-seller ``A Man in
Full,'' which has prompted a testy debate lately among the literary
elite.
</P>
<P>
   John Updike, in The New Yorker, wrote that in spite of its
``grand ambition,'' the novel ``still amounts to entertainment, not
literature.'' And Norman Mailer, in The New York Review of Books,
pronounces that ``it begins to promise that he is ready to become a
great American novelist,'' but that ``at the highest level, it's a
failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that they were putting him down as a mere journalist,
Wolfe countered, ``You have to come up with things that unaided
imagination doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   And he asked, in cream-colored puzzlement, why ``those old
bones'' would try to shoot down his book.
</P>
<P>
   Why indeed? Updike's own books have clearly proved highly
entertaining to many readers, but that surely doesn't disqualify
them as literature. (Entertain, the dictionary says, means ``to
hold together.'' An entertainer is ``one who shows hospitality.''
But that doesn't mean literature is supposed to fall apart and show
you the door.)
</P>
<P>
   And if Mailer, as a member of the literary elite, is entitled to
judge what reaches ``the highest level,'' a question still arises:
How does one join the literary elite?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe C.P. Snow had the answer when he said that Cambridge dons
are not distinguished men, but merely men who confer distinctions
on each other.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
