<HEADLINE>
JOHN TRAVOLTA'S `CIVIL' WAR FOR RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of John Travolta in a scene from ``A Civil
Action.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Everybody seems to love that Travolta guy.
 &HT;    No, not John Travolta, the two-time Oscar nominee who's one of
Hollywood's biggest stars. We're talking about his son, 6-year-old
Jett.
 &HT;    ``I have never seen anything like it in my life,'' Jett's father
says. ``Ever since he was born, everyone has been in love with this
little boy.
 &HT;    ``People love Jett,'' he insists, ``and I don't mean in a
superficial way. I don't mean infatuation. I mean, strangers are
deeply in love with him. He has this effect on people.''
 &HT;    If that doesn't sound like a typical movie-star quote _ nothing
about his own brilliance, his tough struggle to the top, the
importance of ``the work'' or even why he wants to direct _ don't
worry. Travolta Sr. is not a typical movie star.
 &HT;    For example, he doesn't sign autographs anymore. Which doesn't
mean he blows off his fans. Instead he stops to talk to them.
 &HT;    ``People are actually hungry for the communication,'' he
explains. ``When I'm out, I think of life as a social occasion. I
figure fans are people who give me undivided attention. I don't
want to disappoint them and be an a--hole. People have always been
decent and respectful to me _ there is no reason that I should be
disgruntled.''
 &HT;    He's even happily married, to actress Kelly Preston, and is
happy to say that the two still go on dates together.
 &HT;    ``We get dressed up, very black tie. And then we go dancing at
the Rainbow Room in New York. It's very romantic,'' the 44-year-old
actor says. ``At those times, I think that my life is some 1930s
movie.''
 &HT;    It's also some 1990s movie _ two, in fact. This Christmas Day
heralds a virtual Travolta film festival, with the simultaneous
release of ``A Civil Action'' and ``The Thin Red Line.'' The latter
will open only in New York and Los Angeles, however, reaching more
cities throughout January.
 &HT;    Both are serious dramas, a genre with which Travolta has rarely
been associated previously. ``A Civil Action,'' adapted from
Jonathan Harr's based-on-fact best-seller, casts him as Jan
Schlichtmann, a slick lawyer whose life changes radically when he
tackles a toxic-waste case in Woburn, Mass.
 &HT;    Even Harr didn't originally judge Travolta right for the role,
but the actor fought hard for it.
 &HT;    ``I wanted this role,'' he says. ``The fact that the character
is cynical, detached, arrogant and insensitive made it seem fun to
play and watch.''
 &HT;    Travolta also tried to recruit his friend Marlon Brando to play
the opposing attorney, a role Robert Duvall ended up playing.
 &HT;    ``Marlon was offered the film,'' Travolta says, ``but it didn't
work out. He is my buddy, and I would have loved for him to do it.
 &HT;    ``I was just as thrilled with Duvall,'' he hastens to add.
 &HT;    The hardest part of making the film, the actor says, was
visiting one of the real-life families in the case, people who had
lost their 8-year-old son to leukemia.
 &HT;    ``I didn't do it to dig into their pain,'' Travolta says, his
brow furling at the memory. ``I didn't want to grill them on their
issues. I wanted to be John for them.''
 &HT;    He got more than he expected from the visit, he adds.
 &HT;    ``The mother of the little boy told me, `Did you know that when
my son was at his sickest point, we watched ``Welcome Back
Kotter?'''
 &HT;    Travolta, who starred in that 1970s television sitcom, was
touched.
 &HT;    ``In my heart, I felt happy that I did my bit for that family,''
he says. ``If in some minor way I gave that little boy any joy
during his last year ... ''
 &HT;    The actor's voice trails off.
 &HT;    ``I wish I could give everyone some joy,'' he says finally.
 &HT;    Early viewers are already touting Travolta as an Oscar
candidate, a prospect which he admits _ again, most unlike a
typical movie star _ would delight him.
 &HT;    ``To be honest with you, I would be thrilled to be acknowledged
for this particular performance,'' he says. ``It would represent
work that I'm especially proud of when I look back on my films. If
you could choose your career performances, I think this one is it
for me.
 &HT;    ``Of course, I don't want to take anything away from `Saturday
Night Fever' (1977) or `Pulp Fiction' (1994),'' he adds, looking
back on his two previous Oscar nominations. ``I just think this
work has a nobility to it.''
 &HT;    An Oscar would be the capstone to a career comeback that has
stunned even Travolta. All but washed up until ``Pulp Fiction,''
the actor has followed it with a steady stream of hits, including
``Broken Arrow'' (1995), ``Phenomenon'' (1996), ``Get Shorty'' and
``Michael'' (1996).
 &HT;    Of course, there have been disappointments along the way, most
notably two money-losers earlier in 1998 _ ``Mad City'' and the
political satire, ``Primary Colors.''
 &HT;    But every career has ups and downs, even one which began at age
8 when his mother, Helen, an actress and dancer, threw Johnny on
stage at a July 4 fair in their native New Jersey.
 &HT;    ``I did the twist and about 30,000 people whooped with
delight,'' Travolta recalls. ``I wouldn't stop twisting. My mother
finally had to tell the orchestra to stop playing so I would get
off the stage.''
 &HT;    By the time he was a teenager he was doing ``Welcome Back
Kotter,'' which led to his film debut in ``Carrie'' (1976) and then
to the smash-hit ``Saturday Night Fever.''
 &HT;    ``I really enjoyed the solo dance,'' Travolta says. ``At the
time the film was released, I wanted to go out into a disco and
experience what the culture was experiencing, but I couldn't. It
would have created a mob scene.''
 &HT;    There would be one more hit _ ``Grease'' (1978) _ and then a
series of flops. Simultaneously, his private life absorbed a series
of blows. His first girlfriend, actress Diana Hyland, died of
cancer. A year later he lost his mother.
 &HT;    He credits his faith in the controversial religion Scientology
for pulling him through the rough spots.
 &HT;    ``There's nothing Scientology can't handle,'' he says. ``It's a
catchall.''
 &HT;    Nowadays the rough spots are fewer and further between. He and
Preston have mansions in Maine and Los Angeles, and travel back and
forth in the private planes that Travolta pilots himself. Even in
the days of his slump, the actor never endured financial hardship,
having invested his early income cannily.
 &HT;    ``I've had a blessed life,'' he says. ``I always knew the value
of good taste and wise investments.''
 &HT;    His future includes the military thriller ``The General's
Daughter,'' as well as ``The Shipping News,'' a love story in which
Preston will co-star. Further down the line, Travolta is interested
in Martin Scorsese's Rat Pack biopic.
 &HT;    ``I would love to get out there and sing and dance again,'' he
says.
 &HT;    And he has plans someday to do a film biography of Scientology
founder L. Ron Hubbard, and is also developing ``Battlefield
Earth,'' based on a science-fiction book by Hubbard _ both in
keeping with Travolta's view of himself as ``an ambassador'' for
his religion.
 &HT;    In short, the atypical movie star can afford to be nice _ after
all, it would be hard for things to work out any better than they
have recently.
 &HT;    Which leads to his early new year's resolution:
 &HT;    ``I really believe in the joy of life,'' he says. ``I don't mean
that in some frivolous way. I think my resolution is just to
remember that humans should be happy. I don't think we're here to
be in pain or to suffer.
 &HT;    ``We're here to enjoy life,'' he says. ``I wish that on all
people.''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
