<SLUG> BC-JULIA-ROBERTS-IN-STEPMOM-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JULIA ROBERTS: GLAD TO BE GROWN UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Julia Roberts with Susan Sarandon in a
scene from ``Stepmom.'' 
 By JEANNE WOLF and SHEP MORGAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Julia Roberts radiates a disarming, no-nonsense friendliness,
cemented by a startlingly firm handshake, as she enters a suite in
a trendy New York hotel.
 &HT;    Clad in a black sweater and matching jeans, Roberts gives her
dark-brown tresses a toss, takes a healthy gulp of imported water
and flashes the grin that melted hearts in her Academy
Award-nominated performance in ``Pretty Woman'' (1990).
 &HT;    The 31-year-old actress is in high spirits, and why not? Coming
off last year's blockbuster ``My Best Friend's Wedding,'' she's
co-starring with Susan Sarandon in the much-touted ``Stepmom.'' She
has a special man in her life, handsome Benjamin Bratt from the
television series ``Law and Order.''
 &HT;    Last but not least, she's set to collect $17 million _ making
her the highest-paid actress in Hollywood history _ for her next
film, ``Runaway Bride,'' which will reunite her with ``Pretty
Woman'' co-stars Richard Gere and Hector Elizondo, along with
director Garry Marshall.
 &HT;    ``This whole show-business thing is a bizarre, trippy little
ride,'' Roberts says, ``but I'm having fun.''
 &HT;    ``Stepmom'' pairs Roberts with Sarandon, an old friend whom she
met through Sarandon's longtime companion, actor/director Tim
Robbins. Sarandon is cast as a divorced mother who can't cope with
the idea of Roberts, her ex-husband's girlfriend, becoming her
kids' stepmom _ until she herself is stricken with cancer.
 &HT;    The only reservations Roberts had about the film, she says,
concerned its title.
 &HT;    ``Susan and I thought `Stepmom' sounded like a horror film,''
she says. ``The two of us dreamed up scads of titles. I came up
with `If I Needed You,' which is the title of the song I sing to
Susan's young son when he visits her in the hospital. I thought
that would work, but there are always people in a far-distant place
called Hollywood who shoot down your ideas. So `Stepmom' it is.''
 &HT;    Knowing Sarandon well didn't make Roberts any calmer about the
challenge of holding her own with the 52-year-old, Academy
Award-winning actress, she says.
 &HT;    ``You want her respect,'' she explains. ``So the first day we
were on camera together I'm thinking, `What if I suck? What if
Susan thinks I'm really bad?' But I got over it.
 &HT;    ``What's more,'' she continues with a laugh, ``Susan plays this
supermom who spends a lot time basically ripping me apart for
failing to get along with her kids and telling me that I'll never
make a good mother. I know it was only a movie, but there were days
when she was being horrible to me and I thought, `Susan's a great
actress, but I wish she wasn't so convincing!'''
 &HT;    Roberts's character is torn between her lover's children and her
own career as a fashion photographer, a dilemma that the actress
couldn't identify with.
 &HT;    ``I don't really relate to the idea of career vs. family,'' she
says. ``I don't understand the `vs.,' I guess. A lot of us wouldn't
be here if both our parents hadn't worked. I know I wouldn't _ my
mother always had a job.
 &HT;    ``My parents were divorced when I was 4,'' she adds. ``I don't
remember it, but I don't think it was that traumatic for me. I just
accepted it as a circumstance of life.''
 &HT;    Roberts's own rocky, highly publicized journey through love and
marriage has included two broken engagements _ to actors Dylan
McDermott and Kiefer Sutherland _ as well as a brief marriage to
singer Lyle Lovett and numerous other short-term relationships.
 &HT;    Of them all, Roberts says, the one that still means the most to
her is Lovett.
 &HT;    ``He's one of my best friends,'' she insists. ``I can't imagine
him not being in my life.''
 &HT;    Asked about her current relationship, which has spanned the past
year, Roberts chokes on a swig of water.
 &HT;    ``Ben is just the same old guy, the same old date,'' she says,
giggling. ``Why is the media so impatient? It's like, `Marriage,
have kids, get on with it!' Doesn't anybody understand that life
just kind of flows?
 &HT;    ``This isn't something that I ponder on a daily basis,'' she
adds, ``but, having dealt with it in `Stepmom,' I think if you're
in a relationship, and it's an open relationship, then you have to
accept the entire person and everything that comes with them, from
kids from another marriage to the way they dress and what they eat.
 &HT;    ``You can't be too selective and start adding qualifications
that the person you're in love with has to live up to,'' Roberts
says. ``That's not the secret to a happy life together.''
 &HT;    In short, Roberts says, at 31 she's still in no mood to tie
herself down.
 &HT;    ``I'd like to have kids,'' she says. ``It's just that I don't
have a five-year plan. It's more like I'm on the five-minute plan.
I really do enjoy my life, but if you plan too far ahead you can be
way down the road and missing the moment.''
 &HT;    Right now, she'd rather think about ``Runaway Bride,'' which
she's currently filming.
 &HT;    ``It's not a sequel to `Pretty Woman,''' she says, ``even though
we're all back together again. For some reason I just pictured us
all sitting around talking, because we hadn't seen each other in a
while. I forgot that we'd actually have to work. But it's been a
gas.''
 &HT;    She and Gere have a romance in the film, she says, but it won't
include anything to equal their bathtub scene in ``Pretty Woman.''
That may have seemed romantic to the audience, the actress adds,
but in person it was anything but.
 &HT;    ``That was not a fun moment,'' Roberts recalls with a laugh.
``First of all, you spend hours in the water. Then your body
stocking is pinching. Finally, I kept lathering up Richard's chest
with soap and he goes, `You've got to stop, my skin is cracking
open.'''
 &HT;    The media have been fascinated by Roberts's record paycheck for
the film, but she insists that the whole issue has been overblown.
 &HT;    ``I don't think I want to be remembered as the $17 million
woman,'' she says. ``I'd like to be known as the great-actress
woman or the great-friend woman _ even the nice-legs woman would be
OK.
 &HT;    ``Seventeen million is just a number,'' Roberts adds. ``I love
what I'm doing _ don't tell anybody, but I'd do it for free. I'm
certainly not going to perform better just because I get paid more.
And if the movie sucks it's going to suck, no matter how much the
actors got paid.''
 &HT;    More important, she says, is that she wants to continue to
challenge herself as an actress, even if audiences have not always
responded well when she has done so in the past.
 &HT;    ``I think the woman I play in `Stepmom' is the most grown-up
character, the most real-life person, I've ever played,'' she says.
``I'm not sure I could have played her when I was in my 20s _ I
wouldn't have understood her the way I do now. I hope that, as I
mature, my roles will keep on growing up with me.''
 &HT;    Throughout the interview, Roberts has been fingering a silver
medallion around her neck.
 &HT;    ``It's an `Om,''' she says. ``You know, the meditative sound of
harmony.''
 &HT;    The symbol is meaningful to her, she says, because harmony is an
important part of her life, even if she can't always achieve it.
 &HT;    ``It's about keeping things simple, I think,'' the actress says.
``My dad used to talk about how difficult it is to be simple. But
when you're in the midst of chaos, you need to take a moment and
distill things down to the simplest factor.
 &HT;    ``Concentrate on that, and everything else will fall into
place.''
 c.1998 Pentacom Productions  
