<HEADER>
A8272 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAYA-ANGELOU-DIRECTS-     12-14 1459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYA-ANGELOU-DIRECTS-DOWN-IN-THE-DELTA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYA ANGELOU: A NEW ROAD LEADS `DOWN IN THE DELTA' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Maya Angelou directing Wesley Snipes and
Alfre Woodard in a scene from ``Down in the Delta.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    To Dr. Maya Angelou's seemingly infinite list of identities _
poet, teacher, author, mother, actress, grandmother, civil-rights
activist, playwright _ add one more: movie director.
 &HT;    ``To write poetry, one first needs a fluency in the language,''
says Angelou, a larger-than-life woman _ part wistful storyteller,
part imposing, cantankerous taskmaster _ during a conversation at
Beverly Hills' Four Seasons Hotel. ``One needs big eyes and good
ears, then the courage to see and to hear, and then the courage to
say what you see and hear about the human being, about our
condition.
 &HT;    ``The words are the grist,'' she adds. ```Making a movie, I can
use an actor and a camera to tell a volume without one word being
spoken. I can't offer a book at the bookstore with five pages of
nothing on them!
 &HT;    ``So the poetry is of a different kind, but it's all poetry.''
 &HT;    Written by Myron Goble, ``Down in the Delta'' _ which opens on
Christmas Day _ is the saga of Loretta (Alfre Woodard), an
uneducated, substance-abusing, African-American mother of two who
can't find work in her bleak Chicago neighborhood. Desperate,
Loretta's mother, Rosa Lynn (Mary Alice), pawns a family heirloom _
a candelabra dubbed ``Nathan'' _ and sends Loretta and the kids
down to Mississippi to be with Loretta's Uncle Earl (Al Freeman
Jr.), a successful businessman with an appreciation of family, a
sense of history and a contagious air of serenity.
 &HT;    ``The film presented itself, and I loved the story,'' Angelou
says. ``It is such a good, human story that I could have shot it in
Canton, Ohio, or Canton, China, if I knew enough of the particulars
of the culture, the nuances which are the only real differences
between human beings anyway.
 &HT;    ``Do you fry your eggs or boil them? Otherwise, we're all the
same.''
 &HT;    Many first-time directors would have had a hard time lining up
A-list talent for so commercially problematic a film. Not so for
Angelou _ it's pronounced ``AN-gel-oh'' _ whose literary renown and
prestige in the African-American community proved a potent magnet
for actors.
 &HT;    ``When I first read the script, I saw Al Freeman Jr.,'' she
says. ``That character is in every family, in every culture,
sometimes on every block _ irascible, curmudgeonly, gruff. Pull off
one layer, and he's tender as a rose.
 &HT;    ``But we've not seen this man in the black film,'' she adds.
``I've known Al for 25 or 30 years, so it was grand to see him play
that man.''
 &HT;    The neophyte director also knew Alfre Woodard from her acting
stint in ``How to Make an American Quilt'' (1995), in which Woodard
co-starred.
 &HT;    ``You can get lost in the ocean of her eyes,'' Angelou says,
``and I thought, `Boy, wouldn't it be nice to direct her.'
 &HT;    ``And there was no one but (the late) Esther Rolle for the role
of the Alzheimer's (victim) and Mary Alice as Rosa Lynn,'' she
says. ``Then there's Wesley (Snipes). I'd heard him read a poem for
a CD of `Il Postino' (1997), and my jaw dropped. So I wanted to
work with him.
 &HT;    ``The actors gave me everything I asked for and change,'' she
says with a laugh. ``I think each one came to steal the movie,
actually.''
 &HT;    Many observers were surprised when Angelou chose to direct
``Down in the Delta.'' It would have seemed more natural for her to
film one of her own stories, rather than one by another person _
especially one that is, improbably, an African-American woman's
saga written by a white, male Georgian.
 &HT;    Actually, the mere fact that she wanted to direct struck many as
remarkable. It can't be easy for a writer, whose words are hers
alone, completely under her control, to open herself to the
collaborative world of filmmaking. Directors may be at the top of
the cinematic food chain, but even the most absolute movie monarch
must filter his or her vision through the eyes of dozens, even
hundreds of actors, designers, cinematographers, editors and more.
 &HT;    ``That's true,'' Angelou says, nodding. ``I was asked why I
didn't write the script or do one of my own stories, and it's
because I believe in equal distribution of labor.
 &HT;    ``When I finish writing a book,'' she explains, ``I've said all
I know to say about that subject. I don't know any more, and if I'd
known more I would have put more in there.
 &HT;    ``So I had to shift gears. That way I would not be so totally in
the piece that my ego got tripped up in it, too.''
 &HT;    At 70, Angelou is also considerably older than the usual
first-time director. She'd written a couple of screenplays
previously _ for ``Georgia, Georgia'' (1972) and the television
movie ``Sister, Sister'' (1982) _ but ``Down in the Delta'' is her
first time behind the camera, a fact which concerns her not a whit.
In fact, not long ago she told Oprah Winfrey that ``70 is
rocking.''
 &HT;    Angelou laughs heartily at the memory.
 &HT;    ``Somebody asked me the other day about getting old, what do I
think about it?'' she says. ``I said, `Do it. Do it!'''
 &HT;    The trick, of course, is to do it right.
 &HT;    ``I really have the ambition to be great ... inside myself, to
exercise every chance I have,'' she says. ``See, I think we do a
disservice to ourselves by saying, `You shouldn't be a Jack of all
trades and a master of none.'
 &HT;    ``Baloney,'' she says heartily. ``We don't understand
electricity at all. We probably use one-billionth of one-billionth
of one-billionth percent of it, and yet we can plug into a wall and
light a cathedral, a synagogue or a temple, or we can electrocute a
person strapped in a chair.
 &HT;    ``Electricity makes no demands,'' the writer says. ``It says,
`I'm here. If you want to use me intelligently, do so, and if you
want to use me stupidly, do so.'
 &HT;    ``I think talent is like that. I think we're all born with
talent. Sometimes, by the time we're 3 or 4, it's knocked out of
us.''
 &HT;    Angelou endured a tough childhood, one she chronicled in her
memoir, ``I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings'' (1970). She credits her
grandmother for not letting anyone ever knock the talent out of
her.
 &HT;    ``She was incredible,'' Angelou says. ``When she died, she was
still over 6 foot, and she always spoke softly.
 &HT;    ``I was mute for about six years,'' she recalls. ``People
thought I was an idiot, a moron. My grandmother would say, `When
the Good Lord gets ready, you're going to be a teacher.'
 &HT;    ``I used to think, `This poor, ignorant woman. Good Lord!'''
 &HT;    Eventually, however, her grandmother's faith was borne out.
 &HT;    ``I teach all over the world,'' Angelou says, still touched with
wonder. ``I lecture at Exeter and Oxford, I'm on the library board
at Harvard, and I teach in French and Spanish.''
 &HT;    So much teaching. Can there be anything left to learn for one
who's lived so rich a life?
 &HT;    ``Everything,'' Angelou says instantly. ``Everything!''
 &HT;    Nevertheless, she admits that there are some aspects of aging
which intimidate her.
 &HT;    ``Losing my friends is really hard for me,'' the writer says
softly, somberly. ``Jessica Mitford and Betty Shabazz died within
two years. When Jessica died, I went to Betty. When Betty died,
there was no Jessica to go to.
 &HT;    ``This is the hardest part of growing older _ it's not the aches
and pains,'' she says. ``Art Linkletter is absolutely right. Old
age is not for sissies. Oh, no, no, no.''
 &HT;    Angelou grins a bit, and both her energy and wit return.
 &HT;    ``The physical challenges are pretty grim and tiring,'' she
says. ``But you can always have a scotch.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
