<HEADER>
A8273 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAY-ROMANO-IN-EVERYBO     12-14 1422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAY-ROMANO-IN-EVERYBODY-LOVES-RAYMOND-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAY OF HOPE: `EVERYBODY LOVES RAYMOND' COULD CHEER UP EVEN RAY
ROMANO 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Ray Romano with Patricia Heaton and a
small child in a scene from ``Everybody Loves Raymond.'' 
 By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1998 Canadian TV Guide  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You'd think by now he could stop worrying.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Romano, star of ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' has seen his
CBS show weather initially low ratings _ despite critical acclaim _
and go on, in its second year, to become one of television's most
popular comedies.
</P>
<P>
   But no, the notoriously troubled comedian has plenty to worry
about even now _ such as his own past, which reared up to confront
him on a recent plane trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those first-year episodes?'' Romano says. ``American Airlines
shows them. I put my head between my legs, I can't watch them. I
was watching one episode with one of the writers, my friend Tom
(Caltabiano). We were in first class, and there were some
celebrities _ Matt Dillon, Mira Sorvino and Nick Turturro _ and on
comes this one episode that I thought I was particularly horrible
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Romano winces at the memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God, they don't watch,'' he says, grimacing. ``First
class doesn't watch, you know _ but during this one scene, I ducked
down in my seat until I thought it was over. I called to Tom, `Is
it over?' And he said, `Stay down, Ray, stay down!'''
</P>
<P>
   The comic probably qualifies as his own harshest critic. After
all, by now the show is a certified hit. Not only does it regularly
beat Fox's much-hyped ``Ally McBeal,'' but it even occasionally
outscores ``Monday Night Football'' in sports-crazy New York.
</P>
<P>
   This season has found the show _ centering on sportswriter Ray
Barone, his wife (Patricia Heaton), their three kids and his
parents, who live inconveniently just across the street _ in a
strong comic groove, fueled in part by Ray's jealousy of his inept
brother (Brad Garrett), who has moved out of their parents' house
and embraced the joys of single life.
</P>
<P>
   By rights, the ratings should have Romano jumping for joy, but
only now has he reached the point at which, asked if he thinks his
show will last, he responds with a reluctant ``Uhh, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't reach for the Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't make me feel comfortable, you know,'' he adds
quickly, ``because I'd just replace it with other worries. Like,
`Now you're a top-20 show, what does it take to become a top-10
show?' Or, `How do we continue the quality of the story lines?' I
mean, everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sit back and say, `Oh, the show's a well-oiled
machine now, I don't have to worry about it,''' he says. ``Then you
get too lazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even getting laughs worries this fretful funny man.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studio audiences know the show so well. Used to be, we
couldn't buy a laugh because we were all strangers to them,'' he
recalls. ``Laughs were hard to come by, and that was disturbing me.
Now they so love the show that in the beginning, when we start
filming, they laugh at anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that disturbs me _ they're laughing too much now,'' he
says. ``You have to trust your instincts, because you could have a
lame joke in there and they would laugh just the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``So yeah,'' he concedes with a smile, ``there's always
something wrong. But there are worse things to complain about.''
</P>
<P>
   He's feeling more comfortable about acting, he adds. It had been
a legitimate concern before the show began _ after all, he'd never
before played a character other than himself _ but he's worked hard
to improve, and is feeling better in front of the cameras. And that
in turn has improved every other aspect of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're so much better now,'' he says. ``I'm more
comfortable, everybody's more comfortable and the rhythms are all
there, you know. And the writers know the characters better, so
that helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the show struggled because its subject matter _
domestic family humor _ clashed with its tone _ sharp, smart and
more than a little edgy.
</P>
<P>
   People didn't know what to make of the series. ``Seinfeld''
fans, its target audience, avoided it because there was a whiff of
``Full House'' about it. But ``Married with Children'' fans found
it too cerebral.
</P>
<P>
   The support of most critics was a big help in convincing CBS to
stick with the show and let its audience find it. In addition,
Romano says, steady exposure is essential for a show whose humor is
truly character-based.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone else seems to be doing shows joke-to-joke instead of
building characters and relationships,'' he says. ``I don't respond
to those. I think that maybe, as good as `Seinfeld' was, it
inspired some imitations that really were about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``On shows like that, you're only as good as your last joke,''
he adds. ``Rather than creating a show that'll last forever, they
want to create something that will get a laugh this Wednesday at 9
p.m. Everything hinges on the punchline, but then you have to start
over. Nothing is built in terms of characterizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked from a different direction,'' the comedian says.
``Maybe we could've gotten canceled, but people responded to these
characters. It stood out, maybe because it was different, maybe
because it strikes chords that people can relate to.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the show is based on Romano's own life, except for the
character of Ray's overbearing mother (Doris Roberts), who he says
comes more from executive producer Phil Rosenthal's experience.
</P>
<P>
   The eccentricities displayed in Peter Boyle's portrayal of
Raymond's father are fairly dead-on, Romano says. In fact, when
Boyle finally met the comedian's dad, ``He was surprised that he
wasn't a big monster.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Romano doesn't love his father, but he attributes his
own attraction to the applause- and laughter-filled world of comedy
to the lack of warmth in his relationship with his dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``His undemonstrativeness helped,'' he says. ``I think I get my
sense of humor from him. He keeps doing things that bother my wife,
and I keep telling her, `Look, it's 13 years now, don't you know
he's trying to be funny?' He won't stop, and she won't see that
it's the only way he can communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of my father's traits,'' Romano adds. ``It's
weird that I'm in acting, because I'm shy around people, not
demonstrative even with family members. Now that I have kids, I try
to go out of my way to show them affection _ it's so odd, because
you feel it, you love your kid more than anything, yet to say `I
love you,' you're almost embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very strange feeling, although it's getting a lot
easier now.''
</P>
<P>
   Annie, Romano's wife, is a good-natured sort who doesn't mind
being the subject of her husband's humor. For example, he has
reported that, when he signed to do the show, she had qualms about
him kissing other women, qualms that he quieted by agreeing that
for each time he kissed someone else, Annie could buy something.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, he joked that she had gotten so far ahead of
schedule that he was entitled to do an R-rated, ``Fatal
Attraction''-style movie.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Romano insists, her paranoia is escalating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her new thing is, she's watching a scene between me and Patty
and she looks at me and goes, `A lot of eye contact there,''' he
says, rolling his eyes. ``I swear to God. She says, `You're looking
at her the whole time.'
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is, `Honey, the director told me to!'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kronke is the Los Angeles-based senior writer for
Canadian TV Guide.) &LR; 
