<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Discovering some of what drew Central Texas settlers
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKSTUMP VALLEY, Texas _ On the ridge, the Spanish oak
provided a splatter of auburn. Once upon a Central Texas autumn it
was solid color. Now the oaks poke out from among the ever-prolific
cedar, a major irony to oldtimers.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time settlers here had to import cedar wood from
elsewhere in Texas for their fence posts. Imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Now, exasperated landowners spend time pulling pesky,
water-gobbling cedars out of the ground, lest the trees consume
all.
</P>
<P>
   The prairie has changed in many ways. In many ways, it hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian grass once belly-high to a horse is virtually extinct
in these parts, grazed and plowed into history.
</P>
<P>
   But for one who doesn't know the difference it's possible to
stand on a certain spot in this valley, about five miles north of
Iredell, and imagine that this is the way Stacy Tidwell first saw
it, and the Indians before her.
</P>
<P>
   Tidwell, a 90-year-old Waco resident, former Iredell merchant
and one-time Bosque County treasurer, is why we were here, seaching
for a stump. Don't snicker. I got enough of that from my family.
</P>
<P>
   Tidwell had called me months ago about something else. I forget.
But the conversation turned to fascinating things, like riding a
horse to work at 19 to teach at the Flag Branch School, or
attending Blackstump Valley School up on a windswept hill. The
school outhouse was across the road. On either side: unfettered
miles of blackland prairie.
</P>
<P>
   On a stump hunt
</P>
<P>
   I didn't clear it with my wife or sons that we'd spend a
Saturday looking for a charred stump, but that was my mission.
</P>
<P>
   My wife hates when I ask directions. They always get us
somewhere, but rarely ``there.'' Crossing the Bosque at Iredell and
driving north until the end of the pavement on F.M. 216, we looked
for an old school or its remnants. No luck. No stump, either. The
only sign of activity, and hope for solid leads, was back in
Iredell at VFW Post 8559.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, a group of vets and their wives busily prepared a
Thanksgiving feed, while a few slackers concentrated on a good
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for the black stump of Blackstump Valley,'' I told
a foursome elbow-deep in dominoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone,'' said one under his VFW cap. ``I pulled that out
of the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' I reacted, not sensing my leg was being jiggled. ``Well,
do you know where I could find the old Blackstump School?''
</P>
<P>
   The players swiveled and pointed into the kitchen. ``Ask him,''
they said.
</P>
<P>
   A man wiped roll-making shortening off his hands and shook mine.
Doak Simpson is the name. He owns the property on which Stacy
Tidwell's old school sat. I found that to be quite a stroke. Like I
tell my wife, all you have to do is ask.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson is a native of the Blackstump Valley, but lives in Forth
Worth where he retired after a career in engineering. He still owns
a weekend residence in the valley. Brother Tom lives nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The Simpsons' forebears settled here in 1901. Doak Simpson went
to school in Iredell _ Iredell Dragons Class of '47 _ and served in
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderfully accommodating, Simpson readily took us to the site
of the Blackstump Valley School. There's no trace of it today, not
even an indentation.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the black stump? Simpson said the name most
likely came not from one stump but from many. The stumps, long-ago
oaks, had been charred by a range fire.
</P>
<P>
   No, there was no black stump to be found. But we had found
Blackstump Valley School, or the modest hill that seemed tall when
Stacy Tidwell was young. And we found a slice of Central Texas we'd
have never seen. Doak Simpson invited us to dinner with the VFW.
I'd have taken him up on it, but the boys were antsy to end our
stump hunt.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor at the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
