<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Two governors; one inspiring justice
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's beautiful when a plan to ignore
partisan politics comes together. It's more than beautiful when two
governors _ the governor and the governor-elect _ decide
independently that the best candidate for the Florida Supreme Court
is an outstanding jurist with a distinguished legal career who just
happens to be a black woman.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened in Tallahassee last week. The late Gov.
Chiles and Gov.-elect Jeb Bush reached the same conclusion after
separately interviewing four finalists to succeed Justice Ben
Overton, who retires Jan. 4. The debate as to which man has the
legal authority to make the appointment became moot when both chose
Peggy Ann Quince, a judge on the 2nd District Court of Appeal, to
become the court's 79th justice.
</P>
<P>
   When Gov. Chiles appointed her to the 2nd DCA in 1993, she
became the first black woman to serve on one of Florida's five
appellate courts. At that time, the 1975 graduate of the Catholic
University of America law school had completed more than 13 years
with the criminal division of the Florida Attorney General's
Office. She spent five of those years as Tampa bureau chief, and
her handling of death penalty cases earned praise.
</P>
<P>
   As an undergraduate at Howard University (1970-74), she majored
in zoology with the intention of becoming a physician. ``But, you
know, those were turbulent times,'' she said. ``I wanted to know
more about the law.''
</P>
<P>
   By phone Wednesday afternoon, she spoke of her father _ Solomon
Quince, the greatest influence on her life _ with a reverence that
was inspiring. Though he died before she became an appellate judge,
she remembers his advice to always work hard and do your best.
Raised in Norfolk, Va., she is the second-oldest of six children
(three girls and three boys) her longshoreman father raised alone
after her parents separated. She says, ``I haven't seen my mother
since I was 7.''
</P>
<P>
   For soon-to-be-Justice Quince, ``opportunity'' is the key. At
her news conference Tuesday, she said of her appointment, ``It is a
marvelous opportunity for all of the citizens of the state of
Florida to really see that you can work hard, and do all those
things that we're told about from Day One and that it will pay
off.'' On the phone, she repeatedly emphasized that she has
received ``a great opportunity to do important work.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, lawyer Fred L. Buckine, was with her in Tallahassee
for the announcement. Also present was her older daughter, Peggy
Laverne, a Florida
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M senior interested in law. Her younger daughter, Laura
Laverne, a University of Central Florida freshman, remained at
school because she had two exams that day. Judge Quince can't
remember what her daughters said when she called to tell them the
news, except ``there was a lot of screaming for joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether in Tampa or Tallahassee, Judge Quince intends to
continue working in her church and community. She teaches Sunday
school and serves on the usher board at New Hope Missionary Baptist
Church, where her husband is associate pastor. ``Why would I
quit?'' she asks. ``I enjoy it so much.'' Her other activities
include membership in Alpha Kappa Alpha sorority, the NAACP and the
Urban League.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gov. Chiles and Mr. Bush can claim credit for delivering
this victory for all Floridians. Without compromising standards,
both men acknowledged the importance of increased diversity, as
Judge Quince becomes the second woman (with Barbara Pariente) and
second black (with Leander Shaw) on the seven-member court.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Quince says she ``will work hard and do an excellent job
on the court.'' Given her accomplishments, we have every reason to
believe her. She has proven that race or less-than-ideal home
circumstances need not predestine mediocre performance or defeat.
Solomon Quince taught her that. Thanks to the wisdom of two
governors, she has taught us.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson is a columnist for The Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
