<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Car alarm a real turn-off
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Many years ago when we were house-hunting, our
real estate agent picked us up in her new car to show us some
houses. After we got into her car, we heard a robotic voice say
``Your door is ajar. Your door is ajar.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed, we shut the door. ``Thank you,'' came the tinny voice.
That was our first experience with ``talking cars.'' It also was
our last.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want my car to talk to me. If I have to resort to having
conversations with a vehicle, I need to check into the nearest
chapter of Get-A-Life Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   We have been in a car-trading frenzy of late as our aging
vehicles began dying one by one. We now have newer models with
newer gadgets and fancier doodads and geegaws. I don't understand
most of them.
</P>
<P>
   And, like all right-brained people, I do not read instruction
manuals. All of which is fine when nothing goes wrong. Inevitably,
something goes wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I was in the Dallas area with two of our three sons
attending yet another soccer tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Our Saturday games were at night at this lighted complex, so we
rested in our new vehicle between the 7 and 9:30 p.m. games. One
son was dozing peacefully in the back seat as I sat in the front
with my younger son, the soccer player, considering our chances of
advancing to the next day's games.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, our car's security alarm went off, screeching loudly
into the night.
</P>
<P>
   EEE-OOH, EEE-OOH, EEE-OOH.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't even know we had a security alarm. Startled, I snapped
up from my reclined position sputtering ``Wha . . . wha . . .
what?''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the sleeping son jumped up from the back seat, a
fountain of unpleasant words, but offering no help on how to turn
the thing off.
</P>
<P>
   EEE-OOH, EEE-OOH, EEE-OOH blared the alarm as I frantically
pushed buttons, pulled knobs and slid dials.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you turn this thing off?'' I barked at my children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do the opposite of whatever you did to turn it on!'' one
answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I did to turn it on,'' I shot back.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it that children always expect parents to know what to
do? Don't they know that nine times out of 10, we don't have a
clue?
</P>
<P>
   Both sons shouted suggestions to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn the wheel!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Start the engine!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Open and shut the doors!''
</P>
<P>
   A small crowd began gathering outside our car, bemusedly
watching our frantic actions.
</P>
<P>
   In desperation, I opened the door and grabbed the first person I
saw by the coat collar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know how to turn this thing off?'' I begged.
</P>
<P>
   EEE-OOH, EEE-OOH, EEE-OOH.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's your instruction manual,'' he asked reasonably.
</P>
<P>
   ``At home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have one of those automatic locks on your keychain?''
he asked.
</P>
<P>
   I grabbed the keys from the ignition and hit the ``lock'' and
``unlock'' buttons in rapid succession. The alarm stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Silence filled the night, and the grinning onlookers began to
disperse. The boys and I looked at each other and heaved a
collective sigh of relief. I took several deep breaths, and my
heart rate gradually returned to the normal range.
</P>
<P>
   At least during the whole spectacle there hadn't been a robotic
voice informing me ``Your alarm is sounding. Your alarm is
sounding.''
</P>
<P>
   It's times like this I really long for my '67 Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
