</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Stage-four car coasts to road's end
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A good cat and a good car have roughly the same life span.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, a good car and a good cat share a lot of other
similarities, as well. Neither demands constant attention. Both
purr when they're happy and neither leaves messes on the floor.
Neither one will burst into flames unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how good a car or cat is, both start reaching
their design limits after about 15 years. And that's why I found
myself sadly walking from a junkyard recently after selling out a
faithful, 15-year-old, 198,000-mile car.
</P>
<P>
   If Shakespeare calculated seven ages of man, there are four ages
of car.
</P>
<P>
   First, there is the trophy car, smelling of factory solvents and
vacuumed out immediately after the first cheeseburger is eaten
within it. It is parked gingerly and only after scouting. It is a
small island of spiffiness and order in the dangerous, ugly and
messy world around it.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the transport car. It sports supermarket
parking-lot dents that appeared out of nowhere. It was keyed once
along the passenger side, or maybe a branch did that. It has smells
that have a way of returning when summer turns humid.
</P>
<P>
   But in return for these indignities, you gain all the advantages
that come from close familiarity. You know exactly how far from the
capital ``E'' the gas meter can go before you actually need to stop
at a gas station. Because the car is thoroughly broken-in, you do
not fear excessively for its bumpers or upholstery.
</P>
<P>
   This is the golden age of car ownership _ free of the
responsibilities of a trophy car, free of the cares that are
waiting just a short way down the road.
</P>
<P>
   The third stage is the beach car, sighing like a furnace,
creaking like a house that might be haunted. But you can drive it
to the beach and the sand is no problem. You can take it on bad
roads and off roads. Teen-agers hold discussions sitting on its
hood. It's a car that has had adventures, has stories told about
it, has coffee cups hidden within its recesses.
</P>
<P>
   This is a car whose operations involve an oral lore known only
to its operators, matters spoken of in no known manual. ``Listen
for the third click and you're in reverse, no matter what the arrow
says.'' ``Hit it right here if the radio stops.'' ``Put a clothes
pin here if it won't start on a cold day.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a stage proclaimed by bumper stickers that make
grandiose claims about the make of your other car. That say ``don't
laugh, it's paid for.'' In fact, this is the stage when bumper
stickers in general don't detract from a car, they spiff it up.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the organ-donor car. Sans water pump, sans
transmission, sans battery, sans everything.
</P>
<P>
   It is a hard decision to demote a noble beach car to the harsh
fate of a donor car. One feels unaccountably ungrateful.
</P>
<P>
   Mine looked like a forlorn thing parked in the mud of the
junkyard. Its neighbors were younger cars that lived fast lives and
met bad ends. Some had deployed air bags draped like dead, beige
balloons off the steering wheel. All were crunched somewhere and
had undoubtedly been towed to their final rusting place.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its age, though, mine at least made it there under its
own power and without violence.
</P>
<P>
   This was not easy. For it stalled unpredictably when idling and
needed lots of warning to brake. Steering it felt like Indian
wrestling and I didn't always win. Its final trip was carefully
routed for low speed and the ability to make rolling stops.
</P>
<P>
   But car and I creeped to the yard somehow and I slinked away
with $70 in American money. Much more than the cat would have
fetched.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are unhappy with anything but a stage-one
trophy-car. Some ruin the carefree time of a car's middle age by
looking for signs that it is slipping from stage two to stage
three. More prudent people ditch the heap the second they feel
stage-three car ownership upon with them.
</P>
<P>
   But me, I'm a firm believer in last-ditch driving. The beloved
old beast may be at the end of the road, but somewhere there's a
stage-two or stage-three car happily hitting road ruts thanks to
its transmission.
</P>
<P>
   It's the next best thing to reincarnation. Whether the cat can
beat that, I'll leave to theologians.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
