u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN15-COX     12-14 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keeping an eye on the 2000 election
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Albeit inadvertently, Bill Clinton has done
more for women
</P>
<P>
   with political aspirations than any of us ever could have
dreamed. His college-boy shenanigans in the White House have rolled
out a red carpet welcome for a woman in the Oval Office - this time
for all of the right reasons. If I'm reading the mood of this
country correctly, come the 2000 election even Little Mary Sunshine
would be a shoo-in for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, most folks are fed up to here with the mess going on
in the Washington sandbox, and would be happy to vote for Larry,
Moe, and Curly (or have we already done that?) if it would mean an
end to the babble. Lately, I've been trying to calculate exactly
how much of my money has been spent on lawyers arguing the
definition of ``is'' and debating what constitutes a sexual act. A
pretty sorry waste if you think about it, particularly when all we
really had to do was turn the bad boy over Hillary's knee and let
her wail on him with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   Too late for good ideas. We're in this farce up to our elbows
and all we can do now is plan for the future - the 2000 elections.
I have a few suggestions for the slate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vs. Dole: This has a familiar ring but the first names
of the players will have been changed to Hillary and Elizabeth. The
campaign should be squeaky clean since all of the mud has already
been slung.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole seems like a prime choice. She's an experienced
manager and
</P>
<P>
   obviously has plenty of political savvy. I worry a little about
Bob, though. He's obviously a good sport, but would he really be
happy in the little office down the hall from the big office?
</P>
<P>
   Hillary might be a good choice because she knows her way around.
Of course, she'd have her work cut out for her keeping an eye on
Bill. Maybe she should just let Buddy off the leash now that he's
housebroken, and keep Bill at her heel until his obedience training
kicks in. And as long as the First Husband laid off the
cheeseburgers and didn't blow up like an inflatable Ronald
McDonald, he could still fit into his tux and be useful at State
dinners to be sure the seating came out even. Boy-girl, boy-girl.
Of course, that's the stuff that got him into trouble in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Bill seems to have blown Hillary's chances of not
having to gather up the family photos and head for Arkansas come
election day - if he lasts that long. What could have been a simple
seat swap now becomes a classic case of damned if she does and
damned if she doesn't. If she gets rid of him, she's a callous
witch. If she keeps him, she still loses, because nobody really
wants him hanging around for another four years.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe what we need are co-presidents. I nominate Mary Matalin
and James Carville, two highly vocal political pundits representing
an even split - she's intelligent, informed, and a Republican. He's
brilliant, mouthy, and a Democrat. We'd still have the opposition
in bed with one another (as the political saying goes) only in this
case it would be legal.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe we need to look outside the realm of politics.
</P>
<P>
   How about Elizabeth Taylor? She doesn't need the money and she's
a survivor.
</P>
<P>
   She admits, ``I've been through it all, baby. I'm Mother
Courage.'' Elizabeth is pretty good at telling it like it is and
she swears she's finished with men so there'd be nothing to take
her mind off of her work.
</P>
<P>
   Or how about Ann Margret? She's pretty and she's gutsy. And she
rides a Harley.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe Kathy Bates. Gail, my self-described ``fluffy'' friend
in Oregon, says
</P>
<P>
   Kathy's election would strike a note for the ``zaftig'' women in
this country.
</P>
<P>
   My two prime candidates, unfortunately, are dead.
</P>
<P>
   Flinty and abrasive Bella Abzug could have been an Oval Office
virago - a female warrior determined to tell the truth and get
things done - slowing down only long enough to be sure her hat was
on straight.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Jordan would have been my first choice. She was quite a
lady; the first black Texan in the U.S. Congress and the speaker
who mesmerized a nation with her keynote address at the 1976
Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Jordan was a woman of character and when she spoke, she
spoke passionately for all people from a true and beautiful heart.
It's too bad she couldn't have hung around a while longer to give
this country a lesson in good
</P>
<P>
   manners.
</P>
<P>
   Each evening when I'm treated to yet another dose of
inner-beltway insanity on the evening news, a line from ``The Lion
in Winter'' comes to mind. Referring to the sorry state of their
marriage, their kids, and their country, Eleanor asks Henry, her
husband and king, ``How, from where we began did we ever reach this
place?'' Henry shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   Kind of makes you wonder what's next, doesn't it? Hulk Hogan for
President?
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett, a writer and teacher in Gibsonburg, Ohio,
writes for Cox
</P>
<P>
   News Service. Address mail to: 320 West Madison, Gibsonburg
43431 or e-mail to
</P>
<P>
   eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
