<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Job turmoil reflects strength of economy
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lumps of coal are being slipped into workers'
Christmas stockings everywhere. Boeing Co., Bankers Trust, Exxon
Corp., Mobil Corp. and Johnson &AMP; Johnson are among the many
companies announcing massive firings just in time for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Americans who thought they had secure jobs
with healthy companies are suddenly facing a new year filled with
difficult choices. Many will have to move their families to
unfamiliar cities to find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's hard to accept on a gut level, this job turmoil is a
sign of the economy's strength. Yes, strength.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. economy is the world's powerhouse because it adjusts so
quickly to market realities. So when oil prices plunge, the
executives at Mobil and Exxon don't fret about their fates; they
move fast to combine forces and cut costs. By slashing the ranks of
employees, the merged company will be in better shape to ride out
the oil industry's tough times.
</P>
<P>
   These layoffs, cruel as they may be to the individuals involved,
will help hold down fuel prices, making other companies, such as
airlines and trucking companies, even stronger.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence that layoffs can bolster the economy is clear:
While many companies have been firing workers in record numbers,
others have been hiring as fast as they can, sending the
unemployment rate to just 4.4 percent in November. Not counting
agriculture, employers created 267,000 jobs last month, an
amazingly large number.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no matter what our heads tell us about how the economy is
booming, our hearts sink when we get those pink slips. Accepting
the notion that getting fired is good for the country is not easy.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the roughly 300 employees of Atlantic Steel
Industries Inc. will lose their jobs at a company that has provided
paychecks for blue-collar workers since 1901.
</P>
<P>
   The old mill, on the northern edge of downtown Atlanta, will be
leveled and every trace carted away next year to make room for a
spectacular project that promises to create a high-tech office
park, apartments, hotel rooms, movie theaters and stores.
</P>
<P>
   The thousands of jobs that will be created through the Atlantic
Steel redevelopment plan will boost the area's economy. Switching
from metal making to computer networking will guarantee more wealth
in the next century. Sad as it is to see good blue-collar jobs
disappear, city officials were wise to push forward with
redevelopment plans rather than try to save an obsolete plant.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's willingness to embrace change largely explains its
phenomenal growth in the 1980s and 1990s. That was driven home to
me recently during a visit with family in Youngstown, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   There, many of the old steel mill sites, empty for years, still
have not been redeveloped. Instead of focusing all of their
attention on job creation, many local leaders continue to waste
valuable time calling on government to provide more trade
protection to save the few remaining steel jobs.
</P>
<P>
   This desire to cling to the familiar is understandable. But
because of advanced technology and a global marketplace, all
factories now rest on shifting sands and no job can be ``saved''
for long.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, about 45 percent of the private-sector work force
was employed in manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   Today, goods still account for about half of the nation's
output, but only 25 percent of workers are employed in
manufacturing. Robots and other equipment have replaced human
beings in factories. In coming years, that trend will accelerate.
And as skyscrapers sprout where rolling mills once flattened steel,
a new generation of workers will find plenty of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   This process of building up, tearing down and repositioning is
ceaseless. The communities that welcome change are the ones that
will flourish in the new century.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax is a member of The Atlanta Constitution editorial
board. She can be reached at mgeewax(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
