<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unlikely suspect Mercedes-Benz goes hot rod
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When most of us think of hot rods, cars like Z28
Camaros, 5.0 Mustangs or hemi-headed Mopars come to mind. Now
there's a new player in the hot rod segment, and an unusual one at
that.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz offers perhaps one of the most
performance-oriented lineups in the marketplace. Starting with the
C230 Kompressor sedan, the German automaker seems on a mission to
restore an almost lost commodity to the automotive marketplace _
torque.
</P>
<P>
   Any time torque exceeds horsepower ratings, driving enthusiasts
are pleased. The C230 Kompressor is right on target with 200
pounds-feet of torque and 185 horsepower. A zero-to-60-mph time of
8.1 seconds is nothing to sneeze at in a four-cylinder sedan.
Pricing is also palatable, beginning at $31,200.
</P>
<P>
   Want more? The C280 _ a V-6 equipped C-Class _ has 195
pounds-feet of torque and 194 hp. After a stint on an autocross
with a C280 equipped with the ``sport package,'' I experienced an
exceptionally wide power band and a 5-speed electronically
controlled automatic that will never leave you in search of the
proper gear.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the C280 gobble up the course, it ate the
competition on the clock as well. The C280 pricing begins at
$35,600, and the sport package, which you can add to either the 230
or 280, is $890 and provides a quicker-ratio steering box and
16-inch wheels with 205/55R16 performance tires.
</P>
<P>
   Still not enough? How 'bout strapping into the C43. With a price
of $53,000, the C43 is the cream of the C-Class crop.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes will produce only 1,500 of these super-sedans for U.S.
consumption. For the extra dough, you get exclusivity and a new
302-hp 4.3-liter V-8 engine borrowed from the E430 sedan. The C43
rocks with a zero-60 time of 5.9 seconds. Its top speed of 155 mph
is electronically limited.
</P>
<P>
   The C43 is the ultimate sleeper. What looks like a sedate sedan
will blow away most everything you can encounter at the stoplight.
</P>
<P>
   You would think that would be enough from Santa's Mercedes bag.
But, no, the newly announced E55 is an autobahn burner that will be
introduced in the United States this year.
</P>
<P>
   The E55 is as sedate as an Armani suit _ stylish, well-cut and
understated _ but make no mistake, Hulk Hogan is wearing this
outfit. The E55's 5.5-liter V-8 powerplant produces 349 hp and a
staggering 391 pounds-feet of torque at 3,000 rpm. Zero-to-60 is a
mere 5.4 seconds, and you can still take three friends to lunch in
luxurious comfort.
</P>
<P>
   And what a treat the E55 is to drive. It eats mountain curves,
but this full-sized, four-door hot rod will be hard to get.
Mercedes only plans to import 2,000 over the next four years at a
list price of $69,100.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp is a training consultant to auto manufacturers. Her
column is written exclusively for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Or send comments online to
sharpdriver(at)worldnet.att.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
