<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: How do you clean that black, crusted carbon-looking stuff on
the inside of glass fireplace screens? Also, my son and I are
``X-Files'' aficionados. Where can I find stuff for Christmas?
_Judi K.
</P>
<P>
   A: Some readers report luck with foaming bathroom cleaner to cut
the cruddy buildup on fireplace glass. Try it on a corner of the
glass to make sure it does not harm it. The glass must cool before
you clean it or it will streak _ permanently. There are cleaners
made specifically for this nasty stuff. ``X-Files'' shirts are on
sale at E! online. Call (888) 855-4979 or visit shop.eonline.com to
order. Want a Scully badge or the show's signature poster from
Mulder's office (``I Want To Believe'')? Contact the International
UFO Museum and Research Center at (800) 822-3545.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many miles does the average person walk in a lifetime?
_R. Walker
</P>
<P>
   A: The average person, according to the American Podiatric
Medical Association, walks an incredible 115,000 miles in a
lifetime (seems like more if your feet hurt). That is more than
four times the length of the equator.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why, oh why, does the symbol on a Volvo appear to be the
universal sign for ``male'' _ you know, a circle with an arrow
pointing out of it? Just wondering.
</P>
<P>
   _L. Tarver
</P>
<P>
   A: Sorry, no fiendish plot. The symbol dates from the Middle
Ages, says the public relations team at Volvo. It is the
alchemists' symbol for iron, frequently seen over the entrance to
iron mines in Europe. Volvo adopted it because of its association
with strength. The car company was founded in the 1920s by Swedes
Assar Gabrielsson and Gustaf Larson, of the SKF ball bearing
company. SKF gave the men ``seed money'' as well as the name
``Volvo'' (meaning ``I roll'' in Latin), from an extinct line of
bearings. What else but a car could use more ball bearings? Smart
guys, Assar and Gustaf. The emblem is currently used only on the
grill. The company did take a little heat from activists in the
1970s who thought the symbol had some hidden, male domination
meaning. Just not so.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last year you described a Christmas gift-exchange game that
used a version of ``'Twas the Night Before Christmas.'' Would it be
possible for me to get a copy of that? _Margo K.
</P>
<P>
   A: Of course. Players stand in a circle clutching a wrapped
present. They pass gifts (white elephant or otherwise) to the right
or left when the words ``right'' or ``left'' appear in the text. No
one ends up with the gift he brought to the party.
</P>
<P>
   For a copy, check out my name at Austin360.com or send me a
stamped, self-addressed envelope. And to all a good night.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I had the unfortunate experience of having a candle drip wax
onto my sofa. I don't know how to get it removed without further
damage to the fabric. Please let me know if you have a solution.
Also, could you publish this request, because I know I am not the
only person who has done such a bone-headed thing. _L.L.
</P>
<P>
   A: Good idea, since this is candle season and readers usually
find wax stuck to everything from carpet to cashmere. Here is the
process. Remove what you can with a dull knife. Then place the
fabric between two pieces of brown paper or paper towels. I use
grocery bags cut into manageable pieces. With a hair dryer or iron,
gently heat the fabric. A hair dryer is easier to use on furniture.
The wax adheres to the paper. Replace the paper with fresh pieces
and repeat. Eventually you will have only an oil stain, which can
be removed with traditional cleaning _ in the washer, by a dry
cleaner or with upholstery cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In March my VISA card was stolen and a fraudulent charge of
$172.12 came through before the credit card company could recognize
it as stolen. I completed the dispute form and included a letter
with a photocopied receipt clearly showing someone else's name and
signature. The charge is STILL showing up. Over the past eight
months I have logged 30-plus phone calls to all departments of
VISA. Other than a generic ``we're investigating the matter'' form
letter, I have received no replies to my requests. I've spoken with
service reps ad nauseam. I have also called Chase VISA's corporate
offices. The VP of customer service has not responded to my
certified letter. HELP _ I'm stuck in an endless loop! _B.H.
</P>
<P>
   A: You did everything you were supposed to do; Chase VISA
dropped the ball. Judy Miller in Chase's public relations
department has credited your account and apologizes for the delay.
When reporting stolen cards and fraudulent charges, call the
service number on your statement and the fraud division will credit
your account after receiving your written affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane S. Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, Texas 78767;
(512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512)
445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   For copies of Jane's book, ``Thanks for Asking!'' _ a
compilation of more than 600 favorite questions and answers _ call
(800) 424-6291.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
