<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MacPac tunes up PalmPilot's power
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it comes to hand-held computers, Mac users had
been playing second fiddle to their PC counterparts. No longer.
</P>
<P>
   3Com is finally readying Mac software for its popular PalmPilot
hand-held computer after months of delay. The software had been
promised by last summer. Oh well.
</P>
<P>
   The delay, however, appears to have been worth the wait. Initial
reports in the computer trade press say the Mac version of
PalmPilot software is as good, if not better, than its PC
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   If true, that's great news for the Mac community. The PalmPilot,
which has sold some 2 million-plus units in the past several years,
is the only hand-held computer that lets you back up and
synchronize your personal information on a Mac.
</P>
<P>
   There are scores of alternatives now for PC users, including the
PalmPilot itself. What makes hand-held computers powerful is the
ability to maintain one calendar and Rolodex across many platforms.
That is, with the right software, you can update and synchronize
the same information on a desktop and a hand-held computer.
</P>
<P>
   For PalmPilot, the Mac version of this synchronizing software is
called MacPac. The first version was a clunky replica of the PC
software. Worse, MacPac didn't even work on a lot of Macs.
</P>
<P>
   PalmPilot hopes to improve on that with MacPac 2.0, which is
based on the old Claris Organizer. 3Com bought the popular personal
information manager from Apple Computer earlier this year and
announced it would remake the software for its PalmPilot.
</P>
<P>
   That proved a more difficult task than initially thought. But
the final results are looking good. Says reviewer Jason Snell in
the January issue of MacWorld, ``This new Palm Desktop is Mac
through and through, right down to the Apple-gray interface.''
</P>
<P>
   MacPac 2.0 is not yet ready for commercial release. But you can
download a beta version of it from several sites, including
MacWorld and PalmPilot.
</P>
<P>
   Be forewarned. Beta software is often unstable and can corrupt
both operating systems and other software.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
