<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The top 10 Web sites
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As David Letterman proves nightly, everyone loves a
top-ten list. At the end of the year, people love top-ten lists
even more. For the Web, 1998 was quite a year. For what it's worth,
here's my personal top ten Web sites of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   1. Yahoo (http://www.yahoo.com): Still the most popular site on
the Web, what was once just a list of cool links has morphed into a
multimedia empire. Only America Online rivals it in size and scope.
From search to shopping to news, stocks and chat, Yahoo is a force
to be reckoned with for everyone doing business on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   2. The Drudge Report: (http://www.drudgereport.com): Last year,
Matt Drudge was just a punk kid from L.A. dishing the dirt from his
cramped Sunset Boulevard apartment. But that was before he got wind
of Newsweek's story about Monica Lewinsky and the rest, as they
say, is history. Now Drudge is a daily must-read for news
organizations everywhere and the fedora-wearing newshound is
pontificating on his brand of populist journalism at places like
Harvard and the National Press Club. In a year filled with breaking
news, Drudge helped make the Web a major player.
</P>
<P>
   3. Salon Magazine (http://www.salonmagazine.com): The literary
e-zine was already a cult favorite before the relentless attacks on
the Ken Starr investigation and its Henry Hyde expose. The
publicity moved Salon into the limelight where it stays with a
strong mix of news and commentary. It also introduced a voluntary
and novel membership plan as an alternative revenue stream.
</P>
<P>
   4. CNN Interactive, MSNBC, ABCNews.com: Constant updates,
personalization features and the ability to ``stop the presses'' to
make way for breaking news made these the big three of online news.
The rapid response of the net to breaking news such as the Starr
Report or midterm elections proved the Web is one of the best
places to get a quick news fix almost the second it happens.
</P>
<P>
   5. Amazon (http://www.amazon.com): Unless your modem has been
unplugged for the last year, chances are pretty good you've ordered
a book from Amazon.com or know somebody who has. When a friend
remarked he just 'amazoned' a book, and everyone knew what he
meant, it was clear Amazon has become a bookseller and a brand to
be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   6. America Online: With 14 million subscribers, 20 million
users, a zillion chat rooms, fascinating and timely message boards,
spam controls and a shopping environment more secure than Fort Knox
and a new deal with Netscape, AOL is a virtual main street of news,
commerce and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   7. Slate (http://www.slate.com): The Microsoft-run, Michael
Kinsley-edited online journal of ideas defied analysts and began
charging for access to most of its content. The magazine showed
real guts and promise late in the year when it dispatched author
Michael Lewis to comment on the Microsoft trial. Lewis' reports
were largely unbiased, colorful accounts that seemed to reinforce
Kinsley's insistence that Microsoft did not influence Slate's
content or editorial decisions. However, Lewis' tenure was
short-lived and he was soon replaced by Slate staffers who admitted
their Microsoft bias, leaving many wondering how much independence
Slate really has.
</P>
<P>
   8: MindSpring (http://www.mindspring.net): It's not really a Web
site, but Atlanta-based MindSpring, one of the largest independent
Internet service providers, has practically become the poster child
for the wild ride Internet stocks have had on Wall Street. Customer
service is good, busy signals are rare and a three-legged dog is
the company mascot. The fact MindSpring is turning a profit is just
icing on the cake.
</P>
<P>
   9: eBay (http://www.ebay.com): Proof positive that people are
willing to buy almost anything on the Web. Consumers are busy
snapping up Brady Bunch lunchboxes, while publishers are wondering
if they should aggressively pursue putting their classified ads on
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   10. Snap: (http://www.snap.com): In the year of the portal it
seemed like everybody wanted to get into the act, including Snap.
Just another anemic little portal site until NBC came along with
big bucks and big ideas, Snap is constantly developing top notch
areas, including a commerce area and a news area that reports news
from the best sources, not just NBC news sources. Snap illustrates
what a little luck and a lot of money can do.
</P>
<P>
   What's Hot
</P>
<P>
   Dark and Stormy Southern Nights: Grab a lantern and take a long
walk down the Moonlit Road, a beautiful site devoted to ghost
stories and folktales from some of the South's best known
storytellers. http://www.themoonlitroad.comYou've Got Mail: The Web
site for the new Tom Hanks/Meg Ryan romantic comedy has a neat Web
site that's interesting and fun.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.youvegotmail.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
