<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Free gifts are lurking in crevices of Windows 98
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It probably shouldn't work this way but _ at this time
of the year _ almost everything has a price tag on it. If you are
like me, your credit cards have already worked so hard they're
developing muscles.
</P>
<P>
   That's why we'll spend today looking at my favorite kind of
computer software _ free stuff.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start with some software you already have installed if you
own Windows 98. Now, if you are familiar with Windows at all, you
probably think you know the programs I mean. You're thinking about
the nifty games that come with Windows, or perhaps some of the
utilities such as Scandisk or Defrag. Those are excellent programs,
but I want to introduce you to some strangers that are lurking
around your Start menu or hiding even more skillfully on your
Windows 98 installation disc.
</P>
<P>
   My first candidate is almost certainly already on your hard
disk. It's called Microsoft System Information, and you'll find it
by following this twisting trail. Go to the Start menu, then to
Programs, then to Accessories, then to System Tools and finally to
this program.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have it running, you'll see it provides a window into
the inner workings of your computer. If, for instance, you run into
a conflict that makes it tough to install a new sound card or other
device, you'll find a lot of information here. But, as we used to
say back in the days when I wrote commercials, there's still more.
</P>
<P>
   With the System Information program running, go to the Tools
menu and select Registry Checker. You probably already know that
the Registry is where Windows keeps some of its most basic settings
stored. Problems here can really mess up your computer. When you
start up the Registry Checker, it will also automatically make a
backup copy of these settings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, go back to the Tools menu and select System File Checker.
You'll be given the chance to scan Windows for altered files and
given help automatically restoring an intact version. This tool is
really excellent, and I urge you to use it from time to time. It
also gives you the ability to manually restore files from the
Windows installation disc. If you've ever tried doing that with the
archaic DOS command called Extract, you'll recognize that this
program is worth its weight in RAM chips.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of other useful programs under the Tools menu,
including a Version Conflict Manager and a System Configuration
Utility. Take some time learning about these programs on your own
using the Help menu.
</P>
<P>
   I wish there was time to cover them all, but I want to tell you
about one more free program you already own before I run out of
space.
</P>
<P>
   Editing the Registry is really a complicated mess. And mistakes
can turn your computer into a simpering idiot. There is a program
that can help. However, this program isn't installed on your
computer. You'll need to put your Windows 98 installation disc in
your computer and go to the Tools folder. Continue double-clicking
away into the subdirectories of this folder. Open Reskit and then
open Powertoy. Then find a file named tweakui.inf and click on it
using the right button (make sure to use the right, not the left
button) of your mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Now select Install. Once you have the program called Tweak UI
installed _ and that's what you just did _ you'll get automated
help in editing the Registry file. You'll find ways to change
settings on your computer that can only be edited from within the
Registry.
</P>
<P>
   Even with this tool, Registry editing makes a danged poor hobby.
But at least you'll get familiar-looking Windows screens to make
things easier.
</P>
<P>
   OK. That's my Christmas gift this season _ two free programs
that really can make using Windows 98 easier. If you'd like to
thank me, then do something really radical this holiday season.
Turn the computer off for a few nights and sit next to the
altogether kinder light that comes from your fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
