<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHTOOLS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Encarta reference suite comes on single DVD
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To conclude our look at the latest crop of electronic
encyclopedias, we'll take a very brief glance at the 1999 DVD
version of the Encarta reference suite, and then move on to some
other encylopedic sorts of things.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the DVD reference suite is nothing more than the
Deluxe Encarta plus Microsoft's very useful Bookshelf and the
Visual Globe. The trick, of course, is that material which takes up
five ordinary CD-ROMs is here presented on one _ with more
multimedia thrown in for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   This may not sound impressive unless you have gone through the
annoying disc-shuffling that rummaging through all the separate
programs would require. I despair of accurately predicting anything
_ I didn't think CNN would last a year and figured the Internet was
a passing fancy _ so I won't tell you DVD is the wave of the
future. I just hope it is.
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic maps available on CD
</P>
<P>
   Some of you (one hopes) may remember last year's milestone in
electronic reference publishing _ the complete, right down to the
last advertisement, National Geographic magazine, from the first
edition to December 1996. Mindscape, the firm which brought that
off, has both kept the faith and upped the ante. A CD-ROM
containing the complete Geographic for 1997 is now available.
</P>
<P>
   And so, in an eight-disc edition new this fall, is every foldout
map National Geographic ever produced. Called National Geographic
maps, the set comes in a little zip-up case for a remarkable price
of $80 or so.
</P>
<P>
   As with the magazine set, the pleasure is not unalloyed. Once
again, all the material here has been scanned in directly from the
original pages. This meant it was less than ideally sharp and
somewhat hard to read.
</P>
<P>
   With the maps, it means they are small and when zoomed up to
readability, can be hard to read, and are also partially obscured
by an overall image of the map that insists on staying where it is.
The maps can be zoomed, but the original size of the image will not
change unless you manually enlarge the window.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if all you want are current maps, you can get better
quality with nearly any electronic atlas or, for North America at
least, with any of the trip-planning programs. But that's not the
point here. In addition to the current maps, there are a great
number of historical, sociological and other kind of maps.
</P>
<P>
   There are also some absorbing features _ milestones of mapping,
a kind of history of cartography and milestones of the magazine
itself.
</P>
<P>
   And _ wonder of wonders _ Hewlett-Packard worked with Mindscape
to produce a means of printing these maps, in their original color
and detail. Of course, this will generally entail either printing
them one per page, which means most will be too tiny to read,
printing a section of a map or printing a map that is tiled onto
several pages.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, this is one more wonderful resource for the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
