<HEADER>
A8389 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-MECHANIC15-COX     12-14 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leave time for emission testing snags
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Amid the usual plethora of holiday greetings, bills
and catalogs, some of you will be receiving your vehicle
registration renewal notice for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Because 1999 is an odd-numbered year, odd-year vehicles (1975,
1987, 1991, etc.) will need to be emissions tested before new tags
are issued. Most of you are already aware there are two different
kinds of emissions inspection stations. The ``all vehicles
welcome'' stations with dynamometers perform both the two-speed
idle (TSI) and the acceleration simulation mode (ASM). They have
the capability to test all vehicles back to 1975.
</P>
<P>
   However, the ``1993 and newer'' signs for stations performing
only the TSI test may offer some confusion if you are planning to
avoid the rush and get your 1993 vehicle tested early for next
year's tags.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, a 1993 vehicle is considered six years old and no
longer a ``newer vehicle.'' It must be tested at an ``all
vehicles'' test station. The signs don't reflect this because we
are still in the 1998 test year and tag season until Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Mary drives a 1993 Cavalier and must renew her tags
by her birthday, Jan. 2. That means the car needs to be emissions
tested this month so she can mail the paperwork to the tag office.
On Dec. 12, she drives to a ``1993 and newer vehicles'' inspection
station during her lunch hour. After all, she has a 1993 car.
</P>
<P>
   After waiting in line behind two other vehicles, it's her turn.
But the inspector informs her he is not allowed to test her car
because it will be considered more than six years old in 1999 and
he can't test ``older vehicles.'' She must have it tested at an
``all vehicles'' station. Mary drives off, angry and frustrated
because she wasted her lunchtime and still needs to get her car
tested.
</P>
<P>
   Susan's tags for her 1993 Toyota are also due in January. She
takes her car to an ``all vehicles'' station. She is surprised the
car needs a different kind of inspection, the ASM test, instead of
the short TSI test performed in 1997. Before the inspector drives
the car onto the dynamometer, he checks the tire pressure of the
drive wheels and notices the tires are dangerously worn. He informs
Susan she will need to replace the tires with safe ones before he
can test the car.
</P>
<P>
   John's Jan. 3 birthday means he must get a December emission
inspection for his '93 Taurus, but he procrastinates until late in
the month. He goes to the ``all vehicles'' station close to work.
Its ESP test equipment is not working, but it should be fixed by
tomorrow. Not a problem; he has three days. The following morning,
the equipment is still broken. Everyone else who tests ``all
vehicles'' in the area is swamped with fellow procrastinators.
Finally, at 4:30 p.m. on New Year's Eve he races to the ESP station
just as they are getting ready to lock up. The owner takes pity on
him, hands him a beer and tests the car, which passes. He then
speeds to the post office and spends $3 to express mail the
registration paperwork. On the way home he gets stopped for DUI.
His car gets impounded and he spends his birthday in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Please don't let this happen to you. ``1993 and newer vehicles''
test stations cannot test 1993 vehicles for the 1999 tag season. Go
to the right place. Give yourself plenty of time. It might be a
good idea to call ahead to make sure the equipment is operating
and, most importantly, don't drink and drive.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 26 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, is an automotive instructor at DeKalb Technical Institute
and an ASE master automobile technician/L-1. Write her in care of
Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta,
GA 30302. Or send comments online to
nora(at)admin2.dekalb.tec.ga.us or 2wrenchs(at) bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
