 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, December 15, 1998 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ BLACKSTUMP VALLEY, Texas _ A journey to find the
stump and old school that Stacy Tidwell, a 90-year-old Waco
resident, former Iredell merchant and one-time Bosque County
treasurer, still remembers. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-COLUMN _ Michael Skube is on vacation this week. (Skube,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Albeit inadvertently, Bill
Clinton has done more for women with political aspirations than any
of us ever could have dreamed. His shenanigans in the White House
have rolled out a red carpet welcome for a woman in the Oval
Office. Truth is, most folks are fed up to here with the mess going
on in the Washington sandbox, and would be happy to vote for Larry,
Moe, and Curly if it would mean an end to the babble. We're in this
farce up to our elbows and all we can do now is plan for the future
- the 2000 elections. I have a few suggestions for the slate.
(Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's beautiful when a
plan to ignore partisan politics comes together. It's more than
beautiful when two governors _ the late Lawton Chiles and
Gov.-elect Bush _ decide independently that the best candidate for
the Florida Supreme Court is an outstanding jurist with a
distinguished legal career who just happens to be a black woman.
(Jefferson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ A good cat and a good car have roughly the same
life span. Actually, a good car and a good cat share a lot of other
similarities, as well. Neither demands constant attention. Both
purr when they're happy and neither leaves messes on the floor.
Neither one will burst into flames unexpectedly. But no matter how
good a car or cat is, both start reaching their design limits after
about 15 years. And that's why I found myself sadly walking from a
junkyard recently after selling out a faithful, 15-year-old,
198,000-mile car. (Lane, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ The only whistle that might stop the
House impeachment train _ the zealots' express _ is corporate
America. Wall Street. When business talks, Republicans listen.
(Ezzard, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Many years ago when we were
house-hunting, our real estate agent picked us up in her new car to
show us some houses. After we got into her car, we heard a robotic
voice say ``Your door is ajar. Your door is ajar.'' Alarmed, we
shut the door. ``Thank you,'' came the tinny voice. That was our
first experience with ``talking cars.'' It also was our last. I
don't want my car to talk to me. If I have to resort to having
conversations with a vehicle, I need to check into the nearest
chapter of Get-A-Life Anonymous. (Kabat, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
