<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8400 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN15-COX     12-14 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The zealots' express rolls on
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The only whistle that might stop the House impeachment
train _ the zealots' express _ is corporate America. Wall Street.
When business talks, Republicans listen.
</P>
<P>
   If the respected Robert Rubin, secretary of the Treasury, gets
on the horn to big funders of conservative politicians, Speaker
Newt Gingrich and Speaker-to- be Bob Livingston might stop playing
dead. They might stop letting GOP Whip Tom Delay of Texas, who's
filling the leadership void, twist the arms of moderates. No
constitutional whiz, Delay says voting articles of impeachment is
simply a tougher form of censure. Even DeLay might listen to Big
Oil.
</P>
<P>
   Crass tactics? On a par with the crassness of a Linda Tripp, a
Kenneth Starr and a former Georgia prosecutor on Starr's staff,
Bruce Udolf. Udolf is the man who was fined by a federal judge for
violating a citizen's constitutional rights with his unethical
tactics. Udolf was one member of the Starr team who told Monica
Lewinsky, when prosecutors first detained her, that her lawyer in a
civil case couldn't help her. The former Gainesville, Ga., district
attorney actually had a man thrown in jail on a bogus charge to try
to coerce testimony from him. A federal judge fined him $50,000,
ruling a prosecutor's immunity wouldn't protect him from
constitutional violations. Starr hired him 10 years later anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   But nevermind the prosecutors and the lawyers. This battle will
be won or lost on the same factors that win or lose campaigns _
partisan pressure and lobbying. That's where the corporate donors
come in. They may not love Clinton, but they love the economic
climate he's helped create. And they aren't willing to risk market
instability to bring him down.
</P>
<P>
   If the partisan hatred for Clinton can't be overcome by the
American people saying they don't want their vote overturned _
maybe big money lobbies can stop it.
</P>
<P>
   There's no enthusiasm for defending the president's sins. A look
at the strongly worded Democratic censure resolution confirms that.
And Clinton's personal reputation isn't worth saving. But the
country and the Constitution are. So is the national interest that
should weigh as heavily on the minds of conscientious decision
makers (the few around) as whether lying under oath about sex is an
impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   For the few representatives who will strive for independent
courage under pressure, here's my favorite historical model: Daniel
Webster's March 7, 1851 vote to save the union and fend off
Southern secession another decade.
</P>
<P>
   Webster abhorred slavery. But he supported a compromise offered
by Henry Clay that was silent on whether the new Western
territories must prohibit slavery. No Northern Whig concurred with
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish to speak not as a Massachusetts man, nor as a Northern
man, but as an American,'' he said. ``I speak today for
preservation of the Union.'' Historian Henry Steele Commager called
Webster's words an example of ``the highest statesmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Abhorrent as the president's behavior was, it did not subvert
government institutions. The constitutional process will be forever
changed by the House vote to impeach on moral grounds whether the
Senate goes through with a trial or not.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street could save us. But it would be better for the
country if political courage did.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. She can be reached at mezzard(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
