u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN16-CO     12-14 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Britain's Monty dispatched to docket of revisionism
 &HT;    (For release Wednesday, Dec. 16, 1998.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The rewriting of World War II and its immediate
aftermath continues at a furious pace. Begun shortly after the
conclusion of hostilities in 1945, the revisions have encompassed
subjects as varying as the reasons for the turn of certain battles,
Dwight Eisenhower's imputed love affair with his British driver,
and the institutional corruption associated with the confiscation
of funds and property from Europe's Jews during that deadly period.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most dramatic _ and therefore more attractive to the
media _ have been situations involving the Jewish condition during
that war.
</P>
<P>
   It often is said that the winners write the history books on
wars, and by and large they do. But it takes awhile for all of the
story to slip out. Even today, as 1998 draws to a close, particles
of information continue to spew forth from documents long
sequestered in musty files of the winners.
</P>
<P>
   When the 1970 epic film ``Patton'' was released, there was not a
word in it about well-documented evidence that the great Army
commander was a virulent anti-Semite who favored the fallen Nazi
guards over their former Jewish inmates. Indeed, it was that fact
that played the single most important role in Eisenhower's sacking
Patton.
</P>
<P>
   George Patton has long been an American hero. There was no
greater fighting general. Yet, whenever his name is mentioned in
the presence of a Jew, the ugly memory of Patton's biases surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   And, now, his greatest battlefield competitor, an ally no less,
has been unclothed in much the same vein. British Field Marshal
Bernard Montgomery, according to Great Britain's Jewish Chronicle
newspaper of Dec. 11, sought to have the Jews striving for a
national homeland in 1946 ``completely and utterly'' defeated in
that effort.
</P>
<P>
   If Patton was America's most beloved fighting man, Montgomery
was Great Britain's. Accusations such as that can sully his legacy
but only slightly, as it did Patton's.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, a letter written by Montgomery and recently
discovered in England's Public Record Office does show Monty of a
mind to deal harshly with Jewish refugees. Among his postwar
assignments was to monitor illegal movements of Jews from Europe to
Palestine. At times, interdictions of Jewish refugees led to
violence and Monty had to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means war with the illegal Jewish army with all that that
implies,'' the 1946 Montgomery letter says in part. ``The Jew is
clever and cunning. He is likely to refuse to engage in pitched
battles with our troops; instead he will go in for sabotage and
kidnapping and generally will try to exhaust our patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is precisely what Jewish nationalist movements did, and
successfully.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery's letter warned that the death sentence may have to
be imposed on some Jews, or we ``will lay up for ourselves great
trouble in the future. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Are these the words of an anti-Semite, or of a field general
assessing a military circumstance?
</P>
<P>
   This will be left open to interpretation, and I can pretty well
guess that among Jews he'll be seen in negative tones, among
non-Jews as a man carrying out his responsibility against what then
was seen as Jewish terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, however, how will we remember men such as Ike,
Patton and Montgomery? Will they be memorialized for what came out
of World War II's wastebaskets, or for what they accomplished
against the common enemy, Nazi Germany?
</P>
<P>
   As worldwide journalism continues to revel in revisionism, more
of this is likely. It is the stuff of somewhat skewed headlines.
Such as that which topped the front page of the Jewish Chronicle:
``Monty Wanted Jews Executed.''
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
