<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Where have you gone, Archie Moore?
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are some people you never think of in terms of dying.
Archie Moore, the former light-heavyweight boxing champion, was one
of them. His 84-year-old heart finally gave out the other day.
Where have you gone, Archie Moore, the nation turns its lonely eyes
to you, goes the song _ approximately.
</P>
<P>
   Archie Moore _ he was always Archie Moore to me, never just
Moore _ was probably best memorialized in the late A.J. Liebling's
New Yorker essay on his 1955 fight with Rocky Marciano. Archie
Moore, Liebling tells us, had learned that any boxer would go if
hit right. In the second round, Archie Moore hit Marciano right
with a perfect combination. Rocky went down. Archie Moore walked
calmly to a corner. When he turned around he saw Marciano getting
up. The look in Archie Moore's eyes, Liebling tells us, said it was
over. Seven rounds later, Marciano knocked him out.
</P>
<P>
   Archie Moore gave me the best night of sports I've ever known.
It was his 1958 fight with Yvon Durelle, the Canadian light-heavy.
Durelle knocked Archie Moore down four times in the early rounds.
Then Archie Moore started coming back, punishing Durelle with left
jabs. He knocked Durelle out in the 11th. It was the most amazing
demonstration of courage in sports I have ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I know boxing is brutal and dehumanizing and ought to be
outlawed. But what would we have done without Benny Leonard, Joe
Louis, Rocky Marciano, Muhammad Ali?
</P>
<P>
   And Archie Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
