u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     12-14 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LOWERS IMPEACHMENT STANDARD, IMPERILS PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1998 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republicans in the House Judiciary Committee made it clear
Friday that the impeachment action against President Clinton is a
payback for the impeachment articles drawn up against Republican
President Nixon. Nothing more, nothing less.
</P>
<P>
   Committee member Rep. Howard Coble, R-N.C., gleefully pointed
this out in his reference to the Nixon impeachment when the
Democrats were in the majority in Congress: ``It's a lot easier to
throw grenades than to catch them.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP's need for revenge was going to corner a Democratic
president, any Democratic president _ when the time was right, when
the GOP controlled the Congress. It happened to be Clinton _ for
his foolish liaison and for being so embarrassed by it when it was
discovered that he couldn't be forthright in admitting his sexual
escapade.
</P>
<P>
   And so on Dec. 11, 1998, for only the third time in this
nation's history, articles of impeachment were drawn up against a
president _ Andrew Johnson in 1868, Richard Nixon in 1974 and now
William Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's action embroils America in a serious
constitutional crisis. Unless the U.S. House votes against the
articles of impeachment, Clinton's trial in the Senate will end up
degrading the prestige of the office of the president and tilting
the balance of powers toward an imperial Congress.
</P>
<P>
   A key question rang out all week long during the judiciary
committee's hearings: Does Clinton's sexual infidelity and his
lying about it constitute what the U.S. Constitution, Article II,
Section 4 calls ``other high crimes and misdemeanors''? No, say the
committee Democrats, constitutional scholars, and a majority of the
American public. Yes, shout the Republican committee members. The
Republicans outnumber the Democrats on the committee 21 to 16.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who chairs the judiciary committee, has
a ticklish dilemma. He was involved with a married woman 30 years
ago and broke up the woman's marriage. Undoubtedly, he must have
lied many times about and during that lengthy affair. Hyde, too,
was married at the time. Her husband has neither forgotten nor
forgiven Hyde _ for what Hyde glibly calls a youthful indiscretion.
And now Hyde sits in judgment of a man who also had an affair.
Apparently, Hyde doesn't mind throwing the first stone.
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, Clinton was charged with the first article of
impeachment _ that he had committed perjury in his testimony to a
federal grand jury investigating his relationship to Monica
Lewinsky. The vote went down party lines _ 21 to 16.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, the committee voted for a second article of
impeachment _ accusing Clinton of committing perjury by his
testimony in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit. The vote
went down party lines _ 20 to 17. Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., who
could not support an impeachment charge for lying in a civil
lawsuit, voted with the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, a third article of impeachment was adopted by a
party-line vote, 21 to 16. It accuses Clinton of obstructing
justice in the Jones lawsuit and cites seven instances when Clinton
attempted to ``delay, impede, cover up and conceal'' evidence in
the case. This article echoes the language used in the first
article of impeachment against Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   The House committee then adjourned after nine hours of partisan
wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the committee added a fourth article of impeachment
on a straight party-line vote _ charging the president with abuse
of power for not responding honestly to the committee's 81
questions.
</P>
<P>
   The charges sound serious, but federal prosecutors who testified
before the judiciary committee stated that the evidence of perjury
presented by special prosecutor Kenneth Starr would not be
sufficient to seek a criminal indictment. The other charges are
merely high-sounding fluff.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress were to begin impeachment hearings against every
president who had illicit sexual affairs while in office and lied
about it, easily a third of all our presidents would have faced
impeachment. If every president who lied to the American people
over foreign and domestic policies and federal actions were to face
impeachment, no president would finish a term in office.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the lying behind the Iran-Contra, drugs-for-weapons
affair, the presidential lies to cover up our bungling in the
Vietnam War, the misleading statements about why we were involved
in the Gulf War, the lies about the accuracy of our weaponry in
that war.
</P>
<P>
   The founding fathers intended impeachment for only the greatest
offenses _ treason, bribery, misapplication of funds, abuse of
official power, and neglect of duty _ not for covering up an
adulterous affair. They did not intend the impeachment power to be
used to overturn the results of an election _ unless the
president's actions were destroying the very foundation of our
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee has significantly lowered the
impeachment standard. If upheld, these articles of impeachment will
imperil every president who faces a Congress dominated by the
opposing party. The new standard weakens the presidency _ and
throws the checks and balances among the three branches of
government into disarray.
</P>
<P>
   History will not be kind to those who engineered this dangerous
political revenge _ neither should the American voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
