<HEADLINE>
`OUT OF SIGHT' WINS WITH BOSTON CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``Out of Sight,'' a frisky crime-caper movie based on
an Elmore Leonard novel that found favor with critics but not with
audiences, was named best film of 1998 by the Boston Film Critics
Society at its annual meeting Sunday. It edged out John Boorman's
Irish crime movie, ``The General,'' and Steven Spielberg's odds-on
Oscar favorite, ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Janusz Kaminski's best
cinematography award was the only win for ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   The voting was reversed in the best director category. Boorman
took that award, finishing ahead of Steven Soderbergh, the ``Out of
Sight'' helmer. Italy's Roberto Begnini was second runner-up for
``Life Is Beautiful,'' his improbably charming and life-affirming
Holocaust fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Gleeson was named best actor for his portrayals of
Dublin crimelord and anti-authoritarian folk hero Martin Cahill in
``The General'' and a trouble-prone thug in another Irish gangster
film, ``I Went Down.'' He finished ahead of George Clooney's
whimsical thief in ``Out of Sight'' and John Hurt's English
professor obsessed with a young actor in ``Love and Death on Long
Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Samantha Morton was cited as best actress for her riveting
portrait of a young woman grieving for her dead mother in
loose-cannon fashion in a little-seen British film, Carine Adler's
``Under the Skin.'' Ally Sheedy's neurasthenic photographer in Lisa
Cholodenko's ``High Art'' was runner-up. Cate Blanchett's evolving
Queen Elizabeth I in ``Elizabeth'' and Jane Horrocks's agoraphobic
vocal impersonator in ``Little Voice'' were tied for second
runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the supporting acting award winners are better known
to the public than the leading acting winners. Joan Allen was cited
for her mix of dread and excitement as the perfect '50s TV sitcom
mom shoved into colorful change in ``Pleasantville.'' Runners-up
were Patricia Clarkson for her unhappy German artist in ``High
Art'' and Bridget Fonda for her small-town wife affected by her
husband's discovery of tainted money in ``A Simple Plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Bob Thornton was named best supporting actor for playing
the simpler but more soulful of the two brothers who stumble onto
the money in a snowy field in ``A Simple Plan.'' Tied as runners-up
were Stephen Rea for his imploded Irish father in ``The Butcher
Boy,'' Robert De Niro for his updated criminal benefactor in the
``Great Expectations'' remake, and William H. Macy for roles in
``Pleasantville,'' ``A Civil Action,'' and the ``Psycho'' remake.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Frank won the best screenplay award for his adaptation of
Leonard's novel in ``Out of Sight,'' finishing ahead of Tom
Stoppard's witty script for ``Shakespeare in Love'' and the four
writers who fashioned the screenplay for the lowbrow hit ``There's
Something About Mary.'' Finishing behind Kaminski in the best
cinematography voting were John Lindley for ``Pleasantville'' and
Alar Kavilo for ``A Simple Plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The best foreign language award went to Abbas Kiarostami's ``A
Taste of Cherry,'' a nod not only to Kiarostami but to Iranian
cinema's emerging importance. Thomas Vinterberg's ``The
Celebration,'' a scathing family portrait from another Danish
director of the deglamorizing school of filmmaking that produced
``Breaking the Waves'' a few years ago was next, followed by ``Life
Is Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Moore's essay in corporate muckraking, ``The Big One,''
was named best documentary. Also cited were Tim Kirkland's ``Dear
Jesse,'' taking on North Carolina Senator Jesse Helms, and ``Theme:
Murder,'' Martha Swetzoff's personal documentary examining the
unsolved murder of her father.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
