<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Dec. 14, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MARINES-KILLING (Redford, Texas) _ A senior FBI agent and a
Texas Ranger who investigated the killing of a youth by a Marine
leading an anti-drug patrol here contend the military obstructed an
inquiry of the death. They want a grand jury to consider the matter
for a third time. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   RPI-PRESIDENT (Troy, N.Y.) _ Shirley Ann Jackson, whose life
story traverses the mysteries of quantum physics and the realities
of the nation's racial divide, has been named the 18th president of
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute. Jackson is currently head of the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission. By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CORRESPONDENT-MISSING (Mexico City) _ Philip True, the Mexico
City correspondent for the San Antonio Express-News, has been
reported missing while on a hike tracing the route of the Huichol
Indians in a remote area of the Sierra Madre Occidental in the
states of Durango, Jalisco and Nayarit. True, 50, last spoke with
his wife, Marta, on Nov. 29, from Zacatecas, Mexico. By The San
Antonio Express-News.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-LOUNGES (San Francisco) _ Full-body massages. Manicures.
Haircuts. Free drinks. Internet access. Fax machines and copiers,
of course. Nice showers. Steaming dim sum. How about a putting
green? These are some of the lures that airlines use to attract
high-paying business-class flyers in new VIP lounges at major
airports around the world. By DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader wants to know about a
SyQuest SparQ drive that he recently bought and why no one is
answering his pleas for help when he calls the company for support
help. A Q&AMP;A. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WOODEN-TOYS (East Galway, N.Y.) _ There is the interactive world
of Furby, Tigger and Barney, and then there is Woody Herman's toy
shop. Far from this modern toy landscape, Herman's shop is in a
chilly barn, where, from scraps of fine wood, Herman churns out
hundreds of wooden trains, race cars, trucks and helicopters. By
MICHAEL LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   PET-VODKA (Undated) _ One of the more peculiar pairings we've
encountered is between Grey Goose Vodka and the American Society
for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals. The spirit brand gives 1
percent of profits to the ASPCA. The holiday marketing campaign
stretches amusingly to convey its message about how ideal booze is
as a present, while pets are less of a best bet. By STEVE BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   BIRDCAGE-DECOR (Albany, N.Y.) _ Birdcages can be works of art in
themselves. If you're not enthusiastic about cleaning up after
plumed critters or can't stand their chirping, singing or talking,
consider the birdcage as simply a decorative room accessory. By
FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   HANUKKAH (San Francisco) _ On the scale of importance, Hanukkah
is a Jewish holiday that ranks with Purim _ far below Passover,
Rosh Hashana and Yom Kippur. But don't tell David Eiland, co-owner
of Just For Fun, a gift shop. By VENISE WAGNER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-MOVIES (San Francisco) _ The lesson of the poor box
office showing of the ``Babe'' sequel is that viewers found the new
territory too scary. The result was the resignation of Universal
Pictures production chief Casey Silver. By WALTER ADDIEGO.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-CHRISTMAS (San Francisco) _ If you've just found this column
cut out and left on the bathroom sink, someone wants Santa to know
what's on the golfer's wish list. After all, there's something in
every price range, and most gifts can be ordered from catalogs and
by the Internet, as well as from retailers and pro shops. Here's
the top 10 for just about any year and just about any handicap. By
SUSAN FORNOFF.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-BALLOTS (San Francisco) _ The Baseball Hall of Fame
ballots went out last week with all the attendant drama of a sheep
shearing on a sheep farm during the 4-H Sheep Shearing Festival. By
RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (South Lake Tahoe, Nev.) _ Though the winter
solstice is still 10 days off, winter has arrived in force at Tahoe
and the rest of the mountain West. The upcoming ski and snowboard
season is set for a stellar year. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Kathy Branstetter, who co-runs an
on-line conversation conference on earthquakes, says the conference
has been buzzing with advice about the stuff you need to survive a
good shaking or Y2King. Combine a quake with a tornado, a blackout
and the predicted mini-apocalypse of the Y2K computer glitch, and
suddenly a lot of people are checking their battery supply. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Were he to quit now, given all the
suckers around, Bill Clinton's approval rating might go up more.
Clinton could end up like Andrew Johnson, whose enemies in Congress
are recalled by history as venal, vindictive losers. Remember,
though, everybody thought Richard Nixon would go down sword in
hand. Instead, he left office with a prudent whimper. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Because she is the coauthor of a
book about women's friendships, people ask Tamara Traeder what she
thinks of Linda Tripp and her secret phone tapes. ``When that news
got out, you could hear women gasp all over America,'' Traeder
says. She's right. Anyone who violates sacred trust between
girlfriends ought to be impeached _ from the human race. By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   FLORES-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ Advocates for the hungry and
homeless appreciate the attention they get this time of year, but
they await the donation drought that is just around the corner.
It's as if hearts _ and pockets _ have been conditioned to open
only once a year. Who says it has to stop there? By VERONICA
FLORES.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ The controversy over Canadian
death row inmate Joseph Stanley Faulder blew into Austin like a
blast of Arctic air. And the growing debate is testing Gov. George
W. Bush _ and the rest of Texas. By CLAY ROBISON
</P>
