<HEADLINE>
SPARQ TECHNOLOGY IS GOOD, BUT FIRM'S FAILURE PUTS IT IN DOUBT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Yesterday I bought a SyQuest SparQ drive for an excellent
price. I tried to log on to their home page, syquest.com several
times and I got timed out. I am told that the company closed its
doors. Do you know if this is correct? I do not want to get stuck
with a unit without any tech support available.
</P>
<P>
   A: SyQuest Technology's SparQ drives include some excellent
technology. For the price of an Iomega Zip drive, which uses
100-megabyte disks, you can have a drive that holds a full
gigabyte. The disks cost about twice as much as a Zip disk, but
hold 10 times as much.
</P>
<P>
   However, SyQuest was beset by managerial and quality problems.
The removable disk category is a cutthroat one, and right now
Iomega's Zip leads the pack. Of course, Zip and SparQ disks are not
compatible with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, the company cut its work force by half. In
November, SyQuest filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection,
suspended operations and said it has a buyer for its technology.
SyQuest is making provisions to provide support for its products as
part of the sale, according to a news release issued at the time.
However, at this writing, no buyer has been announced.
</P>
<P>
   SyQuest's action was so sudden that it took many of its users by
surprise. They're now scrambling to buy blank SparQ disks, which
reportedly are hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   SyQuest had even bought ads on taxi cabs during Fall Comdex in
November. The ads showed a SparQ drive in a red case and proclaimed
that the drives were ``red-hot.'' The juxtaposition of the ads
against the reality of what's happened to SyQuest drew more than a
few snickers from the Comdex crowd.
</P>
<P>
   If SyQuest indeed has a buyer that will continue its technology
and support users, you did get a great deal. But if not, you've got
the equivalent of a Beta videocassette player in a VHS world.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently bought a new computer. It has Windows 98 on it,
but it didn't come with a Windows 98 disk. Instead, there's
something called a ``System Restore'' disk that will put my
computer back to the state it was in when I first took it out of
the box. I bought some software that asks me to put my Windows 98
CD-ROM in the drive, but guess what? I don't have a Windows 98
CD-ROM! Should I call the company that made my computer and demand
one? Or, do I have to go out and buy it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Just on general principle, I think you should call the
company and ask for one _ but you may not need it. The Windows 98
setup files are probably on your computer.
</P>
<P>
   System-restore disks are a good idea, in theory. If you mess
something up on a PC, it can take you back to the starting point.
But you also lose everything you've put on your computer, including
potentially irreplaceable data files.
</P>
<P>
   Newer system-restore disks are smarter. They'll restore specific
components without affecting anything else.
</P>
<P>
   But there are still times when you really do need a Windows 98
disk. And the PC makers have a way around that problem.
</P>
<P>
   Look in your Windows folder, and you'll probably see another
folder called Options. Look in there, and you'll find one called
CABS. This holds the Windows 98 setup files _ just as though a copy
of the CD-ROM were placed on your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   When a program says it wants the Windows 98 disk, point it to
the windowsoptions folder. It will find the CABS folder and draw
what it needs from there.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, if you have a copy of the Windows 98 disk and you
still have the windowsoptions folder on your PC, you can safely
delete it to save yourself some space.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
