<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA IS LETTING CLINTON'S FOES RUN THE SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The polls and the media are telling us that the public is not
interested in the congressional impeachment proceedings against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   According to one poll, only 20 percent of those surveyed have
followed the historic impeachment hearings conducted by the House
Judiciary Committee ``very closely.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears that folks out here in the hinterlands have tuned out
the political crisis that fixates the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the polls consistently show that somewhere in the
neighborhood of 70 percent of Americans believe that the president
should not be impeached and removed from office _ which suggests
that the masses may not be interested in the impeachment debate but
that they have an opinion about it.
</P>
<P>
   Can the American people have an opinion _ a strong opinion, it
seems _ about something that they are consciously ignoring?
</P>
<P>
   Sure they can.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the anti-impeachment crowd's apparent apathy is
that they have forfeited the debate to the other side. And the
other side is anything but apathetic.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about people who want Clinton's head on a platter.
They want him impeached, convicted, ousted from the White House and
then prosecuted in the criminal courts. In the view of
Clinton-haters who are driving the impeachment process, no
retribution against such a loathsome president could be too harsh.
</P>
<P>
   So. If you don't want the president to be impeached, you need to
tune in instead of tuning out. You need to let your representatives
in Congress know how you feel about all this because, lately, those
representatives haven't been hearing from anyone except
constituents who dream of running Clinton out of town on a rail.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure for impeaching the president, by the way _ for
those who've been napping for 11 months _ is for a majority of the
House of Representatives to approve articles of impeachment
charging the president with high crimes and/or misdemeanors, as
stipulated by the Constitution. The House then forwards the charges
to the Senate for a trial in which a two-thirds vote is needed for
conviction. Conviction on any article of impeachment would result
in the president's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment is a political process that theoretically requires
public support. If they only hear from impeachment proponents,
House Republicans must assume that the public supports impeachment
_ an inevitable assumption if the 70 percent of the people who
claim to oppose impeachment are sitting on their couches watching
soap operas, game shows and sitcoms while the 30 percent who are
screaming for Clinton's scalp are putting their representatives'
feet to the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Even Republicans who are not inclined toward impeachment may
vote against Clinton because of pressure from anti-Clinton
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   All's fair in love and politics, of course, so citizens who
favor impeachment have every right on earth to lean on their
elected representatives.
</P>
<P>
   So do citizens who oppose impeachment _ but they're not
exercising that right. Which means that the majority that doesn't
want impeachment may be losing the argument to the minority that
does want it. We'll find out later this week, when the full House
votes on articles of impeachment recommended by the Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   If the people who oppose impeachment don't really care all that
much one way or the other, well, they deserve whatever happens.
Great thing about democracy: Activism usually trumps apathy.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are truly troubled by the idea that Congress may be
on the verge of overthrowing a duly elected president for offenses
that most Americans don't believe are impeachable, you might want
to take your cue from one of the anti-impeachment Democrats on the
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wake up, America, they are about to impeach our president!''
declared Florida Rep. Robert Wexler as the committee undertook
formal debate of the proposed articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, pro or con, it's time to get off the couch and tune
in.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
