commonly contaminated than higher denominations.
</P>
<P>
   A recent look at money circulating in northern Illinois,
published this May in the Journal of Forensic Sciences, found even
higher rates: close to 93 percent of the sample, and 100 percent of
$20 bills, tested positive for cocaine. ``In fact, most Americans
handle small amounts of cocaine every day, not as packets sold by
drug dealers but on the dollar bills that line their pockets,''
concluded this study.
</P>
<P>
   How has moola become so amazingly infested with cocaine?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the reason you traffic in drugs is to get money,'' comes
the deadpan reply from a spokesman for the Drug Enforcement
Administration who has worked undercover in narcotics and asked not
to be identified by name. ``When drugs come into the country,
traffickers are going to cut the dope with any number of chemicals.
Open the bags, mix in the cut, repackage in smaller bags, sell to
people who sell on the streets. All the time money's changing
hands. It's hard to keep money and drugs apart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But that can't be the whole story,'' adds Tom Jourdan, chief
of the materials and devices unit at the Federal Bureau of
Investigation Laboratory in Washington. The going theory, held by
Jourdan and others, is that one bill brushed through a counting
machine in a bank could contaminate a whole stack.
</P>
<P>
   Something in paper money seems to be binding to cocaine almost
like a biological receptor, and Jourdan thinks that something is
ink: ``I've wiped an old bill on white paper, and ink comes off.
The green pigment never really dries, and drugs of abuse get stuck
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cocaine dissolves in almost anything _ water, alcohol, fat. And
it sticks quite nicely to skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that mean your grandmother in the Midwest is going to be
contaminated by a bill handled by a drug dealer in Chicago?'' asks
David Kidwell, a chemist at the Naval Research Laboratory in
Washington. ``Not very likely. If money's freshly dusted with
cocaine, it will get on you, of course. But once money's been
handled and passed through machines, it's too deeply embedded.''
</P>
<P>
   Simulation studies at Argonne and a ``real life'' test at
Creighton University in Omaha, Nebraska, apparently bear him out.
For the Creighton study, bank tellers were swabbed after a
four-hour shift handling cash. Although cocaine was found on the
cash (even in rural Nebraska), none was transferred to the tellers'
hands.
</P>
<P>
   So money isn't exactly squeaky clean. But it isn't exactly going
to do us in, either. If there's a lesson here, it's that money
reflects whatever activity, and mischief, human hands get up to _
and the activity and occasional mischief of all the microscopic
organisms along for the ride on our skin.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Patricia Gadsby is a contributing editor of Discover
Magazine.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
