<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8633 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-WELD-BOS &LR;      12-14 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WELD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM WELD, WHERE HE WANTS TO BE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT LEHIGH AND FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was Bill Weld Wednesday, right where he says he doesn't
want to be: in the limelight. And his inner circle was just as
surprised as everyone else to see him there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't tell anyone,'' said one friend. ``I think he was
afraid of what the response would be.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been: Stay away. Avoid it like the plague. Don't
embarrass yourself. The safety rule for any Republican _
particularly a former governor of a liberal state who was already
viewed with suspicion by the party's conservative national
leadership _ is not to cross congressional barons intent on
impeaching the president.
</P>
<P>
   But Weld remains what he has always been _ unpredictable.
Calculatingly unpredictable. He can never be taken quite at face
value; he's always striving to appear something other than what he
is. Whatever that is.
</P>
<P>
   His inimitability _ plus a look ahead to presidential election
year 2004 _ helps explain Weld's presence in the capital Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   For all his talk about the joys of being a private citizen once
again, Weld craves the limelight _ and indeed, in his own subtle
way, is masterful in its pursuit. ``It's like jumping into the
Charles River,'' mused one Weld friend, recalling the day the
governor did just that to publicize the passage of river cleanup
legislation. Meanwhile, the House Judiciary Committee hearings
droned on, with the redhead sitting at center stage.
</P>
<P>
   And though Weld walked away from public life last year, he
hardly sees his political life as over. Despite his storied sang
froid, his supposed take-it-or-leave-it attitude, Weld cares deeply
about his career as a politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like malaria,'' says a longtime Weld chum. ``You don't
see it now, but I am sure the fever will break out somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in 1996, Weld displayed resolute good cheer and
studied nonchalance after his failed challenge to US Senator John
F. Kerry. But privately, he appeared so down over the defeat that
close friends worried about him. A Senate seat was all he had ever
wanted, a morose Weld confided to one friend at the time.
</P>
<P>
   That same love of public life is why Weld fought so tenaciously
for the Mexican ambassadorship, pressing a fight in the Senate that
the Clinton White House didn't necessarily want to engage.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why it would be foolish to believe Weld's avowals that
the political fire inside has burned out.
</P>
<P>
   No, he won't be looking at running for national office in 2000,
though there is always the prospect of a Cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Republican Party loses again _ as Weld believes will
happen if it nominates a social conservative _ then by 2004, he
thinks, the party may be willing to move toward the center. If so,
he's told friends, he'll look seriously at running.
</P>
<P>
   That long-range aspiration helps explain both Weld's efforts to
maintain his profile and his efforts to bolster the Republican
center.
</P>
<P>
   Weld was speaking to that sensible center on Wednesday _ and to
the party he hopes will emerge in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, some advisers worry he hurt himself. ``This is
different from taking moderate positions on some issues,'' laments
one. ``This will be seen as aiding the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a week or so ago, Weld aimed at the same moderate
mainstream in an op-ed piece in The New York Times. There, he
preached his own brand of ``light-touch'' Republicanism, laying out
a center way between ``the Democratic left, in hock to unions and
trial lawyers, and the so-called Republican cultural right, in
thrall to homophobia and xenophobia.'' That middle way is not so
very different from the course Bill Clinton steered between what he
called the ``brain dead politics'' of right and left in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   And it comports with Weld's own inner timetable. As he has said
in the past, he sees his career in seven-year increments. He was a
prosecutor for about that long, he spent about that long as
governor, and by 2004 he will have spent about that long as a
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, that lawyering may itself be proving a disappointment.
Recall that Weld's initial private-sector goal was to be a venture
capitalist _ a goal that elicited naught but a yawn from the world
of venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   After several trips to Wall Street, a humbled Weld _ well, at
least quasi-humbled _ instead joined his onetime underling, Bob
Cordy, at the firm McDermott Will &AMP; Emery.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, Weld has done well, carrying his own weight,
his partners say. And yet the money may not be quite what he hoped
to be making. Friends speculate that a need to overcompensate has
led to Weld's recent offputting talk of money: his boasts about the
``big bucks'' he regularly claims to be making, his dismissive
reference to the $100,000 advance for his recent first novel as ``a
tiny little check.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk is the middle-age corollary of the preppie affectation
of casual brilliance, the Harvard student who claimed to have
dashed off his thesis between Hasty Pudding performances, the pose
of the perpetual partier in a student secretly scoring summa cum
laude grades.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there's Weld's insistence that he must sock away
$15 million before ever considering a return to politics.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it. As Weld showed Wednesday, he can hardly stay
away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Scot Lehigh and Frank Phillips are members of the Globe's state
house bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
