<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8638 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLDER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-14 1534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADLY MIXUPS IN NURSING HOMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Last March 26, as an 88-year-old breast cancer patient moaned
in agony despite taking a standard painkiller, a hospice nurse
advised the staff at her nursing home to give her Roxanol, an oral
form of the narcotic morphine.
</P>
<P>
   The woman didn't receive the first dose until another 13 hours
had passed _ and then a distracted nurse at the Randolph Crossings
Nursing Center failed to catch a deadly labeling mistake on the
Roxanol bottle sent by an off-site pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give 5cc. (equals) 100 mg'' every four hours, the pharmacy
label read, meaning five cubic centimeters or 100 milligrams.
That's 20 times the prescribed amount _ a lethal dose. Indeed, the
woman died later that day, leaving lawyers to wrangle over whether
it was the undisputed morphine overdose or her terminal cancer that
killed her.
</P>
<P>
   The nurse on duty ``indicated that she was aware that this was a
large dose of Roxanol,'' notes a federal investigative report.
``She indicated that she was the only nurse on this 40-bed unit and
that she had been very busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Medication blunders occur all the time _ even in the most
prestigious institutions _ and those that happen in hospitals have
been getting overdue attention in recent years. But errors in
nursing homes, which care for the oldest, sickest, most vulnerable
patients in the health care system, are just beginning to appear on
the radar screens of regulators, researchers, and health
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   How often do medication errors happen in nursing homes?
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is, nobody knows,'' says Stephen Feldman, a
pharmacist who has worked with nursing homes for 26 years. ``That's
because traditionally the reporting of medication errors has been
minimal. People think if you talk about it, it invites legal
liability, and if you don't talk about it, it will go away.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt the opportunity for errors is greater in
nursing homes than hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   First, the average nursing home patient is on more than eight
medications. Then there's the sheer number of patients. At any
given time, about 55,000 patients reside in Massachusetts' 600
nursing homes, compared to around 10,200 overnight patients in the
72 acute-care hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, nursing home residents ``are in many ways a
forgotten population of 1.5 million people,'' says Dr. Jerry
Gurwitz, of University of Massachusetts Medical School and Fallon
Clinic in Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   Gurwitz and Dr. David Bates of Brigham and Women's Hospital just
completed a study of medication errors in 18 Bay State nursing
homes. While declining to share the unpublished results, Gurwitz
says: ``Clearly there has been under-recognition and
under-reporting of adverse drug events. Spontaneous reporting
systems don't work in identifying even a fraction of events, and
they often miss very important events.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts health officials this year began to keep closer
track of nursing home medication mistakes. The effort is partly an
outgrowth of a 1994 chemotherapy overdose at Dana-Farber Cancer
Institute that led to the death of Boston Globe health columnist
Betsy A. Lehman and cardiac damage in another patient, according to
assistant health commissioner Nancy Ridley.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the shot heard 'round the world when it comes to
medication errors,'' Ridley says.
</P>
<P>
   According to records obtained through the Freedom of Information
Act, the state received reports of 27 such errors in nursing homes,
involving five deaths, in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials believe this may represent the total number
of such incidents during the two-year period. ``Medication errors
are tracked and have to be reported to the state,'' notes Ann
Turner of the Massachusetts Extended Care Federation, an industry
group.
</P>
<P>
   Others disagree. Often nursing home administrators insist they
have had no medication errors, Feldman says, ``but it's very clear
to me they happen. I truly believe that nursing directors are
usually unaware that they're happening. When something happens all
the time that isn't a good thing, people think of it as normal and
stop perceiving it as a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   One clue: When state officials go out to investigate, they
usually find incidents, major and minor, that went unreported.
``There's no question that what gets reported to us is the tip of
the iceberg,'' Ridley says. ``In fact, it's the molecule at the tip
of the iceberg.''
</P>
<P>
   Randolph Crossings, now called Sunrise Care and Rehabilitation
Center of Randolph, Mass., is a case in point. The ``sentinel
event'' that drew officials' attention to the facility was the
death last December 23 of a 49-year-old man.
</P>
<P>
   The man had an alarmingly high blood level of potassium,
possibly due to dialysis to treat kidney failure. Alerted to the
situation, his doctor ordered an immediate dose of a drug called
Kayexalate to reduce his potassium levels; too much potassium can
disrupt heart rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   The man never got the intended drug. Not only that, but a nurse
on the evening shift gave the patient his routine daily dose of a
potassium supplement at 6 p.m., almost three hours after the doctor
ordered the potassium-reducing medication.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours later, the man was found dead of cardiac arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The incident precipitated a full-scale review of Randolph
Crossings that unearthed serious deficiencies of all kinds. The
state inspection ``evidenced a pattern of medication errors that
placed residents at immediate and serious risk,'' according to the
state report. ``At a minimum there were 15 significant medication
errors'' between January 21 and March 31 this year.
</P>
<P>
   The findings caused the federal Health Care Financing
Administration to levy a $637,000 fine on the facility this year.
The agency is also trying to bar it from receiving Medicare and
Medicaid funds _ which would force it to close _ but the nursing
home's parent company in Albequerque has won an injunction blocking
that step for now.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Goodman, a spokeswoman for Sun HealthCare Group, which
owns that facility, 33 others in Massachusetts and more than 400
nationally, says the company has corrected the problems in Randolph
and that last month the facility was declared ``in substantial
compliance'' with state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always strive for perfection and, unfortunately, we don't
always achieve it _ and neither can anybody when something is being
done by human hands,'' Goodman said. ``We reported the errors. I
don't believe there has been direct cause and effect established,
that the medication errors caused the two deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AVOIDING NURSING HOME PROBLEMS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nursing home residents can do only so much to avoid becoming the
victim of a medication error. Many are too sick, too confused, or
too demented to keep track of what pill, injection, or IV medicine
they're supposed to get, and when.
</P>
<P>
   But families can be an important check on the process, say those
close to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Families should take advantage of a 1987 federal law that
requires nursing homes to meet with relatives every three months to
discuss care plans, advises Adelina Healy, director of nursing at
Wingate of Wilbraham, a 130-bed nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   The medications a resident is taking, and why, should be at the
top of the agenda. The federal law mandating such meetings ``has
made long-term care much better,'' Healy says.
</P>
<P>
   Families are sometimes in a better position than often-transient
nursing staffers to recognize when a patient's physical or mental
condition has changed. ``If family members notice a change in how
their loved one is functioning, the first question to ask is if
there has been any change in medications,'' advises Dr. David Bates
of Brigham and Women's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent study conducted with Dr. Jerry Gurwitz of Fallon
Clinic, Bates says, ``Many of the problems we saw occurred after
some change had occurred and no one had put two and two together.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Coyle of the state Department of Public Health urges
families to be aware of medication side effects ``that could
masquerade as other medical problems,'' and to be familiar with
their loved one's drug regimen. They should also periodically
request to see the medical record, check the Medication
Administration Record against physicians' orders, and review the
required monthly pharmacist's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, nursing home residents and families must
depend on facility staffers, and that's often the weak link. ``We
have found there is clearly a lack of medication knowledge among
the staff,'' says Lori Bassinger, a pharmacist consultant for the
state.
</P>
<P>
   The health department plans to issue recommendations soon urging
nursing homes to test all new professional staffers on their
medication knowledge, and possibly existing staff too. Because of a
recent spate of morphine overdose deaths, the state will circulate
charts designed to help nurses calculate safe doses and head off
potentially lethal mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard A. Knox is a member of the Globe staff. His e-mail
address is knox(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
