<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP FUTURE MAY HINGE ON IMPEACHMENT VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This week's drama on Capitol Hill hinges on whether
moderate Republicans will band together and save President Clinton
from being impeached. But after they vote, the question is whether
moderates will have a place in the Republican Party at all.
</P>
<P>
   By some accounts, it is not just Clinton's fate at stake this
week, but also the fate of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``My party has focused almost exclusively on the president,''
said Representative Christopher Shays of Connecticut, one of the
GOP's leading moderates and an impeachment foe. Shays worries that
much of 1999 will be focused on a Senate impeachment trial instead
of the Republican economic and social agenda.
</P>
<P>
   This is only the latest twist for a party that, just a month
ago, declared it was turning toward the middle after the midterm
elections. When the party lost five House seats instead of picking
up an expected dozen or two, House Speaker Newt Gingrich resigned
amid widespread expectations the party would drop its effort to
impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the opposite has occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The party has pushed for impeachment even more strongly than
before the November election, with much of the effort directed by
the most conservative members, such as the House majority whip, Tom
DeLay of Texas. The speaker-elect, Bob Livingston, has yet to
emerge as the moderate voice some expected.
</P>
<P>
   This has led Democrats to assert, perhaps too hopefully, that
impeachment will backfire on the Republican Party. No sooner did
the House Judiciary Committee approve the first three of four
articles of impeachment on Friday than Clinton's former press
secretary, Dee Dee Myers, suggested on CNN that a Senate trial
would result in a Democratic takeover of Congress in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party will have hell to pay with the American
people,'' Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate impact could be on some members who back
impeachment and represent moderate and Democrat-leaning districts.
In several cases in last month's election, outspoken Republican
proponents of impeachment were defeated by Democrats who made
impeachment a campaign issue. Political analyst Stu Rothenberg said
GOP moderates who vote against impeachment are likely to face
primary challenges from conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But given this year's roller-coaster events, Rothenberg said, it
may be too early to start writing the political obituary for any
party or politician, including the president.
</P>
<P>
   Just as most voters tell pollsters they approve of Clinton's job
performance primarily for the economy, voters may not care about
the Republican Party's impeachment performance if they believe the
GOP has the right agenda for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee spokesman Mike Collins rebutted
any suggestion that the impeachment battle would cast his party out
of the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central themes of this party do attract the American
middle,'' Collins said. ``Putting more money back into the hands of
those who earned it, saving Social Security, a good pension and
retirement _ those are themes that move to the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the impeachment vote, Collins said Republicans ``are
approaching this in a sober, serious, and careful manner, and they
are clearly searching their consciences. That can only help them.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the Senate is tied up in a grueling impeachment trial, it
may be impossible to focus on anything but the president's fate.
While it is widely thought that a trial would take about four
months, some Republican leadership aides have said Senate majority
leader Trent Lott would prefer to limit it to a couple of weeks, so
the party can bring other issues to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans see a bright side to all this. Presuming the
Senate fails to come up with the necessary two-thirds vote to
convict and oust Clinton, Republicans expect Clinton would limp
through his last two years as president, so deeply wounded
politically that Republicans would set the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But that may be as much wishful thinking as the Democrats' hope
that impeachment will backfire on the GOP. The bottom line is that
the Republican Party's poor performance in the November elections
ensured that Democrats could still kill legislation they do not
like, because the Republicans' 55-45 majority in the Senate is
short of the 60 votes needed to stop a filibuster. Clinton,
meanwhile, retains his veto power.
</P>
<P>
   The real direction of the Republican Party is likely to be
determined by the 2000 presidential campaign. The current political
thinking is that an outsider like Texas Governor George W. Bush
will seek and win the Republican nomination. Bush, of course, is
playing no role in the impeachment debate. Yet as a self-declared
``compassionate conservative,'' he already is under attack by some
in the party's right wing for being too moderate. ``The Democratic
Party's Achilles' heel is the far left, and the Republican Party's
Achilles' heel is the far right,'' Shays said. The public might
react negatively if Republicans are viewed as ``a far right party
more into ideology than governing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The question, according to Shays, is whether the public will
perceive possible impeachment and a Senate trial as a manifestation
of Republican ideology or as the consummate duty of governing. ``I
honestly don't know,'' Shays said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
