<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8642 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-ARMY-BOS &LR;      12-14 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ARMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S ARMY LOSING ITS BUSINESS EMPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ It is hard to spend money in China without funding
the People's Liberation Army. Whether you stay at Beijing's luxury
Palace Hotel or buy real estate, whether you play golf or use a
mobile telephone, your money is probably going to the coffers of
the world's largest military.
</P>
<P>
   The PLA &UR;  &LR; has come a long way from its roots as a band of
peasant-revolutionaries who captured weapons from the enemy and
grew their own food to survive. Today, through a mind-boggling
network of 15,000 businesses, the PLA makes billions of dollars a
year to boost its budget.
</P>
<P>
   But its foray into commerce has bred corruption and crime, and
distracted soldiers from defending the nation. It has also created
unfair competition for other businesses, and fueled resentment
among civilians who say the PLA has become an army of profit-hungry
mercenaries. So after 13 years of building a commercial empire with
the blessings of Beijing, the PLA has been told its days of
money-making are over.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the government's effort to reform the economy and
rout out corruption, President Jiang Zemin has ordered the military
to divest its commercial interests by Tuesday. The government will
then run the companies or sell them off, and debt-plagued firms
will be shut down. The state has vowed to supplement the military
budget to make up the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   Drumming the PLA out of business is a bold move that will test
the staying power of Jiang, a leader once seen as weak and
transitional, who has staked his legacy on reform. Jiang is the
first modern Chinese leader without a military background, and
asserting his authority over the PLA is a risky gambit.
</P>
<P>
   If the plan works, it will fundamentally alter the way a growing
military power funds itself and could strengthen the PLA by
restoring discipline and preparedness. It would also reduce the
costly problems of smuggling and copyright piracy, and create a
fairer economic playing field in China.
</P>
<P>
   If the move fails, it would be a major defeat for Jiang, and the
military could succumb to widespread corruption like some other
Asian armed forces. How the PLA copes with this transition will
show a lot about its willingness to be a professional defense force
that serves the state rather than itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be an effort to hold onto the most profitable
enterprises and get rid of the money-losing ones. That's the nature
of reform in China _ everyone tries to keep their finger in the
pie,'' said Tai Ming Cheung, a Hong Kong-based PLA analyst and
author of the soon-to-be-released ``China's Entrepreneurial Army.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: Do the authorities have sufficient manpower
and authority to enforce this? They tend to be very energetic for
the first months, and then run out of steam,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's true the state asked the PLA to halt enterprise in 1993,
but was largely ignored. Even now, the State Economic and Trade
Commission has only a few dozen people overseeing the transfer of
hundreds of thousands of employees and billions of dollars of
assets. But the priority on it this time from the highest
leadership means the stakes riding on success are tremendous.
</P>
<P>
   As one defense analyst noted, ``The commitment is very strong,
certainly at the top levels, though it's a bit harder to say at
lower levels. When it starts impacting on people's livelihood,
jobs, houses _ when the military has to forgo part of their income
_ that's not easily done.''
</P>
<P>
   Jiang's success will depend largely on his ability to make up
lost monies that have gone to improving military living standards.
In China, where defense funding is a fraction of that in the United
States, that will not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   With tentacles that reach into every aspect of life from power
stations and coal mines to frozen shrimp and karaoke bars, the PLA
is estimated to earn at least as much revenue annually _ about $10
billion _ as it officially gets from the state. PLA businesses
account for 3 percent of national output, about the same as a small
province in China.
</P>
<P>
   Ten percent of the nation's pharmaceutical industry is PLA-run,
including the popular 999 brand of herbal medicine, whose red neon
logo flashes over Hong Kong's harbor. Four of China's biggest
garment and shoemakers are PLA-owned. So are three professional
basketball teams and 1,500 hotels.
</P>
<P>
   But the profits from these ventures have lined not only the
coffers of an underfunded military, but also the pockets of some
officials and their families, making it likely that vested
interests will resist change.
</P>
<P>
   Some PLA units are accused of skimming revenues into private
bank accounts and pirating CDs and software. Others launder money,
trade on the black market, and run brothels. Smuggling alone has
cost the state $12 billion a year in lost revenue, according to
government figures.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang has accused PLA corruption of ``threatening to destroy our
socialist system.'' It is also bad for the military, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Illicit activities promote divisions within the armed forces,
dampen morale and distract from defense. They also damage
civil-military relations.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether Jiang, who irked the military last year
by keeping a general out of the ruling Politburo for the first
time, will have the stomach to go after high-ranking officers
involved in illegal activities. After the order to divest came on
July 22, rumors circulated in Beijing that threats were made
against Premier Zhu Rongji, who heads the unit ensuring the
military, police, courts and Communist Party shed their business
interests.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Beijing garrison announced it handed over its
68 military and police businesses to the city. Numerous ventures in
Shanghai, Guangzhou and elsewhere have been transferred. But
observers worry that select, high-profile handovers might
substitute for a wholesale shedding of assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's likely they won't do it all at once and that they won't
meet the deadline,'' said David Zweig, a China scholar at Hong Kong
University of Science and Technology. ``The PLA will do things that
are highly symbolic and visible, and the battle will continue as
the government weeds them out further and further from
non-essential businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The PLA must shed commercial enterprises, but not industrial or
agricultural ones, so officials may try to play tricks with
reclassification.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Vice President Hu Jintao has said military businesses
``must close their doors completely and not in a disguised
manner,'' and has promised punishment and trials for those ``who do
not obey orders.'' Authorities are already investigating an aide to
a senior general in a securities scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main challenge is making sure the implementation actually
takes place,'' said Cheung, the military analyst. ``These companies
should be like any other company, but I think they'll continue to
have all sorts of privileges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
