<HEADLINE>
JEWS DEBATE MEANING OF HANUKKAH IN AGE OF COMMERCIALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VENISE WAGNER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On the scale of importance, Hanukkah is a Jewish
holiday that ranks with Purim _ far below Passover, Rosh Hashana
and Yom Kippur. But don't tell David Eiland, co-owner of Just For
Fun.
</P>
<P>
   Eiland, who grew up in a mixed-faith family (his grandfather was
a rabbi), is bursting with enthusiasm about this eight-day
celebration, which started Sunday at sundown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing with Hanukkah is it's a festive holiday,''
Eiland said with a giant grin. ``It has also become a gift-giving
holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are plenty of goodies to get you in the Hanukkah
spirit, let alone put on your wish list: Hanukkah cards, 3-D
glasses that turn any Christmas light into a dreidel or Star of
David, banners, menorah snow globes, Jewish Holiday Rummy,
stickers, stamps, Curious George musical menorahs as well as
handcrafted classical versions.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are dreidels of every kind. Dreidels suspended in
soap; dreidels that light up and play the ``Dreidel'' song as they
spin; Mickey Mouse dreidels and pinata dreidels.
</P>
<P>
   The Festival of Lights is even going mainstream, as evidenced by
the small selection of menorahs available in Macy's Holiday Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants of Hanukkah items have noticed an increase in demand
over the last five years. Eiland believes that much of the
commercial popularity stems from the contagious buying frenzy that
takes place around this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   The sales, the advertisements, the dazzle and sparkle are
attractive and hard to resist, as they tug and entice the senses.
People get into it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As if it's not bad enough that Christmas is marked by the number
of shopping days left rather than its spiritual significance, some
fear the growing consumer fervor for Hanukkah could make it
increasingly susceptible to commercial influences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The holiday season is the time when Jews realize they are not
part of the mainstream culture,'' said Rabbi Stephen S. Pearce of
Temple Emanu-El in San Francisco. ``So they are trying to
compensate by competing. Something that was originally a minor
holiday has been elevated to the same level of significant holidays
like Rosh Hashana, Yom Kippur and Passover.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is concern that the trend could prove detrimental to
religious integrity, Eiland is unfazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting commercialized, but it's fun and tasteful,'' he
said. ``I look at it differently. There are so many mixed
marriages. So kids don't lose sight of their heritage, (adults)
have to make it fun to learn what the holiday traditions are.''
</P>
<P>
   The gifts are often educational and focus on one aspect of the
Hanukkah story, he said, so it's an opportunity to pass on the
tradition and the culture.
</P>
<P>
   The post-biblical story of the revolt of the Maccabees under
Hellenist oppression is filled with messages of freedom, hope,
miracles and righteousness overcoming domination.
</P>
<P>
   When the Maccabees returned victorious to their defiled temple
in Jerusalem, they found only one vial of oil to rekindle the
eternal flame. With so little oil, the flame should have burned for
no more than a day. But it burned for eight. Hanukkah is the
festival that celebrates the rededication of the temple.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Bashevkin, director of finance and administration at the
Jewish Museum in San Francisco, said the Jewish tradition is full
of such tales that strengthen Jewish identity, particularly when
everyone is assaulted with Christmas advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because it's a minor holiday doesn't mean it's lost on
the radar,'' Bashevkin said. ``There are some great lessons that
are behind the holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Howard Zack, of the orthodox Congregation Beth Jacob in
Oakland, Calif., struggles with the December dilemma. On the one
hand, he does not approve of people seeking meaning or their
identity in consumer goods. At the same time, he understands the
difficulty of fighting the tug to the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm somewhat conflicted,'' he said. ``As a minority culture
and a minority that has chosen in large part to assimilate in the
culture, when you see Jewish symbols (in store windows) you can't
help but be drawn toward that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate we have to turn toward the malls and gift
stores to find our Jewishness. Those who find it there will find
something less meaningful. The fact of the matter is Hanukkah can't
hold a candle to Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to make Hanukkah into a Jewish Christmas is one of Rabbi
Mark Diamond's pet peeves. The extravagant gift-giving that some
families feel pressed to do is inappropriate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be the Grinch who stole Hanukkah,'' said
Diamond, of the conservative congregation Beth Abraham in Oakland.
``But it troubles me. Hanukkah is a beautiful holiday. It's a
beautiful custom. You have a holiday that celebrates the light, in
a dark and depressing time of year. But I fear it's going in the
way of Christmas in terms of presents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
