<HEADER>
A8650 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-VOTERS-BOS &LR;      12-14 1483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VOTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DURABLE PRESIDENT: TARGET AND TOTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eleven months ago, Newt Gingrich was revving up for
a presidential campaign, the Republicans were hoping to win two or
three dozen more seats in the House and reach 60 seats in the
Senate, and Bill Clinton was in the most serious peril of any
president since Richard M. Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the impeachment vote only days away on the House
floor, and the outcome too close to call, Gingrich has all but
disappeared, the Republicans are nursing their wounds from a
historically bad performance in midterm elections, and a president
who has acknowledged, as he did again Friday, ``my own
wrongdoing,'' retains the unambiguous strong support of the
American people.
</P>
<P>
   Most remarkable is this: Even if the House votes for impeachment
_ damaging the president in the history books and linking him
forever with Andrew Johnson, the only other president to suffer
that ignominy _ Clinton's profile in the capital may well be
unchanged. Clinton's storied durability is proving greater than
anyone imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton might disappoint us, offend us, even enrage us, but
in the end, there's something about him that beguiles us,
entertains us, engages us, even comforts and pleases us. And it
fascinates us.
</P>
<P>
   Some inscrutable twist of taste and fate _ and acts of will by
him and the voters _ has placed Clinton in the White House and kept
him there, in good standing even with the public who didn't vote
for him. Never mind that he's been accused of breaking the law,
charged with immorality, blamed for diminishing the office,
portrayed as a poor role model, and called a betrayer of his family
and country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Face-to-face or in a group, this man connects, even with
people who are prepared not to like him,'' says US Representative
John Tierney, the Massachusetts Democrat. ``Something happens,
whether in person or on television, that makes him seem compelling.
Somehow he makes people think that he's like them.''
</P>
<P>
   A cartoon character in the current New Yorker magazine says of
the president: ``He's an idiot and a sleazeball but I still like
him.'' A Fox News/Opinion Dynamics Poll this month found that half
the public believes the Monica Lewinsky scandal has hurt Clinton's
ability to lead the country _ but it also found that seven
Americans out of 10 approve of the job he's doing.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes commentators look down their noses and say we get the
president we deserve. This time, despite what the pundits' noses
tell us, we have the president we want.
</P>
<P>
   We have, after all, had both occasion and excuse to change
horses. But if after Gennifer Flowers, Paula Jones, ``inappropriate
intimate contact'' with intern Lewinsky, deliberate deception of
the press and public, systematic resistance to investigators'
inquiries, dependence on awkward legalisms (the definition of
``sexual relations''), ingenious verbal contortions (the definition
of ``is''), and a parade of incidents involving cigars, breath
mints, treacly gifts, and hallway trysts _ if after all that, we
are sticking with him, then it is clear that the bond between
president and public is nothing ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has something, a special rapport that allows him to
convince the American people that he empathizes with them,'' says
Robert Gilbert, a Northeastern University political scientist.
``You watch him in a public event and he rushes into the audience,
convincing them that he's part of them, that he feels for them. Now
they feel for him.''
</P>
<P>
   American presidents are like abstract paintings, summoning
emotions in the public that they didn't even know they had,
permitting people to see what they want in the brush strokes of a
public life, awakening responses that can be personal, political,
sensual.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my district, there is a group that never felt this way
about Jimmy Carter or Kennedy _ sane, rational, businesslike people
who do not trust this guy or who hate him,'' says Representative
Rob Portman, an Ohio Republican. ``But there is also a large group
that thinks that he is Everyman _ someone with frailties but who
touches a chord. He is likable, he is a charmer, and he is
charming.''
</P>
<P>
   All that, plus a charmed life.
</P>
<P>
   But not the sort of charmed life that came with privilege and
luck. Born to a single mother (his father died in a highway
accident before he was born), reared in modest circumstances,
nurtured by a grandfather and by friends who, even in his youth,
recognized his capacity for remarkable achievement, Clinton was
always a striver. The parents of the youngsters in his circle in
Hot Springs, Ark., spoke openly of the possibility that Bill
Clinton might be president someday.
</P>
<P>
   He chose John F. Kennedy as a hero and model and then maneuvered
to be photographed with him at Boys Nation; he selected Georgetown
University because it was in Washington, where the political action
was; he set his cap for a Rhodes Scholarship because he knew it was
an emblem of the new credentialism; he angled to avoid the draft
but worked just as deftly to retain what he called his ``political
viability''; he set out to win a House seat in his 20s, was
defeated, won election first as attorney general, and then as a
boy-wonder governor.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the keys to his success _ indeed, one of the keys to
his appeal _ is that none of it was easy. In fact, it is possible
to define Clinton by his failures: his failure to win reelection
after a term as governor, which made him the youngest ex-governor
in American history, but also made him older and wiser; his failure
to translate his idealism into an efficient governing style, which
prompted commentators to declare his presidency a failure even
before his 100-day honeymoon was over; his failure to take a
lifetime of policy thinking and planning and put those ideas into
law, which left his health insurance plan in a shambles and
transformed the president from a Great Proposer (sweeping proposals
and visionary ideas) into a Great Suggester (How about school
uniforms?).
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's six years have been remarkably full of tumult for a
peacetime president: A national debate on the health insurance
issue followed by the spectacular collapse of the president's plan.
Mini-dramas on several important Senate confirmation fights. The
specter of the budget deficit miraculously replaced by the
opportunity of the budget surplus. The rise, fall, and rise again
of power-partner Hillary Rodham Clinton. The dalliance with an
intern, the insistent denials, the inevitable revelations, the
angry fallout, the exhaustive investigation, the exhausting
impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   And yet none of those astonishing things was especially
startling.
</P>
<P>
   We knew he was a dreamer, and changing the country's system of
health insurance was a pie-in-the-sky dream. We knew he was an
angler, and so it was no surprise when the man who maneuevered to
avoid the draft also maneuevered to avoid the truth. We knew he was
a ladies' man, and so the sex stories that bubbled around
Washington were no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``In politics you can get away with anything as long as it's
what's expected,'' says Representative Mark Sanford, a Republican
from South Carolina. ``If people expect you to be a rascal, you can
be a rascal. That he is a rascal has been discounted. But he is
also an engaging personality _ and things can't get better than
this in the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton campaign headquarters in 1992, somebody scrawled the
now-famous epigram: ``It's the economy, stupid.'' It was the
economy that propelled Clinton into the White House over an
incumbent President Bush six years ago, and it may be the economy
that keeps Clinton in the White House now. But it's not only the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the president's appeal, to be sure, is, as
Representative Portman says, that touch of Everyman. And like other
presidents who touched their countrymen's imaginations, Clinton is
more a part of the people than apart from the people. The
Fox/Opinion Dynamics Poll, for example, shows that only 16 percent
of Americans polled believe the president is responsible for the
decline in moral standards in the country. Fully 50 percent believe
he is symbolic of that decline.
</P>
<P>
   So, though Clinton may have stumbled more than any president in
the postwar period, the more important thing is that he has picked
himself up, recovered, and fought back more than any other
president. Americans admire that in presidents and athletes and,
more to the point, they admire that in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Americans like Clinton because he reminds us of
ourselves _ not necessarily the better angels of our nature, as
Lincoln told us, but our true nature, as Clinton showed us.
</P>
<P>
   (David M. Shribman is chief of the Globe's Washington bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
