<SLUG> BC-WOODEN-TOYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE TOYS RUN ON IMAGINATION, NOT MICROCHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST GALWAY, N.Y. _ There is the interactive world of Furby,
Tigger and Barney, all talking, purring and bouncing in the ersatz
snow of the mall, and then there is Woody Herman's toy shop.
</P>
<P>
   Far from this modern toy landscape, Herman's shop is in a chilly
barn, where, from scraps of fine wood mainly used in his
furniture-making, Herman churns out hundreds of wooden trains, race
cars, trucks and helicopters. No patterns or production demands
dictate how Herman makes a toy.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, in a rough block of black walnut that was once part of a
pallet, Herman sees a dragster, regardless of the ant holes. Wood
in hand, he asks, ``That's a race car, right there, do you see
it?'' After deftly buzzing the wood through a band saw, the flowing
cuts exposing the streaked grain, Herman in minutes, and by eye,
has fashioned the car.
</P>
<P>
   Herman's final products, sanded smooth and rubbed with non-toxic
mineral oil to a warm glow, are inviting to the touch. Their
planes, like the Shaker-inspired furniture he makes, are pleasing
to the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Do not underestimate the power of the simple toy.
</P>
<P>
   Herman remembers one peculiar craft show about 10 years ago at
the state Capitol complex in Albany. ``I had people in three-piece
suits, the governor's staff, assemblymen and senators, down on the
ground, zooming their cars,'' Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   Herman, 52, a Vietnam War veteran who teaches woodworking for
special education students in suburban Albany, never set out to be
a toymaker.
</P>
<P>
   Toymaking, though, has taken over. He began making them 22 years
ago, to make use of scrap he couldn't bear to throw away. ``I laugh
because people know me as a toymaker or a birdhouse maker. Now, if
you want a piece of furniture, you have to wait three or four
years.'' He uses the profits to support his two daughters' college
educations.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden toys date to colonial America. Though the advent of cast
iron and tin toys, and then later, plastic largely replaced the
wooden toy, Herman said some families continued the homemade toy
tradition. About 15 years ago, the nostalgic interest of
trend-setting baby boomers spurred a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   In a backroom of his 19th-century home in rural upstate New York
are the prolific results of his craft. This room, ``The Country
Shop,'' bears a faint resemblance to Christmas cards and cartoons
that have long depicted Santa and his elves, cobbling wooden trains
together.
</P>
<P>
   In one laundry basket are $3.50 helicopters and planes, made of
oak, but enhanced by tiger maple or cherry blades. His $4
paddleboat, with a cherry paddle that propels the boat across
bathtub waters, is a replica of a 19th-century Mississippi River
toy.
</P>
<P>
   His flatbed trucks carry small cars that fit precisely on pegs.
Some of these cars have a previous life: one came from a scrap of
mahogany flooring; another, with a minivan shape, from the curly
cherry hutch he had made for a customer.
</P>
<P>
   Herman _ whose name, ``Woody,'' is taken from the big band
leader, not his avocation _ believes these toys hold their own
against the electronic world. A video game of a racing car does all
of the work, he notes. But with a wooden car in hand, ``you can
take that car and go, `zoom, zoom' and you can go 300 mph.''
</P>
<P>
   The simplicity, he believes, invokes the basic elements of play.
``Imagination is the word,'' Herman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
