A8653 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-FROST-BOS &LR;      12-14 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FROST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEATON HUMOR FAILS TO SPICE THE HOLIDAY TREACLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
JACK FROST 
Directed by: Troy Miller 
Written by: Mark Steven Johnson, Steve Bloom, Jonathan Roberts, and
Jeff Cesario 
Starring: Michael Keaton, Kelly Preston, Joseph Cross, Mark Addy,
Henry Rollins 
Running time: 100 minutes 
Rated: PG (some profanity, death of a parent) 
Stars: !! 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days, it seems every new holiday film is vying for the
classic status of ``It's a Wonderful Life,'' or more recently, ``A
Christmas Story.'' But somewhere along the way, heartwarming
sentiment has been replaced by teary treacle, which doesn't so much
warm the heart as make your molars ache from all the sweetener.
Such is the case with ``Jack Frost,'' a bit of holiday piffle
starring Michael Keaton as a man who gets a second chance, of
sorts, to be a good father to his son.
</P>
<P>
   Keaton's Jack is basically a decent guy, living in Colorado. He
loves his wife, Gabby (Kelly Preston), and his son, Charlie, and he
sorely regrets just how much he neglects them in pursuit of rock
'n' roll glory. Jack's the Springsteen-esque leader of a band, and
Keaton immerses himself in the complete catalog of rock god moves.
Jack and the band have been working hard for years, and it seems as
if their big break is finally about to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jack just hates the toll his life on the road has taken
on his family. One night, after building a snowman with Charlie,
Jack gives his son a harmonica, and this hokey promise: ``Whenever
you play this, no matter where I am, I can hear it.'' On Christmas
Eve, Jack has an audition with industry bigwigs, but on his way to
the meeting, he has a change of heart, deciding home is where he
needs to be. Bad move. On his way to the family's cabin, Jack is
killed in an auto accident.
</P>
<P>
   Now director Troy Miller and his merry band of writers don't
want to get all bogged down in all that nasty grief and mourning,
so the story fast-forwards one year. Charlie still misses his dad,
and remembering the experience they shared, he builds a snowman
that he dresses in his father's hat and scarf. And, of course, when
he plays that ol' magic mouth organ his dad gave him, the snowman,
with Keaton's voice, comes to animated life.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, there's something to hearing Keaton's snide voice
coming out of the sweet-faced snowman, and there are a few jokes
worth a guilty giggle, but those vague amusements can carry the
film only so far. Certainly, there are moments that will delight
kids (well, very small kids, anyway), such as when Snowman Jack
plays hockey, and fast-flying pucks slice painlessly through his
midsection. The special effects, created by Jim Henson's Creature
Shop, almost save the film, but they, too, are overwhelmed by the
sorts of homespun homilies we've heard hundreds of times before,
and seen in dozens of better movies.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the most amazing thing about ``Jack Frost'' may be that
it took four writers to come up with a film as insubstantial as
tinsel and as leaden as fruitcake. Then again, perhaps none of the
writers wanted to bear the blame alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 1324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
