<SLUG> BC-DREAM-SAVERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD HANDS MAKE THINGS NEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ A 20-pound, 50-year-old Standard typewriter
coddled in his lap, Justin Lopes gingerly lifted keys to clean the
mechanical dinosaur as if they were the fingers of a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``An old typewriter provides the rhythm that makes thinking
easier,'' explained Lopes, the one-man service department at
University Typewriter and Computers Inc.
</P>
<P>
   He paused, stymied by a half-century of stubborn gunk caked on a
joint of the K key, then dabbed an extra dose of pungent-smelling
cleaning solvent on the mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer boxes have come to do all the thinking now. Such a
shame,'' Lopes said, massaging the letter with a swatch of cloth. A
moment passed, K fluttered to life, and Lopes, with just a hint of
a smile, moved on to L.
</P>
<P>
   The progress is incremental and the rewards are modest when
you're in the business of fixing what most folks throw out. Then
again, repairing the arcane isn't for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I see myself as a fixer,'' said Elaine Steward,
who specializes in the repair of dolls at the Elane Doll Co. in
Woburn. ``I think of myself more as a savior of dreams and some of
the memories we all like to hold on to.''
</P>
<P>
   These fixers are, for the most part, an elusive lot who
advertise by word of mouth and work in back rooms where walls are
decorated with neatly organized tools once owned by grandparents.
Their shop music is usually classicial, their hours unpredictable,
their prices reasonable, and their nemesis a throw-away culture
that bottoms out this time of year as advertisers exhort holiday
shoppers to buy new, new, new.
</P>
<P>
   And thus they are also a dwindling lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm unaware of too many people left in this line of work,''
said Lewis Hurxthal Jr., who repairs yacht compasses and sextants
from a shop on Commercial Wharf in Boston. He had just gotten off
the phone with a Danish sailor calling from Greenland with a broken
compass and an unspoken compliment that when you're good, your name
gets around.
</P>
<P>
   One of the perks of the job ``is just working with this mystical
force of magnetism,'' Hurxthal said.
</P>
<P>
   Dorchester has an expert drapery spot remover; Sudbury has a
furniture paint technician who doesn't need (or use) charts to
match colors; Salem has a model ship restorer; and Wayland has
Michael Poisson, who for 30 years has put the tock back in old
clocks using tools inherited from his father and grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I get the feeling because of our junk-it society
that I'm one of the last businesses of this sort on earth,'' said
Poisson, who claims a good clock tuneup lasts 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Name me one other item _ just one other item! _ in a household
that, treated well, will operate 24 hours a day for 20 years
without a service job,'' said Poisson.
</P>
<P>
   These fixers are also a passionate lot, as evidenced by visits
to a few closet repair shops where it sometimes seemed the
commodity that healed best was time.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, Steward's doll infirmary appears to be a
collection of naked, miniature body parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men dropping off a broken doll for their daughter or wife tend
to find this scene somewhat disturbing,'' Steward said of the
remnants around her. ``Women usually talk to their dolls and remind
them that they're going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Steward's average ``patient'' is 30 years old, with a stay
running perhaps a week or more. The bill is about $100 for the
interior re-stringing, hair transplant, and exterior makeover that
give a doll that prime-of-life glow.
</P>
<P>
   The average stay for a typewriter in Lopes's ``service
department'' is one month, where machines come in looking like
faded props from a black-and-white movie. His department measures 5
by 10 feet, the walls so cluttered with tools and repair manuals
that the only place available for the 38-year-old technician to
tape pictures of his family is on the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Born in the Azores, Lopes was a tinkerer by the time he was 5
years old. He started repair work here in 1992, where restoring the
1,000-plus parts of an old Underwood typewriter seemed a logical
extension of the radios he disassembled _ and sometimes patched
together again _ during his youth.
</P>
<P>
   Not all these fixers have roots in the trade. Consider Hurxthal,
whose shop is located at Robert E. White Instruments Inc., a
company that once made compasses. Hurxthal, 69, got his training
studying the breeding habits of ostriches in Kenya for a doctorate
in zoology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reach, but there is a connection,'' said Hurxthal, a
Plymouth resident. ``Once you learn how to repair a Land Rover in
the bush, a compass is no big deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
