<HEADLINE>
VODKA BRAND GIVES PETS A HELPING HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the more peculiar pairings we've encountered lately is
between Grey Goose Vodka and the American Society for the
Prevention of Cruelty to Animals.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit brand, introduced in this country last year, gives 1
percent of profits to the ASPCA. The holiday marketing campaign
(with its adorable photo) stretches amusingly to convey its message
about how ideal booze is as a present, while pets are less of a
best bet.
</P>
<P>
   According to a news release, ``Grey Goose Vodka is a great gift,
(but) the ASPCA reminds the public that surprising someone with a
puppy or kitten under the Christmas tree can be a recipe for
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider all the ramifications and responsibilities before
giving a pet, the ASPCA warns, or the society will have another
abandoned critter on its hands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TASTY BUGS: In a publication called the Nutrition Action
Healthletter, we find some alarming information about the
primary-colored beverage Fruitopia, a product of the Coca-Cola Co.
Although the label boasts Fruitopia to be a ``real fruit
beverage,'' it has only the equivalent of two to four tablespoons
of fruit juice per 20-ounce bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Each bottle contains 275 calories and 17 to 19 teaspoons of
added sugar. Also in Fruitopia is an additive called cochineal, a
red dye made from the pulverized bodies of insects that has caused
severe allergic reactions in some people. It's in at least four
flavors of Fruitopia.
</P>
<P>
   The $24-a-year Healthletter is published by the Center for
Science in the Public Interest, a group known for attacking food of
dubious nutritional value. Subscribe by writing to CSPI, Suite 300,
1875 Connecticut Ave., NW, Washington, DC 20009-5728.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LICKED CLEAN: In the mail we find a product called etc, the
Electric Tongue Cleaner, made by Oralgiene.
</P>
<P>
   It's exactly that: a vibrating base and a curved plastic blade.
Scrape the buzzing thing across your tongue to reduce foul-smelling
exhalations by 85 percent, according to Oralgiene. Brushing your
tongue flattens bacteria into crevices instead of scraping them
away with 8,000 vibrations per second.
</P>
<P>
   I tried the device for a couple of weeks; it's surely the
strangest thing I've ever put into my mouth, and the process rather
feels like I'm mowing my tongue. Nobody ever complained about my
breath before (which may mean only that we have polite friends),
nor has anyone said it now smells sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   Find the $30 etc at Brookstone stores or order directly by
calling 800-933-ORAL (6725).
</P>
</TEXT>
