<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8664 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-PRINCE-BOS &LR;      12-14 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PRINCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PARTING OF THE WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's been a pretty good year for DreamWorks SKG.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in 1995 amid tons of hype, and even more money, the
studio headed by filmmaker Steven Spielberg, former Disney
executive Jeffrey Katzenberg, and all-purpose mogul David Geffen
stumbled for its first few years with such big-screen misfires as
``The Peacemaker'' and ``Paulie.'' And despite generally positive
reviews, ``Amistad,'' Spielberg's fact-based slave ship epic, sank
at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the much-scrutinized entertainment company seemed
to hit its stride. Its comet actioner, ``Deep Impact,'' was the
first hit of the summer, and the World War II movie was revived
with the harrowing ``Saving Private Ryan,'' a title sure to be
heard early and often when Academy Award nominations are announced
in February. Then the studio scored with its computer-animated
``Antz.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, DreamWorks unveils perhaps its most anticipated
project yet _ ``The Prince of Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the oft-told story of Moses, the film features the
voices of Val Kilmer as Moses and Ralph Fiennes as Rameses, as
stepbrothers made foes by conflicting destinies. Other actors who
lent their voices to the production are Sandra Bullock, Jeff
Goldblum, Michelle Pfeiffer, Danny Glover, Patrick Stewart, Steve
Martin, Helen Mirren, and Martin Short. It is the studio's first
traditionally animated feature, and as such, takes direct aim at
Disney, Katzenberg's former employer with whom he had a very
acrimonious split.
</P>
<P>
   And if taking Disney on in a field it has dominated for seven
decades weren't daunting enough, consider this film's subject
matter. Derived from the Old Testament book of Exodus, it is the
story of a man chosen by God to deliver the Hebrews from bondage in
Egypt. There's the Slaughter of the Innocents, brutalized slaves,
and some pretty nasty plagues when the Almighty wants to prove He
means business. Hardly a kid's movie, this is not the sort of
frothy confection some have come to expect in their animated films.
That would seem to make the film a bit of a risk for DreamWorks.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Katzenberg, the film's executive producer, views the
challenge quite differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technique of animation has been used for 70 years to tell
fairy tales. I loved the fairy tales, and for years at Disney, I
loved doing it. But we wanted to try and do something different at
DreamWorks,'' he said recently during a New York trip with cast and
crew to promote the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I compare this to when Steven Spielberg, (director) Bob
Zemeckis, and I were involved in `Who Framed Roger Rabbit.' We told
people this would be different, with live action and animation, and
people would say, `Oh, `Pete's Dragon,' and we would say, `No, this
is something completely different.' To me, there is an unbelievably
rich opportunity to take this technique of animation, and tell
something other than a fairy tale.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has visited this dramatic terrain before. In 1923,
Cecil B. DeMille, the legendary director who never met a biblical
epic he didn't like, made ``The Ten Commandments,'' a silent film
starring Theodore Roberts as Moses and Charles De Roche as Rameses,
the Egyptian king who opposed Moses' quest to free the Hebrews.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three years later, DeMille remade his film as an
all-color, all-talking spectacular starring Charlton Heston as
Moses and Yul Brynner as the sexiest Rameses ever to don a skirt
and breastplate _ ``So shall it be written, so shall it be done!''
The Oscar-nominated film also starred Anne Baxter, Edward G.
Robinson, Vincent Price, and Dame Judith Anderson, and may well
have been a visual guideline for ``The Prince of Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that it was the only guideline for the filmmakers.
DreamWorks sought the counsel and advice of educators, biblical
scholars, Egyptologists, biblical archeologists, and religious
leaders including the Revs. Jesse Jackson, Jerry Falwell, Pat
Robertson, and Cecil Murray, and Rabbi Marvin Hier.
</P>
<P>
   Given the subject matter, the filmmakers were concerned about
historical accuracy, and even reverence for the source material.
One of the most difficult challenges was faced by lyricist Stephen
Schwartz, who wrote original songs for the film. His songs had to
be entertaining, but couldn't be too cute lest they undermine the
tale's seriousness. At one point there even were talking and
singing camels, but they didn't make the final cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bit of tightrope walk, so we kept going back to the
human story,'' said Schwartz, who has also worked on Disney's ``The
Hunchback of Notre Dame'' and ``Pocahontas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on the story was defined as a brother story, and as soon
as I heard that I seized on that,'' he said. ``This is the story of
two brothers who care deeply for one another, but their destinies
pull them apart until, at the end, they are literally separated by
an ocean. Coming back to the emotion and humanity of that story
helps you not worry too much about who you're offending.''
</P>
<P>
   But the film's composer, Hans Zimmer, acknowledged how precious
this story is to the devout and faithful. What is at stake, he
said, goes beyond upstart DreamWorks' fledgling reputation as an
animation titan to rival Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us,'' he said, ``wants to become the Salman Rushdies
of the film business, having offended the majority of the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 1330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
