</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-COMPUTERS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING PERSONAL WITH THE COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)``I honestly think you ought to calm down; take a stress
pill and think things over.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   That is, as cult-film enthusiasts know, one of the most
memorable lines uttered by HAL 9000, the computer that goes berserk
in Stanley Kubrick's 1968 head-trip classic, ``2001: A Space
Odyssey.'' ``Calm down,'' HAL says in that distinctive disembodied
voice, a sort of mellow whine with a malevolent bite. ``Take a
stress pill,'' the dysfunctional computer advises, shortly before
suffering a system breakdown and threatening the mere humans who
brought him into operation one fine day in January 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Poor HAL and his compatriot computers, forever typecast as the
evil menace wreaking danger and destruction. In films ranging from
``Desk Set'' in 1957 to ``The Net'' in 1995, computers have been
characterized on the big screen as dark, sometimes apocalyptic
forces that instill paranoia and fear. Created and operated by
stereotypical programmers portrayed as emotionless bureaucrats,
misfits, or nerds, these huge machines are going to make us lose
our jobs, lose our wars, lose our freedom, lose our very
identities. The message has been clear: Pull the plug.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, that is. The computer has a new screen image _
perky, trim, and so user-friendly you can snuggle up with it in
bed. In ``You've Got Mail,'' the romantic comedy starring Tom Hanks
and Meg Ryan that opens Friday, the laptop computer is more than
just a benign communication tool. It comforts lonely hearts; it
brings unlikely lovers together; it makes folks who live small but
meaningful lives feel significant in the cosmos. It's the yenta of
the 21st century, an unparalleled matchmaker, a silicon chip with a
heart of gold. And the people who use it aren't calculating
scientists or adolescent hackers: They're America's sweethearts,
ordinary sorts harboring that &QC; 
timeless dream that their soul mate is out there, maybe just around
the corner.
</P>
<P>
   The blinking red eye of HAL has segued to the teary hazel eyes
of the adorable Meg Ryan, typing away on the keyboard and praying
for Mr. Right.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a good thing. ``Over the years, the computer has
played the heavy and the villain, but increasingly, we're going to
see the computer as less and less the evil bad guy,'' says
Christopher Morgan, a computer consultant and author of ``The
Official Computer Bowl Trivia Book.'' ``Over the last two decades,
people's impression of computers has changed, and certainly the
personal computer had a role in that. The mystique went away. The
idea that the computer was going to harm us has melted. Now, people
don't think twice about their computers doing good or evil. They're
just an integral part of life, like a car. I can't imagine a movie
about an evil car.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that long ago, it would have been hard to imagine a
children's movie about a friendly computer (HAL the debugged Love
Bug?), but that scenario doesn't seem too far-fetched today.
</P>
<P>
   As the technology has evolved and infiltrated everyday life, so
has the computer's screen image. In fact, the doomsday films of the
last few decades _ and even a few years ago _ seem hilarious today,
even to those without an engineer's sense of humor. It's hard not
to snicker when world leaders with grim faces and trim haircuts are
called in to oversee computer-generated crises in such films as
``Colossus: The Forbin Project'' (1970) and ``WarGames'' (1983).
After all, today President Clinton wants a computer in every
classroom and greets browsers cheerfully on the White House Web
site. HAL, we hardly knew ye.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've Got Mail,'' then, brings the computer image full circle
in more ways than one. Back in 1957, an ``electronic brain'' called
EMMY terrified office workers in ``Desk Set,'' a screwball comedy
starring Spencer Tracy and Katharine Hepburn. The computer itself _
a laughably inauthentic wall of steel and flashing lights, complete
with a Teletype machine _ was a thin plot device to get the
Hepburn-Tracy chemistry thing going. She runs a research office at
a television network, and he has been hired to improve office
efficiency. The researchers are convinced the computer is going to
make their jobs obsolete; they do all end up with pink slips, but
only as a result of a computer error made by the payroll
department. The important thing is that the stars get to battle
wits and acknowledge their attraction by the time the credits roll.
Boy gets girl, despite the computer.
</P>
<P>
   That will-they-ever-get-together theme is central to ``Mail,''
though the computer is now the conduit for love rather than the
obstacle. (Coincidentally, Henry and Phoebe Ephron wrote ``Desk
Set''; four decades later, their daughters, Nora and Delia Ephron,
penned the script for ``Mail,'' which Nora Ephron directed; see
accompanying story.) The male romantic lead has evolved, however.
In his usual frumpy fashion, Tracy played an eccentric MIT
graduate, a kind of antisocial character whose socks don't match
and who seems to idle away the time solving differential equations.
By contrast, Tom Hanks in ``Mail'' is, well, Tom Hanks, the
fresh-scrubbed hero who guided Apollo 13 back to earth safely.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 1331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8666 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-COMPUTERS-2ND &LR;      12-14 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-COMPUTERS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... to earth safely.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its lighthearted, gentle way, ``Desk Set'' started the
tradition of the computer geek on-screen. The Space Age engineers
in ``2001'' are inscrutable, even when interrogated by HAL. (``What
are you doing, Dave?'') In ``Colossus,'' electronics wizard Charles
Forbin describes himself as ``an impartial, emotionless machine, a
paragon of reason.'' The college students in a 1970 Disney comedy
called ``The Computer Wore Tennis Shoes'' are lovable losers; in
the hit ``WarGames,'' an astonishingly young Matthew Broderick fits
all the criteria of the stereotypical hacker _ a brainy
underachiever who is estranged from his parents and has difficulty
communicating with his peers. Two programmers in ``WarGames'' are
quintessential geeks: One is a nasal-voiced nerd in a plaid shirt,
and the other is a volatile nutcase wearing a smily-face T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   The stereotype gets even more absurd in ``The Net,'' which casts
Sandra Bullock against type as a lonely software engineer who has
no friends, rarely leaves the house, and hasn't taken a vacation in
years. When evil computer mavericks steal her identity, she has
nowhere to turn. The film, which came out just around the time the
World Wide Web was emerging as the great new frontier for
nontechnical types, paints in the kind of paranoid shades that
colored movies during the Cold War. In this case, however, the
enemy isn't the abstract notion of communism: It's simply the
computer. In ``The Net,'' the computer isn't going to blow up the
world with one quick blast; it's going to do it slowly, eliminating
us one by one, erasing our identities as well as our humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock is up against evil manipulators who use the technology
maliciously; the people, not the machines themselves, are the
psychopaths who pull the trigger. But in films made during the Cold
War, computers are sentient things with the ability to learn and to
act on their own. In ``2001'' and ``WarGames,'' they can also play
a good game of chess, which shows what most people thought
computers could do in previous decades _ that is, play games and
destroy the universe.
</P>
<P>
   That fear stemmed from the belief that computers really were
electronic brains with the ability to think. For all its spacy
choreography, ``2001'' offers an astute psychological study of HAL,
who becomes maniacal only after his feelings get hurt. When he's
disconnected, he reverts to childhood in that creepy, classic
``death scene,'' singing ``Daisy'' as he remembers his youth.
Likewise, the computer in ``Colossus'' begins to act on its own and
establishes contact with its counterpart in the former Soviet
Union. The two machines communicate via neon messages scrolling
across a marquee; the machine orders military-style executions,
takes over the global defense system, and threatens to launch World
War III. Not bad for a big box with flashing lights. The looming
threat is that man will become a slave to the machine: ``Obey me
and live, or disobey me and die,'' the computer commands eerily.
</P>
<P>
   The apocalypse is also the underlying threat in ``WarGames,''
which starts out as a sort of ``Ferris Bueller's Day at the Video
Arcade'' and turns into a military thriller. After Broderick's
character inadvertently finds a ``back door'' into the Defense
Department's computer system, the machine starts acting on its own,
simulating an international conflict that could end in nuclear
destruction. Broderick's computer geek joins forces with a mad
scientist played by John Wood, whose darting eyes and nervous tics
make him seem a human version of HAL 9000.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but yesterday's madmen and misfits are today's millionaires.
In ``You've Got Mail,'' Tom Hanks is a perfectly sane, perfectly
handsome fellow who uses his personal computer to reach out and
e-mail his on-line buddy. Oh, he also happens to be a filthy-rich
scion of a bookselling empire, but in the film, that's just a
little plot device to get the two cyberpals together. Hanks's
character, Joe Fox, is opening a superstore around the corner from
Ryan's children's bookstore, appropriately called the Shop Around
the Corner (a nod to the title of the 1940 Ernst Lubitsch comedy
that ``You've Got Mail'' remakes). The two feud like competitors:
He represents big business swallowing up the mom-and-pop shops, and
she is a link to a simpler past, where human contact mattered. In
the meantime, Ryan and Hanks are doing a little flirting dance in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The computer here is just a part of everyday life, as routine
as, say, a toaster oven. The machine isn't evil; the people who use
it are regular folks. The film, a sort of cyberversion of
``Sleepless in Seattle,'' even has in-jokes about the computer
industry: A batty character played by Jean Stapleton announces that
she is rich, explaining, ``I bought Intel at $6.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, this isn't the first movie that presents computers as
benign: The machines in such film and television series as ``Star
Trek,'' ``Star Wars,'' ``Lost in Space,'' and ``The Jetsons''
certainly did more good than harm. But in ``Mail,'' the computer
actually brings people together, a fact that isn't lost on folks
who have been preaching about the potential of technology for
decades. ``I'm so pleased to see this type of movie come out,''
says computer consultant Morgan. ``I've been proselytizing about
computers for years, and now they've hit critical mass. They're a
very important part of society, and they're going to revolutionize
the way we live over the next 100 or 200 years. It's about time
movies started to reflect that.''
</P>
<P>
   And yes, ``You've Got Mail'' does just that. In the film, both
Hanks and Ryan are avid customers of America Online, the Internet
service provider and communication service that has 14 million
members. Whatever their differences in the flesh world _ he's the
corporate monolith swallowing up the competition, she is the
competition _ the romantic leads open windows to each other's souls
in the cyberworld. The computer is no longer the heavy; it's a
humanizing tool that enables two strangers who might unknowingly
pass each other at Starbucks to actually sit down over a tall decaf
latte.
</P>
<P>
   Without giving away the ending, let's just say computers are no
longer the evil menace. In fact, the movie asks: How were we ever
human without them?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 1332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8667 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CROWDED-SKIES-BOS &LR;      12-14 1724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROWDED-SKIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIES SAFE, BUT CLOSE CALLS SUGGEST TROUBLE AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A computer system that air traffic controllers rely on fails and
radar screens go blank. Error messages flash on computer screens.
Controllers scramble for pencil and paper and try to reconstruct
what was on their screens and plot where the planes were.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to controllers, two jumbo jets with a total of 372
people on board are on a collision course six miles above the East
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the stuff of made-for-TV movies. It happened. Last
Sunday night. As the planes neared each other, computers on both
aircraft alerted crews to take evasive action to prevent a
collision. A midair disaster was averted.
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, a similar incident occurred. Two planes came
within 300 feet of each other. This time, it was the on-board
computer system that brought the planes dangerously close together.
</P>
<P>
   There are more planes in the sky than at anytime in history, and
during the holiday season, those planes are filled with passengers.
Long-range forecasts call for more airplanes, more flights, and
even more crowded skies. It all makes one wonder: How safe is it to
fly?
</P>
<P>
   The simple answer is it is very safe _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   But there are signs that the air traffic control system is
strained to the breaking point, and the accident rate _ while still
very low _ has plateaued since the last big safety breakthrough of
reliable jet engines. If air traffic increases at expected rates,
and if new safety measures promised by officials are not taken _ or
fail to make the system safer _ experts say that within 20 years we
can expect an airline crash someplace in the world every eight to
10 days.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the good news for nervous holiday travelers: The risk
of being in a fatal airplane crash on a US commercial jet is about
one in 3 million. Overall, our safety systems work and work well;
just consider those two midair events. There were no collisions, no
one died. No one was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1990s, about 5 billion people have flown on commercial
planes in US air space and the number of people killed has been
zero, so that should give us some perspective,'' says Arnold
Barnett, a statistician at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. ``With these two events, it was either a TCAS (the
on-board computer that warns pilots of approaching airplanes)
problem or an ATC (air traffic control) problem, but not both.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me you'd have to have a TCAS failure and an ATC
failure, and some very bad luck, to have a midair collision,'' he
said. ``So in some ways, these incidents suggest the margin of
safety, rather than it is on the brink of collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about the future? Taking the long view, there is reason
for concern about the nation's air traffic control system.
Unplanned outages of power, computers, and radar have been
increasing steadily in recent years as equipment is extended well
beyond its normal life.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Boston Center, located in Nashua, N.H., where
controllers handle all the high altitude flights over New England
and upstate New York. Earlier this year, they faced, on average, an
outage a day. The outages lasted anywhere from a few seconds to
more than a half-hour. But when a radar screen loses crucial data,
controllers _ responsible for keeping planes safely separated _
have no way of knowing if it will reappear with the next radar
sweep, in 12 seconds, or in 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   And nationwide, in 1983 the total unscheduled downtime for air
traffic and navigation equipment was 210,000 hours. In 1997, it was
600,000 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, the Reagan administration vowed to rebuild
the air traffic control system with new technology. But the Federal
Aviation Administration underestimated the cost and complexity of
the task. Parts of the system were obsolete before they could even
be delivered. So equipment that was old in the early 1980s is still
being used today.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA says it will have to spend at least $42 billion to
modernize the air traffic system _ an amount that makes the
nation's largest public works road project, Boston's Big Dig, look
like chump change. FAA Administrator Jane Garvey has said
modernization is her top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Some new equipment _ long-range radar systems, computers, and
controller displays _ are already being installed around the
country. They are going to the centers that handle high altitude
traffic; to the facilities (called TRACONs) where controllers
direct planes as soon as they leave major airports, or just before
they start their final approaches; and to airport towers, which
handle arriving and departing planes and those on the ground. But
complete modernization is still a ways off.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more alarming than the old equipment is the
shortage of people who are qualified to repair it. And spare parts
can be as hard to come by as a certified technician.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have major facilities across the country that do not have
certified people on duty during critical times, and the agency
rolls the dice that nothing will occur during those hours,'' says
Michael Fanfalone, president of the Professional Airways Systems
Specialists, the union representing the technicians who maintain
and repair computers, radar, power systems, and navigation aids.
Los Angeles Airport, he said, does not have technicians on duty 24
hours to repair radar. And in one metropolitan New York facility,
technicians are cannibalizing radar displays for parts to keep the
system working.
</P>
<P>
   Why the shortage of technicians and spare parts? In large part
it is due to the FAA's failure to modernize the system as it
planned nearly 20 years ago. Why keep technicians on, the agency
reasoned, if we will have a new automated system? The only problem
is the new system has yet to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the IBM computers used to run air traffic are so old
that all the engineers who worked on them have retired from IBM.
The FAA could find only one former IBM official willing to go over
millions of lines of code in a mainframe computer used by
controllers to see if the system will be affected by the Year 2000
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the FAA insists the system remains safe.
</P>
<P>
   While one can argue about how much safety is compromised by old
equipment, understaffing, and lack of spare parts, it is
irrefutable that those problems slow the entire system down. Planes
that would have been in the air are kept on the ground, and those
in the air are spaced farther apart. The results are delays and
cancellations that cost consumers.
</P>
<P>
   A panel appointed by Congress, the National Civil Aviation
Review Commission, had this dire warning a year ago: ``Unless the
FAA and various aviation stakeholders _ the Congress, the Executive
Branch, and the aviation community _ change the status quo,
internal and external to the FAA, our nation's aviation system will
succumb to gridlock. Delays will skyrocket while we reminisce about
the reliable flight schedules of the past. This current course will
impair our domestic economy, reduce our standing in the global
marketplace, and result in a long term deterioration of aviation
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has big plans for the future, including the use of an
enhanced global positioning system, or GPS, to help planes navigate
more accurately, and enable them to fly from point A to point B
without having to follow the sometimes-winding route required by
ground-based navigation aids. But the FAA recently had to scale
back its vision of the enhanced GPS satellite systems (known as
WAAS and LAAS) because of a variety of risks, including its cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are relooking at alternatives, keeping more ground
navigation aids, and we are revalidating our cost-benefit study,''
says Steven Zaidman, associate administrator for Research and
Aquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Zaidman, however, says the replacement of the existing computer
and radar display systems controllers use is going ahead and
controllers will have new systems within a matter of months, and
virtually all should have new systems by the middle of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   And the agency is working with the industry to promote so-called
``free flight,'' in which pilots will eventually navigate by
satellite. The idea will take many years to implement, but under
phase one, some facilities will receive equipment by 2002 that will
let pilots and controllers communicate by airborne e-mail, which
should improve communications, and controllers will have better
tools to help them identify potential conflicts in flight patterns.
Prototypes are already in Memphis and Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   But long before ``free flight'' is a reality, the FAA is likely
to experience significant problems upgrading the current computer
and radar display systems with more modern computers.
</P>
<P>
   The backup system that controllers use when the main system is
down, or being replaced, is referred to as DARC. But controllers
say they have little experience working on DARC. As a result, there
is confusion whenever the primary system fails.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Transportation inspector general, in a report
released two weeks ago, and the National Transportation Safety
Board, in a report released two years ago, agreed with the
controllers' demand for more DARC training. The FAA says the
twice-a-year training (much of it video-based) that controllers
receive in DARC is sufficient, even though it does not include
using simulated traffic patterns on the computer system.
</P>
<P>
   While Mike McNally, president of the National Air Traffic
Controllers Association, applauds many of the technological
improvements the FAA is pushing, he says it is imperative
controllers get more training in DARC. And McNally said controllers
also need refresher training in how to safely separate airplanes
when there is no radar coverage at all. ``We've all had that at
some point, but it could have been 10 years ago or more.''
</P>
<P>
   Why is it needed? Radar occasionally does go out; or the
computer failure is so extensive that controllersrely on radio and
pencil and paper. And there are concerns about the new millennium:
``We need the training because of Y2K there could be an extensive
outage,'' McNally said.
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
