<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUT WHAT ABOUT THE CHILDREN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are 10 years old. That's old enough to tell you that the
music you listen to is lame, but young enough to consider ``Jingle
Bells'' the definitive Christmas carol. It's old enough to insist
on cargo pants and waffle-weave shirts as a daytime uniform, but
young enough to prefer pajamas with cartoon characters at bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   They are fourth graders, one-third of the public school
population that took the Massachusetts Comprehensive Assessment
System test last spring, one-third of the 208,800 students in
grades four, eight and 10 whose skills were evaluated in math,
science, and English.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, too many fourth graders failed in one or more subject
areas; too few earned an advanced score. The airwaves crackle with
talk of a crisis in education. The schoolyards hum with the
whispers of anxious parents.
</P>
<P>
   As so often happens with issues involving our children, the
focus has been on the impact of the MCAS results on adults. Will
school superintendents face political pressure? Will principals be
browbeaten? Will individual teachers be forced to alter their
teaching style? Will parents need to help more with homework? Will
legislators reconsider spending levels for education?
</P>
<P>
   But what about the kids who are at the heart of all this? Should
we tell a 10-year-old that she failed the MCAS test or that she
earned an advanced score? Does she need to know where her score
fell in a range between 200 and 280? Will that number mean anything
more to her than yet another opportunity to see how she stacks up
against her pals?
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, students in the eighth or 10th grade can use the
results as an incentive to do better or as reassurance that they
are on the right track. By now, they are pros at the standardized
test routine, veterans of the IOWAs, the ERBs, the MEAPs, the
PSATs. The SATs loom. And starting with the Class of 2003, students
must have passed the 10th grade MCAS test to graduate. It makes
some sense to know how challenging that goal will be.
</P>
<P>
   But what about those 10-year-olds who often look so grown up but
are still so young in the less visible places, where it counts?
</P>
<P>
   The comparison game starts too young in too many arenas already:
the boy convinced there is no point in playing soccer because his
coach says he'll never make the ``A'' team. The girl who quits
piano because she's convinced she'll never play as well as her best
friend. At 10, the world is black and white. ``Are we rich?'' they
ask when you park a new car in the driveway. ``Are we poor?'' they
ask when you tell them that the new car is a used car. Angst, once
the province of adolescence, strikes at an ever younger age. At 10,
they are already asking, ``Am I a geek? Am I cool? Am I smart? Am I
dumb?''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the adults tell them the MCAS test is a
baseline, a tool for improvement, not evaluation. Children have
especially acute radar for hypocrisy. They hear us say that no
single test is an accurate measure of performance. But what do they
see? A mother indignant because her son was deemed proficient in
math when it's clear to her that he is advanced. A father enraged
because his daughter failed, even though she insists she studies
hard.
</P>
<P>
   Mom says he is special; the test says he is merely competent.
Dad says she is lazy; the test says she is a failure. Who reminds
these children that they are 10-year-olds - works in progress?
</P>
<P>
   The disconnect in our homes between what we say and what we do
is as evident on a communal level. John Silber, the chairman of the
state Board of Education, says, ``If you know what the
socioeconomic conditions are in different communities, you have
about 60 percent of all the information you need to predict their
scores.'' Then he talks about how to raise test scores, not how to
address the underlying issues responsible for them. We are going to
spend $20 million for remedial help for students who performed
poorly. How much are we willing to spend for day care, for job
training, for affordable housing, to lift their families out of the
poverty that contributed to those scores?
</P>
<P>
   The night the test results were released, my family made its
annual shopping trip for Christmas ornaments to Lord's, the general
store on Main Street in Medfield, a town where we once lived. The
place was abuzz with talk about Medfield's second place ranking in
overall achievement on the MCAS. ``The value of our houses just
went up,'' the cashier said with real pride. ``We never should have
moved,'' said my son with genuine alarm. And I hadn't even told him
his MCAS score. And I won't.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
