<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANTED: AN EDMUND G. ROSS TO SAVE US FROM OURSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If we don't learn from history, the saying goes, we are doomed
to repeat it. As Congress drives recklessley driven toward the
impeachment of President Clinton, doomed is the appropriate word.
</P>
<P>
   Our nation's democracy could have been, if not doomed, at least
seriously harmed 130 years ago, if not for the one courageous vote
cast against the impeachment of President Andrew Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment process then was as partisan as it is today.
And, ironically, the group that led the rush toward impeachment in
1868 consisted of radical Republicans, a group not much different
in both name and deed from those seeking Clinton's impeachment and
ouster from office today.
</P>
<P>
   The road toward impeachment for Johnson began when those radical
Republicans split with the party's moderates over how to treat
South after the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   The moderates, President Johnson among them, wanted to follow
through on President Abraham Lincoln's plans of reunion and
reconciliation toward the South. The radical Republicans, spurred
on by Lincoln's murder, wanted reprisals and retribution against
the South.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson rejected the radical Republicans' plan, and continued to
pursue reconciliation. And therein lay the seeds of the impeachment
effort.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to seize control of the government, the radical
Republicans passed a law, over Johnson's veto, that prevented a
president from removing a cabinet officer he appoints. Johnson,
knowing that the law was unconstitutional, ignored it. He fired a
disloyal cabinet member, Secretary of War Edwin Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Stanton's Republican backers accused Johnson of a
``high crime and misdemeanor.'' In fact, as history has shown,
Johnson did not even violate the law, since Stanton was appointed
not by Johnson, but by Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it was not a violation of the law, but an intense hatred
of Johnson by the radical Republicans that fueled the drive toward
impeachment. And it is the right-wing Republicans' hatred of
Clinton that is driving the impeachment process today.
</P>
<P>
   The 1868 House vote for impeachment of Johnson was strictly
along party lines; no Democrat voted for it, no Republican against
it.
</P>
<P>
   On the 1998 Judiciary Committee, the votes for articles of
impeachment against Clinton last week were also strictly on
partisan lines. Among the 37 members, all 21 Republicans for the
articles, all 16 Democrats against. The House vote on impeachment
this week is also expected to be largely along partisan lines, with
Clinton's supporters hoping to persuade enough moderate Republicans
to vote against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote on impeachment this week is seen as too close to
call _ reminiscent of the 1868 Senate vote on whether to convict or
acquit Johnson of a high crime and misdemeanor. Johnson's, and the
nation's, fate was decided by a single vote.
</P>
<P>
   One of the radical Republican's own, Edmund G. Ross of Kansas,
broke with his colleagues and cast the deciding vote against
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson had been impeached, Benjamin Wade, the president pro
tempore of the Senate and a Republican, would have been the next
President and the radical Republicans would have carried out their
scorched earth policy against the South.
</P>
<P>
   Ross later wrote to explain his vote: ``If the president must
step down upon insufficient proofs and from partisan
considerations, the office of president would be degraded'' and
``ever after subordinated to the legislative will.'' He added,
``this government had never faced so insidious a danger.''
</P>
<P>
   It is today as it was 130 years ago, when Sen. Charles Sumner
declared, ``Impeachment is a political proceeding before a
political body with a political purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, today's impeachment proceeding is driven by politics and
fueled by hatred and contempt, just as in Johnson's day. Justice
had nothing to do with either proceeding, because justice both
times was pushed aside by a very partisan group of Republicans
seeking to destroy a president they could not control.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's second impeachment proceeding _ against President
Nixon _ was different. After hearing the facts, few doubted that
Nixon indeed did commit high crimes and misdemeanors, including
obstruction of justice during his attempted coverup of the break-in
of the Democratic National Committee headquarters at the Watergate
Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee vote for impeachment against Nixon
came on July 27, 1974, when six Republicans joined 21 Democrats in
the 27-11 vote for the first article of impeachment. Less than two
weeks later, Nixon resigned from office rather than face almost
certain ouster. In this instance, justice prevailed over partisan
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, when the impeachment process is in the wrong hands
_ as it was during Johnson's tenure and as it is in Clinton's _
those driving the process can, in one blast, politically execute a
president and subvert the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there will be a voice _ or voices _ of reason that will
come forth, as Ross did 130 years ago, to prevent an impeachment
vote against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   If there is anything to be learned from the impeachment
proceedings against President Johnson, it's that somewhere in
Congress there are Republicans like Ross who can bring this nation
back from the brink of disaster. All they need to do is to gather
their courage and vote ``no'' against an unfair, partisan,
mean-spirited and dangerous impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   They will know, as did Ross, that they did it not merely to save
Clinton, but to save their country.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
