<SLUG> BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MEANING OF THE MCAS: EDUCATION REFORM IS DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF JACOBY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the great frauds in modern Massachusetts politics was the
Education Reform Act of 1993. Though the law ran to hundreds of
paragraphs, its premise was simple: Throw more money at public
education, and public education will improve.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem with public schooling in Massachusetts, as in
most of America, was never a shortage of dollars. It was a shortage
of accountability. Students who didn't feel like studying knew
their teachers would promote them anyway. Teachers who didn't feel
like mastering their subject or working hard in the classroom knew
their union contract would protect them from being disciplined or
fired. Principals and superintendents who didn't feel like whipping
lousy schools into shape knew that most parents would have little
choice but to keep sending their kids back, year after year after
year.
</P>
<P>
   Government-run schools were doing such a poor job because they
faced no penalty for incompetence. Along came the Education Reform
Act and said: Let's reward incompetence. The treasury's sluices
were thrown open. Money rained down on the very people who had
wrecked the schools in the first place. Five years and $5 billion
of education ``reform'' later, students are as ignorant as ever.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide MCAS test scores released last week are a horror.
Students in the 4th, 8th, and 10th grades were tested in English,
science, and math, and they performed miserably. In every grade and
every subject, save for 8th-grade English, a majority of students
either did poorly or failed outright. Fifty percent of all
10th-graders flunked the math test; another 24 percent wound up in
the second-lowest ``needs improvement'' tier. Among 4th-graders, a
stunning 81 percent earned low marks in English. In science, 71
percent of 8th-graders scored at the lowest levels.
</P>
<P>
   The MCAS (Massachusetts Comprehensive Assessment System) was not
overly tough. On the 8th-grade math test, for example, students
confronted this question: ``According to the 1990 Census, the
population of Massachusetts was 6,016,425. Approximately what
percent of those people lived in Boston?'' The population of Boston
was given as 574,283, and students were offered four choices: (a)
10%, (b) 20%, (c) 30%, and (d) 40%. That is a question an alert
5th-grader should have no trouble with. Three out of four
8th-graders got it wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, which spends more per pupil than almost any other
jurisdiction, the results stank.
</P>
<P>
   In one school, every 4th-grader failed in science and 70 percent
failed in math. More than two-thirds of the 8th-graders can't do
math; three-fourths don't know science. Nearly 90 percent of
10th-graders in the regular high schools failed math; 60 percent
failed English. Unsurprisingly, at the city's worst high school _
the Jeremiah Burke _ virtually every student failed everything. But
even the allegedly elite exam schools disgraced themselves. Among
10-graders in Boston Latin Academy, for example, 87 percent earned
poor or failing marks in science; 71 percent did so in math.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, only an employer intent on bankruptcy would
hand out fat raises to his least competent employees. But in the
warped world of public education, the crummiest schools and
teachers get the most lavish bonuses. The schools that did poorest
on the MCAS will not be shut down. Their principals will not be
fired. No: They will be given a bounty of $20 million. This is what
passes for education reform.
</P>
<P>
   Since April there have been three rounds of state tests for
prospective teachers. These are exams any diligent high school
student should be able to ace, yet 45 percent or more of would-be
teachers _ graduates of colleges of education _ have flunked.
Beacon Hill did not respond by increasing salaries for teachers of
proven excellence, or by stripping the inept education schools of
their credentialing power. No: It authorized $20,000 bonuses for
new, inexperienced teachers so that colleges of education can
recruit even more students. This too is what passes for education
reform.
</P>
<P>
   On the day the atrocious MCAS scores were released, the
Massachusetts teachers union issued a press release. ``The first
year's results should be used to establish a baseline, not to judge
the success of education reform . . . . Education reform is a work
in progress . . . . The Massachusetts public education system as a
whole is very good.'' This nonsense promptly became the line of the
education bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Superintendent Thomas Payzant: ``We don't have to
scramble. This is a baseline. We expect progress in years one, two,
and three.''
</P>
<P>
   State Senator Robert Antonioni, Education Committee co-chairman:
``I wouldn't read too much into this one way or the other. This is
the first time it's been given.''
</P>
<P>
   Board of Education Chairman John Silber: ``I am . . . pleasantly
surprised with the scores on the MCAS. It doesn't give parents,
teachers, administrators, or school committees any cause for
alarm.''
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge Superintendent Bobbie D'Alessandro: ``Remember, this
is just the beginning of the journey and not the destination.''
Wrong. The MCAS debacle is not the ``beginning'' but the end. The
Education Reform Act was an expensive failure. The state's
government schools are wretched and will remain wretched. This is
as good as it gets. ``Reform'' is over. The children lost.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Jacoby is a Globe columnist. His e-mail address is
jacoby(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
