<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8678 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-14 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, UNLIKE NIXON, COULD BOW OUT AS MARTYR 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ He's a nice guy, active in liberal politics,
bright as hell. He called me with this question:
</P>
<P>
   ``Daniel, where was your mind at when you wrote that column?
Didn't you pick up anything from the last election? Nobody cares
what Bill Clinton did in the privacy of his own home with another
consenting adult.''
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton riding a 65 percent approval rating despite the
televised commission of a felony _ namely, perjury before a grand
jury _ I'd written that I simply can't shake the image of Richard
Nixon gazing up from Hell, frowning deeply and marveling at the
Clinton spin team's altogether astonishing job here.
</P>
<P>
   My friend was saying _ like so many other suckers, I'm afraid _
that this is only about sex. It isn't. But, just for argument's
sake, let's pretend it is.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, sex is a gift from God. And what a clever idea on Her
part. But is consensual sex inherently OK under all circumstances?
Or, is there consensual sex that's irresponsible, cruel and hurtful
to others and degrading to everybody forced to confront it? And, if
you believe there is, are you just a puritanical simpleton with a
perverted preoccupation with the uses to which other people put
their genitalia? Or are you a realist?
</P>
<P>
   Also, Clinton didn't fool around with his intern in his own
home. He did this thing in the public's workplace, the Oval Office.
So, the other day, I called my friend back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,` I said, ``did you see today's story about the four
Albany County Jail guards? They got fired because they were getting
sex from inmates in exchange for cigarettes. That was consensual
sex in a public workplace, just like Clinton and his intern. Do you
think it was fair that they lost their jobs while Clinton keeps
his?''
</P>
<P>
   He hemmed and hawed. Different thing, he said. The jail business
was bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, I said, but it wasn't perjury, was it?
</P>
<P>
   And that's the central issue here _ not sex, however tawdry and
distasteful, but perjury, perjury, perjury. And commission of that
felony, admittedly combined with fierce partisanship in the House
of Representatives, is what led to the Judiciary Committee to
recommend the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't been following this, start right now. Twenty-four
years ago, Richard Nixon shocked the nation by resigning after the
committee recommended impeachment _ but before the full House
acted. That's because he knew that he'd committed felonies. And he
feared that, once impeached, he couldn't be pardoned and could face
criminal action somewhere down the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution forbids any president to pardon anybody for
``an impeachable offense.'' The question is whether that means a
criminal offense for which the House impeaches or an offense that
also requires Senate conviction. No court has ever interpreted that
language, and Nixon wasn't taking any chances.
</P>
<P>
   So he made a deal with Gerald Ford and said, ``check, please.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton knows what perjury is. He probably could pardon himself,
but impeachment might invalidate it unless he resigns before the
House votes. He could also cut a deal for Al Gore to pardon him,
and then pull a Nixon. With two out of three people backing him
instead of the one in four supporting Nixon when he left, Clinton
could still portray himself on his way out the door as the innocent
victim of partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   Were he to quit now, given all the suckers around, Clinton's
approval rating might even go up. Unlike Nixon, Clinton could end
up like Andrew Johnson, whose enemies in Congress are recalled by
history as venal, vindictive losers.
</P>
<P>
   Will he do it? Who knows? Remember, though, everybody thought
Nixon would go down sword in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he left office with a prudent whimper.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
