<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT SHOULD REJECT BAD PATRIOTS STADIUM DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If someone had walked into Governor Abraham Ribicoff's office in
December 1958 and proposed that the state of Connecticut spend tens
of millions of dollars to build a new stadium for a mediocre,
out-of-state football team, he or she would have been asked to
leave. If that same person, backpedaling toward the exit door, had
gone on to propose that virtually all of the economic benefits of
the stadium would accrue to the owner of said mediocre football
team, he or she would have been regarded as deranged.
</P>
<P>
   What was true then is true today. Publicly financed stadiums
don't generate economic activity. If anything, they displace it. If
you have any doubts about this, visit the South Bronx, where the
most profitable sports franchise in America, the New York Yankees,
reside.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly financed stadiums don't ``pay for themselves.'' If you
have any doubts about this, revisit the South Bronx, where Yankee
owner George Steinbrenner now says he needs more public money to
``enable'' him to keep his team in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly financed stadium deals are, by definition, corporate
welfare. Or, as business columnist Jim Suroweicki wrote this week,
``no deal in which a state or city puts up hundreds of millions of
dollars to build a stadium from which a sports team will derive all
the profit is a good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   For these very reasons, it now seems likely that Connecticut
Governor John Rowland's wacky scheme to bring the New England
Patriots to Hartford will collapse in a heap, as well it should.
Rowland offered Patriots owner Robert Kraft what can fairly be
described as the sweetheart stadium deal of the 20th century. Smith
College professor Andrew Zimblast, an expert on such matters,
recently catalogued the extent of the giveaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal,'' Zimblast wrote, ``includes, at Connecticut's
expense, a riverfront stadium for at least $280 million, $70
million to acquire and improve the site, $25 million to $100
million for environmental cleanup, land for a pavilion and hotel, a
$15 million practice facility, $170 million in a fund for future
improvements, and assorted state guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In return, Robert Kraft, the team owner, would pay no rent for
the 30-year life of the deal and keep all the revenue from ticket
sales, luxury suites, parking, concessions, and so on. All told,
Kraft's stadium income could be $100 million a year. The state
would get only a 10 percent ticket tax.''
</P>
<P>
   As in all bad deals, a prestigious accounting firm was engaged
to obfuscate matters. To no one's surprise, the firm engaged, KPMG
Peat Marwick, reported back that the state would break even on the
stadium when all was said and done. The deal, the firm said, was
``revenue neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   KPMG consultants may well be the only people extant who actually
believe this. An independent analysis conducted by the Connecticut
state Legislature's Office of Fiscal Analysis (OFA) found that the
state would, of course, lose money on the deal, and OFA's analysis
didn't even consider the opportunity costs.
</P>
<P>
   As details of the extent of the giveaway have surfaced,
Connecticut legislators have grown increasingly nervous about the
sudden rush to enact enabling legislation. In fact, key legislators
are now said to be wondering whether the deal should be scuttled
altogether. ``The mood has changed,'' says one Rowland adviser.
``We're scrambling to keep this thing on the rails.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Rowland announced that he would go back to Patriots
owner Robert Kraft to try to get new language that would
significantly decrease Connecticut's exposure to downside risk.
``There may be some changes in the guarantee,'' said Rowland,
meaning that there would have to be to keep key legislators on
board. Rowland's problem is that Kraft and his family have no real
incentive to give up what they have already gained. From their
point of view, ``a deal's a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   What is most amazing about all this is that there is a fairly
simple solution to the Patriots' problem. Let us say that the
Patriots are worth (and this is a very generous assessment) $350
million. Let us further say that they need $150 million in stadium
and infrastructure improvements. Let us overlook the fact that they
are a profitable enterprise and say that they need a state or
municipal government to provide them with the $150 million worth of
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. Connecticut or Massachusetts cuts a check for that amount.
Either state then builds a stadium, does the improvements, builds
the practice facility, etc. In return, the state gets a 30 percent
ownership stake in the team and is entitled to 30 percent of the
team's annual profits. The state also gets two seats on the board,
but pledges not to interfere with management, except in cases of
fiduciary or criminal misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut should insist on just such a deal. Anything less
will lead to nothing but grief. If Kraft balks and moves his team
to Los Angeles as a result, good riddance. Better the lesser fool
than the greater one.
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
