<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ICEMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A   5,000-YEAR-OLD PRESCRIPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The history of western medicine just got longer _ by a couple of
thousand years.
</P>
<P>
   More than five millenia ago, Stone Age people in Europe had a
highly evolved system of medical diagnosis and treatment, judging
from new clues provided by the Ice Man, whose well-preserved mummy
emerged seven years ago from a melting glacier in northern Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Recent analysis of the Ice Man's remains, along with two
heretofore puzzling walnut-sized spheres he was carrying on his
fatal expedition, has yielded evidence of some of the earliest
known uses of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The two spheres, threaded on leather thongs, were not tinder for
starting fires, as researchers earlier believed. Instead, Professor
Luigi Capasso of Italy's National Archeological Museum has found,
they are the woody fruit of a tree fungus that acts as a powerful
but short-acting laxative and also contains oils that are toxic to
intestinal parasites.
</P>
<P>
   That find dovetails with the earlier discovery by Professor
Horst Aspoeck and his colleagues at the University of Vienna, who
examined the contents of the mummy's intestines and discovered the
eggs of Trichuria trichiura, an intestinal worm that probably
caused the Ice Man periodic pain and anemia.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the evidence together in the British journal The Lancet,
Capasso concludes that the Ice Man (or his tribal healer) was able
to recognize the nature of his illness and use a remedy that was
remarkably specific for his condition.
</P>
<P>
   The remedy would have killed at least some of the intestinal
parasites and purged the bowel of its eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The discovery of the fungus suggests that the Ice Man was
aware of his intestinal parasites and fought them with measured
doses of Piptoporus betulinus,'' Capasso writes in the medical
journal. ``The toxic oils in the fungus were probably the only
remedy available in Europe'' until thousands of years later, when
considerably more toxic oils to treat parasite infections were
imported from the New World.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans' use of the American fungus to treat intestinal worms
persisted until the past century, Capasso said in a interview.
``The laxative was used in popular medicine in Italy and Poland to
facilitate the excretion of the worm,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Capasso, who specializes in diseases of prehistoric humans,
notes that other archeologists have found evidence of vegetable
oils in coprolites _ fossilized feces _ from prehistoric sites in
Utah and Nevada, possibly signifying that these peoples were trying
also to treat infestations of intestinal worms.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sign of parasite eggs and worm fragments in the
North American coprolites that bear traces of oils, in contrast to
other samples from the same time and regions. That ``demonstrates
the efficacy of the oil in the cure of intestinal worms,'' Capasso
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said he was surprised to find such ancient
evidence of prehistoric parasite disease and treatment in the Ice
Man, who died about 5,300 years ago. ``We have no other finding in
this condition of comparable antiquity for Europe.'' Ancient
Egyptians concocted complicated remedies for specific diseases, but
Capasso said the earliest Egyptian evidence he knows of _ a
prescription on papyrus for a brew of macerated pomegranate bark
and beer to treat a parasitic disease the Egyptians called ``aaa''
_ is one or two milennia more recent than the Ice Man's era.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the evidence of parasites in the Ice Man's bowel
and the fungal remedy he was carrying, Capasso discovered that his
fingernails were underdeveloped in a pattern that suggested
repeated interruptions of their growth. In addition, the iron
content of his skeletal muscles was abnormally low.
</P>
<P>
   Both these clues are consistent, the researcher noted, with the
growth cycle of Trichuris trichiura, an intestinal parasite known
to cause anemia, or iron depletion.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence suggests, Capasso said, ``the man had recurrent
generalized stress at roughly 30-day intervals during the last
phase of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   The fungal spheres are the strongest hints thus far that the Ice
Man may have benefited from a system of medical knowledge, but
they're not the only signs.
</P>
<P>
   Capasso suggested in 1993 that the many tattoos on the Ice Man's
body were not decorations but the traces of therapy for muscle and
joint pain. From evidence that includes medical and surgical
instruments found in the ruins of Pompeii, destroyed in A.D. 79 by
an eruption of Mt. Vesuvius, researchers know the tattoos were made
with special scalpels and the incisions filled with herb mixtures
that were then set on fire. The heat cauterized the wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Ice Man's tattoos, Capasso noted, were on the skin
over joints in the spine, knee, and ankle that showed clear signs
of arthritis. ``The Ice Man might have used these tattoos as a form
of localized therapy for muscle and joint pain,'' Capasso said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard anthropologist David Pilbeam, a specialist in
paleolithic cultures, welcomed Capasso's findings as an antidote to
conventional thinking about ``primitive'' humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have empirical minds,'' Pilbeam said. ``Western culture
tends to underestimate the knowledge base of other cultures and
other times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
