<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S IN FLATUS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why is it that lighting a match seems to dispel the odor of
flatulence?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Intestinal gas is not heavily studied. But Dr. Michael
Levitt, chief of research at the Minneapolis Veterans
Administration Hospital, has studied flatus since 1965.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think lighting a match covers up the smell more than it
actually dispels the odor,'' he says. He believes the combustion
does change some of the offending molecules so they no longer bind
with the same smell receptors in the nose, but that mostly it
provides olfactory camouflage until the flatus dissipates.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt says most of the gas we produce (on average, up to 2,000
milliliters, or about 120 cubic inches, in 13-14 episodes daily) is
non-aromatic, made up of nitrogen, oxygen, carbon dioxide,
hydrogen, and methane. (Methane is natural gas, the kind we cook
with.)
</P>
<P>
   Most of these gasses are produced when bacteria in our
intestines feast on food not fully broken down. That's why some
fruits and vegetables with complex carbohydrates that we can't
fully digest are so gaseously productive. A small portion of the
gas we pass is plain old air we swallow as we eat.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt says less than 1 part in 10,000 of flatus is odiferous.
Hydrogen sulfide, methanethiol, and dimethyl sulfide are the
principal nasal nasties. Sulfur is the key ingredient in all of
them. Half of it comes from what we eat. Half is naturally
produced, in our bile, and in the mucus and linings of the
intestine.
</P>
<P>
   These gases are highly toxic. We've evolved to detect them at
extremely low levels, so it doesn't take many molecules to trigger
a response. (They're chemically similar to the ingredients in skunk
spray and the odorant added to natural gas so we can detect leaks.)
</P>
<P>
   To confirm what makes flatus smell unpleasant, Levitt fed study
participants pinto beans and collected the resulting gas before
passage. The gaseous components were analyzed and separated. Two
``smell experts'' said the most unpleasant were the hydrogen
sulfide, methanethiol, and dimethyl sulfide.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we should send Levitt an air freshener for his lab.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Capital offense
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several alert readers have corrected us about the explanation on
how the calorie totals on food packaging are calculated. They point
out that the calorie (small c) on food packaging, is actually a
Calorie (capital C). That's a kilocalorie, 1,000 calories. Which is
bad news for those dieters trying to cut down on the calories they
consume by counting the Calories on food package labels.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 1342EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8686 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-14 1477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENSION PLAN OFFERS AN INVESTMENT OPPORTUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BY KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I recently received a proposal from a company where I used to
work, giving me a number of options involving my pension. At what
age would it be best to start taking my pension benefits, and could
you suggest a fund to have the money deposited in? I am now 48
years old, and I plan on retiring at age 59. The earliest I would
qualify for benefits is Nov. 1, 2000, when I will be 50 years old.
If I did that, I would be paid $279 per month. Other benefits, and
the age at which I would qualify for them are $385 a month at age
55, $533 at age 60, $649 at age 62, and $839 at age 65.
</P>
<P>
   W.R., Port Murray, N.J. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you have the discipline to follow through on this, my
instinct would be to take the pension at the earliest age you can
and then religiously invest the benefits for your retirement.
Here's an example: Suppose you drew down the $279 a month at age 50
and invested all the benefits in a stock mutual fund. Suppose
further that the fund achieved average 10 percent annual returns.
After nine years you would have accumulated $47,633.
</P>
<P>
   Now suppose that when you retire you moved this money from your
stock fund and reinvested it in fixed-income holdings providing you
with a 6.5 percent yield. Thus you could expect that $47,633 to
bring in $258 a month. Combined with the ongoing pension benefit,
this would give you a $537 monthly income stream _ pretty close to
the $553 you would be eligible for if you waited until age 60. In
fact, if you continued investing your pension benefits until age
60, the pool would grow to $55,903, using the same assumptions, and
from that you might expect a $302 income stream. That would combine
with the continued $297 pension benefits to give you $581 a month
income _ better than the pension would have offered at age 60.
</P>
<P>
   These projections assume not only that you use other funds to
pay the taxes that result from the pension payments, but also that
you pay any tax liabilities that the ongoing savings pool
generates. You may be able to use a tax-deferred savings vehicle
such as an IRA or a 410(k) to get away from the latter category of
taxes, but if you take the pension benefits at age 60, count on
paying taxes on an extra $3,350 annual income.
</P>
<P>
   But why _ I hear you ask _ why pay all those taxes and also
assume the uncertainties of the markets if I'm going to end up with
an income stream that's very similar to what I'd get if I simply
started drawing from the pension at age 60? The answer is that if
you follow the program outlined above until age 60, you would not
only have the larger income stream, but you would also have that
$55,903 in principal _ a fund which you could you count on in
emergencies, or as a part of your estate.
</P>
<P>
   As for investments, I'd go pretty straight down the line,
putting half the money in a mutual fund that tracks the Standard
and Poor's 500 Index (or a subset thereof) and the other half in a
solid balanced fund. With the Vanguard family, for example, you
might select the Most other fund families offer similar funds.
</P>
<P>
   As for the later pension options, they become attractive only if
you expect to live to a very ripe old age _ well past age 80; in
your situation I'd take the bird that comes to hand in two years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am confused. I need income to supplement my pension. I have
$40,000 in the Vanguard GNMA fund. What's wrong with the long-term
bond fund, which has a higher yield? I understand that the price of
a share will probably fluctuate more, but if one is only interested
in the income from the fund, wouldn't the long-term fund be better?
</P>
<P>
   V.B., Brea, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I've never been particularly enthusiastic about long bonds,
mostly because I don't think the spread between the rate paid on
these bonds and on shorter-term instruments is adequate to reward
the holder for the extra risk that goes along with the longer
duration.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in the current market, there's only one Vanguard fund
with a higher yield than its GNMA fund, and that's the High Yield
Corporate Bond _ read ``junk bond'' _ fund.
</P>
<P>
   The latter has a yield of 8.47 percent as this is written,
compared to 6.44 percent for the GNMA fund and 5.90 percent for the
Long-Term Corporate Bond fund and 5.11 percent for Vanguard
Long-Term U.S. Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Why the better yield for the GNMA, which is holds an
intermediate-term portfolio, than for the long-term funds? This is
because a GNMA fund carries an extra element of risk when compared
to traditional bond funds. The Government National Mortgage
Association securities in the GNMA fund portfolio represent bundled
mortgages. Although the government guarantees both principal and
interest payments on these mortgages, the government has no control
over whether the borrowers prepay the mortgages. When interest
rates fall, bond holders in general should be happy. But while the
holders of GNMA funds can see their net asset value rise in times
of moderate rate reductions (or rumors thereof), when there is a
steady and sizable sequence of rate increases, mortgage borrowers
have growing incentive to prepay their mortgages or to refinance
them. When these mortgages are retired, the fund manager then must
go out into the market and replace the holding with new securities.
And in a climate of falling rates, the fund manager who is
replacing GNMA securities end up paying more money to buy
lower-yielding securities _ thus causing the fund's yield to fall.
That effect tends to mitigate the gains that typical bond funds
achieve when interest rates fall.
</P>
<P>
   It's only when you look at the long-term record that the longer
term bond funds come out on top. Of the funds cited above,
Vanguard's Long-Term U.S. Treasury comes out on top, with an
average annual total of 10.80 percent over a 10-year period. The
Long-Term Corporate Bond fund follows, with a 10.49 percent
average, followed by 9.41 percent for the High-Yield Corporate fund
and 8.81 percent for GNMA.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those figures, I still don't like the long bonds. When
you lend money for 20 years or more, you are basically hoping that
inflation will be more or less under control in the future. I don't
think that's a reasonable expectation, so I prefer the
intermediate-term holdings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have money invested in Columbia mutual funds. How are they
rated in relation to other funds of their size? Are there other
funds that are better? Living here in Oregon, I would like to do my
investing in the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   A.M., Springfield, Ore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Of Columbia's 11 mutual funds, Morningstar Mutual Funds
tracks nine on a regular basis. Of these nine, five are rated above
average, two are average, one below average, and the final fund is
not rated because it has yet to post three-year records. Moreover,
the fund that's rated below average _ Columbia Special _ is in the
mid-cap growth category, where there are very few winners. (Of the
62 mid-cap growth funds Morningstar tracks, only six merit an
above-average grade, and none get the top five-star rating.) So all
in all, I'd say the Columbia funds get a pretty good report card.
</P>
<P>
   As for a comparison with fund families of similar size, I don't
think such an analysis is worth the effort. First of all, each
individual fund is its own legal entity, so investors shouldn't be
worried about the size of the fund family. And in general, they
need to be concerned about the size of an individual fund only when
it is at one extreme or the other _ very small or very bog. A very
small fund can be disadvantageous because there are fewer investors
to bear the fixed costs of managing the fund. (But fund families
frequently absorb substantial amount of the expenses during the
early years of new funds, and in addition very small funds also
tend to be more nimble investors, and therefore more profitable,
than their rivals.) But there's very little in mitigation when
funds grow giant.
</P>
<P>
   Funds such as Fidelity Magellan or Kaufmann fund have been
regularly criticized for becoming so large that they are unwieldy,
producing substantially lower returns for their investors than when
they were slimmer and held smaller total portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the one benefit that very large funds should be able
to deliver _ lower expenses based on the large asset base _ rarely
seems to materialize. The one category of fund where the investor
doesn't need to worry about the size of the assets under management
is index funds, where fund management is more science than art, and
where expense ratios are, or should be, very low to begin with.)
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
