<HEADER>
A8690 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-CELEBRITY-BOS &LR;      12-14 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-CELEBRITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE, CELEBRITY, AND THE PURSUIT OF HAPPINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   as America's passion come full circle? What has been a national
obsession about celebrity is becoming a national obsesssion about
that obsession. It's the subject of Woody Allen's latest movie,
which (like most of his recent movies) is loaded to the gills with
celebrities. It's also the topic, at least in part, of Neil
Gabler's book, ``Life the Movie: How Entertainment Conquered
Reality.'' Even Bret Easton Ellis, of all people, is getting into
the act with his forthcoming novel, ``Glamorama.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this comes a moment too soon, particularly Gabler's
intriguing new book. As we awaken to Washington pundits angling for
elbow room to tell jokes on ``Imus in the Morning'' and fall asleep
to the governor of New York on ``Late Night with David Letterman,''
it seems as if everyone is measuring out his worth in the pursuit
of celebrityhood, which becomes a more and more trivial pursuit
with each passing day.
</P>
<P>
   That's something of the message in Allen's movie, which is
certainly not among his best but does represent a huge improvement
over his self-pitying earlier movie on the subject, ``Stardust
Memories.'' Here, celebrity is a dead-end pursuit, leading the
protagonist from one bedroom to another with nothing to show for it
but a cinematic cry for help. (Ironically, his wife gets all the
goodies that celebrity confers, without even trying for such
status.)
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Branagh plays the protagonist caught in his own private
Inferno, a character many viewers assume is Allen. Interestingly,
Allen tried directing Branagh away from playing him, but the
British star apparently couldn't help himself. We play the parts
that celebrities play, even in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Gabler takes that thesis and runs with it gracefully in ``Life
the Movie,'' noting how the heroic archetype in Joseph Campbell's
``The Hero With a Thousand Faces'' has become the celebrity
archetype of today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campbell's archetype addressed fears extant in all societies:
the anxiety of separation; the terror of the unknown; the dread of
forces larger than ourselves; death. The celebrity archetype
addressed social fears extant in modern America: the anxiety of
losing one's identity or never finding it at all; the terror of
having too little amid plenty; the dread of anonymity; the awful
suspicion that some were blessed and some were not and that most
Americans were among the latter.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking to popular culture for our heroes is nothing new. It was
striking to be reminded, after Frank Sinatra died, how many men of
a certain generation modeled themselves on the way he wore his hat,
to quote the title of Bill Zehme's book (subtitled ``Frank Sinatra
&AMP; the Lost Art of Livin' ''). Or as Pete Hamill writes in ``Why
Sinatra Matters,'' recalling a meeting in 1970: ``For decades now,
Sinatra had defined the glamour of the urban night. It was both a
time and a place; to inhabit the night, to be one of its restless
creatures, was a small act of defiance, a shared declaration of
freedom, a refusal to play by all those conventional rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Later generations would model themselves on other pop-culture
celebrities, looking for swagger wherever they found it, from Elvis
to Michael Stipe, from Norman Mailer to Bruce Willis. I asked a
friend what female pop-culture icons she grew up wanting to emulate
in the 1960s and her first response was Fess Parker's wife in
``Daniel Boone'' because she was the spunkiest woman on television.
She called a friend who said Paul McCartney's wife. Girls had to
get their heroes from books, like Anne Frank and Nancy Drew. Is it
a sign of progress that girls can stop reading books and find
heroes of their own in pop culture, from Buffy to Oprah?
</P>
<P>
   The real question, though, is whether celebrity is the place
where any of us should be getting our heroes, and perhaps books
like Gabler's and movies like Allen's represent a sense that we're
looking for a source of strength and identity in all the wrong
places.
</P>
<P>
   In noting the similarities between mythic heroes and celebrity
heroes, Gabler cites Campbell as saying, ``In the end it has been
the (mythic hero's) function to show us the continuity between the
natural world outside us and the spiritual world within.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's precisely what the overwhelming majority of celebrity
heroes don't do, even one possessed of the artistry of Sinatra. In
a perceptive review of ``Why Sinatra Matters,'' Christopher
Lehmann-Haupt pays tribute to Hamill's ability to prove the point
of the title. He notes Hamill's observation, ``The message was
there in the music, the attitude, even the hat: he had come through
a hard, dark time, and he wasn't ever going back into the
darkness.'' But Lehmann-Haupt offers this important objection:
``The darkness being women, presumably. This is not a message
worthy of high art. In Mr. Hamill's handling at least, those wee
small hours of the morning are a landscape of adolescence.''
</P>
<P>
   Branagh's cry for help at the end of Allen's movie is at least
in part a cry for help at being stuck in perpetual adolescence,
which is ultimately the destination of a celebrity-transfixed
nation. ``Imus in the Morning'' is nothing if not a codification of
the adolescence of the national political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   The mythic heroes that Campbell was writing about take us out of
adolescence, which is why we were all probably better off when we
had to turn to books for our heroes, who _ chief among their
responsibilities _ led us from childhood to adulthood. The cult of
celebrity can be a lot of fun, but in the end it's really nothing
more than child's play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
