<HEADER>
A8692 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-BLUE-ROOM-BOS &LR;      12-14 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-BLUE-ROOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NOT SO COLORFUL `BLUE ROOM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Those Brits really do have to get out more often. The
way the men who run their media and many of their male theater
critics drooled over Nicole Kidman in ``The Blue Room,'' you'd
think they had never seen an actress bare her bottom onstage
before. Apparently everything we've heard about repressed Englismen
is true.
</P>
<P>
   So gaga did they go that ``The Blue Room'' is now here for a
three-month stay and Kidman is on the cover of ``Newsweek,'' which
says this is the hottest ticket for a nonmusical in Broadway
history.
</P>
<P>
   The hype may all underline the point of David Hare's adaptation
of Arthur Schnitzler's ``La Ronde'' _ that sex makes the world go
ronde. It certainly proves that audiences will do anything to
experience eroticism, even vicariously.
</P>
<P>
   But was it good for me, too? Not really. And to judge from the
respectful but relatively tepid response at Friday night's preview
performance, I'm sure I'm not the only person to wonder what the
big deal is about. Don't get me wrong; I wouldn't kick Kidman out
of my theater company. She's a fine actress and the other virtues,
the ones that sent Rupert Murdoch and the other Fleet Street boys
into a frenzy, are apparent for all to see.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Blue Room'' is essentially a mediocre play and a
mediocre theatrical experience. Hare has written a lackluster
contemporization of Schnitzler's now classic turn-of-the-century
play, and Sam Mendes has directed it with the same cynical
detachment and soulless sexuality that marks his other hugely
successful London transfer, ``Cabaret.''
</P>
<P>
   The twist in this adaptation is that two actors, Kidman and Iain
Glen, play all the roles called for in Schnitzler's play. Kidman
starts out as a teenage hooker looking for sex and hoping for money
with Glen as a self-impressed taxi driver.
</P>
<P>
   In the next scene he seduces an au pair who then connects with
the young man in the house, and on and on until we've come full
circle back to the teenage hooker, now a little less naive. Using
the same two actors underscores how we're driven by the same urges,
across class and age lines.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the contemporization seems to be that for all
the changes in this century, we're still the same as our Victorian
predecessors, denying the power that sex holds over our lives on
the one hand, but proving otherwise with every step we take on the
other. Again, the success of ``The Blue Room'' would seem to bear
out the wisdom of the thesis with hordes on both sides of the
Atlantic lining up for a peep show disguised as a night in the
theater.
</P>
<P>
   That in itself isn't cause for alarm, unless you're a member of
the House Judiciary Committee. The problem is there's nothing
special here, about the peep or anything else. First of all, it's
still Hare's responsibility to show that the more things change the
more they stay the same, that we're all still prisoners of our
Freudian passions despite our moralistic protestations. But in
updating the action, the characters don't seem terribly
contemporary. They're prefeminist souls in postfeminist posings.
That is, many of them still possess the longings of Schnitzler's
characters to hold onto a Romantic vision of love rather than
accept a more Modernistic sensibility. Unlike Patrick Marber's
``Closer,'' though, these characters seem caught up in a time warp
where women are all powerless and men are all predators posing,
even to themselves, as romantics. That might have been prescient of
Schnitzler to note in 1900 and fashionable for theater of, say, the
1970s, to develop, but these characters now seem to provide a
seriously simplistic and outdated model for human behavior. Hare
got well past such reductionism in ``Skylight.''
</P>
<P>
   That these characters aren't easy to bond with has nothing to do
with the considerable talents of the two actors. Glen and Kidman
have an easy chemistry between them even if there's really not that
much of an erotic charge onstage. (There is an electric charge,
though. Each sex scene is blacked out, with a crackling monitor
announcing length of duration.) Kidman projects the innocence that
sets the hearts of Hare's men aflutter, and she is an extremely
gifted comedian who proves in one outing that she can play a
variety of roles. Glen carries himself like a young Ian McKellen as
he goes from part to part, from swaggering cabdriver to fuddy-duddy
aristocrat.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what marks ``The Blue Room'' is the sheer unremarkability
of anything onstage. Not only are ``Skylight'' and ``Closer'' far
more compelling and articulate stagings of a similar debate, but
Kidman's is not even the most dazzling performance by an overseas
actress on Broadway (Zoe Wanamaker in the decidely unsexy
``Electra''). Kidman doesn't even have the best nude scene onstage,
as Glen literally does cartwheels to make people notice how he's
letting it all hang out. But if bare bodies are really what you're
after, Runway 69 is still around the corner in Times Square and
probably a whole lot cheaper. (I, of course, wouldn't know.)
</P>
<P>
   Mark Thompson's staging may be more creative at the Cort
Theatre, with changes of scenery fed into the claustrophobic blue
room where sex is the only thing that matters. Hare's sense of
humor is certainly working, particularly in self-referential
scenes. Kidman plays an actress, chastizing her lover for not
displaying the same ardor as the men in the audience _ ``Every
night I feel them out there pulsing, vibrating, wanting to rise out
of their seats and have me.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, perhaps we do, but Hare's and Mendes's staging makes it
very easy to contain ourselves about everything in ``The Blue
Room.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
