<HEADER>
A8699 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-LIEBER-BOS &LR;      12-14 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-LIEBER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING 45 YEARS OF LEIBER AND STOLLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forty-five years ago, 17-year-old Jerry Leiber showed up at
17-year-old Mike Stoller's door with a pad full of song lyrics.
That afternoon, they started writing songs together. And they've
been at it ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the short list: ``Hound Dog'' for Big Mama Thornton.
``Jailhouse Rock,'' ``Love Me Tender,'' ``Loving You,'' and ``Treat
Me Nice'' for Elvis Presley. ``Spanish Harlem'' and ``Stand By Me''
for Ben E. King. ``There Goes My Baby'' and ``On Broadway'' for the
Drifters. ``Yakety Yak,'' ``Poison Ivy,'' ``Charlie Brown,'' and
``Searchin' '' for the Coasters. ``Is That All There Is?'' for
Peggy Lee. ``I'll Be There'' for Gerry and the Pacemakers. ``D. W.
Washburn'' for the Monkees. ``Ruby Baby'' for Dion.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just a hint at what they've produced over nearly five
decades years of work.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, that work gets another celebration when the
Broadway hit ``Smokey Joe's Cafe: The Songs of Leiber and Stoller''
opens at the Shubert Theatre for a 2 1/2-week run.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first called Mike he didn't give me a helluva lot of
encouragement,'' said Leiber, now 62, of that California afternoon
in 1953. ``I got his name from a drummer but Mike wasn't
interested. I twisted his arm and talked him into letting me come
over. I was just 17 and I showed up with my notebook with 10 or 15
lyrics written in pencil. He really dug Miles Davis, Charlie
Parker, Dizzy Gillespie, and all the great bebop musicians. And I
was into the blues _ Jimmy Witherspoon, John Lee Hooker, Memphis
Slim. He smiled at me as if he thought he was placating me and, in
a semi-patronizing manner, asked if he could take a look at the
book. `These aren't songs,' he said. `These are the blues. You
write the blues. Man, I love the blues.' That's what started it
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Their first big hit was Thornton's version of ``Hound Dog''
(1953), which sold 125,000 copies and topped rhythm and blues
playlists for months. Three years later, Presley's version sold 7
million copies. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Big Mama's `Hound Dog' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of my favorites,'' said Stoller, in another phone
interview from Los Angeles. ``The Big Mama Thornton version with
our lyrics.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of ``Hound Dog'' is a model of how talent and
serendipity merged into a fortuitous hit back in rock 'n' roll's
infancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew Johnny Otis, a drummer and band leader who made
records for Big Mama Thornton, Little Esther, Three Tons of Joy,
and Mel Williams,'' recalled Leiber. ``Big Mama wore overalls and
she was big . . . and tough. She had razor scars on her face and
she had a piano player named Lady Dee who had arms like Popeye's.
She was a lot of trouble. When we first showed up, we left without
leaving any songs. But, on the way back, in Mike's '37 Plymouth, I
started beating out rhythm with my right hand. It was a variation
of a buck dance.''
</P>
<P>
   And Leiber started singing, ``You ain't nothin' but a . . . '
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to be a very blue song,'' Leiber continued, ``so I
threw in `hound dog' as a dummy lyric until I could think of
something else. Hound dog sounded too prissy. I wanted something
dirty. We got to his house and we didn't even sit down. He went to
the piano and banged out the tune and we had the song done in 10 or
12 minutes. We drove back to South Central . . . to Johnny Otis's
place and handed the paper with the song on it to Big Mama. She was
snide and patronizing because we were two white boys writing the
blues. She started crooning . . . like it was a love song.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Mama, that ain't the way it goes,' I said.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Why don't you tell me how it goes, white boy,' she said.
Johnny came up to see what was going on. `This little white boy
wants to show me how it goes,' she said.
</P>
<P>
   `` `You let him,' Johnny told her. `You let him tell you how it
goes.' He was imitating her.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I did it. A bluesy version that had the band clapping in
their own way. `I like that,' Big Mama said. `Yeah, I like that.'
Three days later we recorded it and that was that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Elvis version &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In late 1955, Elvis Presley was strolling through a casino
lounge (neither Leiber nor Stoller recalls which one) when he heard
Freddie Bell and the Bell Boys, a white band, performing their
version of Big Mama's hit. Because the original lyrics were written
for a woman, Bell had rewritten a couple of lines.
</P>
<P>
   Big Mama sang, ``You ain't nothin' but a hound dog, don't come
sniffin' 'round my door. You ain't nothin' but a hound dog, I ain't
gonna feed you no more.''
</P>
<P>
   Freddie Bell sang, ``You ain't nothin' but a hound dog, cryin'
all the time. You ain't never caught a rabbit, and you ain't no
friend of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Presley, unfortunately, recorded the latter.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1956, Mike Stoller was returning from a European trip on
a luxury liner, unaware that Presley had recorded the song.
</P>
<P>
   `I had no idea who Elvis was,'' said Stoller. ``I remember,
after we docked, Jerry telling me that it was a huge hit _ but,
frankly, that's not what made the trip memorable.''
</P>
<P>
   What did make the trip unforgettable for Stoller is that he was
aboard the legendary Andrea Doria, the ship that sank after a
collision with a freighter. He escaped in a life boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I was a bit numb. I was just glad to be back on terra
firma,'' said Stoller. ``Elvis or no Elvis.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Leiber and Stoller prefer Thornton's version of the song
anyway (and in ``Smokey Joe's Cafe,'' it's the original that the
cast sings). As Leiber put it, Presley's cover is ``a nervous,
hyped-up version. There's a lot of things wrong with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship with Elvis led to a contract with MGM to
write the songs for Presley's 1957 feature, ``Jailhouse Rock,''
directed by Richard Thorpe, best known for making ``The Student
Prince'' with Mario Lanza.
</P>
<P>
   According to Leiber, they checked into the Gotham Hotel in New
York and were given about 10 days to come up with the eight to 10
songs required for a soundtrack. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Four songs in four hours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But New York was Mike's town. He grew up there,'' said Leiber.
``And he wanted to show me the town. We spent days and nights going
to clubs and not getting any work done. It was very exciting and we
really got caught up in it. One day there's a knock on the door and
it's Jean Aberbach, a Bavarian, who published all of Elvis's music.
He was a very big guy. He was very polite but he wanted his songs.
We told him we couldn't write nine songs in one afternoon, even
though we often wrote five in one day. He needed the score that
afternoon. We told him he could have it that night. He was very
firm. He pushed the sofa against the door and laid down on it and
put his hat over his head like he was some kind of gangster in a
pool hall.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1 and 5 that afternoon, Leiber and Stoller wrote
``Jailhouse Rock,'' ``Treat Me Nice,'' ``I Want to be Free'' and
``Baby, I Don't Care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That bought us more time to come up with the rest of the
songs,'' said Leiber.
</P>
<P>
   For most of their careers, Leiber and Stoller functioned as both
songwriters and record producers, gathering the talent, selecting
the bands, creating the arrangements, and making sure the record
got a good send-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did the same with this show,'' said Leiber. ``We worked
with the band and the performers to get the right color and rhythm.
It's a whole different kettle of fish. We don't have Ben E. King
singing `Stand By Me' _ he does it great, but he can't dance or
move around; he stands in front of a microphone. This is theater.
We have a terrific cast. We're just very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   One more question.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it always Leiber-Stoller and not Stoller-Leiber?
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while it went back and forth,'' said Stoller. ``But we
finally settled on Leiber-Stoller. What did he say?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Leiber-Stoller sounds better,'' said Leiber. It's got rhythm.
It swings.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's still swinging after all these years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
