<HEADLINE>
NEW AND RECOMMENDED RECENTLY REVIEWED BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Amsterdam'' by Ian McEwan (Doubleday, $21). Two Englishmen are
brought together by the death of a lover they shared. Winner of the
1998 Booker Prize. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Love of a Good Woman'' by Alice Munro (Knopf, $24). Eight
new stories by the Canadian master of the form. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hours'' by Michael Cunningham (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$22). A lovely triumph, both a re-imagining of the story of
Virginia Woolf's modernist classic ``Mrs. Dalloway'' and an homage
to the original. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Life of Thomas More'' by Peter Ackroyd (Nan A.
Talese/Doubleday, $30). A scrupulous treatment of the ``man for all
seasons,'' and of the passing of the Middle Ages in England. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Samuel Johnson: The Life of an Author'' by Lawrence Lipking
(Harvard University Press, $35). A biography that concentrates on
Dr. Johnson the writer, not the wit or ``character.''
</P>
</TEXT>
