<P>
   MIDEAST-HILLARY (Dateline to kum) _ With Mrs. Clinton; the
Palestinians love her. By William A. Orme.
</P>
<P>
   Other Mideast as warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ANGOLA-REBELS (Luanda) _ The sale of diamonds enables Angolan
rebels to keep fighting, and a U.N. embargo to cut off the sales
isn't working, according to a new study. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-ANNAN (United Nations) _ Secretary General Kofi Annan sums
up the world at year's end, in a press conference and an interview.
By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-U.S. (Washington) _ Developments in U.S.-North Korea
relations.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSIDENTS (Beijing) _ The crackdown continues: Two
founders of the new political party to be tried on Thursday. By
Eric Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-CHURCHES (Harare, Zimbabwe) _ The World Council of
Churches ends its meeting calling for debt relief for poor
countries. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ The World Briefing column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MATTEL-LEARNING (Undated) _ Mattel buys the Learning Co. for
$3.8 billion. It also issues an earnings warning for the fourth
quarter and the full year. Its shares fall 17 percent. By Dana
Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   SATURN-APPOINT (Detroit) _ Stuck in the shrinking small-car
market and trying to rebuild its frayed labor relations, Saturn
appoints a sport-utility-vehicle expert as its new chairman and
president. The new executive is the first woman to head a division
at General Motors, which was criticized for not naming any women to
the top three tiers of management in a recent shakeup. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   SHELL-CUTBACK (London) _ Royal Dutch/Shell will take a charge of
$4.5 billion to sell assets and cut staff. The sweeping
reorganization is meant to save $2.5 billion by 2001 and leave
Shell able to weather oil prices of less than $10 a barrel. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   NABISCO-CUTBACK (Undated) _ RJR Nabisco is cutting an additional
1,000 jobs at its tobacco division because it expects lower
cigarette sales following the price increases imposed to pay for
its legal settlement with the states. It will take a pretax
restructuring charge of $335 million in the current quarter. Its
Nabisco Holdings unit will take a pretax charge of $124 million to
cut costs. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-BANKS (Toronto) _ The Canadian finance minister, Paul
Martin, blocks Royal Bank of Canada's proposed purchase of Bank of
Montreal and Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce's planned merger
with Toronto-Dominion Bank, transactions that would have reduced
the number of big Canadian banks to three from five. He says the
two deals would have lessened competition among brokerage houses,
in the credit card business and in the awarding of some business
loans. The announcement causes Canadian banking shares to fall
sharply. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   FCC-PHONE-MERGERS (Washington) _ The Federal Communications
Commission holds holds more hearings to discuss the proposed
mergers of AT&AMP;T and Tele-Communications Inc., Bell Atlantic and GTE
and SBC and Ameritech. MCI, Sprint and a group of local phone
company officials and consumer advocates will urge that the
combinations be rejected. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   CITIGROUP-CUTBACK (New York) _ Folo on reports that Citigroup
will announce a restructuring charge estimated at about $1 billion
and provide details of an extensive cost-cutting plan in an effort
to highlight the benefits of the Citicorp-Travelers Group merger
even when the financial markets are rocky.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Developments at the trial:
Edward Felton, the technical expert, is cross-examined about his
view of the Microsoft browser. By Joel Brinkley and Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-QWEST (Undated) _ Microsoft will invest $200 million
for a 1.3 percent stake in Qwest Communications, accelerating the
long-distance carrier's plans to offer Internet services on its
high-speed fiber optic network. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-BOYCOTT (Washington) _ In an antitrust ruling, the
Supreme Court answers the question, what is a boycott? _ deciding
on a narrow definition of an agreement among suppliers or an
agreement among sellers, and rejecting situations in which a buyer
and a seller conspire to exclude another buyer. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   HUGHES-SATELLITE (Los Angeles) _ General Motors' Hughes
Electronics buys United States Satellite Broadcasting for about
$1.3 billion in stock or cash to fortify its position in
direct-broadcast satellite television. Hughes will combine its
DirecTV satellite-broadcasting business with United States
Satellite's satellite assets. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:25 p.m., the industrial average was
down 82 points, or 0.8 percent, and the Nasdaq index was off 43
points, or 2 percent. Elsewhere, prices fell 2 percent in Tokyo and
1.3 percent in Hong Kong. They rose half a percent in Frankfurt,
0.1 percent in London, 4.9 percent in Brazil and 0.4 percent in
Mexico. On the American debt market, the long bond was up 14/32
point at midday, with the yield at 5 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
