<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8703 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-VIETNAM-BOS &LR;      12-14 1592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-VIETNAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM CREATED A NEW JOURNALISM FOR A NEW KIND OF WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every war is unhappy in its own way. Vietnam was especially so,
and one of the principal ways it became unhappy was through
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   With some exceptions _ the War of 1812, the Mexican War _
American journalists gladly enlisted in the country's wars,
fighting with their typewriters, rallying the home front, battling
to keep the fighting spirit alive and high. Then came Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam changed much in American culture: public respect for
professional soldiers, the broad assumption that the nation's
leaders spoke the truth to the people, the orthodoxy that our wars
are just, the notion that when the United States fights a war, it
wins it crisply, unambiguously, and honorably.
</P>
<P>
   But no institution in American life, not even the military, was
changed by the Vietnam War as profoundly as journalism. The ancient
craft entered the war with a wink and emerged with a scowl. Its
practitioners entered the war with skepticism and left with
cynicism. Its best-known names entered the war as mere observers of
great power and left the war wielders of great power.
</P>
<P>
   And so the appearance of an anthology of Vietnam journalism, in
two elegant volumes of the Library of America, is a landmark. But
it is also a recognition of how journalism changed that war and,
just as important, how that war changed journalism. In 1,715 pages
of writing that remains remarkably resilient _ still gripping after
all these years _ the full tragedy of Vietnam is visible, audible,
palpable, along with the whirr of the helicopter rotors and the
spit of the M-16 rifles and the tears of the families of the 58,000
American dead.
</P>
<P>
   These are volumes that can be dipped into, skimmed _ or read
slowly, page after page, one volume following another. Any way will
do, and any way will leave the reader with a richer view of
Vietnam. But the very best way to read these volumes is to
accompany them with the two volumes the Library of America
published three years ago, ``Reporting World War II'' (also $35 a
volume). The World War II volumes add 1,900 pages of reading, to be
sure, but they also add an immensely valuable perspective.
</P>
<P>
   One example is especially searing. In Tunisia in World War II,
Ernie Pyle looked back upon the men who perished in the ferocious
fighting of 1943 and wrote: ``They died and thereby the rest of us
can go on and on. When we leave here for the next shore, there is
nothing we can do for the ones beneath the wooden crosses, except
perhaps to pause and murmur, `Thanks, pal.' ''
</P>
<P>
   No reader would ever mistake that passage for one written about
Vietnam, which was simultaneously an overseas military conflict and
a domestic political one.
</P>
<P>
   Then consider how these two wars began, and how journalism
responded. The run-up to World War II was freighted with tension,
and the reporting that endured _ from William L. Shirer, Dorothy
Thompson, A. J. Liebling, Edward R. Murrow, among many _ was
ominous in its tone, unmistakable in its underlying assumption: The
National Socialism of Hitler's Germany was evil, it was destined to
cause conflict, and America was destined to become involved, and
should.
</P>
<P>
   The beginnings in Vietnam, too, were full of warning, but the
blasts were of a far different nature. As early as January 1961,
for example, Stanley Karnow was writing of the South Vietnam
government that was America's ally: ``Beneath the appearance of
calm and stability, and despite all the government's assurances of
security, President (Ngo Dinh) Diem's regime may well be
approaching collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 13 months later, Homer Bigart, whose coverage of World War
II was far less political, sounded a tocsin in The New York Times
that wasn't heeded: ``The United States seems inextricably
committed to a long, inconclusive war. The Communists can prolong
it for years. Even without large-scale intervention from the north
. . . what may be achieved at best is only restoration of a
tolerable security similar to that achieved in Malaya after years
of fighting. But it is too late to disengage; our prestige has been
committed. Washington says we will stay until the finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Karnow and Bigart weren't alone, far from it. The alarm bells
were sounding all over the landscape, even in the pages of the
Saturday Evening Post, never suspected of pink ideology. In a July
1962 interview with Bernard B. Fall, the North Vietnamese leader Ho
Chi Minh said: ``I think the Americans greatly underestimate the
determination of the Vietnamese people. The Vietnamese people
always have shown great determination when they were faced with a
foreign invader.''
</P>
<P>
   As US involvement escalated, as domestic support eroded, and as
the biggest indigenous antiwar movement in US history grew, all
these elements became clearer. But it was a mistake then, and is
now, to believe that the elements of American failure in Vietnam
became clear only in 1966 and 1967 and 1968, when opposition to the
war broadened and deepened. Those elements were known, and
publicized, from the very start.
</P>
<P>
   But if the war was sustained by myths, then its course in the
popular mind is shrouded also in myth.
</P>
<P>
   Journalism has severe limits as a craft, and even more severe
ones as a chronicle of history; in almost every case, the
historian's view of events is more interesting, more thoughtful,
and more enduring than the reporter's. (Compare, for example, how
historians view two of the signal events of this century _ the
causes of the Great Depression and the causes of World War II _
with the way reporters viewed them, and the chasm is clear.) But
journalism is a reminder that the myths of history also sometimes
have to be swept away. In the Vietnam era, that is especially so.
Two examples, drawn from coverage of two completely different
aspects of the war years:
</P>
<P>
   --By plowing through a portrait of the first teach-in, at the
University of Michigan, we are reminded of the passion of the
antiwar movement. We are reminded, too, that some of the passion
was stirred by the energies of young people living in a world we
hardly remember. For example, protests were sexually integrated in
ways that many other campus activities weren't. Here is the account
from the Michigan Daily: ``Women were allowed all-night permission
to attend the teach-in and as Jared Stammel, '68, remarked, `This
undoubtedly gave a big stimulus to the event.' ''
</P>
<P>
   --By rereading the remarkable reporting by Seymour M. Hersh of
the massacre at My Lai, we are reminded of the sense of innocence
Americans had about themselves and about their war as late as
November 1969. In the two volumes' 1,700-odd pages, perhaps the
most memorable single sentence comes from the mother of one of the
GIs at the village: ``I sent them a good boy and they made him a
murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many memorable moments in these volumes, including the
account by John McCain, now a Republican US senator from Arizona,
of being shot down ``right in the center of Hanoi'' in 1963, being
charged with being a war criminal, being beaten and forced to live
in brutal solitary confinement; the writing of Norman Mailer at one
of the domestic battles of the war, Chicago in 1968, and of Tom
Wolfe, who caught the great tension between the war at home and the
one in Vietnam; the account of Doris Kearns (now Goodwin) of how
President Johnson chose the bombing targets and felt the great
frustration of the war; and the graceful writing of H. D. S.
Greenway, now the editor of the editorial page of this newspaper,
whose unforgettable account of a night with the Viet Cong began:
``At night in the Mekong River Delta, pale lights bob and flicker
like fireflies through the banana trees and over the rice paddies,
dry in the harvest now and white in the moonlight.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a war as brutal as World War II, and in an era when
many Americans' views about World War II come from Spielberg, it is
worthwhile to remember the brutality of the war that came two
decades later. Listen to Jack P. Smith, who was wounded at Landing
Zone Albany in the Ia Drang Valley in 1965, and who now is an ABC
correspondent: ``This was a massacre, and I was one of a handful
not yet wounded. All around me, those who were not already dead
were dying or severely wounded, most of them hit several times. I
must have been talking a lot, but I have no idea what I was saying.
It think it was, `Oh, God, Oh, God, Oh God,' over and over. Then I
would cry.''
</P>
<P>
   But the standards were different in Vietnam. The New York
Times's fabled Sydney H. Schanberg quotes an Air Force general
saying, ``We wiped out whole cities, whole cities, in World War II,
and there wasn't a single protest. Now one bomb falls outside the
target area and they scream in righteous moral indignation.''
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam was, like most wars, the extension of politics by other
means. And at the heart of the struggle over the war was a complex
generational conflict between the wise old men, many with
worldviews rooted in World War II, and the young wise guys, whose
worldview was rooted in the gritty war in Vietnam. The old men were
Omar Bradley, Douglas Dillon, Matthew Ridgway, and Dean Acheson.
The young guys were David Halberstam, Malcom W. Browne, Neil
Sheehan, and Charles Mohr.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the wise young guys won the argument and won over
the Wise Old Men. It was, for better or for worse, the triumph of
journalism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
