<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8707 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-14 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOP EXERCISE IN MOB JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- At the moment of truth, the Impeachment Party has
served up the Mike Espy case in doubly disgusting form, repackaged
for a pseudo-Constitutional stage. That's the best light available
for an exercise in dumbed-down mob justice.
</P>
<P>
   More harshly, it's Andrew Johnson Lite, an attempt by one
political party to separate House impeachment from Senate trial and
removal from office, thus unconstitutionally shredding the Founding
Fathers' design for a double-barreled protection against abuse of
presidential powers.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment of truth, moving onto the House floor this week,
the Espy and Johnson Lite bastardizations of the constitution have
actually merged, illegally into an illegitimate hybrid.In public
now, the House's de facto leader, Majority Whip Tom DeLay of Texas,
can only arrange a tiny majority for impeachment by selling it to
undecided Republicans as something else.
</P>
<P>
   In the open, he and his allies are candidly calling impeachment
censure, transforming it from a constitutional protection of the
country into a partisan, punishment message.And in private, DeLay
and his allies are trying to arrange their tiny majority by telling
House members two even more constitutionally illegitimate tales:
</P>
<P>
   --You don't have to be convinced of President Clinton's guilt of
anything. You're simply the equivalent of a grand juror or inquest
participant looking for probable cause to ``send it to the Senate''
for trial. In flagrant contravention of the standards of the
Judiciary Committee chairman of Watergate fame, Peter Rodino,
current chairman Henry Hyde is DeLay's messenger.
</P>
<P>
   --There won't be any big trial in the Senate anyway, most likely
none at all. It will be halted somehow and either censure will
ensue there or your impeachment vote will stand as Clinton's
punishment. On a pseudo-constitutional stage, the ``prosecutors''
of the president are asserting that the ``indictment'' is in effect
punitive as opposed to accusatory. At least in the discredited case
against former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy, the equally
discredited independent counsel, Donald Smaltz, had the sense to
withhold his extra-legal remarks until after he had lost the trial.
</P>
<P>
   But like the Espy case, this one depends upon a prosecutor's
narrative and theory that is unsupported by his own witnesses _
from Monica Lewinsky's concept of sex to Betty Currie's explicit
denial that she was pressured to say something false.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Starr and David Schippers could make headlines by telling
stories, spiced by selected quotes from uncross-examined grand jury
witnesses. But they cannot try the case in public, and Hyde can't
try the case before the Senate, because their witnesses contradict
each other and the prosecutors' theories.The only exception _
enshrined in first impeachment article _ would involve using Ms.
Lewinsky to allege sexual details her damaged credibility could
never establish in a normal trial.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Starr and Schippers used inference, narrative, and
invective to make cases their witnesses don't. That is why Hyde
contravened another Rodino principle from Watergate and called no
fact witnesses during his four-month process to resolve
contradictions and test the strength of contested grand jury
statements. That is why even the articles of impeachment on perjury
do not specify the actual statements considered perjurious, and
would be dismissed in a second for vagueness in a normal case.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where Andrew Johnson Lite comes to the rescue. One
hundred and 30 years ago, the radical Republicans of the post-Civil
War era set a policy as opposed to perjury trap for Lincoln's
successor; the House sprang it by voting his impeachment even
before they bothered to draft the articles.So rabidly partisan was
that bunch that they thought conviction by the Senate would be
equally preordained, but seven gutsy Republicans eventually stood
in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the variation is that partisan impeachment by the House
can suffice and avoid the embarassment of failing to produce
credible evidence at a trial.
</P>
<P>
   As Representative Bill Delahunt, one of the few who has tried to
reach across party lines and is a leading censure player, put it,
the result is an extra-legal change in the Constitution to remake
``impeachment as a routine punishment for presidents who fall short
of our expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's more.
</P>
<P>
   Cowering under an expiring independent counsel law, the House
has abrogated its constitutional responsibility to exercise the
sole power of impeachment. It has simply received, publicized, and
rewritten the work of Starr, an employee of another branch.And its
leaders seek impeachment without proof of guilt on the expectation
that trial in the Senate can neither succeed nor is even likely to
occur.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny margin in favor that might be arranged next week will
be more than covered by the number of pro-impeachment Republicans
who will be replaced by anti-impeachment Democrats in a matter of
days.If that isn't illegitimate, the word has no meaning. At the
moment of truth, the punishment will become, not fit, the alleged
crime.
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
