<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING READY FOR THE APOCALYPSE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Kathy Branstetter co-runs an on-line
conversation conference on earthquakes for The Well, a
Sausalito-based computer service. Lately it's been buzzing with
stories and advice about the stuff you need to survive a good
shaking or Y2King.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conference gets unusually quiet, and suddenly there's a
little tremor and everybody's strolling through.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently her conference was renamed the ``earthquake and other
catastrophe conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Combine a quake with a tornado, a blackout and the predicted
mini-apocalypse of the Y2K computer glitch, and suddenly a lot of
people are checking their battery supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are coming in and asking what they need,'' said Stan
Deorian, manager of the Earthquake Outlet in Emeryville, which
sells everything from first-aid kits to chemical toilets.
``Basically, you need food, water, medical supplies, flashlights
and light sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said, ``There are those who get more prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   You survivalists know who you are. You're the ones who can't get
the spare tire out of the trunk of your car because of all the
emergency gear.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Francisco area, survivalists don't wear fatigues.
Kathleen Maxwell is a tastefully dressed art historian who wants to
buy a motorcycle _ not for the image, but to escape San Francisco
when the Big One comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city will burn, and we won't be able to get out of town,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She already has two metal garbage cans filled with supplies _
including a radio, flashlights, batteries, clothing, walking shoes,
a crowbar, bleach to purify the gallons of water she keeps
elsewhere, a little stove and Hefty bags ``for yucky things.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell is serious about her emergency preparedness. ``How far
can you go on a motorcycle's tank of gas?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband Paul Maxwell has the opposite preparedness
personality type. ``I just have a small bottle of water from
Lourdes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Spoofing his wife, he said, ``I can't divulge the details, but
we're building a small nuclear reactor.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most people in the area, I'm somewhere between a
survivalist and a guy who can't find the flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   After the '89 earthquake, we stocked the house with water and
cases of canned food. Gradually, the chili and Dinty Moore
disappeared due to dinnertime laziness.
</P>
<P>
   The batteries ran down, but the Pacific Gas and Electric Co.
thoughtfully reminded us they had by providing us with blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   We've never fully restocked our earthquake supplies, but the
trunk of the car is unusable because of the clutter of clothes,
dead batteries and water aged in the canteen.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know what you need in case of emergency, there's
a good guide in the front of the phone book. However, the phone
book fails to mention one necessity: cash.
</P>
<P>
   As many of us learned during the big blackout last week, ATMs
are controlled by the forces of darkness at PG&AMP;E. I learned the
need to keep a stash of cash in the days following the '89
earthquake. Believe me, bartenders don't give out free beer, even
if it is warm.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, someone keeps stealing my stash of cash. I'm not
very good at hiding it from myself.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing the phone book doesn't mention: Whiskey isn't a
bad thing to keep on hand, in quantities large enough to settle
your nerves, but small enough to keep you from looting.
</P>
<P>
   When we think about being prepared for the worst here, we tend
to think about material things. The San Francisco Bay area is a
material place. But there's more the true survivalist can do than
build stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Fire Department offers a course called
Neighborhood Emergency Response Training, or NERT.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't invent the name,'' said Lucien Canton, director of
the Mayor's Office of Emergency Preparedness. ``The program began
when citizens who fought the Marina fire came to us and said they
wanted some training.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the program more than 8,000 people have been trained in
the basic medical, firefighting and rescue skills they'll need
before the professionals arrive. That could be a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Canton says not everyone has to take the training. ``One trained
volunteer can help manage five or six people who aren't trained,''
he said. ``It's what the military calls a force multiplier.''
</P>
<P>
   Or what people in the Bay area call cooperation, similar to the
cooperation they displayed in last week's blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Get the water, food and batteries. But I don't think you need a
motorcycle to flee town.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
