<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8772 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INJURIES-SECRET-BOS &LR;      12-14 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INJURIES-SECRET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMS FEEL IT HURTS TO REVEAL A LOT ABOUT INJURIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They tell us they do it because they want to keep the other team
guessing.
</P>
<P>
   They say it's to protect their players' privacy.
</P>
<P>
   They swear it's a matter of money _ as in not shifting the odds
for bettors, be they in Las Vegas or the office gambling pool.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the result is that professional sports
teams regularly mislead the press and public, or at least they
don't own up to the full truth about how hurt their stars are and
how they're being treated. That's what the Patriots did last week
when they kept mum about the pin doctors inserted in Drew Bledsoe's
finger Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The long tradition of deception has gotten to the point where
Americans know more about the polyps scraped out of President
Reagan's colon _ and the way their fathers and brothers are popping
Viagra and Propecia _ than we did about how Bledsoe's doubly
fractured finger was being readied for a game against the St. Louis
Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody was betting on how many polyps Ronald Reagan had,''
explains Bob Cousy, the driving force of the Celtics from 1950-63
who is now the team's television analyst. ``In the case of
professional athletes, and especially a key performer such as
Bledsoe, everyone concerned has to take great precautions. They
don't want to exaggerate an injury to alarm the betting public, or
to underplay it, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easiest way to deal with it is to give the minimum amount
of information.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is precisely what the Patriots have done with Bledsoe, and
did earlier this season with star receiver Terry Glenn. It's what
the Celtics did for years with Larry Bird and his finicky back,
what the Red Sox did with Roger Clemens's inflamed throwing arm,
and what Bill Parcells did during his Patriots coaching tenure
whenever it suited him. And it's how other pro franchises across
the country typically handle things whenever a critical player
sustains a critical injury.
</P>
<P>
   They say as little as possible. They insist that team doctors do
the same. And they hedge right up until game time or, in Bird's and
Bledsoe's cases, even after the game is under way and they're
playing but it's unclear whether they will return after a break.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it has been done for decades, or at least for the
36 years that Gene Monahan has been around minor and major league
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it hasn't really changed much,'' says Monahan,
head trainer for the World Series champion New York Yankees. ``In
fact, for the most part, it has been less secretive recently. Head
coaches now are more open and frank with the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Players also have less incentive than before to hide their
injuries, says Dick Johnson, curator of the Sports Museum of New
England: ``Before this age of agents and guaranteed contracts,
players were scared to death that if they told owners they were
hurt, they'd lose their jobs. Willie O'Ree, the first black player
in the National Hockey League, who played for the Bruins, hid the
fact that he'd lost 90 percent of his vision in one eye because of
an injury in junior hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were only 100 players in the NHL then, and he knew if he
told anybody, he'd never receive the opportunity to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, with Bledsoe, it's the team that seems to be
doing the hiding. The Patriots did confirm Friday that their ace
quarterback had a pin inserted in his finger to provide the
stability that a cast and splint had offered in recent weeks, but
they released that information only after it was reported in
Friday's Globe. And they declined to provide further details about
the operation or what it could mean for Bledsoe, offering up only
the National Football League-required information that he's
``probable'' to play and has a finger injury.
</P>
<P>
   Why do teams provide so little?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strictly strategic,'' says Patrick Sullivan, whose family
used to own the Patriots and who was the team's general manager
from 1983-90. ``If you're St. Louis and you're trying to get ready
for a game, there's a big difference between preparing for a game
with Drew Bledsoe compared to Scott Zolak.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Lowery, spokesman for the Patriots' current owners, agreed:
``Obviously, the less information we share about a particular
injury, the better position it puts us in competitively.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambling is another consideration, much as it has been since
Cousy started playing nearly half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed Macauley and I would come back to our hotel from Mass on
Sunday morning and some guys with pushed-in noses would be sitting
in lobby chairs watching us,'' Cousy recalls. ``We'd deliberately
limp or put our arms in slings and watch them scatter to the
phones, imagining them calling their bookies telling them we were
injured.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor keeping teams and team doctors from telling all
is recognition of a player's right to the same privacy enjoyed by
other patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unethical to talk about your case to a third person
without your permission,'' says Arnold Scheller, the Celtics'
doctor. ``The athlete is always a patient first.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but others insist that star athletes give up their privacy
rights because they are stars, much the way President Reagan and
other public figures do. That's what most reporters presume and
why, if the team and its doctors won't talk, the press ferrets out
responses from doctors not involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (ticks) me off,'' says Scheller, who acknowledges that he
occasionally does the same thing when asked about athletes he
hasn't treated. ``What you do is get doctors who enjoy the ego
(gratification) of being asked a question and they'll start running
at the mouth without really knowing the details. That's not
constructive for anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Another downside of professional teams keeping secret their
players' injuries is the example it sets for younger athletes.
``Even at the high school level, teams try to hide the fact that
certain players have an injury,'' says Dr. Lyle Micheli, director
of sports medicine at Children's Hospital in Boston and a
consultant to the NFL Players Association. ``This has all taken on
a new dimension.''
</P>
<P>
   Another argument against teams keeping quiet about injuries is
that it's getting tougher and tougher to keep such secrets,
especially from opponents who have increasingly sophisticated
scouting operations. Bledsoe's surgery eventually leaked out to the
press, and Micheli says it was known even earlier through the
medical grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposition sure as heck knows he's got a bad finger,''
agrees Milt Schmidt, who learned what it was like playing injured
during his 20 years as a Boston Bruin, during which he was named
the NHL's most valuable player and leading scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much difference if the public or opposition
knows,'' adds Hall of Famer Schmidt, now 80. ``And if he has a bad
finger, the team has something to lean on if it loses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
