<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8775 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPORT-LOUNGES-HNS &LR;      12-14 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-LOUNGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES WOO BUSINESS TRAVELERS WITH ON-THE-GROUND HOSPITALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Full-body massages. Manicures. Haircuts. Free
drinks. Internet access. Fax machines and copiers, of course. How
about a putting green?
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the lures that airlines use to attract
high-paying business-class passengers in VIP lounges at major
airports around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Business travelers are what airlines call ``high-yield''
passengers. They pay much higher fares than coach travelers,
providing carriers with a big chunk of their revenue.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Chicago-based Cambridge Group travel research
firm, business travelers accounted for just 9 percent of passengers
but 45 percent of revenue in 1997. The airlines compete both in the
air and on the ground to woo these lucrative customers.
</P>
<P>
   Syndicated travel writer Ed Perkins noted that round-trip
business-class fares from the West Coast to London ``are averaging
about $6,000. First-class can reach $8,000-$9,000. By comparison,
you can usually get something in coach for $700 or $800 this time
of year.''
</P>
<P>
   Business-class fares have jumped about 40 percent since 1996,
according to American Express Travel.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins said business travelers are the beneficiaries of
``almost everything the airlines are doing in terms of
innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes VIP lounges. And with most major airlines involved
in global alliances with other airlines, passengers may now access
worldwide networks of lounges regardless of the airline they are
using.
</P>
<P>
   In the air, business-class passengers have more legroom, wider
seats and better food than coach passengers, not to mention free
drinks, individual video screens at their seats and other perks.
</P>
<P>
   But the pampering starts even before take-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience you have at the airport is part of your
experience of an airline,'' said Karen Goodwin, editor of Frequent
Flyer magazine, a Chicago-based national monthly.
</P>
<P>
   At the 5-month-old Chek Lap Kok airport in Hong Kong, the Cathay
Pacific Airways VIP lounge has a cool, minimalist style. It's built
on a mezzanine to enhance openness, airiness and views, and it lets
the soaring rooftop of the main passenger terminal double as the
lounge ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want chintz and velvet, don't go there,'' said Cathay
chief executive David Turnbull.
</P>
<P>
   At the San Francisco International Airport, United Airlines
operates three business-class Red Carpet Clubs _ two in the
domestic terminal and another in the international terminal. United
estimates half its 30,000 daily passengers at the airport frequent
a lounge.
</P>
<P>
   First-class and business-class passengers, frequent fliers and
others who pay a yearly fee of up to $400 can avoid jammed, noisy
departure gates by slipping into the Red Carpet lounges. There,
they find Internet access, small meeting rooms (bookable in
advance), finger foods, cappuccino, newspapers and magazines, and
occasional wine tastings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of our corporate focus is on the business traveler, and
some of our biggest customers are in Silicon Valley,'' said Laurie
Giammona, United's manager of customer service at the San Francisco
airport. Giammona said United maintained separate business centers
outside the lounges for corporate road warriors who fly a minimum
100,000 miles a year on the airline.
</P>
<P>
   VIP lounges at some major airports are even snazzier. At
London's Heathrow, Chicago's O'Hare, Miami International and Los
Angeles International, Chicago-based UAL offers new Arrivals by
United lounges that have showers, concierge service, marble walls
and granite countertops and shelves, toiletries by Molton Brown of
London, and baggage check-through to the traveler's destination.
</P>
<P>
   While some travelers use the lounges to relax, others use them
to work.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Alfred, a Houston-based executive for the Oracle Corp.,
spent part of Thursday morning working on his laptop computer in
the Continental Airlines business lounge at the San Francisco
airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I manage global accounts,'' Alfred said. ``Members of my team
are scattered all over the world. I had a meeting in San Ramon with
a colleague who left for London. She's in Dubai now. I use the
lounges quite a bit _ anywhere I can plug in and sit down.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother of all airport lounges may be Virgin Atlantic
Airways' Virgin Clubhouse at Heathrow. It has a putting green, a
beauty salon, video game room, library, music room and showers. In
addition, Virgin offers passengers in Upper Class _ the airline's
moniker for merged business and first class _ complimentary
transport to and from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be driven in a chauffeured car, a Range Rover or on a
motorcycle, or take a `limoboat,''' said Elvi Taveras, a Virgin
spokesman in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Virgin, founded 14 years ago by the flamboyant British
entrepreneur Richard Branson, also offers in-flight massages, up to
100 movies and a stand-up bar at 35,000 feet. According to Taveras,
Virgin introduced individual video screens in business class in
1989, installing them in economy class in 1991 _ the first in the
world to do so.
</P>
<P>
   All this came about, Taveras said, because ``Richard Branson was
tired of these long-haul flights, and being bored to death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
