<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Tuesday, Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   POLLOCK-NAMUTH (New York) _ The figure of Jackson Pollock _
action painter, dancing dripper, sullen rebel _ was made by Hans
Namuth's camera. Namuth's camera helped make Pollock famous and
Namuth's camera was blamed for Pollock's demise. Now, on the
occasion of Pollock's retrospective at the Museum of Modern Art,
Namuth's camera is there again. Namuth himself died eight years
ago. But his photographs and films are being used to strip away the
layers of paint and lore that have covered Pollock since the 1950s.
Of course, the stripping is tricky, because Pollock's tortured
relationship with Namuth is itself part of the myth. A critic's
notebook by Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-PROTEST (Istanbul) _ Arts Abroad: Turkey's most prominent
young novelist, Orhan Pamuk, has turned down the coveted title of
``state artist'' awarded to him this month. Of the 85 writers,
actors, singers and other cultural figures who were chosen for the
honor several declined, saying they disapproved of the selection
process or did not want to be associated with some others on the
list. But Pamuk was the only one who said he was doing so for
political reasons. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PLUTO-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Breakfast on Pluto,'' by Patrick
McCabe (HarperFlamingo). Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
