<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Because of eased regulations from
the Food and Drug Administration, scores of drugs that were once
promoted only to doctors are now being promoted directly to
millions of consumers in magazines and newspapers and on television
and radio. This year the pharmaceutical industry is expected to
spend well over $1 billion to try to persuade you to ask your
doctor about one or another prescription drug. The tactic has its
benefits and risks, its champions and detractors. But before
consumers ask a doctor to prescribe a drug from an ad, they should
heed what the experts are saying about these ads and how wise
consumers should respond to them. By Jane E. Brody. (1250 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PASSIVE-SMOKE (Undated) _ Effects of passive cigarette smoke
were gauged among California bartenders before and after the
smoking ban went into effect. After the ban, even the bartenders
who smoked themselves showed some health improvements. By Erica
Goode. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-YOGA (Undated) _ Tackling power yoga, a highly
sweaty workout. The purpose of it is to build up body heat and, as
a result, sweat, which enhances flexibility and makes some of the
pretzel-like postures easier. By Gary Taubes. (1250 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MELANOMA (Undated) _ New digital-imaging techniques may soon
help doctors search for early signs of melanoma, the most deadly
form of skin cancer. By Anne Eisenberg. (580 words)
