<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8845 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIRDCAGE-DECOR-HNS &LR;      12-14 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRDCAGE-DECOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRDCAGES CAN DRESS UP A HOUSE WITHOUT FEATHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Birdcages can be works of art in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not enthusiastic about cleaning up after plumed
critters or can't stand their chirping, singing or talking,
consider the birdcage as simply a decorative room accessory.
</P>
<P>
   Victorians were very fond of such cages, whether displayed
empty, filled with a plant or housing an intriguing songbird. Gilt
cages could be found in Europe as early as 1700.
</P>
<P>
   With a little imagination or sense of humor, a cage can make a
dramatic statement as a display case, especially if it's entwined
with rustic grape vines, leaf or flowering plants and contains a
fake bird. Unusual props can create a conversation piece, such as a
fake stuffed or ceramic teddy bear, bunny, fish or cat.
</P>
<P>
   It's also fun to decorate a birdcage so that it's in style with
each season and/or holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Birdcages come in various sizes and shapes in metal and wood.
Most are made from wood with delicate metal rods, hooks and
latches.
</P>
<P>
   Many decorative wood cages are stained in a warm wood, painted
in a fashionable color or antiqued to look like aged brass, bronze
or copper. Early cages were often made from expensive woods, such
as mahogany, to match suites of furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Some even come unfinished, where the finished look is up to you.
</P>
<P>
   If you do plan to house a live bird in the cage, you might want
to select an unfinished cage or a metal one, so that there are no
dangerous finishes for tweetie to gnaw on.
</P>
<P>
   A decorative birdcage can be used in virtually every room in the
house, including an ornate one hanging in the foyer or a bamboo or
rattan one on the patio. Large birdcages can make great storage
places for towels in the bath.
</P>
<P>
   A hot-air-balloon cage comes with a hook at the top. Once hung,
it looks like it's floating across the room. The basket under the
balloon is often used as a planter.
</P>
<P>
   Others that are shaped like churches, houses, palaces, temples
and pavilions often come with short legs or a flat bottom for a
table top or pedestal setting. Some styles can be wall-mounted.
</P>
<P>
   Antique Hardware and Home in Bluffton, S.C., 800-422-9982,
carries a vast selection of decorative birdcages that cost from
about $89 to $799.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage cages often can be found in antiques shops, at flea
markets or at yard and garage sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 1520EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8873 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAZA-SCENE-1215-COX     12-14 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAZA-SCENE-1215-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ADDRESSES GAZANS AMID HISTORY OF TRAGEDY, TERRORISM AND
ANTI-AMERICANISM
 &HT;    With COX-MIDEAST-CLINTON-1215.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, The Gaza Strip _ On the wall is a photo of the most
notorious bomb-maker in Palestinian history. On the beat-up old
television is U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And, seated Monday evening on the thin floor cushions and cheap
rugs of their crumbling block house, the Badrasawi family likes
what they see.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are happy that the president of the world is coming here to
see the tragedy we live in,'' says Ibrihim Badrasawi, a 37-year-old
tile worker who earns about $15 a day to support a wife and six
children.
</P>
<P>
   His family is like thousands of others sandwiched between a
violent past and a glimmer of hope brought by the first visit of an
American president to the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   America was long seen as an imperialist force here, backing only
the Israeli occupiers at the expense of the 1 million Gazans.
</P>
<P>
   But, Monday was a day of jarring sights and sounds signaling a
change in the way Americans and Palestinians view each other.
</P>
<P>
   There were barefoot children carrying plastic American and
Palestinian flags. There were former guerrilla fighters, having
traded in fatigues for double-breasted suits, fixated on a hotel
television that broadcast Clinton's helicopter arrival.
</P>
<P>
   And the Badrasawi house, nearly unfurnished and with his
children in front of the TV, was a mind-boggling mix of desperation
and wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   They live off one of the sandy, labyrinthine alleys in the
50-year-old Beach Refugee Camp. Just off the Mediterranean Sea, it
is packed with 50,000 Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrihim Badrasawi's brother was shot to death by Israeli troops
in 1990. It was during the height of the Intifada uprising that
turned the narrow streets of these refugees camps into flashpoints
where Palestinian kids and Israeli soldiers clashed and died almost
daily.
</P>
<P>
   Another brother was arrested six weeks ago by Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat's police, accused of being active in the terrorist
group Hamas that America and Israel urge Arafat to smash.
</P>
<P>
   In a gold frame on the wall is Hamas bomb-maker Yehye Ayash,
whose bombs killed dozens of Israelis until 1995, when he was blown
up by a booby-trapped cellular phone in what was widely believed a
mission of Israeli agents.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Badrasawis say they are tired of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see a Jew killed or an Arab killed,'' says
Mudalaleh Badrasawi, Ibrihim's 60-year-old mother. ``I sacrificed
my son. What are we going to get? We want a Palestinian state, of
course.''
</P>
<P>
   The family fled what is now Israel in 1948 and is among the more
than 700,000 Gaza refugees. The peace process has left Gaza under
Palestinian control and there have been physical improvements. Raw
sewage does not flow down their alleys as much.
</P>
<P>
   But Gazans make an average of 20 percent less money now than
five years ago and Ibrihim Badrasawi can no longer go to work in
Israel, where he made about five times as much money.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes Clinton can change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago there was hatred toward the Americans,'' he
says. ``Now we are all carrying the American flag because the
American president is here.''
</P>
<P>
   On his 8-year-old television, he watches leaders in the
Palestinian National Council stand and affirm that they no longer
want to destroy Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have now proved that we do not want to push Israel into the
sea. They have no more excuses,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he endorses peace or Hamas is unclear. Many Palestinian
families are split among the political and non-political, fighters
and breadwinners.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, he says the bomb-maker's picture was left behind by the
brother who is now in prison. A few of the brother's children are
around too, now his responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   During the long, televised Palestinian leadership meeting,
Badrasawi has changed from his dusty work clothes and washed away
the dirt that caked his eyebrows and hair.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Clinton speaks, Badrasawi is clean-scrubbed and
sitting on the floor next to his mother. He looks like a new man
hoping for a new era.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit means that there will be a Palestinian state, he
predicts, and that all the tragedy will have been worth something.
His face lights up as ``president of the world'' talks about the
``dispossession'' of Badrasawi's people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never expected an American president to talk about our
suffering. This is really big for us,'' he says. ``Of course,
nobody will ever forget this. Not even the children.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 1529EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8885 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-MOVIES-HNS &LR;      12-14 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-MOVIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BABE' SEQUEL FALLS VICTIMS TO TODAY'S MORALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WALTER ADDIEGO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The recent resignation of Universal Pictures
production chief Casey Silver was the least surprising news out of
Movieland in a while. There's no mystery: Few of the studio's
recent major releases _ dating back to ``Primary Colors'' _ came
anywhere close to what the industry calls success.
</P>
<P>
   The last straw was the new ``Babe,'' a big-budget sequel to the
surprise 1995 hit about a sweet-tempered, talking pig. Universal
considered the follow-up a can't-miss deal. But when the crucial
numbers from the long Thanksgiving weekend came in, the $90 million
sequel had made less than $8.5 million, which, by the arithmetic of
audience falloff, means it had rolled over and died. Following
``Meet Joe Black,'' another high-profile disappointment, it was
curtains for Silver.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to ``Babe: Pig in the City'' (and Casey Silver)
goes beyond the reporting on how much money is involved in
family-oriented, G-rated movies. (And it's a considerable sum _ ``A
Bug's Life,'' ``The Rugrats Movie'' and ``Babe'' placed in the top
five over this do-or-die weekend.) The important story is the
radical shift in the content and mood of these pictures, and the
erosion of the boundary between entertainment for children and
adults.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing troubles may have hurt the new ``Babe,'' but so did
the picture's surprisingly dark mood. The charm of the original
film was in the little pig's naivete in the face of life's troubles
and his determination to overcome his limits. In the new movie,
Babe has the same positive qualities, but he's almost peripheral to
the picture's black comic sensibility. As the title indicates, he
leaves the farm for the big city, but it's an urban nightmare, a
police state where animals get the short end of everything.
</P>
<P>
   Who is the audience for this movie? The director, George Miller,
created the ``Mad Max'' movies, over-the-top satires about humanity
struggling in a world of depleted resources _ hardly films for kids
(at least by the old standards). In spirit, the G-rated ``Babe''
sequel echoes the outrageous, barbaric world of Mad Max, with its
comic-book violence, savage characters and mordant view of human
nature. Picture good old Babe wearing a dog collar with nasty metal
studs, as he does in the film; Miller doesn't believe the old
categories are worth respecting any longer.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful undercurrent of irony and doubt dominates this new
style of cross-generational entertainment. Take ``The Rugrats
Movie,'' which debuted at No. 2. Maybe it doesn't push the edges
quite as hard as the ``Babe'' sequel, but it still offers, by
conventional standards, a pretty curdled viewpoint. The ``Rugrats''
TV show on Nickelodeon, and other recent animated TV offerings,
look different, and provide a comically critical look at American
domestic life.
</P>
<P>
   A recent New Yorker piece by Mimi Swartz discusses the
``Rugrats'' phenomenon: ``The babies had an addled, homely look
that made them hipper than their smooth, glossy counterparts on
other kids' shows. ... The show projected a jaded view of family
life and consumer culture.''
</P>
<P>
   This barbed outlook has been pushed even further in other cable
shows (e.g. ``The Angry Beavers''), and the ratings prove it has a
considerable audience. The genius of cable programmers, and in
particular Geraldine Laybourne, former Nickelodeon president, was
to see that they could use these shows to make inroads on
mainstream TV _ which is now playing catch-up.
</P>
<P>
   While the edgier sensibility in family entertainment is gaining
influence, declaring victory would be premature. At the box office,
the more conventional ``A Bug's Life'' is the major success (it
opened in first place, and remains there; ``Rugrats'' is fourth,
while ``Babe'' has dropped to No.7). Tradition-minded parents have
little use for the more pointed stuff and have objected loudly to
the ``Babe'' sequel.
</P>
<P>
   Network TV, and the Disney Co. have gravitated toward programs
for kids that won't draw fire from conservative critics. The
result: shows and movies that were dull and dishonest in turning a
blind eye to noncomforting realities.
</P>
<P>
   This safety-first mentality begins in the idea of childhood as a
separate, special stage of existence, a golden age that responsible
adults are bound to try to protect. The notion peaked in the 19th
century, though of course there were subversive voices to be heard,
even in the heart of the Victorian era _ Lewis Carroll comes to
mind. But in the main, respectable parents wanted their children to
digest respectable lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are a lot of children (and adults) uninterested in this
sort of lesson, but now it's no secret that a steady diet of
moralistic entertainment is just too much medicine. Storytellers
have always known that fairy and folk tales with frightening,
violent, mature or non-optimistic content aren't simply something
that children can be exposed to, but stories they must hear _ for
the sake of their mental health, or spiritual development, however
you choose to view it.
</P>
<P>
   So the cat is out of the bag, or, more aptly, the pig is out of
the poke. Many Americans have accepted a more challenging sort of
entertainment that is less age-specific. That conservatives are
waging a cultural war against this new material is a testament to
its success. Parents trying to hold the line are having a tough
time because the stuff is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, the ``Babe'' sequel and ``The Rugrats Movie''
define how far the change has progressed. With its modestly
subversive content, ``Rugrats'' is a hit, while the more
challenging ``Babe'' tried to go too far, too fast.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to the unfortunate Casey Silver, who
gambled that a mass ``family'' audience was willing to be led
somewhere it hadn't gone before. The box office suggests that
viewers found the new territory too scary. Silver was trying to
stay ahead of the curve, and instead spun off the road and crashed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
