<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-KIDS-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTRODUCING KIDS TO COMPUTERS
</HEADLINE>
  By LIZ RUSCH 
 c.1998 Child 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because computers play a greater role in parents' lives at home
and at work, kids can't help being curious about these exciting and
powerful machines. But how should we introduce our children to
computers? And when?
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Saltzman of Seattle let his 5-month-old son bang on the
keys of his home computer, but Barklay wasn't truly interested in
the computer until he was about 18 months old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he was ready to sit on my lap and watch me scroll through
text,'' says Saltzman. ``At 30 months, Barklay would click the
mouse if I held it steady. By the time he was 3, he could control
the mouse by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Barklay's early experience with the computer is typical of many
children's. By 30 to 36 months, your child may develop the fine
motor skills that are needed to manipulate a mouse or to peck at
the keyboard. Around this age, he may also show a desire to play
with the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Should you let him? Go ahead. Gone are the days when early
childhood experts wondered if we should shield young children from
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are no longer asking if its developmentally appropriate to
use computers,'' comments Douglas Clements, professor of learning
and instruction at the State University of New York at Buffalo.
``Preschoolers have shown enjoyment and confidence using them.
Rather than being frustrating, computers are a source of pride.
Rather than isolating children, computers can be a catalyst for
social interaction with parents and with other children.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say you should plop your little one in front of a
monitor as soon as she can hold up her head. ``I don't think that
children under the age of 2 need to touch the computer other than
to explore its physical nature,'' says June Wright, professor of
early childhood education at Eastern Connecticut State University
and director of the Computer Discovery Project, a research program
that looks at the role computers play in children's learning.
</P>
<P>
   But even banging on the keyboard or seeing you at the computer
can teach a lesson. ``If you hold a baby on your lap as you work on
the computer, she'll see that something happens when you push a key
and that it happens on the screen,'' says Barbara Bowman, president
of the Erikson Institute, a graduate school in child development in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   There's no reason to pressure a young child into using a
computer. But when she's ready, here are some suggestions on how to
get her started:
</P>
<P>
   _ Help her master the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   During your child's first encounter with the computer, don't be
surprised if she tries to use the mouse like a TV remote control,
says Wright. But, she adds, ``many young children figure out how to
use the mouse without much guidance.''
</P>
<P>
   If your child needs some help, avoid programs that require her
to click and drag. Pointing and clicking are enough of a challenge.
Sit down with her and demonstrate using the mouse. Then, lay your
hand on top of hers, positioning her index finger over the mouse
button. Help her move the cursor to a large target and click on it,
Clements recommends.
</P>
<P>
   If your child still has trouble, let her point at the screen to
indicate what she wants to select, and you can click on it for her.
Or move the cursor into position, hold the mouse steady, and let
your child do the clicking.
</P>
<P>
   Some kids find typing easier because the keyboard is stationary.
To acquaint your child with the keyboard, set the font size to 24
or larger and let her press the keys to make letters, Wright
suggests. Some software for young children uses only a few keys,
such as the enter key or the space bar. Tape construction paper
onto these keys so that she can find them easily.
</P>
<P>
   _Choose an appropriate program.
</P>
<P>
   Test it first at a library or computer store (the Web sites of
many software companies also have demos that you can try). Look for
programs with attractive animation and characters who have engaging
voices. Software that uses classic songs, such as ``The Wheels on
the Bus,'' and favorite games like peekaboo also help children feel
at home.
</P>
<P>
   Toddlers are especially delighted with software that lets them
click and explore. For example, a program may let a child click on
the door of a house and go inside, then click on a cuckoo clock to
hear its sound. Try to avoid software in which an action occurs _
such as a dog wagging its tail _ without the child making it
happen. These programs make it more difficult for children to
understand cause and effect thereby encouraging passivity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't make the computer a baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   Once your child is up and running, he'll want to play with the
computer by himself. This often happens between ages 3 and 4,
depending on the child. ``By then, children will explore a program
to its fullest'' says Wright. But computers shouldn't become
electronic baby sitters. Break up time on the computer with other
activities, such as reading, drawing and playing outdoors with
friends, says Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that most young children seem to limit
themselves, Wright has observed. ``Three-year-olds seldom stay on
the computer for more than 15 or 20 minutes at a time,'' she says.
``A 4- to 6-year-old may get more involved, for up to 30 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Restrict your child if he spends over an hour in front of e
screen every day, says Clements. The American Academy of Pediatrics
suggests that children over age 2 shouldn't be allowed to watch TV
for more than one to two hours daily, and many experts believe you
should include the time your child spends on the computer in this
limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computers ask kids to make decisions, which encourages a more
involved and active stance than the passive way they take in TV,''
notes Clements. But, he says, watching a good TV program is better
than playing with a lousy computer program.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Liz Rusch is a contributing editor to Child and is the former
managing editor of Teacher Magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS at (800) 972-3550 or fax
her at (212) 499-3382.
</P>
