<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WREATHS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE YOUR OWN WREATHS FROM THE LANDSCAPE
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of a wreath in a homemade frame. Call
212-499-3342 or 499-3355 for for e-mail delivery; or download from
www.newscom.com. See BC-LIFEBEAT-ADVISORY for instructions. 
 By SUSAN MCCLURE 
 c.1998 Susan McClure 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rebel against the expense and extravagance of the holidays by
making wreaths that cost you next to nothing and help tidy up your
landscape. Use greenery clipped from around the yard for a small
wreath to snuggle around the bottom of a candle or a larger wreath
for the front door. Here's how.
</P>
<P>
   1. Use hand-held pruning shears to prune off 4- to 6-inch long,
supple, young stems on evergreen trees and bushes. Target lanky
shrubs in need of a trim to give hedges and shrubs a final shaping.
</P>
<P>
   Yews, which grow in foundation plantings around many houses,
have fine needles that compress nicely into a velvety, dark green
wreath. More aromatic pines and hemlocks also are suitable if you
can find unwanted sprigs or branches to remove. Select carefully as
these branches will not resprout.
</P>
<P>
   Use sprigs of other evergreens with varying colors and textures
to decorate the surface of the wreath. The glossy blue-green
foliage of hollies, golden- or blue-hued junipers and false
cypress, and fan-shaped sprays of arborvitaes make handsome
contrasts. Other choices include the petite rounded leaves of
boxwood and toothed, dark green leaves of teucrium.
</P>
<P>
   You also will need some showy red berries, nature's ornaments
conveniently provided in holiday colors. Cotoneasters, winterberry
holly, viburnums, multiflora and shrub roses, and crabapples all
produce beautiful berries you can use.
</P>
<P>
   For variety, consider tracking down clippings of gray,
stem-hugging northern bayberries with a quiet appearance made up
for by the delightful bayberry aroma.
</P>
<P>
   If you look even harder _ in a perennial garden, meadow, or
shrub border _ you can find plants such as old-fashioned
hydrangeas, ornamental grasses and milkweeds that have interesting
pods and seed heads to add to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Use them naturally clad in earthy shades of gray, tan, and brown
or spray paint them bright colors such as red, gold, and silver.
</P>
<P>
   2. Other supplies you will need are fine green florists wire and
a wreath shaper.
</P>
<P>
   To make a wreath shaper, use a clean piece of wood for the
wreath frame base. Secure two concentric circles of 3- to 4-inch
high pegs or small-headed nails onto the wood. Put the pegs or
nails 1 to 2 inches apart. For a large wreath, make the diameter of
the outer circle 12 inches and the inner circle 6 inches; a small
wreath will be 6 inches and 2 inches.
</P>
<P>
   For a distinct holiday touch, purchase red velvet bows, golden
ornaments, or other festive nicknacks you insert into or tie onto
the finished wreath.
</P>
<P>
   3. Assemble the wreath by filling the wreath frame with an
evergreen base of yews, pines, or other fine-leaved sprigs. Firm
the sprigs down, molding the young stems around the curve of the
frame pegs. Don't worry if some small shoots slip out of
confinement; they will give the wreath a soft, natural appearance.
</P>
<P>
   If you intend to top the wreath with a heavy layer of dried
flowers and decorations, a simple foundation of yew sprigs will
likely be all that's necessary.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a texture-rich blend of greenery to top with
berries, add other evergreens _ junipers, blue spruce, and the like
_ when the space between the concentric pegs is almost full. Lay
these sprigs on the base as desired, but don't be surprised if they
shift a bit when you secure the wreath with wire.
</P>
<P>
   To hold the wreath together, wrap it with florists wire. Begin
by circling the wreath once with wire and twisting the loose end to
the rest of the wire to secure it. Continue to loop the wire around
the wreath, slipping it under and around about an inch from the
previous loop until you have encircled the entire wreath. When
finished, cut the wire and secure the loose end to a nearby wire.
</P>
<P>
   4. Spray the evergreen wreath with Wilt-Pruf to keep it fresh
longer. Dilute 1 part Wilt-Pruf emulsion in 10 parts water and
spray it outdoors when the temperature is over 40 degrees. Let the
wreath dry in daylight before bringing it in.
</P>
<P>
   5. Add decorative materials. If you are using dried flowers or
pods and seed clusters, cut large sprays down to small sprigs,
about 3 to 4 inches long so they stay in scale with the wreath.
Slip the stem base under the wire and into the wreath to hold it in
place.
</P>
<P>
   To maintain a feeling of balance, repeat similar looking
materials like the feathery heads of foxtail grass or dried sprays
of statice around the wreath. Angle them so the tips flail toward
the outside of the wreath, giving it a graceful look.
</P>
<P>
   Or, use just one kind of material, like red-dyed sea-oats
available at craft stores, to ribbon the center of a wreath,
leaving green highlights on either side. Maintaining a symmetrical
appearance gives a pleasing uniformity to smaller wreaths used
around candle bases.
</P>
<P>
   A larger door wreath is a good candidate for asymmetrical
decorating. You can tie a bright bow or put a golden gilded leaf
and cone at the base of a door wreath. Then arrange sprays of dried
flowers to emerge from either side of it. The top of the wreath can
be a quieter blend of varying greenery or berries.
</P>
<P>
   5. Arrange small wreaths around the base of thick scented
candles or holiday candle sticks to dress them up for special
occasions. Secure larger wreaths to the front door.
</P>
<P>
   If you intend to give wreaths as a gift, store them outdoors in
a cool, dry location until the last minute. They keep better that
way.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Susan McClure is a free-lance writer based in Valparaiso,
Ind) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS at (800) 972-3550 or fax
her at (212) 499-3382.
</P>
