<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMEDIES-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATURAL REMEDIES FOR A COLD WAR
</HEADLINE>
  By CHARLES DICKSON 
 c.1998 magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It always seems to happen at the most inopportune times. You
have a sales meeting, or a speech or a date and pow _ you get hit
with a cold. Now you look like Rudolph and bark like Rover and feel
like something the cat dragged in.
</P>
<P>
   Any drugstore has an aisle of products for cold symptoms. Many
are combination cold remedies formulated to wipe out several
symptoms with one capsule. They typically contain one or more of
the following: an antihistamine (to dry up your runny nose), a
decongestant (to open up your stuffy nose), an antitussive (to
quell your cough) and a pain reliever (to ease your aches).
</P>
<P>
   If you want to use the combination products, you do so with the
government's blessing as long as your symptoms match up
specifically with those on the label. The problem is that shotgun
remedies may give you too much or too little of a certain drug or
you could be getting a drug ingredient that is just plain useless
for your symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look at some natural alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   The widespread use of vitamin C was stimulated by the writings
of Linus Pauling, winner of Nobel prizes in chemistry (1954) and
peace (1962), who promoted vitamin C as a preventive for colds.
Those who take it for this purpose generally ingest 300 to 500
milligrams a day.
</P>
<P>
   For those who already have a cold, studies have shown that
taking up to 1,000 milligrams per day can reduce both its severity
and its duration. Most physicians warn that such a high dosage
should not be taken daily over a long period of time since such
amounts tend to interfere with copper absorption in the body and
can also cause diarrhea and cramping.
</P>
<P>
   What about chicken soup? Benefits of this folk remedy have been
confirmed by a study at Mt. Sinai Medical Center in Miami Beach
which found that hot chicken soup got nasal mucous flowing
significantly better than a cup of hot water. At the University of
Nebraska in Omaha, researchers found that in a test tube chicken
soup slowed the movement of neutrophils _ immune cells activated by
cold viruses. ``When you have a cold, neutrophils normally migrate
from the blood to mucous membranes stimulating such symptoms as
inflammation and mucous secretion and perhaps fever and cough,''
says Stephen Rennard, chief of pulmonary and critical care medicine
at the university's medical center.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's spice up that chicken noodle Soup with three
additional cold fighters: garlic, onions and hot pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic has been found to contain compounds with chemical actions
similar to those of antibiotics. While it's considered to work best
against fungal infections, garlic has antibacterial and antiviral
effects as well. You're aware of how the juice of freshly sliced
onions can make your nose run and your eyes water. Onion has been
used by homeopathic physicians to treat colds and allergies with
these same particular symptoms. Onions contain many of the same
compounds found in garlic and may also stimulate the immune system.
And hot pepper is effective since it contains capsaicin, which
causes you to perspire and make your nose and eyes run, thus
enabling you to cough up mucous or clear your nose when you blow.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of teas have been shown to be effective in winning the
cold war. There is mullein, a yellow flowering member of the
snapdragon family. Place two teaspoons of dried leaves in a cup of
hot water and let it steep for 10 minutes, then drink it. Mullein
is available at health food stores as well as being a common
roadside weed in most of temperate North America. It is very
effective in relieving congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Pungent ginger, is also effective. Place a teaspoon in a cup of
boiling water. The oil found in ginger is similar to that found in
red pepper. It has an irritating effect on the nose and throat that
helps to thin mucous, making it easier to cough up when you are
congested.
</P>
<P>
   The pretty purple flower known as echinacea has an impressive
reputation as a natural antibiotic. Make a tea by using capsules of
the root powder (available in health food stores or your herb
garden). This herb has a long history of use among Native American
tribes and scientists have found that a compound in echinacea helps
kill a broad range of disease-causing viruses and bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you don't mind the bitterness, you might find relief
in goldenseal, a member of the buttercup family. To make a tea use
one teaspoon of powdered root in a cup of hot water. Steep for 10
minutes and add honey, sugar or lemon to mask its bitter taste.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Charles Dickson holds a Ph.D. in chemistry and is a free-lance
writer based in Hickory, N.C.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS at (800) 972-3550 or fax
her at (212) 499-3382.
</P>
</TEXT>
