<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELVIS-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER MONUMENT TO ELVIS
</HEADLINE>
  By JAY ATKINSON 
 c.1998 Jay Atkinson 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLY SPRINGS, Miss. _ You have been to Graceland, paid the $10
to tour Elvis Presley's Memphis home and final resting place.
</P>
<P>
   You've passed the glass peacocks outside the Music Parlor, seen
the 17 television sets, the tacky shag carpet in the Jungle Room,
the gold records in the Trophy Room, the graves in the Meditation
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   You may think you've seen it all but you haven't. Not by a
Mississippi mile.
</P>
<P>
   Here in this town off Highway 78 in northwestern Mississippi,
about midway between Memphis and Presley's birthplace of Tupelo,
Miss., is a bizarre attraction called Graceland Too.
</P>
<P>
   It has been the home for 44 years of Paul B. MacLeod, who lives
here now with his 25-year-old son, Elvis Aaron Presley MacLeod. The
elder MacLeod's wife of 22 years left him, he says, after she told
him to choose between her and his museum.
</P>
<P>
   It is a rickety two-story house packed literally to the ceiling
with Elvis photos, records, costume replicas and other Presley
memorabilia. It is open every day of the year, 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   The entrance fee of $5 includes the commentary of MacLeod
himself. Standing in the unheated entranceway, his hair slicked
back and wearing a sheepskin coat and muttonchop sideburns, the
middle-aged MacLeod says, ``We got more facts on Elvis than the
Library of Congress. If alien life were to visit, stopping here
would do more to explain American culture than any other place on
earth.''
</P>
<P>
   In the continuous, punctuation-free monologue of a carnival
barker, MacLeod regales his visitors with facts, half-truths and
hearsay about the complicated doings of the King, who died in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Holding an automobile antenna, MacLeod points to a portrait of
Presley and says, ``The only scar on Elvis was this little one
above his eye because he liked to do his own fight scenes in movies
and he got that in 'Wild in the Country.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I hope I die in 10,000 years but when I do I'll be buried
in this-here copy of a gold suit made for the movie 'Kid Galahad'
and my epitaph will be 'Here Lies the World's Greatest Elvis
Fan'...''
</P>
<P>
   In the collection is every TV Guide reference to Presley since
1956 and several photographs of Paul MacLeod posing with his son.
In one, a teen-age Elvis MacLeod strums a guitar while his
jumpsuited dad looks on with pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the people down there in Tupelo worried,'' says Paul
MacLeod referring to the Presley birthplace about 70 miles
southeast. Asked if his collection is insured, MacLeod says, ``If
they can get by me and my son, who's 6-5, they can have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling his first glimpse of Elvis on television almost 40
years ago, MacLeod says he decided ``that a guy who sang like that
and dressed like that and combed his hair like that, he was more
than just a flash in the pan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you a personal friend of Elvis?'' asks one towheaded
young visitor.
</P>
<P>
   MacLeod's blue eyes dart around the room. ``I got close to him a
few times,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR:
</P>
<P>
   Graceland Too
</P>
<P>
   200 E. Gholson
</P>
<P>
   Holly Springs MS 38635
</P>
<P>
   telephone: (601) 252-7954
