<HEADER>
A8915 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-JULIA-ROBERTS-AR     12-14 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-JULIA-ROBERTS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD'S $17 MILLION WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides and black and white photos of Julia Roberts, Susan
Sarandon, Liam Aiken and Jena Malone in ``Stepmom.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``I don't want to be known as Hollywood's $17 million woman,''
says Julia Roberts, ``although I've been known as worse things.
 &HT;    ``I'd prefer to be known as the 'great friend woman,' 'the great
actress woman' _ or the 'nice legs woman.' Now that would be OK.''
 &HT;    Nevertheless, the 31-year-old Roberts is picking up that fat
paycheck for the film she's currently shooting _ reuniting with her
``Pretty Woman'' co-star Richard Gere and director Garry Marshall
in ``Runaway Bride.''
 &HT;    She's earning considerably less for playing the title role
opposite Susan Sarandon and Ed Harris in ``Stepmom'' (opening Dec.
25), although she and Sarandon could clean up nicely if the film
turns out to be a box office smash because they were producers on
the film.
 &HT;    In ``Stepmom,'' Sarandon plays Jackie, whose ex-husband (Harris)
has married Isabel, a vain, ambitious fashion photographer played
by Roberts. Not surprisingly neither Sarandon nor her two young
children are wild about their father's new spouse.
 &HT;    Things change, however, when Jackie learns she is dying. At
first Isabel is less than thrilled when she realizes she's
inheriting a family. She has to learn to change her priorities and
win the love and trust of the ailing Sarandon and her young
children if she is to grow into the stepmom role.
 &HT;    Roberts, looking relaxed with her hair down to her shoulders and
dressed in sweater and slacks, was in obvious good humor she showed
up at New York's Waldorf-Astoria to talk her role, which she calls
the most mature of her career.
 &HT;    Roberts, without children of her own, still found herself in
sympathy with Isabel since the character's life was much like that
of a career-driven actress.
 &HT;    ``Isabel says she never wanted to be a mom and yet finds herself
struggling to cope with being a surrogate parent--an unwanted
stepparent,'' says Roberts. ``Given her age she's more interested
in her career than stuck with a family. I can relate to that. And
it's a no-win situation because Jackie is the perfect mother and
Isabel can only come off a poor second when she tries to become a
parent.''
 &HT;    Should Roberts herself decide to become a parent, she says she
is certainly not about to become a stay-at-home.
 &HT;    ``I don't understand this one-versus-the-other business,
especially in this generation. Would any of us be here as capable
human beings if our parents didn't work? My mother always worked. I
know people talk as if this work I do would make it more difficult.
I have no children so maybe I'm talking out of the side of my head,
but it seems to me that you work for four months and then you don't
work for like nine months. That's a lot of kid time.''
 &HT;    And she's the first to admit that the kind of money her
star-wattage commands would pay for a lot of mother's helpers. Now
that she's become Hollywood's highest paid female star, however,
the actress insists getting paid big bucks is the last thing she
thinks about.
 &HT;    ``I love what I do and I'd do it for free,'' she says. ``I'm not
going to perform better if I get paid more or less. It's not pound
for pound--where you only pay for the legs or the smile or the big
hair. That's not how it works. When you're up at 4 a.m. and out in
a bikini and it's 30 degrees outside--it doesn't matter how much
they're paying you. At that moment you still think it's not
enough.''
 &HT;    Roberts says she's no longer the callow, vulnerable 20-something
star whose personal life has been chronicled to the point of
exhaustion since she first burst on the scene in ``Mystic Pizza''
(1988), ``Steel Magnolias'' (1989) and then as a star in ``Pretty
Woman'' (1990).
 &HT;    ```Stepmom' is first real-life grown-up part that deals with
real complex issues and problems I've ever done. It's about kids,
husband, job, not about makeup and wardrobe. I couldn't have done
it five years ago--it wouldn't have had the same value to me.''
 &HT;    Besides teaming up with Gere again she has just finished
``Notting Hill,'' shot in London, in which she gets to romance Hugh
Grant for writer Richard Curtis who wrote ``Four Weddings and a
Funeral.''
 &HT;    And her career is riding high again after a series of flop
movies like Woody Allen's ``Everyone Says I Love You'' (1996),
Robert Altman's ``Ready to Wear'' (1994), the horror film ``Mary
Reilly'' (1996) and ``The Conspiracy Theory'' (1997) opposite Mel
Gibson.
 &HT;    Her private life reads like a five-reeler: In l991 she broke off
her engagement with Kiefer Sutherland three days before the
wedding. In l993 she married singer Lyle Lovett but they divorced
21 months later. In between were relationships with Dylan McDermot,
Liam Neeson, Jason Patric and New York gym-owner Pat Manocchia.
 &HT;    She insists her relationship with TV actor Benjamin Bratt (``Law
and Order'') is still on despite published reports to the contrary.
But she says, ``I'm not getting married any time soon.''
 &HT;    Bratt has lasted more than a year on her arm but she still lives
alone in a New York apartment not far from her sister Lisa who is
two years older. (Roberts also has an older brother, actor Eric
Roberts.)
 &HT;    In the long-awaited reunion with Gere she plays a woman who goes
from man to man. Is the role based on her own penchant for skipping
from boyfriend to boyfriend?
 &HT;    She good naturedly handles the question: ``Of course not, '' she
says. ``The movie is fiction.''
 &HT;    But there's no doubt she's delighted to be back with her
``Pretty Woman'' star, and she adores the film's director,
Marshall.
 &HT;    ``The whole film has been a gas,'' she says. ``Garry is
fantastic and gets me to go out on a limb and do things I wouldn't
do for other directors. I know I can trust him. On `Pretty Woman'
he had me do something I was scared about. I thought I'd humiliate
myself forever but when I saw the scene in the finished movie with
an audience, people were peeing laughing.''
 &HT;    Since shooting ``Stepmom'' she has become bosom buddies with
co-star Sarandon, who has a family with actor-director Tim Robbins:
``Susan and Tim are my absolute idols,'' says Roberts. ``Some day I
would like to have the kind of career that Susan has and the kind
of relationship with a man that she has with Tim.''
 c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.)  
