<HEADER>
A8928 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICIANS-UPANDCOMERS     12-14 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICIANS-UPANDCOMERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME OF THE FEMALE ARTISTS EXPECTED TO BREAK OUT IN 1999
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies BC-FEMALE-MUSICIANS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN and MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So which female artists are coming up behind Celine, Sarah and
Lauryn in 1999? Our picks:
</P>
<P>
   BEWITCHED: This teen all-gal quartet plays the same sort of
teeny-bop pop as the Spice Girls and All Saints, but these Dublin
girls are touting a wholesome image: They wear jeans, not Ally
McBeal-short skirts. Europe's all over them: Bewitched's first two
singles _ ``C'est La Vie'' and ``Roller Coaster'' _ both entered
the chart at No. 1. ``Bewitched'' gets a U.S. release Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   LILA McCANN: At the ripe age of 17, McCann has had several
country hits and has seen her debut, ``Lila,'' go gold. She also
toured stadiums last spring with George Strait. The Seattle high
schooler has cut a Bryan White/Steve Wariner song, ``You're Gone,''
for her sophomore effort. The as-yet-untitled CD is due out in
March; good timing, especially because fellow teen LeAnn Rimes
plans to cut back on live work next year while trying to break into
films.
</P>
<P>
   NICOLE RENEE: Prince, or whatever we're supposed to call him
now, is a good reference point for this 23-year-old Philadelphia
singer. Her recent self-titled debut, which will receive a major
push in '99 from its label, Atlantic, combines spirituality with
sexuality, and the music is as indescribable as anything Prince has
done, crisscrossing every genre from R&AMP;B to rock. A tour is slated
to begin in mid-'99.
</P>
<P>
   KELLY WILLIS: How long must this woman wait to be a big deal
outside Texas? Not long, judging by the advance copy of ``What I
Deserve,'' her forthcoming CD on Rykodisc, and her first since
1993. Due out Feb. 23, ``Deserve'' should bring her the acclaim
she's due. Willis wrote three songs with Jayhawks leader Gary
Louris; her husband of two years, Bruce Robison, chips in on one;
and she also does commendable covers of Nick Drake's gorgeous
``Time Has Told Me'' and Paul Westerberg's ``They're Blind.''
Expect ``Deserve'' to be on more than a few best-of-the-year lists
this time next year.
</P>
<P>
   SEAN YSEULT: When White Zombie sundered this fall, lead vocalist
Rob Zombie got all the ink, releasing a CD and heading off on tour.
Meanwhile, bassist Yseult formed a trio called Famous Monsters and
released ``In the Night,'' a fun, scuzzy blast of metal, surf and
punk.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
