<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEFENDERS (Washington) _ Allies of President Clinton are
mounting grass-roots efforts to persuade the Republican House to
reject impeachment and impose censure. The efforts by Vice
President Al Gore, the People for the American Way, the AFL-CIO and
civil rights activist Jesse Jackson are expected to culminate in a
massive demonstration at the Capitol Thursday. By STEWART M.
POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-REPUBLICANS (Washington) _ As President Clinton faces a
House impeachment vote later this week, Rep. Christopher Shays,
R-Conn., a key Republican moderate who has strongly opposed
impeachment, now says he is having second thoughts and wants a
meeting with Clinton to discuss the issue. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-WHISTLEBLOWER (Washington) _ The Supreme Court upholds the
rights of whistle-blowers. It rules that a former employee of a
Georgia home health care company, who claims he was fired for
helping uncover Medicare fraud, can sue the firm for damages. By
MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DISABLED (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to
decide a dispute over whether people with mental disabilities
should get a choice of care options rather than being sent to
institutions. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Gaza, Gaza Strip) _ President Clinton says a
Senate trial will not be good for the nation and says he is willing
to accept any punishment short of impeachment by the House of
Representatives, which is likely to take up an impeachment vote
later this week. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GAZA (Undated) _ In a historic speech on 10th
anniversary of President Ronald Reagan's visit to Middle East,
President Clinton says the Palestinian people are free to
``determine their own destiny on their own land.'' By JOHN C.
HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-STATION (Houston) _ Fresh from linking the first modules
of the international space station, the Endeavour astronauts
prepare for a Tuesday night landing in Florida _ although clouds,
rain and winds could be a factor. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-GROCERY (Monterrey, Mexico) _ U.S. grocers are turning
more attention on Mexico. In addition to a stabilized economy, U.S.
grocers realize Mexico is an enormous market ripe for the picking:
96 million consumers who spend 3.5 times more of their disposable
income on groceries than Texans. Perhaps the most aggressive
entrant into the market is San Antonio-based H-E-B, which in 1999
plans to open seven more stores south of the border. By JENALIA
MORENO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Republican congressional leaders are
nuts to demand President Clinton's resignation. Do they really
prefer to run against incumbent Al Gore in the year 2000? They are
deceiving themselves if they think voters won't take revenge on
them for hounding Clinton from office. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
