<SLUG> BC-THEWEIR-THEATER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG IRISH PLAYWRIGHT STAGES BLARNEY-FILLED SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by LONDON STAGE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In the vibrant days of Sean O'Casey and John Millington
Synge in the 1930s and '40s, Irish drama was the bravest expression
in world theater, and the most buoyant. There was a marked decline,
then a resuscitation by the '60s, when the gaudy wave that gave us
Brendan Behan also delivered the enduring Brian Friel.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is a new star in the firmament of Irish theater. He is
Conor McPherson _ can't get more Irish than that _ and he is only
28, but ``The Weir'' is his third play to be staged in both Ireland
and England. And ``The Weir'' is on its way to being the most
talked-about event of the current London theater experience.
</P>
<P>
   Under the title ``La Fille de Dublin'' (The Woman of Dublin),
McPherson's drama also has conquered Paris. A New York date is in
the offing, and the prediction here is that ``The Weir'' will make
it a grand slam, especially if its felicities are exhibited in one
of the more intimate Broadway playhouses.
</P>
<P>
   The drama actually arrived in London 17 months ago, but in a
tiny habitat _ upstairs at the Royal Court. Having thrived since
1888, the Royal Court at Sloane Square qualifies as England's
longest-established theater with the dedicated aim of producing new
plays. But the venerable building is undergoing some much-needed
repair; so ``The Weir''_ despite having captivated critics from the
word ``go'' _ could not be moved into the Royal Court's ample
auditorium, necessitating some other West End location.
</P>
<P>
   It's rather confusing. Here's ``a Royal Court Theatre
production'' housed since October in the Duke of York's Theater on
St. Martin's Lane; and every evening, some playgoers go to the
wrong house. Once they find ``The Weir,'' though, they're in for a
riveting experience.
</P>
<P>
   Conor McPherson's two previous plays, ``This Lime Tree Bower''
and ``St. Nicholas,'' struck Londoners as charming freaks that
somewhat stretched the definition of ``play.'' They were hardly
more than distended monologues, and McPherson certainly has a knack
for winding up a character and really letting him go with the old
blarney.
</P>
<P>
   That proves to be an aspect of ``The Weir,'' too, but here the
long, rambling, hilarious, ridiculous, character-enriching speeches
punctuate a stunning theatrical conceit. There's no tragedy quite
like tragedy unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   It's a 90-minute play of continuous action, and there's no
intermission. That's good, because the drama, after a sluggish
beginning, keeps mounting like perking coffee until it almost boils
over.
</P>
<P>
   The single, simple set is a tiny bar in an unnamed small Irish
village. The bartender is joined by his first customer, they carry
on, and for a time we think we're witnessing a revival of ``Juno
and the Paycock'' or ``The Playboy of the Western World.'' But no.
The bantering duologue between young barkeep Brendan and seedy,
50-ish Jack carries meaningful exposition. They talk about the
mysterious young woman from Dublin who is moving into their
sequestered lair for reasons they know not.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the woman, Valerie, is among them, accompanied by Finbar,
her realtor. Then raffish Jim comes in for a snort, and the full
company is complete _ a cast of five well-drawn characters nicely
limned by their players.
</P>
<P>
   Irish men are legendary liars; and Jack, Jim and Finbar by turns
concoct wild and ironic tall tales, each determined to outdo the
others in impressing the beguiling Valerie. She listens patiently,
then it's her turn ... and she shames the men with a gripping
personal account as genuine as theirs are phony.
</P>
<P>
   The quintet of Irish actors is barely known in England and known
not at all to Americans. Jim Norton as crusty Jack is a standout
among the men, but Dermot Crowley (Finbar) and Kieran Ahern (Jim)
shine in their appointed moments; and Brendan Coyle (Brendan), the
only player without a long, personally illuminating discourse, is
an appealingly youthful contrast. As for Michelle Fairley
(Valerie), she holds her audience spellbound.
</P>
<P>
   A weir is a barrier for withstanding water or wind or whatever.
There's an oblique reference to a weir in the early banter, but
that may be taken metaphorically: Valerie is the weir of truth,
exposing and repelling the fraudulence around her.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be hearing more about ``The Weir''; and Conor McPherson
bears watching now, and surely for a long while.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is a theater critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
