<HEADLINE>
ALSO ON THE BOARDS IN LONDON ...
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies THE WEIR-THEATER) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PERRY STEWART 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conor McPherson's ``The Weir'' is not the only live theater game
in London town. A perusal of the current stage scene there reveals,
of course, that Andrew Lloyd Webber is well-represented: Sir Andy's
cash kitty, ``Cats,'' is purring at the New London on Drury Lane;
``Starlight Express'' is roller-skating at the Apollo Victoria;
``The Phantom of the Opera'' haunts Her Majestys.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of playwright Alan Ayckbourn should note that ``Things We
Do for Love'' is in residence at the Duchess _ where
``Copenhagen,'' by Michael Frayn (''Noises Off''), is scheduled to
open Feb. 9.
</P>
<P>
   At present, Frayn's ``Alarms &AMP; Excursions'' is ensconced at the
Gielgud.
</P>
<P>
   Among the American imports are ``Into the Woods'' at the Donmar
Warehouse, ``Rent'' at the Shaftesbury and ``Grease'' at the
Cambridge, where the kids of Rydell High are ``booking to the
Millennium,'' according to a recent Times of London ad.
</P>
<P>
   A revival of the venerable ``Oklahoma!'' is due to arrive Jan.
21 for a limited run at the Lyceum. And if you can't score a ticket
to Casa Manana's Fort Worth production of ``The Complete History of
America (abridged),'' they'll be happy to accommodate you at the
Criterion.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on London theater, those with Internet
access can try albemarle-london.com.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
