<SLUG> BC-MICROBROADCASTERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME FOR FCC TO EASE UP ON `MICRO' BROADCASTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By JOHN AUSTIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lots of us love microbrewing. Ditto microwaving. There's another
micro out you might like, too _ if only the federal government
would allow us a taste.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking micro broadcasters. They air low-watt signals,
typically broadcasting programs on topics of interest to small
segments of the community from undisclosed locations _ say, a van.
They usually have a range of a few square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, running your own little station without federal
approval violates the law, as a Connecticut micro broadcaster
recently learned when the FCC busted his gospel-music micro
operation. Though there was a time when smaller operators could
legitimately crank up as few as 10 watts, that was legislated out
of existence decades ago. Though the low-watters are commonly
termed broadcast ``pirates,'' one prominent micro broadcaster calls
the phenomenon ``electronic civil disobedience.''
</P>
<P>
   The feds, however, may finally be ready to concede that although
bigger is sometimes better, downsizing can be cool, too. At least
in small doses.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC appears to be poised to let the little kids back into
what has become a very high-stakes game. Hearings set for Thursday
in Washington, D.C., should determine whether regulations will be
loosened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chairman is very interested in trying to make that
happen,'' said Andy Schwartzman, president of the Media Access
Project, referring to the head of the FCC. The Media Access Project
is a public interest law firm based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of room on the air. Here's hoping the regulators
let the micro broadcasters give us a breath of something fresh.
</P>
<P>
   (John Austin is radio critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Contact him at jaustin(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
