<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGICAL SCHOOL NAMES NRC HEAD PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ Shirley Ann Jackson, whose life story traverses the
mysteries of quantum physics and the realities of the nation's
racial divide, has been named the 18th president of Rensselaer
Polytechnic Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, the current head of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission,
holds the sort of national stature trustees hope will put
Rensselaer Polytechnic on the map of elite technological schools,
along with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and Stanford
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our old established image is the male-dominated, technological
nerd-based school,'' said Edwin Rogers, a computer science
professor who sat on the presidential search committee. ``This
sends a message, and hopefully the world will listen.''
</P>
<P>
   When she takes office in July, Jackson, 52, will become the
first black woman to head a major U.S. research university.
</P>
<P>
   And if the standing-room only crowds and four ovations at a
ceremony Friday were any indication, she has star power.
</P>
<P>
   With a few brief strokes, Jackson quickly established a rapport
with the university community, jokingly calling herself ``the
Energizer Bunny'' and graciously inviting Acting President
Cornelius Barton to the podium for a round of applause. She won
another ovation simply for being a mom _ delaying her move to Troy
until her son finishes high school in June.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson replaces R. Byron Pipes, who stepped down in April.
Pipes, though generally lauded as a fund-raiser, fell out of favor
for his inability to work with the faculty. By contrast, Jackson
spoke of ``a shared vision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To be effective, a leader must be able to motivate those she
leads and to build consensus among diverse shareholders,'' she told
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the NRC, which has a $500 million budget and 3,000
employees, Jackson weighed the competing interests of
environmentalists and industry-heads in the politically charged
world of nuclear power.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after her appointment by President Clinton in 1995, Time
magazine ran a cover story on Connecticut's Millstone Power
Station, infamous for its repeated violations of safety standards
and reprisals against whistle blowers.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, even the NRC's harshest critics give Jackson high
marks for acknowledging the commission's mistakes and taking
responsibility for the actions of her predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a person of character,'' said James Riccio, staff
attorney at Public Citizen, a Washington-based advocacy group.
``Ms. Jackson came in as an academic. Her predecessor was smooth,
but she was much more solid.''
</P>
<P>
   The trustees selected Jackson Sunday from a field of three
finalists. They voted twice, the second time unanimously.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling her young experiments with live bees, Jackson repeated
the advice of her father: ``Reach for the stars and at least you'll
get off the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   At MIT, Jackson became the first black woman in the country to
earn a doctorate in physics, but was shot at, spat on, and told by
an MIT professor that ``colored girls should learn a trade.'' In
the 30 years that followed, Jackson served on the boards of MIT and
Rutgers University, taught physics at Rutgers and worked for 15
years as a research physicist at AT&AMP;T Bell Laboratories in Murray
Hill, New Jersey. Earlier this year, she was inducted into the
women's hall of fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm not unaware of the historic significance of the
things I've accomplished,'' she said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's salary was not disclosed, but it is undoubtedly more
than the $137,000 a year she made at the NRC. At the time Pipes
resigned, he earned an annual salary of $270,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
