<HEADLINE>
10 GIFT IDEAS FOR THE GOLF ENTHUSIAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN FORNOFF  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shopping for a gift for your favorite golfer?
There's something in every price range, and most gifts can be
ordered from catalogs and by the Internet, as well as from big
retailers and some area pro shops.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top 10 for just about any year and just about any
handicap:
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 10, $10 to $50: A dozen golf balls, of either your
recipient's favorite make, or a cut above. Do your homework. Do not
take pot luck. There are too many choices on the market, and if you
offer rocks when your golfer wants marshmallows, you've bogeyed.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 9, $10 to $30: A golf glove or six. White is the safe
color if you're giving only one, and, remember, this is for the
player's non-dominant hand. If the golfer's a right-hander, the
glove is for the left hand. And if you're guessing at size, err on
the large side, not the small side.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 8, $40 to $140: An all-weather microfiber windshirt, in a
great color or pattern. These have replaced the golf sweater in our
climate because they are so lightweight and suitable for all-season
play.
</P>
<P>
   _ No.7, $40 to $400: A lightweight, good-looking and, most
important, waterproof rainsuit.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 6, $20 to $50: A waterproof hat that won't blow off.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 5, if your golfer loves Christmas: An golf-theme ornament
for the tree, to be had for $3 and up.
</P>
<P>
   _ No.4, starting at $20: Custom labels for the golfer's clubs.
At the lower prices, these are adhesive strips that wrap around the
shaft; at higher prices, one will find engraved metal inserts for
the grip end.
</P>
<P>
   _ No.3, $500 and up: A battery-powered golf cart that walks
along with the player. These are the absolute best gift for the
senior on your list who golfs as much for the walk as the game.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 2, at about $30 and up: A video/computer swing analysis,
lesson, series of lessons or, for the big spender, golf school.
</P>
<P>
   _ No.1: A golf outing _ either a gift certificate from a
particular course or your own promise of a round at the course of
the recipient's choice. If the gift is for a couple or a
significant other, a nice touch would be to include child care.
There's no better gift to the golfer than the game itself.
</P>
<P>
   Happy holidays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
