<HEADLINE>
STARS WHO DESERVE THE HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Baseball Hall of Fame ballots went out last
week with all the attendant drama of a sheep shearing on a sheep
farm during the 4-H Sheep Shearing Festival.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, we know that George Brett, Carlton Fisk, Nolan
Ryan and Robin Yount will be voted in, at least some and maybe all
four on the first ballot. The other 24 names, from George Bell to
Mike Witt, have little chance without the help of the Veterans
Committee, either because their accomplishments won't stand the
test of modern attention spans or because they've been on the
ballot so long they are starting to turn green.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, there will be no campaigns like the one the San
Francisco Giants assembled to try to usher Orlando Cepeda into the
Hall three years ago (although you may get some in the near future
on players like Dave Concepcion, Steve Garvey, Dale Murphy or Tony
Perez). There will be no great debates, no virulent arguments about
the merits of Mickey Lolich as opposed to Mike Boddicker. The news
will, in short, be about as riveting as the House Judiciary
Committee's impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   What of the game's contemporary stars?
</P>
<P>
   First, let's eliminate the 10 no-brainers, the sure or near-sure
first-balloters, the ones who dominated their positions for an
extended period of time and would get in if they never play another
inning. Those would be Barry Bonds, Roger Clemens, Dennis
Eckersley, Ken Griffey, Tony Gwynn, Rickey Henderson, Randy
Johnson, Greg Maddux, Mark McGwire and Cal Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   Next, let's eliminate the ones who have been very good for a
long time but not nonpareil at any particular point, or so dominant
that you can't imagine the Hall without them. That list would
include Mark Grace, Robby Alomar, John Franco, Bret Saberhagen,
Mike Mussina, Frank Thomas, Rafael Palmeiro and Craig Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves you with a debatable list of maybe 10 others, some
who ought to make it eventually, and others who will probably end
up enduring the same fate as Perez, who might be the most qualified
Hall of Famer not in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, take John Smoltz and Tom Glavine, both of whom
thrived in Atlanta, and not just on Maddux's coattails. They are
very nearly as dominant, and Glavine was indeed better than Maddux
this year. And yet, one can make a case for them being sort of Don
Sutton-ish ... very good for a long time but never The Man. And
Sutton got in this past year mostly out of voter exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Or Paul Molitor. Many folks will maintain he is a no-brainer
based on his amassed numbers, but he did miss a chunk of his career
with injuries and played in the long shadow of Yount for much of
his career. Molitor is a probable but not a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   Or Barry Larkin, whose career has been obscured by (a) his
Midwestern reticence and (b) playing in Cincinnati for one World
Series winner and now a series of bad teams. He, like Molitor, has
had a good share of injuries, and when people called him the
National League's best shortstop, they never called him the best
shortstop in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Or Orel Hershiser, the best pitcher in the game in the late
'80s, living on guile and tooth enamel even at this late stage. Has
a World Series ring, played in Los Angeles, and can do the
schmooze.
</P>
<P>
   Or Jeff Bagwell, the inside-baseball crowd's favorite player but
not a national figure by any means. None of them would shame the
Hall by their inclusion, but it would not be seriously diminished
by their absence, either.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the guys who seem sure to make it but haven't
played enough to pass the ``could he get in today?'' test. Like
Mike Piazza, who is probably a sure thing but has two or three more
big-number years to accomplish. Or Mo Vaughn, who probably doesn't
get in now but could with two or three more monster years. Or Wade
Boggs, who spent a lot of years hitting .300 and well beyond but
was competing with Gwynn for the title and didn't last as long at
the top of his game. He wouldn't be a first-ballot inductee because
of that but probably would get in eventually.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, there is Albert Belle. His numbers are as good as
his image is bad, and by any mathematical stand he either is in or
will be as soon as he gets a good look at Camden Yards. Since there
is no deportment clause that gets you into the Hall (Ty Cobb got
in, after all), and the only real rule that could keep a player out
is betting on baseball (Pete Rose and Shoeless Joe Jackson haven't
gotten in, after all), there is no really good reason not to vote
Belle unless a voter flat doesn't like him. And there are plenty of
those.
</P>
<P>
   We'll be having this discussion again in a few years, with more
seeming sure things like Alex Rodriguez, Juan Gonzalez, Chipper
Jones, Sammy Sosa, Mariano Rivera, Nomar Garciaparra and Ivan
Rodriguez. We'll argue about David Cone and Jose Canseco and Trevor
Hoffman and Curt Schilling. And we'll all be in agreement on Jeff
Juden.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, it will eat up valuable time that has been spent
of late arguing about why Jose Offerman is worth six times as much
as Rich Aurilia, debating about rich clubs eating not-rich clubs as
though it were not a century-old phenomenon, or speculating where
the Expos, Pirates and A's are moving next week (hey, Albuquerque
is open, no credit checks, no waiting period). December is indeed a
very blessed time of year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
