<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9069 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PRINCEOFEGYPT-TE     12-14 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PRINCEOFEGYPT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES `PRINCE OF EGYPT' HAVE WHAT IT TAKES TO BE A `LION KING'?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The exodus of DreamWorks' ``The Prince of Egypt'' from page to
screen may not have endured locusts, frogs or fire, but it did
survive one of the fiercest plagues of all: the media.
</P>
<P>
   When rumors of an animated musical based on the Ten Commandments
began circulating a few years ago, naysayers went into overdrive,
dubbing the seemingly ridiculous notion ``Dreamworks' The Zion
King.''
</P>
<P>
   And even as the movie prepares to open Friday, doubts persist:
Will animation fans sit still for a more adult-themed, dramatic
story? After Jeffrey Katzenberg's departure from Disney, can he
hope to wrench a piece of the animation pie from the monster Mouse
he helped create? Considering Disney's run-ins with the Religious
Right, can an animated film (a medium not known for faithfulness to
source material) adequately adapt a story from the Bible? And most
importantly, what do you mean there are no Moses action figures?
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg and company certainly hope to provide satisfying
answers to allthose queries with their animated epic, which may
have cost as much as $100-plus million to make.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Katzenberg, Steven Spielberg and David Geffen formed
DreamWorks SKG in 1994, Spielberg had suggested the idea of an
animated movie based on the Old Testament story of Moses. Geffen
agreed, with reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be one of the single greatest pieces of advice I've
ever had in my professional career,'' Katzenberg said. ``David
said, `Jeffrey, when you were at Disney, your tradition was take
these fairy tales and adapt them to do what you wanted to. ... You
changed the stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do that with this. If you're going to tell the story
... one, you will have to do it faithfully; two, you will have to
do it accurately; three, you don't know anything about it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So Katzenberg and producer Penney Finkelman Cox set out to find
the folks who did. They traveled the world, consulting more than
500 archaeologists, Egyptologists, scholars, theologians, biblical
experts and clergy.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said myriad experts corrected inaccuracies and eliminated
anachronisms, a move that was often criticized in the entertainment
press as an attempt to appease religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   But making a film based on the religious beliefs of millions of
people meant the filmmakers had to take a little more
responsibility than animated films have been noted for taking.
Disney's revisionist history in ``Pocahontas,'' its racial
stereotypes in ``Aladdin'' or its forced happy endings in any of
its adapted fairy tales just wouldn't wash with a retelling of the
Book of Exodus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain formulas that we just threw out because they
just didn't apply to this movie,'' said Cox.
</P>
<P>
   As pundits in magazines like ``Entertainment Weekly'' and
``Premiere'' delightedly point out, the absence of a cartoon
formula favorite _ the wacky, cuddly sidekick _ might make the
picture a hard sell for younger viewers. Katzenberg says the
filmmakers grappled with the idea, even taking Steve Martin's and
Martin Short's voicing of the Pharaoh's court magicians much more
over the top. But it didn't work, so they went back to a more
serious tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would even be more risky if they had tried to
introduce those kind of characters in something as sacred as a
Bible story,'' said Fox Animation's Gary Goldman. Goldman has some
experience with audience fickleness, considering the disappointing
performance last year of Fox's ``Anastasia,'' which he co-produced
and directed. But Goldman says that, based on the success of Pat
Robertson's Christian Broadcasting Network anchored by ``The 700
Club,'' Christian households are a vastly untapped market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine too many homes, whether they're Jewish homes
or Christian homes, that wouldn't want that in their library ...
because it's educational and serious, yet entertaining,'' he said.
``But our fingers are crossed for him (Katzenberg) to have a hit
there. We need to break this concept that Disney are the only
people that can create a satisfying animated product.''
</P>
<P>
   But Disney is credited with re-invigorating the genre, and along
the way moviegoers have been programmed to believe that animation
is aimed at the young. And what better way to dominate young
viewers than by flooding the market with a tidal wave of tie-in
toys? But don't look for ``The Prince of Egypt'' locust farm at
Toys R Us. You won't find it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `How come there are no lunch pails or stuffed
animals?' Because we didn't make a movie that has that stuff,''
Katzenberg said. ``... I think when you see it, you'll understand
this is not a candidate for a Happy Meal.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``The Prince of Egypt'' will focus on things like its
three soundtracks, 25 books and educational opportunities within
its multi-denominational study guides. (They're due online in
mid-December at princeofegypt.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story and marketing approaches alone weren't enough to
distinguish DreamWorks from the Disney mold. Katzenberg says the
look of the film was crucial, prompting the DreamWorks artists to
come up with a visual approach he dubs ``painted realism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to bring paintings to life. It's not live-action and
it's not cartooning. It's dramatic, the characters are
three-dimensional. We're hoping that 15 seconds into the movie, you
actually relate to them as human beings, not as caricatures, not as
cartoons,'' Katzenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether audiences relate to ``Prince'' at all remains to be
seen, but even an unlikely box-office bath won't spell Armageddon
for DreamWorks animation any time soon. The surprise success of its
computer-animated ``Antz'' was a shot in the arm, and the studio is
already hip deep in ``The Road to El Dorado,'' an animated ``Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid''-inspired comedy due in November.
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Contact him at tcamp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
