<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ As the impeachment vote neared in the
House, several of President Clinton's few Republican supporters
began to waver Monday. Instead of conciliation, the White House
turned to the attack with Vice President Gore denouncing
Congressional Republicans for refusing to allow a vote on censure
and asserting they were thwarting the overwhelming will of the
nation. With photo. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-POLL (Washington) _ Even after the House Judiciary
Committee voted to impeach President Clinton, the latest New York
Times/CBS News Poll shows that the American people remain
remarkably consistent: overwhelmingly, they do not think Clinton
should be impeached. By Richard L. Berke. With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on the impeachment
situation. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MAIL (Washington) _ Congress may be out of session and
members out of town, but the Capitol is ablaze in advance of
Thursday's vote on the impeachment of President Clinton. Voters
have sent Hill aides into overdrive, clogging their phone lines,
maxing out their voice mails, draining dry the toner in their fax
machines and putting their e-mails on tilt. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
