<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9148 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LOGIC15-COX     12-14 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LOGIC15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE LOGIC OF DEMANDING A CLINTON CONFESSION
 &HT;    450&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fence-sitting members of Congress argued Monday
that it is not illogical to demand that President Clinton admit to
an impeachable offense in order to win their votes against
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it much like a defendant in a court trial,''
explained Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   If the accused criminal admits his guilt and asks for
forgiveness, the judge can impose less than the maximum penalty,
Foley said. If the defendant remains unrepentant and refuses to
concede the wrongdoing, the judge can hand out a stiffer sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens every day in a courtroom setting,'' said Foley, who
is among more than three dozen undeclared members from both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these have expressed dismay that Clinton still sticks to
his claim of having testified truthfully _ at least technically _
in his deposition in the Paula Jones lawsuit and before Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr's federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the president can do is to deal with the reality of what
he has done to confront the truth. Two simple words, 'I lied,'
would have gone a long way,'' said Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., in an
appearance on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is to fix what the truth is _ not to
have a degradation of what the truth is, because it impacts on the
dignity of the presidency, the dignity of Congress, and the dignity
of our country,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Another of these moderates, Rep. Bob Franks, R-N.J., wrote a
letter to the president last week warning that he was inclined to
support an article of impeachment charging perjury unless Clinton
comes forward and admits that he lied under oath.
</P>
<P>
   The first Democrat to urge Clinton to resign, Rep. Paul McHale
of Pennsylvania, has said he would oppose impeachment if the
president would just admit to lying.
</P>
<P>
   The seeming contradiction _ demanding a guilty plea in exchange
for a vote of acquittal _ has not been lost on some veteran Capitol
Hill observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has really puzzled me,'' said Norman Ornstein, a
congressional expert with the American Enterprise Institute. ``It
would seem to me that a member of the House has two duties in this
situation. One, determine for yourself what you believe that the
president did. Second, determine for yourself whether what he did
constitutes an impeachable offense. What he says about it should be
completely immaterial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The logical explanation is that they're looking for an
excuse'' to give their constituents for a no-win vote, Ornstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good out. You know (Clinton) is not going to'' admit
lying under oath, said Larry Sabato, a political scientist at the
University of Virginia. ``So it's probably good cover'' for an
impeachment vote, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Sabato said Clinton's stubbornness reminds him of President
Reagan during the Iran-contra scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reagan insisted to the end _ and probably insists to this day
_ that he did not trade arms for hostages although it was obvious
that he did,'' said Sabato. ``Clinton insists that he did not lie
under oath, although it's obvious that he did.''
</P>
<P>
   But some members insist that Clinton must confess perjury before
they will consider a vote against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Louisiana, people have great compassion and great affection
for repentant politicians,'' said Ken Johnson, a spokesman for Rep.
Billy Tauzin, R-La.
</P>
<P>
   For Rep. Bob Ney, R-Ohio, though, it is ``too late'' for the
president to say anything that could affect his vote on
impeachment, said Ney's spokesman, Neil Volz. Ney believes Clinton
committed perjury and is now weighing whether this perjury rises to
the level of an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   But Ney thinks still Clinton should come completely clean ``for
the good of the country,'' said Volz.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
