<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Dec. 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of Monday afternoon, temperatures in Jacksonville,
Fla., hovered in the middle 50s with light rain falling. Tuesday,
clouds and spotty rains will limit temperatures across the northern
two-thirds of the Florida peninsula as Atlantic moisture wraps
inland around an offshore low-pressure system. Clouds and rain will
extend farther north along the coast, affecting eastern sections of
Georgia, South Carolina and perhaps southeast North Carolina. Ocean
winds averaging 15 to 25 mph with higher gusts will prevail along
the Southeast Coast from Jacksonville to Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated showers and mountain snows will struggle to develop
over Arizona as a formidable but moisture-deprived Pacific low
swirls slowly inland. Thus, no organized areas of precipitation are
likely.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the low will still have significant impact on other
parts of the Southwest as the large contrasts in barometric
pressure between the low and a high over southern Idaho generate
strong winds from the east through the mountains of southern
California. These Santa Ana winds may gust to 50 mph or more at
times below narrow canyons.
</P>
<P>
   The northern Middle Atlantic states will be very chilly early
Tuesday morning with single-digit readings possible in the cold
micro climates of northern Pennsylvania and West Virginia. Farther
east, winds from the west averaging 15 to 25 mph will warm on
descent from the Appalachians, boosting afternoon temperatures in
eastern New England 10 to 15 degrees above average.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Tropical Storm Faith
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Typhoon Warning Center in Guam issued a final warning
for Tropical Storm Faith on Monday as the system marched toward its
demise over the mountains in southeast Vietnam. The tropical system
had been a typhoon on Sunday, with sustained winds over 100 mph
while over the open seas. Unlike the tropical Atlantic and eastern
Pacific basins, where hurricane season has ended, the western
Pacific never sleeps, with typhoon season spanning the entire year.
High sea-surface temperatures in this region are the primary factor
in the year-long risk of tropical storms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 1746EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
