<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON _ GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip _ In his most dramatic
speech on foreign policy, President Clinton Monday told the
Palestinian people they are free to ``determine their own destiny
on their own land.'' He then witnessed a Palestine National Council
vote annulling parts of the Palestinian charter that deny Israel's
right to exist. That action quickly met with the approval of
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. It was the first visit
to Palestinian-controlled territory by an American president, and
Clinton applauded PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat for making bold moves
toward peace with Israel and said it was time to think harder about
ways to cement the peace and ensure a more prosperous future for
all Palestinians. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service 800).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GAZA-SCENE _ In one of the many refugee camps here, a Hamas
family watches Monday's historic events; American President Bill
Clinton on the television, a picture of the radical Palestinian
group Hamas' chief bomb-maker on the wall. They are a clear example
of the new Palestinian view of Clinton and the United States, as
U.S. flags were draped all over, offices were closed and thousands
of people holding American flags for the first time without burning
them crowded the streets. Will also include general reaction from
Palestinian leaders to Clinton visit. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ From the Gaza Strip Clinton says he's looking for a
``reasonable compromise with Congress'' to avoid impeachment.
Meanwhile, one of a handful of anti-impeachment Republicans in the
House today signaled a possible shift in position and asked for a
face-to-face conversation with President Clinton to discuss his
case. ``If I had to vote today I would vote against impeachment,''
said Rep. Christopher Shays, (R-Conn.), who has set a meeting with
constituents for Tuesday night. He added, ``I don't have the same
level of conviction I had a week ago. In a second ominous
development for the White House, Rep. Frank LoBiondo, (R-N.J.)
issued a written statement saying he would support impeachment.
(Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON _ JERUSALEM _ President Clinton again signaled
his willingness to accept censure Monday, saying, ``I don't believe
it's in the interest of the United States and the American people
to go through the impeachment process and have a trial in the
Senate.'' (Deans, Cox News Service 300).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ADVICE _ WASHINGTON _ What could President Clinton do
between now and Thursday to sway the impeachment debate in his
favor. Political consultants offer their advice. (Shepard, Cox News
Service).IMPEACH-LOBBY _ WASHINGTON _ Impeachment is said to be a
vote of conscience, but that hasn't halted efforts to pressure the
undecided House members. A pro-Clinton rally organized by Jesse
Jackson is planned for Thursday. Each side is accusing the other of
hardball tactics. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LOGIC _ WASHINGTON _ Logic suggests that if House
members believe President Clinton committed impeachable offenses,
they should vote to impeach him. But several undecided Republicans
say otherwise. They say that if Clinton confesses to conduct they
consider impeachable, they will vote against impeachment, but if he
continues to insist he is not guilty, they will vote for
impeachment. Seeking members, spokesmen or experts to explain this
seeming paradox. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-GADEL _ Nathan Deal announces that he will be voting for
impeachment, and Jack Kingston says he is leaning that way, though
he is chastened by the idea that this is a vote for history.
(Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Continuing spot coverage of the
Microsoft antitrust trial. (Regan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   CENTURY _ Gov. Lawton Chiles will return a final time to this
small town on the Florida-Alabama state line where, as an obscure
state legislator, he became ``Walkin' Lawton,'' taking the first
step on a statewide trek toward election to the U.S. Senate and
eventually the Governor's Mansion. A motorcade Tuesday will take
Chiles' body from Century to Tallahassee over familiar roads he
walked to win repeated elections and, frustrated and depressed, he
made his decision to withdraw _ only temporarily as it turned out _
from politics after 18 years in the Senate. (Crowley, Palm Beach
Post).
</P>
<P>
   JASPER _ Live coverage of the pretrial hearing of William King,
one of three white men accused of killing James Byrd Jr. last
summer. Rulings expected on publicity, but the change of venue may
not be decided. (Gamino, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
