<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PATCH-ADAMS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR IN A CLOWN SUIT BATTLES ILLS OF HIS PROFESSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va., W.Va., Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dressed in a clown costume of fiery red, orange and
yellow, Dr. Patch Adams reflected one recent afternoon on the movie
that is about to make him famous and on other topics, including the
most terrible disease in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie has changed my life,'' Adams said, not altogether
cheerfully, as he hoisted his 6-foot 4-inch frame out of a chair to
answer yet another telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   The movie ``Patch Adams,'' which is directed by Tom Shadyac and
opens nationally next week, stars Robin Williams as a doctor who
sees medicine itself as critically ill from an emotional void
between doctors and patients, the disappearance of the
old-fashioned house call and the near-industrialization of the
healing arts.
</P>
<P>
   Like the doctor in the movie, the real-life, 53-year-old
physician has spent his adult life thumbing his nose (often
Pinocchio-long or red and bulbous in clown's makeup) at the medical
establishment and at what he sees as its cancerous hunger for
profits.
</P>
<P>
   But why play the clown, both as man and doctor, as he has for
years?
</P>
<P>
   ``Humor is an antidote to all ills,'' he likes to say. He does
not disdain X-ray and CAT scan, stethoscope and scalpel. He just
believes in the restorative powers of compassion, love and
laughter, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And what is the great sickness afflicting medicine and the
world? ``Greed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Adams's faults, a lust for money does not seem to be
among them, if a visit to his book-crammed and decidedly modest
town house in suburban Arlington, Va., is any indicator.
</P>
<P>
   He has vowed that whatever money he gets as a result of the
movie (he received an unremarkable fee from the movie makers, but
acknowledged that he now commands speaking fees in the thousands)
will go toward construction of a hospital on a 310-acre tract in
West Virginia, where patients will be treated, free, not just with
medication but with humor and love.
</P>
<P>
   The West Virginia land is owned by the Gesundheit Institute,
which he founded nearly 28 years ago to promote changes in society
as well as changes in medicine. Supported by small donations and
volunteer work, the institute, which at first operated out of
doctors' homes, treated desperately ill people who were drawn to it
by word of mouth, the doctor said. They got drugs and medication,
if they wanted them, but larger doses of friendship and compassion,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I entered medicine to use it as a vehicle for social change,''
he said, allowing that he misses the turbulent 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   At its height, the institute had a score of medical workers,
including Adams and two other doctors. Although he is weak on
specifics, Adams said thousands of people, including many children,
were treated.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1983 he was featured in The Washington Post Sunday
magazine, and suddenly the institute was overwhelmed with queries.
The staff was eventually unable to handle the load, Adams said, so
it stopped seeing patients, and he threw himself into fund-raising
and promotion in order to finance construction of a hospital and
other buildings in West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been able to raise only a fraction of the money
needed, and at this point the site contains only a barnlike
building erected by volunteers. Adams said his ``treatment'' of
patients in recent years has mainly consisted of emotional support,
letter-writing and entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he hoped the movie would generate enough interest,
and thus speaking fees and donations, to reopen and expand the
institute. Hollywood came calling not long after producers got wind
of his book, ``Gesundheit!'' (co-written by Maureen Mylander and
published by Healing Arts Press in 1993), and heard a 1993
interview on National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting ready to live the nightmare of my life,'' Adams
said, fearful that publicity about the movie will distort his
views. He added, though, that the film remained true to his beliefs
while taking some license as biography.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Patch Adams has not just taken a road less traveled. He has
blazed paths that most people would not dream of.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking his journey from Army brat to middle-aged iconoclast
can be difficult, as his eclectic mind wanders from mundane
biographical facts down serpentine detours, stopping now and then
to quote poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Washington, Hunter D. Adams grew up in Germany, Japan,
Texas and the other places his soldier father was stationed. By
high school in Arlington, his father had died and Patch (he does
not know why he got the nickname) had earned a reputation as ``a
math and science nerd'' who got top grades with little effort.
</P>
<P>
   Those years were very difficult for him. Twice in his senior
year he was hospitalized for ulcers. Then he was devastated by the
suicide of a beloved uncle. He himself flirted with suicide,
overdosing on aspirin and standing at the edge of a cliff. His
mother signed him into a mental hospital.
</P>
<P>
   After he got out, he said, he began telephoning strangers at
random, just to make human contact. He said he still does it.
</P>
<P>
   He attended George Washington University and after his junior
year was admitted to the Medical College of Virginia. There, he
said, he was infuriated by teachers who told fledgling doctors to
keep an emotional divide between themselves and patients. They, in
turn, were infuriated when he questioned their pronouncements and
dressed as a clown to make patients laugh.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, he worked part-time as an emergency room
doctor but had already begun to bid farewell to mainstream medicine
and mainstream life. In 1971, he founded the Gesundheit Institute,
so-named because ``gesundheit'' is a wish for good health.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, he has donned paint and pantaloons while
visiting sick adults and children. Each year, he and institute
colleagues go to Russia to entertain orphaned and hospitalized
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to clown where suffering is great,'' he said, though he
admitted that he cannot laugh away all his personal sadness. He and
his wife, Linda, with whom he had two sons, are estranged.
</P>
<P>
   He realizes that his approach to life and medicine is not for
everyone. ``We are not the answer,'' he said. ``We are a stimulant
to ask questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Wade, a senior vice president of the American Hospital
Association, said some of Adams' principles have been embraced in
recent years as doctors have been encouraged to be more open with
patients and hospitals have been designed to make them more
cheerful. ``The world needs more Patch Adamses,'' Wade said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his ideas about life are just plain bizarre, though.
``Wearing underwear on the outside of your clothes can turn a
tedious trip to the store for a forgotten carton of milk into an
amusement park romp,'' Adams wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Adams acknowledged that he is most at home on the fringe. ``I'm
not a blend-in kind of guy,'' he said. Some of his dreams _ free
medical care, and medical care built on total trust and without
malpractice lawsuits _ seem remote. And if his hospital is to
become a reality, it will need people with the cool-eyed business
talents that he disdains.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Adams said that he gladly pays the price for being what
he is, and he bristled at the notion that he might be on the outer
limits of eccentricity. ``Everyone who goes to a job he doesn't
like is a lot weirder than I am,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
