<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9214 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-14 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO RESIGN OR NOT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers   WASHINGTON - Republican congressional
leaders demanding that President Clinton resign to spare the
country further exposure to the ugly impeachment process are not
thinking clearly. Actually, they are not thinking ahead at all.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do they really prefer to run against incumbent President Al Gore
in two years instead of a vice president campaigning in the shadow
of that lying lecher who occupies the White House?
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton resigns, Gore will have the opportunity to stamp his
own identity firmly on the country before the election and draw a
contrast between his own stuffy image and that of scandal-scarred
Bill Clinton. As a sitting president, Gore is likely to escape a
Democratic primary challenge and dominate his party's political
direction in a way he cannot now do as the sidekick of a crippled
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time months earlier in this sorry saga when it was
appropriate for Clinton to resign, before we began drowning in the
sordid details of Oval Office hanky-panky. This columnist was for
it. He might have been saved some shame. It might have helped to
preserve the dignity and power of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But now it is too late. We already know more about this disaster
than we ever cared or needed to know. The damage to his reputation
is done. The damage to the institution of the presidency is already
incalculable.
</P>
<P>
   With the House Judiciary Committee's party-line vote to
recommend impeachment, it became imperative to let the political
process play out to its conclusion. The committee made no serious
attempt to go about its legal duty in a judicious way. After
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr irresponsibly argued for
impeachment by interpreting every contradiction and ambiguity in
behavior and recollection in the case against Clinton, the
committee's GOP members gave him a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   This is pure politics, and it isn't over.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows whether the House will vote by simple majority to
send impeachment charges to the Senate for trial. The Republicans
have the majority. If it is another straight, mindless party-line
vote, they will prevail. That would confirm the extreme
polarization of Washington politics but give us little confidence
that the legislative branch has considered the historic importance
of its decision.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has the support of two thirds of the public and he has
been, in his public duties, a good and sound president. This is a
two-party system, and he is correct not to give up and crawl away
solely on Republican say-so.
</P>
<P>
   The real test of our democratic process is yet to come in the
Senate. To convict him there, a bipartisan two-thirds vote will be
required. The Republicans cannot bring him down by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The president will be able to call and cross-examine witnesses
in his own defense. Months, not just days or hours, will be spent
debating the problem. Minds may actually be changed. An alternative
penalty like censure, forbidden by GOP leaders in the House, may
finally be considered.
</P>
<P>
   And there, in the Senate, the conclusion is likely to be that
while he has undoubtedly sinned, he has not committed the high
crimes for which being booted out of office is the appropriate
remedy. He will remain in office.
</P>
<P>
   Sane legislators would like to avoid this protracted scenario.
But the way out is to impose some penalty short of removal,
involuntarily or not.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republicans manage to hound Clinton out of town
prematurely, voters may well be so upset that they will seek
revenge in the next election, returning both houses of Congress to
Democratic control and electing Gore president in his own right.
Voters have been trying to tell the deaf GOP through polls and last
November's election that they do not want Clinton impeached.
</P>
<P>
   But a backlash is a risk the GOP is foolish enough to take. Some
partisans are blithely contending the public memory is so short
that few voters will remember all this two years from now. No way.
This sex stuff is all too memorable, as it applies to both the
perpetrator and his persecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Do the Republicans forget the outrage against the party's
inflammatory advertising campaign attempting to turn the November
election into a mandate to impeach Clinton? It reduced the GOP
numbers in the House and drove Speaker Newt Gingrich from power. In
their dream of sticking the Democrats with scandal, the Republicans
impaled themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is disgraced. He has repeatedly confessed to wrongdoing.
His own party is demanding a censure that would include painful
financial penalties. Nobody defends what he did. The demands that
he confess to specific criminality are unrealistic. If he did so,
he would be subject to indictment as soon as he is out of office.
</P>
<P>
   In a rational world, censure would do it. He will be gone from
Washington soon enough anyway, and the power of his office has been
diminished.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leadership's cry for Clinton's head is driven by
emotion, not logic. Far better for the party to have a brow-beaten
Clinton in the White House to scorn than a lively Gore to contend
with.
</P>
<P>
   Gore in the White House could also give Clinton the ultimate
protection that Presidents Gerald Ford and George Bush provided GOP
officials in danger of going to jail. Ford pardoned President
Nixon, the unindicted Watergate co-conspirator, and Bush pardoned
Secretary of Defense Caspar Weinberger, indicted for lying to
Congress under oath.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republicans really want to see Clinton behind bars, they
shouldn't be eager to make it easier for Gore to defeat Texas Gov.
George W. Bush or whoever wins the GOP presidential nomination. But
that would require a unified party strategy, which they do not
have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
