<HEADER>
A9225 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES-PLAYERS-CO     12-14 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-PLAYERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Players not surprised 'tough guy' Reeves didn't let on he was in
pain
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The players who go way back with him, to New York or even
Denver, aren't surprised that their coach never disclosed by word
or involuntary gesture his own physical condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk about Iron Mike (Ditka), but Dan's a tough, tough
guy,'' offensive lineman Dave Widell, a former Bronco, said Monday.
Widell knew that Falcons coach Dan Reeves was at that moment
undergoing coronary bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves endured five knee operations by his mid-20s but refused
to give up the game he loved and played at South Carolina and with
the Dallas Cowboys. He underwent two angioplasty procedures to
remove arterial blockages, one in 1990 and another in '91, when he
coached in Denver, hardly missing a beat.
</P>
<P>
   Suffering a familiar burning sensation in his chest and throat
in recent weeks, Reeves must have suspected that he was in trouble,
but his players were not aware of anything until Monday when they
heard the news on the radio or when they arrived at Suwanee for
team meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known him for six years,'' said former Falcons tight end
Bob Kozlowski, a former Giant. ``He never gave us an indication
that he wasn't feeling well. He's a strong, strong guy. He'll fight
through this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, the news really surprised me,'' Kozlowski said. ``I'm
sure none of us saw this coming.''
</P>
<P>
   And Widell said that's how Reeves wanted it. ``He knew how
important this stretch of games was to our team, and he didn't want
anything to affect the way we played. That's how he is.''
</P>
<P>
   And tough as Reeves is, offensive lineman Robert Tobeck said,
``He'll be back on the sidelines before the season's over. I really
expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   For running back Jamal Anderson, the day meant a double blow.
Temporarily, he lost the architect of the offense that has enabled
him to rank second in the NFL in rushing with 1,596 yards. Anderson
said he knows that Reeves will return, but the same can't be said
for fullback Bob Christian, his principal blocker who went on
injured reserve with damage to the medial collateral and anterior
cruciate ligaments of his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``After today, I may have to go see a priest or something,''
Anderson said. ``It's just unbelievable coming off a big game, and
everybody is feeling good, and Dan goes down like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the Falcons on the verge of clinching their divisional
championship, there's no time for a misstep, Anderson said. ``I
don't really know how you deal with it, but you have to go on. You
can't let it stop you.''
</P>
<P>
   For cornerback Ray Buchanan, Reeves' surgery was staggering. ``I
just found out,'' Buchanan said shortly before 1 p.m. ``We were
excited and joyous. We came out (of New Orleans) with a victory
with no clue that this was happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his nature that he didn't say anything,'' Buchanan noted.
``He betrayed no signs of illness. Now, it's up to us to get the
job done until he gets back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
