<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VIEW FROM THE GUNBARREL: A WINTER WONDERLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH LAKE TAHOE, Nev. _ From the brink of the Gunbarrel, you
can scan down the powder-white mountain slopes and beyond across
cobalt-blue Lake Tahoe, and enjoy one of the prettiest winter
scenes available anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Though the winter solstice is still a few days away, the view is
now a testimonial that winter has arrived in force at Tahoe and the
rest of the mountain West, and that the upcoming ski and snowboard
season is set for a stellar year.
</P>
<P>
   Gunbarrel is often the best ski run where to make this
assessment. It is routed on the lower face of Heavenly at South
Tahoe, the West's biggest and most beautiful ski area. From the top
of Gunbarrel, you get a view of nearly the entire Tahoe Basin, and
it answers the fantasy of many skiers and snowboaders who dream of
cutting an edge through fresh powder while being continually
exhilarated by a panorama of California's most beautiful lake.
</P>
<P>
   From the parking lot, anybody can take the Gunbarrel Express
($14 per person) to a cafe with an outside deck with a view set at
8,250 feet. From here, skiers and boarders can jump on the
Stagecoach Express, which will lift you to the top of Heavenly at
10,100 feet. It can be very cold up here, and of course, you dress
for it, but it is the views that provide the lasting chills.
</P>
<P>
   I used to think you had to climb mountains to get views like
this; at Lake Tahoe, for instance, it was climbing Mount Tallac, a
challenging all-day thump-and-grunt to the summit at 9,735 feet.
But in the winter, you get a similar view in relative minutes by
taking the high-speed quads, then skiing down. It seems effortless
and euphoric, and to absorb it all is breathtaking, the expanse of
Tahoe contrasted against the surrounding white mountains.
</P>
<P>
   It is not only the picture of an excellent start to the ski
season at Heavenly and the rest of Tahoe, but also across Northern
California and Nevada. The inside word in the ski industry is that
the combination of a warm December in the northeast yet early snows
in the West has a number of easterners canceling ski holidays in
New England and rebooking for Tahoe and Sun Valley in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   The last two ski areas always open early for winter, Ski
Homewood, set on the west shore of Tahoe, and Badger Pass on
Glacier Point Road in Yosemite, opened too on Friday, making it a
perfect 20-of-20 ski areas in Northern California and Nevada that
are up and running.
</P>
<P>
   Heavenly is always the centerpiece, and with 42 to 60 inches of
snow (depending on elevation), 22-of-26 lifts are open here,
providing access to 74 runs. This has become one the priciest lift
tickets around, $52 a day, and you can add in a ton of extras, like
mid-level mountain cafes and dining (where a small cup of wine and
a beer costs $10). But people are lining up, with the conditions,
views and experience among the best anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkwood on Highway 88 out of South Tahoe was reporting the most
snow of any area, 93 inches on top, nearly eight feet, a huge
amount for so early in the season. Of course, the unofficial
contest among ski areas to report the most snow is always subject
to verification. What is more important are the number of lifts
operating (which is easily documented) and the surface conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Tips: Always have lodging reservations before heading out. If
there are any questions over prices, conditions, access and lift
lines, call the ski area first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
