<HEADER>
A9239 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ADVICE15-COX     12-14 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ADVICE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL EXPERTS SAY CONFESSION CLINTON'S ONLY CHANCE
 &HT;    470 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With support of moderate Republicans threatening to
erode, President Clinton's only chance of avoiding impeachment by
the House of Representatives on Thursday may be a public confession
of guilt, some political experts said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to do that,'' said Dick Morris, the campaign
consultant to whom Clinton has often turned in times of trouble
throughout his political career.
</P>
<P>
   After the president returns Tuesday night from the Middle East,
he should meet as soon as possible with the handful of moderate
Republicans who have signaled their possible opposition to
impeachment, Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   After that, ``he should go out in public in the Rose Garden, and
they should cut a deal for a big fine and censure and an apology
and, most importantly of all, a confession,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   It was a mistake for Clinton to go to the Middle East as the
House Judiciary Committee was approving four articles of
impeachment, Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be here now,'' meeting with the dwindling number of
Republicans who could save his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Morris' advice echoed that of Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn.,
who acknowledged Monday that he does not have ``the same level of
conviction'' he had a week ago for opposing impeachment when it
comes to a vote in the House on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Shays said Clinton needs to declare ``that he did not tell the
truth'' before the grand jury that investigated his affair with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky and to express a
willingness to ``face the court like any other American citizen''
after leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said the president is wrong to be so concerned about
possible criminal prosecution after leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   ``His confession is not going to make any difference after he
leaves office,'' he said. ``They'll either prosecute a former
president, or they won't. He'll either be pardoned, or he won't.
This confession won't matter. But it will matter right now to the
20 or so moderate Republican congressmen.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Pitney, a former Republican strategist who now teaches
political science in California, said he would advise the president
to ``go to church,'' confess that he had ``broken God's law'' and
declare his offense ``far more serious than anything that members
of Congress are debating right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an event would catch the public's attention but would not
contain a specific admission of perjury, Pitney said.
</P>
<P>
   And it would allow Clinton defenders to pose rhetorical
questions such as: ``Which is more important _ a technical
violation of a federal statute or a violation of God's
commandment?'' and ``Now that he's confessed to violating God's
law, why not leave the punishment up to God?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This approach, of course, would be cynical and manipulative,''
Pitney said. ``That's why I think Clinton might take it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
