u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-GIFTS-PARENTS1     12-14 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-GIFTS-PARENTS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On the flip side, kids can find affordable presents for parents
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While it may seem to most kids that Mom and Dad have everything
they could possibly want, believe it or not, they still expect
something for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the stuff you hear parents talking about like golf
clubs and designer clothes is totally out of your price range, and
even if somebody handed you a million dollars, you wouldn't know
where to buy it, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   America Online's Giftfinder helps you find the right gifts by
asking questions about the person you're shopping for. If Mom is a
super-organized bookworm and Dad is a home-improvement-gadget
freak, the Giftfinder will suggest things they might like. From
here, you can surf to other sites for more choice and selection.
</P>
<P>
   But a word of warning before you head off into the world of
online shopping: If you order something online, you need a credit
card to pay for it. If you don't have any plastic, use the Web as a
research tool to check out possible gift ideas and then head to the
nearest retailer to pick the gift up in person and pay with cash or
a check.
</P>
<P>
   Even though most kids are on limited budgets, they can use the
Web to locate a variety of gifts their folks will love for less
than $100.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps while you're reading this, your parents are buying you
some CDs or videos for the holidays. You can return the favor and
get them books or videos on their favorite subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Check out Amazon.com (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .amazon.com) for book and movie suggestions. If you know Dad
loves biographies or Mom loves murder mysteries, here's a great
place to look over new titles, get suggestions and read reviews
from people who have already read the book.
</P>
<P>
   You might also want to check out Amazon.com's custom gift
matcher, which will help you choose gifts based on personal likes
and dislikes. A test drive of the Amazon gift matcher turned up
both books and videos that seemed appropriate for the parents in
question. If your folks have a long commute to work _ it's a good
bet they do _ you might want to try a selection from Audiobooks
(http://www
</P>
<P>
   .audiobooks.com).
</P>
<P>
   Several online sites have compiled their own list of ``can't
miss'' gifts, including REI's Web site (http://www.rei.com), which
is full of great ideas for outdoorsy types of all ages. For golf
lovers, you can check out golf balls at Golfballs.com
(http://www.golfballs.com). For the gourmet cook, there's Digital
Chef (http://www.digitalchef.com), which boasts the largest
selection of utensils and food products on the Web. And if you want
to surprise your family and cook a holiday dish yourself, try the
Web site for the TV Food Network (http://www.foodtv.com).
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
