<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES-NEWCOACH-C     12-14 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-NEWCOACH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves, Brooks relationship helped turned Falcons around
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He strode to the podium with ambivalence. Rich Brooks is a
coach, and the good, ambitious ones want the responsibility of the
head job. But his boss and friend, Dan Reeves, was in the hospital
Monday, making Brooks' walk to a bouquet of microphones difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks did not want to return as a head coach this way. But
that's what he'll be for the Atlanta Falcons until Reeves recovers
from bypass surgery. It could be two weeks or three weeks or four
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us are extremely concerned with Dan's condition,''
Brooks said. ``That being said, we have to go on with the job. We
have to treat Dan's absence as a player out with an injury who you
expect back in a couple of weeks. Everybody else has to pick up the
slack around him and do a better job to make up for his absence.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves made Brooks his assistant head coach and defensive
coordinator after Brooks was fired by the St. Louis Rams after the
1996 season. The two have formed a working relationship that has
helped the Falcons ascend from the doldrums to the top of the NFC
West. More than that, they have become friends.
</P>
<P>
   It was Reeves who threw Brooks a lifeline after the 1996 season.
And it came at a time when Brooks was trying to get over a firing
that was hard to take. He was given only two years with the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I thought we were going in the right direction,'' Brooks
said. ``I was disappointed that I wasn't able to see it through. I
would have liked more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves knew of Brooks from his Giants defensive coordinator Mike
Nolan, who played under Brooks at Oregon. Reeves called Brooks for
advice about the vacant St. Louis job. Brooks told Reeves he'd be
interested in working for him with any team other than the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Falcons hired Reeves, he recalled the complimentary
words Nolan said about Brooks, the way the Rams played under him
and Brooks' interest in working under Reeves. Reeves called. St.
Louis' loss was Atlanta's gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for Rich,'' Reeves said in October.
``He's very honest and clearly can work with anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it was something St. Louis couldn't see. When Brooks
was hired from Oregon, the Rams' hierarchy sought a quick fix
instead of building a solid, young team through the draft and wise
free-agent signings. Brooks was fired before he could put his own
stamp on the team.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the Falcons have prospered on defense, improving in
every category since 1996 under Brooks. The Falcons' defense is
ranked seventh overall, second against the run and second in
takeaways.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks has relied on an aggressive system that allows players to
attack and exploit opponents' weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   The transition from head coach to assistant went about as
smoothly as could be expected for someone who had been in the top
spot for 20 years. ``I don't know if I'd say it was smooth,''
Brooks said. The Falcons would disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said there's a certain amount of pressure and
responsibility that comes with replacing Reeves, who demands
professionalism and effort at all times. He also hopes his
head-coaching experience is beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) I don't know how important that is,'' he said. ``I feel
fortunate that Dan gave me an opportunity to come in and be a part
of what we're doing here. I just hope that I can fill a role.''
</P>
<P>
   Filling that role means producing victories in the last two
games against Detroit and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to finish this thing correctly,'' Brooks said. ``We
want to go on the road in a tough place to play against a very good
team and win at Detroit. Then (we want to come) home against Miami
and (finish) that off with a win. And then we can go into the
playoffs, hopefully with a first-round bye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope . . . to continue what he's done here,'' Brooks
said. ``That's what would make Dan feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
