<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9260 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-GIFTS-TEENS13-     12-14 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-GIFTS-TEENS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A trip online plus a little savvy can equal a great gift for a
finicky teenager.
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Got any really good gift ideas for the teenager in your life? A
gift so perfect the teen in question will maybe even say thank you?
</P>
<P>
   Didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping for teens is harder than shopping for the rest of the
folks on your holiday list. After all, just one dorky gift _ like
mittens or a bathrobe _ might brand you forever as unhip, uncool
and hopelessly out of touch. But never fear, the Net is here to
help you find the ideal gift for your lovable but moody teen.
</P>
<P>
   Smart and sneaky parents are doing their holiday shopping for
teens on the Web. On the Web you can log on, order and log off
before you can say ``Buffy, the Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   But for parents, aunts, uncles, godparents and others who find
themselves working without a net this holiday season, America
Online offers a neat jumping-off point called the Giftfinder. AOL
members can access the service at Keyword: Giftfinder, while
non-AOL members can find it on AOL's Web site at
http://www.aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Giftfinder is designed to guide befuddled shoppers to the ideal
gifts. Users select what type of item they want to buy, answer some
preliminary questions about the recipient, including age, likes and
dislikes, and the Giftfinder offers a suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Brown, AOL's vice president of electronic commerce, says
when using Giftfinder it's important to remember that not every
item is going to be the perfect gift for your finicky teen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tricky thing is you tend to look at the list and go,
`Totally not me,' but if you hit one or two that are right then
it's OK,'' she says. ``The Giftfinder is a great tool and will get
you started in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Another way to divine what teens are thinking is to check out
AOL's teen message boards. One board called Furby: The Greatest or
the Lamest seems to have more ``nay'' than ``yea'' votes for the
overhyped talking toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``C'mon people, we're teenagers,'' said one member. ``Why are
people still into ugly stuffed animals?'' Teens also seem to have
more perspective on Furby madness than many parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ages of the kids who want these dolls range from three to
five,'' remarked one teen. ``So if you can get one, your child
won't even know ...''
</P>
<P>
   The Style message board also offers teens' opinions of what's
hot and what's not all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   From the chatter, it's possible to divine that the Gap, Guess?,
Abercrombie and Fitch, and J. Crew are some of the hottest clothing
shops for teens. So if you absolutely must purchase your teen an
item of clothing, head for the Web sites of these retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Movies and music are sure to charm even the sulkiest teen. Sites
like Reel.com (http://www.reel.com) or Amazon.com have miles of
titles you know kids will love. Reel.com also has a service where
you can rate movies you've seen to find videos you might like.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you really want to play it safe, remember you can
never really go wrong with CDs. Check out CDNow's special section
called the ``MTV CD Lounge.'' Here you'll find MTV's top 20 and
lists of music played on some of the music channel's more popular
shows. CDNow also has a gift registry, which you should check out
to see if anyone you know has made a list and checked it twice.
Remember to check the delivery dates on each site. If you're doing
last-minute shopping online, you may have to pay extra shipping
charges for timely delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Note to teens: You can help out your Web-savvy parents. Bookmark
your favorite e-shopping sites and put them in a folder called
something like ``Jennifer's Christmas Links.'' It's subtle, shows
how resourceful you are and there isn't a parent in the world who
won't want to peek.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
