<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9270 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KROQ-CONCERT-LADN     12-14 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KROQ-CONCERT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ALMOST' ISN'T ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``It's All Been Done,'' sang Canada's high-octane
Barenaked Ladies, perhaps summing up today's rock scene in the
title of one of their hits Friday during the opening night of
KROQ's pair of ninth annual ``Almost Acoustic Christmas'' shows at
the Shrine Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   The 6,000-plus young fans at the popular eight-act event also
responded loudly to radio hits from Blink 182, Offspring, Reel Big
Fish and Sugar Ray, while paying attention to Hole, the Cardigans
and Korn.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day Christmas show, which this year relocated from the
Universal Amphitheatre to the Shrine, always sells out in an
instant, but much of Friday's lineup suffered from monotony.
One-dimensional acts like Korn, Sugar Ray, Blink 182 and Reel Big
Fish offered energetic but ultimately empty sets.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Courtney Love was the night's wild card and musical
highlight, appearing at first unsteady but later showing that first
impression was the result of a calculated pose. Fronting her band
Hole, Love sang ragged but right versions of ``Malibu,''
``Celebrity Skin'' and other pop-rock gems from her new album.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the charismatic guitarist and singer introduced a
friend named Eduardo whom she said she'd ``picked up'' on Hollywood
Boulevard. The fellow, who turned out to be Love's beau, actor
Edward Norton, strummed an acoustic guitar in the background for a
song before giving Love a quick kiss and sprinting off stage.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's other memorable moments came courtesy of
Offspring, who kept the goofing around to a minimum, aside from an
opening gambit that involved two pairs of little people dressed in
s&AMP;m gear for a dance routine to cover versions of Soft Cell's ``Sex
Dwarf'' and Devo's ``Whip It.'' Afterward, the Orange County
quartet churned out a lively set of well-arranged, melodic pop-punk
tunes such as the current hit, ``Pretty Fly (For a White Guy).''
</P>
<P>
   Barenaked Ladies, Reel Big Fish and Blink 182 drew a strong
response from the youngest members of the audience, who welcomed
the groups' jungle-gym stage antics and vapid ditties like Blink's
radio hit, ``Dammit (Growing Up).''
</P>
<P>
   Playing early in the evening, Sweden's Cardigans miscalculated
by concentrating on several slow, droney dirges that kept new
arrivals firmly in their seats or in the lobby's long beverage
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Those who didn't leave the downtown auditorium to race to the
Roxy, where Hole was playing a just-announced after-midnight set,
heard Korn's approximation of Mettalica, minus the material. The
frowning Bakersfield thrash quintet, which enjoyed a huge
commercial breakthrough this year, does one thing over and over, a
hard-on-the-ears single-chord stop-and-start effect that has indeed
all been done many times before.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 1825EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
