<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9272 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      12-14 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Tuesday, Dec. 15. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ As the impeachment vote neared in the
House, several of President Clinton's few Republican supporters
began to waver Monday. Instead of conciliation, the White House
turned to the attack with Vice President Gore denouncing
Congressional Republicans for refusing to allow a vote on censure
and asserting they were thwarting the overwhelming will of the
nation. With photo. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ Since his days as an
undergraduate, Bill Clinton has believed, his oldest friends say,
that he could talk his way out of any predicament. From then until
now, he has usually been right. Suddenly, whether last week in
Washington or this week in the Middle East, Clinton has turned
pensive, wan and remote. BY R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON (Gaza City, Gaza) _ With President Clinton as
their witness, hundreds of former Palestinian terrorists voted here
Monday to rid their organization's charter of any clauses calling
for the destruction of Israel, knocking down a critical roadblock
on the rutted path to peace. By Deborah Sontag. With map.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-LAWYER (Undated) _ How one tobacco lawyer, fearing that
his fees would be slashed because of an overall cap on payments,
pumped up his bill from $50 million in hopes of getting a bigger
piece of the pie. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-DEPORTATIONS (New York) _ In the two years since Congress
passed tough anti-immigration laws to stem the flow of illegal
immigration to the United States, federal authorities have deported
almost 300,000 immigrants to countries all over the world, more
than twice the number of people who were sent back in the two years
before. The unprecedented high number of deportations have been
possible because for the first time the INS has both the
congressional mandate and the financial resources to investigate
and prosecute violators of immigration law, arrest immigrants with
criminal convictions as well as would-be immigrants at the border
and swiftly deport them from the United States _ sometimes in less
than 12 hours. By Mirta Ojito.
</P>
<P>
   NY-VACCO-CONCEDE (Albany, N.Y.) _ State Attorney General Dennis
Vacco on Monday conceded he had lost the disputed Nov. 3 election
to Eliot Spitzer, as a judge tossed the Republican incumbent's
lawsuit out of court.
</P>
<P>
   MATTEL-LEARNING (Undated) _ Mattel Inc., the world's largest toy
maker, said Monday that it had agreed to acquire the Learning Co.
in a $3.8-billion stock deal that would position the company as a
leader in the fast-growing market for educational and entertainment
software.
</P>
<P>
   TARNISHED LAUREATE (Undated) _ A Nobel laureate is accused of
untruths in an autobiography. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EVOLVE (Undated) _ The study of evolutionary convergence has
taken on a new twist, as researchers look beyond such flamboyant
cases of anatomical similarities to detect subtle instances of
convergence among molecules. They have found striking analogies
between the antifreeze proteins that allow two unrelated groups of
fish swimming on opposite ends of the globe to endure in icy
waters. They have detected a bizarre form of antibody protein in
species as different as camels and sharks _ antibodies that look
eerily like each other, and unlike the antibodies of most
vertebrate creatures, yet that evolved along entirely autonomous
pathways. By Natalie Angier.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
