<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9284 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON15-COX     12-14 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IMPEACHMENT TRIAL WOULD HURT THE COUNTRY, CLINTON SAYS
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza _ Battling his Capitol Hill foes even as he
campaigns for Mideast peace, President Clinton said Monday that an
impeachment trial in the Senate would hurt the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe it's in the interest of the United States or
the American people to go through this impeachment process with a
trial in the Senate,'' Clinton said in response to questions
shouted at a photo opportunity with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he referred to his stated willingness to accept censure
for his relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky
and his efforts to mislead the public and court officials about
that relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have offered to make every effort to make any reasonable
compromise with the Congress,'' Clinton said. ''I'm still willing
to do that. That's all I know to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton addressed the issue publicly and directly only once in a
day devoted almost entirely to diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   But some listeners also heard a veiled reference to impeachment
in Clinton's remarks to members of the Palestinian National Council
in this tiny swath of Palestinian-controlled territory.
</P>
<P>
   In a reference to the need for reconciliation between Israelis
and Palestinians after five decades of enmity and bloodshed,
Clinton paraphrased Jesus Christ's admonition to those who would
harshly judge others.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the wisest things He ever said was, 'We will be judged
by the same standard by which we judge; but mercy triumphs over
judgment,''' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The president was apparently referring to Matthew 7:1-2, in
which Jesus says, ``Judge not, that ye be not judged. For with what
judgment ye judge, ye shall be judged: and with what measure ye
mete, it shall be measured to you again.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the president spent very little time Monday dealing
with impeachment. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said at a
news conference that ``the president's not cutting short his
trip,'' due to end Tuesday evening, to return to Washington to deal
with the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, meanwhile, accused House Republicans on
Monday of ignoring public opinion in their drive for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people, by overwhelming majorities, have decided
that notwithstanding that what the president did was wrong, he
should not be impeached and removed from office,'' Gore said at an
appearance with Attorney General Janet Reno in Washington. ``What
they favor instead, is censure, to give the president the
punishment ...they feel is appropriate in this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What the leadership of the Congress has done is to prevent any
kind of compromise along the lines that the American people want to
see. And instead, they threaten to put the country through this
long ordeal that would ensue, and it's not the right thing to do,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart, asked at a news briefing
here how an impeachment trial would harm the country, replied,
``Any student of the markets will say that uncertainty is bad for
the markets. I think a Senate trial lends uncertainty. As far as
the economy as a whole, it can't be a good idea to tie up the
Senate for months on end.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Lockhart said Clinton would not heed calls to
resign in order to avoid a disruptive trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that would send a pretty sorry message to the American
public, that on a partisan basis, a party, because they had the
majority, could remove the president on something that never
reaches the standards of an impeachable offense,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
