<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9286 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MELANOMA-ART-NYT &LR;      12-14 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MELANOMA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING COMPUTERS TO ZOOM IN ON SKIN CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New digital-imaging techniques may soon help doctors search for
early signs of melanoma, the most deadly form of skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, doctors or medical photographers have used
high-end cameras and 35-mm film to take two dozen or so photographs
of the entire bodies of those at high risk for melanoma. Each time
a patient visits, doctor and patient view the slides and compare
present moles with the photographic record. Small changes in moles
may be the first indications of malignancy.
</P>
<P>
   Though patients will still have to endure standing nude or near
nude for the full-body photographs, now a new digital method has
been developed by Dr. James M. Grichnik, an assistant professor at
Duke University Medical Center in Durham, that substitutes a
computer and a CD-ROM for a slide projector and color
transparencies.
</P>
<P>
   Grichnik digitizes the color slides he takes of his patients and
displays the images on his computer monitor by way of a CD-ROM. If
a mole appears questionable, he zooms in for a closer look.
</P>
<P>
   Though the new technology is available only at Duke, Grichnik
said, experts expect digital-imaging techniques will gradually
replace standard photography as more professionals shift to
electronic records.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sylvia Owen, a medical resident in dermatology at Duke
University Medical Center, has used both a slide projector and a
computer monitor and prefers the new system.
</P>
<P>
   ``A patient may have a dozen moles on his shoulder blade _ and
all of them look alike,'' she said. ``Instead of spending five
minutes squinting at slides to make sure I have the right mole, I
can immediately move to a monitor for a full, close-up view. This
is more than high-tech fun; baseline images like these are
lifesaving.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients pay $225 for the CD-ROM, frequently out-of-pocket, as
many policies do not cover dermatologic photography.
</P>
<P>
   Grichnik is marketing the digitizing service to convert color
slides to CD-ROMs as well as the software to display the 33 views
of the patient through a company he set up, the Malachite Corp.
</P>
<P>
   At Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in Manhattan, Dr.
Allan C. Halpern, chief of dermatology, is evaluating several ways
to use digital images. ``We want images that are easily accessed
and manipulated, and that are more available for transmission from
one office to another,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Melanoma is the most lethal form of skin cancer. Although it
accounts for only 5 percent of all skin cancers, it is responsible
for more than three-quarters of all deaths from the disease. Dr.
Darrell Rigel, a professor at New York University Medical Center
and president-elect of the American Academy of Dermatology,
estimates that 7,300 Americans will die of melanoma this year.
``Prompt recognition is critical because this form of cancer
spreads rather early,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those at risk for malignant melanoma include people with a
family history of the disease, fair-skinned people with a tendency
to sunburn easily, and those spending considerable time in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Perry Robins, president of the Skin Cancer Foundation, a New
York public information group, says that in addition to seeing a
doctor for a full-body baseline examination, people should also do
regular self-examinations ``at least on their birthday and a couple
of times a year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
