<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9289 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-BRIBES-COX     12-14 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-BRIBES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta Olympic officials repeat denials they didn't 'buy' '96
Games
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta Olympic officials were aware that influence peddlers
lurked close to International Olympic Committee members, but they
continued to maintain Monday that the city did not ``buy'' the 1996
Games by bribing IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never talked to those people; they never approached me,''
said Billy Payne, president of the Atlanta Committee for the
Olympic Games. ``It's legend in Olympic lore that there are some
influential people. But I couldn't name any of them today. Nor did
we hire anybody. Nor did we pay any IOC members.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne's strident denial came after Marc Hodler, the Swiss
Olympic official who rocked the Olympic movement this weekend with
accusations of vote-buying, repeated his charges Monday at the
close of an Olympic meeting in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Without offering any details, Hodler, 80, linked Atlanta to a
pattern of bribery and other ethical malpractice in the bidding and
selection of at least four Olympic host cities _ the others are
Nagano, Sydney and Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Hodler alleged that four ``agents,'' including one IOC member,
were involved in vote-buying during the past 10 years. He said it
was difficult to imagine ``Atlanta could have been facing this
blackmail'' from agents without ``doing something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This man for 10 years was my friend,'' Payne said, referring
to Hodler. ``I was shocked and surprised, and I did not like being
lumped into a 'well-if-somebody-does-it-everybody-must-do-it' list.
I want folks to know that we acted honorably throughout this
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Battle, who with Payne was on Atlanta's original
volunteer bid committee and who now advises bid cities competing
for Olympics in 2008 and 2012, says even those cities are aware of
``agents'' offering to produce IOC votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these (bidders) say there are people who claim they
can help them with this constituency or that constituency,'' said
Battle, now president of Central Atlanta Progress. ``I'm aware of
people out there who claim they can help you. But I think it is
more influence or helping understand (IOC members) rather than
actually paying them money.''
</P>
<P>
   Battle echoed Payne, noting, ``I know we were never involved in
any of that, whether anybody approached us or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the moment in 1990 that Atlanta was the surprising
selection to host the Games over the favorite _ Athens, Greece _
rumors began that the city must have ``bought'' the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Greek newspapers proclaimed that Coca-Cola, historically a top
corporate Olympic sponsor, used its influence to win the Games for
its hometown. The newspaper Ethnos headlined a story: ``Coca-Cola
beat Athens.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, a German news magazine and an Australian newspaper
carried articles containing accusations that IOC members accepted
bribes for their votes.
</P>
<P>
   The influential magazine Der Spiegel reported in 1991 that
Atlanta Olympic officials offered IOC members gold credit cards,
free heart surgery, scholarships in American universities for their
children and cash bribes of as much as $120,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Der Spiegel's report claimed that Australian and Greek Olympic
officials had a list of 18 IOC members who allegedly took bribes,
although none ever was identified.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations were unsubstantiated and denied by Atlanta
officials, but often they were based loosely on real incidents.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Atlanta committee did provide medical treatment
to David Sibandze, an IOC member from Swaziland, who suffered a
heart attack while visiting the city. ACOG paid for part of his
treatment at Piedmont Hospital, which wrote off the rest as a
courtesy.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 book, ``The New Lords of the Rings,'' British
journalist Andrew Jennings said ACOG paid college tuition for the
stepson of a powerful Russian Olympic official.
</P>
<P>
   Andrei Smirnov, the stepson of then-IOC executive committee
member Vitaly Smirnov, enrolled at the University of Georgia in
1991. Payne, a powerful alumnus and former football player, said he
worked on the younger Smirnov's behalf but never made payments. He
said the assistance never went beyond a few telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine months after the vote, I was advised he was on the way to
the U.S. and his mom and dad were worried about him and wanted us
to help him get into some schools to learn English,'' Payne said
Monday. ``I recommend a lot of people every year for university
admission because I am asked to do so by friends. We helped him as
we would a son of any friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Petelin was enrolled at the university from 1992 through 1994,
but he received no scholarship money from the school or the
University of Georgia Foundation, said Tom Landrum, chief of staff
to university President Michael Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Landrum said school officials did not know the Russian student
was related to an Olympic official until they saw news reports of
the bribery allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Since allegations of vote-buying first arose, the IOC has
tightened its rules on travel, hospitality and gifts. Historically,
bidding cities offered IOC members and their spouses first-class
travel, lavish parties and luxury accommodations _ all in an effort
to tout their city's attributes.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta officials, for example, always paid expenses for IOC
members' trips to the city, including air fare, meals and lodging
at the Marriott Marquis. They also arranged housing in private
homes, threw parties and offered small gifts, such as silver mint
julep cups and Cabbage Patch dolls. Payne also hosted golf outings
to the fabled Augusta National Golf Club, which he was promoting as
a site for Olympic golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like any other business venture; you do a certain amount
of entertainment and building friendships,'' Battle said. ``These
don't involve bribes but do involve bringing them to your hometown.
And gift-giving is always going to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We in Atlanta have wonderful memories of our Olympic
experience,'' Payne said. ``Those memories will not be eroded by
unfounded accusations leveled at our integrity. We did nothing
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 1837EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0292 </DOCNO>
