<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-REPUBLICANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GOP MODERATES ENDORSE IMPEACHMENT; SHAYS SAYS HE IS MULLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton got jolting news on the
impeachment front Monday when two undecided moderate House
Republicans announced they will vote for impeachment while Rep.
Christopher Shays, R-Conn., said he is reconsidering his support of
the president.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by the two moderates _ Reps. Frank LoBiondo of
New Jersey and Jim Walsh of New York _ was significant because the
outcome of the House impeachment vote later this week hinges on a
small group of moderate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   LoBiondo said he will vote for impeachment because ``I cannot in
good conscience allow the nation's chief law enforcement officer to
violate the law without consequences.'' Walsh said the prospect of
a Senate impeachment trial was less unseemly than the importance of
the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Another moderate, Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., said he will
disclose his decision on impeachment at a news conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Shays, previously a strong critic of impeachment, said he was
having second thoughts because he was ``troubled by the president's
statements and his continued inability to tell the American people
the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays said he would vote against impeachment if he were voting
today but that he wants to hear what his constituents say at a
community meeting Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   After Shays said he wanted to meet with the president to discuss
those views, the White House arranged a meeting after Clinton
returns Wednesday from his trip to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Shays was one of five Republican House members who had announced
their opposition to impeachment. The others are Reps. Peter T.
King, Amo Houghton Jr. and Jack Quinn of New York, and Mark Souder
of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he appears to be wavering, Shays joined some two dozen
uncommitted Republican House members whose undeclared sentiments
have made the outcome of the impeachment vote impossible to
predict.
</P>
<P>
   The House is scheduled to begin debate Thursday on impeachment
charges that Clinton committed perjury, obstruction of justice and
abuse of power in connection with the coverup of his affair with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have a 228-207 majority in the House where a
majority vote in favor of one or more articles of impeachment would
trigger a Senate trial. If convicted by a two-thirds majority in
the Senate, Clinton would automatically be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Shays, 53, who just won his 7th term, is known for his
independent stances. He was a key sponsor of the first major piece
of legislation to become law after the Republicans claimed control
of Congress in 1994. The Congressional Accountability Act, part of
the GOP ``Contract with America,'' required that Congress follow
many of the same health, labor and civil rights laws that apply to
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Shays occasionally joins Democratic House members to vote for
environmental protection and abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Shays' press secretary Seth Amgott said the congressman hasn't
felt pressured on the impeachment issue except for his own desire
to do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows he's not going to make any friends with this,''
Amgott said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republican moderates in the House face possible
conservative challengers in the primary election if they don't
support impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The fear of enraging GOP party activists is probably greater
than that of alienating moderate voters, said Marshall Wittmann,
director of congressional relations at the conservative Heritage
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's party politics vs. general election politics,'' Wittmann
said. ``Party activists will have a longer memory than the general
electorate.''
</P>
<P>
   For the wavering moderate Republicans whose votes will determine
the fate of the president later this week ``the pressure doesn't
get any higher than this,'' Wittmann said. ``It's definitely not a
stress-free holiday season for them.''
</P>
<P>
   To swing moderates like Shays away from impeachment, Clinton
``is going to have to acknowledge that he lied or perjured himself
before the American people if not the grand jury,'' Wittmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Also announcing their support for impeachment were conservative
Republican Reps. Zach Wamp of Tennessee, Charles Bass of New
Hampshire and Rick Hill of Montana.
</P>
</TEXT>
