<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9306 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      12-14 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINE LEADERS RESPOND TO CLINTON URGINGS FOR PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA - President Bill Clinton Monday delivered the strongest and
most compassionate message ever by an American president to the
Palestinian people and convinced their leaders to move forward for
peace.
</P>
<P>
   With the first U.S. leader to set foot in Palestinian territory
at their side, hundreds of top Palestinian officials met a key
Israeli demand by reaffirming the annulment of sections of the
Palestinian charter that called for the destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``By revoking them once and for all, you have sent a powerful
message not to the government, but to the people of Israel,''
Clinton told a packed audience of the Palestine National Council
and other Palestinian officials. ``You will touch people on the
street there. You will reach their hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the audience of about 1,000 stood with their hands
raised to signify a clear revocation of the offending language. In
doing so, they cleared away one of the major hurdles blocking the
next Israeli troop withdrawal in the West Bank scheduled to take
place Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Clinton's dramatic trip to convince Israelis and
Palestinians of the benefits from the peace agreement he helped
forge at the Wye River Plantation in Maryland in October seemed to
be worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   The focus now shifts to the Israelis. But there were signs that
the move may not have persuaded Israel to resume its troop
withdrawals from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very important step. I welcome it. It is a positive
step,'' Netanyahu said at a press conference after the vote.
``That's not enough, there have to be acts.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis insist that Arafat, among other things, must also
clearly retract his repeated assertion that he will unilaterally
declare an independent state on May 4, the day that would mark the
end of the interim peace process begun in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A three-way meeting among Clinton, Palestinian Authority
President Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu is scheduled for early Tuesday at the Erez checkpoint
separating Israel and Gaza to strengthen further the fragile peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye agreement is a land-for-security deal that calls for
Israel to cede an additional 13 percent of the West Bank, which it
captured from Jordan in 1967, and for Palestinians to intensify the
fight against terrorism directed at Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had originally hoped that this trip would be a
celebration of Wye, which broke an 18-month deadlock in the
process. But it was transformed into a rescue mission to salvage
Wye as relations between the Israelis and Palestinians deteriorated
in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dark shadow of impeachment that threatens his
presidency, Clinton delivered what many observers considered one of
his most eloquent and forceful foreign policy speeches. With a firm
sense of evenhandedness, he addressed the crowd of aging guerilla
fighters, old men in red and white kaffiyahs, younger men in
business suits, Muslim clerics in turbins and Christian leaders in
black vestments. There was a noticeable absence of women in the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palestinians must recognize the right of Israel and its people
to live safe and secure lives today, tomorrow, and forever. Israel
must recognize the right of Palestinians to aspire to live free
today, tomorrow, and forever,'' Clinton said to thunderous
applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must acknowledge that neither side has a monopoly on pain
or virtue,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have reaffirmed the fact that you now intend to share this
piece of land without war with your neighbours forever... They have
heard you, they have heard you.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and they must now determine what territory you will have.
Will it be grudging and mean-spirited...or will it be generous and
open?'' he asked the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the speech was remarkable in its candid recognition
of the difficulty Palestinians face in their daily life: ``For too
many Palestinians, lives are hard, jobs are scarce, prosects are
uncertain and personal grief is great.''
</P>
<P>
   These words would have been unthinkable from an American
president a mere a decade ago, when the United States would not
even allow its officials to talk directly to Arafat's Palestine
Liberation Organization.
</P>
<P>
   An exuberant Arafat introduced the president at the Palestinian
Authority's Shawwa Center, calling Clinton ``a president whom we
love and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   But his speech quickly turned to condemnations of Israeli
settlement expansion in East Jerusalem and in the West Bank and
Gaza. He also deplored the continued detention of Palestinian
prisoners in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our sons to return to their homes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat repeated Palestinian intentions to form a state with
Jerusalem as its capital but, importantly, he avoided previous
statements to do so next May.
</P>
<P>
   The day began with the president's helicopter descending over
the dust, palm trees and ramshackle refugee camps of Gaza - one of
the poorest and most crowded places on earth.
</P>
<P>
   After landing at the newly opened Gaza International Airport,
Clinton, accompanied by his wife Hillary and daughter Chelsea,
received a red-carpet welcome. Enormous U.S. and Palestinian flags
hung from the control tower at Gaza airport.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential motorcade sped along the Mediterranean coast
and through a security corridor to the conference center where
Clinton was to speak. Some 10,000 Palestinian police, clad in blue
fatigues and armed with automatic rifles, blanketed the city to
protect the Clinton entourage. They were joined by scores of
American Secret Service and CIA agents also discreetly stationed
along the route.
</P>
<P>
   The motorcade passed young children waving Palestinian and
American flags. There were banners that read, ``Bill Clinton:
Welcome to Palestine.'' And placards that stated in bold white on
black lettering ``We have a dream: Free Palestine.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Plaza of the United Nations, an elementary school band
dressed in red plodded through an spirited, if off-key, rendition
of the Star Spangled Banner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a great moment,'' said Ayman H'maida, 33, an
electrician, who stood with his 4 year-old son, Yusef, who waved a
small plastic American flag stapled to a stick. ``The president of
the greatest country in the world is visiting us for the first
time.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why American flags were burned during anti-American
and Israel rallies just a few weeks ago yet now are waved on the
streets, H'maida answered, ``Those who were burning the flags don't
understand what peace means. They are off the track of those of us
walking toward peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazen Said, 22, was an active participant in the intifada
uprising a decade ago and in rallies where he took part in the
burning of the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I burned the flag because the US has always supported Israel
against the Palestinians. They never put real pressure on Israel to
secure human rights of Palestinans. When I see the kids waving
American flags now, I see a start, a new beginning of
American-Palestinian relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Marwan Kanafani, Arafat's spokesman and a Palestine National
Council member, said, ``This opens a new chapter between the
Palestinian people and America. We have never had a president speak
to us, our concerns, to the realities our life in this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanafani added, ``His words and our vote tonight prove that the
peace process is not in jeapordy because of a lack of US commitment
or a failure on our part to live up to the agreement. It's in
jeopardy because Netanyahu doesn't want to implement it.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were many Palestinian leaders who boycotted the vote,
showing that bitter feelings still exist.
</P>
<P>
   Younis Al Jarou, a central committee member of the Popular Front
for Liberation of Palestine, boycotted the ratification because it
was ``convened at Israel's behest.''
</P>
<P>
   He also sharply criticized the Palestine National Council as an
amorphous body whose very size remains unclear and which operates
without clearly posted procedures or rules of debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the voting today in the PNC will not satisfy Israel,'' Al
Jarou claimed to explain why he was not participating. ``They will
keep asking for more. No one now is saying we should throw Israel
into the sea, but they should not throw us into the sea either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
