A9308 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-WHISTLEBLOWER-H     12-14 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-WHISTLEBLOWER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES THAT WHISTLE-BLOWER CAN SUE COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: FILED in ``f'' and ``w'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a decision that could help whistle-blowers, the
Supreme Court ruled Monday that a former employee of a home health
care company could sue the firm for damages after he claimed he was
fired for helping uncover its Medicare fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling unanimously in favor of the employee, Michael A. Haddle,
the high court overturned two lower court decisions, which said
that state law permits an employer to fire workers without a reason
so long as they don't have employment contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Workers without such contracts, who make up a large percentage
of white-collar workers, are known as ``at-will'' employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hold that the harm alleged by (Haddle) ... has long been a
compensable injury and we see no reason to ignore that tradition in
this case,'' Chief Justice William Rehnquist wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   Haddle was a Medicare reimbursement expert for Healthmaster, an
Augusta, Ga., company that became the target of a federal Medicare
fraud investigation in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   On June 21, 1995, Healthmaster fired Haddle, allegedly because
he cooperated with federal authorities and because it wanted to
deter him from testifying in the pending criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which had annual Medicare revenue of nearly $100
million, and three of its top executives eventually were charged in
a 133-count indictment. The owner, who pleaded guilty to 10 felony
counts, was sentenced to 33 months in prison and ordered to pay
$11.5 million in restitution. The two other executives also
received prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Haddle filed suit against the company using a
Reconstruction-era law that protects federal witnesses from
intimidation. He said the 1871 law was the only recourse for
private employees without job contracts who are fired for
cooperating with federal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Haddle's case was dismissed by a federal district judge and
later by the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. Both ruled that
Healthmaster officials could not have conspired to take away
Haddle's job because he didn't have a legal right to employment in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The circuit court said that Haddle needed to show that
Healthmaster conspired to ``injure'' him or his property before he
could be allowed to use the 1871 law.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court disagreed, ruling that ``intimidation or
retaliation against witnesses in federal-court proceedings'' was
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that (Haddle's) employment is not property does not
mean that loss of his employment may not injure him,'' the court
said, adding it had found ``ample'' evidence that the ``conspiracy
here may give rise to a claim for damages.''
</P>
<P>
   Haddle's lawyer, Charles C. Stebbins, called the court's
decision a victory for his clients and other white-collar workers
who cooperate with federal investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling should send a strong message that people who help
the government and give truthful testimony in court will be
protected from being fired for doing their duty,'' Stebbins said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 1844EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
