A9310 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      12-14 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING DISTANT QUASARS  
 RETHINKING MARS  
 VULCANOLOGY FROM AFAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An ambitious effort to create a detailed map of part of the
universe has borne its first fruit, discovering the most distant of
all quasars. In fact, the project, the Sloan Digital Sky Survey,
has discovered three of the four most distant quasars, all in the
first few months of its operation.
</P>
<P>
   Quasars are about the size of our solar system but have a
brightness equal to 100 galaxies or more. The objects are not
completely understood, but are thought to have a massive black hole
at the center that draws gas and dust into it. The brightness is
the result of the extreme gravitational forces acting on the
material.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers measure distance by calculating how far toward the
red end of the spectrum light from an object has shifted. The
greater this red shift, the farther away the object is. The most
distant quasar has a red shift of 5.0; it is so far away that the
light reaching Earth began its journey when the universe was only a
billion years old. (It is not the most distant object yet
discovered, however. That distinction is held by a galaxy with a
red shift of 5.64.)
</P>
<P>
   The Sloan Survey, a collaboration of researchers at eight
institutions, plans to create a three-dimensional map of a quarter
of the sky. It uses two telescopes at an observatory in southern
New Mexico, one that performs the initial scans and another for
follow-up studies. Among other things, the project aims to
determine the red shifts for about a million galaxies and 100,000
quasars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first detailed topographical survey of the north pole of
Mars has been completed, and the results may force some changes in
theories about the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Using a laser altimeter aboard the Mars Global Surveyor
spacecraft, a team of researchers has determined that although the
Martian ice cap is about 10,000 feet thick, it sits in a bowllike
depression that is about 16,000 feet below the average elevation at
the equator.
</P>
<P>
   That poses problems for a common theory about water on Mars,
that it traveled from the pole to the equator in a subsurface
aquifer system. The new elevation data show that it would have been
practically impossible for such transport to occur.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also showed that the ice cap is smaller than
previously thought, with a volume about half that of the Greenland
ice sheet. Determining how much water there is on Mars, and what
happened to it, is crucial to unlocking the planet's history. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vulcanologists like to sample the gases produced by volcanoes,
``reading'' them for hints of the activity within. But gathering
gas samples in or near an active volcano can be, and has been,
lethal.
</P>
<P>
   Two reports in a recent issue of Nature, however, demonstrate
that remote sensing of volcanic gases is now possible. The studies,
at Popocatepetl in Mexico and Mount Etna in Italy, make use of an
instrument called a Fourier-transform infrared spectrometer.
</P>
<P>
   The spectrometer detects infrared light as it passes through,
and is absorbed by, a plume of volcanic gas. Because different
gases absorb different frequencies of light, the composition of the
plume can be determined.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is finding a source of infrared light. Hot
rocks or lava are one such source, and occasionally scientists have
gotten lucky and located lava in the right place to take readings.
Other times an infrared lamp has been used, although placing one in
the field is often as hazardous as trying to sample gases.
</P>
<P>
   The two new techniques find their infrared in the sky. The Etna
researchers made use of the sun as a source, and were able to
analyze the volcano's plume from about seven miles away. The
scientists at El Popo, as the Mexican volcano is known, compared
readings of the plume against the sky versus those of the sky alone
to do their analysis from up to 10 miles away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
