<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUDGE SCOLDS MICROSOFT LAWYER
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Microsoft attorney pressed a computer expert
Monday to admit that Windows 98 is a single, integrated product,
but U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson scolded the lawyer
for trying to bait the witness into making a careless error.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange took place during the cross-examination of Edward
Felten, a Princeton University computer science professor. Felten
repeatedly told the court that Microsoft had combined different
computer functions into four Windows files, making it impossible to
completely delete its Internet Explorer browser software.
</P>
<P>
   But in a 30-minute video, Felten showed the court how he was
able to write a 600-word program that ``disenabled'' Internet
Explorer without adversely affecting the Windows operating system.
The program made it possible to install Netscape Communications
Corp.'s competing browser without having Internet Explorer
occasionally appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of no reason why Microsoft was technologically
compelled to design things this way without consumer choice,''
Felten said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft attorney David Heiner insisted repeatedly that Felten
address the issue of whether it was possible to completely remove
all computer code related to the Internet Explorer browser
functions.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson interrupted, saying, ``He's told you a dozen times,
maybe more, that some of this code is related to browser
functionality and some of it is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems you are trying to get the witness to commit some slip
of the lip, and I think that is an inappropriate
cross-examination,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer moved onto another trouble spot when he asked Felten
whether his computer program caused problems with Microsoft's
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Felten charged that his program had not caused any problems with
Windows operating system until Dec. 4. Then he said Microsoft
changed functions in its Windows Update page on the Internet, which
allows users to download the software updates over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``These changes occurred after I gave them the source code for
my program,'' Felten said.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Jackson intervened: ``You mean you gave them the source
code to your program and then they made changes to their operating
system?''
</P>
<P>
   Several minutes later, Heiner concluded his questioning and the
judge called a recess, ending Felten's cross-examination a day
earlier than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Mark Murray said Felten was confused about
changes made to the Windows Update page. The problems arose, he
said, because the company on Dec. 4 had posted a test version of
Internet Explorer 5.0, not because the company was trying to
sabotage Felten's program.
</P>
<P>
   Felten's testimony has been billed as key to the government's
case because the Department of Justice and 19 states have accused
Microsoft of using its dominance in the operating system market to
also corner the browser market.
</P>
<P>
   In a federal appeals court case this summer, it was ruled that
Microsoft could bundle its browser into an earlier version of
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The lead government attorney, David Boies, said this trial is
focusing on another aspect of antitrust law: Whether Microsoft is
using its dominance in operating system to force consumers to use
their browser by tying it to the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is whether the consumer can be given a choice,''
Boies said. ``And if a government witness can do it, then we feel
certain that Microsoft with all its software engineers can do it _
maybe even better.''
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's attorney, John Warden, bitterly disagreed. ``All
this witness has done is remove the ignition key. He hasn't removed
the browser functionality at all.'' ``I expect the government to
come up with some competent proof that these are, in fact, two
different products. That hasn't been done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is scheduled to continue Tuesday and Wednesday with
the government's presentation of its final videotaped depositions,
including parts of the testimony of Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
