<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9338 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     12-14 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD LYING APPLICANT BE GIVEN BENEFIT OF DOUBT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Question: We interviewed a very good applicant,
but when we took references, we found that he lied about being a
college grad. He did attend the college, but never graduated. We
asked him about this and he immediately apologized and said he had
never done this before. We need his expertise, and everything else
checked out perfectly. Do you think we should make him an offer?
D.A.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: In a word, everything checked out perfectly except this
applicant's honesty. The fact is that he apparently had no
difficulty looking you in the eye and boldly lying about his past.
Since he did this so well, it is possible that he has a good deal
of experience in this area.
</P>
<P>
   If you do hire him, you will never forget about this incident
and it's going to be difficult to fully trust him. He has
demonstrated that he is capable of lying quite effectively and if a
question arises concerning matters of ethics, theft, or
credibility, it will be difficult to give him the benefit of the
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of the larger picture, you need to decide how much
lying is tolerable in your company. At one end of the continuum,
you can conclude that the applicant apologized, learned the error
of his ways and deserves a chance. At the other end, you can take
the position that lying in your organization is absolutely
unacceptable. It will be quite telling to see where your
organization lies on this continuum.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The yearly evaluation is coming up, and I have a strong
feeling I am going to get a bad review because I don't get along
with my manager. He always gives me a hard time. For example, I was
10 minutes late the other day and he made a big deal about it, but
he said nothing to another employee who was late. Do I have a right
to refuse to sign my performance review? R.P.
</P>
<P>
   A: Before focusing on whether you should sign your performance
review, you should focus on a more important sign, namely the
working relationship with your manager. You do not need to wait for
a yearly evaluation to evaluate what is going on. The two of you
need to sit down, independent of the evaluation, and discuss the
work-related problems and the possible steps that you both can take
to correct them.
</P>
<P>
   As for signing the review, your signature typically does not
mean that you accept every point in the review as being an
undeniable truth. Rather, your signature indicates that you have in
fact read the review. Most performance review systems provide a
space for you to add your own comments. If there is no such space,
you can tell your manager that you will be writing a response to
the evaluation and you would like it included in the file. If you
write such an addendum, focus on the facts of your performance, and
not on the way your manager may have favored a co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   You might also suggest that your company consider using a
360-degree feedback process in which the employees evaluate their
supervision. This approach has numerous advantages, one of which is
that favoritism quickly falls out of favor.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been posting memos and announcements on the company
bulletin board, and in recent months someone, or perhaps more than
one person, has been marking them up and adding snide comments that
are supposed to be funny. I have heard that this is part of humor
at work, but I see it as destructive. Is this type of thing
acceptable now? K.G.
</P>
<P>
   A: Although humor at work is a growing trend, your letter may
also indicate another growing trend: employee sabotage. Humor at
work is supposed to be uplifting and clever. It does not mean
destroying company property or ridiculing a company's programs.
</P>
<P>
   Sabotage typically comes from disgruntled employees. Perhaps
there has been a recent downsizing and they feel insecure, perhaps
the anticipated bonuses are not going to happen, or maybe the
employees feel that the company has treated them inequitably. As a
result of these kinds of developments, they are striking back.
</P>
<P>
   It may be worthwhile to have more direct communication with the
employees in order to develop a clearer picture as to how they feel
about the company. To the extent that significant levels of
dissatisfaction are found, there are probably actions that
management can take to correct at least some of them.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it will also be important for the employees to
understand that sabotage of any kind is not going to be tolerated.
In a word, employees who are working against the company are not
going to be working for the company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
