u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRINITY-OPPENHEIMER-B     12-14 0287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRINITY-OPPENHEIMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRINITY TO JOIN FORCES WITH OPPENHEIMERFUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trinity Investment Management Corp., a private money management
firm whose Boston-based owner and chairman is seeking to retire,
agreed Monday to be acquired by OppenheimerFunds Inc., a New
York-based mutual fund firm.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the deal was not disclosed, but financial sources
put the sale price at around $175 million. The transaction, typical
for smaller investment companies whose owners are seeking to
convert their assets into cash before retiring, allows Trinity to
retain its name, staff, offices, and computer-driven investing
style.
</P>
<P>
   The deal marries Trinity's $8.2 billion in accounts managed for
institutions with OppenheimerFunds' $97 billion in mutual fund
assets, and paves the way for Trinity chairman Stanford Calderwood,
78, to retire. Trinity will be an independent unit of
OppenheimerFunds' institutional money management arm, Harbor View
Asset Management.
</P>
<P>
   Rumored for months, the deal makes Trinity ``the centerpiece of
our institutional money management effort,'' said Len Darling,
executive vice president of OppenheimerFunds.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction involves a portion of cash paid up front and a
series of payouts to Trinity's six other shareholders over five
years, according to Trinity spokesman Richard Tucker. The
executive-shareholders will continue to run the company, while
Calderwood, who had owned around 50 percent of the firm, would exit
the business.
</P>
<P>
   OppenheimerFunds, the nation's 13th largest fund firm, is a unit
of Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Co. of Springfield, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
