<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTEL-PLAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MATTEL, KEEPING UP WITH THE TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mattel Inc.'s plan to buy Learning Co. and establish a larger
presence in the educational and entertainment software business is
just the latest step for a toy company and a toy industry that are
trying to reinvent themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, the world's largest toymaker announced its
proposed $3.2 billion acquisition on the same day that it shocked
Wall Street by saying that sales of its famous Barbie doll products
could fall 12 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Learning Co. acquisition could further
California-based Mattel's strategy to transform itself into a sort
of hybrid toy-and-entertainment software company that is less
dependent on traditional toys such as Barbie and on
brick-and-mortar retailers such as Toys ``R'' Us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Age compression'' may be a key phrase in understanding why
Mattel wants to buy an educational-software company known for such
products as ``Where in the World is Carmen Sandiego?'', and the
game ``Myst.'' Or maybe the operative word is ``KAGOY.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an acronym for `kids are getting older younger,''' said
Diane Cardinale, the assistant communications director for the Toy
Manufacturers of America, an industry trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Once a child would get a Barbie doll or a G.I. Joe action-figure
at age 4 or 5, then play with it until he or she turned 10 or 11.
No more. Today's computer-savvy children quickly tire of rag dolls
and toy soldiers. At an early age, they want educational software
such as the CD-ROMs made by the Learning Co. or video games from
the likes of Sony and Nintendo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are going on the computer in kindergarten,'' said editor
Chris Byrne of Playthings Marketplace, an industry newsletter.
``Kids are giving up traditional toys by 6 or 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattel chairman and chief executive Jill Barad acknowledged as
much in a conference call with Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the process of transforming ourselves from a
traditional toy company into a global children's products
company,'' said Barad, who noted that the acquisition of Learning
Co. could mean that nearly a quarter of Mattel's sales could come
from interactive products.
</P>
<P>
   That was the good news. The bad news, which caused Mattel's
stock price to plunge, was that sales for Mattel's traditional toys
have been nearly flat. This holiday season, consumers seem
reluctant to pay full price for traditional toys, noted Salomon
Smith Barney analyst Jill Krutick.
</P>
<P>
   After US consumers shelled out $22.6 billion for traditional
toys in 1997, the toy manufacturers group was expecting a 1998 gain
of 3 percent, with just more than half the annual total coming
around the holidays. But in light of Mattel's announcement, that
forecast may be too optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sales of video games, which are measured separately
from traditional toys, are on pace to jump 32 percent from the 1997
total of $5.1 billion, according to the NPD Group, a research firm
based in Port Washington, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   For educational and entertainment software, the kind made by the
Learning Co., NPD said sales will rise about 4 percent in 1998,
according to Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   With the sales for traditional toys cooling, toymakers want to
gain a bigger presence in the hot educationalandentertainment
market, just as brick-and-mortar retailers are looking for ways to
avoid getting stuck with unwanted inventory.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Toys ``R'' Us has revamped its ordering
policies. Faced with competition from giant discounters such as
Wal-Mart and Target, Toys ``R'' Us wants to be lean and mean.
</P>
<P>
   That has translated into fewer orders to its chief suppliers,
Mattel and Hasbro Inc., the industry's No. 2 toy maker. In recent
months, both Mattel and Hasbro have complained that new Toys ``R''
Us inventory policies have squeezed their profits.
</P>
<P>
   For Hasbro, of Pawtucket, R.I. the 1999 outlook may be brighter.
Two of its toys are holiday hits, Furby and Teletubbies, and movie
licensing agreements have it poised to exploit next year's release
of the first of three ``Star Wars'' sequels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think Hasbro has solid underlying product momentum,'' said
analyst Krutick, who covers both Hasbro and Mattel.
</P>
<P>
   As Mattel looks to the future, the acquisition of the Learning
Co., of Cambridge, Mass., could help with its goal of lessening its
dependency on bricks-and-mortar retailers such as Toys ``R'' Us.
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Co. sells some of its software directly to schools
and some of its product directly to consumers through toll-free
telephone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   And the maker of the American Girl doll series, another recent
Mattel acquisition, relies heavily on catalog sales.
</P>
<P>
   Distribution aside, Toy Book editor Jim Silver sees Mattel's
purchase of an educational software company as a smart move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big problem for the industry is that children are growing
up much faster,'' he said. ``The toy companies are looking for ways
to hold onto kids as long as they can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
