<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9363 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAR-COX     12-14 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Astronomers see seeds of life in star's makeup
</P>
<P>
   By Dick Stanley
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Genesis has one version of creation, and astronomy has another.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomy says we all come from supernovas, dying stars whose
explosions seeded what became Earth and us with calcium, carbon and
the 101 other chemical elements that we share with the sun, planets
and stars. But what kind of supernovas is a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Now, University of Texas astronomer Chris Sneden and colleagues
elsewhere believe they have found the first solid clue to the
identity of our progenitors. It's a unique star that may have been
one of the first recipients of the seeding from a class of
supernovas that could have been the granddaddies of us all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neat stuff,'' said J. Craig Wheeler, a UT astronomer whose
speciality is supernovas. ``I find it stimulating.''
</P>
<P>
   Sneden and colleagues from the University of Oklahoma and
Carnegie Observatory in Pasadena, Calif., found their special star
during a routine study of some old stars in a thin halo surrounding
our Milky Way galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   Sneden's specialty is calculating the amount of elements present
in a star, as revealed by the signatures of chemicals in the star's
electromagnetic radiation. His brand of stellar accounting helps
scientists like Wheeler figure out what the supernovas that seeded
the stars were like before they blew up.
</P>
<P>
   Though supernovas are believed to be routine events in the long
life cycles of stars, their origins remain elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons (astronomers) got so excited about the
supernova in 1987 in the Large Magellanic Cloud galaxy,'' Sneden
said, ``was because for the first time ever we knew the star
beforehand.''
</P>
<P>
   Supernovas occur when a star's fusion furnace starts to run out
of fuel and begins to consume the star itself. The resulting
explosion creates a cloud of gas and chemical elements, called a
nebula, which during the course of billions of years coalesces to
become new stars that will begin the cycle anew.
</P>
<P>
   Other remnants of supernovas, meanwhile, turn into weird things
like pulsars, neutron stars or black holes.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers believe the nebula that became our sun and its
planets was made by many supernovas throughout the history of our
Milky Way galaxy. But what kind of supernovas is the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you try and figure out the different element proportions
in the solar system and what kinds of supernovas were responsible,
you can't,'' Sneden said.
</P>
<P>
   Until, perhaps, now. The star that Sneden and colleagues found
``has a distribution of elements that looks an awful lot like the
element distribution in the solar system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The star has the unromantic designation of CS 22892-052. CS
stands for Campanas Star, meaning it was first charted by
astronomers at Las Campanas Observatory near Santiago, Chile.
</P>
<P>
   The star isn't impressive looking. It's just one of the
thousands of bright dots in the night sky. It's what's inside it
that makes it unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was really strange and noticeable about it right away,''
Sneden said, ``was there were more of the exotic, heavy elements
(uranium, lead, mercury, etc.) than we had any right to expect in
such an old star.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from its amount of thorium, a radioactive element that
loses half its atoms every 14 billion years, the researchers dated
the star at between 13 billion and 16 billion years old.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the sun is only about 4.5 billion years old.
</P>
<P>
   After analyzing the star's proportions of heavy elements, the
researchers concluded that they could only have come from a
particular kind of supernova _ and a nearby one at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to be a local thing that donated this freakishly high
number of heavy elements,'' Sneden said. ``We've never been able to
say that about a star before.''
</P>
<P>
   Sneden and his colleagues have applied for observing time on the
Hubble Space Telescope to try to learn more about their star. They
hope to use it as a basis for the more complicated problem of
figuring out what kind of supernovas made the chemical elements in
our solar system.
</P>
<P>
   But the supernova itself, a possible predecessor of our ancestor
supernovas, is long gone.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler speculates that it probably was a star of the necessary
size to turn into a neutron star after the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's floating around in intergalactic space somewhere,''
Wheeler said. ``But we have no idea where.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
