<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-GROCERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
H-E-B HITS IT OFF WITH MEXICAN GROCERY CUSTOMERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JENALIA MORENO 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTERREY, Mexico _ The store is as bare bones as possible.
</P>
<P>
   No background music. No high-priced, fancy deli. No glossy
displays at the end of each aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Floors are concrete, and staples like cereal boxes and flour are
stacked ceiling-high.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the shoppers stream into H-E-B's new Economax here as if it
were giving away food.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need marble floors to sell tomatoes,'' said Miguel
Angel Suarez Arellano, the store's manager.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. grocers have been crossing the border into Mexico for
years. But it's only been since last year, when the economy
stabilized, that grocery chains have made their first real gains.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is an enormous market, ripe for the picking: 96 million
consumers who spend 3.5 times more of their disposable income on
groceries than Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most aggressive entrant into the Mexican market is
San Antonio-based grocery chain H-E-B, which in 1999 plans to open
seven more stores south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S.-based grocery stores are doing quite well,'' said Chuck
Gilmer, editor of the Shelby Report, a trade publication based out
of Gainesville, Ga. ``A lot rides on the stability of the economy
down there.''
</P>
<P>
   The strengthening economy in recent years and the massive market
base have encouraged hundreds of retailers to set up shop in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A drive through downtown Monterrey, population 3.5 million,
shows that people here dine at Kentucky Fried Chicken, rent
subtitled U.S. movies from Blockbuster Video, enjoy a scoop of ice
cream from Baskin Robbins or lease the popular Nissan Sentra from
Thrifty.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first major retailers entering the Mexican market was
Wal-Mart seven years ago. Things apparently have gone so well for
Wal-Mart that in June of last year, the Bentonville, Ark., company
paid $1.2 billion to take a 53 percent controlling interest in
Cifra, Mexico's largest retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart has 27 stores in Mexico and Sam's Club has 31. Cifra,
its partner, has nearly 200 other grocery stores in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart Corp. followed Wal-Mart into the Mexican grocery market,
teaming up with retailer El Puerto de Liverpool. But Kmart's
experience wasn't as successful as Wal-Mart's.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1997, Kmart announced the sale of its three
hypermarkets in Mexico City and another store in Cuernavaca to
Contoladora Comercial Mexicana, the second-largest retail chain in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   But about the same time the Troy, Mich.-based retailer was
getting out of the Mexican supermarket business, H-E-B made its
move into the market, spending nearly $23 million to open two
grocery stores in Monterrey.
</P>
<P>
   But these, unlike the Economax, were no ordinary grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   The chain, which has 253 U.S. stores, went great guns for the
Mexican market, building elegant grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   The first store the chain opened is flanked by Monterrey's
famous Chipinque Mountains and is located in the exclusive
Garza-Garcia subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   It's massive, at 75,000 square feet, and had a price tag of $8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Because Mexicans often shop with several family members, store
planners added an indoor playground in the corner of the building
for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a bakery, coffee shop and deli.
</P>
<P>
   And finding an excuse to throw a party, H-E-B officials did just
that before opening day. Nearly 1,000 guests attended, including
the mayor of the suburb and the state's governor.
</P>
<P>
   And on opening morning, the store was blessed.
</P>
<P>
   The $15 million, 80,000-square-foot H-E-B store in the Contry
subdivision in Monterrey wasn't to be outdone and similar
festivities were held for its opening months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``H-E-B has primarily targeted upscale demographics down there
and has met with some real success,'' Gilmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Economax is a new concept for H-E-B, which rang up $6 billion in
sales last year. Essentially they are low-cost versions of the
Pantry stores it offers in Texas. It's the exact opposite of the
two all-frills stores H-E-B opened last year.
</P>
<P>
   The 38,000-square-foot store, a steal at only $3 million to
construct, stands in the shadow of a low-rent apartment project.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Colonia Hacienda los Morales warmly welcomed the
grocery store to the neighborhood and were greeted by a salesman
dressed as the store's mascot, a blue and yellow bee named Max.
</P>
<P>
   Store officials reported more than 9,000 sales receipts a day
during opening week in October. Lines trailed off onto the parking
lot, said H-E-B's spokeswoman in Mexico, Lola Landa. Even a week
after the store opened, it was difficult getting through the
crushing crowd at the front door.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the store said interest has not waned and they're
bagging 7,000 sales a day.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers marveled over the low prices one weekday morning as
they filled their shopping carts with hamburger meat, sweet bread
and spices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came for the first time to see how the prices were,'' said
Maria Elvia Andrade de Valdez, who was inspecting the store's
assortment of spices with her husband, Raul Valdez Zuniga.
</P>
<P>
   The couple was so pleased with their first visit they said they
would return with their children and grandchildren to do their
weekly shopping here.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other two Monterrey stores, Economax will sell H-E-B's
low-cost brand of Texas' Hill Country Fare goods. And the company
is working on a Mexican brand called Tierra Linda, which will
include a line of salsas, oils and purees.
</P>
<P>
   Landa said Economax is filling a niche in the Mexican community,
serving the needs of low-income consumers like the Valdezes.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the recent plunge in the Mexican peso and
inflation at 18 percent because of the global financial crisis,
Suarez said Economax is helping consumers stretch their peso.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mexico we have had problems with the economy all of our
lives,'' Suarez said. ``We're in front of the difficult economic
conditions. The people have to eat no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of the stores the company plans to open next year likely
will follow the Economax style and most will be built in the
northern Mexico city of Monterrey, company President Howard E. Butt
III said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   But competitors like Ignacio Toussaint, head of corporate
finance for the Grupo Gigante, one of Mexico's largest chains, said
he's not too worried about small player H-E-B yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That store is doing very well, but it's only one store,''
Toussaint said. ``We have 18 stores in the Monterrey area.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
