<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEFENDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ALLIES WAGE GRASSROOTS CAMPAIGN TO BATTLE IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defenders of President Clinton, led by Vice
President Al Gore, intensified efforts Monday to rally a grassroots
campaign to persuade the Republican-led House to reject impeachment
in favor of censure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton allies accused GOP congressional leaders of turning
their backs on public opinion that favors bipartisan censure to end
an 11-month struggle brought on by the president's sexual dalliance
and alleged cover-up of an extramarital liaison with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-impeachment chorus reached beyond the White House to
include a radio advertising blitz by the liberal advocacy group
People for the American Way, as well as grassroots organizing
efforts by the Democratic Party, the AFL-CIO and the National
Partnership for Women and Families.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have concluded that Clinton's behavior was ``terribly
wrong,'' but that he ``should not be impeached and removed from
office,'' Gore insisted in an appearance at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The unwillingness of Republican leaders in the House to permit
consideration of a censure motion thwarts ``any kind of compromise
along the lines that the American people want to see,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican congressional leaders insist that censuring a
president is not an option given the House by the U.S.
constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The latest nationwide public opinion surveys, however, detected
a slight softening of support for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN/USA Today survey released on Sunday found 38 percent
favored impeachment _ up from 32 percent before the House Judiciary
Committee adopted four articles of impeachment over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   As for the president's resignation, 37 percent voiced support
for Clinton stepping down _ up from 33 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Craig, the White House lawyer orchestrating the
anti-impeachment operation, said in an interview on NBC News'
``Today'' program that Americans want Congress to adopt a ``motion
of censure, which would be bipartisan and would bring this matter
to a close.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, scheduled to return to Washington from Israel late
Tuesday, said in Jerusalem on Monday that he had offered ``to make
every compromise with Congress'' in order to bring the episode to a
speedy conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders planned to reach a decision on Tuesday on the
rules that will govern the scheduled debate Thursday on four
articles of impeachment for perjury, obstruction of justice and
abuse of power. Those articles were recommended by the House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   People for the American Way, a liberal advocacy group founded by
television producer Norman Lear, ordered a $75,000 radio blitz in
three cities in an effort to persuade eight moderate Republicans to
vote against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jean Collins, the organization's vice president for field
operations, said radio advertising in Philadelphia is designed to
reach voters in districts represented by Reps. Jon Fox and Jim
Greenwood of Pennsylvania; Michael Castle of Delaware; and
Christopher H. Smith of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast ads in Columbus, Ohio, will reach voters in the
congressional districts of Reps. David Hobson, Rob Ney and Deborah
Pryce, Collins said. Ads in the District of Columbia are designed
to sway voters in the suburban Maryland district of Rep. Connie
Morella.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have awakened,'' Collins said. ``It's finally sinking
in that Clinton might be impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   A toll-free telephone line used to patch callers through to the
Capitol Hill switchboard has been inundated with 130,000 telephone
calls in 72 hours, Collins said. The toll-free line received 17,000
telephone calls between midnight and noon on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been completely overwhelming,'' Collins said. ``People
are just hopping mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said that grassroots efforts to forestall impeachment
are coalescing around a Thursday prayer vigil planned by civil
rights activist Jesse Jackson on Capitol Hill as the House
considers impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Dion, spokeswoman for the AFL-CIO, said the nation's
largest coalition of labor unions is helping to organize grassroots
rallies as well as the national vigil on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO President John Sweeney is scheduled to join Jackson to
address the rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Union folks are outraged at what is going on,'' Dion said.
``People are looking for what they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said ``thousands of people'' are expected for the rally.
``It's pretty amazing given the short time we've had to get it
organized.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Ratcliff, spokeswoman for the Democratic Party, said the
party headquarters has urged state party leaders to enlist
Democratic officials in the grassroots campaign to dissuade a vote
on impeachment in favor of censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are urging people to call radio talk shows, write to their
members of Congress or write letters to the editor,'' Ratcliff
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judith L. Lichtman, president of the National Partnership for
Women and Families, said in a statement that Clinton ought to ``pay
a price for his shameful behavior'' in the form of a censure to
``bring a just and swift end to this destructive process.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen organizations representing women, led by the
National Organization of Women and the Feminist Majority, have
scheduled a news conference in Washington on Tuesday to urge
congressional censure rather than impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-impeachment campaign has been built upon momentum
generated by an Internet-based organization _ www.MoveOn.org _ that
began operations before the Nov. 3 congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   The operation, ``Censure and Move On,'' has helped funnel
telephone calls to People for the American Way that then relays the
calls to members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't act now, the president will be impeached,'' the
Internet organization said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The organization urged readers to telephone Rep. Bob Livingston,
R-La., the incoming speaker of the House, to appeal for House
consideration of a censure vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he lets his party members vote their conscience,
impeachment will probably die and members will vote censure,''
MoveOn.Org counseled. ``If he continues to threaten the `full wrath
of the Republican Party' to members who break ranks, the President
will be impeached on a purely partisan vote.''
</P>
</TEXT>
