<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMERLY UNDECIDED BASS JOINS PRO-IMPEACHMENT FORCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER _ US Representative Charles Bass of New Hampshire has
left the small group of House Republicans in the undecided column
and cast his lot with those calling for the impeachment of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy statement issued late Monday Bass called his
decision ``one of the most arduous'' he has ever made as an elected
official. ``Yet my conscience is secure in the knowledge that what
I do is in honor of and respect for the truth,'' Bass said. ``This
is not about punishing the president. It is about restoring and
protecting the integrity of the office, the rule of law, and the
Constitution of the United States,'' Bass said.
</P>
<P>
   The full House begins debate Thursday on the four articles of
impeachment passed by the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we are faced with two difficult choices: hold
the president accountable for his crimes by supporting articles of
impeachment or turn a blind eye to his criminal activity,'' the
second-term Republican representative said.
</P>
<P>
   Calls from the congressman's constituents were split roughly
equally between pro- and anti-impeachment camps. No member of the
House Republican leadership called Bass to sway his vote and the
congressman did not return the one call he received from a White
House staffer seeking to lobby him on behalf of the president, said
Bass's press secretary, Sally Tibbetts.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bass had to beat a Democrat to win his seat in what has
been a historically Republican district he emphasized that citizen
input was only one factor in his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``To yield to polls in the face of such criminal conduct, I
maintain, would be dangerous to our constitutional government,''
Bass said. ``It would mean that popular presidents who have
committed high crimes and misdemeanors could escape impeachment
simply because they are strong in the polls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
