<SLUG> BC-SMITHSONIAN-CLOSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITHONIAN CLOSES ART RECORDS OFFICES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By M.R. MONTGOMERY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A minor Boston outpost of the Smithsonian Institution
disappeared last month. Almost no one noticed, but those who did
are variously disappointed, outraged, and discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   It was, until just before Thanksgiving, the 28-year-old Boston
office of the Archives of American Art, a one-man operation on
Beacon Hill. The Archives survives, but all its regional offices
were closed on Nov. 23 in a budget decision that irritated and
flabbergasted its local advisory committee.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Master-Karnik, a committee member, called ``vital'' the
archive's task of collecting the papers and business records of
artists and galleries and museums. Those that it doesn't collect,
it microfilms for the convenience of scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the now-unemployed archivist in the Boston office,
Master-Karnik added that ``what Bob Brown did was essential to
collecting, he knew everybody, he stayed in touch with everyone. He
did enormous work with ... papers that are critical to scholars and
museums.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who was surprised, if not stunned, by the closing of his
office and the end of nearly 30 years of employment by the
Smithsonian, said last week that the great shame was not merely
closing his office, but abandoning the concept of collecting
records and materials nationally. ``There was not a serious attempt
to raise money'' to continue the work of the regional offices, he
said. ``There was never an explicit appeal. In fact, I was never
hired to do fund-raising; I was told explicitly that `fund-raising
is not in your picture.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara de Marneffe, former chair of the New England advisory
committee and now a trustee of the Archives of American Art,
acknowledged that there had been rumors and hints that the regional
offices would be closed, but still, when the word came in
September, it was a shock. ``There wasn't any question of keeping
the office open,'' she recalled, ``and when officials came up from
Washington it wasn't to discuss the decision, it was just to
explain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Smithsonian couldn't continue to fund it,'' de Marneffe
added, ``at least they could back us in fund-raising. We're hoping
to raise private funds; we're going to notify the New England
congressional delegation. Taking a full-time collector away from
New England is very, very shortsighted.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan now is to send out collecting teams from the
Smithsonian headquarters when a gallery closes or an artist's
papers become available. ``That just doesn't work,'' according to
Sinclair Hitchings, curator of prints at the Boston Public Library
and another member of the advisory committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The returns from Bob Brown's collecting have been fabulous.
He's got a retentive memory and a network of friends and contacts.
As for the officials at the Smithsonian,'' Hitchings added, ``they
are defiantly wrongheaded.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``defiantly'' is an adverb that applies to many actions
since the closing was announced. Relations between the director of
the archives, Richard J. Wattenmaker, and his Boston committee,
couldn't be more defiant. Concluding a written response to
complaints from staff at the Museum of Fine Arts, Wattenmaker noted
that the Boston committee hadn't raised any serious money since the
1970s, and had no authority to tell him how to run his department.
In a letter in The New York Times, he asked rhetorically: ``When
the Museum of Fine Arts put up that ugly shopping mall wing, did I
call them up and say, `Why are you putting all this trash in the
museum?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Wattenmaker's final thought on the matter, referring to
criticism from two curators at the MFA, Jonathan L. Fairbanks and
Theodore Stebbins, was simple: ``How about they run their business,
and the Smithsonian runs its business?''
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been,'' the BPL's Hitchings remarked, ``some
gratuitous nastiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is looking for a job, and Hitchings and a few others are
hoping that some arrangement can be made not only to keep him
employed, but to keep the paper and microfilm flowing to
Washington. But no one is very hopeful. The problem, Hitchings
concluded, was that those people in Washington didn't understand
the rest of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
