<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVIDED COURT REINSTATES CALIFORNIA MURDERER'S DEATH SENTENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Stands for SCOTUS-DISABLED) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A sharply divided Supreme Court on Monday summarily
reinstated a murderer's death sentence _ at least for now _ and
ordered a lower court to reconsider whether the trial judge
confused the jury with inaccurate instructions before the panel
condemned the defendant.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual 5-4 decision for which no justice claimed
authorship, the court acknowledged that a California judge
incorrectly told the jury that the governor could commute a life
sentence without parole. But the high court majority, which took
the rare step of issuing its decision without first hearing
arguments, ruled the judge's mistake might have had no effect on
the jury's final verdict to sentence Russell Coleman to death.
</P>
<P>
   Although the majority opinion's author was not disclosed, a
stinging dissent was signed by the court's liberal quartet of
Justices John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg
and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision overturned a 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals ruling that the trial judge's mistake improperly led the
jury to condemn Coleman out of fear that he could one day be
released by a sympathetic governor. California law, in fact,
requires that four state Supreme Court justices approve a
governor's decision to commute a life sentence without parole for a
twice-convicted felon such as Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court returned the case to the 9th Circuit and
told that court to decide if the judge's mistaken instruction had a
``substantial and injurious effect or influence on the jury's
verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   By process of elimination, the five members of the majority were
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia,
Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   In other action, the high court agreed to consider whether the
federal Americans with Disabilities Act allows states to treat
mentally disabled people in an institution even if the individuals
can receive adequate care while living at home.
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty case arose Sept. 5, 1979, when Coleman raped,
sodomized and murdered Shirley Hill in San Francisco. After
convicting Coleman and hearing the judge's mistaken instruction,
the jury sentenced the defendant to death.
</P>
<P>
   The California Supreme Court upheld the penalty, but federal
courts later reversed. The 9th Circuit, upholding a decision of a
California federal court, said the judge's erroneous instruction
confused the jury by creating ``the false impression that the
governor, acting alone,'' could commute a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court said the 9th Circuit incorrectly set aside
the death sentence ``without first determining that the error had a
substantial and injurious effect on the jury's verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens led the dissenters in assailing the majority's
``ill-conceived'' decision to even grant California's appeal, let
alone rule for the state without having heard arguments in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenting justices said the 9th Circuit correctly ruled
that the judge's confusing and inaccurate statement of the
governor's authority discouraged the jury from considering a
penalty less than death. A juror said after the sentence that many
on the panel feared that, unless Coleman was condemned, a governor
could later order him paroled, the dissenters said.
</P>
<P>
   In the disability case, Georgia is appealing an 11th Circuit
decision ordering the state to treat mentally disabled residents at
home rather than in institutions if they can function outside a
hospital. The ruling was based on a Justice Department regulation
under the Americans with Disabilities Act that requires states to
administer services ``in the most integrated setting appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas, 20 other states and Guam joined a brief Florida submitted
to the justices in support of Georgia's position that neither
Congress nor the department has the constitutional authority to
decide how states should treat mentally ill residents unless the
states are violating the civil rights of these individuals. The
justices are expected to rule by July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
