A9385 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTMASGIFTS-TEX     12-14 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMASGIFTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OH, WHAT FUN IT IS TO BUY ... GIFTS FOR EVERY RELATIVE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CHRISTMAS-IDEAS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year for Hanukkah, Julie Yolles is buying her
impossible-to-shop-for dad the same thing she gets him every year:
a subscription to a boating magazine. Paul Cuadros' dad is getting
a pair of khaki pants for Christmas _ whether he needs 'em or not.
And Dianna Connor will force herself to buy her sister-in-law
``something pretty,'' even though her brother's wife once gave her
an address book made out of a license plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that lame?'' she groans.
</P>
<P>
   Gift shopping for relatives can be painful any time of year. But
when it has to be done en masse, like before the winter holidays,
buying presents can turn even uber-shoppers into whimpering mall
saps. The pressure to choose the right item at the right price in
the right size and color _ and that also sends the right message _
can be paralyzing.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, some families have developed solutions, such as
formulas for satisfying everyone's fancy _ like swapping elaborate
lists. Or just giving cash (there are ways to present it
creatively, one expert says).
</P>
<P>
   Many of us, though, still flail around helplessly. Like Cuadros,
we just take a stab in the dark. Like Yolles, we stick to
successful but predictable goodies.
</P>
<P>
   And, like Connor, we end up with unwanted stuff that gets shoved
into a corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually hate gift-giving (at Christmas), because it's
forced,'' said Connor, an editor in Santa Fe, N.M. ``You're going
out, and you have to buy 20 things in one day. How thoughtful can
you get?''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be thoughtful in the least if Uncle Al has
supplied you with a list of all the goodies he's hankering for. The
benefit in this is obvious: no shopping angst.
</P>
<P>
   But doesn't list-making take the creativity and intimacy out of
gift-giving? There are arguments on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The online shopping arm of QVC, iQVC, has adopted the wish-list
philosophy for its Holiday Gift Boutique, introduced in November.
Sign up on the wish list and specify everything from your clothing
sizes to favorite fragrances to specific gift choices, then send
friends and relatives your password.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lists are something consumers have been trained to create
since day one, sitting on Santa's lap and telling him what you
want,'' said an iQVC spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   This can be a good way to satisfy picky relatives. Then again,
some list-making routines are so elaborate, it takes more time to
make the list than to actually do the shopping.
</P>
<P>
   One colleague's family shops exclusively by catalog, compiling
lists of everyone's wants, then sending copies to each household.
Each potential gift specifies which catalog it comes from, the item
number, color, size and the catalog's 800 number.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you receive a list, you decide what you are going to
`sign up for' and then you have to call all the other people in the
family and let them know what you're getting so they don't get it,
too,'' she breathlessly explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely in favor of families making wish lists, really
having fun with it,'' said Michelle Passoff, the New York-based
author of ``Lighten Up! Free Yourself From Clutter.'' ``I think
it's a good practice to know what you want and to let other people
know it. Then you don't end up with what you don't want, which ends
up as clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   Passoff encourages drawing up lists that include everything from
your simplest desires to the most extravagant _ and letting your
family use their imaginations. Ask for a trip to the French
Riviera, and you might at least get an evening of French films and
food.
</P>
<P>
   Or, instead of tangible items, think about giving
``experiences,'' Passoff added, like a night at the theater or a
baby-sitting IOU or breakfast in bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My honest feeling is that (lists) kind of take the fun out of
it,'' noted Chiquita Woodard, author of ``It's Just What I've
Always Wanted! More Than 2000 Imaginative and Unique Gifts _ From a
Ride in a MiG Jet to a Singing Telegram.'' Woodard, the former
director of merchandising for Smith &AMP; Hawken and the gift expert on
America Online for two years, divided her book into chapters for
Valentine's Day, birthdays, baby showers and, of course, the
holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard's book is filled with fresh and affordable gift ideas,
like signing up a fishing fanatic for the Fishing Lure of the Month
Club; or, for the ``woman with everything,'' making a charitable
donation in her name.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever you do, said Woodard, ``don't head out to the malls
blindly trying to find something, because you will be frustrated,
you will be stressed and you'll spend more money than you want to
spend.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
