A9406 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-DEMOCRATS-BOS     12-14 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DEMOCRATS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRAT DEFECTORS COULD DECIDE CLINTON'S FATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While attention has focused on moderate House
Republicans who are undecided about impeachment, a small number of
wavering Democrats could ultimately determine President Clinton's
fate.
</P>
<P>
   In a House vote later this week that many lawmakers consider too
close to call, a handful of Democratic defections could make it
more difficult for Clinton to avoid being impeached and undercut
the administration's argument that this is a partisan exercise
orchestrated by the Republican majority.
</P>
<P>
   At least three conservative Democrats have said they plan to
vote for impeachment _ Representatives Ralph M. Hall of Texas, Gene
Taylor of Mississippi and Virgil H. Goode Jr. of Virginia. That
means the White House needs at least 14 of the 228 Republicans to
vote no for impeachment to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Paul McHale, a Democrat from Pennsylvania, also
said he is leaning toward voting for impeachment. He was the first
member of the president's party to call on him to resign, but
recently he had been working with House minority leader Richard A.
Gephardt on a censure resolution.
</P>
<P>
   At least five other Democrats say they are undecided. White
House and Democratic leadership aides speculated Monday that two or
three of those votes may be cast in the president's favor.
</P>
<P>
   For every Democratic vote Clinton loses, he will need the vote
of a Republican, only five of whom have publicly announced they
will support him.
</P>
<P>
   Like their Republican counterparts, fence-sitting Democrats say
they have been pummeled with calls and e-mails that are split down
the middle.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most closely watched undecided Democrats is
Representative William O. Lipinski of Illinois, who represents the
southwest side of Chicago and neighboring middle-class suburbs. As
a social conservative, he embraced more of the Republican agenda
after nearly losing his seat in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Lipinski has been a mystery for White House aides and their
allies who have dispatched Commerce Secretary William Daley, who
hails from Chicago, to talk with him. Calls have poured into
Lipinski's office at the rate of one every minute, or so it seems,
an aide said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get threats from both sides,'' said Julie Turner, a
spokeswoman from another undecided Democrat, Representative Charles
W. Stenholm of Texas. ``If you vote this way, I'll never vote for
you again. If you vote that way, I'll never vote for you again,''
she said, recalling some of the calls. ``It's surprisingly
two-sided.''
</P>
<P>
   The other three undecided Democrats are Representatives
Christopher C. John, a conservative from Louisana; Robert E.
``Bud'' Cramer of Alabama, whose district rejected Clinton for
president in 1992 and 1996; and Pat Danner of Missouri, an abortion
opponent considered the most conservative woman in the Democratic
Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   McHale, who is retiring at the end of this term, said he will
vote to impeach Clinton unless he learns new information, since the
chances the GOP will allow a censure vote on the House floor have
diminished.
</P>
<P>
   All nine Democrats were among the 31 party members who voted
with Republicans in October to launch an open-ended impeachment
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt has phoned all 31 to get a feel for where they stand.
In those conversations, he has stated his own disapproval of
Clinton's conduct for lying about his affair with a former White
House intern. But the minority leader also has suggested that the
president's offenses are not impeachable, according to his aides.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, one Democratic leadership aide said of the undecided
Democrats: ``You got to keep your eye on them.'' But this aide
quickly added optimstically: ``They will come home. They will
support the president.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, a senior official said the administration
was not discounting the damage if more than three Democrats walk
away from the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every vote counts,'' said the official, who spoke on the
condition that his name not be used. ``We're doing what we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rozell, a political scientist with the University of
Pennsylvania, said Democratic defections are more politically
harmful to Clinton, particularly on such a historic vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly carries a lot more weight,'' he said. ``The
president and his people have made the case that this whole
endeavor is a partisan travesty. It's a little bit more difficult
to make that case credible if a significant number of Democrats
also side with the Republicans,'' Rozell said, asserting that six
or seven Democratic defections would be significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the emphasis on moderate Republicans is justified, but
they should not ignore the wavering Democrats at the same time,''
he continued. ``If so, they do so to their own peril, especially if
this comes down to a handful of votes, which it very well may.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
