<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBA: THE ISLAND OF THE TORTOISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``What country has the perfect model?'' asks Foreign Minister
Roberto Robaino.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not said that ours is perfect.'' The unspoken
implication is clear: Cubans, along with many others, see the
United States as trying to remake the rest of humankind in its own
image.
</P>
<P>
   Robaino's deeper message is that Cuba is not averse to
democratic change _ at its own pace and initiative.
</P>
<P>
   That Cuba is changing, everyone agrees _ internally, through
experimental economic and political reforms; externally, in its
perceptions of the world and its own role in the family. The speed
and adequacy of Cuba's metamorphosis are what provoke the
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Government spokesmen like Robaino and National Assembly
President Ricardo Alarcon believe their country deserves credit for
steps that mark a clean break from the past. For one thing, Cuba
has abandoned military aid to subversive movements in other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't send soldiers anymore,'' says Ricardo Alarcon. ``We
send doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   He points to trained medical rescue teams that Cuba had on the
ground in places like Honduras and the Dominican Republic in the
immediate wake of Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   Fidel Castro, during our three-and-a-half-hour conversation last
month, offered to supply physicians and medical technicians without
charge _ if some other country will provide the vaccines, which
Cuba doesn't have in sufficient quantity _ to inoculate people in
Haiti, where reports say 35,000 die each year from preventable
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your country and mine could work together there, we'd
clearly save thousands of lives,'' he offers.
</P>
<P>
   Cubans are proudest of their attainments in health and
education. Theirs is an enviable 96 percent literacy rate, arguably
the best in the hemisphere. Public health standards also are high,
reflected in low disease and infant mortality statistics. Medical
treatment is free.
</P>
<P>
   The university system has educated more physicians and full
professors, in fact, than Cuba's domestic institutions need.
Efforts are afoot to export their professional skills to other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 62,000 trained physicians in Cuba today,'' boasts Dr.
Raul Gomez, head of Havana's spotlessly impressive, 952-bed modern
hospital. ``In 1959, there were only 6,500 doctors in the entire
country. All of them were in the large cities. Today we have
physicians in every rural community and several foreign
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital performs sophisticated surgery _ heart bypasses and
organ transplants. ``What we need and do not have,'' says Gomez,
``are enough medicines and up-to-date medical equipment.'' It costs
at least 40 percent more, he estimates, to secure these from
Germany and Japan than it would if Cubans were allowed by U.S. law
to buy such necessities from American manufacturers and
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Several welcome political changes have come upon the scene in
the last few years. One is the Cuban government's treatment of
religion. Once an avowed ``atheist state,'' Cuba now has a
constitutional amendment granting religious freedom. This repealed
bans on various types of public religious activity.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas, discontinued as an official national holiday in 1969
on the ground that it interfered with the sugar harvest, was
formally reinstated last year by Castro. That one-time action now
is being made permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Castro himself seems profoundly moved by his personal visits
with Pope John Paul II. To several of us at dinner, the old
revolutionary volunteered repeated exclamations of admiration for
the pontiff's ``intellect, integrity and understanding of the human
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Today there are notably fewer political prisoners, some greater
freedom of expression, and easier access for foreign media. The
government has welcomed the establishment of permanent Havana
bureaus for CNN and The Associated Press. In October, Castro hosted
U.S newspaper editors and publishers, answering their questions at
length.
</P>
<P>
   The Republic of Cuba is not a democracy by official U.S.
definition. It holds regular, constitutionally mandated elections
but within a one-party system that features town-hall nominating
procedures. Castro heads both the party and the Council of State.
</P>
<P>
   Our U.S. chief of mission, Michael Kozak, calls it a
``top-down'' political structure with inadequate power
diversification and human rights guarantees. Cuban leaders respond
that, whatever their imperfections, they are moving toward a more
open society and that the U.S. pursues cordial relations with
China, Vietnam, Saudi Arabia, Arab emirates and other countries
that Kozak's description would fit equally well.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba's Popular Assembly, or national legislature, convenes in
two brief sessions annually. A product of the new Constitution, the
legislative branch is only evolving as an instrument of national
power. Currently, it's wrestling with laws to disperse more
authority to state and municipal governments.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly President Ricardo Alarcon is a careful student of the
U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He plies California Rep. Estaban Torres and me with probing
questions. That day he wanted to know how soon a printed copy of
the latest omnibus appropriations bill would be available. He was
anxious to scour it for any publicly unreported riders that might
affect his country.
</P>
<P>
   Alarcon, 60, easily could be mistaken for an American. His
English is excellent, as is his sense of humor. He laughs now about
several embarrassing inconveniences during the years when he was
his country's ambassador to the United Nations. Alone among their
peers from around the world, Cuba's diplomats were prohibited by
U.S. law from going any farther than 25 miles in any direction from
the U.N. headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Alarcon is a realist. He makes no claims of Cuban political
purity.
</P>
<P>
   The country has ``no deeply established legislative
traditions,'' he volunteers. ``We'd like to move carefully so as to
avoid all the pitfalls we can.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
