<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9418 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES-COX     12-14 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves expected back for playoffs after bypass surgery
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta Falcons coach Dan Reeves is expected be moved from
intensive care to a private room today at Piedmont Hospital, where
he is recovering from four hours of quadruple-bypass surgery Monday
to relieve blockages in three heart arteries.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old Reeves, a leading candidate for NFL coach of the
year honors for guiding the Falcons (12-2) to first place in the
NFC West, had angioplasty procedures in 1990 and 1991 to clear
blockages.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves is expected to be back on the sideline for the playoffs
and could talk with his assistants as early as today. He will not
make the trip to Detroit on Sunday for a game that could clinch the
team's second division title in 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant head coach and defensive coordinator Rich Brooks will
be the interim head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Harrison, one of the team's physicians and one of the
doctors who diagnosed the blockages Monday morning, said the
location and nature of Reeves' blockages called for bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Cardiac surgeon James Kauten bypassed one artery that appeared
to be completely blocked and two others that were more than 80
percent blocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statistically, he has a 99 percent or better chance of doing
fine,'' Kauten said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison said that, because Reeves suffered no damage to his
heart muscle, the coach could go back to work on a part-time basis
as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing Dan Reeves, I suspect we'll be able to discharge him
Friday,'' Harrison said. ``He did not have a heart attack. He has
never had a heart attack. We've got wonderful, viable heart muscle
to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this reason ... I would not be surprised see Dan
participating in some game-planning for the Dolphins (on Dec. 27).
Whether he'll be on the field, I can't say. But I see no reason ...
why he couldn't be back for the playoffs (which begin for wild-card
teams on Jan. 2) and the Super Bowl, which I say with confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Players and coaches reacted with disbelief and reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in to work this morning, and nobody knew anything
about it,'' 12-year veteran linebacker Cornelius Bennett said. ``We
know what kind of ship coach Reeves runs, and Rich is going to do
his thing. But it's up to us as veterans to hold this team together
and keep the boat afloat.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie wide receiver Tim Dwight said: ``It just takes it right
out of you. One moment, you see the guy on the sideline all happy
after a game, and the next thing you know he's in the hospital
fighting for his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him on the plane (Sunday) night, and he didn't look too
good. He was talking to the Doc, and I thought maybe he was sick or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, 57, was head coach of the St. Louis Rams in 1995-96
after serving as head coach at the University of Oregon for 17
years.
</P>
<P>
   He will remain in the coaches' box above the field to call the
defenses. While he won't get involved in offensive play-calling, he
said he would be involved in critical decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks coach Jack Burns called plays from the coaches' box
down to Reeves, who wore a headset on the sideline and sent them
via radio headset to quarterback Chris Chandler. Now, Burns will
relay plays to running backs coach George Sefcik, who will radio
them to Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan obviously has changed some of those (plays called by
Burns),'' Brooks said. ``I'll have a switch on the headset upstairs
where I can listen in to the offense. (He, Burns and Sefcik) will
talk about different situations, (whether to) run or pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be involved just situationally, not that I want to run
the off-tackle play or throw deep. (I'll be involved in)
fourth-and-one, whether to go for it, kick a field goal, those
types of situations.''
</P>
<P>
   No other coaching responsibilities have changed, pending further
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves first told Harrison that he had been experiencing chest
pain and a burning sensation in his throat after Sunday's 27-17
victory at New Orleans. That victory tied the team record for
victories in a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan summoned me into the corner of the locker room after the
game ... and said, 'I'm probably overreacting, ... but I just want
to tell you I'm having a burning sensation in my chest like I did
in 1990, and I've had it for several weeks,' `` Harrison said.
``What do you think we ought to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison gave Reeves two aspirin on the plane to thin his blood
and recommended that the coach undergo a heart catheterization
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the blockage in the circumflex artery probably
was causing the burning sensation in Reeves' chest and that if it
closed all the way, the result would have been, in Harrison's
words, ``a catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, whose regular-season career record of 160-117-1 ranks
him eighth on the NFL's all-time victory list, is a native of
Americus. He played at the University of South Carolina before
joining the Dallas Cowboys in 1965 as an undrafted free-agent
running back.
</P>
<P>
   He played running back for seven years and then coached nine
years for the Dallas Cowboys under Tom Landry. He became the
Broncos head coach in 1981, leading Denver to Super Bowls after the
1986, '87 and '89 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He was fired after an 8-8 season in 1992 and coached the New
York Giants from1993-96. When the Giants went 11-5 his first year,
he was named NFL coach of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants fired him after a 6-10 season in '96, when Reeves
repeatedly butted heads with the front office on issues of control.
</P>
<P>
   When the Falcons hired him in January 1997, he was given the
title of executive vice president of football operations. After a
1-7 start last year, the team has won 18 of 22 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of coach Reeves' greatest strengths is the organization he
has put together,'' Falcons president Taylor Smith said. ``He feels
as I do that we have the type of players and coaches ... to move
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, meanwhile, said the team has no choice but to march on.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about a guy who has meant everything to this
organization,'' he said. ``What Dan has done is just unbelievable
... a remarkable turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to,'' Brooks said, pausing, ``pick up the slack and
make it easy on him during his recovery. I know Dan. He's going to
feel a lot better about getting well if we take care of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
