u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS     12-14 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOMENTOUS VOTE IN CONNECTICUT; DAMAGE CONTROL IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Connecticut lawmakers were going over the final details
of the $350 million New England Patriots stadium proposal, expected
to pass the General Assembly in a historic vote Tuesday, while
Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham sat in his Beacon Hill office
thinking one thing.
</P>
<P>
   Last rites.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would probably be the appropriate sacrament,'' Birmingham
said Monday, leaning back in a leather chair and gazing out the
window. ``It didn't have to come to this. I mean, we had negotiated
an agreement with the Patriots that would have kept them here for
25 years playing in a $200 million privately-financed stadium. And
it was a winner for all of the taxpayers in the Commonwealth,
whether they're Patriots fans or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the marble State House hall, Governor Paul Cellucci stood
in the anteroom of House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran's office,
waiting to meet with the man who many believe drove the team across
the state line by refusing to compromise on a Senate bill that
would have provided $72 million in land and improvements around
Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have the votes,'' Cellucci said of Connecticut's
legislature, ``It's pretty much over. I feel bad for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut officials see Tuesday's vote as fatalistic, too,
but, obviously, with a much brighter outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Representative (Moira) Lyons is on board and told the
caucus she will vote for the bill,'' Larry Perosino, spokesman for
Connecticut's House Democrats, said referring to the incoming
speaker of the house, who had been the deal's most vocal critic.
</P>
<P>
   Perosino said leaders expect the debate and voting on the
publicly-financed stadium to be finished by the end of Tuesday, and
ready for the signature of Governor John Rowland, who secretly
negotiated and signed a memorandum of understanding with franchise
owner Robert Kraft less than a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a core of people who are going to vote against it
and they have a right to say why they don't think it's a good
public policy and offer up amendments,'' Perosino said. ``But once
again, the speaker encouraged members that if they were thinking of
filing amendments that changed the deal in a substantial way, he
would encourage them to vote no and not put forth their
amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, referring to the reduction in the luxury seat guarantee
the state is providing Kraft, Perosino said: ``You can't negotiate
with the entire legislature. The governor has negotiated and
addressed a number of concerns...and now we're ready to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   In the original proposal, Connecticut would have guaranteed up
to $17.5 million a year in luxury seating at the open-air facility
-- a component which many lawmakers and citizens felt was too
generous.
</P>
<P>
   But over the weekend, Rowland reduced that guarantee by 25
percent _ or as much as $4 million a year -- lowering the price of
club seats and making the state responsible for a smaller
percentage of unsold premium tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft has also agreed to pay off the state's remaining bonds and
make up for the revenue the state would have made if he pulls the
team out of Connecticut before the 30-year lease expires.
</P>
<P>
   The state will pay up to $374 million for construction, which
includes site preparation and inflation. Kraft will have to pay for
additional costs.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's House of Representatives, with 96 Democrats and 55
Republicans, is expected to vote on the measure first, followed by
the 36-member Senate.
</P>
<P>
   On Beacon Hill, the damage control stretched for hours Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham, citing recent legislative approval for a convention
center and a replacement for the Boston Garden, said the Patriots
stadium ordeal here was ``aberrational.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Both were journeys that had a lot of twists and turns in the
road, but we eventually got there. This was one where we didn't.
And, in terms of atmospherics, that's not positive for
Massachusetts,'' Birmingham said. ``I regret it came to this
because it didn't have to. But I am quite confident, quite
comfortable, that we in the Senate did all that was required to
keep the team here. ... But we didn't give away the shop in the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham said he had no reason for optimism that the team --
and their nearly $10 million in annual tax revenue -- would stay
here, given the specter of Tuesday's vote, which will bind the
Patriots and their corporate offices to move to Hartford as early
as 2001.
</P>
<P>
   However, even outside the State House, a sense of resignation
has settled in. Phone calls criticizing Beacon Hill's inaction on
the stadium issue are down to a trickle, the senate president said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``Senators have something to say when asked why
the Patriots are leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   The implication: It's Finneran's fault.
</P>
<P>
   And Cellucci, even while standing in the Speaker's office, also
blamed the House and its leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's unfortunate is that we were very close here in
Massachusetts an unable to complete it,'' Cellucci said. ``The
House appeared to be almost unwilling to try to sit down and work
it out. It looks to me like it's too late now. ... It looks like
they have the votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Finneran appeared in the waiting room next to his
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which part of the governor's statement is inaccurate?'' he
sarcastically asked. ``The governor and I get along personally and
professionally but there's perhaps a difference of opinion and a
difference of philosophy ...''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do agree that we would not ask Massachusetts to put up the
kind of money that Connecticut put up,'' the governor said.
``That's something we agree on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
