<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DRUG MAY AID IN BREAST CANCER TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE FOY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A promising, yet preliminary, new drug appears to
bypass the resistance women with breast cancer inevitably build up
to existing treatments, one of the nation's top breast cancer
researchers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The drug Faslodex also seems to work better and longer in the
fight against breast cancer than the widely used drug tamoxifen,
said Dr. C. Kent Osborne, chief of medical oncology at the
University of Texas Health Science Center in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne, who is also director of the Breast Cancer Program at
the San Antonio Cancer Institute, said Faslodex could prove more
powerful than tamoxifen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tumors are smart guys,'' he said. ``They tend to have the
ability to eventually develop resistance to almost any therapy. But
I'm optimistic about Faslodex because it seems to be much more
potent.''
</P>
<P>
   The drug remains in development and is being used in clinical
trials in the United States and Europe. A small, preliminary study
indicated Faslodex cured cancerous tumors in mice.
</P>
<P>
   Whether such results translate to humans remains to be seen, but
Osborne said he was excited about the odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if we can't get cures from it, we can at least get much
more prolonged control over the disease,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne spoke to colleagues during an international breast
cancer symposium that ends Tuesday. The San Antonio Breast Cancer
symposium, an annual event, has attracted about 2,550 researchers
and physicians.
</P>
<P>
   The symposium marks one of the largest _ if not the largest _
gatherings of breast cancer investigators anywhere in the world,
organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne will join the Baylor College of Medicine in Houston next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Tamoxifen has been used for decades as a first-line treatment
against breast cancer. But many patients become resistant to the
drug and doctors then turn to second-line, anti-estrogen drugs such
as anastrozole, sold under the brand name Arimidex.
</P>
<P>
   Faslodex, manufactured by the Zeneca Group of Britain, would
provide yet another alternative once women become resistant to
tamoxifen. A clinical trial a few years ago in the United Kingdom
showed that 60 percent of patients responded to Faslodex after they
no longer responded to tamoxifen, Osborne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shown that when the tumor becomes resistant to
tamoxifen, you can make it respond again and shrink again by using
Faslodex,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The current, ongoing trials now are comparing Arimidex and
Faslodex when used after tamoxifen treatments.
</P>
<P>
   To unlock the mystery of tamoxifen resistance, researchers hope
to pinpoint why the drug, after it is administered for a while,
begins actually to stimulate _ rather than suppress _ tumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tamoxifen is this funny drug. It has these dual activities,''
Osborne said.
</P>
<P>
   Faslodex could be the critical link to bypassing resistance and
thereby outsmarting tumor growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faslodex could be the answer to this,'' he said. ``Maybe if it
winds up being effective in people, and we wind up using it after
surgery like we've used tamoxifen ... that will be very
effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne also indicated that a type of intermittent therapy
approach against breast cancer appears to be effective in some
patients who build up drug resistance. Although no scientific
evidence exists regarding the process, Osborne said he has used it
on a few patients and has had some success.
</P>
<P>
   One of Osborne's patients, for example, became resistant to
tamoxifen. After using other treatments, Osborne returned to
tamoxifen a second time to try and ``trick'' the tumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something that doctors try a lot,'' he acknowledged.
``But with the appropriate patient, it's worth a try.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the approach has worked could indicate resistance
is not a permanent state, Osborne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an important thing,'' he said. ``That tells us that
it's not so much a change in the genetics of the tumor, but it's
more of an adaptive thing that the tumor does and that process can
go away ... if you stop the drug.''
</P>
</TEXT>
