<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N. KOREANS MAY ALLOW INSPECTIONS IN EXCHANGE FOR FOOD
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ North Korea has dropped a demand that the United
States pay hundreds of millions of dollars for the right to inspect
a huge underground center that American intelligence agencies had
feared would be used to make nuclear weapons, according to senior
Clinton administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with State Department officials in New York and
Washington this month, they said, the North Koreans suggested that
they would be willing to allow the United States to inspect the
center in exchange for food to ease the famine that has plagued
North Korea for years.
</P>
<P>
   American officials welcomed the new North Korean negotiating
stance _ both because it could salvage a 4-year-old agreement
intended to shut down North Korea's nuclear weapons program, and
because it suggested that North Korea had not yet begun building a
nuclear reactor at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, they said, the North Koreans had demanded a payment of
$300 million in exchange for the inspection _ a demand quickly
rejected by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is that they have agreed in principle to allow
access to the site, which suggests that there probably isn't
anything there,'' a senior administration official said. ``It also
indicates that whatever plans they had for this facility have been
scrapped.''
</P>
<P>
   Another senior official, also speaking on condition of
anonymity, said: ``We seem to be in a problem-solving mode. We're
still apart, but there seem to be real negotiations going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials had insisted that the United States
would never make a cash payment for the right to inspect the
underground center, which is being built 25 miles from the North
Korean nuclear complex at Yongbyon.
</P>
<P>
   But they said Monday that it would be easier to justify
additional food and other relief aid, especially given recent
reports of widespread starvation in North Korea. The United States
has already provided North Korea with 500,000 metric tons of food
this year
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot pay them for access to the site,'' an administration
official involved with the issue said. ``But obviously we've
provided them with humanitarian aid in the past for humanitarian
reasons, and we might be willing to do that again.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department refused to confirm that the North Koreans
had dropped the cash demand for inspection of the site.
</P>
<P>
   But department spokesman James Foley acknowledged that ``some
progress had been made'' in the recent talks between American and
North Korean negotiators. ``Important gaps remain,'' he said,
adding that further meetings would be held ``as soon as possible to
try to close those gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials denied news reports in South Korea that
a deal to allow American inspection of the construction site had
already been reached between the United States and North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Aerial photographs taken earlier this year on behalf of American
intelligence agencies showed that thousands of laborers were at
work on the huge underground plant. The discovery led to fears that
North Korea had decided to revive its nuclear weapons program at
the site in violation of a 1994 agreement with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   American officials announced progress Monday with North Korea on
another issue: the search for the remains of American troops
missing there since the Korean War. The Defense Department said the
United States and North Korea had agreed to expand joint searches
in the North next year for the remains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
