<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTEL-LEARNING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARGEST TOYMAKER MATTEL BUYS SOFTWARE MAKER LEARNING CO. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world's largest toymaker is buying itself a $3.2 billion
Christmas present _ Learning Co., the second-largest maker of
personal computer software for the home.
</P>
<P>
   If shareholders of both companies approve the deal, it will
instantly establish Mattel as a major force in the software
industry. The addition of Learning Co., a Cambridge, Mass. company
that markets popular titles such as ``Carmen Sandiego'' and
``Myst'', could also help revitalize the House of Barbie, which
finds itself struggling in its traditional business segments.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel chairman Jill Barad prefaced her announcement of the
Learning Co. deal with news that Mattel's profit would fall short
of analysts' expectations this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   The news sent Mattel stock plunging $8 1/8 to $22 Monday, while
Learning Co. stock sank $3 5/16 to $25. Both firms trade on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news may have soured the announcement of the Learning
Co. acquisition and it may have reduced the deal's value to
Learning Co. shareholders. Mattel, based in El Segundo, Calif.,
agreed to a one-to-one stock swap with Learning Co., with an extra
two-tenths of a Mattel share if the giant toy maker's stock price
falls below $27.50.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel and Learning Co. said the deal was worth $3.8 billion
based on Friday's share prices, but the value dwindled to $3.2
billion by the end of trading Monday. The final price will be based
on the average price of Mattel stock over a 20-day period.
</P>
<P>
   The buyout could deal a blow to the work force and presence of
the Learning Co. in Massachusetts, one of the state's largest and
most well-known software companies.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Learning Co.'s software development operations are
in California. About a third of the company's 990 employees are
based in Massachusetts, and they mainly perform administrative and
customer service functions. While Learning Co. president Kevin
O'Leary and chairman Michael Perik have both signed contracts to
continue with the company, it's not yet clear how other positions
will be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Barad made it clear that Mattel is planning significant cost
cuts to bolster its bottom line. Mattel spokesman Glenn Bozarth
said that Mattel was eager to keep the Learning Co.'s experts in
educational and entertainment software, but confirmed that there
might be job cuts in administrative areas _ exactly those functions
concentrated in the Bay State.
</P>
<P>
   Learning Co., formerly known as SoftKey International Inc.,
transformed itself into the nation's largest maker of educational
software through a string of acquisitions. The expansion over the
last four years was engineered by O'Leary and Perik, a pair of
aggressive Canadian-born entrepreneurs. Three months ago, Learning
Co. purchased Broderbund Software Inc., acquiring the Carmen
Sandiego and other well-known product lines.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Learning Co. is on the other side of the acquisition table.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel's financial woes illustrate its reasons for acquiring the
software giant. Learning Co. has built up a portfolio of popular
and well-known software titles, including ``Reader Rabbit'' and
``Carmen Sandiego'' educational software as well as the
best-selling games ``Myst'' and ``Riven.''
</P>
<P>
   Learning Co. president O'Leary said that the deal will give
Mattel instant credibility in the education and entertainment
software market, a market which boasted 1997 sales of $1.8 billion
and is expected to grow rapidly thanks to surging sales of cheap
home computers. ``There's a tremendous synergy across these two
companies,'' said O'Leary. ``We're beginning to see that the toy
industry and the educational software industry are almost morphing
together.''
</P>
<P>
   James McNeal, professor of marketing at Texas A&AMP;M University,
says that Mattel's traditional toys are losing their appeal to
parents, who want Junior to learn as he plays. ``Play items had
better have learning value,'' McNeal said. The Learning Co. will
bring popular educational software into the Mattel stable, and help
Mattel create educational programs based on its own established
brands like Barbie and Hot Wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mattel is finding it harder to sell its established
toys, such as Barbie dolls, through traditional retail outlets.
Barad said that the company's unexpectedly weak numbers were caused
when major toy stores failed to place their traditional restocking
orders the week after Thanksgiving Day. Retailers, she said, are
trying to keep their own inventories as lean as possible, and are
willing to run out of popular items rather than be stuck with
unsold toys.
</P>
<P>
   Barad vowed to reduce her firm's reliance on retail sales. She
said that the acquisition of the Learning Co. is part of that
strategy, along with the purchase in July of the Pleasant Co.,
makers of the popular American Girl doll line. Learning Co. sells
about 14 percent of its products directly to schools and consumers,
while Pleasant Co. sells most of its products through catalogs.
Mattel's eventual goal is to use the expertise of these companies
to move a growing percentage of its annual sales away from
retailers, and toward catalogs and the Internet. In particular,
Barad said the Learning Co. acquisition ``will accelerate our
efforts to take our own brands into the interactive space.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
