<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9429 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALESTINIAN-REACT-121     12-14 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIAN-REACT-1215-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON VISIT HERALDS NEW U.S.-PALESTINIAN RELATIONSHIP
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-CLINTON-1215.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, The Gaza Strip _ Eager to show the new relations
between the PLO and the United States, Palestinian Legislator Hatem
Eid raised his voice in a crowded seaside fish restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have good relations with the U.S. Embassy,'' said the wiry
former inmate of Israeli jails, ``We also have good contact with
the CIA!''
</P>
<P>
   For a PLO activist to brag publicly about contact with the grand
agent of imperialism seemed unthinkable just a few years ago. The
PLO resented the United States, and the United States vilified the
PLO as hijackers and terrorists. But Monday in Gaza, the new
relationship between the United States and the PLO was confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   In the first visit of a U.S. president to Palestinian-controlled
territory, President Bill Clinton not only spent a day in Gaza but
addressed several hundred PLO activists.
</P>
<P>
   Many were former guerrillas, who fought in Lebanon or as street
activists in the Intifada uprising. Hundreds spent time in Israeli
jails.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that in 1979, then-U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations Andrew Young lost his job because he met with PLO
representatives without telling his boss, then-President Jimmy
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   The cliche in the streets of Gaza Monday, from the
heavily-patrolled avenues to the sandy alleys of the refugee camps,
was that this was the first time you saw U.S. flags in Gaza when
they were not in flames.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S.-Palestinian relationship, at times encouraged and
at times detested by Israelis, has developed over the years. There
were secret talks going back to the 1970s. In 1988, the U.S.
coached Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, long considered a
dangerous man, on how to officially recognize Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis point out that, when former Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin shook Arafat's hand in 1993, it cleared the way for Americans
to get closer to him. Arafat, the former terrorist now has a Nobel
Peace Prize and is seen as key to keeping the Palestinians on a
moderate path.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the CIA has trained Arafat's security forces.
Since 1994, the United States has given $75 million in economic aid
to the incipient Palestinian government.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton caused a stir
when, speaking to a group of Israeli and Arab youth, she said it
would be appropriate for the Palestinians to have some sort of
state.
</P>
<P>
   Those comments, though disavowed by the White House, were not
lost on Palestinians or their children. Hundreds of them waved
flags and lined the roads of a refugee camp to give an enthusiastic
greeting to the first lady on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians still feel that President Clinton's administration
favors Israel, but they see a change coming. Clinton lavished
praise on the activists gathered Monday, thanking them for dropping
their call for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very, very, different situation and we feel we are
going to get our rights,'' said Khaled Musmar, who ran the Voice of
the Palestinian Revolution radio station in Lebanon in the early
1980s. He was among several PLO officials watching with intensely
as a hotel television showed Clinton arriving in Gaza by
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
