u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRID-NEES-BOS &LR;      12-14 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRID-NEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL GRID LOOKING TO MORE US ACQUISITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ National Grid Group Plc is expected to use New England
Electric System as a beachhead to acquire more US electric
utilities as states begin to open their markets to competition,
officials of the British company said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to develop a strong busines here in the northeast with
the goal of expanding into other parts of the United States that
undergo deregulation,'' said David G. Jefferies chairman of
National Grid, which runs the electricity transmission network in
England and Wales. ``Naturally there may be other opportunities and
NEES would be the natural platform.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston Monday, Jefferies and Alfred D. Houston, New England
Electric System's chairman, formally announced that National Grid
is offering to buy New England Electric for $3.2 billion in cash.
The deal, signed late Sunday, values New England Electric shares at
$53.75 apiece, a 25 percent premium over Friday's closing price of
$43 a share.
</P>
<P>
   However, news of the deal prompted the Westborough, Mass.
utility's shares to soar 5 1/4 points to close at 48 1/4, reducing
the acquisition premium to 11.4 percent. National Grid said it will
also assume $1.4 billion of long-term debt. National Grid's shares
fell 10.5 pence to 488 pence on the London stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the latest scramble among major foreign utility
companies to enter the US market, which is undergoing a rocky
transition toward open competition after nearly 100 years of
monopolistic practices. Last week ScottishPower Plc said it would
take over PacifiCorp, an Oregon utility, for $7.9 billion. National
Grid's purchase also follows a deal by BEC Energy, parent company
of Boston Edison, to pay $950 million for Commonwealth Energy
System of Cambridge, Mass., creating the largest Massachusetts
utility with nearly 1.3 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is increasing pressure on nearly any utility trying to
survive on a stand alone basis,'' said James F. Calllahan, a
partner at Arthur Andersen LLP in Boston and director of its New
England energy practice. ``Companies that come in, like National
Grid, are looking to improve efficiencies, gain better economies of
scale in the transmission business, and will invest in more
technology if its spread over a large customer base.''
</P>
<P>
   Just whether foreign ownership of New England Electric, which
operates in Massachusetts, New Hampshire and Rhode Island, will
result in regulatory problems remains unclear. US law makes it
difficult for a overseas companies to buy American utilities. And
while Congress in the early 1990s modified the foreign ownership
rules, the PacifiCorp buyout is expected to be a test case for the
changes, several analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Monday said he did not expect any problems getting
federal regulatory approval. The purchase of New England Electric
will also need a series of approvals from within the states it
serves and Hart-Scott Rodino approval. Monday officials from both
companies said they would seek shareholder approval early next
year. When the deal is completed Richard Sergel, New England
Electric's president and chief executive, will join the National
Grid board and Houston who will step down as chairman. He will
remain a consultant for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Monday Jeffries said both companies began initial discussion
last December about a possible union with more serious negotiations
beginning in September. A major appeal for Nationial Grid was New
England Electric's strength in the transmission business _
high-voltage lines between power generation plants and the New
England electric grid that distributes power where its needed. New
England Electric, with 2,040 miles of transmission cables,
dominates Massachusetts and is second only to Northeast Utilities,
which is the largest in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that if we expand to the United State we want buy
into strength and we soon realized NEES had what we wanted with a
strong management team, proven track record in operations, a
well-trained work force, and very good cash flow that will add to
our earnings immediately,'' said Jefferies who helped form National
Grid in 1989, when the British government exited from electric
transmission business and sold it to investors to create an
independent company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nearly 10 years experience in the competitive electric
transmission business in England; Massachusetts is just getting
strated. So we see a lot of opportunities here.''
</P>
<P>
   New England Electric said no layoffs were planned as a result of
the deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
