<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAY THE PATRIOTS LEFT BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ship of Fools that is the Connecticut state legislature will
set sail sometime Tuesday. Destination: Poor House.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the experts in these matters say. I'm just passing
along the news.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, the local entry in the National Football League
will cease to exist as we know it. They will belong to someone
else. They will be the (Future) Connecticut Patriots. From this day
forward, they belong to Them, not to Us. That's just the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   For 28 years they have officially been known as the New England
Patriots, but they have always remained the (de facto) Boston
Patriots. There has never really been any ambiguity about that.
They will continue to be known as the New England Patriots, but
once they cross that state line they will be the (de facto)
Hartford Patriots, and God bless 'em. Bob Kraft will have made his
choice, and his choice will be Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is Boston. Hartford is Hartford. What's ours is ours.
What's theirs is theirs. We have very little in common. That's a
totally different market down there, no matter what Greg Aiello
says.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Aiello is the NFL's vice president of public relations. He
tells us in the pages of Sports Business Journal that ``Boston will
still be designated as a primary market for the Patriots. The
Patriots will still be Boston's team; they'll just be playing at
another site in that region.''
</P>
<P>
   Where's this guy from? (itals)Montana?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Earth to Greg: Go to Hartford and ask for a frappe and see what
you get.
</P>
<P>
   I don't care how many season ticket-holders the Patriots already
have from Connecticut, Central Mass., Western Mass., and Rhode
Island, people who will actually find it easier to get to the game.
That isn't the point, and never was the point. The Patriots as
we've known them have always had a Boston base. They were born
here, and they never really left here. What's such a big deal about
going to Foxborough? It's Greater Boston. Hey, in Houston, it would
easily be inside the city limits.
</P>
<P>
   But Hartford, that's an entirely different matter. The Patriots
might just as well be going to Maui. That's Them territory, not Us
territory.
</P>
<P>
   I do feel somewhat sorry for Bob Kraft, even though he is going
to make a lot of money in his new stadium. He is not, contrary to
what his growing number of detractors think, all about the money.
He is mostly about the money, sure, but not completely. Going to
Hartford is going to be a very painful thing for a man as vain as
Bob Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   By going to Hartford Bob Kraft will never get what he really
wants, and that is to be Mr. Boston. It's either got to be Newton
or it's got to be Newington; you can't have both. Given a choice,
he'd take the former.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he is desperate enough, and foolish enough, to think he
really can have it all. He may believe he can yank the Patriots out
of Massachusetts _ out of (itals)Boston(unitals) _ and no one will
mind up here because he moved the team to Hartford instead of Los
Angeles. He may share the Aiello view. Well, if he does believe
that, he will be wrong. By about the third game of that first
season in Hartford, he will discover that interest in his precious
team up here will be waning. Sometimes I think he's confused. He
acts as if he owns the Red Sox, and not the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut is right to want the Patriots, Red Sox, Celtics,
Bruins, Revolution or any other Boston sports team. Sports
franchises are good for a region. To argue otherwise is to reveal
terminal ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   They are important, but they're not all-important, and the tail
must never wag the dog. In the modern world of finance, it is
appropriate and logical for government to help a franchise get
things done, but that is the clear order, not the other way around.
In the case of Connecticut, the state is not helping Bob Kraft; it
is slobbering over him.
</P>
<P>
   What it has done to induce the Patriots to abandon Massachusetts
is overpay, and overpay to such an extent that the deal concocted
by Governor John Rowland and his henchmen establishes a new
standard for boosterism lunacy, even outdoing the laughable
giveaways in such places as St. Louis, Baltimore, and Charlotte. I
have a name for the new edifice they plan on building atop the
toxic waste dump down there _ the P.T. Barnum Memorial Stadium. All
in all, it's not a bad name at all, since the great 19th century
showman was a bona fide Connecticut guy. They could also re-name
Interstate 91 Tom Thumb Drive if they choose.
</P>
<P>
   Don't these legislators in Connecticut read the papers? Don't
they know that Bob Kraft was willing to accept a deal from the
Massachusetts state senate that was so favorable to the state that
the senate president framed it as a deal Kraft had to refuse?
Except that he didn't? Kraft was willing to accept a very fair
(perhaps even poor in the context) deal from his own state senate.
But the minute he crossed the state line he became the No. 1
candidate for World's Greediest Man. The more the pathetic
supplicants in Connecticut offered, the bigger his eyes got.
</P>
<P>
   The deal makers in Connecticut come away looking hopelessly
desperate and Bob Kraft comes away looking utterly shameless. Did
he not have a warning buzzer of some sort in his head telling him
to stop being so greedy? Where was son Jonathan, or Andy Wasynchuk,
or (itals)anybody(unitals) to save Kraft from himself? They have
subsequently modified the agreement with terms that are more
reasonable for the state of Connecticut, but it still stands as the
single most ridiculous demonstration of, to borrow a phrase,
corporate welfare doled out in the history of this country.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he shouldn't be going anywhere, and he wouldn't be if
our own loathsome legislators were not living in terror. God forbid
anyone in the House should question Tom Finneran, the esteemed
Speaker, who, like so many modern meglomaniacs, loves to refer to
himself in the third person.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Bob Kraft is lying about his financial plight, I do not
know. All we know is that he has chosen to make his play now, and
that play is a move to another state, another market, another
culture and, frankly, an entirely different world where they don't
talk quite so funny.
</P>
<P>
   Today they will officially be lame ducks, the (Boston) Patriots
no more. They're all yours, Hartford. Maybe you can get a bearded
lady to sing the first national anthem at P.T. Barnum Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
