<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATURN-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HEAD OF SATURN SHATTERS GLASS CEILING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Tenn., Del.)   (jw) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Facing a shrinking small-car market and struggling to
repair its once-legendary labor relations, General Motors' Saturn
division Monday appointed an expert on sport utility vehicles and
factory management to become chairwoman and president on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The new head of Saturn, Cynthia Trudell, will become the first
woman to head a car division at any domestic or foreign automaker.
GM had been criticized both inside and outside the auto industry
when a management shake-up on Oct. 6 left white men holding all the
jobs in the top three layers of management.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Trudell said that she wanted to push Saturn into new
segments of the auto market while strengthening the division's
experiment in close cooperation between management and labor.
``It's near and dear to my heart that it values partnerships and
relationships,'' she said in a telephone interview from Saturn's
giant factory in Spring Hill, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Saturn workers voted last summer to authorize a strike to
protest what they perceived as GM's lack of commitment to the
division, but the threat faded away after the automaker promised to
continue expanding its Tennessee operations.
</P>
<P>
   With the small-car market shriveling as gasoline prices tumble,
Saturn plans to enter the midsize-car market with a new model next
summer. Ms. Trudell said that after next summer, Saturn is
``definitely looking for ways to expand the portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Zarrella, GM's new president for North American
operations, acknowledged in an interview last month that Saturn was
working on a sport utility vehicle. ``We're trying to get that in
as quickly as we can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Trudell is now president of IBC Vehicles, a GM subsidiary in
Luton, England, that makes Frontera sport utility vehicles for the
European market. Set up in 1987 as a joint venture with Isuzu of
Japan, IBC is now wholly owned by GM, but the Frontera still
resembles the Isuzu Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   Saturn's current chairman and president, Donald Hudler, is
retiring after 43 years with GM and will become chief executive of
Saturn Retail Enterprises, a separate company that GM is setting up
with some Saturn dealers to own dealerships jointly, instead of
leaving auto retailing to the dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Trudell is one of the industry's very few female executives
who have spent a lot of time in factories. The industry's few
female managers have tended to wind up in the personnel, legal,
safety and governmental affairs divisions, often with limited
opportunities to advance.
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian who earned a doctorate in physical chemistry from the
University of Windsor in Ontario, Ms. Trudell worked from 1981 to
1990 at GM's huge transmission factory in Ypsilanti, Mich., where
she served as a senior engineering supervisor, superintendent of
manufacturing, manufacturing engineering manager and finally
operations manager. In the early 1990s, she worked on future engine
technologies and ran an engine factory and foundry in Canada. From
1995 until last year, she ran the assembly plant in Wilmington,
Del., where the Saturn midsized car will be produced.
</P>
<P>
   GM and Ford Motor Co. now have women running their Canadian
operations, and this fall, GM gave two women the title of general
managers of Buick and Oldsmobile, but those divisions have
virtually ceased to exist as separate organizations within GM. They
long ago lost their factories, and in the autumn reorganization
they were stripped of their sales and marketing operations, so the
new general managers are limited to managing the brands.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, full-fledged car divisions like Saturn with their own
manufacturing and marketing operations have been led only by men at
automakers in the United States and overseas, said David Lewis,
professor of business history at the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who is also a former aide to two GM presidents, said that
the domestic automakers had little interest in hiring or promoting
women, blacks and Jews until the late 1960s. While attitudes have
changed since then, resistance remains particularly strong to
putting women in charge of manufacturing operations.
</P>
<P>
   Some auto executives still ``will say privately that it's a
man's world and will stay that way,'' Lewis said, adding, ``They
wonder whether a woman can control things.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Hughes, a GM executive vice president, said in an
interview early this year that GM kept track of the number of women
and minorities in a wide range of jobs and looked at these figures
during every meeting on executive promotions. The automakers have
also set out strict policies against sexual harassment and they are
trying to halt the industry's longtime practice of holding business
lunches in strip bars.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of the insular Detroit auto industry for not promoting
women and minorities, long heard from outsiders, has recently been
voiced within the industry as well.
</P>
<P>
   Automotive News, a weekly trade journal that is required reading
for auto executives, accused the industry in a recent editorial of
saying that women and minority executives were ``in the pipeline''
but never promoting them. ``On the diversity front, there is
progress, but to see it you need to run an arthroscope down the
pipeline,'' the magazine said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
