<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-NEWCLASS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Delta business class a legroom up
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines on Monday unveiled its new
premium-service section, dubbed BusinessElite, to be phased in on
international aircraft over the next eight months.
</P>
<P>
   BusinessElite will replace separate first- and business-class
sections on 57 MD-11 and Boeing 767 jets that fly overseas. It also
will be installed in 14 new Boeing 777 widebodies on order.
</P>
<P>
   The first MD-11 fitted with the new seats and cabin decor will
enter service on an Atlanta-London route Wednesday. The rest of the
planes will be refitted over the next eight months.
</P>
<P>
   Delta said it will spend $314 million on the project.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of BusinessElite is legroom. Seat pitch _ the
distance between a point on one seat and the same spot on the seat
ahead _ will be 60 inches.
</P>
<P>
   That's from 5 to 12 inches greater than other carriers'
business-class sections and 2 inches more than the current
first-class pitch on Delta's international 767s.
</P>
<P>
   Delta marketing chief Fred Reid said customer research showed an
industry-leading seat pitch was the surest way to win favor. ``For
(international business) travelers, comfort translates into one
word: space,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new recliner seats also feature electric controls and
built-in video entertainment consoles. Delta said it also will
boost the flight attendants-to-passengers ratio and revise food and
drink menus, with those changes appearing next spring. Fares will
remain at current business-class levels.
</P>
<P>
   Delta follows a handful of other carriers that have ditched
separate first- and business-class sections in recent years. The
risk lies in alienating first-class passengers, who typically
include a mix of high rollers and frequent fliers using upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   But the business-class market is much larger and growing faster,
and Delta does not compete on many prime first-class international
routes, Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are routes with a critical mass of investment bankers,
supermodels and rock stars, and we're just not on many of them,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Samuel Buttrick of PaineWebber said first class remains
a valuable perk for an airline's loyal passengers. But he added
Delta ``will be improving the product for a lot more people than it
will be degrading it for.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately Monday, Delta said it finalized a ``code-share'' deal
to market seats on thrice-weekly China Southern Airlines flights
between Los Angeles and Guangzhou, China. The deal gains Delta its
first presence in China.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2003EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9449 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-2ndTake     12-14 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: pitfalls we can.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cuba is determined that its election process never become
dependent upon big private financial contributors, for one thing.
The presiding officer also hopes he can help it avoid the spasms of
harsh personal vituperation he sometimes sees in Congress.
Reputedly the most influential of Castro's top-tier advisers,
Alarcon is said to have the last word on dealings with our country.
He talks freely of changes in Cuban society, apparently comfortable
with their pace of development.
</P>
<P>
   Along the streets and quaint public squares of several Cuban
towns, free enterprise has established a modest beachhead at the
retail level. Officially sanctioned for only the past four years,
family-sized entrepreneurial businesses are setting up shop every
day. Most of these families own small restaurants in private homes
or sell produce grown on individual farms, displayed in open,
city-built markets.
</P>
<P>
   Few if any of these independent merchants grow rich. But most
with whom I talked express satisfaction with the chance to promote
their own economic betterment.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, all groceries had to be purchased at state-owned
``supermarkets'' where public coupons are redeemed and only pesos
are accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can sell everything I grow and bring _ every day,'' boasted
one vendor of fresh vegetables. He tells me his family farm is
almost two hours distant from the market site. Another said she
lives almost three hours' drive time away. Each makes the trek
daily during the prime growing season with a truckload of produce,
and both expect to sell everything they have on display before
beginning the homeward drive. Saturdays are the best.
</P>
<P>
   At one open-air market in Havana one Saturday, I counted 67
vegetable stalls, 15 meat market vendors and five merchants of
home-baked pastries, jams and bottled fruit juice. They display
their wares in seven rows arranged rectangularly under strips of
roofing to offer shade from the Cuban sun. Several hundred
customers browsed while others congregated, discussing prices and
the day's events, under trees that line the avenue and give a leafy
awning to the crowded sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   All the merchandise I saw was homemade or homegrown. There were
individual displays of fruits and vegetables, including some exotic
wares rare to North American grocery shoppers: yucca root, papayas,
guavas, shallots and capotes (a melon-like delicacy).
</P>
<P>
   Most fresh vegetables are quoted at prices that would be cheap
by our standards. Newly picked limes and grapefruit went for less
than three cents a pound. Fresh pork, depending on the cut, varied
from 70 cents to $1.20 in U.S. money. Ribs were offered at 95 cents
a pound. Chickens, available at other markets, had sold out here.
Reportedly, they're cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   What can a small business entrepreneur take home for his day's
work? One assured me that he'd cleared 1,350 pesos the previous
Saturday. On the official exchange rate, this comes to $64 _ not
bad in a country where average family income has been estimated at
around $100 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Local units of government are, in effect, the landlords. They
build and maintain the markets. Stalls are rented to vendors for
the peso equivalent of $7 a day, plus a tax of 13 percent on the
appraised value of the merchandise before sale.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable vendors have little or no trouble disposing of all
their wares each day. For meat marketers, things are less certain.
Cuban families can afford to serve meat only two or three times a
week.
</P>
<P>
   A major key to the success of any retailer, of course, is the
public's buying power. Among Cubans, cash has always been scarce.
But supply and demand under this limited experiment have been
working gradually in favor of both vendor and customer, I learned.
For the past three years, retail prices have gone down while the
volume of sales has grown.
</P>
<P>
   Pork is the main protein staple, its price a major index to the
cost of living. To sell beef is against the law. Cuba reserves its
cattle feed and pasture for milk-producing dairy herds and still
must import about half its dairy needs. Pork prices at the free
markets today, I'm told, are approximately one-third less than the
going retail rate three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At state-operated ``supermarkets,'' every family gets a free
basic monthly food ration to cover minimum diet requirements of
beans, rice and pork. The state dispenses coupons to each family
based on the number and age of its members. Every young child is
entitled daily to approximately a quart of milk without charge.
This package covers about half the average family's food
requirements, observers estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody gets rich, and nobody starves. Joy Gordon, in the January
1997 edition of The Atlantic Monthly, called what I'm seeing ``an
economy of loaves and fishes.'' Cubans need surprisingly little
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Besides food and free medical care, the state subsidizes cheap
public transportation and low rent. Housing costs a typical Cuban
family only about 8 percent of its income. But even in a land of
modest luxuries, everybody must have some money. Here, everybody
works, but wages are low.
</P>
<P>
   How do trained physicians and full college professors subsist on
salaries as little as $60 a month? Some, I'm told, moonlight as
taxi drivers or guitar strummers who serenade tourists in the old
city by night.
</P>
<P>
   Most Cubans, judging by those with whom I talked, think things
are getting better _ slowly. Hardened by adversity and reconciled
to reality, they cling to hope.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or e-mail: j.wright &LR; tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
