<HEADER>
A9450 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      12-14 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS, UNDER CLINTON'S GAZE, VOTE TO CHANGE CHARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (htv) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip _ With President Clinton as their witness,
hundreds of former Palestinian guerrilla fighters voted here Monday
to rid their organization's charter of any clauses calling for the
destruction of Israel, knocking down a critical roadblock on the
rutted path to peace.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said he accepted the vote, a
show of hands before a worldwide television audience, as ``a real
change, a very positive change.'' But he added that he would not
agree to meet the Friday deadline to return more land to the
Palestinians until they complied with more Israeli demands for
change.
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of breaking stalemates on such other sensitive
issues as the Israeli release of Palestinian prisoners, a three-way
meeting between Clinton, Netanyahu and Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, was scheduled for Tuesday morning at the Erez
checkpoint between Israel and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   With a flurry of fingers, some barely held aloft, some thrust
into the air with exhilaration, the vote here Monday was momentous
for the Palestinians partly because it represented a new political
pragmatism and partly because it was overseen by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Playing preacher and healer, Clinton presided over what amounted
to a large reunion of the Palestine Liberation Organization at the
moment of its public transformation from outlaw group to nearly
sovereign entity and diplomatic partner of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am profoundly honored to be the first American president to
address the Palestinian people in a city governed by
Palestinians,'' Clinton said, bringing hundreds to their feet, as
he congratulated them on the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``By turning this page on the past you are taking the lead in
writing a new story for the future,'' he continued. ``And you have
issued a challenge to the government and the leaders of Israel to
walk down that path with you.''
</P>
<P>
   In the isolated Gaza Strip, the Palestinians pulled out all the
stops Monday to make Clinton's visit a celebration of imminent
statehood and endorsement by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a dream same as you,'' read posters pinned to trees
and lampposts and donkeys' saddlebags.
</P>
<P>
   American and Palestinian flags fluttered side by side on every
available pole, from the huge hand-sewn flags that draped the
control towers at the new Palestinian airport, where Clinton's
Marine One helicopter landed, to the paper flags in the hands of
schoolchildren adorning the littered route of the motorcade.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat reveled in the moment, which both he and the Americans
called historic many times. The flowery language flowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ancient city that receives you today has not seen many
happy days during its history,'' the Palestinian leader said. ``But
your presence here made us relive the golden days of Palestine.''
</P>
<P>
   At a ceremony to inaugurate the passenger terminal at the new
airport, the Palestinian leader prolonged the ribbon-cutting so
that mementos could be produced.Before viewing stands packed with
dignitaries, Arafat held steady the red ribbon while Clinton cut
off strip after souvenir strip.
</P>
<P>
   Mamoun Tamimi, who had traveled from Jordan to vote against the
change in the covenant, was not terribly impressed by the pomp.
``We should not give a freebie to Israel,'' he said. ``We should
link it with a deal that Israel should recognize our state and we
will recognize theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, everything in Gaza was pre-programmed, and there was no
element of surprise when the Palestinian National Council together
with other Palestinian leaders raised their hands in support of
Arafat's decision to amend the charter.
</P>
<P>
   It was nonetheless a delicate day of diplomacy for the Americans
because Netanyahu's acceptance could not be guaranteed. Clinton
risked a failed trip, but, given the unrest in the West Bank for
the last few weeks, the failure would be much larger than his.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
