<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9451 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-2NDTA     12-14 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip: than his. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nahum Barnea, an Israeli newspaper columnist, asserted that the
looming challenge for the Americans was ``how to conclude their
visit without leaving the country in flames.''
</P>
<P>
   Pronouncing the visit to Gaza a success, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright made it clear that the Americans believed the
Palestinians, in voting, had met a critical demand of the Israelis,
and that the Israelis would be called upon to comply with their own
promises, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis had insisted on the chrter change, she pointed out,
adding,``It's important for the Israelis to move forward on the
redeployment and I think it would be unfortunate if that did not
happen soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said he did feel vindicated by the Mondays vote.
``They told us it was impossible, and if you insist on it you're
jamming the process,'' he said. But to him, he said, that proved
that he could hold firm on the other demands, ``and in the same way
try to achieve the other changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Six days before he faces the threat of doom in a no-confidence
vote by the Israeli Parliament, Netanyahu is considered loath to
make any sudden moves forward on the peace agreement that cost him
his right-wing support.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian National Council was the Palestine Liberation
Organization's leadership in exile. This marked only its third
meeting on its home ground in the last 25 years. The first took
place in Jerusalem in 1964, before Israel annexed the eastern part.
</P>
<P>
   The second occurred in Gaza just two years ago, and it was
convened to do just what the leaders did Monday: annul the
offending clauses in the PLO charter. Although the Americans and
the previous Israeli administration accepted the results of that
meeting, the Israelis pointed to the continued inclusion of the
clauses in copies of the charter. They also said the vote should be
loud and public in order to send a message to the Palestinian
people.
</P>
<P>
   For the Palestinians, the Monday vote, attended by about 500 of
an estimated 650 members of the Palestinian National Council, did
not represent a newly felt renunciation of hostile feelings toward
Israel. It was a pragmatic move, most said, meant to appease
Clinton by satisfying Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   A student from the Islamic University, Mohammed Salah, 22, said
the vote itself, even if it produces a breakthrough in the peace
effort, was not terribly significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The charter is not a substantial issue for us,'' Salah said.
``Most people knew nothing about this charter until the Israelis
brought it to our attention. What was substantial was President
Clinton's visit because it sends many signs. It is a recognition.
Clearly, we are not considered anymore a people who nobody wants to
recognize.''
</P>
<P>
   With his special blend of empathy and stern counsel, Clinton at
once endorsed the Palestinian struggle, saying that he felt the
pain of the Palestinians' ``dispossession'' from their land. And he
advised them to feel empathy for the Israelis' point of view as
well, and suggested that Palestinian children not be taught to
glorify suicide bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our great American prophet, Martin Luther King, once said,
``The old law of an eye for an eye leaves everyone blind.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was one remark that went unapplauded by the Palestinians
gathered in Gaza.
</P>
</TEXT>
