<SLUG> BC-BBO-MOORE-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baseball has always had haves, have nots
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To those expecting the sky over baseball to crash any
day now, you can relax. The sun isn't headed for earth. If the Los
Angeles Dodgers can shove everything except the deed to the Pacific
Ocean into Kevin Brown's pockets, they can afford it.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for the sugar daddies of Mo Vaughn, Randy Johnson,
Mike Piazza and others with yearly earnings enough to push Asia
toward financial bliss by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is splurging on players' salaries, because baseball has
the money to do it. In fact, baseball hasn't been healthier.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance is all the way back to its record level before the
strike of the mid-1990s. The game is broadcast more than ever,
locally, nationally and internationally. There is baseball's boost
from last year's dream season, when Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa
ripped their way past Babe Ruth and Roger Maris in the record
books.
</P>
<P>
   Still, folks have this queasiness. It increases when a $57
million deal for Greg Maddux becomes obsolete after Bernie Williams
signs for $87 million or when the next player turns Brown's deal
into a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   This queasiness also is from the myth about baseball's haves and
have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees just won their second World Series in three
years, and they rank with the haves. So do the Atlanta Braves,
owners of a record seven consecutive trips to the postseason. While
the Baltimore Orioles, Boston Red Sox and Dodgers also own more
resources than most, the Pittsburgh Pirates, Montreal Expos and
Kansas City Royals don't.
</P>
<P>
   The myth? Thanks to the staggering deals by the Murdochs of the
game, baseball is becoming less competitive because of the greater
division between the haves and the have-nots. ``As for the truth,
baseball always has had these divisions, and it actually was much
worse in the past,'' said Leonard Koppett, the noted baseball
historian who has a recently published book, ``Koppett's Concise
History of Major League Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People keep talking about Montreal and Pittsburgh having
trouble competing. Listen, the St. Louis Browns were around for 52
years, and they finished first just once. I could go on and on.
Prior to free-agency (in 1975), if you were on the bottom, you
stayed there much longer. That's because the teams with the good
players were keeping them under the binding nature of the reserve
clause.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Koppett's research, from 1901 through 1968, four
teams won 79 percent of the AL pennants, and four teams won 75
percent of the NL pennants. From 1969 to 1981, when baseball went
to divisional play and still wasn't affected much by free-agency,
Koppett determined that four teams won 81 percent of the AL
division titles and four teams won 77 percent of the NL division
titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, here's the thing,'' Koppett said. ``Since 1982, when
baseball supposedly was going to have all of these problems from
free-agency, all 14 AL teams have won a division title at least
once. Every NL team has done so, except Montreal and the two
expansion teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Koppett chuckled, before saying, ``One of those two
expansion teams (the Florida Marlins) was a wild card in 1997, and
all they did was win the World Series. Twenty years from now, even
with the current salary rise, you'll see the same thing _
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: tlmajc(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
