<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-RAIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pittsburgh's problem summed up: QB
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The Pittsburgh Steelers left here Sunday evening
looking for a miracle that might put them in the playoffs. They
won't get one, so director of operations Tom Donahoe and coach Bill
Cowher might spend the offseason searching for an experienced
quarterback to lift the offense out of its doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of reasons explain why the club has managed only two
offensive touchdowns the last 18 quarters, but most of them revolve
around the regression of quarterback Kordell Stewart. In his second
season as the full-time starter, Stewart has lacked the big-play
spark that highlighted his '97 performance.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem is that first-year offensive coordinator
Ray Sherman doesn't have full command of the attack. Sherman is
trying to serve as coordinator and quarterbacks coach at the same
time. That was fine for predecessor Chan Gailey, who has more
experience. It's been tough, however, on Sherman, a stand-up guy
who is under all kinds of pressure.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that Stewart wept openly on the sidelines after
being replaced by Mike Tomczak. A few veterans noted that the
display would hurt his standing in a city whose fans want tough
guys at every position.
</P>
<P>
   Gotham gurus
</P>
<P>
   A photo of a glaring Bill Parcells was on the cover of Sports
Illustrated last week. After Sunday night's victory at Miami, the
magazine ought to consider his New York Jets coordinators, Charlie
Weis (offense) and Bill Belichick (defense), for this week's front.
Belichick had a masterful game plan, protecting suspect corners
Otis Smith and Ray Mickens (in place of the injured Aaron Glenn),
and forcing Dan Marino to throw everything underneath. Weis worked
to create great matchups, especially when he was able to get
wideout Wayne Chrebet working against strongside linebacker Robert
Jones on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   For the record
</P>
<P>
   Former Dolphins players Bob Griese, Larry Csonka and Dick
Anderson all conceded last week that they were pulling against
Denver's bid for an undefeated season. In a quieter corner of the
world, so was Hall of Fame receiver Dante Lavelli, who played 11
seasons (1946-56) with the Cleveland Browns. From Oct. 19, 1947,
through Oct. 9, 1949, the Browns went unbeaten 29 games in a row,
posting a record of 27-0-2. ``All they talk about is Miami going
17-0 in 1972, and now Denver maybe not losing this year,'' Lavelli
said last week. ``What about our 29-game streak?'' The problem is,
the Browns accomplished their record in the old All-America
Football Conference. When the AAFC folded after the '49 season, the
NFL absorbed three of its franchises but didn't recognize any of
its records. When the NFL and AFL merged in 1966, all of the
statistics from the younger league were included.
</P>
<P>
   Zebra time
</P>
<P>
   Ever heard of Kirk Dornan? He's the back judge who helped keep
the Dolphins' unbeaten record unchallenged. Dornan is the official
who came across the end zone to rule correctly that Giants wide
receiver Amani Toomer had held on to the 37-yard scoring pass from
Kent Graham that gave New York its 20-16 victory against Denver.
The field judge, David Warden, originally signaled that Toomer had
not controlled the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Low profile
</P>
<P>
   Notable in The Sporting News' list of the 100 most powerful
people in sports published last week is that it included zero NFL
players. The league was represented by commissioner Paul Tagliabue
(No. 2), Dallas owner Jerry Jones (25), Denver owner Pat Bowlen
(42), Seattle owner Paul Allen (45), league president Neil Austrian
(54), Denver coach Mike Shanahan (58), Carolina owner Jerry
Richardson (62), NFLPA executive director Gene Upshaw (64), NFL
Properties president Sara Levinson (71), Cleveland Browns president
Carmen Policy (73) and Green Bay coach Mike Holmgren (87).
</P>
<P>
   Big-play Ray
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta agent Ray Anderson always has had a player clientele
that reflects the classy way he conducts business, and now he's
becoming a power-broker among coaches as well. Anderson represents
Dennis Green of Minnesota and Tampa Bay's Tony Dungy, and he could
have a very busy offseason. Anderson also represents Vikings
offensive coordinator Brian Billick, Stanford coach Tyrone
Willingham and Oakland defensive coordinator Willie Shaw. All three
are likely candidates for NFL vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback update
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-eight different quarterbacks now have started at least one
game in '98, and the number could pass 60 next week. Steve Bono
will start for St. Louis in place of the injured Tony Banks. With
Jamie Martin out for the season and Mark Brunell still lame with an
ankle injury, rookie Jonathan Quinn will start for Jacksonville. In
New England, team doctors have recommended that Drew Bledsoe rest
his surgically repaired right index finger, so Scott Zolak could
get a start against San Francisco on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tops
</P>
<P>
   Wideout Terance Mathis battled the flu Sunday but still posted
big numbers in Atlanta's victory at New Orleans. The perennially
underappreciated Mathis, never noted for speed, averaged 33.0 yards
on six catches and scored touchdowns of 62 and 63 yards. His 198
yards are a club record. Quarterback Chris Chandler's 345 passing
yards were his most in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive best
</P>
<P>
   Giants linebacker Jesse Armstead has struggled through an
injury-marred season, but he had 13 tackles, two quarterback
pressures and one pass defensed in the upset victory over the
Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Truly special
</P>
<P>
   Even with kickoff returns for touchdowns by Corey Harris and Pat
Johnson (Baltimore) and David Palmer (Minnesota), it's tough to
overlook the performance of Vikings kicker Gary Anderson. The
15-year veteran hit six field goals Sunday, setting an NFL record
for 34 consecutive conversions on three-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Many happy returns
</P>
<P>
   Besides the three kickoff returns on Sunday, the NFL had a punt,
four fumbles and five interceptions run back for scores. The 13
return touchdowns brings the 1998 total so far to 100, which
projects to 115 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing . . . .
</P>
<P>
   Second-year veteran Matthew Hatchette was scheduled to be the
Vikings' third wideout this year, but that was before Randy Moss
came along. Hatchette has the kind of size (6-2, 195) the Vikings
love. Filling in for the injured Jake Reed on Sunday, he had five
catches for 95 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Stat stuff
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Ravens are 6-18 in the division since owner Art
Modell moved his franchise there in 1996, just another reason why
coach Ted Marchibroda will be fired in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations to former Falcons wide receiver Bert Emanuel,
who plays in Tampa Bay. He and wife, Teri, recently welcomed their
third daughter, Brittni. . . . San Diego general manager Bobby
Beathard has asked Bob Toledo about his interest in coaching at the
NFL level, but he denied that the UCLA coach is a candidate for the
Chargers' vacancy. . . . The Oakland secondary, already missing
Eric Allen, continues to be ravaged by injuries. At one point
Sunday, the Raiders had former wide receiver Bucky Brooks at one
cornerback spot and one-time college tailback Calvin Branch at
strong safety. . . . Browns president Carmen Policy met Saturday
night at the Broncos team hotel with Denver coach Mike Shanahan in
what was termed a ``philosophical discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   The last word(s)
</P>
<P>
   Seattle strong safety Jay Bellamy on the performance by San
Diego rookie quarterback Ryan Leaf in a mop-up role: ``He threw
some passes that weren't even professional. I'm not trying to be
cruel; I'm just trying to be honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
