<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-HEALTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves surgery a preemptive strike to prevent future damage
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Doctors averted probable disaster Monday when they
repaired the heart of Falcons coach Dan Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   One of Reeves' heart arteries was completely blocked and two
others were nearly as clogged, Reeves' doctors said after his
open-heart, quadruple-bypass surgery at Atlanta's Piedmont
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had waited any longer, there would have been damage to
the heart muscle _ a heart attack,'' said Dr. Charles Harrison, the
Falcons' team physician.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors emphasized that Reeves, whom they described as a strong
man in good physical condition, should recover fully and rapidly.
In a few weeks he may be able to return to coaching in a limited
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very optimistic that he's going to have a very good
result,'' said Dr. James Kauten, the cardiac surgeon who performed
the four-hour operation.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves is expected to be transferred from the intensive care
unit to a regular ward this morning and should be discharged from
Piedmont on Friday or Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The diagnosis and decision to operate were sudden. On Sunday
night, after the Falcons game in New Orleans, Reeves told Harrison
he had had pains in his chest and throat for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The pains were familiar: Reeves, who has no family history of
heart disease and no risk factors except high cholesterol,
underwent balloon angioplasty in August 1990 to repair two artery
blockages. The blockages later recurred, but Reeves never took
heart medication, only drugs aimed at reducing his cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans, Reeves tried to dismiss his pains as heartburn
or indigestion and told Harrison, ``I know I'm overreacting.'' But
Harrison insisted that he undergo tests as soon as he returned to
Atlanta. On the plane, Harrison gave Reeves two aspirin, which thin
the blood, making it flow more easily.
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday morning, Dr. Charlie Brown of Piedmont performed a
heart catheterization, a diagnostic procedure in which dye is
injected into the heart vessels.
</P>
<P>
   The catheterization revealed serious blockages. One heart artery
was completely blocked by plaque, a substance made of fatty cells
that accumulate on the inside of arteries. Another artery was 90
percent clogged and a third was 80 percent to 90 percent blocked,
Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors considered performing balloon angioplasty, a procedure
in which a surgeon inserts a tiny balloon into a blocked artery and
then inflates it to force plaque out of the way. But they opted for
bypass surgery because of the extensiveness of the blockages.
</P>
<P>
   To create the bypasses, Kauten grafted onto Reeves' heart blood
vessels from other parts of his body. He used both internal mammary
arteries, which lie behind the pectoral muscles of the chest, as
well as two pieces of vein from Reeves' right leg, removed via two
short incisions.
</P>
<P>
   As usual during open-heart bypass surgery, Reeves' heart was
stopped, and he was kept alive by a heart-lung pump. Because the
breastbone must be cut in half to perform the operation, Reeves can
expect to feel some pain as it heals. His right leg also might
cause him temporary discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors will prescribe Reeves analgesic medication to control
the pain, but they don't expect him to stay on it for very long.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time he gets back to coaching football, he won't need
pain medication any more,'' Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison also said he plans to put Reeves on a more vigorous
cholesterol-reducing regimen, including medication and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been such a workaholic,'' Harrison said wryly, ``but
we'll encourage him to do more exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
