<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-HUMMER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves' strength as coach will show in coming weeks
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The day before, the only team Dan Reeves had given his
heart to was a collection of soiled birds atop the NFC West. By
Monday morning, all that had changed. We interrupt this Falcons
dream for a message from Real Life, maker of all sorts of fine
complications. Suddenly, looming large was the very clean
catheterization team. And the heart pump team. And don't forget the
surgical team. The coach couldn't have made it without them. Today,
we appreciate the fact that their records are a little better than
12-2.
</P>
<P>
   If anything should have been learned during the brief Reeves
regime, it's that he surely will try to put open-heart surgery
behind him quickly. That's him, an old-school tough guy whose first
inclination would be to rub a little dirt on the clogged artery and
get back in the game. ``He actually sounded like he felt a little
guilty for having a health problem,'' team president Taylor Smith
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Concern for the man took the point Monday. Reeves is a member of
that club that has turned competitive drive into arterial disease.
``In the NFL, we know that coaching is a major risk factor, but
it's not listed in most of the heart books,'' Falcons team doctor
Charles Harrison said, only half-kiddingly. Following close behind
had to be dark thoughts about it just being the latest curse on a
blighted franchise. Here the Falcons were, completing the most
enjoyable season in 18 years, with their fans holding their breath
the whole way for fear of it all blowing away. Then the designer
and philosophical core of the whole deal goes in for major surgery
just weeks before the playoffs. ``Oh, so this is where it all falls
apart,'' those programmed to pessimism had to think.
</P>
<P>
   I can't quite go along with the company line that the Falcons
will not miss a beat. Of course there's reason to worry about the
team's direction. If it were that easy to get by without the head
coach, why not send them all on early vacation every December and
let the assistants get a little experience? Does your business
operate as smoothly without your boss around? (Perhaps a bad
example.)
</P>
<P>
   What happens the next few weeks will be the ultimate test of
Reeves' organizational model. Appeals to emotion will come and go.
Emergency head coach Rich Brooks offered the first of those Monday:
``(Beating Detroit Sunday) will do more for his health than
anything.'' But more tangibly, it's the system that Reeves has
installed that will have to be strong enough to survive his
absence.
</P>
<P>
   They scurried about Suwanee trying desperately to simulate
normalcy. Brooks began his presentation by reviewing Sunday's
Saints game in minute detail, just as Reeves usually does on
Mondays. They even served the traditional Monday grub, even if that
meant the ironic twist of dishing up pepperoni pizza at a press
conference centering on blocked arteries.
</P>
<P>
   While on the medical front, the word was encouraging. To hear
the doctors tell it, Reeves will be game-planning in two weeks, on
the sideline in four weeks and scaling Everest by June.
</P>
<P>
   Just so long that the coach is not rushed back into the
competitive kiln. No mistake, this is the point upon which a
fantastic season will turn. But it can't mean as much as a single
heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hummer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: steve(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
