A9457 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MEETINGS-NOTES15-     12-14 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MEETINGS-NOTES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves stay status quo, don't make roster changes
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ The Braves leave baseball's winter meetings
this morning as they arrived four days before _ with open ears,
empty agenda and zippered wallet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of these meetings came seeds of ideas that may grow into
something more than just ideas,'' general manager John Schuerholz
said. ``But that's pretty much what we expected. We didn't expect
to take any action. We still don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Although left fielder Ryan Klesko remains the most eligible
Braves player for dealing, nothing came close. The Boston Red Sox
made a serious inquiry, but progress stopped after the Braves asked
for right-hander Derek Lowe in addition to a middle-infield
prospect, possibly shortstop Adam Everett. The offer might be
revisited. Everett, from Kennesaw, was Boston's first-round pick
last year and cannot be traded until June, when he will have spent
a full year in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Reported interest in Klesko by the Tampa Bay Devil Rays never
progressed, and while Arizona had serious internal discussions
about the left fielder, they did not act upon them. The meetings'
biggest names _ Kevin Brown and Roger Clemens _ passed by without
any interest by the Braves, contrary to widespread rumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to a couple clubs where there may be some ideas
that, depending on how they finish their moves, may allow something
to work between two clubs,'' Schuerholz said. ``But it is not an
urgent matter. No one is forcing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Rule 5
</P>
<P>
   Braves minor-league outfielder Tyrone Pendergrass, whose 110
steals the past two seasons led the organization, was taken by the
Chicago White Sox with the final pick of the Rule 5 draft Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Pendergrass, a 22-year-old switch-hitting center fielder, led
the Class A Danville 97's with 143 hits, 73 runs and 10 triples
while stealing 39 bases, third most in the Carolina League. But
with prospect George Lombard slotted for Atlanta in 2000, the
organization declined to protect Pendergrass on the 40-man roster.
In four years in the system, he has played just five games above
the Class A level, and although he has 163 career steals in 382
games, he also struck out 196 times over the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Rule 5 draft involves minor-leaguers with three years of
experience who are left off 40-man rosters. Since their 40-man
roster is full, the Braves were ineligible to draft. The
organization lost no players in the Class AAA or Class AA phases of
the draft.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought
</P>
<P>
   Toronto GM Gord Ash hoped to have traded Clemens before he came
to Nashville and then expected to deal him before he left the
Opryland Hotel. Ash heads back to Canada 0-for-2.
</P>
<P>
   Although Texas remains a favorite to wind up with Clemens _
owner Tom Hicks has made it a personal mission _ dealings have
grown so complicated it might take months for Ash to sort his
options.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees and Houston remain in the running, with the
Astros staging a remarkable comeback. Owner Drayton McLane
apologized to Clemens' agents for incendiary remarks by Astros GM
Gerry Hunsicker, who on Sunday said he was ``outraged'' by
financial demands made by agents Randy Hendricks and Alan
Hendricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drayton said he was very sorry,'' Randy Hendricks said, ``and
asked if I wanted a personal apology from his employees and said he
did not do business that way. What they showed with their press
conference was that they're petty and jealous because I was dealing
with the owner.''
</P>
<P>
   McLane then offered a three-year deal at the Hendricks'
requested $43.5 million with an option year. Hendricks replied that
that offer already had been topped, not identifying a five-year $75
million offer made by Hicks. Whenever the money issue is resolved,
the participating teams still have to hash out a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Moves
</P>
<P>
   Butch Huskey , who hit .252 with 13 homers and 59 RBIs with the
Mets, was traded to the Mariners for minor-league pitcher Lesli
Brea. . . . Mark Petkovsek, 7-4 last season in St. Louis, was
traded to Anaheim for a player to be named. . . . Minnesota sent
outfielder Alex Ochoa (.257, two HR) to Milwaukee for a player to
be named. . . . Free-agent catcher Chad Kreuter signed a one-year
contract with Kansas City. . . . The Detroit Tigers signed free
agent catcher Bill Haselman to a two-year contract. . . . Former
Braves pitcher John LeRoy was released by Tampa Bay after going a
2-2 with a 7.75 ERA in the minors. LeRoy was Tampa Bay's 17th pick
in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
