<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT SUFFERS SETBACKS IN FIGHT TO AVOID IMPEACHMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton suffered new setbacks in his
battle against impeachment on Monday as his allies escalated their
counterattack on the Republican-led Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that political momentum may be moving against the
president, Republican Rep. Chris Shays of Connecticut said he is
reconsidering his earlier opposition to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Shays, a GOP moderate, requested a face-to-face meeting with
Clinton to discuss the president's insistence that he did not
commit perjury. White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton
intends to meet with Shays tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   In another blow for the White House, Republican Rep. Frank
LoBiondo of New Jersey, who had been undecided, declared his
support for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot in good conscience allow the nation's chief law
enforcement officer to violate the law without consequences,''
LoBiondo said.
</P>
<P>
   But the news wasn't all bad for Clinton. CNN reported that Rep.
Virgil Goode of Virginia, one of three Democrats who had declared
support for impeachment, is reconsidering his position. Goode could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The other two pro-impeachment Democrats are Rep. Ralph Hall of
Rockwall and Rep. Gene Taylor of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   A subdued Clinton repeated his willingness to cut a deal with
Congress that would result in a censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it's in the interest of the United States and
the American people to go through the impeachment process and have
a trial in the Senate,'' Clinton told reporters in Gaza City, in
the Gaza Strip, during a visit to the Middle East. The president is
scheduled to return to Washington tonight to await Thursday's House
vote.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton spoke of compromise, his allies criticized
Republican leaders for refusing to permit a vote on the censure
alternative. The House is scheduled to consider four articles of
impeachment accusing Clinton of perjury, obstruction of justice and
abuse of power. The four articles list 14 possible criminal
violations stemming from Clinton's efforts to hide his extramarital
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the leadership of the Congress has done is to prevent any
kind of compromise along the lines that the American people want to
see,'' Vice President Al Gore said. ``And instead, they threaten to
put the country through this long ordeal. It's not the right thing
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, who was traveling with the president, accused GOP
leaders of using the impeachment process to pursue a political
vendetta.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a small group in the Republican leadership who have
made it their mission in life to remove the president,'' Lockhart
said. Gore and Lockhart also ruled out the possibility that Clinton
will resign to avoid a protracted impeachment battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, of course that's not going to happen,'' Gore said.
Lockhart said Clinton's resignation ``would send a pretty sorry
signal to the American people'' that the president surrendered to
partisan pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Partisans on both sides agree that the outcome Thursday is
likely to hinge on about two dozen undecided Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Tarrant County lawmakers are expected to vote along party lines,
with the three Republicans _ Rep. Kay Granger of Fort Worth, Rep.
Joe Barton of Ennis and House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Irving
_ voting for impeachment. Democratic Rep. Martin Frost of Dallas
favors the censure alternative.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid impeachment, Clinton needs help from at least 13 of the
228 Republicans in the 435-member House. Only five, including
Shays, have indicated that they will oppose impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Shays said he had second thoughts when Clinton told reporters
again Sunday that he did not commit perjury. The Connecticut
congressman said Clinton's refusal to admit a criminal violation
shows that ``he still doesn't get it, and he's so intent on
avoiding prosecution that he's willing to put this country in
tremendous turmoil.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rep. Peter King of New York, who opposes impeachment,
urged House leaders to permit a vote on a censure resolution
condemning Clinton's behavior. Critics contend that censure, which
is not mentioned in the Constitution, would amount to a
congressional copout.
</P>
<P>
   King asserted that at least 15 Republicans privately favor
censure over impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's coming down to the wire. Right now it's too close
to call,'' he said on NBC's ``Today'' show. ``If everyone said
publicly what they're saying privately, this would be a whole
different story.''
</P>
<P>
   As the vote neared, outside organizations stepped up the
pressure on lawmakers. The liberal People For the American Way
announced a $75,000 radio ad campaign aimed at undecided lawmakers.
The ads will run Tuesday through Thursday in Washington,
Philadelphia and Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton supporters, including the Rev. Jesse Jackson, also
planned to hold a vigil outside the Capitol during Thursday's
debate. Conservative groups have been just as forceful in arguing
for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does this `rise to the level' of impeachment? You bet,''
Phyllis Schlafly, head of the conservative Eagle Forum, wrote in
Internet column on Monday. ``Clinton is a national embarrassment at
home and abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
