<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-ANNAN-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. CHIEF SAYS U.S. GOES TOO FAR IN CALLING FOR IRAQI'S OUSTER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan distanced himself
from the Clinton administration's policy on Iraq on Monday, saying
American calls for the overthrow of President Saddam Hussein went
beyond a Security Council resolution on what is demanded of Iraq
and ran contrary to the opinion of other United Nations members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The council resolution doesn't talk about getting rid of the
leadership,'' Annan said in an interview Monday, referring to the
1991 cease-fire agreement that laid down the conditions for lifting
sanctions imposed on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait in August
1990.
</P>
<P>
   In recent speeches, most clearly in one last week by National
Security Adviser Sandy Berger, Clinton administration officials
have offered the Iraqis a quick end to crippling sanctions in
return for a change in their leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Annan's remarks about differences with the United States were
made against a backdrop of worsening relations between the United
States and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The issues involved include Washington's refusal to pay more
than $1 billion in overdue assessments to the United Nations and
the administration's efforts to enhance the role of NATO while
paying what diplomats here see as only lip service to the
importance of the United Nations to American policies.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Annan met with four influential members of Congress
and was left with the impression, he said, that a new House and
Senate would have to take up outstanding issues anew next year, and
that there was no progress in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the secretary-general said the road to lifting sanctions
had been defined by the Security Council. Once Richard Butler, the
chief arms inspector, decides that Iraq has met the disarmament
qualifications laid down in the critical 1991 resolution, he said,
there should be no excuses for keeping sanctions _ in particular,
an oil embargo _ in place.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has said it will argue against lifting the
embargo until Hussein also meets other demands, including
accounting for Kuwaiti prisoners and improving Iraq's human rights
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's assume that tomorrow, or six months from now, Butler
were to say, `We've disarmed; we're moving on to monitoring,' ''
Annan said. ``The council will have to act, and then it creates a
very serious situation. What will the U.S. do with its veto? What
will the other 14 members do? And how does the world react?''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference earlier in the day, Annan said that ``there
are areas where Washington's policies diverge from that of the
U.N.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one case in point is that of Iraq, where the council
has made it clear that we should disarm Iraq,'' he said. ``And the
moment we get the indication from the inspectors, from Butler, that
Iraq has been disarmed, sanctions will be lifted. American policy
goes beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Annan also indicated that an early
comprehensive review of Iraq's relations with the United Nations
should take place no matter what kind of a report Butler submits in
the next few days on Baghdad's cooperation with inspections _ or
lack of it _ over the last three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Butler's U.N. Special Commission said Monday
that the report was likely to go to Annan by Tuesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The United States and Britain have said there should not be a
review until Iraq cooperates, although both countries appear to
accept that it is inevitable, and Clinton administration officials
have not told diplomats here how hard they will fight to postpone
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that the comprehensive review is something that
Iraq deserves or does not deserve,'' Annan said at his news
conference. ``I think the council itself would want to know, after
eight years of sanctions, where it stands.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general, summarizing the past year and looking
ahead, was not optimistic that war could be avoided in Iraq or in
Yugoslavia, where under Western pressure, President Slobodan
Milosevic has at least momentarily halted his campaign to put down
ethnic Albanian separatism in Kosovo Province.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best we can say is that in Kosovo, and in Iraq, all-out
war has been avoided for the time being,'' Annan said. ``But unless
people abide by their commitments, and unless they redouble their
efforts to find peaceful solutions, we have every reason to fear
the worst in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, as arms inspection teams were completing their
withdrawal from Iraq after conducting surprise searches, the Iraqis
renewed personal attacks on Butler, a former Australian
representative at the United Nations, calling him ``a failed
diplomat and a trivial spy.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan said he did not condone this Iraqi tactic, but he also
repeated criticisms of Butler, an outspoken arms control expert who
has often given Iraqis as good as he gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I don't think there should be any rhetoric when
we have serious and hard work to do,'' the secretary-general said.
``I don't believe in megaphone diplomacy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9466 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-DELAY-BOS &LR;      12-14 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DELAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAN DELAY KEY TO POSSIBLE CLINTON IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Representative Tom DeLay, hardly a household name
anywhere but in the US House, could go down in history as the
lawmaker most responsible for impeaching President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, a Texas Republican and the House majority whip, has been
one of the president's earliest and harshest critics. But it's no
exaggeration to say DeLay almost singlehandedly has blocked the
House from seeking a lesser punishment than impeachment through his
staunch and compelling opposition to consideration of a censure
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats curse DeLay and many Republicans fear him, but
all on Capitol Hill agree that he has earned his nickname _ ``the
Hammer'' _ with his relentless Clinton-bashing and his skill at
nailing down votes for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat on the
House Judiciary Committee, said if the House vote, scheduled for
Thursday, had taken place Monday, Clinton would have been
impeached. Meehan believes DeLay has been successful in rounding up
the votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how DeLay can say with a straight face that he is
not putting pressure on members when he engages in this visible and
aggressive advocacy,'' Meehan said. ``There is not only pressure.
DeLay is providing them a rationale, and a cover, for impeaching
the president.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said on ``Meet the Press'' Sunday that the vote was ``too
close to call, it could be a 50-50 chance for impeachment.'' He
insisted he was just doing his job ``to gather intelligence and be
the eyes and ears for the leadership,'' and he denied that he was
twisting arms or urging members to remove the president from
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not asked one member to vote one way or another,''
DeLay said. ``I tell my detractors, `Name one member that I have
threatened or asked to vote one way or another.' They can't do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But DeLay clearly took advantage of a GOP vacuum at the top
after the November election _ he was the only member of the
leadership not to face a challenge for his post _ to press his
fervent desire to bring Clinton to trial. And while Speaker-elect
Robert L. Livingston was steering clear of the impeachment debate,
DeLay weighed in, arguing that censure was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the other leaders have maintained such an
extraordinarily low profile on impeachment, DeLay's very passionate
position has had a greater impact on the members,'' said Paul
Weyrich, a conservative commentator who admires DeLay as a ``moral
force'' in the GOP House. ``You've got lawmakers saying, `Gosh, I
may not feel as strongly as Tom, but I respect him, and I know I've
got to be able to work with him.'''
</P>
<P>
   The job of the majority whip _ the No. 3 position in the House
leadership, after speaker and majority leader _ is twofold: to
track where members stand on important issues and to cajole or
coerce wavering lawmakers and bring them into line with the party's
position. Whip-watchers say DeLay is a master of both.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boss says DeLay is the best whip he's ever served with in
28 years in the House,'' said Don Carlson, chief of staff to
Representative Bill Archer, the Texas Republican whose Houston
district is adjacent to DeLay's. ``He has an uncanny ability to
relate to members. He knows their districts and he knows where they
are on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlson believes DeLay honed his skills in the Texas House from
1978 to 1984, when being an effective Republican required
considerable dexterity in the Democratically controlled
legislature. DeLay, who before politics ran a pest-control business
in suburban Sugar Land, was elected to the US House in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, 51, got appointed to the powerful House Appropriations
Committee in his second term and has brought millions of dollars
home for transportation improvements and the Johnson Space Center
in his district. A born-again Christian, DeLay is a favorite of the
Christian Coalition and social conservatives who oppose abortion
rights and support school prayer and school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been his tenure since 1995 as majority whip that has
earned DeLay a reputation as both an accommodating Mr. Fixit and a
hardball legislator.
</P>
<P>
   GOP consultant Frank Luntz calls DeLay a ``go-to guy,'' because
he is always there when members need advice, a favor, or very
practical help in setting up an office, hiring staff, or running a
fund-raiser. Indeed, DeLay is making space in his own office during
this week's lame-duck session for members displaced by retirement
or defeat in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason DeLay has done so well is that he is honest,
straightforward, and loyal,'' Luntz said. ``He's not afraid to take
on an uphill battle or back up a colleague. This isn't typical
behavior in a body where people like to run the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   But DeLay isn't called the Hammer for nothing, said Norman
Ornstein, a political analyst at the American Enterprise Institute.
``He is relentless and very, very tough; some would say mean,''
Ornstein said. ``He relishes combat and is much feared for what he
is willing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Ornstein cited DeLay's recent assault on the
Electronic Industry Association. When the trade group hired former
Democratic Representative David McCurdy of Oklahoma to be its head,
passing over retiring Republican Bill Paxon of New York, DeLay
instructed GOP members to refuse to talk to association lobbyists.
He also threw wrenches into two copyright treaties the trade
association wanted ratified.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry, to its credit, didn't cave, but it showed that
DeLay has every intention of coercing the firms on K Street to hire
Republican lobbyists,'' Ornstein said.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's reward for helping elect Livingston to the speakership
was more power to keep lobbyists, as well as legislators, in line.
But the whip denies that he is a hammer, a name he said the
Washington Post gave him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'm a little blunt and forthright in what i believe,
and that's created an image that I don't think I am, quite
frankly,'' DeLay said Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
