<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9467 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH15-COX     12-14 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lobbyists seek undecided votes in Congress; Clinton faces vote
for impeachment
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More Republican lawmakers said Monday they would
vote to impeach President Clinton as lobbying efforts to sway the
undecided intensified in advance of Thursday's historic debate.
</P>
<P>
   With the president telling reporters in the Middle East that he
is open to ``any reasonable compromise,'' Vice President Al Gore
criticized House Republican leaders for not allowing a vote on
censure of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the leadership of the Congress has done is to prevent any
kind of compromise along the lines that the American people want to
see, and instead, they threaten to put the country through this
long ordeal that would ensue,'' Gore said in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The latest public opinion polls continue to show a clear
majority of Americans oppose Clinton's impeachment for his actions
to cover up his affair with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But the country also does not want to see the president escape
punishment. The polls show most Americans favor censure, a formal
denunciation of Clinton that the president last week signaled he
would accept.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the news Monday from Capitol Hill was not reassuring for
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans Frank LoBiondo of New Jersey and James Walsh of New
York, two Northeasterners whom Democrats had identified as
potentially friendly to Clinton, announced they would vote for at
least one of the four articles of impeachment accusing the
president of perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans who said Monday they would support impeachment
are: Nathan Deal of Georgia, Charles Bass of New Hampshire and Zach
Wamp of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   One other Republican who has said he would oppose impeachment
edged away from that position. Rep. Christopher Shays of
Connecticut said he is ``willing to reconsider'' his opposition and
requested a meeting with Clinton when the president returns from
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides were trying to arrange the meeting for as
early as Wednesday, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Shays said he was disappointed by Clinton's speech from the
White House Rose Garden on Friday and his remarks in Israel
insisting that he did not commit perjury in his deposition in the
Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit, his testimony to independent
counsel Kenneth Starr's grand jury and his written response to 81
questions posed by the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's comments both before he left and in Israel are
very unsettling to me because it shows me he still doesn't get it,
and he's so intent to avoid prosecution that he's willing to put
this country in tremendous turmoil,'' Shays told The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   One of a handful of anti-impeachment Republicans, Shays said he
will meet with constituents tonight to discuss the issue. ``I don't
have the same level of conviction I had a week ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton should ``say that he did not tell the truth and in fact
he lied, and say he's willing to face the court like any other
American citizen and be held accountable for his actions'' after
leaving office, Shays said.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Craig, a Clinton aide, said Republicans are making an
unfair demand on the president ``that he plead guilty to a felony
in order to avoid impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   White House counsel Charles Ruff told the Judiciary Committee
last week that Clinton would not accept a pardon when he leaves
office, Craig added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's chances of avoiding impeachment rest on moderate
Republicans like Shays who come from districts whose voters
supported Clinton in the 1996 election and are split between
Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 Republicans in the House would have to vote ``no'' on
impeachment to tip the balance in Clinton's favor, if Democrats are
correct that no more than six members of their caucus will join the
pro-impeachment camp.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican lawmakers who remain undecided, at least
publicly, reported a sizable jump in telephone calls, faxes and
e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our offices (in Washington and Georgia) are getting
continuous calls,'' said Grace Cummings, chief of staff to Rep.
Jack Kingston (R-Ga.). Kingston said Monday he is ``leaning in
favor'' of a vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leadership in the House, meanwhile, continued
preparations for the impeachment debate, expected to begin at 10
a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers probably will have six to eight hours to speak on
impeachment, followed by a vote on each of the four articles, said
Michele Davis, spokeswoman for House Majority Leader Richard Armey
(R-Texas).
</P>
<P>
   The voting is likely to start Thursday evening, unless
parliamentary tactics by Democrats intent on allowing a censure
resolution push the votes to Friday, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are trying to devise a way to force a procedural vote
on censure, believing that most Democrats and enough Republicans
would jump at the chance to bring the impeachment issue to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Livingston (R-La.), the speaker-designate, has vowed
to prevent the censure move, calling it a test of loyalty for House
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee staff members expect to finish the report
recommending impeachment late tonight or early Wednesday. The
report will be available on the Internet at
http://www.house.gov/judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   The clerk of the House will distribute the report to all
members' offices Wednesday along with the Democrats' dissenting
views on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Most House members will drift into town Wednesday, when both
parties are expected to stage closed-door meetings to discuss
strategy for the first televised impeachment debate in the House's
history.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
