<HEADER>
A9474 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-GADEL-COX     12-14 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GADEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another Georgian will vote to impeach
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The ranks of the undecided in Georgia's
congressional delegation dwindled further Monday as Republican Rep.
Nathan Deal said he would vote to impeach President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Two Republicans, Speaker Newt Gingrich and Rep. Jack Kingston,
and Democratic Rep. Sanford Bishop remain officially undecided in
advance of Thursday's debate, just the second time in history that
the House will consider impeaching the president.
</P>
<P>
   But vote counters in both parties expect the Georgians to side
with the overwhelming majorities in their respective parties _
Republicans in favor of impeachment and Democrats opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Deal, a lawyer and former Democrat who represents North Georgia,
said he believes Clinton broke the law in his efforts to conceal
his sexual relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is regrettable that we are faced with this matter,'' Deal
said in a statement. ``To ignore it, however, would be to diminish
our respect for the rule of law and would violate my obligation to
support and uphold the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   He held off announcing his position until the Judiciary
Committee finished its work Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Kingston said Monday that he is ``leaning in favor of voting for
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kingston acknowledged the gravity of the coming votes on
four articles accusing Clinton of perjury, obstruction of justice
and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a vote that must stand the test of time,'' Kingston said.
``You won't have any second shots on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kingston's office has been besieged by callers on both sides of
the issue, constituents as well as people from as far away as
California.
</P>
<P>
   A Baltimore man told Kingston Chief of Staff Grace Cummings that
he had stayed home from work Monday to call each of the 435
representatives and register his support for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our message machines ran out over the weekend,'' Cummings
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Bishop's office, the calls were running about even, said
spokesman Selby McCash.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop is the one Georgia Democrat who some analysts have said
may be open to casting a vote for impeachment because he represents
a conservative agriculture district in southwest Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   But when the House voted to open an impeachment inquiry just
weeks before the congressional election, Bishop voted against a
broad Republican proposal and for a more limited Democratic
alternative. He easily won re-election to a fourth term in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop's Democratic colleagues in Georgia, John Lewis and
Cynthia McKinney, oppose Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, a strong supporter of the president's, has not sought to
lobby any of the undecided Republican moderates whose votes are
likely to determine whether Clinton is impeached, Lewis spokesman
Jack Pannell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Democrat would be a logical choice to attempt to
enlist Republicans in opposition to impeachment because he is part
of an interracial, bipartisan group in the House that meets
periodically to talk about race.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls and faxes to Lewis' office have been solidly
against impeachment, Pannell said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats at one point thought that Republicans Saxby Chambliss
and Charlie Norwood could be persuaded to vote against impeachment
because they represent districts that Clinton won in the 1996
election and that have large African-American populations.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, both men announced their intention to support
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans Bob Barr, Mac Collins and John Linder also will vote
to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Linder predicted that at least one of the four articles would
``very narrowly'' pass the House, putting Clinton in the company of
Andrew Johnson as one of the only two presidents to be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
