<SLUG> BC-PEACHBUZZ15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miss America, she's on a real-life mission
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Miss America 1999 Nicole Johnson was missing a
crowning fashion accessory when she visited Grady Memorial Hospital
in Atlanta, Ga., on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't wear the tiara at all,'' Johnson told Buzz as she
kicked off a national diabetes awareness and screening campaign.
``I have this disease myself so this campaign is very personal to
me. I want people to hear what I have to say and not be distracted.
If I'm up there wearing a crown, my validity is shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta stop is part of a 17-city tour designed to motivate
at-risk people to be tested for the disease, which can cause
serious health problems if untreated. ``It only takes 60 to 90
seconds and it's just a finger prick,'' says Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   As for her and Miss America 1998 Kate Shindle's equally
progressive AIDS awareness campaign, Johnson is philosophical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really just the luck of the draw that both campaigns
turned out to focus on public health concerns,'' she says. ``What's
enjoyable for me is to see how the Miss America program is
modernizing and how it's become more realistic. We need a woman
who's normal that we can relate to. We don't need a Barbie doll.''
To learn more about the diabetes screening, call 1-800-708-7001.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: buzz(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   For more juicy gossip and keen commentary, see what Vixana has
to say on ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Richard L. Eldredge writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
