<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9506 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-1215-     12-14 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-1215-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLIINTON LAUDS, LEGITIMIZES PALESTINIANS FOR REMOVING DIVISIVE
LANGUAGE FROM CHARTER
 &HT;    EDs: Optional trim begins at 550 words.
 &HT;    With GAZA-SCENE-1215, PALESTINIAN-REACT-1215.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza _ President Clinton journeyed to this stark
sliver of Palestinian controlled land on Monday and addressed the
loosely arrayed beginnings of representative government here,
conferring the aura, if not the formal stamp, of American
legitimacy upon Palestinian aspirations for statehood.
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented speech to more than 700 Palestinians,
Clinton called on Israel to recognize ''the right of Palestinians
to aspire to live free,'' and told the Palestinians gathered here
that they have ''the opportunity to shape a new Palestinian future
on your own land.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians reciprocated by removing from their charter
decades-old language calling for the destruction of Israel, in a
dramatic move White House officials insisted would help salvage the
deeply troubled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu were scheduled to meet together early
Tuesday at the Israeli-Gaza bordertown of Erez to discuss modest
steps meant to hold together the U.S.-led effort to move ahead with
a process through which Israel has essentially vowed to surrender
certain occupied territories to Palestinian control in exchange for
Palestinian measures to combat terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   With key ingredients of that process stalemated, and Netanyahu's
political future in doubt, there was no assurance that Tuesday's
meeting would bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, with Netanyahu facing a possible no-confidence
vote in the Israeli Knesset as early as next week, White House
officials fear that Israel will continue to delay promised troop
withdrawals from occupied West Bank territories. A Friday deadline
for one phase of the planned redeployments is not expected to be
met.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials voiced guarded hope, though, that Monday's
breathtaking historic developments might provide a badly needed
opening for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have had really quite an extraordinary day,'' U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told reporters late Monday
night. ''A page was turned.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stopped short of endorsing the creation of a free
Palestine, a potentially explosive issue near the heart of five
decades of Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   By making a ceremonial arrival at the new Gaza International
Airport, where he was feted by a Palestinian honor guard and
received by a broadly beaming Arafat, Clinton's visit and his
dramatic words of support clearly added incalculable momentum to
the goal of carving out a Palestinian state from long-disputed
lands.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am profoundly honored to be the first American president to
address the Palestinian people in a city governed by
Palestinians,'' a line that drew a standing ovation from a crowd of
some 700 Palestinian officials, executives and activists that
filled the largest public hall in this struggling city by the
Mediterranean Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know that the Palestinian people stand at a crossroads,''
Clinton told the delegation, ''behind you a history of
dispossession and dispersal, before you the opportunity to shape a
new Palestinian future on your own land.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton, ''This moment would have been inconceivable a
decade ago,'' later adding, ''I hope you have begun to see America
as your friend.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional trim follows.)
</P>
<P>
   For decades, U.S. and Palestinian interests have been in direct
confrontation, chiefly because the Palestinian charter -- a sort of
de-facto constitution for the stateless Palestinians -- contained
provisions calling for the destruction of Israel, Washington's
closest strategic ally in the oil-rich Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, the Palestinians and their Arab backers have
fought a series of wars with Israel since the creation of the
Jewish state in 1948. Separately, thousands have been killed on
both sides of the conflict by terrorist attacks, mostly
Palestinian, and military action, mostly Israeli.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, however, roughly two-thirds of the Palestinian
National Council, a sort of rough start at representative
government, affirmed the nullification of all charter references to
Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that this will close this chapter forever,'' said
Arafat. ``We are determined to contnue our quest for peace -- peace
of the brave -- nd coexistence on the basis of respecting jutice
and international legitimacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the delegates, ''You did a good thing today in
raising your hands. You know why? It has nothing to do with the
government in Israel. You will touch the people of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear how many of the council's 650 members were
present -- many boycotted the meeting in protest -- but White House
officials estimated that at least 500 council members attended and
perhaps 80 percent signaled their approval with uplifted hands.
</P>
<P>
   The charter amendments have been a sticking point in the
implementation of agreements Clinton brokered between Arafat and
Netanyahu six weeks ago at the Wye River Plantation in rural
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very important step,'' Netanyahu said at a press
conference after the Palestinian meeting. ''I welcome it. It is a
positive step.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also applauded the move. ''I thank you for your
rejection -- fully, finally and forever -- of the passages in the
Palestinian charter calling for the destruction of Israel,'' he
told Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ''It does not hurt Israelis to hear Palestinians peacefully and
pridefully asserting their identity, as we saw today,'' Clinton
said. ''And it does not hurt Palestinians to acknowledge the
profound desire of Israelis to live without fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking the point a step further, Clinton said, ''Palestinians
must recognize the right of Israel and its people to live safe and
secure lives today, tomorrow and forever. Israel must recognize the
right of Palestinians to aspire to live free today, tomorrow and
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   White House National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger
explained later that Clinton went to great pains to not
specifically endorse Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   That issue, Berger said, can only be addressed through direct
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations, as part of so-called final status
talks, aimed at drafting a comprehensive plan for enduring peace in
the fractious Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe very strongly that that is an issue that ought to
be negotiated between the parties,'' Berger told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, Clinton's visit here -- agreed upon by Arafat and
Netanyahu at Wye -- clearly conferred an aura of presidential
legitimacy upon the Palestinians' aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people in that room felt validated as human beings, as
Palestinians, as a people, by virtue of the fact that the president
of the United States came to Gaza and spoke to them,'' said Berger.
''But, in no way was this an effort to prejudge what only the
parties can decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Berger, ''Does the president coming here, by agreement
between Israel and the Palestinians, give some legitimacy to the
Palestinian people? I think it does.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he continued, ''I think there's a difference between that
and a question of what the ultimate status of the territories
are.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
