<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUZZLING-PYONGYANG-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA: ABOUT THAT MYSTERIOUS HOLE IN THE GROUND...  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 900-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 12 Dec. 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING AND SEOUL _ Hundreds of South Korean tourists have been
making the first visits to a long-forbidden part of their country _
the northern side of the world's last Cold-War frontier.
</P>
<P>
   After being bused along roads lined with barbed wire and guarded
by soldiers, they found not much to see apart from Diamond
Mountain. Nevertheless, North Korea expects to collect $150 million
a year from the South for allowing the trips.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Americans too want to visit, and they know what they
want to see: a large hole which they suspect is meant to become a
site for developing nuclear weapons. North Korea wants $300 million
to arrange that trip.
</P>
<P>
   America refuses to pay. Now an agreement by which North Korea is
supposed to freeze its nuclear program could be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   Amid heightened tensions, the South Korean government is
concerned at what it sees as America's new hawkish stand. China,
one of North Korea's few remaining friends, has called for
patience.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Japan prepares to duck again, amid reports that the
North Koreans are preparing to test-fire another missile (the
first, they claimed, was launching a satellite) in its direction.
</P>
<P>
   America's special envoy on Korea, William Perry, was in the
region this week. While in Seoul, the South's president, Kim Dae
Jung, told him: ``North Korea is at a crossroads. It can either
risk war through military provocations, or open up.''
</P>
<P>
   In response North Korea declared its army of 1.2 million
``determined to annihilate the U.S. imperialists, Japanese
reactionaries and South Korean puppets at one stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   Really? Since an armistice ended the Korean war in 1953, the
peninsula has been divided by a heavily fortified demilitarized
zone, four kilometers (2 miles) wide. South of it stand 670,000
South Korean troops, backed by 37,000 Americans. America has
another 40,000 servicemen in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Most defense analysts think North Korea, with its economy on the
brink of collapse and much of its population underfed, is incapable
of a sustained attack.
</P>
<P>
   Yet incapacity does not mean it would not try. The regime has
always been unpredictable, if not crazy, its remoteness from
reality reinforced by a stifling personality cult built around the
late ``Great Leader,'' Kim Il Sung, and now extended to his son,
Kim Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
   Desperation for foreign money has not made the regime any less
dangerous. Far from it: missile sales have been one way it has
raised foreign currency. It has offered to stop that trade, but
again at a price.
</P>
<P>
   The present controversy is over a 1994 deal in which North Korea
agreed to freeze its nuclear-weapons program in return for the
supply of fuel oil. This would keep it going while America, South
Korea and Japan built for it two nuclear-power plants of a type
with limited ability to produce weapons-grade material.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans now claim to have evidence that North Korea may be
breaking the agreement, by building a giant underground complex
that they believe is nuclear-related.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's government reckons there is time to negotiate with
Pyongyang. Since he was elected a year ago, Kim has been pursuing a
``sunshine policy'' in an attempt to thaw out relations with the
North. The recent tourist trips are one small, but significant,
result.
</P>
<P>
   Kim has told Perry that North Korea is belligerent because it is
weak. To dispel suggestions of a rift, Kim and Perry agreed to
respond ``sternly'' to North Korean provocation, but also said that
this was not the time for Seoul to give up its policy of
engagement.
</P>
<P>
   Some in South Korea believe the two approaches may prove to be a
useful carrot and stick. But China was the next stop on Perry's
trip, and it has its own agenda. China backed the North during the
Korean war, but some foreign analysts think it understands far less
about the hermit kingdom than many outsiders assume.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly China is frustrated that North Korea's behavior is
giving Japan good reason to take a more prominent role in regional
security. In the longer term, China's objective is probably to keep
other powers, especially (but not only) Japan, from having too much
influence in the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   To justify that, China looks to history: the Sino-Japanese war
of 1894 started in Korea, and ended in a humiliating defeat for
China. Japan also used Korea as the base for its 1937 invasion of
China.
</P>
<P>
   Perry too, however, has a domestic agenda. The 1994 accord is
considered a major foreign-policy success by President Clinton's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican-dominated Congress approved funding for it
only provided he could supply written assurances that North Korea
was not violating the deal. Paying $300 million to find out about
the hole in the ground would send Congress ballistic.
</P>
<P>
   Kim has suggested payment might instead be made with
humanitarian aid, such as grain and medicine, and backed up by
normalizing diplomatic ties and the ending of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Such a deal, his officials say, should not be confined to the
suspected nuclear site, but part of a broader package negotiated
with the North to ensure more openness on its part. Otherwise, they
fear, more sinister holes will appear in the ground along with more
demands for money for the right to visit them. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 900-word article, it must be purchased from New
York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York
at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
