<HEADLINE>
FEW OPTIONS FOR BLEDSOE'S DOCTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The urgency of getting Drew Bledsoe back on the field
has grown each week, but unfortunately his doctors' options have
been narrowing.
</P>
<P>
   First they tried a specially-designed plastic cast. When that
didn't provide sufficient stability they inserted a pair of pins.
Monday they reconfigured the pins and ordered up the one other
thing guaranteed to help Bledsoe's healing if not his team: asking
the quarterback to sit out a week.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors, the team and the player apparently had no choice.
They'd exhausted the only logical treatment techniques and outside
orthopedic experts say the one trick left would have been to try
and secure the fractured bone in place with screws and a thin
plate. But if he'd undergone the open surgery that would have
required, the surgeons agree, Bledsoe certainly would have been out
next Sunday and possibly a week or two longer.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative was to do what they've apparently decided to,
trying again with pins and a splint and letting him rest long
enough to let them work.
</P>
<P>
   Hand specialist Dr. James Herndon and Patriots physician Bert
Zarins examined Bledsoe Monday at Massachusetts General Hospital,
then launched this new course of treatment. The doctors declined to
discuss what they did, but the team released a statement saying
that Bledsoe had had a ``minor surgical procedure,'' and that his
playing status for Sunday is ``uncertain.'' A source confirms that
he will not be suiting up against San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to see him out of action, including his doctors,
but there simply are only so many choices for treating a doubly
fractured finger like his. And that list has gotten shorter each
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're trying to keep the fragments in a good position so when
it heals, the finger is fully functional,'' explains Dr. John
Richmond, chief of sports medicine at New England Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   A specially-designed three-quarters cast seemed to do the job at
first, but when Bledsoe had trouble nine days ago against
Pittsburg, his doctors opted to add a pair of wire-thin pins to
provide extra stability. The pins, however, moved out of position
during Sunday's game in St. Louis, either because they hooked onto
something when Bledsoe was slammed to the ground by Rams rushers or
because the fracture shifted and pried them loose.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, ``if they slip out five or six days later
it's a warning sign that they aren't holding, that they aren't
doing the job,'' says Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe's doctors tried Monday to remedy that by revising the
placement of the pins, a team spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The other option open to them, and one they might someday turn
to if the pins don't work, would be to try and hold the bones
steady with a tiny metal plate secured by stainless steel or
titanium screws. ``The screws go through the plate and hold it to
the bone, the plate holds the allignment of the bone, and typically
a splint also is used for some period,'' says Dr. Paul Tornetta,
director of orthopedic trauma at Boston University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Screws are substantially more stable than pins, much the way a
screw drilled into wood holds better than a nail. But that gain
comes at a price: pins can be inserted simply be stabbing them
through the skin, whereas screws require an incision that opens the
facture site, exposes the bone and requires a recovery process that
means Bledsoe, in Richmond's words, ``probably would not be coming
back for next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Leach, editor of the American Journal of Sports
Medicine and former chief physician for the US Olympic Team, is
even more pessimistic. With such surgery, he says, Bledsoe
``certainly wouldn't play on day seven or 14. He might on day 28.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the screws rip out like the pins did, Tornetta adds,
``there's a big hole there. If you try and put another screw in
you'll need to drill an even bigger area.''
</P>
<P>
   The condition of Bledsoe's finger is topic number one in most
orthopedic departments across Boston these days, much as it is in
homes and offices. But like everyone else, the orthopedic surgeons
are in the dark about what's actually happening because the
Patriots doesn't want its doctors talking, the doctors feel they
have to respect the wishes of their patient as well as their
employer, and the team is trying to keep San Francisco and the Jets
guessing about which Patriots quarterback will suit up against
them.
</P>
<P>
   Several doctors who haven't examined him say that if Bledsoe had
been rested from the time he was first injured against Miami three
weeks ago, his fractures might be healed by now, although of course
the Patriots would have been without his services for critical
games against Buffalo, Pittsburg and St. Louis. Each time another
treatment approach is tried and fails, Leach explains, ``they sort
of start over again. It's not back to day 1, but it puts full
healing a little further along. ... It's not an easy situation for
either his doctors or for the player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
