<HEADER>
A9526 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIREHELMET-COX     12-14 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREHELMET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firefighters get clearer vision, thanks to Ohio company, Air
Force
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ With help from the Air Force, a small
Beavercreek, Ohio company has developed a prototype device that
lets firefighters see clearly in blinding smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Zybron Inc. and the Air Force Research Laboratory developed the
infrared imaging system under an $825,000 Small Business Innovative
Research contract. The battery-powered device includes a
camera-like lens, viewer and transmitter, all built into a
firefighter's helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force and company officials dramatically demonstrated the
technology Monday with the help of the Dayton Fire Department.
Firefighter Lt. Thomas LaVielle donned the helmet and strode into a
smoke-filled building at the department's fire training site.
</P>
<P>
   A TV monitor set up outside showed a black-and-white TV image of
what LaVielle was seeing in his viewer. Details inside the room
were clearly visible, as were two other firefighters who crawled
across the floor to recover a dummy and hose down flames licking in
the background.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, LaVielle put his gloved hand against a concrete
wall and left a glowing handprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a very clear picture of the whole room,'' LaVielle said
afterward, but he said he couldn't have seen anything without the
imaging system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't imagine you could see two feet in there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only could such a device help firefighters find victims,
they could use it to find fires burning in concealed places,
because the infrared imager can spot heat coming through walls or
ceilings, LaVielle said.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers and pilots use infrared systems to find the enemy at
night, but this technology was developed with safety in mind, said
Juan Vitali of the Air Force Research Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial impetus behind it was to enhance the readiness of
firefighters on air bases,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vitali said the Air Force developed the device because nothing
comparable is commercially available.
</P>
<P>
   Zybron president Evan Zhang hopes that will soon change. Zhang's
10-employee firm hopes to refine the prototype into a smaller
package that adds less than a pound to a firefighter's helmet.
Besides the military, Zhang sees a potential market in civilian
fire departments.
</P>
<P>
   He estimated volume production models would initially cost about
$5,000, then drop to about $2,000 as demand increased.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang, a native of China and a U.S. citizen, sees a wide range
of potential uses for inexpensive infrared viewers based on this
technology. As one example, its ability to detect tiny temperature
changes could allow surgeons to tell living tissue from dead tissue
or pinpoint blockages in blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   But Zhang admitted it's a long step from development to
production. He said his 10-year-old company has developed three
other commercial products based on optical electronics technology,
but it has not been able to raise the venture capital it needs to
manufacture them.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
