<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9531 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX     12-14 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSISTENCY, THOU ART A JEWEL _ A RARE ONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB RAY SANDERS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The very thought of helpless, hungry people is enough to turn
the stomach, but the sight of starving children _ thousands of them
with their swollen stomachs, skeletal rib cages and bulging, teary
eyes _ is more than enough to break the heart.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen these sights far too many times in recent years in
places like Ethiopia, Bangladesh, Somalia, Kurdistan, Bosnia and
Sudan, just to mention a few.
</P>
<P>
   Although such scenes are always discomforting, they are
especially troublesome when it is apparent that part of the reason
children and adults around the world are dying of starvation is
because their political leaders (dictators or warring rebels) find
it more appropriate to buy arms and equip soldiers than to feed the
people.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that war (cold or hot) decimates a people, too
often the rest of the world finds it easier to wait and debate
rather than intervene.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton was visiting South Korea last month,
complimenting American and Korean soldiers for their valiant
service along the most heavily guarded border in the world,
Americans sitting comfortably in their living rooms and dens were
shown new pictures of malnourished children in the economically
depressed, but military-ready, North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   We know little about it except that since the end of the Korean
War in 1953, it has continued under Communist control; is still
separated from South Korea by the five-mile stretch called the
Demilitarized Zone; has been a constant threat to its southern
neighbor (actually, ``kin''); and now is in economic and social
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   I've never pretended to understand American foreign policy,
especially as it related to certain countries and continents that
this country never pretended to care about. But I must admit that,
considering recent global events, I'm even more confused by what
appears to be a double or triple standard when it comes to dealing
with certain ``undesirable'' nations.
</P>
<P>
   For the purpose of this discussion, let's talk about countries
known to be enemies of the United States _ countries where we know
people are suffering primarily, or even slightly, because of those
countries' leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Again, for the purpose of this dialogue, let's rule out Russia
or any other former state of the Soviet Union, all countries in
Africa and those in South or Central America. We can even rule out
most of Asia and the rest of Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to North Korea, Iraq and ... what's that little
island a few miles off the coast of Florida?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   We have 40,000 troops helping to defend the people on the Korean
peninsula, a place Clinton calls ``the last fault line of the Cold
War.''
</P>
<P>
   Photographs from a U.S. spy satellite reveal that thousands of
North Korean workers are digging a huge hole in a mountainside not
far from that country's nuclear complex. It is presumed that North
Korea is preparing to build a large facility to produce nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has asked for permission to inspect the sites,
but so far North Korea has refused. Instead, the Communist country
has asked the United States to pay $300 million for the privilege
of inspecting the area.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as North Korea expands its nuclear arsenal at a huge
cost, about 2 million people have died there in the last three
years as a result of the country's severe food shortage.
</P>
<P>
   So far there have been no threats of bombing the enemies in the
North. In fact, the president is still extending an olive branch _
or at least an olive ``twig'' _ to the leaders in North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   In Iraq, on the other hand, American ships and planes stand
ready with loaded missiles to attack that country because its
defiant leader continues to divert humanitarian aid from starving
families to feed the army.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the limited humanitarian assistance, a devastating
embargo continues against Iraq _ and maybe rightfully so, but I
doubt it. (Keep in mind, I don't understand American foreign
policy.)
</P>
<P>
   And in Cuba, where an aging revolutionary still refuses to bow
to the Yankees of North America, we impose some of our most
punitive sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cuban families may be getting tired of rice and beans,
no one is starving to death there. The babies are not crying of
hunger, because they are getting their daily ration of milk.
</P>
<P>
   In Fidel Castro's Cuba, precious dollars and devalued pesos are
being used to rebuild a crumbling infrastructure and a ravaged
economy, not to build weapons.
</P>
<P>
   While we encourage our South Korean ally to have dialogue with
its northern kinsmen, we chastise those would want to communicate
or do business with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is time that we treat the leader and the people of Cuba
with at least the same dignity as we treat the leader and people of
North Korea. Of course, I'm probably way off base, because I
``really'' don't understand American foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ray Sanders is associate editor and a columnist for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. He can be reached at (817) 390-7775 or
bobray(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
