<HEADER>
A9532 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-CALLS15-PA     12-14 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CALLS15-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        LOCAL DELEGATION FLOODED WITH CALLS ABOUT IMPEACHMENT
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 14, -- Rep. Bob Borski calls in to his office
regularly to check on feedback from folks on whether President
Clinton should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   When he can get through, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lines have been busy and busy,'' said Borski,
D-Philadelphia. ``We have been swamped with calls. I have never
seen anything come close to this much response in my legislative
career. I think people cannot believe we have gotten this far in
the impeachment process and feel a sense of urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   As Congress members prepare to vote this week on whether to
impeach Clinton, feedback from their constituents has reached a
crescendo in the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional phone lines are busy, the switchboard is swamped,
and folks are resorting to e-mail or faxes to register their
opinion, said staffers for Pennsylvania House lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Borski, who has come out strongly against impeachment, said his
office received 100 calls Friday, and 400 calls Monday. On an
ordinary day he would receive only a dozen. He said the calls were
``almost all'' from folks who thought Clinton should not be thrown
out of office.
</P>
<P>
   But suburban area moderate Republican Reps. Jon Fox, (R-13th
District) Jim Greenwood, (R-8th District) and Curt Weldon, (R-7th
District) who remained undecided Monday, received a much greater
response.
</P>
<P>
   David Lintgen, Fox's senior legislative assistant, said their
office has been flooded with calls. They've also received nearly
7,000 e-mails since this weekend when the House Judiciary Committee
voted out articles of impeachment accusing Clinton of perjury and
abuse of power regarding his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Half are from folks favoring impeachment, and half from those
against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get creative with the e-mails. One guy wrote impeach a
thousand times in all different directions, fonts and sizes,''
Lintgen said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, Greenwood, and Weldon, are among a group of about 40
undecided Republicans and Democrats, whose swing votes will
determine the fate of the presidency. Fox, who was unseated in the
last election, is in the unique position, of casting his vote and
leaving office. Greenwood's office received 127 calls Wednesday,
709 calls Friday, and even more Monday, according to his
spokeswoman Niko Yen, who said the calls were almost exactly half
for impeachment and half against.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never seen that high volume,'' Yen said. ``We are
getting calls from all over the country. I think we get so many
calls in part because Greenwood is undecided. We have so many calls
our office is paralyzed.''
</P>
<P>
   Weldon's office received 1500 calls Friday and Monday, and 600
e-mails over the weekend, said his spokesman Pete Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response is neck and neck for and against impeachment,''
Peterson said. ``But the congressman is undecided and he must
disregard that and examine the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The level of feedback Congress has received, illustrates the
connection people from outside the Beltway feel to this process,
said Rep. Bob Brady's spokeswoman Karen Warrington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The callers are quite vocal and passionate,'' Warrington said.
``With this, there is not that disconnect from Washington to the
real world. People are calling from row-house Philly to out in the
suburbs. Doctors and industrial workers. Some are calling on behalf
of their husbands, their wives, their neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   By noon Monday, Brady, who is against impeachment, received 180
calls such calls, only 14 of which were in favor of impeachment.
Warrington said.
</P>
<P>
   Staffers for Rep. Chaka Fattah, D-Philadelphia, said they
received about 100 calls, some spurred on by organized lobbying
groups.
</P>
<P>
   One group, called Censure and Move On, has a website that
encourages people to call members of Congress who are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pundits say people are disconnected from Washington,'' said
Hal Rosenthal, a Philadelphia attorney and spokesman for the group.
But I think it's the other way around. Congress is disconnected
from people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
