<HEADER>
A9533 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-COX     12-14 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State Farm sues for fraud claims
 &HT;    By Earl Golz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State Farm Mutual went to court Monday to
recover $4.8 million from lawyers and medical groups accused of
staging car accidents to collect claim payments in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits were filed in federal courts in Houston and Dallas
under the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations law. The
law permits recovery of three times the actual damages, which in
State Farm's case could exceed $14.4 million. Government agencies
also can file criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Insurance is aware of the same type of
fraudulent activity involving staged auto accidents in Austin and
is investigating ``at least one case,'' said insurance department
spokesman Lee Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Perpetrators usually target a new car because it is probably
insured, said Texas Insurance Commissioner Elton Bomer. They
position an auto to slam on its brakes and be hit from behind by
the target car.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, a group of nine lawyers, law office operators and
employees, and healthcare providers were responsible for 199 staged
crashes, most of them rear-end collisions, with fraudulent claims
amounting to $2.8 million between 1992 and 1997, according to the
State Farm suit there.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, 16 defendants staged 153 collisions for fraudulent
claims exceeding $2 million between 1993 and 1995, the suit there
alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Though the insurance company has no information that the fraud
rings in the two cities were operating in tandem, it named as
defendants two brothers who are chiropractors, Michael Giventer in
the Houston suit and Alexander Giventer in the Dallas case.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the Giventer brothers could be located for comment
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Other defendants include lawyers and others who operated law
offices and clinics, a ``capper'' who organized some of the crashes
and another person who laundered funds so that intended recipients
didn't get them, the suit states.
</P>
<P>
   One of the accused, Steven Price, a medical doctor in Spring,
also submitted false bodily injury claims based on 28 auto
collisions, State Farm alleged. Another defendant, Slavic Stein, a
resident of California who used four aliases, employed lawyers
licensed in Texas to negotiate settlements through so-called
``Stein Law Offices'' in the Houston area for at least 550
claimants in fraudulent bodily injury and property damage claims
based on 199 collisions, State Farm alleged.
</P>
<P>
   Price's office in Spring said he was not available for comment
Monday. Nor could Stein be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The National Insurance Crime Bureau has estimated that fraud
costs insurance companies at least $20 billion a year and the
average household pays an additional $200 a year in premiums to
cover the cost of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Allstate Insurance in the past two years has filed anti-fraud
cases seeking $167 million against parties who have staged auto
accidents for false claims in California, Illinois and New Jersey.
The company in 1997 was awarded $10 million in California after it
used the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations act to sue
several lawyers and chiropractors for filing false auto insurance
claims.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Golz writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
