<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, DECEMBER 15
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-IRAQ-U.N.-NYT (moved on Thursday, Dec. 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Dec. 10,
about United Nations arms inspections in Iraq misspelled the name
of a London-based Arab-language newspaper that interviewed
Secretary General Kofi Annan. It is Asharq al-Aswat, not Ashraq
al-Aswat. The article also included an incorrect rendering from the
newspaper for a comment by Mr. Annan. In discussing the chief arms
inspector, Richard Butler, Mr. Annan did not tell Asharq al-Aswat
that Mr. Butler's diplomacy ``is seasonal.'' The newspaper said
that it had erred in transcribing Mr. Annan's remarks and that he
had called Mr. Butler's diplomacy ``seasoned.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-AETNA-PRUDENTIAL-NYT (moved on Thursday, Dec. 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Dec. 10,
about the plans of Aetna Inc. to buy Prudential Health Care
misidentified one of the three largest nationwide health insurance
companies. Along with Aetna and the United Healthcare Corporation,
the company is Cigna, not Kaiser Perma-nente.
</P>
<P>
   A chart with the article misidentified the chief executive of
Prudential Health Care. He is Steven J. Shulman; Arthur F. Ryan is
chief executive of Prudential Health Care's parent, the Prudential
Insurance Company of America.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-KAZEN-NYT (moved on Saturday, Dec. 12)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Rabbi Yosef Kazen, sent by the New York Times
News Service on Saturday, Dec. 12, misspelled the surname of his
brother-in-law, the development director at the Lubavitch world
headquarters, and omitted the director's title. He is Rabbi Moshe
Kotlarsky, not Kotlarksi.
</P>
<P>
   BC-AT-THE MOVIES-NYT (moved on Thursday, Dec. 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Dec. 10,
about the new film ``Shakespeare in Love'' misstated the given name
of one writer. He is Marc Norman, not Zack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
