<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9545 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-HOUSE-BOS &LR;      12-14 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP MODERATES IN HOUSE SWING TOWARD IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's last-ditch struggle to stave
off impeachment grew more imperiled Monday as a number of pivotal
moderate Republicans rebuffed the beleaguered president and vowed
to recommend removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden burst of GOP moderates abandoning Clinton drastically
increased the prospect that the House this week will approve at
least one impeachment charge, setting up the first Senate trial of
a sitting president in 130 years.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the surge were several Northeast Republicans, including
Representative Charles F. Bass of New Hampshire, whose votes were
seen as critical for Clinton to secure if he is to avoid the
ignominy of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, several other House Republicans who had announced they
would oppose impeachment were reconsidering their positions.
</P>
<P>
   With no undeclared GOP lawmakers emerging to oppose impeachment,
the developments were ominous for Clinton, who Monday renewed his
appeal for an alternative sanction and set aside Wednesday to meet
with the dwindling ranks of undecideds before they vote on Thursday
or Friday on whether to recommend his ouster.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also suggested that a bitterly divisive impeachment
trial could cause a national trauma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it's in the interest of the United States and
the American people to go through the impeachment process and have
a trial in the Senate,'' Clinton said during a historic visit to
Israel and Gaza. ``That's why I have offered to make every effort
to make every compromise with Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton's situation worsened, Vice President Al Gore came to
his defense, accusing the Republican majority in the House of
ignoring ``the wisdom of the American people'' by refusing to allow
a vote on an alternative resolution of censure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also has begun reaching out to House Democrats for
last-minute advice, as he did late Saturday night when he phoned
Representative Barney Frank from Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, of Massachusetts, is a senior member of the House
Judiciary Committee, which voted on party lines last week to
approve four articles of impeachment charging Clinton with two
counts of perjury and one each of obstruction of justice and abuse
of power. All the counts stem from Clinton's alleged effort to
conceal his sexual affair in the White House with the former
intern, Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Frank said he told Clinton that House Republicans are trying to
persuade undeclared GOP members to back impeachment by casting the
issue as a way to punish the president without removing him from
office. Although the Senate might hold a lengthy trial on the
Lewinsky matter, members of both parties believe there is too
little support to garner the 67 votes that would be required for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans should be consulting Jesse Ventura,'' Frank
said in an interview, referring to the Minnesota governor-elect who
is a former professional wrestler. ``They are doing all this
grunting and groaning, but saying, `Don't worry, the good guy will
win in the end.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bass was among more than two dozen Republicans who were targeted
by the White House because their districts solidly supported
Clinton in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I do not relish the specter of putting the country
through the anguish of a Senate trial, I recognize that ignoring
the president's felonious acts would endorse his criminal behavior
and set a dangerous precedent for future presidents,'' Bass said in
a statement. ``After sober reflection and much soul-searching, I
announce with a heavy heart that I must vote to impeach the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   The tide rose for Clinton's impeachment as political leaders and
special interests on both sides of the issue stepped up their
advocacy efforts. Amid the burgeoning campaign, the moderate
Republicans turned against Clinton in the face of polls that show
overwhelming opposition to his impeachment. The lawmakers said the
issue was more important than public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the will of the American people should always be a
factor in an elected representative's decision, there is a time and
place for polls,'' Bass said. ``This is not one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The other Northeast Republicans who had ranked as high
priorities on the list of prospective Clinton supporters but vowed
to oppose him were Representatives James T. Walsh of New York and
Frank A. LoBiondo of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot in good conscience allow the nation's chief law
enforcement officer to violate the law without consequence,''
LoBiondo said.
</P>
<P>
   Three other Republicans who were seen as possible Clinton
supporters announced they will vote to impeach him: Representatives
Rick Hill of Montana, John M. Shimkus of Illinois, and Zach Wamp of
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a leading GOP foe of impeachment, Representative
Christopher Shays of Connecticut, abruptly announced he was
rethinking his vote and asked to meet with Clinton before he makes
a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   Shays and many others who were leaning against Clinton said they
have become increasingly frustrated by the president's
unwillingness to acknowledge that he lied about the Lewinsky matter
in court proceedings, as they believe he did.
</P>
<P>
   The White House immediately granted Shays' request for a meeting
and said Clinton will be available to meet on Wednesday with other
House members ``if they believe that would be constructive and
helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other GOP members who were reconsidering their plans
to vote against impeachment was Representative Jack Quinn of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The developments unfolded as House Democrats worked privately on
toughening their censure proposal in a final effort to win enough
support from rank-and-file Republicans to force GOP leaders to
permit a vote on the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Without such pressure, the prospects of orchestrating a censure
vote are seen as highly remote. For example, Representative J.
Joseph Moakley, the highest ranking Democrat on the House Rules
Committee, has been searching for a way to force a vote despite
opposition from Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But Moakley has yet to find an opening. ``It's pretty
airtight,'' said his spokeswoman, Karin D. Walser.
</P>
<P>
   In a related move, the three authors of the Democratic censure
resolution, including Representative William D. Delahunt of
Massachusetts, were writing to the Rules chairman, Gerald B.H.
Solomon of New York, to ask that he permit the censure vote despite
the opposition from GOP leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impeachment was designed by our nation's founders as a means
to resolve a national crisis,'' Delahunt said. ``Instead, we are in
the process of creating such a crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Solomon, who is retiring after 20 years in the House,
has rarely bucked his party leaders and is unlikely to do so as his
last congressional act.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
