<HEADLINE>
ENDEAVOUR CREW PREPARES TO END MISSION WITH FLORIDA LANDING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Endeavour astronauts on Monday stowed equipment and made
preparations to end their space station assembly mission with a
rare night landing at NASA's Kennedy Space Center in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle was to touch down at 11:54 p.m., EST, Tuesday at
Kennedy. There was a second landing opportunity at 11:30 p.m., CST,
in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Low clouds and rain could interfere. Mission managers elected
not to ready the shuttle's backup landing site at Edwards Air Force
Base, Calif., unless the Endeavour crew was still aloft Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a suit up and let's see how things look,'' said
Endeavour commander Bob Cabana, a reference to the bulky pressure
suits they must don while ground control teams sort out the weather
below.
</P>
<P>
   The five Americans and the Russian cosmonaut aboard the shuttle
seemed in high spirits on the eve of their return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are feeling terrific. We are ready to start packing and
come home, see our families just in time for Christmas,'' said
astronaut Nancy Currie. ``We could not be more pleased with the way
the mission has gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts stowed tools and other equipment used during
their successful effort to join the first components of a new
international space station. They checked steering thrusters and
the hydraulic systems needed as they re-enter the Earth's
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour blasted off Dec. 4 with ``Unity,'' the first
American-built component of the new station. After catching the
Russian-build ``Zarya'' module launched Nov. 20, the shuttle crew
joined the two modules and conducted three spacewalks to activate
electrical power, computer systems and communications gear. The
astronauts ventured into the modules to prepare them for more
assembly missions planned next year.
</P>
<P>
   It was a moment NASA and its international partners had been
working toward since 1984 when former president Ronald Reagan
proposed a global science outpost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we looked out the window and saw (Unity and Zarya)
out there sitting in the payload bay, we just kept pinching
ourselves and saying it can't be real,'' Cabana told a pre-landing
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   He attributed the mission's success to teamwork amongst the U.S.
and Russian space agencies, their contractors, the trainers, and
flight crews and planners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have our work cut out for us,'' Cabana said of the
many assembly flights to come. ``It takes a great deal of effort to
pull off a mission successfully that is this complicated, but I
think we have shown it can be done if we prepare properly.''
</P>
<P>
   The 12-day flight's only disappointment was a test flight of the
back mounted jetpacks that will be worn by spacewalking station
astronauts. The device is the only means spacewalkers have of
rescuing themselves if the two safety tethers they wear were to
snap.
</P>
<P>
   Astronaut Jerry Ross cut short a brief test flight during his
final spacewalk when it appeared he was out of fuel. Later, the
electronic fuel gauge indicated he had fuel left.
</P>
<P>
   A valve on the jetpack failed during a 1997 test.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little frustrating we don't have a fully functional
(jetpack) at this point,'' said Ross. ``We will need to pursue this
fairly vigorously.''
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle crew planned to spend its last night of its mission
deploying the second of two small satellites they carried into
orbit.
</P>
<P>
   The 705-pound Mighty Sat satellite was developed by the U.S. Air
Force as a means of testing advanced electronics and power
generating solar arrays. Late Sunday, the astronauts deployed the
first of the two, a 590-pound satellite developed by Argentina and
equipped with experimental guidance equipment, a camera and whale
tracking instruments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
