<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYEES GAIN PROTECTION FOR FEDERAL TESTIMONY
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal civil rights law protects workers against
retaliation for testifying against their employers in federal
court, the Supreme Court ruled unanimously Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In an opinion by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, the court
said the protection extends even to those employees who have no
guaranteed tenure, and who may ordinarily be dismissed at the will
of their employers.
</P>
<P>
   The decision overturned a 1997 ruling by the federal appeals
court in Atlanta, which held that because such ``at-will
employees'' have no vested interest in their jobs, they are not
covered by a Civil War-era law that permits people who become
targets of a retaliatory conspiracy as a result of their testimony
in federal court to sue for damages to their ``person or
property.'' A job from which a person may be dismissed at will is
not an aspect of ``property,'' the appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the court, Rehnquist said the appeals court had
misunderstood the focus of the 1871 law, often known as the Ku Klux
Klan Act. ``The gist of the wrong'' at which the law was directed,
he said, ``is not deprivation of property, but intimidation or
retaliation against witnesses in federal-court proceedings.'' He
said that nothing in the law required a plaintiff to prove injury
to a ``constitutionally protected property interest,'' as the 11th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals had insisted.
</P>
<P>
   The limitation the 11th Circuit placed on the law was a
substantial one, because most private-sector workers _ 88 percent,
according to one brief submitted in the case _ have no contractual
protection against dismissal and fall under the category of at-will
employees. Other federal circuits had applied the law more broadly,
and the Justices used the case, Haddle vs. Garrison, No. 97-1472,
to resolve the conflicting interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff, Michael A. Haddle, had been a manager for a home
health-care company in Augusta, Ga., that was under federal
investigation for Medicaid fraud. He cooperated with the
investigation and appeared before a federal grand jury, although he
apparently did not actually testify. The owner of the company
pleaded guilty to Medicaid fraud, went to prison, and was ordered
to repay the government $11 million. Haddle lost his job.
</P>
<P>
   He sued the owner and two other officials for conspiring to
retaliate against him in violation of the Civil Rights Act of 1871,
which prohibits conspiracies to ``deter, by force, intimidation, or
threat,'' a witness from testifying in federal court or to injure a
witness ``in his person or property'' because of his testimony.
Congress passed the law to preserve access to the federal courts in
the Reconstruction-era South in the fact of rampant intimidation by
the Klan.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion, Rehnquist said there was a long legal tradition
of treating employment relationships as protected from wrongful
interference, without making a distinction between at-will
employment and other kinds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   These were among the Court's other activities Monday:
</P>
<P>
   Community Placement
</P>
<P>
   Accepting an appeal filed by the state of Georgia, the court
agreed to decide whether a state violates the Americans with
Disabilities Act by treating people with mental illness and
retardation in institutions rather than in residential placements
in the community, when such placements are appropriate for the
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling earlier this year in a suit brought on behalf of two
mentally retarded patients at the Georgia Regional Hospital, in
Atlanta, the 11th Circuit ruled that the disabilities act required
treatment in the least restrictive appropriate environment, and
that budgetary constraints are generally not a defense.
</P>
<P>
   In its appeal, Olmstead vs. L.C., No. 98-536, Georgia is arguing
not only that the appeals court misinterpreted the 1990 law but
that, if the interpretation is correct, Congress exceeded its
enforcement authority. This case could produce the court's second
major ruling under the disabilities act; last year, the justices
examined the law's definition of disability and held that people
with nonsymptomatic HIV infection were protected against
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Ex Post Facto Laws
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, the court turned down appeals by the state of
Kansas from two rulings invalidating new approaches to giving state
prison inmates credit toward early release on the basis of good
behavior. In both cases, Kansas appellate courts ruled that the new
regulations, imposing stiffer requirements on the inmates by
changing the rules after the inmates began serving their sentences,
amounted to unconstitutional ex post facto laws.
</P>
<P>
   One of the regulations invalidated by the Kansas Supreme Court
required inmates convicted of sex offenses to participate in a
``sex abuse treatment program'' as a condition of accumulating
``good-time credits'' toward parole eligibility. The regulation was
challenged by two inmates who had previously been able to earn
good-time credits merely by staying out of trouble, and who refused
to participate in the treatment program because it required
accepting responsibility for their crimes while their cases were
still on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six states joined Kansas in appealing the state court
ruling, which the states argued would deprive prison administrators
of the ``necessary administrative flexibility'' to take advantage
of ``a host of new medical and sociological theories.'' The cases
were McKune vs. Steltzlen, No. 98-366, and Hannigan vs. Stansbury,
No. 98-367.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
