<SLUG> BC-MATTEL-LEARNING-ART-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATTEL ANNOUNCES PLAN TO BUY SOFTWARE FIRM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mattel Inc., the world's largest toy maker, announced Monday
that it planned to acquire the Learning Co. in a $3.8 billion stock
deal that would position the company as a leader in the high-growth
market for software.
</P>
<P>
   But Mattel also warned investors to expect disappointing
financial results for the fourth quarter and the year, sending its
shares tumbling nearly 27 percent, or $8.125, to $22. That was a
52-week low for the stock, which was the most actively traded issue
Monday on the Big Board. Shares of the Learning Co. fell $3.3125,
to $25. The deal, based on a value of $33 a share, could be in
jeopardy if Mattel's price continues to slide or fails to rebound,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   While shareholders typically cheer news that a company is
broadening its product line and is thinking ahead, Monday's news of
the bleak financial outlook ``is so disappointing that it is really
hard to say what it means for the deal,'' said Martin Romm, who
follows Mattel for Credit Suisse First Boston. He said continued
stock volatility could threaten the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a decline in orders from large retailers, Mattel, the
maker of Barbie and Hot Wheels, said its revenue would be flat and
earnings would be significantly below projections. ``This situation
is very painful and disappointing for us,'' said Jill Barad,
chairwoman and chief executive of Mattel, which is based in El
Segundo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring the Learning Co., the nation's top maker of
educational programming, would significantly increase Mattel's
competitiveness in software by combining Mattel's strengths in
research and development, distribution and purchasing with the
other company's expertise in software development. The Learning
Co., with projected 1998 revenue of $850 million, is the world's
second-largest independent maker of consumer software, after
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   If the combination goes through, consumers might see, for
instance, Mattel's popular Tickle Me Elmo doll transformed into a
tutor on CD-ROM or the Learning Co.'s Reader Rabbit animated
character developed into a plush toy with the electronic brains to
read to children or teach them the alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, consumers would be likely to see faster delivery of
new educational and entertainment programs at competitive prices in
more stores, toy industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will mean more selection, better distribution and more
traditional Mattel toys delivered via software,'' said Tim
Ghriskey, senior portfolio manager at the Dreyfus Corp., which
owned 191,200 shares of Mattel in September but has sold its stake.
</P>
<P>
   Educational and entertainment software is becoming increasingly
important in the $22 billion toy market, as manufacturers seek ways
to retain young consumers who are shoving traditional board games
and action figures to the back of the toy chest in favor of
action-packed electronic alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   While sales of traditional toys declined 0.6 percent this year
through October, revenue in the $1.8 billion category of education
and entertainment software rose 4 percent, according to the NPD
Group.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Some kids are now abandoning toys early and getting into
computers at earlier ages,'' said Gene Gilligan, executive editor
of Playthings magazine, a trade publication, and toy companies are
responding by moving ``products into some of these high-tech
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Learning Co. deal, Mattel would have $1 billion in
software sales and an edge in electronic products over Hasbro Inc.,
the No. 2 toy maker. Hasbro has also been strengthening its
position in high technology, recently acquiring the software game
manufacturer Microprose Inc. and Tiger Electronics, the maker of
Furby, this holiday season's must-have toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together we have the engine and the content to redefine
leadership in the interactive world,'' said Michael Perik, chairman
and chief executive of the Learning Co., which is based in
Cambridge, Mass. He will join Mattel's management team. The deal
has been approved by the boards of both companies, but remains
subject to regulatory and shareholder approval.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing its bleak financial news, Mattel said it had been
hurt by decreased sales from several retailers, including Toys
``R'' Us, which has halved its inventory of Mattel products this
year as it tries to improve its own poor performance. ``This has
negatively impacted our sales by approximately $350 million this
year,'' Ms. Barad said of the cutbacks by the retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding its troubles, Mattel said that it had switched to
just-in-time product shipment to manage inventory better, but that
the move would reduce sales by an additional $150 million this
year. ``Given this $500 million revenue decline, we expect our 1998
sales to be flat with last year,'' she said. The company had
revenue of $4.84 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel now expects earnings for the year to be about $1.20 a
share before a one-time charge, a 33 percent decline from the
company's previous estimate. The analysts' estimate on annual
earnings had been $1.78 a share, according to a poll by First Call.
Earnings in the previous year were $1.65.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magnitude of the problem in terms of the write-downs taken
to move inventory did catch a lot of investors off guard,'' said
David Leibowitz, an analyst at Burnham Securities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
