<HEADER>
A9572 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      12-14 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS' OPINIONS ASIDE, REPUBLICAN SUPPORT FOR IMPEACHMENT GELS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also IMPEACH-POLL, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-DEMS,
IMPEACH-MAIL, IMPEACH-RODINO) 
(htv) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL and JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the House vote on impeachment drew closer, the
ranks of Republicans supporting President Clinton's impeachment
grew Monday and, in a more ominous sign for the White House, some
of the few Republicans who have been on the record against the
impeachment drive began to waver.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican votes for impeachment continued to solidify
despite a remarkable stability in public opinion. Sixty-four
percent of Americans, including a majority of independent voters,
said they did not want their representatives to vote for
impeachment, according to the latest New York Times/CBS News Poll
conducted Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that while most voters do not dispute the
accusations of perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse of power
outlined in the articles of impeachment approved by the House
Judiciary Committee, only 24 percent want the House to actually
vote to impeach Clinton. Another 37 percent of Americans want
Congress and Clinton to work out a compromise; 37 percent want the
matter dropped entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to escape questions about the fate of his Presidency as
he continued a Middle East peace-making mission, Clinton said that
he was open to ``any reasonable compromise'' short of impeachment.
``I don't believe it's in the interest of the United States and the
American people to go through the impeachment process and have a
trial in the Senate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But with the White House increasingly pessimistic about the
President's ability to win the vote in the House, Vice President Al
Gore was anything but conciliatory. He denounced House Republican
leaders for refusing to allow a vote to censure the president and
accused them of ignoring the ``wisdom of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's sharp-edged comments came at the end of an otherwise
routine White House announcement on a new round of law enforcement
grants. ``It's very unfortunate that the leadership of the House of
Representatives has made a decision to reject compromise and force
a vote only on impeachment, and not give the members of Congress a
chance to vote their conscience,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   His tone was echoed by the White House press secretary, Joe
Lockhart, who said, ``There is a small group of the Republican
leadership who have made it their mission in life to remove the
president against perhaps the will of the House but certainly
against the will of the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   He also raised the specter that a Senate trial could undermine
the economy. ``I'd say that any student of the markets will say
that uncertainty is bad for the markets,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that a direct campaign to lobby Republicans would be
counterproductive at this point, the White House and its allies
focused many of their efforts on trying to energize the public and
stoke a backlash against impeachment. John J. Sweeney, president of
the AFL-CIO, instructed union members to use a toll free line to
call the Capitol and press Republicans for a censure vote. He also
urged union locals within 100 miles of Washington to wage a mass
demonstration and vigil on the steps of the Capitol when the
impeachment debate begins Thursday, and the Rev. Jesse Jackson
called for a prayer vigil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effort to impeach President Clinton has moved beyond
reason or responsibility,'' he said in a letter to union
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``People for the American Way,'' a liberal advocacy group, said
it would broadcast 30-second radio spots Tuesday evening urging
Americans to use a toll-free line to call Capitol Hill. The ad
features a couple locked in conversation about impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country's going to be paralyzed,'' a woman says. ``And you
know who is going to suffer?'' Her companion answers: ``We will.''
</P>
<P>
   Capitol offices were already deluged Monday with phone calls,
e-mails and telegrams. The phone traffic was so heavy that callers
to House offices often received an electronic message: ``All
circuits are busy. Please try your call again later.''
</P>
<P>
   And some Clinton allies did try personal appeals. The actor
Robert DeNiro made calls against impeachment Monday to at least two
New York Republicans _ Reps. James Walsh of Syracuse and Sherwood
Boehlert of Utica. Neither congressman returned his calls, and
Walsh had already declared for impeachment this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee sought to stiffen
the resolve of members. They drafted a set of talking points for
Republicans on the committee to use in explaining the committee's
votes for four articles of impeachment. It struck three main
points: that ``the evidence is overwhelming;'' that ``our laws
should apply equally to every American,'' and that ``America and
the Constitution are strong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the height of egotism to suggest that the president's
well-being and the well-being of the country are the same,'' said
one of the talking points.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans appeared to be moving steadily toward impeachment.
Rep. Christopher Shays, who was one of the first Republicans to
speak out against impeachment, softened his position Monday on the
eve of a town meeting in his Connecticut district.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the vote were today, I'd be voting against,'' Shays said.
``But it is not the same kind of certainty I had a week ago. My
certainty has been shaken by the president's failure to come to
grips with his problem.'' He was particularly critical of Clinton's
statement of contrition last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just dug a deeper a hole,'' Shays said. ``I think he needs
to say he did not tell the truth. And he did not. Like all
Americans, he must abide by the laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays said he wanted to meet with the President before he casts
his vote. The White House was so alarmed that John Podesta, the
White House chief of staff, called Shays to arrange the meeting
immediately after reading his remarks on a new wire.
</P>
<P>
   One other in the handful of Republicans who have expressed
opposition to impeachment also signaled a possible change of heart.
Aides to Rep. Jack Quinn, a Republican from outside Buffalo, said
he was now undecided.
</P>
<P>
   In the lame-duck 105th Congress, Republicans hold 228 seats. The
Democrats have 206, and there is one independent who usually votes
with the Democrats. Democratic leaders are hoping to hold all but
three to five Democrats against impeachment. That means Clinton
must win support from 14 to 16 Republicans to prevail by just one
vote.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to see how he can reach that number, with only Reps.
Amo Houghton and Peter T. King, both of New York, and Mark Edward
Souder of Indiana still solidly against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The pool of undecided Republicans shrank Monday, when Reps.
Wayne T. Gilchrest of Maryland, Frank A. LoBiondo of New Jersey,
Charles Bass of New Hampshire and Zach Wamp of Tennessee, all
declared their alignment with the majority for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans were picking and choosing among the articles of
impeachment. Wamp said he would support the articles accusing
Clinton of perjury before a grand jury and of obstruction of
justice, but said he was still weighing the other two articles of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who were still searching for converts to the
President's cause, said that most of the Republicans who declared
their positions Monday had never been considered likely to support
him. A senior Democratic leadership aide said, ``It's going to come
down to three or four votes but it's still doable.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle for votes is expected to intensify over the next few
days. The House begins consideration of the president's impeachment
on Thursday and the leaders of the two parties were still
negotiating over the time to be allowed for debate. Republicans
were offering six to eight hours and Democrats _ still looking at
parliamentary maneuvers to force a vote on censure _ were seeking
as much as two days.
</P>
<P>
   But even before the critical vote, there were signs that much of
Washington was turning its attention to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In an op-ed article in The New York Times on Tuesday, Bob Dole,
Clinton's Republican Opponent in the 1996 presidential race, urges
the Senate _ whether or not impeachment is approved by the House _
to pass a tough censure measure that Clinton would have to sign. He
suggests that all Congressional action should be complete by Jan.
2.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert G. Torricelli, a New Jersey Democrat, said that the
Senate would be operating in ``a legal twilight zone'' with only
one precedent, the trial of Andrew Johnson 130 years ago. He
suggested the Senate could choose to toss out the impeachment case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the first judgment to be made in the United States
Senate is whether a motion will be entertained to dismiss the
impeachment resolution passed by the House of Representatives,'' he
said. ``It would be the legal equivalent of a motion to dismiss.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
