<SLUG> BC-NY-VACCO-CONCEDE-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 6 WEEKS, VACCO ACCEPTS ELECTION OUTCOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ After battling the inevitable for six weeks,
State Attorney General Dennis Vacco returned to his hometown on
Monday to concede to Elliot Spitzer, his Democratic opponent,
declining to say why he had stubbornly fought the results of last
month's election but pledging to cooperate fully in the transition.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer accepted Vacco's belated concession with a smile. ``He
was gracious today, and that's all I am going to say,'' the
attorney general-elect said. ``As of today, it is no longer a
matter of looking backward.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vacco concession came after a protracted, controversial
series of legal challenges by Vacco's campaign, which asserted that
his re-election was thwarted by widespread voter fraud and election
irregularities in New York City. Vacco and his lawyers were unable
to substantiate their allegations, and their legal fight came to an
end on Monday when a State Supreme Court justice dismissed all of
the complaints brought by the Vacco campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Thomas Keegan, said Vacco _ who sought to be named
attorney general by the court or to have a new election ordered _
had failed to demonstrate his contention that thousands upon
thousands of votes were cast illegally in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come to bring finality to this election,'' the
judge said.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision paved the way for the State Board of
Elections to certify Spitzer as the next attorney general on
Tuesday, with a lead of slightly more than 26,000 votes over Vacco
out of more than 4 million votes that were cast.
</P>
<P>
   In speaking to reporters and a large crowd of family members,
colleagues and supporters, Vacco did not directly address how or
why he decided to abandon his legal maneuvers to remain in office.
``I've got a lot to say about that,'' said Vacco, speaking in a
large ballroom in the office building that also houses the attorney
general's office in Buffalo. ``But now is not the time and place.''
</P>
<P>
   Invoking the names of his two young sons, Vacco added: ``This
decision was based on what's in the best interest of Alex and
Connor. This was the right decision for them.''
</P>
<P>
   At times smiling broadly and at others tight-lipped and fighting
back tears, Vacco said little on Monday about the six-week legal
wrangling that, at various points, ensnared the courts and
threatened a crisis over whether either candidate would be
certified as the state's 63d attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Nov. 3 election, Vacco has been vilified by Democratic
leaders in the state for his efforts to forestall Spitzer's
ascendancy. In particular, Vacco was criticized for his
unsuccessful attempt to invoke a seldom used state law that would
have police officers conduct door-to-door visits to verify the
voting eligibility of more than 100,000 New York City residents.
</P>
<P>
   He was accused of attempting to intimidate the black and
Hispanic neighborhoods where Spitzer won handily. But that plan
fell through, when Mayor Rudolph Giuliani refused to instruct the
police to cooperate unless ordered to by a judge, which was not
forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Vacco made it clear that he intended to cooperate
fully with his Democratic successor in the weeks before Spitzer
takes office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transition will be like a hot knife through butter,''
Vacco said. ``It will occur in an orderly process.''
</P>
<P>
   Vacco had called Spitzer on Monday morning to congratulate him
and to pledge his support in assuring a smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
   In the Spitzer camp, Vacco's concession drew expressions of
relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``He waged a fight that he believed he had to fight,'' Spizter
said at an afternoon news conference at his law office in midtown
Manhattan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a brief statement, Gov. George Pataki praised the work of
Vacco, a fellow Republican, and congratulated Spitzer on his
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``During his tenure as attorney general, Dennis Vacco
demonstrated that he has been a fighter who put the best interests
of the people of New York first,'' Pataki said. ``He was a national
leader in our efforts to crack down on those who use the Internet
to prey on children, as well as in passage of Megan's law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward,'' Pataki said, ``to working with Attorney
General-elect Spitzer to continue the progress we have made in
protecting consumers, preserving our environment and making New
York an even better place to live, work and raise a family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
