<HEADER>
A9585 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MATTEL-SFCHRON &LR;      12-14 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Mattel To Buy Learning Co.  &HT;       
 Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
In a deal that partners Barbie and Carmen Sandiego, toymaking titan
Mattel Inc. said yesterday it will buy educational software giant
The Learning Co. Inc. in a stock swap valued at $3.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Co., which has spent the past year gobbling up
independent Bay Area software-makers like Broderbund, Mindscape and
Creative Wonders, is in turn being swallowed by the world's biggest
toy company.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will make Mattel the second biggest consumer
software-maker behind Microsoft Corp. It also will accelerate the
El Segundo toymaker's plans to produce more interactive, high-tech
toys and to reduce its reliance on traditional retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel Chairman and chief executive Jill Barad paired the merger
announcement with a warning that Mattel's profit would not meet
analysts' estimates this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the process of transforming ourselves from a
traditional toy company into a global children's products
company,'' said Barad. ``We have known interactivity is the future
and the future is now.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal, expected to become final in March or April, will bring
together some of the most well-known brands in the toy and
educational software kingdoms.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel, which expects sales of its franchise Barbie doll to drop
off this year for the first time since 1976, said new toy orders
from mainstream retailers came to ``a screeching halt'' after
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   But Mattel, buoyed by strong sales of the popular Barbie CD-ROM
titles, has grown its new interactive business to $100 million in
revenues. With the Learning Co. acquisition, Mattel expects to hit
$1 billion in software &UR;  &LR; sales within five years.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, Mattel hopes to use the Learning Co. as a
springboard to increase direct-to-consumer sales _ through the
Internet and catalogs _ to about $1 billion in the next few years,
Barad said.
</P>
<P>
   With The Learning Co., based in Cambridge., Mass., Mattel adds a
stable of software titles that includes the Reader Rabbit series
that was acquired when SoftKey Corp. bought the original Learning
Co. of Fremont for $600 million in 1995. SoftKey then changed its
name to The Learning Co.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Learning Co. paid $150 million for Novato-based
Mindscape, maker of Mavis Beacon Teaches Typing and American
Greetings CreataCard Gold.
</P>
<P>
   And in June, Learning Co. acquired the best-selling Carmen
Sandiego educational series and the popular game Myst when it
bought Broderbund for $420 million. Just last week, Learning Co.
added San Rafael's Palladium Interactive to the fold.
</P>
<P>
   A Learning Co. spokeswoman said few staff reductions are
expected with the merger, which gives ``a tremendous opportunity to
get the Mattel brand into educational software, sort of a Learning
Math with Barbie.''
</P>
<P>
   All the while Learning Co. was on its buying binge, it was
already in talks with Mattel. Barad disclosed the two companies
began discussing a merger about one year ago, and talks intensified
within the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toy industry and the educational software industry are
almost morphing together,'' Learning Co. President Kevin O'Leary
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to create new products that fit this new vision
where we both think the industry is going. Together, we're already
in almost every home in America in terms of toys and software.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts liked the long-term prospects of the deal, but were
dismayed at Mattel's earnings warning.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel predicted that 1998 earnings will be about $1.20 a share,
far below Wall Street estimates of about $1.78 a share. Last year
it earned 95 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel stock plummeted $8.12 to close at $22. Learning Co.
closed down $3.31 at $25 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel has almost $5 billion in revenues and Learning Co. has
about $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strategically it makes sense, because it reflects the
convergence of toys, computers, software and mass marketization,''
said Larry Marcus, an analyst with BT Alex Brown.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the timing, given Mattel's earnings pre-announcement, is
very quizzical. Given the big pullback in Mattel stock, the jury is
still out on whether Learning Co. shareholders are going to be able
to benefit here in the near term.''
</P>
<P>
   Software industry analysts Rob Enderlee of Giga Information
Group said Mattel, along with the toy industry in general, is
realizing ``where the future growth appears to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattel's main competitor, Hasbro Inc., has also been building
its interactive division, and this year acquired electronics-maker
Tiger Electronics Inc. and educational software-maker MicroProse
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are still successful independent software-makers
like Electronic Arts of Redwood City, the Mattel-Learning Co. deal
is another step in the consolidation of the software industry into
``more powerful companies that can weather a broad set of financial
storms,'' Enderlee said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
