<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Schwab Plans to Go North of the Border  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Charles Schwab Corp. said yesterday it agreed to buy two small
Toronto securities firms, giving it a toehold in Canada for its
brand of electronic and traditional discount brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco firm will buy Priority Brokerage Inc., a
discount broker founded last year, and its sister company,
Porthmeor Securities Inc., which provides retail investment advice
and investment banking services. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The two firms will be combined to form Charles Schwab Canada.
Paul Bates, the president and chief executive of both companies,
will stay on to run the unit.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab's expansion into Canada follows previous purchases in
Britain and Hong Kong. Schwab recently said it was also talking
with potential partners in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Schwab dominates the traditional and
online discount brokerage businesses, offering customers access to
their accounts in branches, over the telephone and by computer. The
firm's online brokerage business is surging, with computer-based
transactions representing nearly 60 percent of its trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overseas markets probably represent Schwab's greatest
potential for growth,'' said Michael Flanagan, an independent
brokerage industry analyst in Pennsylvania. ``The international
markets are relatively less well-developed and have significantly
less competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Priority and Porthmeor will give Schwab only a tiny presence in
Canada. Together they have $120 million in customer assets compared
to Schwab's $461 billion. The two firms have only 28 employees and
a handful of offices, and aren't even licensed yet to do business
in Quebec, Canada's second largest province, and Manitoba.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab is buying the firms ``because they share our philosophy
of offering customers multiple channels'' for doing business,
spokeswoman Marta von Loewenfeldt said. About 30 percent of
Priority's trades are handled by computer.
</P>
<P>
   The firm will open new branches in key cities, von Loewenfeldt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schwab probably won't invest heavily to build branches in
Canada and is likely instead to launch a marketing blitz promoting
its electronic brokerage business, Flanagan predicted.
</P>
<P>
   With its population scattered over a vast territory, ``the
geography of Canada makes building a physical brokerage business
difficult.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians aren't strangers to discount electronic brokers. At
least 11 firms let customers trade stock online.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab's arch rival, Palo Alto electronic broker E-Trade,
entered Canada two years ago through an alliance with Versus
Brokerage Services.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Schwab stock jumped 5 percent yesterday, rising $2.19
to $41.56, partly on speculation that Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the
largest U.S. brokerage, would buy it, Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Merrill filed documents with the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission to issue $15 billion in new stock and debt
securities, a move some Wall Street traders said could be aimed at
building a war chest to buy Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts discounted the possibility, noting that Schwab's market
value is $17 billion, probably too expensive for Merrill to afford,
Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab's stock has also been buoyed by data showing that trading
volume is growing much faster than expected, boosting earnings
prospects. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
