u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LOBBY15-COX     12-14 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LOBBY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ALLIES, FOES STEP UP LOBBYING EFFORT
 &HT;    710 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With only days to go before the historic vote,
White House allies kicked into action Monday, clogging the
congressional phone lines, deluging fax machines and planning a
last-minute prayer vigil to halt the possible impeachment of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, public opinion polls have shown overwhelming approval
for the president's job performance. But in recent days,
presidential backers have moved to rally opposition to the
impeachment resolution the House will consider Thursday, while
pro-impeachment forces continued to circulate petitions and send
faxed and e-mailed messages to undecided House members.
</P>
<P>
   Mobilizing their response, the liberal group People for the
American Way announced it was spending $75,000 for radio ads in
Washington, Philadelphia and Columbus, Ohio, asking the public to
use a toll-free number to call moderate Republicans in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The group also has allied itself with an Internet effort that
generated more than 130,000 calls to Congress over six days.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, who has been Clinton's private spiritual
counselor after the president admitted to a sexual affair with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, is spearheading a public
prayer vigil planned for the U.S. Capitol on Thursday, to begin
just as debate opens on the resolution that could make Clinton the
second president ever to be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of buses are expected to bring supporters from Chicago,
Baltimore, Pittsburgh and New York, said Dina Anderson, spokeswoman
for the Rainbow/Push Coalition, the organizers of the vigil. She
said churches, labor unions and individuals would foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Other groups including the AFL-CIO and civil rights and feminist
groups have endorsed the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly alarmed state Democratic Party organizations also have
swung into action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough is enough,'' said Molly Beth Malcolm, chair of the
Texas party, in a message to fellow Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Send Congress a message,'' she instructed in an alert that
included a list of the state's delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Democrats bought newspaper ads telling readers to ``ask
Congressman Bob Ney (a Republican) to vote to end impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment advocates expressed less urgency, though the Rev.
Jerry Falwell sent out a special edition Friday of the ``Falwell
Fax'' to urge members of his Liberty Alliance to contact undecided
lawmakers, as congressional offices reported a flood of calls on
both sides of the impeachment issue.
</P>
<P>
   At the Christian Coalition, executive director Randy Tate said
his group had no plans for any public demonstrations in support of
impeachment and would stick with a petition drive that began in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lobbying this issue is like trying to speed up an avalanche,''
Tate said. He said his group already had gathered ``several hundred
thousand'' signatures on petitions and delivered them to members of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Vice President Al Gore lashed out publicly
at the Republican House leaders for refusing to allow the House to
consider the less drastic measure of censure of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the leadership of the Congress has done is to prevent any
kind of compromise along the lines that the American people want to
see,'' Gore said, in arguing that most Americans prefer censure to
impeachment followed by a trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   However, the White House has ``felt constrained in
orchestrating'' an all-out effort, said Jody Powell, who served as
press secretary for President Carter and who is now informally
assisting the Clinton team.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the vice president told reporters at a White House
ceremony that he would not make personal calls to House members.
Clinton has said it would be ``inappropriate'' to make calls unless
a lawmaker sought him out.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the White House had to fight off allegations of
hardball tactics. In an anonymous quote in the Arkansas
Democrat-Gazette, one unnamed White House aide was quoted as saying
that Rep. Jay Dickey, R.-Ark., would be committing political
``suicide'' if he voted for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton press secretary Joe Lockhart told reporters traveling
with the president in the Middle East on Monday that he would fire
anyone who made such a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
