<HEADER>
A9590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RODINO-820&AMP;AD     12-14 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RODINO-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODINO, BREAKING SILENCE, WARNS GOP ON IMPEACHMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-POLL, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-DEMS,
IMPEACH-MAIL) 
 (nk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST ORANGE, N.J. _ Peter Rodino, the man who presided over the
impeachment hearings of President Nixon, could hold his tongue no
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Blind in one eye, his vision half gone in the other, Rodino, now
89 but still only semi-retired, sat in front of the television over
the last few weeks without public comment, watching in disbelief as
the House Judiciary Committee pressed ahead toward a recommendation
that President Clinton be impeached, wincing as his name was
invoked, seething as comparisons were drawn between Clinton's
conduct and Nixon's cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Rodino broke his silence. He had said in interviews
before the hearings that he did not believe that Clinton's conduct
rose to the level of impeachment. But now he warns that impeaching
Clinton for perjury will cheapen the Constitution and weaken the
presidency. Rodino, a Democrat, endorsed censure of the president
as an appropriate punishment for what he called Clinton's
``appalling, reprehensible'' behavior and urged members of Congress
to heed polls showing a majority of Americans oppose impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Hyde has said the country is going to be put through
tumult and turmoil,'' he said, referring to the Judiciary Committee
chairman, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill. ``Well, let's save it from that.
Not just because we want to save President Clinton but because it
would be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his penthouse condominium here, overlooking the Eagle
Rock Reservation, Rodino, still dapper in blue corduroys and wool
sweater, kept reaching for a well-worn copy of his committee's 1974
impeachment report. He need not have. His memories of those
hearings are still powerful and contrast starkly with what he sees
happening in Washington now.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled listening in sorrow, as Judiciary Committee
chairman, to a recording of Nixon instructing his chief of staff,
H.R. Haldeman, to order the FBI to stop investigating the Watergate
cover-up, citing fictitious national security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lie,'' Rodino said. ``The political intelligence
committees, blackmailing their enemies, ordering IRS audits, the
break-in at Fielding's office, the wiretaps _ these things affected
our rights, our liberties, our privileges. They affected me as they
affect you.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the new speaker, Rep. Robert Livingston, R-La., seemed
to misunderstand the difference between Nixon's offenses and
Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read that Livingston will turn around and say, `Why
shouldn't we impeach Clinton, when we impeached Nixon for covering
up a burglary committed by others' _ that's not what we impeached
Nixon for,'' Rodino said. ``It's the totality of the many actions
which resulted in grave harm to the republic, which if permitted to
go on, would've destroyed the constitutional system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to consider whether what has been committed by Clinton
warrants that kind of action,'' he continued. ``One has to find
that the system of government is harmed so greatly, so seriously,
as would have been the case had Nixon been permitted to stay on.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than continuing with impeachment, Rodino said, the House
ought to vote for a strong censure, which he argued was ``not
impermissible,'' though it was not specifically contemplated in the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had read with dismay that some members of Congress,
mindful that a conviction in the Senate was unlikely, viewed the
act of impeachment itself as a form of censure. ``If that is in the
minds of some, that we are only doing this as an act of censure,
then we are violating the oath to account to the Constitution,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodino, virtually unknown outside of New Jersey when the
Watergate hearings began, was initially criticized by his own party
for moving too slowly, but won universal acclaim after the
Judiciary Committee reached a bipartisan decision, with seven
Republicans joining the Democrats in voting for impeachment. Nixon
resigned before the full House could act on the panel's
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Rodino recalled reining in the more aggressive Democrats on the
1974 panel, reminding them that the committee's decision would be
judged by the public in turn, and that the nation might not accept
their verdict if Democrats were seen to have rushed to a partisan
decision.
</P>
<P>
   He said the same standard applied to last week's party-line
votes on Clinton's fate. ``Those members on the committee have got
to be aware of the fact that there were 21 and 16, and there is a
division,'' he said. ``And what do we do? Are we so far apart, that
we permit it? We have got to think about the people and the union
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that the Hyde panel had not taken its duty
seriously enough. ``It may not be that it was a deliberate failure,
but this committee was never immersed in finding out what high
crimes and misdemeanors are all about,'' he said. ``They spent one
day devoted to that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rodino, now a professor of constitutional law whose occasional
lectures at Seton Hall University's law school in Newark, are
standing-room-only affairs, said his main concern was that a
worrisome new standard was being set, lowering the constitutional
threshold for ousting a sitting president.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is our country going to be governed in the future?'' he
said. ``Is there going to be someone who says, `I don't like how
things are going now, so we should impeach?'''
</P>
<P>
   Rodino recalled ``agonizing and anguishing'' during the 1974
hearings. He said he had been hospitalized for a few days then, for
``nightmares.'' He said he had hoped never to see an impeachment
again in his lifetime. He said the anguish had come back recently.
</P>
<P>
   As one who had lived through the gravest constitutional crisis
in American history, he said, he hoped to make people in Congress
and across the country realize the gravity of what is happening
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I'm going to change a single vote,'' he
said, falling back into his chair. ``Does this one voice do
anything?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
