A9591 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXPERTS-SFCHRON &LR;      12-14 1550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPERTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Stock Gurus Fear 1999  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Many investment gurus are feeling timid and frightened about the
prospects for the stock market in 1999 _ the Year of the Rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle asked 10 experts _ money managers, strategists,
researchers, economists and writers _ to predict how 1999 will
shape up for investors, and to recommend investment strategies for
the New Year.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of them disgorged a litany of worries and laments.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly they are worried about the global financial crisis. Some
fear that deflation, not seen on a sustained basis since the 1930s,
could pervade the U.S. economy and sap corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   They expressed concern about how the financial markets will
react as the Year 2000 _ and its dread computer problem _ looms
closer.
</P>
<P>
   And they are bedeviled by the uncertainties surrounding
President Clinton's political fate.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, they cite declining interest rates, which
tend to buoy stocks, and the potential streamlining of the European
economy when it switches to the new Euro currency next year.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a summary of their comments _ edited for space and
clarity.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Marshall Acuff &LR; , market strategist, Salomon Smith Barney, New
York:
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 challenge is that because of the global crisis, the
world continues to have significant excess manufacturing capacity.
It will take a while to rebalance supply and demand, which implies
that 1999 will be a year of slower growth. Profits could be down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The types of stocks I'd be interested in are those that grow
their earnings no matter what. Drug and medical-product stocks fit
that description. I'd include food chains such as Albertsons, and
food processors such as Philip Morris. I like defense stocks,
because the defense budget for fiscal 1999 will rise for the first
time since 1985.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _ &UR; Richard C. Blum &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Richard C. Blum &AMP; Associates, San
Francisco:
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy will continue to slow, certainly in the first half
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on in Asia is decidedly uneven. Thailand and
possibly Korea might snap out of it sometime soon. Hong Kong looks
like it is bottoming out or even turning around. Japan is still
stuck. China is still declining. Indonesia is still in chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the feeling that 1999 in Asia will be worse than 1998,
but later next year we're going to see turnarounds in some places.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are value investors, and we still believe that certain
companies we are already major shareholders in _ including URS, the
engineering company; Playtex, which makes personal care products;
and Nielsen, the media research company _ represent good value.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _ &UR; Don Phillips &LR; , &UR;  &LR; publisher, Morningstar Inc., Chicago:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with taking some money off the table for
a while. If you've been invested for the past five or 10 years, you
are probably further along the path to meeting your goals than you
expected to be at this point. You might want to move some assets
into something conservative, like fixed-income securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a fan of stocks in the small-cap and international arena,
both of which have been beaten up quite badly because of the
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Large caps have had the advantage for years, but at some point
gravity will take hold. Still, I wouldn't move over to small caps
all at once, because guessing when a trend will change is a futile
exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _ &UR; Alfred Goldman &LR; , chief market strategist, A.G. Edwards &AMP;
Son, St. Louis:
</P>
<P>
   ``The big picture, in my opinion, is still a bull market. The
economy will continue to grow next year. Corporate earnings will
rise moderately, and interest rates will continue to decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the Dow reaching a high for the year of about 10,500. At
the end of the year I expect it to be down to 9,500, because
sometime, nine or 10 months from now, investors will be getting the
heebie-jeebies about the Year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would focus on those companies best-positioned to grow their
earnings next year. In pharmaceuticals, I would look at
Warner-Lambert; in regional banks, Banc One; in retail food
Albertsons; in general retail, May Department Stores; in
technology, Compaq.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Todd Bakar,  &LR; director of research, Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, San
Francisco:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the global economic environment, there are
still some uncertainties. It looks and feels like we're seeing
slower economic growth. In an environment like that, what drives
stocks is earnings growth. Technology will continue to outperform
the broader markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within technology, sorting out winners from losers is tricky.
We continue to be big believers in technology services, information
technology, things of that ilk. One interesting company is CSG
Systems International, which provides billing services to cable
television and broadcast satellite companies. It is a strong
company, attractively positioned.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _ &UR; John Rothchild,  &LR; financial writer, author of ``The Bear
Book'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Valuations in the market are still tremendously high. It's
time to be a little defensive, a little cautious. We can't overlook
the fact that there are problems abroad that have yet to be solved.
I would advise caution, especially for people who need to take
their money out in the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a look at the classic bear market hedges: utilities, some
of the consumer stocks, companies that offer you a hefty dividend,
in case you don't get significant price growth for a while.
Consider companies like Fannie Mae, the tobacco companies and drug
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another interesting area is corporate bonds. They currently
provide good yields. In a low interest rate environment, with
profits not looking too lively, it might be a good idea to get into
the bonds of solid companies with decent yields.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _ &UR; Gary Schlossberg &LR; , &UR;  &LR; economist, Wells Fargo Capital
Management, San Francisco:
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporations are beginning to feel the dark side of deflation.
Our economy benefited for a while from the drop in import prices
and commodity prices. But now our companies are feeling pressure on
their profit margins. Price-raising power is practically
nonexistent in some industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask yourself what industries and companies are
best-insulated from deflation's impact on profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those that have well-recognized brand names will be best able
to maintain their prices and even increase them. Companies with
strong market niches might do well, because their products are
resistant to commoditization.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _ &UR; Joe Turner &LR; , &UR;  &LR; president, Pring Turner Capital Corp., San
Ramon:
</P>
<P>
   ``The negatives are pretty well known: the global economic
slowdown, the profit squeeze, which could be a big one, maybe the
impeachment process, Y2K, not to mention the fact that the market
is overvalued, especially large-capitalization stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the positive side is a falling-off of interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most exciting things that could affect the markets
is the Euro currency. It will eliminate protectionist policies and
speed up transactions between European countries. The Eurodollar
could pose serious competition for the U.S. dollar. We could see
more money flowing to European markets. There's going to be real
opportunity in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States, we're partial to health services
companies like Healthsouth Corp. and Sierra Health Services, which
are selling at reasonable price-earnings multiples. Energy is a
good place to look for bargains. Shell Transport, Apache Corp.,
National Fuel Gas and Questar are high-quality companies.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _ &UR; Greg Weiss &LR; , &UR;  &LR; money manager, editor of Investment Quality
Trends newsletter, La Jolla:
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the Asian crisis has not played itself out. There
is a great deal of depression in Asia, and that will have a
dilutive effect on U.S. corporate earnings and a depressing effect
on the U.S. equities markets. We expect a 10 percent decline from
the all-time highs in the first quarter of the year, followed by a
buying interlude, followed by a another downleg that takes the
market 20 percent below the highs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even so, there are undervalued stocks out there.
Archer-Daniels-Midland, the world's largest food commodities
processor, for one. And Worthington Industries, the nation's
leading processor of rolled flat steel, which has a nice 4.5
percent dividend. Another is Ennis Business Forms, whose stock has
been depressed because people claim the business forms industry is
dead, with everyone using laptops and laser printers. But in fact
Ennis is making software for that market.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _ &UR; Kurt Brouwer &LR; , Brouwer &AMP; Janachowski, Tiburon:
</P>
<P>
   ``1999 will be a year of transition _ probably a decent year,
provided corporate earnings don't slide, but not awesome. Because
the market is quite high, people will be looking real hard at the
earnings situation. Some excellent companies, including Intel and
Hewlett-Packard, are still attractive values.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will have a shorter fuse, and be less tolerant of even
modest, temporary earnings setbacks. We will see more of a trading
mentality, rather than long-term buy and hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to have a president impeached? That could have an
impact on investor confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
