 Setting Up A Roth IRA For a Child  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; QUESTION: &LR;  I want to set up a Roth Individual Retirement Account
for my son. The law allows a maximum annual contribution up to
either $2,000 or the holder's earned income for the year _
whichever is less. My son does not earn money. Can I get around
that by paying him $2,000 for cleaning his room?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANSWER: &LR;  You mean your son actually cleans his room???
</P>
<P>
   But seriously: No, you can't get away with that dodge. Payments
by parents to children for household chores _ even authentic ones _
won't cut it with the Internal Revenue Service if you get audited.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if your kid starts earning money from outside
sources for genuine services rendered, and can document the total,
he will be permitted to contribute every cent _ subject to the
$2,000 annual limit _ to an IRA.
</P>
<P>
   If he works part-time at the local hardware store, for example,
he will receive a W-2 form at the end of the year documenting his
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   If your neighbor pays him to cut the lawn or do other chores,
that counts too. Ask the neighbor to pay by check. Then, before
cashing or depositing each check, make a photocopy to store with
your tax records.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't bureaucracy wonderful?
</P>
<P>
   Simple IRAs
</P>
<P>
   Q: &LR;  The small firm where I work has one of the new SIMPLE IRA &LR; 
 &LR; retirement plans for its employees. At the end of the year, the &LR; 
 &LR; employer deposits an amount equal to 2 percent of each &LR; 
 &LR; employee's gross salary into each of our IRA accounts. Because &LR; 
 &LR; business has been weak, our employer is thinking about &LR;   &LR; canceling
the plan. Is he permitted to do this? As an &LR;   &LR; alternative, could he
just stop making payments until business &LR;   &LR; gets better? If he does
cancel the plan, can I roll my SIMPLE &LR;   &LR; IRA over into a regular
IRA? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Your employer can cancel the SIMPLE plan _ an acronym for
Savings Incentive Match Plan for Employees _ any time he chooses.
He doesn't even have to tell you that he is doing it, although he
does have to notify the plan sponsor _ the financial institution
that set the plan up and administers it.
</P>
<P>
   Skipping payments is not permitted. Once the payments stop, the
plan dies. However, your employer would have the option of starting
a new plan later.
</P>
<P>
   You might suggest that he set up a different version of the
SIMPLE plan, which would allow him to temporarily scale back his
payments. Your plan currently excludes employee contributions, and
therefore the 2 percent employer contribution is mandatory, up to a
maximum of $3,200 per employee per year.
</P>
<P>
   If your employer switches to a plan that permits employee
contributions, he normally will be required to match those
contributions up to a maximum of 3 percent of the employee's
salary. Three percent is greater than 2 percent, of course. But in
a hardship situation, your employer can reduce his contributions to
1 percent annually for two years during any five-year period.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MONEYBAG () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  It's probably a long shot, but you should at least ask him.
</P>
<P>
   As for rolling over to a regular IRA, you won't be able to do it
until at least two years have elapsed since your employer made the
first contribution to your account. SIMPLE IRAs were created by
Congress effective January 1, 1997 _ so as of today no rollovers
have been permitted.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason to roll your SIMPLE IRA money over into a
traditional IRA, notes Ann von Germeten, director of retirement
products at Charles Schwab. Both accounts are taxed the same way
and are subject to the same rules.
</P>
<P>
   But rolling over into a Roth IRA might make sense, because
investment gains earned in a Roth are tax-exempt. However,
converting will require you to pay any taxes owed on the money in
your old IRA.
</P>
<P>
   More on Roths
</P>
<P>
   Q: &LR;  I have a regular IRA that I am thinking of converting to &LR;   &LR; a
Roth IRA. I've read about how it would be best to convert &LR;   &LR; before
the end of this year, so I can spread my tax payments on &LR;   &LR; the old
IRA over four years. If I convert after this year, I &LR;   &LR; would have
to pay the tax all at once. But why can't I just &LR;   &LR; convert
one-fourth of my IRA every year for the next four &LR;   &LR; years? That
would spread the tax over four years, wouldn't it? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   But your question indicates that you are forgetting the best
reason for converting to a Roth: Any further investment gains on
the converted funds become tax-exempt.
</P>
<P>
   If you convert your present IRA in annual installments over a
four-year period, you will have to pay taxes on the investment
gains that accumulate in the old account during those years.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that there are investment gains, your method probably
would leave you holding substantially less after-tax money in your
Roth by the time the four years have elapsed.
</P>
<P>
   However, what you propose could make sense if there's a strong
chance that your tax rate might plunge during the next four years.
In that case, you would get to pay taxes on the conversion at the
future, lower rate, rather than at this year's higher rate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
