<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Oracle, Sun Micro Hatch New Plot Against Microsoft  &HT;       
 By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Silicon Valley powerhouses Oracle and Sun Microsystems joined
forces yesterday to try to derail Microsoft by eliminating the need
for the Windows operating system in some corporate networks.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle, the leading maker of database software, said Sun's Unix
operating system _ not Microsoft Windows NT _ will run a new
computer it is designing for Internet commerce. Oracle chief
executive Larry Ellison called the Sun system faster and more
reliable than Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   The new computer, code-named ``raw iron,'' could slow the
assault of Microsoft into the corporate market, where powerful
personal computers with Windows NT have been waging a battle with
Unix-based systems from Sun, Hewlett-Packard and IBM.
</P>
<P>
   The new Oracle-Sun computers will be designed to easily handle
financial transactions, inventory control and other aspects of
e-commerce. They could find a warm welcome among companies that do
business on the Web _ many of whom already use Oracle databases and
Sun's computers and operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new computers will be sold only to businesses, they
could result in faster online transactions for consumers, according
to Oracle officials.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle said the first raw iron computers will be rolled out in
March. A source close to the deal said Sun will build them, and
Oracle also hopes other companies such as Compaq and Dell will
offer their own versions.
</P>
<P>
   As part of yesterday's cross-licensing deal, Sun will combine
Oracle's database technology with e-commerce software that Sun is
getting as part of America Online's acquisition of Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts gave Redwood Shores-based Oracle and Mountain
View-based Sun a good chance at succeeding in their latest move
against Microsoft _ especially now when the software giant is under
the microscope of a federal antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now there's a lot of interest in finding products that
work around the Microsoft monopoly,'' said Bruce Raabe of Collins &AMP;
Co. ``This is a new way to move information that doesn't rely on
Windows at all, and if anybody's going to have a chance at making a
dent in the NT environment, it will be companies like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Oracle and Sun are the same companies that three years ago
touted the ``network computer'' as an alternative to PCs on the
corporate desktop. Ellison turned the NC into a personal crusade,
even starting a company _ Network Computer Inc. _ to develop it.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison proposed an under-$500 computer that could be used to
access the Internet or a corporate network. But when prices of
fully loaded PCs dropped well below $1,000, the NC found itself
without a market.
</P>
<P>
   Network Computer Inc. recently gave up on NCs and turned its
attention to software that connects consumer devices to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Sun makes an NC called the JavaStation which has enjoyed only
modest sales.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts yesterday, Ellison said the
new database appliances embody the idea of the NC. ``The vision is
the same,'' he said. ``We believe that what's going on is that the
PC is in the process of mutating into a network computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, however, think the failure of the NC has
tarnished Ellison's credibility. ``You really have to take
everything he says with a grain of salt,'' says Rob Enderle of Giga
Information Group. ``He's been long on promises and very short on
execution.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also the question of whether a mutual dislike of Bill
Gates will be enough to ensure a smooth relationship between
Ellison and Sun's CEO Scott McNealy, two of technology's freer
spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of these companies have strong leaders who like to go in
their own directions,'' said Enderle. ``And after a while the
direction of one may not include the other one. It will be cool if
it works, but it really ends up depending on how well these folks
can cooperate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
