<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 Amazon.com's German Rival Keeps Pressure on America's
Top  E-Tailer.  By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
German media giant Bertelsmann AG continues to up the ante in its
bid to supplant Amazon.com as the Web's top bookseller.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann Ventures of Santa Barbara, a venture capital fund of
the Bertelsmann Group, is expected to announce today that it has
taken a minority stake in Muenchhoff &AMP; Janz GmbH.
</P>
<P>
   Muenchhoff is a German technology company that created Acses_ a
well-known shopping service that searches the Internet to find the
lowest book prices offered over the Web. Terms of the investment
were not available.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann, which recently spent $200 million for a 50 percent
stake in online bookseller Barnesandnoble.com, says it hopes that
its stake in Acses will keep it apace of Amazon in the e-commerce
race. Acses allows Web users to shop the electronic aisles of some
25 Internet bookstores simultaneously, providing online shoppers
with the lowest price available for a particular book. Shipping
costs and delivery times also are included in the price search.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the system can search the prices of several books
at a time, gathering information for an entire electronic basket of
merchandise. Thus, the buyer only needs to shop at a single Web
site to find the lowest price for his or her total purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the ability to shop for multiple products on various
sites could become a huge factor as e-tailers such as Bertelsmann
and Amazon continue to expand into broader merchandise categories.
For its part, Amazon acquired a similar technology last August when
it bought Junglee, which is best known for its ability to perform
career searches on the Web. Amazon.com closed yesterday at $222.25,
down 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Financial Fudging: &LR;  What is it lately with financial advisers
and their propensity to misrepresent their backgrounds and
qualifications?
</P>
<P>
   First there was San Francisco money manager Frank Husic, now
there's personal finance guru Suze Orman. Before you run out to the
mall or dial into your favorite e-tailer to buy Orman's
best-seller, you might want to check out the latest issue of
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   The financial fortnightly reports that the 47-year-old East Bay
author and financial expert isn't everything she purports to be.
According to Forbes, Orman's latest book _ ``The 9 Steps to
Financial Freedom'' _ includes a biography of the author that
basically lies about her past.
</P>
<P>
   Orman's book calls her company, Suze Orman Financial Group of
Emeryville, a ``financial planning firm.'' Despite that claim,
Forbes contends that she doesn't perform financial planning work
any longer. In fact, aside from book royalties and speaking fees,
Forbes contends that her primary strength is selling insurance. Her
biography also claims that Orman has a current commodity trading
adviser license, but Forbes says the license expired in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But the creative writing doesn't end with Orman's book. In
addition, Forbes says, the text of one of her videotape jackets
claims that Orman has 18 years of experience working at major Wall
Street institutions. To the contrary, the magazine contends that
Orman spent only seven years toiling for Street firms.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls to Orman Financial were referred to a public
relations firm in New York. Telephone calls to the publicist were
not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Another cornerstone to the Forbes piece was the fact that Orman
is a regular guest on Oprah Winfrey's television talk show,
appearing five times.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Oprah's syndicated gabfest commands considerable sway
upon American popular opinion. If Forbes got its facts right, will
Orman continue to get booked on the show? A spokesperson for
Winfrey's Harpo Productions in Chicago says the decision will be
left up to the talk show's executive producer, who was unavailable
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Clarification:  &LR; In Friday's Street Smarts column, utility
consultant Gayatri Schilberg commented on the performance of PG&AMP;E.
Attribution to Schilberg should have been limited only to
comparisons between PG&AMP;E and other in-state utility companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
