<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DEMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS COUNT IN THE IMPEACHMENT EQUATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-POLL, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-DEMS,
IMPEACH-MAIL, IMPEACH-RODINO) 
(htv) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although nearly all the speculation in the last few
weeks has focused on certain Republicans in the House, a small
group of renegade Democrats could also affect the arithmetic and
fate of an impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   By last weekend, three Democrats, all from relatively
conservative districts in the South, had come out publicly in favor
of impeaching President Clinton. On Monday, Rep. Paul McHale of
Pennsylvania all but definitively joined that short list by voicing
some of his strongest sentiments yet for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   McHale said in a telephone interview Monday evening that he
still did not want to commit himself intractably to any vote, but
he portrayed himself as tilting even more sharply toward impeaching
Clinton than he did a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barring additional information that I would find to be
persuasive, that is the way I'm leaning,'' McHale said. ``I don't
feel I have any other alternative but to hold him accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   The other three Democrats who have publicly said that they favor
impeachment are Reps. Gene Taylor of Mississippi, Ralph M. Hall of
Texas and Virgil H. Goode Jr. of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor confirmed in a telephone interview Monday that he would
vote for impeachment. An aide to Goode said Monday that Goode was
standing by a statement last month supporting impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Hall did not return several telephone messages left with aides
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At least another eight Democrats were still officially undecided
Monday about what they would do when the full House votes on
impeachment, probably later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials predicted that, in a worst-case scenario,
no more than 10 Democrats in all would vote in favor of
impeachment. They said that party leaders were making appeals in an
effort to limit that number to 5 or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thinking is that we really have to keep our numbers as low
as possible,'' said Laura Nichols, a spokesman for House minority
leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri. ``For every Democrat you lose,
you've got to pick up a Republican, and that's very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one Democrats voted in early October for a formal inquiry
to determine if Clinton's actions stemming from his relationship
with Monica Lewinsky warranted impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But both Democratic and Republican officials said Monday that
most of those Democrats were expected to vote against the actual
impeachment of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them _ including Reps. Carolyn McCarthy of New York and
Jim Maloney of Connecticut _ have confirmed since the conclusion of
the House Judiciary Committee's work that they opposed impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney said in a telephone interview Monday that though it was
essential to have a thorough investigation into Clinton's actions,
the inquiry has shown that ``the wrongdoing does not amount to the
`high crimes and misdemeanors' standard set forth in the
Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Maloney said that he had received one call from a Democratic
Party leader and another from someone associated with the White
House in recent weeks, but that neither caller had pressured him.
</P>
<P>
   Aides for three other Democrats thought to be undecided said
Monday that the lawmakers would almost certainly vote against the
articles of impeachment. Those Democrats were Reps. James A.
Traficant Jr. of Ohio, Mike McIntyre of North Carolina, and David
Minge of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The list of Democrats who, aides said, were still at least
officially undecided Monday included Reps. Ike Skelton of Missouri;
Chris C. John of Louisiana; Lane Evans of Illinois; Robert E. (Bud)
Cramer of Alabama; Leonard L. Boswell of Iowa; Ron Kind of
Wisconsin; Charles W. Stenholm of Texas; and William O. Lipinski of
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic officials and political analysts said that most
of those people would probably end up voting against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pat Danner of Missouri was also thought to remain undecided
on Monday. Her spokesman did not return a telephone message.
</P>
<P>
   Charles E. Cook Jr., editor of the Cook Political Report, a
nonpartisan journal, said that most of the Democrats likely to vote
for impeachment come from predominantly Republican districts and
regularly buck the Democratic Party line.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could make a good case that political self-interest is
very much involved,'' Cook said. He said the one clear exception
was McHale, who did not run for re-election in November and will
leave the House next month.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said that while a solid majority of his constituents in
Mississippi support impeachment, he was going to vote that way
because he believed that the president had committed perjury and
should be held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is the law and everybody has to live by it, no matter
how wealthy or powerful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McHale expressed similar views, saying the president's apologies
over time seemed incomplete and somewhat disingenuous. He said he
kept waiting for a better one, but it never came.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in politics for 20 years, and I've been in public
service for 15 years, and no issue has ever come close in terms of
its importance or the degree to which it's pulled at my
conscience,'' McHale said. ``This is an absolutely sobering
decision of historic consequence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
