<HEADLINE>
GORE CANCELS POLITICAL TRIP IN ORDER TO STAY IN WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., eliminated earlier, this story is now restored; shorted)  
(sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore on Monday night canceled a
political trip that he had scheduled to New Hampshire on Thursday,
saying he would remain in Washington to support President Clinton
during the first day of impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Gore canceled the trip after it became clear to aides that the
visit to New Hampshire might produce conflicting television images
on Thursday night: The vice president tending to his political
career at the same moment that Clinton was battling impeachment
proceedings in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides said the trip to New Hampshire, the site of the
first presidential primary, had been scheduled before the
impeachment schedule had been announced. They insisted the
cancellation was not a political decision, though, saying Gore
instead wants to be available if Clinton needs him.
</P>
</TEXT>
