<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9604 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MAIL-ART-NYT &LR;      12-14 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MAIL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CONGRESS, SEPARATING GRASS ROOTS FROM `ASTROTURF' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., N.Y., Calif., Ohio, Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-POLL, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-DEMS,
IMPEACH-RODINO) 
(jw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If America does not care about impeachment, tell it
to Cathy Bassett. She works for Rep. Wayne Gilchrest, R-Md., who
until Monday morning had not revealed how he would vote on Thursday
on President Clinton's future. (He is now pro-impeachment.)
</P>
<P>
   Like hundreds of aides in the warrens of Capitol Hill, Ms.
Bassett spent Monday lifting her telephone receiver once or twice a
minute and listening to the views of voters across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lake Tahoe votes Impeach!'' Ms. Bassett declared, dropping her
pen because she did not record votes from outside Gilchrest's
district, from which calls were running about 60 percent in favor
of impeachment. But the caller had little more to say. ``He had to
go and catch the 1 o'clock ski lift,'' Ms. Bassett said before
taking the next call.
</P>
<P>
   Congress may be out of session and members out of town, but the
Capitol is ablaze in advance of Thursday's historic vote. With
unions mobilizing against impeachment and conservatives mustering
in favor, the volume of opinions has sent the Hill into overdrive,
clogging phone lines, maxing out voice mails, draining dry the
toner in fax machines and pushing e-mail systems to tilt.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Union office in the Cannon Office Building on the
House side of the Capitol has churned out more than 12,000
``opinion grams,'' more than four times its regular number, in the
last few days. The grams, a favorite method of communication among
lobbyists, are as numerous now as they were at the height of the
hearings on Supreme Court nominee Clarence Thomas in 1991. ``We're
processing them as fast as the printers will allow,'' said Mark
Harrop, a spokesman for Western Union Commercial Services.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter King, R-N.Y., said that several members of Congress
could contact their offices only by cell phone because their
regular phone calls were being bumped to that soothing voice that
is the curse of the electronic age: ``All circuits are busy. Please
try your call again later.'' Some aides said they blocked all calls
for various half-hour periods in the day just to clean their voice
mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the contacts were clearly orchestrated. One
anti-impeachment group _ ``Censure and Move On,'' an impromptu
online organization in Silicon Valley _ boasted Monday on the World
Wide Web that it had ``delivered'' 94,659 calls to the Capitol
since Wednesday and could blast fax messages to the three dozen
wavering members of Congress at once.
</P>
<P>
   Three congressional offices reported that they had received
8,000 e-mail messages each over the weekend. Aides to Rep. Tom
Campbell, R-Calif., who has not announced how he will vote, said he
received 900 e-mail messages over the weekend. ``We had to come in
over the weekend and go through them or today the server would have
crashed,'' spokesman Suhail Khan said Monday, adding that most
calls seemed scripted.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitol switchboard registered more than 14,000 phone calls
by midafternoon Monday, which is double the usual volume and does
not include the tens of thousands of calls swamping individual
offices. Rep. David Hobson, R-Ohio, who has not announced how he
will vote, logged about 600 calls Monday here and in his district.
The district phone system, not equipped for so many calls, was
getting ``nuked,'' said Scott Milburn, an aide.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the hub of democracy,'' said Jason Poblete, an aide on
the House Oversight Committee, which keeps track of the mechanics
of running the 435-member House. ``Any time you have an issue that
affects people, they call.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said that their calls were running largely in favor
of impeachment. Democrats said just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this district is any indication, the nation is waking up to
the fact we're right on the edge,'' said Rep. Bill Delahunt,
D-Mass., a member of the Judiciary Committee who said calls to his
Cape Cod district were running 5-1 against impeachment. He said his
office was getting so many calls, ``we can't handle them.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports of an e-mail system crash on the Hill were exaggerated,
Poblete said, noting that there was merely a bug in two of 14
electronic message servers. He said the problem was not caused by
overload, although there certainly was overload. He said some
people had been calling the main switchboard without knowing who
their representative was, and Capitol operators were taking the
time to direct them.
</P>
<P>
   Other callers were clearly going down lists of names and hitting
``redial'' to the Capitol. Aides in one office said that some
callers seemed confused when they got through. ``Whose office is
this?'' they asked before reading prepared remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the calls we are getting in the D.C. office, about half are
Astroturf and half are real,'' said Milburn, in Hobson's office,
using Washington parlance for calls that seem to be from
individuals but are in fact orchestrated by lobbying groups.
</P>
<P>
   Just who is behind the campaigns is not always clear.
</P>
<P>
   Some are overt, like the effort organized by 1199, the National
Health and Human Service Employees Union, which has transformed its
80-person telemarketing office in New York into an anti-impeachment
phone bank. Dennis Rivera, president of the union, said the
telemarketers were calling people who live in the districts of
eight House Republican moderates, whom he would not identify.
</P>
<P>
   Others were murkier in origin. Several offices have received the
same faxes. A popular one was ``Stop the Insanity of Christmas
Impeachment!'' Some of these appear to be from individuals. Typical
was one addressed simply to ``Dear Representative.'' It read:
``Censure is not enough! Impeachment may be too lenient! This
president is totally untrustworthy.'' It was signed, ``R. Gloria.
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   How much attention do such faxes receive? Not a lot. They are
collected, but aides in several offices said they did not have time
to read them, and most pay attention only to word from their
districts.
</P>
<P>
   At the prompting of a reporter, an aide in one office went
through a three-inch stack of faxes that had piled up Monday
morning. ``Oh, we have some real faxes in here,'' she said,
sounding surprised as she pulled out a message on Puerto Rican
statehood. She then squealed with delight at the most welcome
message of all: ``Oh! Party invitation! Yes!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
