<HEADLINE>
SHORTS ON HEALTH AND FITNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Minn., N.Y.)   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIDE EFFECTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ice Resurfacers Foul the Air at Rinks &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A truck being driven around inside a large enclosed space a
dozen times a day does not sound like a prescription for good air
quality. But it is what happens daily at indoor ice rinks, often
causing nitogen dioxide levels to reach worrisome levels, a study
of 19 public rinks in the Boston area has found.
</P>
<P>
   Place the blame on ice resurfacers, often known as Zambonis for
the original brand, the vehicles that chug slowly round and round
the rinks between periods at hockey games and other ice events,
scraping off slush and putting down fresh water to make a smooth
new top coat of ice.
</P>
<P>
   In a report published recently in the American Journal of Public
Health, researchers found a direct link between the kind of ice
resurfacer used and the levels of nitrogen dioxide in rink air.
</P>
<P>
   Rinks where the resurfacer was powered by propane had average
levels of 206 parts per billion of the gas _ twice the World Health
Organization's recommended maximum level of 110 parts per billion.
Those powered by gasoline averaged 132 parts per billion and rinks
with electrical resurfacers averaged 37 parts per billion.
</P>
<P>
   Some studies have linked chronic exposure to high levels of
nitrogen dioxide to increased risk of respiratory illness. In an
ice rink near St. Paul, a group of teen-age hockey players reported
difficulty breathing after 30 minutes of play in a rink where the
gas level was estimated at 4,000 parts per billion.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan I. Levy, a researcher and doctoral student at the
Harvard School of Public Health, said discomfort that some players
routinely write off as ``hockey lung'' _ tightness in the chest
from exertion in the cold _ could be a result of air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   During the study, four rinks switched from gasoline-powered
resurfacers to electrical ones. The nitrogen dioxide levels at the
rinks dropped sharply, from an average of 124 parts per billion to
35 parts per billion. But electrical resurfacers are expensive,
costing up to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Levy said less expensive measures _ from tuning the engines of
resurfacers to improved use of ventilation systems _ also showed
results.
</P>
<P>
   John O'Neil &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRO &AMP; CON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gifts From Patients Create a Quandary &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most physicians are delighted by the gifts their patients give
them. They are gracious tokens of affection and gratitude. But
theoretically, gifts from patients may cause ethical problems by
creating a sense of obligation and hence potential conflicts of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   For example, what if a doctor accepts gifts as ``payment'' for
extra time and attention in this age of managed care?
</P>
<P>
   Conflicts of interest like these are potentially harmful but not
as immediately harmful as rejecting a gift from a patient, which
may irrevocably fracture the patient-physician relationship. Such
conflicts may be avoided if the physician is careful not to let
gifts influence treatment.
</P>
<P>
   A doctor may also tactfully redirect cash or extravagant gifts
to a charitable or institutional fund. If a gift is inappropriately
extravagant or intimate, the physician should examine the patient's
motivation. The most appropriate response in most situations is a
sincere ``thank you.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laurie Lyckholm &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Assistant professor of internal medicine, Virginia Commonwealth
University &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The anthropologist Marcel Mauss said that gifts, by their very
nature, create an obligation. There are at least two ethical
problems with this practice. First, by accepting gifts physicians
may be telling patients that such gifts are expected. If one of my
patients learned of a gift given by another patient, she might
conclude that such gifts are a necessary part of our relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Second, managed care requires that physicians be stewards of
scarce resources like tests, procedures and their time. I want to
be sure that I am always willing to spend an hour on hold with an
insurance company for a patient, whether or not she has given me a
gift.
</P>
<P>
   When my patients offer me gifts that might seem to create an
obligation for other patients, or that might improperly influence
my judgment, I explain that I do this work because it's what I
love, not because I expect a reward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Casarett &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Associate medical director, Wissahickon Hospice, University of
Pennsylvania &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   PREVENTION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Folic Acid, in a Timely Fashion &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many women know that taking 400 micrograms of folic acid, a B
vitamin, early in pregnancy can reduce the risk of their babies'
having certain birth defects of the brain and spine. But a new
survey conducted by the March of Dimes warns that most women take
it too late in pregnancy to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Because nearly half of pregnancies in the United States are
unplanned, doctors suggest that women of childbearing age should
take a multivitamin with folic acid whether they are pregnant or
not.
</P>
<P>
   But, the March of Dimes researchers noted, only 25 percent of
women between the ages of 18 and 45 who are not pregnant take a
multivitamin containing folic acid, and the number drops to 19
percent among 18 to 24-year-olds who are not pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to be effective in preventing birth defects,'' said
Dr. Richard B. Johnson, Jr., medical director of the March of Dimes
in White Plains, N.Y., ``folic acid must be consumed before
conception and during the first four weeks of pregnancy.''
</P>
<P>
   Folic acid helps prevent neural tube defects, which are
responsible for birth defects in an estimated 2,500 babies each
year and can result in miscarriages and stillbirths.
</P>
<P>
   Spina bifida, a leading cause of childhood paralysis, is the
most common neural tube defect.
</P>
<P>
   Experts also advise pregnant women and those who want to
conceive to eat a balanced diet with foods high in folic acid, like
leafy green vegetables, orange juice and beans.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Villarosa &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CONSEQUENCES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fasten Your Seatbelt _ and Take a Walk &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When travelers sit for a long time in cramped airline seats, the
consequences can be far more serious than swollen ankles or an
aching back.
</P>
<P>
   Hours in one position can trigger blood clots in the legs. If
the clots dislodge and move into the lungs, they can be deadly.
Doctors know the problem formally as deep vein thrombosis, but some
of them call it economy class syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, former Vice President Dan Quayle was treated for blood
clots in both lungs and his right leg after frequent domestic
flights. And in 1996, a passenger on a British Airways flight
collapsed when multiple blood clots moved into his lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Now doctors at Tripler Army Medical Center in Honolulu found
that about one-fourth of 134 patients suffering from clumps of
clotted blood in the lower legs _ and that 82 percent showed
symptoms as long as two weeks later. There were 36 percent of
travelers who had no other predisposition for the syndrome, said
Dr. Joel Brown, one of the authors of the study.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting for long periods _ four hours or more _ reduces
circulation in the legs by 50 percent, the researchers said.
Besides clots, the results can include pain, swelling, redness,
tenderness in the calves and, infrequently, fever.
</P>
<P>
   The dry air in airline cabins only makes things worse, they
said, because it makes the blood more viscous, encouraging clots.
Smoking, pregnancy, obesity, use of oral contraceptives, a history
of deep vein thrombosis, varicose veins and eating fatty foods can
also raise the risk of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Experts recommend exercising before the flight and during the
flight, either by walking in the aisles or in your seat. Drinking
plenty of water, taking aspirin (with a doctor's approval) and
wearing below-the-knee support hose if you have varicose veins,
also help prevent the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Farrol Kahn &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
