u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES16-C     12-14 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson's best blocker placed on IR
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the sight of Atlanta Falcons backup running back
Gary Downs putting a sock on the left foot of fullback Bob
Christian after Sunday's 27-17 win at New Orleans wasn't enough to
bring tears to the eyes of running back Jamal Anderson, the news
Monday may have done it.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons placed Christian on injured reserve with torn
anterior cruciate and medial collateral ligaments in his left knee,
leaving Anderson without the man who was lead blocker for many of
his 1,596 yards and 12 rushing touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Christian was replaced on the active roster by tight end
Roderick Monroe (6 feet 4, 244 pounds), who was signed off the
practice squad for a prorated salary of about $18,600 for the final
two games. He'll share backup tight end duties with Ed Smith as No.
2 tight end Brian Kozlowski becomes the primary fullback.
</P>
<P>
   Christian, who leans heavily on his faith, may have taken it
better than Anderson. The 5-foot-11, 230-pounder was on crutches
Monday, his left leg in a brace, as he went on injured reserve for
the third time in his seven-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to have to hump it (in rehabilitation) to get back
for training camp,'' said Christian, who caught 19 passes for 214
yards and a touchdown and rushed eight times for 21 yards and two
touchdowns. ''This will make me stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves has repeatedly called Christian ''the best
blocker I've ever seen.'' Anderson has no argument.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has worked so hard, and has been so valuable,'' he said.
''I don't know this (offensive) system without Bobby Christian. I
have confidence in his backups, but I'm not looking forward to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have no other true fullbacks on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   The replacements
</P>
<P>
   Kozlowski (6-3, 255), who occasionally subs for Christian, will
become the primary blocking back, and Downs (6-1, 218) will take
over some of Christian's third-down responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe, who will become a backup tight end, played basketball
for three years at the University of Cincinnati, and then played
football as a walk-on, catching two passes for 33 yards and a
touchdown last year. He also had 30 knockdown blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas drafted Monroe in the seventh round and cut him in
training camp. He has shown athletic ability in practice and fine
pass-catching skills, although his route-running is suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 29, the brother of 49ers tight end Irv Smith, has no
catches in his two-year career after spending seven years in
minor-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The team will add a player to the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   Other than Christian, the Falcons emerged from Sunday's win over
the Saints fairly healthy, although weakside linebacker Cornelius
Bennett's knee sprain is serious enough that he underwent an MRI
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Exact results were not known Monday night, but vice president of
football operations Ron Hill said it was his understanding nothing
should cause Bennett to miss playing time.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year veteran had nine tackles against the Saints, and is
tied with middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle for the team lead with
105.
</P>
<P>
   ''I started wearing knee braces in '89 (when he was with
Buffalo),'' said Bennett, who missed only a few plays because of he
injury. ``There's no doubt the brace saved my knee (from further
damage).''
</P>
<P>
   Reserve cornerback Randy Fuller, who missed the past two games
with a strained shoulder, will practice Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chasing history
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (12-2) will have plenty of incentives to win Sunday
at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   A victory would set a franchise record, surpassing the team's
12-4 mark in '80, when they won the only NFC West title. It would
also clinch the division title, and tie the Falcons' mark for best
road record, giving them a 6-2 ledger to match what the '80 team
did.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has won seven straight games, and if the Falcons win
their last two games, including a Dec. 27 home game against Miami
(9-5), the nine straight wins would tie the franchise mark, set in
'80.
</P>
<P>
   Big, little numbers
</P>
<P>
   After hitting the Saints for a season-high 504 yards, the
Falcons have moved up to No. 6 in the NFL in total offense,
averaging 348.1 yards per game. The defense, meanwhile, remains
ranked No. 7, allowing an average of 291.1 yards, 211 over the past
four games. . . . Atlanta has allowed 256 points, third-fewest in
the NFL, and scored 380, fourth-most.
</P>
<P>
   Milestones
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Ray Buchanan's interception against the Saints gave
him seven. He leads the NFC, and is one short of his career high,
set in '94 with the Colts. . . . With 10 touchdown receptions this
year, wide receiver Terance Mathis has scored 43 since becoming a
Falcons in '94. That's fifth-most in the NFL behind Minnesota's
Cris Carter (57), Cincinnati's Carl Pickens (50), Detroit's Herman
Moore (45 before Monday night), and San Francisco's Jerry Rice (44
before Monday night). After scoring twice at New Orleans, Mathis is
third in team history in TDs scored, trailing wide receiver Andre
Rison (56) and running back Gerald Riggs (48). His team-record 198
receiving yards Sunday (on six catches) were the second-most in the
NFL this year, trailing a 204-yard effort (on 13 catches) by
Pickens Oct. 11 against Pittsburgh. . . Quarterback Chris Chandler
is the league's fourth-rated passer, with a rating of 96.2. His
career high was 95.1 last year, when he was No. 2 in the NFL. His
21 TD passes this season are a Falcon record. . . . . Defensive end
Lester Archambeau had Atlanta's only sack against New Orleans,
forcing a fumble by Kerry Collins. That increased Archambeau's
team-leading numbers to 10 and seven, career highs in those
categories.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Bowl picks
</P>
<P>
   Players around the league voted Monday on who they think should
make the Pro Bowl, and rosters will be announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons with the best chances of getting selected as
players' votes count one-third, coaches' votes one-third, and fans'
votes one third are Anderson (who is second in the league in
rushing), Chandler, Buchanan, Tuggle, and Mathis (61 catches, 1,085
yards).
</P>
<P>
   The next tier in what can be a political process includes
Bennett, defensive end Chuck Smith (71 tackles, 7.5 sacks, 32
quarterback pressures, nine tackles for a loss, two fumble
recoveries), Archambeau (74 tackles, four for a loss, two fumble
recoveries), and left tackle Bob Whitfield.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Shane Dronett (72 tackles, 6.5 sacks) and free
safety Eugene Robinson (81 tackles, three interceptions, two
fumbles forced, one recovered) are longshots.
</P>
<P>
   Upon review
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield committed four penalties against the Saints in a span
of a few minutes. But game film indicated that New Orleans
defensive end Joe Johnson had just one of his team-high eight
tackles and one quarterback pressure while matched up against
Whitfield.
</P>
<P>
   Time change
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game at Detroit, where the Falcons (12-2) have lost
five straight and 12 of 14, has been changed from 1 p.m. to 4:15
p.m. It will be carried on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
