A9625 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      12-14 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NEWS AND NOTES  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARYLOU LUTHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Off to Beijing &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Beene, who's shown his designs at American Embassies in
Italy, France, Belgium and Austria, is going to stage his first
fashion show in China, on March 26 at the China International
Clothing and Accessories Fair in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new adventure, a new continent, a way to further the
cause of American design,'' Beene said.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Fuller, an international apparel-industry consultant who
is working with the Chinese government to prepare the event, says
about 100,000 people are expected to attend the four-day fair,
which will end with the Beene show.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime advocate of American design that is free of European
influences, Beene, 71, will show such highlights from his career as
his sequined football-jersey dress of 1967, his sweatshirt-fabric
and denim evening dresses of 1970, his ``Little King'' sequined
comic strip evening dress of 1971, his ``ballgown of the 21st
century'' (a black silk crepe jumpsuit) of 1989, and his spiraling
zipper dresses for spring 1999.
</P>
<P>
   (The zipper dresses, which will be featured in six windows at
Saks Fifth Avenue in February, are technological breakthroughs
achieved in the Beene workrooms. As the designer explained, ``No
one makes curving zippers, so we created our own.'')
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Karan's Youngest Line &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan, a baby boomer in good standing (she turned 50 in
October), has a new baby. The designer said she gave birth, so to
speak, to a new infants and toddlers line because ``everyone around
me is having babies.'' The clothes, which will be in stores in
January, will reflect what the designer calls ``the esthetics of
the parents _ nothing fussy, nothing cutesy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the line is not meant to be a downsized version of DKNY
clothes, the look is definitely urban, featuring sweatshirt
dresses, jumpsuits emblazoned with the Statue of Liberty, hooded
nylon athletic jackets, drawstring pants and shorts, jeans and jean
jackets, oxford-cloth diaper covers and T-shirt dresses. The most
expensive item is a washable silk dress at $60.
</P>
<P>
   The line, which will carry a ``dkny'' logo, all lowercase, is a
division of Ms. Karan's DKNY Kids collection. A spokeswoman said
the most popular items with the stores where the clothes will be
sold _ Bloomingdale's, Lord &AMP; Taylor, Macy's West, Neiman Marcus
and Saks Fifth Avenue _ are two $40 designs, one a heart-print
jumper and the other a dotted peasant dress.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Karan says her muses are her four stepgrandchildren,
MacKenzie, Miles, Etan and Maya.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Workroom to Showroom &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Pattern makers make patterns, of course, creating a blueprint
from a designer's sketch. Few step out of the sample room into the
showroom. But one who has is Ling-Shan Li, who says she has always
had the soul of a designer. ``That's what I studied at F.I.T., and
now I think I'm ready,'' said Ms. Li, who was born in Taiwan. So do
the buyers at Linda Dresner and Takashimaya, who have bought Ms.
Li's first collection, for delivery next spring.
</P>
<P>
   With Fang-Ching Li, her sister who is also a pattern maker (yes,
there's a pattern here), the designer has formed her own business,
with a showroom at 137 Fifth Avenue. Her first designs, priced from
about $225 to $500, demonstrate her skills at cutting and draping
and underscore her aesthetic connection to Rei Kawakubo of Comme
des Garcons and Yohji Yamamoto, designers she said she admires
greatly.
</P>
<P>
   One jacket is cut so that the lapels end with the selvage of the
fabric. Dresses, many with one seam, are often cut on the bias with
a loose, sometimes twisting fit rather than the curve-tracing lines
normally associated with cross-grain cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Francis Roth, a designer who once hired Ling-Shan Li,
called her ``serious, professional, and she has this amazing
calming effect.'' So do her coolly serene clothes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
