<SLUG> BC-BY-DESIGN-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMOND DAYS ARE HERE AGAIN  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe it's the time of year. Maybe it's the time of
the century. Whatever the reason, stores report that diamond
jewelry is selling, from a few tiny stones on a chain to elaborate
necklaces. So the entry of Robert Lee Morris into the fine jewelry
field seems to be well timed.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who is known for hand-wrought, sculptural jewelry of
silver or gold-toned metal, recently introduced a collection of
18-karat-gold and platinum pieces with diamonds and pearls. He has
used many of his signature motifs of crosses, links and toggle
closings in an extensive collection of earrings, necklaces and
cuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $700 for a tiny diamond cross on a chain to
$250,000 for a reversible bib with 17.5 carats of diamonds on one
side and 35 Biwa pearls on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Saks Fifth Avenue has some pieces. The entire collection is at
the Robert Lee Morris store, 400 West Broadway, near Spring Street.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9627 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-QUOTAS-COX     12-14 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-QUOTAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tobacco farmers expecting low quota for '99 crops
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWN SUMMIT, N.C. _ Luke Lambeth, a 35-year-old farmer, had
once hoped that his young children would have the opportunity to
grow tobacco, just as their ancestors had done since the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   But today, thousands of tobacco growers across the South will
learn how severely the golden leaf's declining fortunes will
threaten their livelihoods. The U.S. Department of Agriculture has
until midnight to announce how much flue-cured tobacco farmers can
grow next year.
</P>
<P>
   Farm leaders predict the government could slash flue-cured
allotments by as much as a third. The quota cut for 1999 would be
on top of a 17 percent reduction in the quota on this year's crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some farmers out there are going to go broke as it is now,''
said Lambeth, who barely broke even this fall on the 140 acres of
tobacco that he harvested in the North Carolina Piedmont. ``A man
with a big debt load cannot survive with a 40 percent cut in
income.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco allotments, or quotas, much like real estate, can be
bought, sold or leased. In many rural communities, income from
leased quotas, coupled with Social Security, often pays for
farmers' retirement. Last month's national settlement between major
cigarette producers and 46 states promises to speed the downward
spiral of America's tobacco industry. After signing the deal,
manufacturers hiked cigarette prices by 45 cents a pack to pay for
the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The industry agreed to pay $206 billion over 25 years in
exchange for the states, including Georgia, dropping lawsuits
seeking reimbursement for the costs of treating sick smokers.
</P>
<P>
   The historic settlement requires that the tobacco manufacturers
discuss a separate settlement with farmers. Growers fear that
higher cigarette prices will reduce smoking and thus cut demand for
their crop. Farmers immediately rejected as too cheap a tentative
plan that would reimburse farmers as much as $5.1 billion in lost
profits over 10 years. The No. 2 manufacturer, R.J. Reynolds,
quickly withdrew from that plan, saying rather than bail out
farmers, it would buy enough of their tobacco to keep them
profitable. Luke Lambeth's father, Phil, 71, had accumulated quotas
on about 140 acres. But reductions by the federal program have cut
the acreage by half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent my life savings, and now they are taking it away 20
percent at a time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a government-sponsored referendum a year ago, the elder
Lambeth was among more than 97 percent of flue-cured tobacco
growers who said they favored retaining the quota program.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Phil Lambeth said, ``I am not sure I would vote for it
anymore. If they keep the quota system in, it may drive us out of
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as tobacco quotas have guaranteed growers a minimum price
for their flue-cured leaf, some farmers are advocating what just a
few years ago seemed unthinkable. They think Congress should phase
out the Depression-era program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an archaic system,'' said Rick Apple, 41, a
fourth-generation grower in Brown Summit who depends on tobacco for
half of his farm income. ``Looking in my crystal ball, I'm guessing
that the existing program cannot last for more than two to five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH'S GOLDEN LEAF
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco remains a major cash crop in the South. Here are the
1998 sales figures for flue-cured tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   N. Carolina $1.03 billion
</P>
<P>
   Georgia 174.5 million
</P>
<P>
   S. Carolina 171.1 million
</P>
<P>
   Virginia 164.7 million
</P>
<P>
   Florida 32.8 million
</P>
<P>
   Source: U.S. Department of Agriculture
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
