<HEADER>
A9631 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LAME-DUCKS-60     12-14 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LAME-DUCKS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME LAME DUCKS, THE FINAL VOTE IS THE GRAVEST
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-POLL, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-DEMS,
IMPEACH-MAIL, IMPEACH-RODINO) 
(nk) 
By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The lame-duck pens, as they are rudely known by
some, will be situated in spare office space in the Rayburn House
Office Building, where the 40 members who are not returning to
Congress next year will find temporary desk space on Thursday for
the final and most fateful vote of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mike Pappas, R-N.J., rebuffed by the voters last month and
physically evicted from his House office suite 10 days ago, has no
need of the Rayburn space. He has a House colleague who will let
him hang his hat as he goes to the floor for the last time, to vote
on impeaching President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very somber time,'' said Pappas, who will be closing out
what, in baseball terminology, is a cup-of-coffee career, finished
at the minimal two years of service. He has cast 1,178 votes so
far, but none with such thumbs-up or thumbs-down gravity as that
attending the 105th Congress' grim curtain call.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot look away; we cannot pretend it hasn't happened,''
Pappas said. He spoke from his forced political retirement in New
Jersey's 12th Congressional District and kept his last vote to
himself before heading here for his closing day as a House member.
Pappas talked guardedly, but the sadness of some other lame ducks
is evident as they return for this final bout of debating and
voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought it would come to this,'' said Vic Fazio,
D-Calif., who chose to retire after an eventful 20-year career
that, he emphasizes, he will cherish forever. ``This vote is not
something that elevates your service here,'' he said quietly.
``It's such a frustrating and wasteful issue, indicating how
polarized the country has become, maybe going back to Watergate.''
</P>
<P>
   Fazio said he tried to spend this year in a kind of electoral
withdrawal of happily savoring the honor of public service. But his
parting mood is devoid of celebration. ``We're at such total
loggerheads,'' he rued of the two sides in the impeachment issue.
</P>
<P>
   Others are angry as much as sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really resent having to end my career on this vote,'' Louis
Stokes, D-Ohio, who is retiring after 30 years in Congress. ``It's
not pleasant. This will precipitate a crisis in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My constituents have never been so irate,'' Stokes said as he
prepared to fly back here from Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the impeachment decision, the lame ducks will
gather with their respective party caucuses in momentous farewell
this week. At his final House Republican conference meeting, Pappas
will join in the full emotional flow of the event among his
returning colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas was defeated in November by Rush Holt, a Democrat and
physicist who has never held elective office. Pappas traced his
defeat to a gaffe he committed on the floor of the House, when he
whimsically sung out in praise of Kenneth Starr's impeachment
inquiry into Clinton's sex-and-mendacity scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twinkle, twinkle, Kenneth Starr, now we see how brave you
are,'' Pappas sang last July, and Democrats soon were accusing him
of partisanly trivializing grave events.
</P>
<P>
   July was an eon ago in the political life of the Clinton
scandal, and Pappas claims no comfort in the initial estimates in
this tumultuous week that the president could very well be
impeached by a narrow vote. The situation here is fluid, indeed
sloshing with torrents of vox pop that Pappas and the 39 others who
are leaving cannot adequately sample with their offices closed and
their old phones on taped farewells.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm still accessible,'' he insisted almost achingly. ``I'm
still hearing from the people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   By his own word, Pappas loved his two years here as much as
Fazio loved his 20 or Stokes his 30. Nothing, not even the
impeachment vote, can spoil the honor and memory of it, Pappas
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is a wonderful thing in that we each have our hills and
valleys,'' declared Pappas, a study in humility as he prepares to
vote this last time as a congressman. He retires with the comfort
of a 100 percent attendance record and an obvious belief that human
resilience is at the heart of all politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm keeping my office open,'' said the single-termer,
referring to the ``Pappas for Congress'' storefront in central New
Jersey, and clearly tempted to start running all over again right
now for the chance to come back here after the impeachment vote is
history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
