<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS' BIG CONTRIBUTOR GETS 5 YEARS' PROBATION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (jw) 
 By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Johnny Chung, a prolific donor to Democrats and
frequent visitor to the Clinton White House, was sentenced to
probation and community service Monday for his involvement in
illegal campaign contributions during the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   At the sentencing, U.S. District Judge Manuel Real expressed
doubt over Democratic Party officials' assertions that they did not
know about fund-raising abuses, and said he was ``surprised'' that
Attorney General Janet Reno did not appoint a special prosecutor to
look into them, ``as much as that term has become something of a
pariah.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge, appointed to the bench by President Lyndon Johnson,
said he had reviewed transcripts of Chung's testimony before a
grand jury investigating those accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has said that in making her decision she based it on the
facts and the law and had not found sufficient grounds for
appointing an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Donald Fowler, the former chairman of the
Democratic National Committee, and Richard Sullivan, the
committee's former finance director, the judge added, ``If Fowler
and Sullivan didn't know what was going on, I think they are the
dumbest politicians I've ever seen.'' Rick Hess, a spokesman for
the committee, declined to respond to Real's comments.
</P>
<P>
   Chung, 43, who faced up to 18 months in prison, was granted
leniency following a recommendation by prosecutors and pleas from
his lawyer on the basis of his cooperation with an investigation
into campaign fund-raising abuses during the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   Chung was sentenced to five years' probation and 3,000 hours of
community service. He pleaded guilty to bank fraud, tax evasion and
conspiracy charges, and admitted circumventing individual limits on
donations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2141EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
