<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9639 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      12-14 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE CRITICIZES GOP LEADERS FOR REFUSING CENSURE VOTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
and NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With an impeachment vote looming in the House,
President Clinton's support among Republican moderates softened
Monday as the White House criticized GOP leaders for refusing to
allow a vote to censure the president and avoid trial in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, during a meeting in the Gaza Strip with Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat, warned that the process aimed at removing
him from office was not in the public interest and offered to
consider ``any reasonable compromise'' with Congress to end the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, polls released Monday indicated that although a
majority of Americans believe Clinton lied under oath, they do not
want him impeached. At the same time, a majority says that, if the
House votes to impeach him late this week, the president should
resign rather than face a Senate trial over his effort to cover up
his affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The full House is to meet Thursday to begin debating impeachment
of the president, deliberations that have not occurred in 130
years. Four articles of impeachment accusing Clinton of perjury,
obstruction of justice and abuse of power were approved in
party-line votes by the House Judiciary Committee, which built its
case against the president mostly on evidence developed by
independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Before formally ending its inquiry Saturday, the
Republican-controlled committee rejected efforts by Democrats to
send the full House a resolution rebuking the president. That
resolution of censure, an alternative to impeachment, has been
embraced by the president and several Republican moderates who are
being wooed by the White House in an effort to end the impeachment
process.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., signaled that he was
backing away from his anti-impeachment stand announced more than a
week ago. He asked for and was granted a meeting with Clinton when
he returns from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to vote today, I would vote against impeachment, but
I am troubled by the president's statements and his continued
inability to tell the American people the truth,'' Shays said.
</P>
<P>
   Also boding ill for Clinton's chance of fending off impeachment
in the House were announcements by Reps. Frank LoBiondo of New
Jersey and Jim Walsh of New York, both of whom were on the White
House list of potential impeachment opponents, that they would
instead vote to send the president's case to the Senate for trial.
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans holding 228 of the 435 House seats, Clinton's
ability to avoid a Senate trial would require winning all 206
Democratic votes, the lone independent and at least a dozen
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   So far, five moderate Republicans, including Shays, have said
they would support the president. At the same time, three Democrats
have said they will vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, including House Majority Leader Dick Armey
of Texas, Whip Tom DeLay of Texas and Judiciary Committee Chairman
Henry Hyde of Illinois, called for Clinton's resignation Sunday.
The three leaders have been urging GOP members to vote against an
anticipated procedural move by Democrats to raise censure as an
alternative to impeachment during Thursday's debate.
</P>
<P>
   In Gaza during a press conference with Arafat, Clinton said it
is not ``in the interest of the United States or the American
people to go through this impeachment process with a trial in the
Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   The president added that he has ``offered to make every effort
to make any reasonable compromise with the Congress. I still
believe that and I'm still willing to do that. That's all I know to
do. Meanwhile, I'm going to keep working at my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it was appropriate for Republicans to call for his
resignation while he was overseas, Clinton said: ``The boundaries
of what's appropriate have been changed rather dramatically over
the past few months. They'll have to be the judge of their own
conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Vice President Al Gore said Republicans were
defying ``the wisdom of the American people'' in refusing to
consider censure. Regarding calls by Armey, DeLay and Hyde for
Clinton to resign, Gore said: ``That's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart was sharper in his criticism
of Republican leaders who, he said, have rewritten the book on
partisanship. They are blocking a censure vote, he said, because
they know it has a strong chance of passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a small group of the Republican leadership who have
made it their mission in life to remove the president against
perhaps the will of the House but certainly against the will of the
American public,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   A survey over the weekend by the Pew Research Center found
two-thirds of American adults oppose impeaching Clinton or removing
him from office. A CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll released Monday
indicates that six in 10 Americans oppose impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   An ABC News/Washington Post poll found a similar number of
Americans opposed to impeachment, but found an almost equal number,
58 percent, saying that if he is impeached by the House, Clinton
should resign rather than fight for his job in a Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   While half of the adults surveyed by Pew said they are not happy
with his handling of the investigation into his affair with
Lewinsky, 61 percent approve of the job he is doing as president, a
number that has remained fairly constant since January. Sixty
percent of those in the Pew survey disapproved of the way
Republicans have handled impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton allies have intensified efforts to encourage
voters to contact their congressional representatives to oppose
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson said he will hold a ``prayer vigil''
outside the Capitol on Thursday as lawmakers inside debate the
impeachment articles.
</P>
<P>
   People for the American Way began airing radio advertisements
providing a toll-free telephone line that will route them to their
lawmakers' office. Before the ads began airing, the phone-in
campaign produced more than 130,000 calls against impeachment, the
liberal civil liberties group said.
</P>
<P>
   Phone lines to Capitol offices rang off the hook Monday with
calls on the issue. Calls to the main Capitol switchboard doubled
from their usual volume, a House spokesman said, and calls to many
member offices produced recordings that all circuits were busy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
