<HEADER>
A9641 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUEBEC-ENGLISH-ART-NY     12-14 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEBEC-ENGLISH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBRARY ONE OF THE LAST BASTIONS OF ENGLISH-SPEAKING QUEBEC 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(rl) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUEBEC _ On dark days when the river broods and mists hang heavy
on outlying hills, it is easy to think of Quebec as it once was, a
distant outpost of the British Empire where hardy people dreamed of
doing great things that would not soon be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what they did has withstood the tides of time, because
for the last 174 years, the Literary and Historical Society of
Quebec has dedicated itself to preserving the memories and
achievements of the early settlers of one of North America's oldest
cities.
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, it is the society itself that is most in
need of preservation.
</P>
<P>
   English-speaking people have been in the minority here since the
British conquered the French in 1759. But they thrived until about
30 years ago, when the first stirrings of the independence movement
in Quebec Province made them start to feel unwelcome.
</P>
<P>
   Now, fewer than 2 percent of the 167,000 inhabitants of the city
of Quebec consider themselves native English speakers. A great
number of the rest regard institutions like the society, one of
North America's oldest, as uncomfortable reminders of Quebec's
colonial past.
</P>
<P>
   That the society's library is seen as a vestige of British power
is one reason that something as seemingly innocent as a literary
fund-raiser recently became a cause celebre.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the Lit &AMP; His, as its devotees know it,
was a learned society. In the days long before commercial
publishing companies and research organizations, the society
undertook scholarly and scientific investigations. But it hasn't
published anything for more than 70 years; its primary focus now is
its 35,000-volume library, housed in an old prison building on St.
Stanislas Street in what is left of the English Quarter of Quebec.
The books are overwhelmingly in English.
</P>
<P>
   Membership in the private library has dropped to about 300,
while the cost of maintaining the old books, and occasionally
buying new ones, has grown burdensome. A nearly century-old
investment fund generates some support but not nearly enough.
</P>
<P>
   So in October, library directors invited the Montreal novelist
Mordecai Richler to read from his latest work. It would be a
literary event, and, it was hoped, raise some badly needed money.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Quebec officially supports the library, providing
space and a grant of $1,500 a year. But when Mayor Jean-Paul
L'Allier heard about Richler's visit, he called the invitation
``clumsy'' because of the author's curmudgeonly opposition to
Quebec's independence movement.
</P>
<P>
   Richler, who alternates between London and Montreal, said he
agreed to take part because he had heard about the library's
plight, not because he thought Canada should stick together. But
what he found at the library that night surprised him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got there I asked the organizers if they had publicized
much, and they told me no,'' Richler said, still taken aback by how
small the crowd had been, just a few dozen. ``They said they didn't
want to attract too many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Walk over the creaking wooden floors and through the narrow
aisles between towering bookcases and it becomes clear that the Lit
&AMP; His library is not a place that brooks much folderol. Most of the
books on the gracious first floor are old. Those up on the
mezzanine are really old.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's 19th century or older we just don't let it
circulate,'' said Sylviane Dubois, librarian for the last 12 years.
Books from the 1920s and 1930s are common, and they do circulate,
at least in theory. One chosen at random, ``A Thousand Lines,'' by
Martin Farquhar Tupper, was last checked out on March 12, 1940.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest books are kept in a glass case, locked with a
skeleton key. Before she opens it Ms. Dubois rushes back to her
desk for a pair of white gloves. ``You need it to protect the books
and to protect yourself,'' she said. The oldest books, dating to
the 17th century, sometimes carry irritating mold.
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult to trace the slow ebbing of time in a
place like this. There's not a computer terminal, Internet screen
or copy machine anywhere in sight. The old card catalog still does
just fine.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get the idea that the library is totally resistant to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not opposed to progress right across the board,''
insisted Tomas Feininger, a geologist who is president of the
society. He conceded that there are some things computers are
pretty good at, like indexing, and said the library was thinking of
using one to organize the material in the Canadiana collection.
</P>
<P>
   Egad, a computer! ``But of course it won't ever be in this
room,'' Feininger said, snugly seated in the main reading room.
``It would hidden off somewhere in a corner, where it belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently the Lit &AMP; His undertook a rare renovation, moving the
main doors back some 20 feet to make room for the rapidly expanding
large type books that have become popular as the society's
membership ages.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is not a place just for codgers. Michael Bath, 42,
showed up one afternoon with his 5-year-old daughter, Emilie. Bath,
a transplanted Ontarian who fell in love with Quebec and married a
Quebecois, stops by every month for an armload of books.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I moved to Quebec it took me about a year to find out
about the library from other Anglophones,'' he said. ``It's a
wonderful place to come and feel history.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting the society's $38,000 annual budget requires all sorts
of inventiveness. At the beginning of the year, the library
auctions off magazine subscriptions. The high bidder gets to take
all the old issues when new ones come in.
</P>
<P>
   On her desk, Ms. Dubois always keeps a stack of old books that
need repair. (``They're not difficult to find here,'' she said.)
Every once in a while, a retired bookbinder, Jacques Roy, quietly
peeks in. He takes what's there, and if he likes the books he reads
them, repairs them and brings them back.
</P>
<P>
   The Lit &AMP; His will celebrate its 175th anniversary in 1999. In
all that time, Quebec has seen many changes. But a small group of
English speakers and their French-speaking friends in this
beautiful walled city on the St. Lawrence River can count on some
things never to change. And that in itself represents a small
victory over that old enemy, time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving into a virtual age where wood is being replaced
by melamine, letters are being replaced by electrons, and so on,''
Feininger said. ``This place is becoming more and more unique
because it's reality, so to speak. And an awful lot of people
appreciate that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
