<SLUG> BC-ENVIRON-NUCLEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY DEPARTMENT MOVES TO SETTLE COMPLAINTS OVER WEAPONS CLEANUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Energy Department Monday promised to establish
a $6.25 million fund for environmental groups, community
organizations and Indian tribes to spend on technical and
scientific analyses of the department's cleanup work at nuclear
weapons manufacturing sites, and to create a huge Internet database
about the sites' radioactive and chemical contamination.
</P>
<P>
   The department took the unusual actions to avoid being found in
contempt of court in a 1989 lawsuit by environmentalists over how
the weapons complex cleanup would be handled.
</P>
<P>
   The department settled the suit in 1990 by promising to perform
a ``programmatic environmental impact statement'' that would weigh
every alternative at all sites in the cleanup program. The program
is expected to take decades and cost hundreds of billions of
dollars. In 1995, the department canceled the analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Anne Sullivan, the department's general counsel, said
Monday that the new settlement, which includes providing research
money to groups that have opposed the department for more than a
decade, would help accomplish the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think if people are better informed about our work, they're
more likely to agree with us,'' she said in a telephone briefing
with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   And, said Ms. Sullivan, one of the major users of a unified,
well-organized database would be the Energy Department itself,
which sometimes has trouble keeping track of what it knows about
its sprawling complex of weapons production and energy research
sites, many of them now shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   She said the department's effort to study all the sites
together, which it abandoned in 1995, was not useful because each
site was different.
</P>
<P>
   Another department official, James Werner, director of the
office of strategic planning and analysis, said he thought the new
settlement ``will have a clear impact on helping improve waste
management, just understanding the data.''
</P>
<P>
   Werner himself illustrates how the Energy Department has changed
from the days when nuclear weapons were still widely produced and
the department, and its predecessor, the Atomic Energy Commission,
kept everything secret. When the first agreement was made, Werner
was an environmental engineer with the Natural Resources Defense
Council, one of the plaintiffs in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of some of the 38 environmental and other
nonprofit groups that sued the Energy Department said this was the
first time they knew of that the department had agreed to pay for
such outside research.
</P>
<P>
   They also said they believed the agreement Monday was better
than the 1990 settlement, because the environmental impact
statements the department was producing under the original deal
were late and low-quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They merely go through the motions, they don't do the
comprehensive, thorough analysis of the alternatives,'' said Robert
Schaeffer, director of the Alliance for Nuclear Accountability, an
umbrella group representing several plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department has declassified millions of pages of
files in the last few years. The new database will not include any
classified or secret information.
</P>
</TEXT>
