<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-Q-AND-A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q and A: Tobacco will fight ban `like the devil,' counsel says
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pinetops, N.C. lawyer Phil Carlton has represented Big Tobacco
in two rounds of negotiations over a national tobacco settlement. A
$368.5 billion deal died in Congress last summer, after the tobacco
industry fought legislation that would have increased industry
payments to $516 billion over 25 years. Last month, 46 states,
including Georgia, agreed to a $206 billion settlement that imposes
fewer marketing restrictions on cigarette makers. Carlton, 61, a
former North Carolina Supreme Court justice, talked about tobacco's
future .
</P>
<P>
   Q: The White House and health advocates have urged Congress to
enact tobacco control legislation next year that goes beyond the
recent $206 billion settlement. How would the tobacco industry view
broader legislation?
</P>
<P>
   A: With all those people who want to put the companies out of
business stirring, you have to assume there may be some activity. I
am sure (health advocates) will ask for the authority to ban the
product, and we will fight that like the devil. I think the
national settlement agreement with the states has taken a lot of
steam out of it. You can't take billboards down but once, and we've
already agreed to take them down.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some months ago, former U.S. Surgeon General C. Everett Koop
used the word ``bluffing'' in reference to the industry and its
threat to back out of the proposed $368 billion settlement. But the
industry wasn't bluffing. Did the health advocates simply blow
their best shot by pressing for more than the $368 billion?
</P>
<P>
   A: Absolutely. It is just that simple. If you think about where
we would be today if the $368 billion and everything in that June
20, 1997, agreement had been enacted, just think how peaceful life
would have been for the past year. They would have had everything
they ever dreamed of having. As it is, we are still fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A major goal of the White House and health advocates was to
curb youth smoking. When cigarette billboards come down and other
requirements of the recent settlement are in place, do you expect
youth smoking to go down?
</P>
<P>
   A: I never have thought that advertising had a lot to do with
it. I think the more adult you make the product, the more
intriguing it becomes to young people. I do believe that a
combination of . . . price increases, advertising restrictions and
so forth may help some, but I obviously don't think it will help as
much as they do. Actually, I don't think they do, either. I still
think what they want is prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
