<SLUG> BC-MARKETPLACE-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GOLDMAN, A 4TH QUARTER TO FORGET
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The old snapshots of Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
tell the story. In his days as rising star and then chairman of
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., Rubin was usually pictured cheek-by-jowl with
traders on the crowded bond floor, in shirt sleeves, a phone to his
ear. The private partnership he helped build has long had a
seat-of-the-pants management style that makes some Wall Street
competitors seem timid.
</P>
<P>
   These days, though, timidity might sound tempting to the
partners at Goldman. The firm said Monday that its pretax profit
fell 81 percent to $107 million in the fourth quarter _ the worst
such period it has had since 1994 _ and attributed the weak results
exclusively to trading losses. Earnings were down from $567 million
in the fourth quarter of last year, and off 86 percent from the
$754 million it posted in this year's third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's results showed how the firm's aggressive emphasis on
trading _ both for its customers and for its own account _ can
cause steep losses in down markets as surely as it can magnify
profits in good ones. That makes Goldman's earnings more volatile
than those of some competitors and seems likely to further postpone
the day that it becomes a public company.
</P>
<P>
   The miserable final period derailed the stellar earnings
momentum Goldman had built up in its first half, when it earned
more than $1 billion each quarter and prepared to sell shares in
the firm for the first time in its 130-year history. For the year,
Goldman earned $2.92 billion, down from $3.01 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Changes already are underway. Its co-chairmen and chief
executives, Jon S. Corzine and Henry M. Paulson Jr., said they had
reduced the firm's risk profile and renewed their emphasis on
expanding investment banking and money-management businesses, which
remained highly profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We freely admit that we have a strategy to shift our earnings
mix more towards banking and asset management,'' Paulson said. For
that reason, he said, Goldman raised its budget for recruiting new
investment bankers by 9 percent this year, when some rivals are
cutting back. Goldman has also recently poached some mergers and
acquisition stars from Morgan Stanley, Dean Witter and Citigroup's
Salomon Smith Barney unit.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Goldman's trading losses came in September and October,
when stocks and especially bonds took a beating worldwide. Markets
have stabilized since then, but Goldman says it is taking no
chances on a repeat of a trading period that Corzine called the
worst he had seen.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, who like Rubin worked his way to the executive suite
from the bond-trading floor, said that Goldman had greatly shrunk
the size of its balance sheet, or its assets and liabilities. In
effect, that means it is using much less borrowed money to trade
securities. Most of that cut _ Corzine said it came to a third to a
half of the firm's pre-September balance sheet _ took place in
October and November, when the firm sold trading positions at a
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are battening down the hatches for another storm,'' Hal
Schroeder, an analyst at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods, said. ``They are
taking some losses, but they see it as a long-term preservation
move.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Trading losses have not been unusual on Wall Street recently.
Merrill Lynch, Bankers Trust and Salomon Smith Barney posted
hundreds of millions of dollars in such losses in the third
quarter, which ended a month later than Goldman's third quarter.
The sharp downturn in bond markets around the world and sharp
recessions in emerging markets were the main culprits.
</P>
<P>
   But Goldman is more trading-oriented than any of those firms.
The investment bank earned nearly half its profits in the first
half of the year from trading on behalf of customers and with its
own capital, a much higher share than either Merrill or Morgan
Stanley, its top peers.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman powered ahead of its rivals this year in the two areas
that are the most profitable for investment banks: advising
companies on mergers and acquisitions and underwriting initial
public offerings. Even so, the downturn in bonds in the fall
dragged down its overall results.
</P>
<P>
   The firm lost heavily in making what it called relative value
trades, which try to exploit what are seen as temporary price
disparities between two similar stocks or bonds. It also lost money
trading bonds in the United States, Paulson said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, its trading profile was in some ways similar to that of
Long-Term Capital Management, the hedge fund that Goldman and 13
other banks and brokerage houses rescued from bankruptcy in
September. Goldman itself was hit by the shock-induced flight from
risky securities that undercut the value of virtually all bonds
except U.S. Treasuries. And it was hurt all the more because so
many hedge funds and securities firms pursued similar trading
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our risk model did not take into account enough the copy-cat
problem,'' Paulson said. ``Everyone has similar positions and in a
liquidity crisis is forced to reduce at the same times.''
</P>
<P>
   The earnings instability is most likely to push back the day
Goldman revives its plans for a public offering. November was a
profitable month, and December looks good so far, Corzine said. But
he did not rule out the possibility that future shocks, from an
impeachment of President Clinton or fresh instability in Russia,
for example, could send markets down sharply again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the greatest base on which to do an offering,'' he
said. ``So I expect it will be some time to run before we seriously
consider it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
