<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Tuesday, Dec. 15. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Undated) Bill Clinton is abortion. Bill Clinton is
capital punishment. Bill Clinton is opera, the designated hitter,
Affirmative Action. Bill Clinton is one of those subjects about
which you made up your mind a long time ago. And there's no
changing it. E.J. MONTINI Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K''
categories.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN (Undated) _ ``Where have you gone, Albert
Belle?/A nation turns its lonely eyes to you.'' I don't think so.
Somehow I doubt we'll ever hear Beck or Sheryl Crow immortalize any
of today's baseball players in a pop song the way Paul Simon did
Joe DiMaggio in Mrs. Robinson. Why would they? What baseball player
today _ what athlete in any sport _ transcends his game so much
that a succeeding generation would bemoan his loss, and beckon to
him for lost innocence and hope? None, by my count. My generation
has no one who comes close. And we are poorer for it. By BILL
GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GOLDMAN (Phoenix) Fred Goldman, whose son was brutally murdered
along with O.J. Simpson's wife, Nicole, has been hired by the
Arizona Attorney General's Office to work on victim's rights
issues. Goldman moved to Arizona earlier this year. By MIKE MCCLOY.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BISKIND (Phoenix) A doctor too busy eating his lunch to check on a
patient who was bleeding heavily. Staff so inexperienced that they
didn't know where the pens were. An administrator who asked for
medical help 20 minutes away rather than from the hospital across
the street.
</P>
<P>
   A Phoenix police investigation report, exclusively obtained by
The Arizona Republic, painted a picture of medical chaos on the day
33-year-old Lou Anne Herron died after going to the A-Z Women's
Clinic for an abortion. The Republic also obtained copies of a
police investigation into a 37-week-old baby who was nearly aborted
at the clinic two months after Herron's death. By JODIE SNYDER and
SUSIE STECKNER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
W/ MMM (Phoenix) 15-18'' _ A scalpel slips. A diagnosis misses the
mark. A doctor makes a fatal error. When is a doctor's mistake
malpractice and when does it become a crime? The distinction
between malpractice and manslaughter can be as thin as the cutting
edge of a surgeon's scalpel, legal analysts say. By JODIE SNYDER.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
