<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-COX     12-14 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jasper murder trial may leave Jasper
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas - A white man accused of dragging a black man to
death had only one friend show up in court Monday ``after a bunch
of people'' decided to stay away to testify that this East Texas
town can't give him a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Joe Bob Golden said he would rule today on
whether to move John William ``Bill'' King's Jan. 25 murder trial
to another city. He also may rule on whether to allow television
cameras in the courtroom and public access to evidence.
</P>
<P>
   King, wearing a white prison T-shirt that exposed his elaborate
tattoos that authorities say depict white supremacy symbols, sat
stone-faced at the defense table. Just 10 feet away, the father and
sisters of murder victim James Byrd Jr. watched the court hearing
from a front-row seat. King never looked their way.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd was dragged behind a pickup until he was dismembered in the
early hours of June 7. King and two other white men are accused of
killing Byrd because he was black.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors presented five Jasper County witnesses who said the
worldwide media coverage of the murder would not prevent a fair and
impartial trial here.
</P>
<P>
   But King's lawyer found only one King family friend to testify
against a hometown trial along with a Jasper lawyer who testified
only because he was under subpoena. The judge even called a short
recess to allow King's lawyer to telephone people who had pledged
to testify for a change of venue, but who did not appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a bunch of people who for some reason felt
uncomfortable in coming,'' C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs, Jr. of
Beaumont, the court-appointed attorney for King, said during a
break. ``We had a hard time getting people, I'll be honest with
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper homemaker Nelda Woods, a longtime friend of King's
family, said, ``There's too many people here already, judging from
what I've heard.''
</P>
<P>
   As she left the witness stand, King flashed her a soft smile and
then resumed his day-long position of resting his elbows on the
defense table and holding his clenched hands to his chin.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray presented news
stories from the Austin American-Statesman, the Houston Chronicle
and the Dallas Morning News to support his contention that readers
across the state were told more details of the crime than local
residents.
</P>
<P>
   He said the papers had written more extensively than local
papers about King's tattoos and allegations of blood on his shoes.
Local residents have heard less provocative information than
big-city residents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not entitled to change of venue because of publicity,''
James said during a break. ``It has to be inflammatory publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and Cribbs agreed the jury should be sequestered
during King's trial, but the judge has not yet ruled.
</P>
<P>
   King, 24, is accused of being the ringleader of the gruesome
attack on Byrd. His cigarette lighter _ inscribed with his
nickname, ``Possum,'' and a triangle formed by the letters KKK _
was found on the road where Byrd was killed.
</P>
<P>
   King claims he is innocent. Last month, he released a letter
through his father in which he blames Byrd's death on Shawn Berry,
one of his co-defendants who owned the pickup used to drag Byrd.
King said he was at home when Byrd was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Berry and Lawrence Russell Brewer have also been charged with
capital murder, but their trials have not been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   During Monday's hearing, King's disabled father sat in a
wheelchair with a portable oxygen tank to help him breath. His
severe osteoporosis and respiratory problems would prevent him from
attending an out-of-town trial for his son, but he supports a
change of venue. ``I want things to be as good on my boy as
possible,'' he said, adding that he loves his son and wants to
believe he did not kill Byrd. ``It's been hell on me,'' he said.
``I've cried and carried on.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder King, a retired lumber worker, lives in Jasper, just
four blocks from the Byrd family, although he never has met them.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the case is over and done with and settled with, I'd
like to be able to sit down and talk with them,'' he said. ``It's
impossible now.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Gamino writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
