<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- NY-VACCO-CONCEDE --, 12-14
-- Attorney General-elect Eliot Spitzer announces his victory on
Monday in his law offices. After battling the inevitable for six
weeks, State Attorney General Dennis Vacco conceded to Spitzer, his
Democratic opponent, declining to say why he had stubbornly fought
the results of last month's election but pledging to cooperate
fully in the transition. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- IMPEACH-2, 12-14 --
Attorney General Janet Reno speaks before Vice President Al Gore at
an event announcing grants for community policing in the Roosevelt
Room of the White House. With the White House increasingly
pessimistic about President Clinton's ability to win the
impeachment vote in the House, Gore denounced House Republican
leaders for refusing to allow a vote to censure the president and
accusing them of ignoring the ``wisdom of the American people.''
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WEST ORANGE, N.J. -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- IMPEACH-RODINO-2,
12-14 -- Peter Rodino, former chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee during Watergate during an interview in his home. Rodino
warned that impeaching Clinton for perjury would cheapen the
Constitution and weaken the presidency. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- BAGELS, 12-14 -- Helmer
Toro, owner of H&AMP;H Bagels on New York's Upper West Side, stands
near his product as workers fill the bins. Since Jerry Seinfeld
began using the H&AMP;H store, or rather a stage-set version of it, as
a regular sit-com site, its reputation as a New York institution
has reached into far corners of the country. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1998 --US-DEPORTATIONS, 12-14 --
Maria Judith Valencia sits alone in the apartment she used to share
with her son Fernando Giraldo before he was deported. Giraldo, who
had lived in the U.S. for 10 years after illegally entering the
country, was deported in 1987 after keeping an appointment to speak
to an immigration officer about obtaining a permanent residency.
(Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) QUEBEC -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- QUEBEC-ENGLISH, 12-14 -- A
view of the library of the Literary and Historical Society of
Quebec which has dedicated itself to preserving the memories and
achievements of the early settlers of the region. English-speaking
people have been in the minority here since the British conquered
the French in 1759. But they thrived until about 30 years ago, when
the first stirrings of the independence movement in Quebec Province
made them start to feel unwelcome. (Robert Galbraith/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- IMPEACH, 12-14 -- Brandon
DeFrehn, left, an intern for Rep. Constance Morella, R-Md., and
Rocco Mark Gerhardt, a research fellow, tally constituent responses
to the impeachment vote against President Clinton in Morella's
office on Monday. Anti-Impeachment opinions are stacked at right.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WEST ORANGE, N.J. -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- IMPEACH-RODINO,
12-14 -- Peter Rodino, former chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee during Watergate, refers to a copy of his committee's
impeachment report during an interview in his home. Rodino warned
that impeaching Clinton for perjury would cheapen the Constitution
and weaken the presidency. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
