<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9659 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ALIOTTI-LADN     12-14 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ALIOTTI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALIOTTI ON THE DEFENSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Oregon's 1995 Rose Bowl berth was one of the
happiest moments in Nick Aliotti's life. He had masterminded the
Ducks' Gang Green defense, building it practically from scratch,
and was considered one of the best defensive coordinators in the
Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Aliotti is again coaching a Rose Bowl defense
_ but without the nickname and certainly without the joy.
</P>
<P>
   In his first season as UCLA's defensive guru, Aliotti is under
siege. His defense ranks 99th in the nation and was largely
responsible for the Bruins' 49-45 loss at Miami. His methods have
been questioned by his head coach. His job security is the hot
topic within the Morgan Center and he is not answering the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the toughest season of my coaching career and
it's not even close,'' Aliotti said last week. ``It's tough, but
I've got to get my head out of the toilet and move on. There's
never been anything close to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Aliotti is his own harshest critic, but Bruins coach Bob Toledo
is a close second. In November, after horrific defensive
performances against Stanford and Oregon State, Toledo publicly
criticized Aliotti's strategy and methods. Last week, when asked to
assess Aliotti's future, Toledo offered no support and said he'd
evaluate the situation after the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``That upset me,'' Aliotti said. ``Wouldn't it upset you?''
</P>
<P>
   So Aliotti dangled. His defense was ridiculed throughout the
Pac-10, across the nation and within his own locker room. Every
finger, every ounce of blame, it seemed, was pointed at the
44-year-old coordinator with a husky voice and no answers.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week. That's when Toledo returned from a four-day
recruiting trip, reviewed film and revised his position. Saturday,
he gave Aliotti a vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the scheme or the alignments, it was the execution
of the system,'' Toledo said. ``I think we're doing the right
things, I really do. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better after watching the video. If it had been poor
alignments and true coaching problems, I'd be more concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Watch the game five times or 50 and there's only one
conclusion:The Bruins could not tackle. They could not execute the
most fundamental principle of defense. Time after time, they were
in position to stop Hurricanes tailback Edgerrin James and let him
slip away. They did not shed blocks and they did not make plays.
For that, fairly or unfairly, Aliotti has accepted the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody lives in my shoes but me,'' he said. ``It's hard to
fathom.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, Aliotti stepped into the most difficult situation for
a defensive coordinator: mixing a new system with a young defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have two senior starters and two junior starters.
Their three best linemen are true freshmen. Seventy-five percent of
the linebackers and 50 percent of the secondary are second-year
players, either redshirt freshmen or sophomores. At times against
Miami, they had eight freshmen and sophomores on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``What went wrong is what we said at the start, we're young and
inexperienced,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins endured the same trouble in 1996, when first-year
coordinator Rocky Long installed his unconventional system. With a
slew of sophomores and juniors, UCLA ranked near the bottom of the
Pac-10 in total defense (370 yards) and scoring defense (29
points).
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you put in a new system, you have to anticipate
growing pains,'' said Long, who left UCLA last winter to become the
head coach at New Mexico. ``There's a learning curve you have to go
through. It happened in 1996 and I'm sure it happened this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only people who really understand the process are the
coaches. Even the players don't realize what a difficult transition
it is. I can sympathize with Nick. People can get impatient, but
he's a good coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Aliotti is well-regarded within coaching circles and would be
hired in a nanosecond if he left UCLA. But he seemingly
miscalculated on several fronts this season, which partly explains
UCLA's average points (27.5) and yards (432.5) allowed.
</P>
<P>
   His system is based on blitzing the quarterback, playing
man-to-man coverage and _ here's the kicker _ reacting to offensive
personnel. The Bruins don't line up and play. According to
cornerback Marques Anderson, they line up, read the offensive
personnel and formation, then process their assignments.
</P>
<P>
   It worked at Oregon and it worked with the St. Louis Rams, where
Aliotti spent three seasons. But the Bruins don't have NFL talent
executing the scheme and they don't have an all-conference
cornerback like ex-Duck Alex Molden playing man-to-man coverage.
</P>
<P>
   As Toledo noted last month, Aliotti didn't temper the scheme to
suit the personnel. He seemed to be coaching a system the young
Bruins could not process.
</P>
<P>
   ``His scheme is good, it's sound,'' Anderson said. ``There are a
lot of details and it takes time to have to master the defense,
almost become scholars, and you just can't learn a new system in 2{
months. This year was a learning experience for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Toledo believe he'll welcome Aliotti back for
1999 if Aliotti agrees to tweak the system, emphasize fundamentals
and use more zone coverage. For one thing, they're good friends,
having coached together at Oregon in 1988. In addition, Toledo
understands the combustible combination of youth and a system
change, having endured the same problems with UCLA's offense in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the currents of history are at work.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, needing a scapegoat for several disappointing Cotton
Bowls, Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum fired his offensive coordinator
_ an energetic, creative play caller named Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   It was, of course, a disastrous move. Toledo has built one of
the nation's most dynamic offenses at UCLA, and the Aggies haven't
moved the ball consistently in four seasons. Last year, Slocum
acknowledged his gaffe. Toledo probably doesn't want to make the
same mistake. &UR; !dlim! &LR; !end!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
