<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-FALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET SHRUGS OFF CLINTON DILEMMA, BUT DOW DROPS 126 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ US stocks tumbled again Monday, with the Dow Jones
industrial average losing more than 126 points as hundreds of
companies warned that slowing growth and overseas troubles were
damaging their ability to make money.
</P>
<P>
   In its focus on money-making, Wall Street seemed curiously tone
deaf to the renewed controversy surrounding Bill Clinton and to the
rapidly rising chances that he will become only the second
president in American history to be impeached. The House is
scheduled to debate four articles of impeachment Thursday stemming
from Clinton's affair with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky and from his efforts to hide the liaison.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts conceded that financial markets would be deeply shaken
if Clinton were actually driven from office, but argued variously
that a House Judiciary Committee decision to send impeachment
articles to the full House was merely procedural, that House
Republicans are bluffing in their talk about removing the
president, and that the impeachment effort will die in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of old music,'' said Michael W. Clark, head of US
equities trading at Credit Suisse First Boston in New York.
</P>
<P>
   What attracted investment professionals' attention instead of
impeachment was word that Mattel Inc. will miss its annual profit
target by a wide margin because of declining sales to retailers.
Shares of the world's largest toymaker plunged 8 1/8 to 22, their
steepest drop in 16 years and enough to trim $2.5 billion from the
firm's market value. The company also announced it will buy
Learning Co. of Cambridge, Mass. in a $3.2 billion stock deal.
</P>
<P>
   In saying it won't make its profits target, Mattel became the
latest of hundreds of companies to warn they will disappoint
investors on earnings, and it renewed fears that the stock market's
recent recovery had been built on little more than thin air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on track for a record number of negative
pre-announcements,'' said Charles L. Hill, research director for
First Call Corp. in Boston, which tracks corporate earnings.
Pre-announcements are the way companies warn about profits in
advance of releasing the actual numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Profit worries have been eating at investors since late
November, when the market hit new highs. Analysts said these
warnings are largely responsible for trimming the Dow's value by
more than 7 percent since its Nov. 24 peak. The well-known market
measure is still up almost 10 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Those worries took an especially heavy toll Monday on technology
stocks, which had been among the big winners in the market's
recovery from its earlier stumble this fall. The computer-laden
Nasdaq Composite index lost 62.59 points, or 3.1 percent, to close
at 1966.92
</P>
<P>
   Computer titans like IBM, Microsoft, and Intel all lost ground.
IBM shares fell 5 1/8 to 162 7/8. Microsoft stock shed 6 1/16 to
close at 127 15/16. Intel dropped 4 7/8 to 11 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   The losses in high-tech shares follow a recent trading frenzy
that pushed up the sector far beyond what many market watchers
consider to be realistic levels.
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet stocks have doubled since October, although
they've yet to turn a profit. The Nasdaq itself spiraled 60 percent
from Oct. 8 to Dec. 8, according to Bill Meehan, chief market
analyst for Cantor Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   For the day, the Dow was off 126.16 points, or 1.4 percent, to a
six-week low of 8695.60. Declining issues outnumbered advancers by
an 11-to-4 ratio on the New York Stock Exchange, with 2,283 up, 828
down and 455 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 887.04 million shares, vs. 823.9 million in
the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 25.28 points, or
2.2 percent, to close at 1141.18.
</P>
<P>
   The American Stock Exchange composite index fell 9.77 to 647.99,
and the Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was off 7.43 to
387.94.
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
