</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- IMPEACH-2, 12-14 --
Attorney General Janet Reno speaks before Vice President Al Gore at
an event announcing grants for community policing in the Roosevelt
Room of the White House. With the White House increasingly
pessimistic about President Clinton's ability to win the
impeachment vote in the House, Gore denounced House Republican
leaders for refusing to allow a vote to censure the president and
accusing them of ignoring the ``wisdom of the American people.''
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WEST ORANGE, N.J. -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- IMPEACH-RODINO-2,
12-14 -- Peter Rodino, former chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee during Watergate during an interview in his home. Rodino
warned that impeaching Clinton for perjury would cheapen the
Constitution and weaken the presidency. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- BAGELS, 12-14 -- Helmer
Toro, owner of H&AMP;H Bagels on New York's Upper West Side, stands
near his product as workers fill the bins. Since Jerry Seinfeld
began using the H&AMP;H store, or rather a stage-set version of it, as
a regular sit-com site, its reputation as a New York institution
has reached into far corners of the country. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1998 --US-DEPORTATIONS, 12-14 --
Maria Judith Valencia sits alone in the apartment she used to share
with her son Fernando Giraldo before he was deported. Giraldo, who
had lived in the U.S. for 10 years after illegally entering the
country, was deported in 1987 after keeping an appointment to speak
to an immigration officer about obtaining a permanent residency.
(Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) QUEBEC -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- QUEBEC-ENGLISH, 12-14 -- A
view of the library of the Literary and Historical Society of
Quebec which has dedicated itself to preserving the memories and
achievements of the early settlers of the region. English-speaking
people have been in the minority here since the British conquered
the French in 1759. But they thrived until about 30 years ago, when
the first stirrings of the independence movement in Quebec Province
made them start to feel unwelcome. (Robert Galbraith/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- IMPEACH, 12-14 -- Brandon
DeFrehn, left, an intern for Rep. Constance Morella, R-Md., and
Rocco Mark Gerhardt, a research fellow, tally constituent responses
to the impeachment vote against President Clinton in Morella's
office on Monday. Anti-Impeachment opinions are stacked at right.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WEST ORANGE, N.J. -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- IMPEACH-RODINO,
12-14 -- Peter Rodino, former chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee during Watergate, refers to a copy of his committee's
impeachment report during an interview in his home. Rodino warned
that impeaching Clinton for perjury would cheapen the Constitution
and weaken the presidency. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) GAZA CITY -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- MIDEAST-CLINTON-2, 12-14
--A large banner welcoming President Clinton hangs on a building as
a Palestinian police officer stands guard on the rooftop. Clinton
addressed Palestinian legislators in Gaza shortly after they
officially removed a statement in their charter calling for the
destruction of Israel. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK-- Dec. 14, 1998 -- SAVITRI-OPERA-REVIEW, 12-14
-- Kyo Won Han as Death and Jessica Miller as the heroine in
Holst's ``Savitri,'' based on a Hindu tale. ``Savitri'' touches on
the Hindu concept of maya, which is the illusion of the physical
world. When Death tells Savitri that her husband is about to die,
Satyavan calms her fears by reminding her that everything,
including fear, is illusion. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ISTANBUL, Turkey, -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- TURKEY-PROTEST ,
12-14 -- Turkish novelist Orhan Pamuk in his home in downtown
Istanbul. Pamuk has turned down the coveted title of ``state
artist,'' awarded to him this month, for political reasons. (Staton
R. Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- IMPEACH-MAIL-2, 12-14 --
A computer screen shows Rep. Stephen Rothman's incoming e-mail on
Monday. Rothman, D-N.J., says that he estimates the mail was about
65 percent against impeachment of President Clinton. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- IMPEACH-MAIL-1, 12-14 --
Staffers at Speaker-elect Bob Livingston's office keep up with the
daily mail on Monday. Livingston's Press Secretary Mark Corallo,
second from right in background, says the mail was running about 60
percent against the impeachment of President Clinton. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WOBURN, Mass. -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- DREAM-SAVERS --, 12-14
-- Elaine Steward repairs a doll at Elane Doll Co. Steward's
average ``patient'' is 30 years old, with repairs taking a week or
more. The bill is about $100 for the interior re-stringing, hair
transplant, and exterior makeover that give a doll that
prime-of-life glow. (David L. Ryan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- COINS-DISPUTE-BOS, 12-14 --
The front and back side of Athenian coins buried more than 2,000
years ago. Just after the coins were dug up in 1984 did an epic
saga with remarkable twists began to unfold. (Pam Berry/Boston
Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) GAZA CITY -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- MIDEAST-CLINTON , 12-14 --
School children wave American flags along with posters bearing
portraits of President Clinton and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
in Gaza City on Monday. Clinton addressed Palestinian legislators
in Gaza shortly after they officially removed a statement in their
charter calling for the destruction of Israel. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- ASSISTANTS-FASHION-2, 12-14
-- At right, Michael Hyacinth, in turtleneck, and Tiong Tan, who
both work for designer Jackie Rogers, study the drape of fabric
across a mannequin. At left, Craig Natiello, assistant designer for
Bill Blass, helps Brooke de Ocampo choose an outfit for the
upcoming Winter Wonderland Ball. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- ASSISTANTS-FASHION-1, 12-14
-- Every one of us has an area of expertise, and the designer draws
on that,'' says John Nickleson, who heads Oscar de la Renta's
design studio, top. ``I don't think there's a designer in the world
who doesn't have an assistant or a design team behind him,'' says
the designer Carolina Herrera. ``But few people talk about it. ``
She works with her assistant, Damiano Biella, at her showroom,
below. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photos)*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- SCI-WIT, 12-14 -- Kathleen
Chalfant, in bed, plays a college professor undergoing cancer
treatment in the play ``Wit'' at the MCC Theater. The play takes
the audience through the the perspective of a scholar's
understanding of life and death while being treated for the
disease. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CAMBRIDGE, -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- SCI-MIRROR-TECH, 12-14 --
Prof. Edwin Thomas, right, and Yoel Fink, a graduate student,
members of the M.I.T. team that invented the ``perfect mirror,'''
hold one of their inventions along with a mirror tube that can
guide a beam of laser light. The mirror is called perfect because
it reflects light at any angle with virtually no loss of energy. It
promises to have significant applications in many fields, including
fiber optics, cellular telephones, and energy conservation. (Ed
Quinn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) DURHAM, N.C. -- Dec. 14, 1998 -- SCI-MELANOMA, 12-14 --
Dr. James Grichnik points to an area showing a melanoma on one of
his patients diagnosed with the help of a digital-imaging program
at the Duke Comprehensive Cancer Center at Duke Hospital. New
digital-imaging techniques are helping doctors search for early
signs of melanoma, the most deadly form of skin cancer. (Jennifer
Warburg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ARLINGTON, Virg. -- Dec. 14, 1998 --SCI-PATCH-ADAMS,
12-14 -- Dr. Hunter D. Adams, better known as Patch, clowns with
some props in this home in the Washington, D.C. suburbs. ``Humor is
an antidote to all ills,'' including the greed that afflicts the
medical profession, says Adams, better known as Patch. (Carol T.
