<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0468 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9663 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BASEBALL15-COX     12-14 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mariners a no-show in trade talks with Reds
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Because Cincinnati Reds general manager Jim
Bowden likes to shoot for the moon, he has been left with his feet
firmly entrenched on Planet Earth on the trade market during
baseball's winter meetings in the vastness of The Opryland Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Better he should have spent his time with wife, Amy, perusing
the many specialty shops under the glass roof at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds and Seattle Mariners met twice Sunday, with talks
centering on right fielder Reggie Sanders. Another meeting was
scheduled for 10 a.m. Monday, but the Mariners didn't show.
</P>
<P>
   ``No reason to show,'' said one Seattle executive. ``What else
is new? Not only did Bowden want top prospects, he wanted our top
prospect. For Reggie Sanders? I think not.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's top prospect is 6-10 left-handed pitcher Ryan
Anderson, billed as The Young Unit, the next Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Mariners turned to the New York Mets for outfield
help, acquiring Butch Huskey for 20-year-old relief pitcher Lesli
Brea out of Class A.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he stood-up Bowden, Seattle general manager Woody
Woodward said, ``Have our talks been productive? No, but with
Bowden there is always the possibility he'll wheel and deal, that's
for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds and St. Louis Cardinals met Monday morning to talk
about the perceived excess of Cincinnati pitching, but the
Cardinals were told Pete Harnisch and Denny Neagle are no-nos.
Barry Larkin's name came up, too, but Bowden left the impression he
doesn't really want to trade Larkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know who I want for Larkin?'' Bowden told St. Louis
general manager Walt Jocketty and manager Tony La Russa. That would
be outfielder J.D. Drew and pitcher Rick Ankiel, two St. Louis
untouchables.
</P>
<P>
   Said one Cardinal official, ``Bowden made it clear he doesn't
want to trade Larkin by the demands he makes and by the fact he
pointed out to us that Larkin's contract would have to be
re-negotiated if the Reds traded him.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin denies that the possibility of having his contract
re-negotiated is the reason he wants to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, this year's meetings continued on the same path they
were on in the early 1990s, before commissioner Bud Selig pulled
the plug on them after 1992. Instead of trades, free-agent signings
dominated.
</P>
<P>
   Against Selig's wishes, the meetings were revived this year . .
. and it's the same thing. Selig didn't attend and he was correct.
</P>
<P>
   The only significant player transaction was the crater-making
seven-year, $105 million free-agent signing of pitcher Kevin Brown
by the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds had the third biggest announcement _ the signing of
pitcher Steve Avery to a one-year, $1.5 million contract. The Mets
signed Rickey Henderson to a $1.8 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   Trades? Few. Three minor deals.
</P>
<P>
   Left hanging was the eventual destination of pitcher Roger
Clemens, who has been promised a trade by the Toronto Blue Jays. He
is scheduled to make $16 million over the next two years, but he
wants that re-negotiated by his new team to a three-year $43.5
million deal, which would put him close to Brown's $15 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the New York Yankees are in the forefront with
Clemens, causing one American League scout to say, ``The Denver
Broncos were trying to win all their NFL games, now the Yankees are
trying to win all their games.'' The Indians talked with the Blue
Jays most of Monday, but it is believed the Yankees planned to stop
the Tribe from acquiring Clemens by topping anything the Indians
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden is one of the small-market people howling over the
Brown-Clemens absurdity, but he understands. In fact, he was
runner-up to Kevin Malone for the L.A. general manager's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame Malone or manager Davey Johnson,'' Bowden said.
``If I had been GM of the Dodgers and they wanted me to spend $90
million a year on salaries, I'd do it, even though I don't think
it's fiscally responsible. Heck, I'd spend $250 million a year _
and owner Rupert Murdoch can do that _ acquire all the All-Stars
and win 150 games and lose 12 . . . and that would be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson agrees. While everybody talks about parity, Johnson
flatly says, ``Parity isn't the American way. The American way is
to dominate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, though, is frustrated by the lack of trade prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of deals Monday fell apart and died, so we threw away
the life support and here we sit in our rooms,'' Bowden said. ``We
wanted to do more. But we'll all just get in our cars and on planes
and go home. Two clubs expressed interest in Barry Larkin (St.
Louis, Seattle), but neither offered quality big-league players or
top-notch prospects. We listened, but nothing was substantial.
Teams felt they could steal him for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
