<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE UNLIKELY TO TAKE FIELD AGAINST 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Drew Bledsoe will be holding a clipboard,
not a football, when Steve Young, Jerry Rice, and the San Francisco
49ers come to Foxboro Stadium Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At least that is the plan as of Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Plans have been known to change, but it appears that if the
Patriots are going to reach the playoffs, they need Bledsoe to be
healthier than he is now for the regular-season finale against the
Jets Dec. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots coach Pete Carroll would not name a starter for the
49ers game, hinting that both Scott Zolak and Tom Tupa could be in
the mix.
</P>
<P>
   According to a source familiar with Bledsoe's medical situation,
doctors at Massachusetts General Hospital recommended that Bledsoe,
who had a painful day in a 32-18 loss to the St. Louis Rams Sunday,
rest the finger this week and most of next week so he can be ready
for the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots feel that game will be more important to their
playoff fate than the 49ers game.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback had the finger reevaluated Monday by specialist
Dr. James Herndon and team physician Bert Zarins. Bledsoe had
another X-ray which, according to the source, revealed that Bledsoe
had not suffered any more damage to the finger, but the pins that
doctors had placed in the finger to stabilize one of the two breaks
were surgically restabilized.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe also suffered some bleeding as a result of the pins
moving around and popping out the other side through his skin.
</P>
<P>
   The prolonged rest is expected to allow more healing of the
cracked bone, and the doctors feel the pins won't have the tendency
to dislodge when more healing has taken place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our thinking that we have to give him this week off,''
Carroll said at Monday's press conference. ``He's been doing about
all he can. We're thinking right now that we have to give him a
break this week. He's not able to perform the way he's capable of
playing under the current conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if he didn't have a broken finger and he doesn't
practice, it definitely takes away from the preparation for the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   In a release Monday detailing the treatment Bledsoe received,
the Patriots would only say that Bledsoe's playing status for
Sunday is ``uncertain'' and that his condition would be updated
later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   The coach, who called Bledsoe a ``warrior,'' said Bledsoe's
problems began after his warmups, during which it appeared he was
throwing with accuracy and velocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the warmups it started to change,'' said Carroll. ``The
intricacies of this go beyond what we can understand right now. He
came upon some problems. It was was like sending the fighter to the
corner and sending out the cut man for a while, but now it's
progressed too far. Drew is the kind of guy who will go out there
at all costs. We've made it clear to him that he needs to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   While it appears Zolak is the likely replacement, Carroll left
the door open for Tupa, or perhaps both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two guys will take care of the QB position,'' insisted
Carroll. ``We're going to take more time to make the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak played in parts of two series against the Rams, but
fumbled when Ray Agnew sacked him and St. Louis recovered at the
Patriots' 13. ``It was a tough play, but even if I had three guys
hitting me, I shouldn't have fumbled the ball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak has been preparing as the starter the past three weeks in
practice. ``It's up to Pete,'' Zolak added. ``He makes all the
decisions. I've been practicing like I'm going to play. It's tough
_ it's like a seesaw thing. I thought I'd play in the Buffalo game,
but Drew made it back, which was good for him. It's a little
draining but it's my job. I'm the backup.''
</P>
<P>
   Tupa said he took just as many snaps as Zolak last week.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa has more experience in terms of games started, 13-5. Zolak
has completed 54.4 percent of his passes to Tupa's 51.3. Tupa last
started a game in 1991 with the Cardinals, while Zolak hasn't
started since November 1995 against the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Both Zolak and Tupa have incentive to perform _ both are
unrestricted free agents at the end of the season. Tupa obviously
has value as a punter, but he would have a chance to show that he's
still a player the Patriots or another team can consider a
quarterback and thus save roster space. The Browns and the Jets
will be two teams eyeing Tupa if the Patriots don't re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll likes Tupa's throwing ability, which is why he always
mentions him in the mix. One downside to starting Tupa is the
possibility he could get hurt and thus be lost as a punter. Adam
Vinatieri is the team's backup punter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in a sitaution like this where two
quarterbacks could play in the same game,'' said Tupa. ``If Drew
can't go, they might have a game plan that might benefit me. I
guess we'll know more (Wednesday).''
</P>
<P>
   Tupa is involved in all of the quarterback meetings with Bledsoe
and Zolak, so he knows the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't rule anything out at this point,'' said Carroll. ``We
could use both guys, but we'll make a clear-cut decision on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak was somewhat skeptical about using two quarterbacks in a
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Pete's decision,'' he said. ``You have to get a rhythm
and get going. It's tough for me and the guys around me.''
</P>
<P>
   How will either Zolak and Tupa win the trust and confidence of
their teammates in such a crucial game?
</P>
<P>
   ``They see me in practice and they see what I can do,'' said
Zolak. ``These guys have busted their tails all year in practice
and in games. I have to show them that I can move the offense down
the field and move the markers. I have to show them I can get the
ball in the end zone, for no matter how you do it, you have to do
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
