<SLUG> BC-HUGHES-SATELLITE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGHES TO BUY SATELLITE TV COMPETITOR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Minn.)   (jw) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hughes Electronics Corp. agreed Monday to pay
about $1.3 billion in cash and stock to buy U.S. Satellite
Broadcasting Co., a move aimed at fortifying Hughes' DirecTV unit
as the nation's leading provider of television programs transmitted
directly to homes by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition comes two weeks after the Echostar
Communications Corp. agreed to buy satellite television assets from
the News Corp. and MCI Worldcom, giving it more channel capacity
than DirecTV. Together, the deals reduce the number of satellite
television companies in the United States to three from five,
although the News Corp.-MCI partnership had never actually provided
service. All the companies are in a high-stakes battle to sign up
enough subscribers to become profitable.
</P>
<P>
   DirecTV has nearly 4.3 million subscribers and Echostar has 1.8
million, and each added about 100,000 in November. The third
remaining company, Primestar Partners, which is owned by several
cable television companies, has about 2.3 million subscribers and
grew in November at half the rate of the two others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's starting to look like a two-horse race between DirecTV
and Echostar,'' said Tom Watts, an analyst with Merrill Lynch, who
said Primestar was less competitive because it required a larger
antenna.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, each U.S. Satellite share can be exchanged
for either 0.3775 share of General Motors class H stock or the
equivalent in cash. The exchange ratio is fixed as long as GM class
H stock trades between $27.82 and $47.68 in the days before the
deal closes. Hughes Electronics, based in El Segundo, Calif., is
owned by GM but has stock that reflects its own financial results.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Hughes' closing price of $38.25 on Friday, the offer is
valued at $14.44 a share, 50 percent above U.S. Satellite's closing
price of $9.625 that day and about double its price before rumors
of the deal began spreading on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   GM's class H shares fell $1.5625 Monday, to $36.6875. U.S.
Satellite rose $2.8125, to $12.4375.
</P>
<P>
   DirecTV and U.S. Satellite already operate with common
satellites and common viewer-receiving equipment. But viewers must
order the services separately and pay two monthly bills if they
take both. Executives said merging would eliminate customer
confusion and spur sales. ``We had to make the up-front sales
simpler,'' Stanley Hubbard, U.S. Satellite president, said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Existing consumers of either or both services would not have to
change their equipment but would receive a single bill. DirecTV
officials said they did not plan immediately to change prices but
might offer new packages of programs.
</P>
<P>
   Eddy Hartenstein, DirecTV president, said the deal would save
$160 million to $180 million a year, though he declined to say how
many people would lose jobs. DirecTV would increase the number of
channels it offers to more than 210 from 185 and could fill a big
hole in its lineup by offering Home Box Office and Showtime movie
channels, which U.S. Satellite now carries.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   DirecTV would not gain many new subscribers because all but
200,000 of its competitor's 2 million subscribers are already
DirecTV customers, as well. But executives said DirecTV revenue
would immediately increase by $800 million to $900 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   DirecTV forecasts revenue of $1.5 billion and an operating loss
of $100 million this year. It expects to break even on a cash-flow
basis around the second quarter of 1999, though a profit is not
expected until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition requires approval of U.S. Satellite shareholders
and the FCC and antitrust regulators. More than 51 percent of U.S.
Satellite shares are held by Hubbard Broadcasting of St. Paul,
Minn., which owns television and radio stations. Hughes officials
said that they expected no regulatory problems and that the deal
would close in mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the FCC barred DirecTV from participating in an
auction for an orbital position for a satellite, fearing that it
would control too many.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
