<HEADLINE>
TRADE TALKS LEAVE RED SOX POWERLESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ There are still 10 shopping days until Christmas,
two months until the start of spring training, and almost four
months until Pedro Martinez takes the mound in Kansas City on April
5 and throws the first pitch of the 1999 season for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Time, in other words, for General Manager Dan Duquette to
accomplish what he was unable to do in three days of trade talks
here: Find a power hitter and some significant pitching help.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette acknowledged Monday night that he'll more than likely
leave empty-handed Tuesday from baseball's winter meetings, which
have been distinguished by one mega-signing (Kevin Brown's $105
million deal with the Dodgers) and little else.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether the groundwork undertaken by
Duquette and his lieutenants here eventually will bear fruit,
though some intriguing acquisitions were discussed. Here they are,
though hardly in order of their likelihood of happening:
</P>
<P>
   --Frank Thomas. White Sox General Manager Ron Schueler said he
was approached by one club here about his remaining marquee player,
who ranks No. 1 among all active players in both on-base percentage
(.443) and slugging percentage (.584), despite having an off-season
by his exalted standards (.265 batting average, 29 home runs, 109
RBIs). That team was the Red Sox, Duquette confirmed Monday. And
while he said it is ``premature'' to envision the Big Hurt in a Red
Sox uniform, Thomas ranks as the one player who might be available
who could fill Mo Vaughn's considerable shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Schueler isn't shopping Thomas, but at least he expressed a
willingness to listen. And the Red Sox are a team that would not be
scared off by the approximately $78 million that Thomas' contract
guarantees for the next eight years. Thomas, who will be 31 on May
27, might even be considered a bargain by today's standards, and
would immediately return the Sox to contender status. Expect some
followup conversation.
</P>
<P>
   --Ryan Klesko. The 27-year-old first baseman-outfielder was a
prime topic of conversation between the Red Sox and Braves. Klesko,
is owed $17 million over the next three years and is coming off an
off-season in which his production dropped to 18 home runs and 70
RBIs, though he can point to an in-season appendectomy as a
contributing factor to his decline. The Braves, who signed
free-agent Brian Jordan, have a surplus of outfielders but are in
no hurry to part with Klesko. They're looking for a middle
reliever/setup man (Derek Lowe) in return, plus a top prospect from
the Sox. According to two National League sources, they've asked
about shortstop Adam Everett, Boston's No. 1 pick last June, as
well as shortstop Julio Guerrero, brother of Expos' star Vladimir
Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are prohibited by baseball rules from trading a draft
pick until one year after he was drafted, so Everett couldn't be
included in a deal until June. Expect the Sox to try and entice the
Braves with other prospects. This deal has a chance.
</P>
<P>
   --Russ Davis. The Sox envision converting Davis, a leaden-handed
third baseman for the Mariners last season (32 errors) into a first
baseman. Davis played first base in the Yankees' system, and after
hitting 20 home runs in each of the last two seasons, the Sox think
it's not out of the question for the right-handed hitting Davis,
29, to blossom into a 30-homer man in Fenway Park. The Mariners may
also be asking for Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   --Gregg Jefferies. He's still available as a free agent, but
Duquette said Monday that ``he's not very high on our list. We're
looking for a little more power.'' The switch-hitting Jefferies hit
nine home runs last season.
</P>
<P>
   --John Jaha. Another free agent, Jaha has played 100 games in a
season only once in the last five seasons because of injuries. The
Red Sox have looked at his medical records and Duquette said Monday
they're bringing him to Boston for further medical evaluation, but
the 33-year-old former Brewer ranks no better than a fallback plan
if nothing else materializes.
</P>
<P>
   --Kevin Appier. Another high-risk possibility after undergoing
shoulder surgery in March and missing most of last season, the Sox
nonetheless talked to the Royals about the 31-year-old righthander,
who has $4.8 million remaining on his contract for next season. If
Duquette waits to see if Appier is healthy in spring training,
he'll risk competition from other suitors. And while that would
seem to be the prudent thing to do, Duquette has been known to take
that risk before.
</P>
<P>
   --Tim Belcher. The 37-year-old righthander has at least one
three-year offer from a club, agent Scott Boras said. Duquette said
the team has not made a formal offer, and would not be willing to
go more than two years on a deal. Doesn't look like a match.
</P>
<P>
   --Dan Miceli. The Padres' setup man, who has appeared in 138
games the last two seasons, would be a welcome addition to a
bullpen thin behind Tom Gordon, Jim Corsi and Lowe. The Padres are
said to want a top prospect in return, one close to big-league
readiness. The Red Sox may not be a match.
</P>
<P>
   --Roger Clemens. For the last time, the Rocket won't be coming
back. Duquette admitted as much Monday night, in the wake of
Clemens' demands for Kevin Brown-type money in any deal to which he
agrees. ``That's a little rich for us,'' Duquette said. Which
doesn't even address the fact that the Sox would have little to
entice the Blue Jays to make that deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
