<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASSEL SAVORS THE UNLIKELIEST OF VICTORIES  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Jim Fassel found it easy to smile Monday
morning at Giants Stadium. He was at his office at 6 a.m., making
coffee and musing on the surprising succession of events that had
led to Sunday's 20-16 shocker over the Denver Broncos when the
assistant coach Rod Dowhower appeared in the doorway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim,'' Dowhower said. ``Before you look at the regular Kansas
City tape, take a look at these other two.''
</P>
<P>
   Dowhower handed Fassel videotapes of the Kansas City Chiefs, the
Giants' opponent on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geez, Rod, I haven't even had my coffee yet,'' Fassel said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the driven, dutiful Fassel was anxious to take a few
moments to enjoy the biggest National Football League
regular-season upset in several years. Monday, for the first time
in several weeks, Fassel looked comfortable in the wake of a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team deserves to feel the way it feels,'' he said. ``The
team played hard and with confidence and never once sensed there
was any reason to lose hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel's primary recollection of the Broncos game was how smart
and aware his team played. Receiving more praise than any other
player was Kent Graham. For the first time, Fassel conceded Monday
that Graham might compete for the starting quarterback's job next
season with Danny Kanell, and that Graham could be the team's
quarterback of the future.
</P>
<P>
   That has never before been acknowledged by any Giants official.
Fassel also said Graham would probably start the team's final two
games. ``I'd say that's a really safe assumption,'' Fassel said.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing what an upset victory over a previously unbeaten
team will do. Last Monday, Fassel indicated that he was going to
have Kanell ready to replace Graham at a moment's notice _ that
Graham's audition at quarterback could be over as soon as he was no
longer leading the Giants to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when asked if Graham was a part of next year's quarterback
picture, Fassel said: ``Oh, yeah, sure. I've always believed that
if you see a guy do it one time, you can get him to do it again.
This game shows he's capable of playing this way. From our
standpoint, in a lot of ways, he was the difference in yesterday's
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Graham's play, Fassel seemed to be marveling at the
wherewithal of his 6-8 team against the Broncos. It was, after all,
just four weeks ago that the Giants had lost three straight games
and five of their last six.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Fassel Monday recalled in detail how guard Ron
Stone hopped 45 yards across the field on one leg in the game's
final 80 seconds to save time and help keep a Giants drive alive.
</P>
<P>
   Stone had a bruised calf, and since the Giants were out of
timeouts, the game officials would have taken 10 seconds off the
clock if he needed assistance to leave the field.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the Giants didn't need those 10 seconds. Three
plays later, with 48 seconds left, Graham hit Amani Toomer with the
game-winning touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   But at the time, with 1 minute 12 seconds to play, those seconds
seemed precious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stone knew he had to get off the field,'' Fassel, who gave the
players Monday off, said. ``The guys on the bench knew they
couldn't help him. Jerry Reynolds ran in to replace him, and Kent
turned and had Stone in the corner of his eye, waiting for Stone to
get off the field before he snapped the football.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that is very impressive, for a bunch of guys to have
that presence of mind in a big situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game showed the Giants off at their best this season,
and it inevitably made Fassel think back to games lost _ at
Washington and at Oakland _ that the Giants were expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Giants won even one of those games, they would be tied
with the 7-7 Tampa Bay Buccaneers and Arizona Cardinals for the
final National Football Conference wild-card berth.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they are one game behind in that race, with few of the
tie breakers in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always look back and say, `Gosh, if we had just won this
one game,''' Fassel said. ``The way we're playing now magnifies the
losses in some games. But you can kill yourself if you go back too
much. In every season, win or lose, you can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, this morning, Fassel seemed anxious to momentarily
postpone the usual pattern of his coaching life, with its
one-game-at-a-time, on-with-the-next-game existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a coach's mentality,'' he said. ``But still, this was a
really special win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
