<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GIANTS SHOW JETS SUPER IS POSSIBLE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, the day after the rookie wide receiver Randy
Moss of the Minnesota Vikings had riddled the Cowboys with three
touchdown receptions on Thanksgiving, Bill Parcells was holding his
daily news briefing in Jetsworld when an impertinent question was
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you thought,'' somebody said, ``about how you're going to
stop Randy Moss in the Super Bowl?''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' coach rolled his eyes, shook his head, glanced at the
ceiling and never answered.
</P>
<P>
   He understood the question for what it was then, an irrelevant
joke.
</P>
<P>
   It's not such an irrelevant joke now.
</P>
<P>
   With a 20-16 upset Sunday that should be remembered as one of
New York's most memorable pro football games, the Giants showed the
Denver Broncos to be fallible and thereby showed the Jets, now 10-4
after their 21-16 success in Miami, the way to Super Bowl XXXIII
where Randy Moss and the Vikings might be waiting.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jets' road to Miami on Jan. 31 has several tollbooths _
beginning in Buffalo on Saturday and eventually in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The toll collector in Buffalo will be Doug Flutie, who surely
doesn't want to be embarrassed as he was five weeks ago in the
Jets' 34-12 rout. Until then, Flutie had generated 14 touchdowns,
but that day he put only four field goals on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been five years since I got my tail kicked like this,''
Flutie said then, alluding to a Canadian Football League game.
``Their four linebackers and four defensive backs gave me
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Be assured that Flutie will be using a different game plan.
Should the Bills win, they would tie the Jets for first place in
the American Football Conference East; the Bills finish in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Jets roll through Buffalo, they will clinch first
place in the AFC East. And if the Jacksonville Jaguars, shaky since
quarterback Mark Brunell suffered a severely sprained ankle, lose
in Minnesota on Sunday night, the Jets will have earned a bye
through the Jan. 2-3 wild-card weekend of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Jets and Jaguars both win, another Jet victory in
their season finale at Giants Stadium against New England would
assure the bye.
</P>
<P>
   When Parcells twice won the Super Bowl with the Giants, after
the 1986 and 1990 seasons, and when he took the Patriots to the
Super Bowl two years ago, he had the benefit of the bye each time.
It not only provides players a bonus week of rest, but it is one
fewer game to win, one fewer game when anything can happen, one
fewer game when an important player can get hurt.
</P>
<P>
   With a bye, all the Jets would need to do is win their division
playoff, perhaps against Jacksonville, and they would be in the AFC
championship game _ probably in Denver, now in mourning ever since
the acrobatic wide receiver Amani Toomer caught Kent Graham's
37-yard touchdown pass to make the Giants' season.
</P>
<P>
   That touchdown also made the 1972 Dolphins' season. As the only
undefeated and untied team in National Football League history,
those Super Bowl VII champions with Larry Csonka and Nick
Buoniconti were 17-0. The Broncos, with a chance to go 19-0 if they
repeated in the Super Bowl, were threatening to upstage them.
</P>
<P>
   For all the hype of their 13-0 record, the Broncos had been
vulnerable in their two previous victories, over the San Diego
Chargers and the Kansas City Chiefs. Now, with their hopes for 19-0
shattered, the Broncos must regroup for next Monday night's visit
to Miami, where the Dolphins desperately need to win if they are to
salvage a wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Broncos are no longer a lock to represent the AFC
in the Super Bowl, especially if Parcells and the Jets arrive at
the Denver tollbooth. The 1990 49ers and Bills will attest to that.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, along with Bill Belichick and his other Giants
coaches, prevented those 49ers (with Joe Montana and Jerry Rice)
from having an opportunity to win three consecutive Super Bowls
with a 15-13 victory in the National Conference title game in San
Francisco. Then Parcells' ball-control game plan kept the ball away
from Jim Kelly and the Bills in Super Bowl XXV, 20-19.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Jets get through all those tollbooths on the road to
the Super Bowl, Bill Parcells might need to figure out how to stop
Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
