<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLCOL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL GETS IT RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The three-game suspension handed down Monday by the NHL to Kings
defenseman Rob Blake was a harsh decision, overly punitive _ and a
very good sign for those tired of the savagery that eternally has
dragged down the sport of hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, by no means a dirty player, insists he wasn't trying to
deliver a cheap shot Saturday night when his two-handed chop landed
on the elbow of Vancouver's Harry York. Instead, Blake insists he
simply aimed badly in trying to connect with York's stick in an
effort to create an outnumbered attack for the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason not to believe Blake. The last thing he would
have wanted with a third-period, two-goal lead and a man already in
the penalty box was to give the Canucks a two-man advantage, which
is exactly what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Logic dictates that Blake's play was accidental, and relatively
harmless accidents (York was not seriously injured) should not be
met with three-game suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the NHL's image has historically been tarnished by
barbarism on the ice. It appears the cleansing period the sport has
long needed is upon us.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, when Brian Burke was the NHL's director of
discipline, he suspended 15 players for a total of 45 games. That
included the ludicrously brief four-game suspension assessed to
then-Chicago defenseman Gary Suter for a vicious cross check to the
chin that almost ruined the career of Mighty Ducks star Paul
Kariya.
</P>
<P>
   This season, former New York Rangers coach Colin Campbell has
replaced Burke, who is now the Canucks' general manager. In about
one-third of a season, Campbell has issued 16 suspensions totaling
57 games for infractions ranging from stick fouls to slew-footing
to Chicago's Reid Simpson hurling a water bottle at a fan (two
games).
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to gripe about individual miscarriages of justice,
such as the discipline to Blake. But a period of harsh judgments
can only help to clean up hockey and promote the elements of speed
and skill that should be the NHL's most attractive assets.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coffey break: Former Kings defenseman Paul Coffey, who has
appeared in just four games this season for the Chicago Blackhawks,
recently visited the Mayo Clinic to find out what was wrong with
his back. It turned out that Coffey, 37, suffered nerve damage when
he received an injection to numb the pain of his original back
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit a nerve,'' Coffey said. ``I'm bitter it happened, but
I don't have any axes to grind. I just wish I had known sooner
because then I wouldn't have been tormenting myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept pulling my hamstrings and hip flexors in those games,
because I was overcompensating. The (Mayo Clinic) doctors told me
it will be another month before the nerve is totally healed. But
once I get the strength built up in my quads and hamstrings, I can
skate again, maybe in another two or three days.''
</P>
<P>
   __ IHL memories: With goalie Felix Potvin in limbo as he awaits
a trade, Toronto recalled Glenn Healy from the IHL's Chicago
Wolves. The Leafs were paying Healy $1.2 million to play in the
minors while they tried to resolve Potvin's situation.
</P>
<P>
   Of his stay in Chicago, Healy said, ``We had a seven-hour bus
trip to Cincinnati. It was the longest airport runway of my life.
You couldn't get NHL scores on the out-of-town board, just the
Federal League (of ``Slap Shot'' fame).
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day on our way to the rink, we would pass this wild
store that sold liquor, cigarettes, tobacco chew and handguns. We
wondered how our coach (ex-Leaf John Anderson) would feel about us
sitting in the car, drinking and smoking and shooting off our guns
on our way to work.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Desert pucks: The Phoenix Coyotes could play host to an
upcoming All-Star Game. All Arizona taxpayers have to do is vote
for a new arena in Scottsdale to replace the sparkling America West
Arena, which is 6 years old.
</P>
<P>
   About a quarter of the seats in the America West Arena have
obstructed views, something the Coyotes' owners were fully aware of
a few years ago when they abandoned loyal fans in Winnipeg.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Coyotes have emerged as a Stanley Cup contender,
what better time to try to reach into the public till to build a
new facility?
</P>
<P>
   __ Loose pucks: Dallas' Joe Nieuwendyk had an exceptional
accomplishment last week in a 3-3 tie with San Jose, winning 20 of
21 faceoffs. ``I think we all take a lot of pride in that part of
the game,'' he said. ``We know how important it is.'' . . . Guy
Carbonneau, Dave Reid and Brian Skrudland have formed a line for
the Stars lately, a group with an average age of 35.7. A Dallas
writer dubbed it the ``Older Than Dirt'' line. . . Edmonton's
Andrei Kovalenko bought 20 Nashville Predators jerseys to outfit a
youth team in the Ukraine. ``I thought they might like something
new, not (Oilers jerseys),'' he said. . . The IHL has named its
Comeback Player of the Year Award after John Cullen, who missed all
of last season with cancer. Cullen retired after a brief comeback
this season with the Tampa Bay Lightning and in the IHL. ``When
(the IHL) phoned me and mentioned it, it caught me off-guard,''
said Cullen, now a Lightning assistant coach. ``When I hung up the
phone and started to think about it, I couldn't believe what an
honor it was. It makes me see and realize just how far I've come
back from the disease. That trophy is going to be around for a long
time and it's a huge honor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
