<HEADER>
A9682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-BANKS-NYT &LR;      12-14 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA REJECTS MERGERS OF MAJOR BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Finance Ministry rejected two mergers Monday that
would have left just three big banks in Canada. But the door was
kept open for other mergers once regulations have been overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Paul Martin said he rejected the proposed deals
because they ``would lead to an unacceptable concentration of
economic power in the hands of fewer, very large banks.'' He
expressed concern about branch closings, job losses and a
tightening of credit for small businesses if the mergers took
place. And he released a report by the Federal Competition Bureau
that said the merged banks would have too much control over the
credit card and retail brokerage businesses.
</P>
<P>
   At least two of the banks involved in the deals indicated that
they could have addressed the issues raised by the competition
bureau. But Martin made it clear that he preferred to have the new
regulatory framework in place first.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's banking industry is already among the most highly
concentrated in the world. The proposed mergers would have created
two huge banks controlling 70 percent of assets.
</P>
<P>
   Martin did not rule out mergers among Canada's big banks but put
them off for at least a year while rules for the industry are
overhauled and a new merger review process is put in place.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, he said, ``the new proposals will first have to
demonstrate, in the light of the circumstances of the day, that
they do not unduly concentrate economic power, significantly reduce
competition or restrict our ability to address prudential
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's cold shoulder comes almost a year after Canada's
financial services industry was shocked by the announcement that
the Royal Bank of Canada, the country's largest bank, planned to
merge with the Bank of Montreal, the third largest.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Martin was clearly displeased at not receiving
advance notice of the plans. Things got no better in April when the
second-ranked Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce announced a merger
with the Toronto-Dominion Bank, the fifth largest of Canada's top
five.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Godsoe, chairman of Scotiabank, the only large institution
not involved in a merger, eventually became an outspoken opponent
of the deals.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Martin began a news conference in Ottawa Monday
morning to announce his decision, it was well known that his answer
would be no. Shares of all four banks involved in the mergers
declined, the biggest drop by the Bank of Montreal, which fell
$1.55, to $62.05 (Canadian).
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts who supported the mergers are worried
that Canada's banks will be hurt by the decision. ``The banking
system in Canada is not going to have the scale and efficiency it
needs to fend off attacks from south of the border,'' said James
Andrew of Renaissance Worldwide, a strategic consulting firm in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts thought the mergers were not necessary for the
Canadian banks to remain competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``With or without the mergers, they can be survivors in the
North American arena,'' said Jamie Keating of Merrill Lynch Canada.
``They just had visions of being better, longer and more profitable
survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed consolidations were never popular in Canada.
Opposition was especially strong in suburban and rural areas that
were almost certain to lose branches.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Martin's decision was announced, the Canadian
Imperial Bank of Commerce and Toronto-Dominion officially
terminated their merger plan. The move was no surprise because
Toronto-Dominion had released a statement more than a week ago
indicating that the deal was as good as dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Bank and the Bank of Montreal issued a joint statement
indicating that they would make a decision about their merger after
reviewing the government's decision, although they are not expected
to press on with the plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
