<SLUG> BC-GUN-LOCKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON POLICE TO USE GUN LOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Continuing its campaign against gun violence, the city
of Boston plans to announce Tuesday its police force will begin
using new, personalized gun locks, becoming the first major
department in the country to mandate the combination locks.
</P>
<P>
   The plan will equip all 2,247 officers with the $79.95 lock _ a
black device that can be unlocked within seconds, even in pitch
darkness, but is impenetrable to children, the manufacturer said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is expected to further rattle gunmakers, who
earlier this month learned they will be the target of a massive
Boston liability lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the major defenses that the industry put forward was
that it was going to take years to make guns more
child-resistant,'' said Dennis Henigan, legal director of the
Washington-based Center to Prevent Handgun Violence. ``Here you
have a police force doing just that. It certainly puts the industry
on the defensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The lock, produced by SafTLok, a company based in Tequesta,
Fla., was greeted with accolades from law enforcement officials
when it was introduced on the market earlier this year, according
to company president Frank Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 police departments, including Boston's, have been
testing the device for months, Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   After attaching the black device to either a Glock semiautomatic
pistol or a revolver, officers unlock the devices by pushing metal
buttons under the fingers of their firing hand. The combination
does not require sighting: like a Morse code, it unlocks after
receiving the proper number of clicks, a 2-3-2 pattern, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't require the brain to really think,'' Brooks said.
``You can dial it quickly, while you're talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, police will be required to learn operation of the
safety device during regular gun training, according to Sergeant
Margot Hill, a Boston police spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   And although the device is easy to disarm, gun safety analysts
said police would be unlikely to keep their guns locked during work
hours.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal is in the off-hours; rather than just keeping
sidearms on the top shelf, officers will now have a surefire way to
keep the weapons from harming children, according to John
Rosenthal, founder of Stop Handgun Violence, the
Massachusetts-based advocacy group that bought the first 100 test
devices for Boston police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the intent of the city of Boston and the police
department is to lead by example,'' Rosenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   Other municipalities have bought the device in smaller
quantities, and SafTLok has donated 2,300 to its local sheriff's
department in West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In Orland Park, Ill., Police Chief Tim J. McCarthy _ a former
White House bodyguard who was gunned down alongside Ronald Reagan
during the 1981 assassination attempt _ equipped the 100 officers
on his police department with the device earlier this year,
immediately after it was put on the market. McCarthy said he spent
$5,000 of his equipment budget to ``provide the best method to keep
guns safe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that, particularly in this day and age, we should
provide an opportunity for the officers to safeguard their
weapons,'' said McCarthy. ``This lock provides a different way to
unlock it. I don't think a child or an intruder would even have any
idea it was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun industry analysts see the SafTLok initiative _ coupled with
Mayor Menino's announced intention to sue the gun industry with 30
other cities nationwide _ as signaling an increasing attack on
gunmakers. In the past, gunmakers, who are unregulated by consumer
safety guidelines, have reluctantly acknowledged the possibility of
designing personalized guns and advanced safety devices, but called
them too expensive and still largely theoretical.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Henigan said, it is obvious that we are ``not talking
about Star Trek futuristic technology here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about a system that is no more complicated than
your average locking briefcase,'' he said. ``That it can be
feasibly used for handguns is now being demonstrated by the Boston
Police Department.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
