A9695 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      12-14 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHING PRESIDENT ANCHOVY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Clinton is abortion. Bill Clinton is capital punishment.
Bill Clinton is opera, the designated hitter, affirmative action.
Bill Clinton is one of those subjects about which you made up your
mind a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no changing it.
</P>
<P>
   You're convinced he's done enough to be impeached and removed
from office, or you're convinced he's not done enough to be
impeached and removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, you have all the information you need.
</P>
<P>
   More than you need.
</P>
<P>
   You've had it for months, and so have all the politicians in
Washington. They're no different from you, except for one small
thing.
</P>
<P>
   They lie about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   All during the impeachment hearings in the House of
Representatives they pretended they hadn't reached a decision about
the president.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, most of them _ Democrats and Republicans _ decided
about Clinton years ago. Long before the special prosecutor issued
his final report.
</P>
<P>
   They're politicians, though, and don't have the guts of ordinary
citizens when it comes to speaking their minds.
</P>
<P>
   So, they decided to hold hearings to pass judgment on Clinton's
lies, all the while lying about their own opinions.
</P>
<P>
   And they're not done yet. &QL; 
The `undecided' &QL; 
Over the next few days, the ones who want Clinton impeached and the
ones who don't will be busy trying to twist the arms of the
``undecided.'' In a real trial, that would be called jury
tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it matters.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, there are no ``undecided'' members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The ones who say they haven't made up their minds on impeachment
aren't doing so because they haven't reached a verdict on Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   How can they ``not'' have?
</P>
<P>
   They're either trying to put the squeeze on party leadership for
some pet project or legislation, or they're waiting to see which
vote, yes or no, will play best at home.
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing could be taken care of in about an hour. First,
the House votes to impeach and tosses the ball to the Senate. The
Senate holds a 30-minute ``trial,'' during which time they pretend
they haven't quite made up their minds. Then they vote.
</P>
<P>
   He goes. He stays.
</P>
<P>
   We move on.
</P>
<P>
   The reason you didn't watch live TV coverage of the House
impeachment hearings is because you knew all you needed to know. &QL; 
Nothing new &QL; 
You knew there'd be nothing new revealed, and there wasn't. Just as
there won't be anything new in a Senate trial, if and when it comes
to that.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton is anchovies.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton is a Neil Diamond song. Bill Clinton is instant
replay as an officiating tool in football. He's Seinfeld. He's
prayer in public schools. He's euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   He's the National Endowment for the Arts and the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   He's rap music.
</P>
<P>
   He's broccoli.
</P>
<P>
   He's karaoke.
</P>
<P>
   The national opinion polls haven't changed much over time. The
majority of people don't trust Clinton, or believe him, but still
don't want to go through an impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians may lie, but numbers don't.
</P>
<P>
   By now, nothing Clinton says or does could alter the way anyone
feels.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in his latest apology, Clinton said, ``I am
profoundly sorry for all I have done wrong in words and deeds. I
never should have misled the country, the Congress, my friends or
my family.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., one of the so-called ``undecided''
votes, said he was disappointed the president did not admit he
lied.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for this president to tell the truth,'' Tauzin said.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton had guts or a better sense of humor, he'd look
squarely in the eyes of Tauzin and every other congressman and
answer, ``I will if you will.'' &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
