<HEADER>
A9698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-LABOR-NYT &LR;      12-14 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTLOOK APPEARS BLEAK FOR SALVAGING THE NBA SEASON  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They have tried small, secretive meetings in the
office of a law firm and large, scheduled gatherings in the
ballroom of a hotel. But Monday, as the 167th day of the lockout
passed, it appeared that nothing the players and owners do has done
much to salvage the National Basketball Association season.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after a negotiating session broke off after less than
30 minutes, neither the league nor the union was optimistic about a
rapid settlement to the contentious labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect there to be any talks this week,'' said Russ
Granik, the NBA deputy commissioner. ``We just don't know what to
talk about anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The more frustrated you get, the more you want to
set a deadline to cancel the season. But we refuse to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The union was hoping to jump-start the talks and help end the
five-month dispute by offering concessions to the owners over the
weekend. But the league viewed the concessions as having little
impact toward helping the owners achieve some kind of cost
certainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're just marching in place,'' said Billy Hunter,
the union's executive director. ``We'll talk at some point, but as
of this moment, it's a game of wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   The players were scheduled to miss their third paychecks
Tuesday. With a month needed to restart the season, total salary
losses will top more than $400 million by mid-January. If another
week goes by before an agreement is signed, the league may be
forced to play less than a 50-game season _ a number several
observers feel is a benchmark for the owners weighing whether or
not to scrap the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the league held its annual Christmas party at the NBA
Store on Fifth Avenue. Commissioner David Stern attended. He also
confirmed that the league's staff had been trimmed to about 750
employees through attrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have decreased our size by 125 full-time positions without
mandating layoffs,'' Stern said. The league instituted a hiring
freeze on July 1 and has not filled the vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the league would eventually lift the hiring freeze once
the lockout ended _ or begin layoffs if the season were canceled _
Stern added: ``I don't know. Our business is in the process of
changing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0484 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9703 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS &LR;      12-14 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
'Tis the season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most folks, anyway, as Christmas nears.
</P>
<P>
   But for locked-out basketball players, 'tis not the season _ the
NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of ``Ho, ho, ho,'' it's a case of, ``No, no, no.''
</P>
<P>
   No talks between the owners and the National Basketball Players
Association in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   No notion of when the season will begin _ or if there will even
be one.
</P>
<P>
   And no paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the union, today should have been the third payday
of the season. Instead, the players are in the same holding pattern
they've experienced since the lockout began 168 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you miss money you were expecting to get, it's
tough,'' said the Rockets' Brent Price. ``Obviously, for some guys
it's tougher than for others. If a guy hasn't played long in this
league, or if he's just starting out, then this is a tough time of
year. Right now, the focus should be on getting the season started
as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio's Avery Johnson agreed that the younger players in
the league are most affected by the prolonged lockout, since they
haven't had the opportunity to sock away money like the veterans
have learned to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this hurts different guys in different ways,'' Johnson
said of the missed paychecks. ``I think a lot of us, the veteran
players, were prepared for this, so we just keep on living and
don't miss a beat. But there are other situations where maybe guys
just weren't as prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I wouldn't have been prepared in my first or second
year, no matter what I did, because I didn't handle my resources
properly. I didn't retain anything. I think the veteran players
should be in good shape. We're just worried about the young guys
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because there is no end in sight on this most
unpredictable labor front.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides thought they were closing in on a deal last week,
only to see a Saturday negotiating session fall apart in just 30
minutes. The session was supposed to be about finalizing details
that would contribute to a framework for an agreement, but conflict
again erupted, abruptly ending the meeting and dashing the players'
hopes again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that until they come out with a handshake agreement
and get it on paper, that's when a lot of us will believe it,''
Johnson said. ``Because when we saw they came so close, it was a
case of so-close-but-so-far, as I understand it. A lot of the stuff
that was reported (about a final deal being near) was true, but
unfortunately we change. We wake up with different ideas. We may go
to bed with one idea, but we can wake up with another. Seasons
change, and people change.''
</P>
<P>
   The sudden end to Saturday's session surprised many, especially
since most everyone entered the room believing a deal was in the
works. Instead, confusion over how to administer a complicated
escrow fund over the last three years of the deal got everyone
bogged down.
</P>
<P>
   The escrow deal, by which the players would kick in a percentage
of their salaries when spending goes beyond a determined limit, is
designed to slow the explosive salary growth that triggered the
lockout.
</P>
<P>
   The players would like to share the responsibility of
overspending with the owners and have offered 10 percent of their
salaries if the owners will cover any further overspending with a
tax. Now, the problem is arriving at an agreeable tax rate. Sources
say the owners would like a tax that would be around 600 percent,
meaning owners would have to pay $6 for every dollar they spend
above the predetermined limit.
</P>
<P>
   The players think such a rate is too prohibitive, saying it will
not only stifle salary growth (which is what the owners want) but
will also cause a competitive imbalance since only a few cash-flush
teams _ the Trail Blazers, Knicks and Lakers, for example _ would
be able to afford such a large tax.
</P>
<P>
   NBA commissioner David Stern has said the season will cancel
itself if a deal isn't reached in the not-too-distant future, a
threat the union believes to be a bluff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it does not look good,'' Stern said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
