A9707 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     12-14 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JOLT FROM JOE: TODAY'S HEROES TAKE A FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Where have you gone, Albert Belle?
</P>
<P>
   A nation turns its lonely eyes to you.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't think so. Somehow I doubt we'll ever hear Beck or Sheryl
Crow immortalize any of today's baseball players in a pop song the
way Paul Simon did Joe DiMaggio in ``Mrs. Robinson.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would they? What baseball player today _ what athlete in any
sport _ transcends his game so much that a succeeding generation
would bemoan his loss, and beckon to him for lost innocence and
hope?
</P>
<P>
   None, by my count. My generation has no one who comes close. And
we are poorer for it.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's illness has writers sharpening their pencils and
their wits, ready to raise a toast in tribute to the great Yankee
Clipper, just in case. A great player, a great man, a giant who by
his very carriage moved beyond a mere game and became an icon of
popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   He married Marilyn Monroe. He appears, tangentially, in ``The
Old Man and the'' ``Sea,'' for heaven's sake.
</P>
<P>
   But to my generation, Joe DiMaggio isn't, sadly, Joltin' Joe.
He's Mr. Coffee. If that. Yes, those of us who love sports know
about the 56-game hitting streak, the sweet swing from the heels,
the Hall of Fame career that put him in the rarefied company of the
best of all time.
</P>
<P>
   We've glanced at the black-and-white clips, what there are of
them. We've heard our parents talk about him. But we didn't ``see''
him play, or hear crackly Yankees games broadcast on the radio.
He's a part of history, like FDR and Elvis _ important, yes, but a
part that we never experienced firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   There's no shame in that. We don't choose the time in which we
live. The shame is that so much has changed since DiMaggio's heyday
that we'll never see a hero like him again.
</P>
<P>
   Sports has changed. The closest thing to an athletic cultural
icon we have is Michael Jordan. He is immensely gifted,
preternaturally graceful, probably the best athlete in any team
sport of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that's all he is, an athlete. That and a businessman.
Increasingly we measure his status not by the number of
championships he's won (certainly not a consideration this year,
with the NBA so choked by greed the season is dangerously close to
being canceled) but by how big his last contract was.
</P>
<P>
   Will my children's children hold him in the same esteem people
hold DiMaggio today? Not a chance. A bigger contract will come
along for someone eventually.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not beatifying DiMaggio. I'm sure he has his foibles.
Nothing I've read about him made him sound like someone you'd
particularly want to have a beer with.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter. He wasn't running for Mr. Congeniality. He was
a baseball player. People liked their star athletes a little rough
around the edges. What the fans didn't know didn't hurt them.
</P>
<P>
   That's changed, too. What ``don't'' we know about Dennis Rodman?
Is there an aspect of the addictions of John Daly and Brett Favre
we haven't become intimately familiar with? If the media had delved
as deeply into Babe Ruth's personal life as they do Rodman's, pop
psychiatrists would still be analyzing him. We would name treatment
centers after him.
</P>
<P>
   We want to know every lurid detail about everyone, from
presidents to interns to movie stars to athletes, current and
retired. How else would we know how many times DiMaggio has had the
last rites administered?
</P>
<P>
   I know sports is just a diversion, not the place to go looking
for role models and heroes. Or so we're told, now that there are so
few who fit that bill to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe ``we'' have changed. Maybe we can't abide heroes anymore.
Why else would we tear them down the instant we've built them up?
With our thirst for intimate details has come a cheapening, a
cynicism _ a cynicism that says they're no better than we are,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Joe DiMaggio ``is'' better, to hear my parents' generation
tell it. Heroes are supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   I'm tired of cynicism. I'm ready for my generation's DiMaggio. I
just hope that if he's out there, if he has what it takes to be a
hero, we'll let him be one.
</P>
<P>
   So here's to heroes. Wherever we may find them. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2221EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
