<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAKE'S SUSPENSION STUNS KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Rob Blake will have to miss two more games
as a result of a slashing incident in Saturday's victory over
Vancouver, but the Los Angeles Kings' star defenseman, their coach
and their general manager don't think he should have been suspended
at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's too severe,'' general manager Dave Taylor said
Monday afternoon, shortly after NHL vice president Colin Campbell
handed down his verdict following a brief telephone hearing. ``Rob
slashed (Vancouver's Harry York). The referee (Don Koharski)
assigned him a major penalty, and I think that was appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake received a five-minute major and game misconduct for the
slash during the third period of a 3-0 victory Saturday. That night
Taylor said he didn't expect Blake to be suspended. But Sunday
morning, Campbell suspended Blake for that afternoon's game against
the Mighty Ducks, a 3-0 loss by the Kings. After Monday's hearing,
Campbell tacked two games on to the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the five-minute major was definitely enough,'' said
Blake, who will lose $82,304.69 (three days) of his ($5.2675
million) salary in addition to a $1000 fine. ``(The Ducks game)
probably was one of the most important games of the year. The
damage is done.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Blake, he was swinging at York's stick on the play,
trying to knock the puck free to create a 2-on-1 for the Kings. But
York reached for the puck as Blake swung, and Blake missed his
stick and hit him on the arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hit the guy's stick,'' Blake said, ``it's not even a
penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the severity of the suspension, Campbell said, ``Mr.
Blake used excessive force with a baseball-grip swing to the arm of
the Vancouver player. His use of the stick in this manner caused an
injury, which is something the league can't condone.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Larry Robinson said, ``I don't think he deserved
(the first game of the suspension). They're trying to say it was a
baseball swing. If that's a baseball swing, he must be hitting
singles.''
</P>
<P>
   York left the game with a bruised arm, and X-rays were negative.
</P>
<P>
   Blake will miss Thursday's home game against the New York
Islanders and Saturday's visit to St. Louis, the 17th and 18th
games he's missed this season. He is eligible to return for
Sunday's game at Chicago. The Vancouver game was Blake's first
after a 15-game absence with a broken foot. The Kings (8-18-3) are
3-13 without Blake this season, 5-5-3 with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just puts us in the same position we've been in all
along,'' Robinson said. ``We've got to deal with reality. The
reality is we're not going to have him until Chicago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2221EST &QL; 
