</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGOLA-REBELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SAYS U.N. DIAMOND EMBARGO IS NOT WORKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUANDA, Angola _ The sale of diamonds is still underwriting the
war by Angolan rebels, and a U.N. embargo aimed at cutting off that
income is not working, a report said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The report, by a human rights organization in London, Global
Witness, says blame for the continued rebel traffic in Angolan
diamonds is widespread.
</P>
<P>
   De Beers, the South African company, and its Central Selling
Organization in London, the cartel that controls world prices of
uncut diamonds, lack the controls to make sure that the company is
not buying diamonds from rebel-held territories, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore the United Nations has not made sure that its
members are rigorously honoring the Security Council embargo
imposed in July. Uncut Angolan diamonds make their way to Belgium,
Britain, Israel, South Africa, the United States and other
countries, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, known as Unita, the Portuguese acronym for the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, have earned
$3.7 billion from diamonds since 1992, experts estimate. For much
of that time they controlled virtually all the diamond-producing
areas in Angola, where some of the world's finest gems are dug from
riverbanks.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that the failure of the embargo has let Unita
``restock munitions and supplies,'' which has ``fatally undermined
the peace process.'' More than 500,000 Angolans have died in the
civil war, which began in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an urgent need for the diamond business to
fundamentally change the way in which it works, because it is
clearly unacceptable for diamonds to be used as a major source of
revenue in conflict,'' said Charmain Gooch, a director of Global
Witness. ``How many people, when buying a diamond for their loved
one, have any idea of the horrific price that Angolans have had to
pay?''
</P>
<P>
   De Beers representatives said Monday that they did honor the
embargo. Any diamonds offered to their buyers in Belgium or Africa
``that are obviously of Angolan origin and don't have a certificate
from the Angolan government'' are refused, a spokesman said, even
if they have certificates that say they are from countries like
Zambia or Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Determining the origins of diamonds is difficult. A skilled
buyer shown many uncut stones from one area can make an educated
guess about the area of origin by the mixture of shape, color and
quality. With a single stone or a mixed bunch, that is impossible.
Chemical analysis is theoretically possible. But it is expensive
and would require drilling holes in each stone.
</P>
<P>
   Even if De Beers refuses stones Unita will easily find other
buyers, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The government and the rebels signed a peace treaty in 1994. But
disarming the soldiers and creating a coalition government has gone
slowly, and fighting has resumed in many regions.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting was particularly fierce early this month, as the
government attacked two Unita strongholds and met unexpectedly
tough resistance. One diplomat here said that the rebels had
launched counterattacks in the area, shooting down a government
plane Monday that was delivering food and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials acknowledged the latest round of fighting
for the first time this weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0491 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9712 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-DIRECTORS-SPI &LR;      12-14 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-DIRECTORS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING'S BOARD KEEPS CONDIT ON THE JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After a two-day meeting, The Boeing Co.'s board of
directors quietly left town Monday _ and Boeing Chairman Phil
Condit still had his job.
</P>
<P>
   There had been speculation from Seattle to Wall Street,
triggered in part by a Sunday story in The New York Times, that the
board would sack Condit because of the company's continued poor
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the speculation even led to a crazy rumor Monday
that General Electric was poised to buy Boeing and that Condit
would be replaced by his friend and GE boss John Welch Jr.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the Dow Jones industrial average ended down more
than 126 points, Boeing's stock was up slightly as some investors
gambled that if the board fired Condit the company's stock would
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Although board memebers did not issue any public show of support
for Condit, sources said the board took no action to remove the
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   But Condit took the unusual step of sending an e-mail late
Monday to Boeing managers asking them to disregard rumors and to
focus on getting the company back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many, if not all of you, have heard or read media speculation
about senior management changes,'' Condit wrote. ``Rumors do not
contribute to doing the job that we have before us, so let me put
them to rest. The senior management team is in place and dedicated
to two things _ improving the profitability of The Boeing Co. and
securing its long term future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we reviewed with the board each of our three different
businesses. Aircraft and Missile Systems is profitable and looking
at how to grow its business profitably for the future. We are
investing heavily in Space and Communications for the future and
thus depressing near-term profitability to secure a very profitable
future. Commercial Airplanes is meeting delivery plans, but must
make significant changes to achieve its profit potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect every Boeing person to contribute to these tasks by
doing what we do best _ focusing on our customers and working to
find solutions to the problems that face us. Enough of rumors and
speculation; let's prove how good we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The board met in Seattle Sunday and Monday. It was a regularly
scheduled meeting and a spokesman said two-day meetings are not
unusual.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman added that he spent much of the day on ``rumor
control'' following published reports that Condit might be fired.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Boeing stunned Wall Street when it announced
that profits would not be what it hoped in 2000 and that it was
cutting its workforce by 20 percent, or about 48,000 jobs, by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had believed that Boeing, which suffered its first loss
in a half century last year, was finally getting its act together.
The latest batch of bad news immediately led to speculation that
Condit's days as head of the world's largest aerospace company were
numbered.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, The New York Times suggested in a lengthy Boeing
story that the board might fire Condit when it met Monday and
replace him with Harry Stonecipher, the former head of McDonnell
Douglas who became Boeing's president after last year's merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there was hope on the part of some that Phil would get
the ax,'' said Bill Whitlow, an analyst at Safeco asset management
in Seattle. ``I didn't think that would happen, nor do I think it's
necessary. Most of the changes that have already been made are
probably enough to get the ship turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd Givan, Boeing's longtime chief financial officer, was the
first to resign under pressure earlier this year. In September,
Boeing's Commercial Airplane boss Ron Woodard was fired. He was
succeeded by Alan Mulally, who in turn replaced several key
managers with his own team.
</P>
<P>
   Whitlow, who manages a fund that holds 67,000 Boeing shares,
said many investors ``want blood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an absolute disaster,'' he said. ``But what can
be accomplished by firing Phil now. ... You need to have some
continuity in management. If Phil were to go and Harry took over,
you would have mostly non-Boeing people in the executive suite.
That might be okay for Wall Street, but not for the 160,000 people
who worked for Boeing before the merger (with McDonnell Douglas).
Morale is not good. It's more important to have continuity at the
top than to placate Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``If Phil were fired and replaced by (GE's) Jack
Welch, maybe. But continuity makes more sense.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with the Post-Intelligencer, several industry
analysts said Monday that rumors were flying on Wall Street
throughout the trading session regarding Condit's possible removal
by the board.
</P>
<P>
   One rumor, that General Electric, the country's second biggest
company, would buy Boeing, may have been responsible for Boeing's
stock being up 7/16th Monday to close at 33 9/16 a share, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rumor was nonsense,'' said one analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is just speculation,'' added Pierre Chao of Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter. ``A group of shareholders have been screaming
for Phil's head. But is it the right thing or not? Who knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Aseritis, an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston,
agreed. But he also acknowledged that many analysts believe
Stonecipher might be better suited for the chairman's job than
Condit, an engineer by training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could Harry change the fundamentals so that the commercial
margins in 2000 would be better? I'm not sure. But he would be more
pro-active. It's not Phil's nature to walk in and tell a guy he has
three months to turn this around,'' Aseritis said. ``Harry is much
more direct.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, Aseritis added, is that the company has not
done well under Condit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a fact. The company has not done well and Phil's the
boss. But will he be replaced? No one but the board knows.''
</P>
<P>
   And Monday, the board decided that at least for now, Phil Condit
runs The Boeing Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
