<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-NYT &LR;      12-14 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE JETS, THE SKY IS SUDDENLY THE LIMIT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Grudgingly, but with a hint of admiration,
Bill Parcells said Monday that his playoff-bound Jets were ready
for Buffalo on Saturday, a game that could launch them to a
division title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my team has the mentality now to play in this kind of
game the whole way,'' the coach said the morning after a 21-16
victory over Miami put the Jets in the playoffs for the first time
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   It can get even better for the Jets and their fans, who have not
seen a home playoff game since 1986. The Jets can not only capture
their division by winning one of their last two games, but also get
a first-round playoff bye by staying even with the American
Football Conference Central leader, Jacksonville. Each has a 10-4
record. But the Jets would win all the tie breakers and would be
the second-seeded team behind Denver, guaranteeing a bye. The Jets
could know this by the close of business next Sunday night, when
Jacksonville plays at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   For Parcells, Sunday night's victory over Miami helped him
continue a 14-year-old tradition. In each of his three coaching
posts, first with the Giants in 1984, and then with the Patriots,
he has taken a downtrodden, losing team into the playoffs in his
second season. And since Parcells arrived, the Jets are 19-11 _
better over that span than any team in the AFC except for Denver
and Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   For his players, there was a more important accomplishment: They
have stopped thinking of themselves as upstarts. Their record is
punctuated with a remarkably complementary offense and defense.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Cascadden, the linebacker who returned a Dan Marino fumble
for the crushing score Sunday night, had lived through a 4-28
record his first two years with the team. So, what's it like to see
light at the end of the tunnel?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through that tunnel for a while,'' Cascadden said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this has not been a fluke season for the Jets. Rather,
it is one in which they have grown almost weekly, with a few
setbacks in losses to teams that, based on the Jets' current
standard of play, would probably not be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have occupied first place a few times over the years
since they captured their last division title in 1969, in the old
American Football League. But since then, they have never been in
first place after 14 games, as they are now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not into that decades stuff,'' Parcells said Monday. ``I'm
not sentimental.''
</P>
<P>
   He has had the ability on the Jets to build a team the way he
wants it. ``You've got to coordinate,'' he said of his staff. ``One
thing George Young and I never had a problem with on the Giants was
deciding on players.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells also has no problems with his longtime staff. Bill
Belichick again helped draft a defensive game plan that stymied and
angered Marino, the Dolphins' quarterback. Marino was sacked five
times _ equaling his worst day as a pro. He was intercepted once.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Jets' defense was able to change on the fly.
Jets players are continually surprised each week by the unusual
defenses Belichick devises, new ways to haunt old rivals. For
example, after Seattle's Joey Galloway caught a pair of bombs for
touchdowns against Aaron Glenn, he didn't get another pass all game
_ even though Glenn was injured and replaced by Ray Mickens.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' offense is equally adaptable, evolving under the new
coordinator, Charlie Weis, whose game plans get considerable input
from quarterback coach Dan Henning. After the Jets trounced the
Falcons, 28-3, Atlanta Coach Dan Reeves told Parcells, ``We had a
lot of trouble preparing for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins were exploited, too. They were not accustomed to
seeing so many three- and four-receiver alignments. They were
confused when tight ends lined up as flankers and Wayne Chrebet
appeared out of nowhere to dash to the goal line. The Dolphins, who
came in with the stingiest defense in the league (the Jets are
second), were caught in a monumental mismatch on a pick play when
their ponderous linebacker, Robert Jones, wound up trying to cover
the elusive Chrebet. Result: touchdown. On the play before, Chrebet
had produced a 52-yard reception on third down.
</P>
<P>
   Those crucial downs at clutch times are when the Jets have
shined this season. Quarterback Vinny Testaverde has nine touchdown
passes and no interceptions on third down, leading the league;
Chrebet leads the conference in third-down receiving yardage (378)
and Keyshawn Johnson is the only receiver in the AFC with six
touchdowns on third-down passes.
</P>
<P>
   The team Parcells has created has only a few holdovers with
exceptional talent: Johnson and Chrebet, Mo Lewis and Glenn. But
three defensive linemen from Belichick's Cleveland years _ Ernie
Logan, Rick Lyle and Anthony Pleasant _ were picked up as free
agents and now start. Testaverde was out there, too, and available
during the off season. So was Bryan Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, Parcells believed it might be more difficult
to make the playoffs than it was to take the wreckage of the 1-15
team of 1996 and make it a 9-7 winner last year. Monday he spoke of
the difficulty of this season's tougher schedule, of the 0-2 start
and a realization that ``people are shooting for us.'' So far,
though, the Jets have prevailed, including prime-time road
victories at New England and Miami, and triumphs at Kansas City and
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes a big difference,'' Parcells said. ``I think
they've done an excellent job on the road. We've beaten some good
teams on the road. I think we beat them at a time when most of them
were on top of their game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
