<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9730 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THAI-LOAN-AUCTION-IHT     12-14 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THAI-LOAN-AUCTION-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAILAND HOLDS `WORLD'S BIGGEST ONE-DAY SALE' TUESDAY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Timely for Tuesday, Dec. 15)   (This 800-word ``separate buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from New York
Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``i'' international news and ``f'' financial news files.)  
  
 By THOMAS CRAMPTON  
 c.1998 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK _ By the close of bidding Tuesday afternoon, Thailand
will mark a watershed in the restructuring of Asia's crisis-hit
economies.
</P>
<P>
   On the auction block will be business loans worth nearly half of
the 860 billion baht ($24.03 billion) in assets seized by the
government last year when it shut down much of the country's
financial sector and closed 56 finance companies.
</P>
<P>
   The loans will be sold at a discount to their full value _ up to
60 percent, experts say _ to companies hoping to recover enough
money from the borrowers to make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   But the prices of Tuesday's bids are less important, several
economists said, than the demonstration that Thailand is
restructuring quickly under its $17 billion aid program from the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thailand is setting a benchmark for clearing out bad loans and
this auction will be watched throughout Asia,'' said Jim Walker,
chief economist of Credit Lyonnais. ``After sparking the crisis,
Thailand is taking the lead in cleaning up.''
</P>
<P>
   The rapid pace of Thailand's asset sell-off, which will largely
be complete if everything is sold Tuesday, places the country's
realignment ahead of Indonesia and South Korea, Asia's other two
recipients of multibillion-dollar IMF bailouts, according to Chi
Lo, senior international economist at Hongkong &AMP; Shanghai Banking
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Thailand is allowing foreign companies to bid.
Among those expected to participate are General Electric Capital
Corp. and Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping foreigners out of the banking sector was really a
sacred cow in the Asian model, but this auction is breaking that
system down,'' Lo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Korea, Indonesia and Malaysia really need this sort of auction
soon too, but the first two have not even set a date and Malaysia's
current policies would not allow it to take place.''
</P>
<P>
   Full economic restructuring, however, is far from complete and
faces mounting resistance from critics who say that Thailand, the
only country in Southeast Asia that was never colonized, is now
being sold cheaply to Western bankers.
</P>
<P>
   Led by a group of wealthy senators, opponents of IMF reforms
have already delayed passage of foreclosure and bankruptcy laws
intended to punish delinquent debtors by allowing banks to
repossess collateral.
</P>
<P>
   The laws, which the government attempted to pass earlier this
year, would have significantly increased bidding prices at
Tuesday's auction of unpaid business loans, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The 13,192 loans have a face value of 371 billion baht, but
analysts expect they will sell for at least 60 percent less, with
as many as half not selling at all.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 potential bidders each paid 500,000 baht to examine the
loan documents. Brought together from the 56 defunct finance
companies, the business loans to be sold Tuesday have been
subdivided into 42 lots, each grouping an industry or type of
collateral, such as loans to hotels or steel companies.
</P>
<P>
   As a concession to complaints that the auction favors wealthy
foreign institutions, bidders can commit up to four times their
capital funds by signing up for several lots in order of
preference.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline for submitting an envelope of bids is 1 P.M.
Tuesday and results will be announced within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Unsold lots will be auctioned in a second round, in which the
government's Asset Management Corp. will participate. There is no
minimum price, but low bids will be rejected if authorities deem
them ``artificially low,'' according to Amaret Sila-On, chairman of
the Financial Sector Restructuring Authority.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how little money the auction raises, however,
knowledge of the prices will automatically push forward the next
stage of Thailand's recovery, according to David Fernandez, a
Singapore-based regional economist for J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   The amount paid for the loans will allow banks to estimate the
necessary level of provisions for bad loans and help break the ice
with corporate restructuring as the new creditors start talking to
the companies that owe money, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the process gets under way, I think we could see a rapid
acceleration in bank recapitalization and corporate
restructuring,'' Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker of Credit Lyonnais, who was severely criticized by Thai
authorities last year when he correctly predicted the fall of the
baht months before it occurred, said early signs showed the Thai
economy had hit a pretty solid bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a yearly basis, the `headline' numbers are still way out of
the ballpark,'' he said, referring to the plunge in sales of cars
by 72 percent and motorcycles by 52 percent this year through
October.
</P>
<P>
   By examining shorter periods and making seasonal adjustments,
Walker reckons Thailand's economy bottomed out last March. ``If you
wait for headline figures to change, you've already missed the
recovery,'' he said. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 800-word article from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0504 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9731 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-BRIBES-NYT &LR;      12-14 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BRIBES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIBERY CHARGE STUDIED BY SPECIAL IOC BOARD
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ In this era of EPO and human growth
hormone and widespread skepticism about world records, it required
something remarkable to reduce doping to a minor topic at an
International Olympic Committee meeting. It required evidence of
bribery within the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that evidence leads to resignations or expulsions
depends largely on conclusions reached by a special commission
composed of IOC executive board members who are nearly all lawyers.
The commission was formed here to investigate a scholarship fund
created in 1991 by the bid committee from Salt Lake City that
benefited at least six relatives of IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Before the executive board meeting concluded Monday, the
commission met at least four times with Salt Lake City Olympic
organizing committee members. Commission chairman Dick Pound did
not rule out further meetings and said the commission hoped to
finish its work by the end of January, before the executive board
meets here on the eve of the world conference on doping.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Schultz, executive director of the U.S. Olympic Committee,
said: ``In a way, the Salt Lake City situation is a blessing in
disguise for the IOC. It's the first time they have some facts. We
live in such a litigious society today that, without hard facts, it
is really difficult to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake City's organizing committee had said the scholarship
payments, which amounted to slightly less than $400,000, came from
a privately financed fund that existed from 1991 to 1995. In 1991,
Salt Lake City lost the bid for the 1998 Winter Games to Nagano,
Japan, and in 1995 won the bid for the 2002 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Marsh, a four-time Olympian who is a Salt Lake City
committee trustee, said Monday that he wanted an accounting of the
fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``If some heads have to roll, then so be it,'' he told The
Associated Press. ``This went over the line. And I'll say right now
that if it turns out that I should have known about this, then I'll
resign. That is not what the Olympic movement is about.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Intermountain Health Care, Utah's largest health care
provider, confirmed that in 1994 it gave free surgical services to
at least two people associated with the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   One key question was why it took the IOC until 1998 to come up
with facts made public when a Salt Lake City television station
obtained an incriminating letter and disclosed the existence of the
scholarship fund. The IOC regularly debriefs candidate cities after
votes in an attempt to monitor the selection process. According to
Marc Hodler, an IOC member from Switzerland whose voice was the
most audible here despite a reminder from International Olympic
Committee President Juan Antonio Samaranch that he was not an
official spokesman, debriefings are not conducive to candor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winners never say anything because they have a bad
conscience,'' Hodler said. ``The losers only give information if
they have decided never to run again, and most of them think they
want to run again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodler said that the British bidding team from Manchester, which
bid unsuccessfully for the Summer Olympics, was among the most
helpful, but he added: ``The only things I found out were things I
already knew. And as a lawyer, I know well that they were the sorts
of things that would have someone in an American court yelling,
`Hearsay.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hodler was front and center again Monday when the international
winter sports federations met with the executive board. Because
Hodler, 80, is president of the association of winter sports
federations, he conducted a news conference in the company of
Samaranch. Hodler, who alleged on Saturday that agents were
offering small blocs of IOC members' votes to candidate cities for
bribes, said that ``this meeting is at the end of the three worst
days I have spent in my long period in sports, which has lasted 75
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why, he said, ``Because for a time I thought that those I
trusted most were trying to push things under the carpet and that
might put all the blame on Salt Lake City.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodler, who declined to give the names of the IOC members in
question, said he made allegations about corruption in recent
bidding processes because he did not want Salt Lake City to be the
scapegoat. He also said he was worried that the revelations would
severely hamper the Salt Lake City committee's ability to raise the
$350 million dollars it needs to round out its $1.4 billion dollar
budget. ``We should be grateful to Salt Lake City that this
evidence was found,'' Hodler said.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, however, the Salt Lake City scholarship fund and
its beneficiaries are all that Pound's commission is officially
scrutinizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have proof, we will open new dossiers, too,'' Samaranch
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2239EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
