<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-DENSON-NYT &LR;      12-14 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DENSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM DENSON, PROSECUTED NAZIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William D. Denson, who helped to convict and execute more Nazi
war criminals than any other American while serving as the chief
military prosecutor of those accused of administering concentration
camps in Germany, died on Sunday at his home in Lawrence, N.Y. He
was 85.
</P>
<P>
   In four trials conducted from 1945 to 1947, which focused on
atrocities committed at the concentration camps at Dachau,
Mauthausen, Buchenwald and Flossenburg, Denson prosecuted 177
Nazis, among them Ilse Koch, the sadistic wife of the camp
commandant who came to be known as ``The Bitch of Buchenwald,'' and
August Eigruber, a fanatical Nazi Gauleiter in Austria who shouted
``Heil Hitler'' as the noose was placed around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Most defendants Denson was in charge of prosecuting in 1945 were
much closer to the scenes of the Nazi crimes than those in the dock
in the more famous 1945-46 trials at Nuremberg. Many Nuremberg
defendants had planned the brutal acts, but the underlings who
carried them out drew harsher penalties, in many cases. Of those
Denson prosecuted, four were acquitted and 132 were sentenced to
death, with the rest receiving prison terms. Of those condemned to
die, some had their sentences reduced on appeal, but 97 were
eventually hanged.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, of the 22 most prominent former Nazis who were
the first to go on trial in Nuremberg, 12 received death sentences
and three were sentenced to life in prison, while four were granted
lesser prison terms and three were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   In the trials that Denson oversaw, proceedings were conducted in
Dachau and were presided over by American judges under the U.S. War
Crimes Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the trials, Denson was a 32-year-old West Point
graduate and a lawyer assigned to the Judge Advocate's Office in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   He had seen war, destruction and suffering, and yet, as he
remarked in an interview in 1990, what he heard as he began to
gather testimony aroused disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be perfectly candid with you,'' said Denson, who was by
then an elderly man, ``I thought here were some people who had been
mistreated in the concentration camps and they were seeking
revenge, and that they were really doing a job drawing on fantasy
rather than reality. And when I questioned a number of witnesses,
and they related substantially the same things, then I knew the
events had occurred, because these witnesses did not have a chance
to get together ahead of time and fabricate their stories.''
</P>
<P>
   He said those who were convicted seemed to have had normal
backgrounds, but the more violence and mistreatment they were
exposed to, ``the more unconscionable these people became.'' He
added, ``They showed no remorse, none that I saw.''
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial of the cases was that of Ilse Koch. The,
woman, then 40 years old, was accused of singling out inmates for
beatings and torture that at times brought on their deaths. She was
also accused of possessing lampshades and a photo album made of
tattooed skin.
</P>
<P>
   Because Mrs. Koch was pregnant when brought to trial, Denson
sought and obtained a sentence of life in prison, rather than the
death penalty, for her crimes against non-Germans. But a year
later, Gen. Lucius Clay, the senior U.S. military official in
Germany, commuted her term to four years.
</P>
<P>
   Denson, by then a civilian, called Clay's decision ``a mockery
of the administration of justice.'' But Mrs. Koch was then tried by
a German court for her role in the deaths of German citizens, and
drew another life term in a German prison, where she committed
suicide in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, Denson returned to the United States, joining the
Atomic Energy Commission as chief of litigation. He represented the
commission at the spying trial of Julius and Ethel Rosenberg. In
195O, he married Constance von Francken-Sierstorpff, the daughter
of a princely family he had met in Germany while serving as
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Denson is survived by his daughters,
Yvonne McQuilkin of Cambridge, Mass., and Olivia Fischett of
Parsippany, N.J.; a son, William Denson Jr. of Lawrence, N.Y., and
five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
