<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ WILL RETIRE NEXT YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Michael Rosenthal  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Former two-time world champion Genaro Hernandez,
32, said he will formally announce his retirement early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who has been boxing professionally for 14 years, said
tests revealed ``a trace of blood'' on his brain after the bout in
which he lost the WBC super featherweight title to Floyd Mayweather
on Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   That, combined with waning enthusiasm for the sport, led to his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone or something is telling me, `You should stop,' '' said
Hernandez, who grew up in South Central Los Angeles. ``I don't want
to take any more chances. I've fought 14 years, won two world
titles. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez defeated Daniel Londas to win the WBA 130-pound title
in 1991 and successfully defended it eight times over four years.
He outpointed the great Azumah Nelson in March of last year to win
the WBC version of the championship, perhaps his greatest
achievement in boxing.
</P>
</TEXT>
