<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE FREES PALESTINIAN WHO REFUSED TO TESTIFY 
</HEADLINE>
 RELEASED-NYT  (rl) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Palestinian man jailed for eight months after he
refused to testify before a federal grand jury investigating
terrorism was ordered freed Monday by a judge who concluded that
further imprisonment would not change the man's mind.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was the second in four months in which a federal
judge in Manhattan released a Palestinian imprisoned on charges of
contempt of the grand jury, which has been conducting a two-year
investigation into ``an international scheme to launder money in
support of murder and kidnapping,'' prosecutors said in legal
papers.
</P>
<P>
   The rulings have come amid a widening investigation by federal
prosecutors in New York into worldwide terrorism, and it was
unclear how much of a setback the rulings represent.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Michael Mukasey left little doubt that he believed the
witness, Ismail Elbarasse of Virginia, had been involved in
fund-raising for terrorism. He noted that prosecutors could now
bring criminal contempt charges against Elbarasse and the other
Palestinian, Abdelhaleem Ashqar, for their refusals to testify.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mukasey cited government assertions in court papers that
Elbarasse is ``a Hamas operative'' and other evidence that he
shared a bank account with Mohammed Abu Marzook, the Hamas
political leader jailed in New York during an extradition battle
with Israel before he was released to Jordan last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Mukasey said Elbarasse's close association with Marzook
suggested that he was probably not ``an untested neophyte'' and
therefore was unlikely to agree to testify during the 18-month
period in which he could be jailed on the civil contempt order.
</P>
<P>
   When Elbarasse appeared before the grand jury last April, he
cited political and religious reasons for refusing to testify, ``no
matter what my punishment may be, no matter how long my sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Elbarasse and Ashqar, who went on a hunger strike before he
was freed in August by another judge, were offered immunity from
prosecution in return for their testimony, but each man refused to
answer prosecutors' questions.
</P>
<P>
   Elbarasse's lawyer, Stanley Cohen, who also represented Marzook
in his extradition fight, welcomed the release of Elbarasse, but
sharply criticized the judge's suggestion that both of his clients
had links to terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   He called Elbarasse ``a Palestinian hero'' whose ``only crime is
to have the temerity and the principle to stand against the power
of the U.S. government in its unbridled attack upon the Palestinian
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
