<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9894 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WEBBER-LAWSUIT-530     12-14 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WEBBER-LAWSUIT-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDREW LLOYD WEBBER'S LATEST AUDIENCE: A JURY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andrew Lloyd Webber sat at a piano in federal court
in Manhattan on Monday and played part of a song that another
composer swears he wrote first.
</P>
<P>
   The impromptu recital for a nine-member jury, several lawyers
and a few reporters is likely to be the finale of an 8-year-old
copyright infringement lawsuit brought against Lloyd Webber by Ray
Repp, a composer.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges that Lloyd Webber stole a short passage from a
song by Repp, ``Till You'' (1978), and recast it as the central
theme of the musical ``Phantom of the Opera.'' Lloyd Webber has
strenuously denied the charges, and took to the stand _ and the
piano _ to prove his case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have just always loved these chords,'' he said, playing
several snippets from the main theme of ``Phantom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And so it started like that,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Repp's lawyers, however, insisted that Lloyd Webber had lifted
the melody of their client's song and reworked the tune into his
musical, which has been playing in New York since 1988 and has
grossed more than $1 billion worldwide. The suit seeks part of the
musical's royalties, a figure that could quickly run into the
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proof is in the music itself,'' said William Coulson, a
lawyer for Repp. ``Just listen.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the jury did, listening to recorded passages of music
from several of Lloyd Webber's musicals, while the composer, in the
stand, looked slightly embarrassed. During cross-examination, the
jury also received something of a primer in Lloyd Webber's career
and accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very lucky,'' he said as he told about his many Tony
Awards. ``And as much as I hate to say it, I have been knighted by
the Queen.''
</P>
<P>
   Repp has been less fortunate. A composer of religious folk
music, he says he created ``Till You'' in 1976 while strumming his
guitar. He later added lyrics inspired by the Gospel of St. Luke,
and recorded and copyrighted the song in 1978. Its gross sales,
through 1996, were $75.87.
</P>
<P>
   Repp claims that in 1989, he received a compact disk of
``Phantom of the Opera'' and was struck by the similarity between
several bars in the musical's main theme and the melody of ``Till
You.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I heard it, I said `Holy Cow! He stole my song,'''
said Repp, 56, who lives in Bel Air, Md. ``I want my song back.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Repp's music company, K &AMP; R Music, filed suit. But
in 1991, Lloyd Webber's lawyers struck back with a countersuit
alleging that Repp had in fact stolen the melody for ``Till You''
from a song from their client's 1969 musical ``Joseph and the
Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat.''
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Webber lost that suit, and Repp's suit was dismissed by
Judge Shirley W. Kram, who is also presiding over the current
trial. But in January, the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
reinstated Repp's suit and ordered that it be tried before a jury.
</P>
<P>
   Repp's lawyers Monday offered the testimony of two professors of
music, James Mack and H. Wiley Hitchcock, both of whom said there
were similarities between the two compositions.
</P>
<P>
   The jury is expected to begin deliberations Tuesday. No further
performances are scheduled.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lloyd Webber also testified Monday that the impetus for his song
came in 1983 when he was trying to create a song for his wife at
the time, Sarah Brightman, who starred in the original New York
production of ``Phantom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to play around with what we could do with Sarah's
voice,'' Lloyd Webber said. ``And I just came up with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brightman, testifying earlier in the day, gave the same
version of events.
</P>
<P>
   Coulson also peppered Lloyd Webber with questions about musical
tastes and background, sometimes drawing unintended laughs from the
small crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe there are two types of music,'' Lloyd Webber
said. ``Good and bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is just one of several high-profile copyright cases
involving musicals. In September, the family of the late composer
Jonathan Larson, who wrote the musical ``Rent,'' reached an
out-of-court settlement with Lynn Thompson, whose lawsuit claimed
that she had written some of the show's lyrics and dialogue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
