<SLUG> BC-FCC-PHONE-MERGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE PROPOSED TELECOMMUNICATIONS MERGERS DRAW CHALLENGES AT AN FCC
HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three of the largest proposed telecommunications
mergers in history were challenged Monday by consumer groups and
rival companies at a hearing that raised fundamental questions
about whether the broad deregulation of the industry, intended to
promote competition, was starting to have the opposite effect.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was held by the Federal Communications Commission,
which faces some of its most significant decisions in years as it
considers what to do. If completed, the deals would reshape the
ownership of local and long-distance telephone service in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is reviewing whether to approve, block or impose
conditions on the proposed $56 billion acquisition of Ameritech by
SBC Communications; Bell Atlantic's $52 billion purchase of GTE,
and the AT&AMP;T Corp.'s $32 billion deal to buy Tele-Communications
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The proceeding Monday reflected the strident lobbying war
between the large telecommunications companies _ particularly
between the local and long-distance carriers _ that have so far
survived the wave of consolidation that has followed the passage of
the Telecommunications Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The act was passed by Congress and signed by President Clinton
as the best way to promote competition in the telecommunications
marketplace. It erased decades of laws, regulations and court
decisions that had put sharp limits both on new entrants coming to
market and on older established companies that wanted to expand
into new services and regions.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday some witnesses urged the FCC to intervene to prevent
the unintended consequence of promoting big mergers without
offering consumers any meaningful benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about what happens if the commission does nothing with
these mergers,'' said Gene Kimmelman, the co-director of the
Washington office of Consumers Union. ``This could be the final
nail in the coffin to competition in the local market.''
</P>
<P>
   William Kennard, the commision's chairman, stressed Monday that
the agency was required to review the deals in light of what would
serve the ``public interest.'' But precisely what that means is
months away from being determined.
</P>
<P>
   FCC staff members have begun to question the details of some of
the deals, suggesting that they may ultimately recommend severe
conditions be imposed on one or more of them.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely expected that the commissioners will impose some
conditions on all of the deals, as they have for some prior
mergers. But it is not clear whether there will be three votes
among the five commissioners either to impose onerous terms or to
take the extraordinary step of blocking a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed acquisitions are also being examined by antitrust
regulators at the Justice Department who were criticized last year
by some groups for approving SBC's acquisition of Pacific Telesis
and Bell Atlantic's purchase of Nynex.
</P>
<P>
   As they have in the past, the companies that are seeking to
merge insisted today that they needed to combine in order to
promote competition, enter new markets, enhance their service and
keep prices down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this commission wants to promote competition,'' said
Stephen M. Carter, a senior executive of SBC Communications. ``So
do we. Our merger is a product of competition _ competition for our
most profitable customers requires us to become a national and
global carrier, which will allow us to then compete for business
and residential customers nationwide. If you have any doubts, just
look at how much the competition is doing to stop this merger.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether SBC would be able to be as competitive even if it
did not buy Ameritech, Carter demurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only by scale that you'll get the competition that was
envisioned'' by the Telecommunications Act, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But several of the companies' customers and competitors urged
the commission not to allow local and long-distance phone service _
as well as access to the Internet _ to be in the hands of even
fewer companies.
</P>
<P>
   The SBC-Ameritech deal, for example, would shrink the number of
regional Bells, which were established in the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T,
to only four.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country has spent many years and many billions of dollars
to break up telecom monopolies and have competition,'' said J.
Richard Devlin, an executive vice president and general counsel of
the Sprint Corp. ``We simply cannot afford to go backwards, to
re-create Ma Bell, where prices were high and customer choice was
virtually nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``SBC and Ameritech are already very large companies,'' he
added. ``They are very capable of competing without merging.''
</P>
<P>
   Competitors of companies in the other deals raised similar
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Bell Atlantic's proposed merger with TCI, the giant
cable provider, Jonathan Sallet, the chief policy counsel of MCI
Worldcom, said that there was ``no public interest benefit that
would even come close to outweighing the anticompetitive and
anticonsumer consequences of such a combination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
