<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA HIRES FRED GOLDMAN AS VICTIMS' RIGHTS ADVOCATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By HAL MATTERN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Fred Goldman, whose son was murdered in 1994 along
with O.J. Simpson's ex-wife, Nicole Brown Simpson, has been hired
by the Arizona Attorney General's Office as a victims' rights
advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, who moved to Scottsdale from California this year, will
be paid $23,500 a year as a half-time special assistant in the
Office of Victim Services.
</P>
<P>
   He will address complaints of rights violations and perform
victims' rights compliance audits of criminal and juvenile justice
agencies. He also will evaluate legislative proposals for their
effect on victim protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred Goldman is known the world over as an impassioned voice
for all victims of crime, especially violent crime,'' Attorney
General Grant Woods said. ``He has put a human face on the vast
number of Americans who live with the devastating effects of
violent crime every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who better to serve as this office's special representative on
behalf of Arizona victims?''
</P>
<P>
   Since Ron Goldman and Nicole Simpson were killed outside her
Brentwood, Calif., condominium, Fred Goldman has been adamant in
his belief that O.J. Simpson was the killer.
</P>
<P>
   Although Simpson was acquitted after one of history's most
publicized murder trials, the Goldman and Brown families won a
$33.5 million civil judgment against the former football star. They
have not received any money yet.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said in a statement that he looked forward to his new
job. ``I hope that I can help increase the awareness of the needs
of victims,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Napolitano, who replaces Woods in January as attorney
general, said she wasn't consulted about Goldman's hiring, but had
no problem with the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to meeting with (Goldman) and discussing his
ideas on victim rights,'' Napolitano said. ``I have a pretty
aggressive victim rights agenda myself.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2337EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
