<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0534 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9911 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     12-14 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE next time the empty suit that is Bud Selig stands up to address
baseball's ownership, he will not likely utter the one word that
would be music to the ears of his audience _ collusion.
</P>
<P>
   But don't think it wouldn't be tempting.
</P>
<P>
   That's because baseball is currently experiencing the worst
period in the history of the game. Which, considering all of the
self-destructive ills experienced by the national pastime in recent
years, is like telling survivors of the Titanic that this next
cruise might have some real problems.
</P>
<P>
   A frightening thought, indeed. But undeniably true.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was just over four years ago when baseball
ownership claimed to be standing on the brink of economic disaster
and staring into an oblivion of red ink and shuttered franchises
unless a way were found to place a limit on salaries.
</P>
<P>
   They took a hard-line stance in 1994 in an attempt to implement
a salary cap or, at the very least, a luxury-tax system that would
stifle the spending of big-market clubs that was threatening
competitive balance. They canceled the last two months of the
regular season, cutting off pennant races at the knees. They wiped
the World Series off the sports calendar for the first time in 90
years. They alienated generations of loyal fans, who have only
begun to forgive them after a magical summer of Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the NBA owners sit off to the side nodding their
heads and stiffening their resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball chopped off its foot, apparently for no good reason.
Because the system continues to be warped beyond all recognition as
free agent Kevin Brown signs a contract for $105 million, Mike
Piazza for $91 million, Bernie Williams for $87.5 million, Mo
Vaughn for $80 million and Jose By Gawd Offerman for $26 million.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Roger Clemens. He is not a free agent, but he
wants to be paid like one. He tells us the warm and fuzzy story
that he wants to come home, but not if it means leaving one cold
dollar on the table. The Astros dropped out of Toronto's auction
for Clemens _ until owner Drayton McLane Jr. jumped back in _
because the salary demands by the Rocket and his agents, Alan and
Randy Hendricks, were mind-boggling.
</P>
<P>
   Typical is more like it.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, scheduled to earn roughly $8 million per season over
the next two years, wanted his deal sweetened to an average of $14
million per because of the packages recently given to Brown and
Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   It was only 1993 when the baseball owners said the sky was
falling because Barry Bonds signed a six-year deal worth $43
million, making him the highest-paid player in the history of the
game. Now Los Angeles gives Brown a seven-year contract for $105
million and additional perks, including a hotel suite on the road
and 12 round-trip charter flights for his family each season. No
word on whether Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone has to turn
down Brown's bed each night and leave a mint on the pillow.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' belief that Clemens and the Hendrickses would give
them a financial break because of their Houston connection can be
attributed only to the ultimate in naivet or knuckleheadedness.
Clemens has always been about Roger first and the Hendrickses are,
well, agents. All scorpions sting.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, if we were to believe McLane's claim in 1994 that he
was losing $20 million a year and now his payroll has virtually
doubled, what got him in the Clemens derby to start with? Has he
found a secret revenue source? Has he learned to enjoy losing
money? Or is that just his nose growing longer?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the bidding for Clemens will likely come down to a race
among Cleveland, Colorado, Texas and both New York franchises,
large revenue teams all, as baseball's competitive gap becomes the
most lopsided affair since the Christians vs. the lions. As we sit,
still 10 days before Christmas, you can probably write off about 18
major-league teams as having no shot at the playoffs in 1999, with
the foreseeable future looking just as bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it becomes a little more understandable as to why the NBA
owners are willing to hold firm with their lockout, even if it
means blowing up an entire season. The NBA owners are saying they
will not repeat baseball's mistake by accepting a potentially
crippling deal and finding themselves sitting back in the same
leaky boat in several years.
</P>
<P>
   So the NBA remains in dry dock, which for fans can be
frustrating. But it is preferable to being lost at sea, which for
baseball could be deadly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0535 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9913 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     12-14 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
GOSH, what a big letdown. It really was about money after all.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roger Clemens' expressed longing to come home sounded so good,
especially to ears made suddenly less cynical by Ken Caminiti's
sincere desire to return to his baseball roots here. But what we
now must accept as the true underlying reason for Rocket's interest
in Houston was the opportunity to get filthy, grubby rich, instead
of merely rich. The ``coming home'' part was only an ancillary
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat amazingly, Drayton McLane Jr. actually seems
sympathetic as he battles to keep a slim chance for a trade with
Toronto alive. Having experienced an epiphany because of Randy
Johnson's sudden financial impact, the former Mr. Frugal has gotten
a tad greedy as well. You can just hear him talking to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see, 50,000 fans times 20 home starts times 25 bucks a
head ''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's most tempting to keep the candle burning for Rocket
Roger. He's a special talent, perhaps a unique talent. He is not,
however, a special person, which Caminiti proved to be. He's just
another hypocritical jock, demanding the stars when he already owns
the moon and the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, we now realize, didn't want out of Toronto for
competitive, geographical, meteorological or sentimental reasons.
What he wanted was a renegotiated contract, never mind that the one
he signed _ presumably in good faith _ still has two seasons to run
and guarantees him $16.1 million, not exactly change of the chump
variety.
</P>
<P>
   I know, I know. Roger has to feed his family. He's got four
children. He feels obligated to guarantee their ``security,'' as if
the paltry $16.1 million couldn't possibly do that. In reality,
what he feels is a testosterone-driven desire to ensure that they
inherit more money in the end than either Johnson's or Kevin
Brown's kids.
</P>
<P>
   Grandkids, too.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about quality of life, or even going to the World
Series with one of baseball's best lineups as a supporting cast.
This is about the new golden rule: ``He who has the most gold
rules.'' Winning at the bank matters more than winning on the
field, even if it's the home field, where Clemens' friends and
family could root him on.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens sees Johnson get $52 million for four years, and he sees
red. Then, he sees Brown sign for $105 million over seven years,
and he sees green.
</P>
<P>
   Word is the Astros were supposed to receive a brother-in-law
below-market deal for the five-time Cy Young Award winner's
services. Then came Brown's Dodgers bonanza, which set a new
standard for damn-the-torpedoes free spending and fulfilled every
dire prophecy about the dangers of letting a Rupert Murdoch get in
a position where he could further inflate an already ridiculously
bloated wage scale.
</P>
<P>
   If $43.5 million for the next three years _ two of which, repeat
after me, he's under contract for _ plus a fourth-year ``vesting
option'' for another $15 million is the cut rate, Rocket's sticker
price must be a doozy.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, in case you missed it, Clemens also desires suites, not mere
hotel rooms, on the road. Guess he figures he can't afford to pay
for the upgrades himself.
</P>
<P>
   Are you appalled? You should be, particularly after being
suckered by Rocket's ruse about the teary-eyed allure of home and
hearth. Yes, we should have known better.
</P>
<P>
   The Hendricks brothers, superstar agents Randy and Alan, are
Houstonians, the same as their superstar client. In their business,
they enjoy Clemens-sized stature and have at least as much dough in
the bank as he does to show for it. Their sworn duty, nonetheless,
is to break as many banks as possible on behalf of the many
mercenaries they represent. So don't expect serious compassion from
these homeboys, either.
</P>
<P>
   McLane conceded Monday that the trade has become a ``far, far
long shot'' and talked about being ``responsible'' regarding the
Astros' fiscal realities. But against the advice of his astute
baseball people, namely Executive of the Year Gerry Hunsicker and
the venerable Tal Smith, McLane stubbornly refuses to shoot the
deal in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker, incensed by the contemptible path the process has
taken, tried to follow the prudent path and was left looking
foolish by the owner, who publicly contradicted Gerry's
``not-only-no-but-hell-no'' verdict. McLane is the lone person in
the organization who believes trading two or more good players and
offering Clemens free-agent-type dollars has a smidgen of merit.
</P>
<P>
   You see that, and, whoa, it hits you. Maybe we're the dupes.
Could McLane, contrary to what he has been telling us, not be
losing that much money _ if any _ after all?
</P>
<P>
   And suppose Team Hendricks does lower its extortionate demands
significantly, admittedly an unlikely scenario. Then are we
supposed to be mollified, or does that simply confirm the magnitude
of the scam?
</P>
<P>
   When agents start dictating the terms of trading a player with a
binding contract, it's a safe assessment that baseball remains
very, very ill. We must fear the inmates will yet burn down the
asylum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
