<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0536 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9916 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-HNS &LR;      12-14 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
DENVER _ For the first time since Dec. 8, 1997, the Denver Broncos
were forced to practice on Monday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coach Mike Shanahan has a team rule that says if the Broncos
win, players can come in on their own on Mondays. Most of them are
in and out by 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Broncos lose _ something they hadn't done since
Pittsburgh beat them in the 15th game last season _ they have to
spend Monday at the office, just like normal people.
</P>
<P>
   After losing 20-16 to the New York Giants on Sunday, the Broncos
reported for a full day of film review, weightlifting,
rehabilitation and running.
</P>
<P>
   They barely got away in time to beat the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it hadn't happened in such a long time, a lot of guys
kind of forgot what the schedule was like,'' tight end Shannon
Sharpe said. ``They had to call in and get the information.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I'm not going to sit here and lie. I would have
loved to have been 19-0. It would have been great, but the end
result's still the same. We want to win the big game. Ultimately,
that's what you're going to be judged by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take 18-1, and I say we're still better than the '72
Dolphins.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Broncos blew their chance to join the 1972 Dolphins
as the NFL's only unbeaten and untied champions, become the NFL's
first 19-0 team and set a league record with 19 consecutive
victories, it was hard to tell in the dressing room Monday that
anything out of the ordinary happened Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is weird,'' running back Derek Loville said about the
full day of work. ``We haven't done this in a while. It's not
something we're going to get used to. This is our last Monday (to
practice).''
</P>
<P>
   By losing to the Giants on Kent Graham's 37-yard touchdown pass
to Amani Toomer in the final minute, the Broncos took some of the
luster off next Monday's game at Miami. Of course, they couldn't
care less about that angle.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos were divided on whether the pressure of an
undefeated season finally got to them. They had not dominated in
previous wins over San Diego and Kansas City, two teams with losing
records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we still had that pressure,'' Shanahan said. ``I don't
enjoy losing, but life goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the season we had one goal, and it wasn't to go
unbeaten. It was to win another Super Bowl. Never in my wildest
dreams did I think about going unbeaten.''
</P>
<P>
   As the victories mounted and the pressure increased, safety
Steve Atwater thought the Broncos had become more focused on going
unbeaten than on the next opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't focused on winning,'' Atwater said. ``We were
focused on being 14-0. Sure, we practiced, but in the back of our
minds, the only thing you're thinking about is the outcome of the
game and not the job at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody was looking past them (the Giants) to
Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Neil Smith sounded glad the streak was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a burden, and the burden was heavy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In November, owner Pat Bowlen said he hoped the Broncos would
lose a game to take some of the pressure off so his team could
concentrate on becoming the seventh team to win consecutive Super
Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   After the Broncos finally lost, Bowlen had a change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said that when we were 8-0,'' Bowlen said. ``That was before
we really got into this streak. Now, I'm a little disappointed. I
kind of got caught up in it. It was fun for the city and the fans
of Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Broncos lost two in a row before recovering to
win the regular-season finale against San Diego. They finished 12-4
and came up one game short of Kansas City in the AFC West. They
made the playoffs as a wild card and won four games, including
Super Bowl XXXII over Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   This season, they don't want to lose two of their last three.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a wake-up call,'' Shanahan said. ``We can say, `Hey,
that's over. What are we made of? How do we bounce back?'
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to identify what we did wrong and try not to make the
same mistakes. I'm most concerned about our third-down defense and
our scoring in the red zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than a regular day at the office Monday, Shanahan won't
change a thing about the Broncos' preparation for the Dolphins. One
of the things that make Shanahan such a good coach is his
consistency with his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here to set records or to get individual honors,''
Shanahan said. ``We're here to win the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't beat yourself up after losing, something's wrong
with you. You're not made of the right stuff. But the key is how
you respond to the situation. Everybody has to find out what he did
wrong and what he could have done to affect the outcome of the
game. Then, he has to forget about it when he comes to work
Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   As they prepare for the Dolphins, the Broncos are still united
in their original goal of winning Super Bowl XXXIII, which will be
played at Miami's Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be more of a sense of urgency,'' linebacker Bill
Romanowski said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-98 2350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981214.0537 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9919 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CLEMENSSAGA-HNS &LR;      12-14 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CLEMENSSAGA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ A betting man wouldn't dare predict which team's
uniform Roger Clemens will be wearing next season, and the chances
of the five-time Cy Young Award winner's landing with the Astros
are hardly favorable.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's a far, far long shot,'' Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr.
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why he's so motivated to complete the deal
against all odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made a career out of making complex things work,'' McLane
said. ``Even if it doesn't work out, it was worth the effort.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the effort is the sole responsibility of McLane, who
has emerged from the background as the chief negotiator in the
Astros' efforts to trade for Clemens. The issue appeared dead
Sunday when Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker called a news
conference to announce the Astros were dropping out of the race.
But McLane has pumped life back into the discussions and submitted
a counterproposal to Randy Hendricks, one of Clemens' agents, on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the Astros' offer are not available at this time, but
it's certainly worth less than the three-year, $43.5 million
proposal Hendricks sent to McLane over the weekend. Sources say the
original deal called for a fourth-year option worth an additional
$15 million and a $12 million signing bonus to be spread over the
life of the restructured contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their turn now,'' said McLane, indicating the ball was in
Clemens' court. ``The first proposal was not anything we could come
close to.''
</P>
<P>
   McLane's decision to forge ahead in the Clemens negotiations
presumably goes against the advice of his baseball people. On
Sunday, Hunsicker stated the club's position as being
philosophically opposed to renegotiating the contract of a player
who already is signed for two more seasons, especially when it also
meant trading players to satisfy the Blue Jays' demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, what Gerry said was true,'' McLane said. ``We have
to do something that is fair. Even if we reach something with
Roger, we still have to be able to work out something with the Blue
Jays. I've said it before, but we have to be careful that we don't
do something stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker had no comment on McLane's decision to continue talks.
</P>
<P>
   The general belief among baseball observers is that Clemens is a
player under contract who wants to be treated like a free agent.
But the reality is that Clemens seemingly has unprecedented control
under an agreement with former Blue Jays president Paul Beeston,
who gave Clemens the right to demand a trade (with certain veto
powers) if he ceased to view the Blue Jays as contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some very unique clauses in the contract that allow us
to do the things that we're doing,'' Hendricks said. ``We told
every team that we were looking for a contract extension. Wherever
Roger goes, he wants it to be for the rest of his career. Drayton
felt the first proposal was too rich but not so rich that he
couldn't come back with a counterproposal.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue could be resolved over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Some baseball executives predictably were applauding the Astros'
restraint regarding Clemens' demands after Sunday's news
conference. More than $1 billion has been spent on free agents this
offseason, highlighted by the seven-year, $105 million contract
free-agent pitcher Kevin Brown and the Dodgers agreed to on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig, a good friend of McLane's, has cautioned
owners against the potentially dangerous trend of escalating player
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always pressure (from other owners),'' McLane said.
``But that was blown open Saturday. If we did something (with
Clemens), it wouldn't be anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   There also is the perception of pressure from the Astros'
in-state neighbors to the north. Hendricks said the Texas Rangers
have made a proposal, but as with the Astros, a trade package with
the Blue Jays would still have to be agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
   Some feel McLane is staying in the Clemens sweepstakes because
he couldn't stand to see the Texas legend wind up with the Rangers,
a la Nolan Ryan, who left the Astros to sign as a free agent with
the Rangers in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   McLane said such a perception could not be further from the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has nothing to do with it,'' he said. ``We are not in
competition with the Rangers. Would it be different if I saw that
the Cubs or the Cardinals (both division rivals) were interested?
You bet. But the Rangers are in the American League, and we don't
even play them in interleague play, so that has nothing to do with
it. (Rangers owner) Tom Hicks and I are friends. If they wind up
getting Roger, I'd give him a call to congratulate him.''
</P>
<P>
   McLane intends to exercise caution in the Clemens negotiations
because he believes the Astros are favorites to win their third
consecutive National League Central title even if they don't make
another personnel move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great team,'' McLane said. ``Everyone got all
stirred up last year when we lost Darryl Kile (to the Colorado
Rockies through free agency), but Shane Reynolds won 19 games for
us. We've already got good pitching with guys like Mike Hampton,
Jose Lima. And I think Shane Reynolds is one of the most underrated
pitchers in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like our team, but if there's something we can do to improve
it, we're always going to look at it. I still think (Clemens) is a
long shot, but I'm an eternal optimist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
